<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3026 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-WASHES-AZR &LR;      05-02 1347
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WASHES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOENIX LOOKS AT NATURAL FLOOD CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY KATHLEEN INGLEY  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
(PHOENIX) - A fortress of concrete protects the Phoenix area from
flooding: dams, dikes, channels and culverts. But now Phoenix may
go natural, letting washes carry off storm water.
</P>
<P>
   The city will decide in the next few months whether to ``go with
the flow'' in areas about to explode with development, instead of
pouring more concrete ramparts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The approach can be a model for elsewhere in the Valley,''
says Ray Quay, Phoenix assistant planning director, especially as
growth pushes into uplands creased with major washes.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, there's a move to leave nature in charge of flood
control. It costs less, preserves wildlife habitat and opens the
door to recreation.
</P>
<P>
   But the natural approach means there's less land available for
development. Channels and culverts allow homes and businesses to be
built right up to the edge of a river or wash.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Larry Lazarus, who represents landowners in the north
Phoenix area, worries that large portions of their property could
be made off-limits to development. He argues that well-designed
flood-control structures can blend in with the landscape.
</P>
<P>
   UNIQUE CONDITIONS
</P>
<P>
   Why worry about floods in the desert? The idea puzzles newcomers
to Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the desert's sparse plant cover and the hard soil
encourage runoff. Rapid snowmelt in distant mountains sends spring
floodwaters pouring into the flatlands. Summer thunderstorms can
dump so much water so fast that the ground can't absorb it.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, after a heavy storm covering less than a square mile,
water shot down a wash in Safford fast enough to fill an Olympic
swimming pool every minute.
</P>
<P>
   The old approach to controlling all that water was concrete, and
plenty of it.
</P>
<P>
   Take Cave Creek in Phoenix. Like most creeks and rivers in
Arizona, it carries water only after a heavy rain.
</P>
<P>
   At Greenway Road and 17th Avenue, Cave Creek has been turned
into a concrete chute, as wide as a two-lane road.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a certain elegance in its ability to move a lot of
water quickly that was probably appropriate for its time,'' said
Doug Williams, senior planner for the Maricopa County Flood Control
District.
</P>
<P>
   But the cost is high. Building a major channel runs $2 million a
mile and up, while annual maintenance on large flood-control
projects averages $12,000 per mile.
</P>
<P>
   INCOMPATIBLE SYSTEMS
</P>
<P>
   Another complication is that flood-control structures have been
built piecemeal over the years. New development may also funnel
water into older systems without enough capacity.
</P>
<P>
   In Glendale, for example, developers along lower Skunk Creek
reinforced the banks with a variety of materials, from rock to
concrete, and built to varying design standards. ``It was just a
mess,'' Williams said, and the whole area had to be redone.
</P>
<P>
   To head off such problems, the Flood Control District is working
on master plans to control storm water in four large undeveloped
areas that span Avondale, Glendale, Peoria and Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   They are centered on major washes or dry riverbeds: the Agua
Fria River from the Salt River up to Lake Pleasant; Cave Creek and
Apache Wash; the middle course of New River between Greenway and
Jomax roads; and Skunk Creek.
</P>
<P>
   The county is emphasizing a natural approach. That's not
possible in flatter areas, which get ``sheet flooding,'' where
water spreads across broad areas, and some sort of channel or
culvert is needed to carry it off.
</P>
<P>
   Skunk Creek, east of Interstate 17 and north of the Carefree
Highway, is on the front burner. Last year, Phoenix put development
on hold in the area until Flood Control analyzed strategies for
handling storm water.
</P>
<P>
   The county is examining four alternatives: the natural approach,
the completely structural approach, and two options that make some
use of structures.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLIC MEETINGS &QL; 
Phoenix will hold public meetings on the proposals in the coming
weeks, with a City Council vote expected in June.
</P>
<P>
   The Phoenix area is part of a national move toward flood-control
strategies that don't destroy the habitat around washes and rivers.
</P>
<P>
   Even at the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers, known for its feats of
construction, ``there's a stronger and stronger push to consider
saving natural channels as much as possible,'' senior engineer
Richard DiBuono said.
</P>
<P>
   That's especially critical in the desert, where washes are rich
with plants and animals. Studies of Skunk Creek found twice as many
species and 250 percent more plant cover in wash areas, compared
with surrounding land.
</P>
<P>
   RECREATIONAL AREAS &QL; 
Recreation is another spur to keeping washes intact. Along New
River, Maricopa County will ``armor'' the banks as far as the
existing subdivisions.
</P>
<P>
   But above that point, the riverbed would be left in its natural
state. The plan is to use both New River and the Agua Fria to
create the West Valley Recreation Corridor, including parks and
trails.
</P>
<P>
   Money for recreational features must still be lined up, though.
And not everyone is giving up concrete.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE'S APPROACH
</P>
<P>
   In Scottsdale, city leaders are pushing the Desert Greenbelt, a
$100 million project with five miles of channels, pipes and
retention basins to catch runoff from the McDowell Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents say it's vital protection from a devastating 100-year
flood and will preserve the native environment as much as possible.
But critics say it's designed to support more development in
booming north Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   The Corps of Engineers will decide on a key permit for the
project in the next few months.
</P>
<P>
   COMPROMISE URGES &QL; 
Attorney Lazarus says Phoenix shouldn't reject structural solutions
out of hand. His clients could build on just a third of their 120
acres by Skunk Creek under an all-natural plan. With limited
flood-control construction, Lazarus says more land could be
developed without environmental harm.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is so many people think this is a black-and-white
issue,'' Lazarus said, ``either a concrete conduit or wide open.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazarus also objects to suggestions that the city prohibit
development in the entire 100-year flood plain, an area that has a
1 percent chance of flooding in any given year. Flooding in some
spots might be only a few inches of water, he said.
</P>
<P>
   To preserve all that land, Lazarus said, ``is not a health and
safety issue, it's an aesthetic one.'' The property is effectively
condemned, he argues, and the owner should be paid.
</P>
<P>
   That solution is gaining steam.
</P>
<P>
   Pima County has bought more than 7,000 acres under its
Flood-prone Land Acquisition Program.
</P>
<P>
   Maricopa County, which bought about a dozen small properties in
special cases, is looking at a formal buyout program that would
draw on federal matching funds.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix planner Quay says the city should consider purchasing
property when it might be valuable for preservation or cheaper than
flood protection.
</P>
<P>
   LUCRATIVE CHOICE
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, developers can profit from leaving wash
corridors alone, said Andy Kunasek, chairman of the Maricopa County
Board of Supervisors, because homebuyers will pay the same premiums
to live by open space as by golf courses.
</P>
<P>
   Sunbelt Holdings is counting on that in developing Sonoran
Foothills, an 800-acre project by Skunk Creek.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've really planned this community around the washes,'' said
Heidi Kimball, Sunbelt vice president. They will be the core of a
trail system and offer vistas for drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Sunbelt has the advantage of drainage patterns that leave lots
of land to develop. Still, Kimball said, ``it's never going to be
100 percent natural.'' She doesn't see how to avoid neighborhood
retention ponds or some bridges.
</P>
<P>
   But Supervisor Jan Brewer predicts the Valley won't go back to
the old ways of flood control.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a vision,'' she said. ``We're not going to have ugly
cement channels.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Kathleen.Ingley(at)Arizona &QL; 
Republic.com or (602) 444-8171. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
