<SLUG> BC-KANSAS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI OFFICIALLY REMOVES ACCREDITATION FOR KC SCHOOL DISTRICT 
</HEADLINE>
 CITY-ACCREDITATION-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN HOFFMANN  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Kansas City schools officially lost state
accreditation on Monday, but Superintendent Benjamin Demps Jr.
expressed hope that the district could regain at least provisional
accreditation by this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have known this day was coming since last November, and we
have been preparing to face the challenges it brings,'' Demps said
at an afternoon press conference at district headquarters. ``Our
No. 1 priority in this district is to regain accreditation.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Republican lawmakers and the national media also used
the occasion to make observations on the future of the district.
</P>
<P>
   Four Republican state legislators gathered at district
headquarters earlier in the day to criticize Democrats and to again
express support for a proposal aimed at splitting up the district.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal never was introduced in the General Assembly for
debate.
</P>
<P>
   And media outlets, including The Christian Science Monitor,
National Public Radio, U.S. News &AMP; World Report and Education Week
all produced stories detailing the problems that confront one of
the nation's most closely watched school systems.
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri Board of Education decided in October to strip the
district of accreditation after state education officials found the
district failed to meet any of 11 academic performance standards.
The state board delayed the effective date of the loss of
accreditation until Monday because of a fear by local officials
that students would flee the district in the middle of a school
year.
</P>
<P>
   Loss of accreditation means the state is withdrawing its seal of
approval. More importantly, it means the district now has two years
to raise test scores, boost graduation rates, improve attendance,
or progress in other areas assessed by state performance standards.
</P>
<P>
   If improvement doesn't occur, the district faces the prospect of
state takeover. Ultimately, the district could be dissolved and
students assigned to new or existing districts.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of accreditation also means that students can leave the
Kansas City district for neighboring Missouri districts and that
the Kansas City district would have to pay for tuition and
transportation costs. However, most of those districts are faced
with space problems and cannot accept an influx of new students.
</P>
<P>
   Demps said the district is more focused now than it has been in
recent years and has already improved the student attendance rate,
the vocational program and the number of students enrolled in
advanced courses. District officials hope that improvements in
those areas and in statewide assessment test scores could help
regain at least provisional accreditation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we will succeed because we are placing a strong
emphasis on literacy in every grade,'' Demps said. ``Teachers are
learning new strategies for helping every student achieve to the
best of their abilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Demps said district officials met briefly last week and
discussed filing a lawsuit against the Missouri Department of
Elementary and Secondary Education aimed at blocking the state's
action. Officials dropped those plans, at least for now, Demps
said, until the district can get out of the federal desegregation
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The state legislators, including Connie Cierpiot of
Independence, Carson Ross of Blue Springs, Matt Bartle of Lee's
Summit and Annie Reinhart of Liberty, were not as optimistic about
the district's future. They urged lawmakers to put politics aside
and work together on a plan for improving the district. The group's
plan includes splitting the district of about 30,000 students into
five smaller districts, a move they said would make managing Kansas
City schools easier and more efficient.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two biggest school districts in the state of Missouri are
St. Louis and Kansas City,'' Ross said. ``The two school districts
in Missouri that are failing (the most) are St. Louis and Kansas
City.''
</P>
</TEXT>
