<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 00:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3028 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-WOOD-HNS &LR;      05-02 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-WOOD-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
MILWAUKEE _ In a season when hardly anything has gone the Astros'
way, this almost seems fitting.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of all the teams against which Kerry Wood could have made his
long-awaited comeback from shoulder surgery _ the Chicago Cubs have
19 other opponents on their schedule _ fate blew the Astros into
the Windy City for a reunion they would have just as soon skipped.
</P>
<P>
   Almost two years to the day after he struck out a
major-league-record-tying 20 batters in a game against the Astros
at Wrigley Field, Wood will return to the majors tonight to start
the opener of a three-game series between the Astros and Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Wood was named the National League Rookie of the Year following
the 1998 season, but he missed all of last season after undergoing
reconstructive elbow surgery. Originally scheduled to make his
return this past weekend against the Arizona Diamondbacks, Wood was
pushed back after developing a blister on the middle finger of his
pitching hand.
</P>
<P>
   So by default, not to mention a little misfortune, the Astros
will get an up-close-and-personal look at Wood's first big-league
action since 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should be exciting,'' Astros manager Larry Dierker said.
``I hope he doesn't throw as well as he has the other times we've
faced him, and I'm not just talking about the 20-strikeout game.
He's pitched some very good games against us.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had as much trouble with his breaking pitches as we did
with his fastball. I sure hope he doesn't have that kind of command
again, and I'm sure our hitters feel the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   Wood, who was 13-6 with a 3.40 ERA in 1998, is 1-0 with a 0.53
ERA in two games (17 innings) against the Astros. He also pitched
eight sparkling innings in an appearance at the Astrodome in 1998,
but the game everyone remembers is the 20-strikeout, one-hit
masterpiece.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen anyone pitch like he pitched that day,''
Astros catcher Tony Eusebio said. ``He had command of all of his
breaking pitches, and he was throwing his fastball about 97 mph.
That was just his day. Now he's making his comeback, and there are
going to be a lot of people who want to come out and see him pitch.
It's going to be an exciting day. Hopefully, we'll do better this
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Wood's return falls four days shy of the two-year anniversary of
his memorable day against the Astros, but first-year Cubs manager
Don Baylor insists he wasn't trying to be sentimental.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 20-strikeout game was one of those in-the-zone games for
anybody,'' Baylor said. ``If it (his return) was going to be
against the Pirates, it has the same meaning to Kerry. It just so
happened that's the way it fell with the Astros. There are some
guys there that had a lot of strikeouts in games that he pitched.''
</P>
<P>
   The day in question was not a particularly pleasant one for
Astros hitting instructor Tom McCraw, who watched his high-powered
offense get overpowered by Wood.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking to get his butt this time,'' McCraw said. ``He
dominated us pretty good that day, so I would imagine we'll be
running a few decibels higher this time. It will be interesting to
see how he comes back from surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most guys who have that surgery are never the same, but some
come back a little bit better than they were before. It remains to
be seen how Kerry is going to come back. We won't know that until
he's thrown into the wars. I'm sure he has some doubts, too.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing Wood is certain of is that he won't take memories of
his signature game to the mound tonight before a sellout crowd at
the Friendly Confines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to forget who it was against,'' Wood said of the
20-strikeout game. ``But it's not going to be weighing on my mind,
and I'm not going to go out there and try to strike out guys. I'm
going to go out and get my outs and keep us close and try to give
us a chance to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't worry about expectations. I'm not big into that. I go
out and do my job and let everybody else make expectations. If
everybody else goes out and does their job, then we won't have any
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
