r a BC-ATTENTION-DISORDER-SF     05-02 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATTENTION-DISORDER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUIDELINES ISSUED FOR ATTENTION DEFICIT DISORDER DIAGNOSIS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARL T. HALL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  Hoping to quell some of the controversy surrounding the use of
psychiatric medications in children, the nation's largest
pediatrics group issued Monday the first detailed guidelines for
diagnosing attention deficit disorder.
<P>
   The American Academy of Pediatrics, which has 55,000 members,
said the new guidelines are intended to give doctors a clear,
scientific framework to tell the difference between a child who is
seriously ill and one whose problems may require no medical
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The recommendations apply to schoolchildren between ages 6 and
12. Two years in the making, the guidelines appear in the May issue
of Pediatrics, the academy's scientific journal.
</P>
<P>
   Couched in the precise language of clinical practice, the
voluntary guidelines urge doctors to avoid making any formal
diagnosis of ADD, also known as attention deficit hyperactivity
disorder, or ADHD, unless ``core symptoms'' occur both at home and
at school.
</P>
<P>
   Symptoms must significantly impair school performance, family
functioning or social development over at least a six-month period
to fit the criteria of a bona fide psychiatric disorder.
</P>
<P>
   The symptoms are often difficult to distinguish from the normal
rambunctiousness of a particularly active youngster, a problem made
all the more difficult by the varying attitudes of parents,
teachers and other caregivers.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, however, children are being prescribed medications
to calm them down, typically Ritalin, a mild stimulant, despite the
lack of uniform diagnostic criteria. The use of Ritalin-type
pediatric drugs has increased dramatically during the past decade,
the pediatricians noted.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors' group is working on a second set of parameters to
guide treatment and medication decisions after the initial
diagnosis has been made.
</P>
<P>
   The treatment recommendations are not expected to be ready for
publication until early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Working out a consensus on treatment of ADHD may well be the
more formidable task for the doctors' group. Some physicians are
loathe to prescribe psychiatric drugs to children under nearly any
circumstances, while others maintain the drugs are entirely
appropriate when used correctly.
</P>
<P>
   Given the sometimes explosive sentiments surrounding the issue,
Dr. Martin T. Stein, a San Diego pediatrician and co-chair of the
academy committee that produced the recommendations, urged a
careful, step-by-step approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can get the diagnosis right, the proper course of
treatment will follow,'' he said. ``But it's very important that
the first step is being rigorous about the diagnostic criteria.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, neither he nor the pediatric academy is taking a
position on whether drugs are being overused _ or even if ADHD is
being over-diagnosed in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Practices appear to vary in different regions of the country,
and often from one doctor's office to the next, Stein noted, adding
that there's no clear evidence on which to base an overall
conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people think it's over-diagnosed, but in some parts of
the country, it may be under-diagnosed. We don't have the data to
really answer the question, but I suspect it probably goes a bit
both ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Survey results suggest about 8 to 10 percent of schoolchildren
have ADHD symptoms. For the U.S. population as a whole, including
adults, the prevalance of ``behaviors consistent with ADHD'' runs
about 9 percent of males and 3 percent of females, the physicians
said.
</P>
<P>
   The academy noted that brain scans and other high-tech
diagnostic tools for ADHD are being investigated, but so far do not
yield reliable enough results to replace the careful judgment of a
clinician.
</P>
<P>
   One key difference between normal childlike behavior that adults
find difficult and a psychiatric syndrome that needs medical
attention is whether the behavior lasts a long time and severely
affects development.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors also were urged to devise ways to draw the relevant
details about the child's behavior from caregivers, because the
child's behavior in the relative calm of a doctor's office may
provide few clues as to what is going on at home or school.
</P>
<P>
   Two or three visits may be needed over the course of six months
for the diagnosis to be made properly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not enough for a child just to have these behaviors,''
Stein said. ``The behaviors have to persist.''
</P>
<P>
   The recommendations are intended to prevent snap judgments by
doctors under pressure who provide medications to satisfy parents
at wit's end, desperate to try anything for a child who may need
much more time-consuming types of attention, &LR;  such as counseling or
special schooling.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Russell Reiff, a behavioral-developmental pediatrician at
Kaiser Permanente's San Francisco medical center, said the new
guidelines leave out a lot of key details, such as how doctors
should best gather diagnostic information.
</P>
<P>
   But he also said the detailed recommendations should help by
giving clinicians ``ammunition'' to fend off pressure to scribble
out a scrip against their better judgment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doctors face this incredible pressure from parents who come in
saying, `Can't we just try the medication and see if it helps?' ''
he said. ``This will help. Now it's down on paper. We really need
to step back and think about this and get some information in a
more cogent way, a slower, more deliberate way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-00 0038EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
