<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 MAYOR ZIPS HIS LIPS ON INDICTMENTS  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Five grand jury indictments were handed up last
week, accusations of heavy corruption in San Francisco's minority
contracting program, and we all know exactly where the mayor of San
Francisco stands.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Willie L. Brown Jr. is angry! He is absolutely opposed to
the use of cell phones in public! He thinks it is rude and
uncivilized!
</P>
<P>
   As for those pesky indictments?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a legal proceeding, and it would be inappropriate at
this time to comment,'' Brown spokeswoman Kandace Bender said.
</P>
<P>
   Funny, this seems like a stunningly appropriate time to comment.
</P>
<P>
   It would also be a marvelously appropriate time to hold a press
conference (no cell phones allowed! &LR; ) and actually give real
answers to hard questions.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing more embarrassing than having a scandal like this
come down in your government is trying to make it go away by not
publicly addressing it.
</P>
<P>
   I WISH Willie was talking, because he might be the only one who
can sort out the 49ers' quarterback mess.
</P>
<P>
   Remember how Da Mayor helped the team get rid of Elvis Grbac?
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers seem pretty sure they don't want Steve Young back.
They say they're worried about his health, with the concussions and
all, but cynics say the 49ers simply don't want to rebuild the team
around a very expensive and very old quarterback who has a glass
cranium.
</P>
<P>
   And Steve's had several months to make a decision on whether or
not to retire, but he's still scratching his head. Hope he'll read
defenses faster than that.
</P>
<P>
   This is becoming as painfully awkward as the wedding of Darva
and Rick.
</P>
<P>
   How does coach Steve Mariucci feel? On the air with Ralph and
Tom on KNBR, coach Mooch said, ``I don't want to stick my neck out
on a limb here...''
</P>
<P>
   Does that sound more like Willie Brown or Yogi Berra?
</P>
<P>
   I WILL BUNGEE-JUMP to conclusions here and say: Bring Steve
Young back for one more run at the Big Chalupa. Launch the New QB
Project next year. Tell Jeff Garcia, ``May we put you on hold?''
</P>
<P>
   Hey, with NFL parity, even the 49ers will have a (distant) shot
at the Super Bowl, with Young.
</P>
<P>
   Young's big salary is a problem because of the salary cap, but
maybe he'll take a senior-citizen discount.
</P>
<P>
   Even in his elderly and fragile state, Young is a thrilling and
dangerous player. And imagine how inspired he will be this season
with his wife watching.
</P>
<P>
   ENEMY TERRORISTS sneaked into my column last week and planted a
typo. Superchef Jeremiah Tower left San Francisco for Manila in
1998, not 1988. Those old decades all look alike to me.
</P>
<P>
   PHONE RINGS.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hello.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Bill Jones from the Philip Morris Co., may I speak to
Michael Haworth?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Speaking. What can I do for you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to ask you some survey questions, if I may.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My oldest son, daughter-in-law and I suffer from bronchitis.
My mother-in-law is dying from emphysema. All due to smoking, even
though we all quit long ago. My youngest son is currently addicted.
Now, what questions do you have?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any questions. Thank you for your time.''
</P>
<P>
   SERIOUS wine fans (grape heads? cork sniffers?) are quietly
hoarding a Wine-Country secret.
</P>
<P>
   Many Napa Valley wineries are owned and run by people with kids.
The kids go to schools that raise money by auctioning donated
items. What these parents donate is cool wine and wine-related
stuff.
</P>
<P>
   So at these little school auctions, amazing deals. Cult winery
issues, rare wines, insider tours, etc. At the May 13 auction for
St. Helena Elementary, for instance, you can bid on a magnum of '96
Screaming Eagle Cabernet Sauvignon.
</P>
<P>
   I hate it when eagles scream, but it's for a good cause.
</P>
<P>
   SURF'S WAY up: Steven Cannata saw an article in the Los Angeles
Times on the possibility of a tsunami hitting Santa Monica. The
article was accompanied by a list of helpful safety tips.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tip No. 2: Tsunamis are not surfable. They are not V-shaped or
curling.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like a challenge, dudes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
