<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAITING GAME FOR LEFTY PEREZ
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Los Angeles Dodgers bought themselves at least
four weeks in deciding what to do with left-handed pitcher Carlos
Perez.
</P>
<P>
   Under major-league rules, a player has the right to refuse an
assignment to the minor leagues once he accrues five years of
service time at the major-league level. Perez reaches that mark
Saturday, but he and the Dodgers agreed to extend the deadline
until May 31.
</P>
<P>
   Perez, who makes $5 million this season and is owed $7.5 million
next season, said he had no problem with the extension because he
believes he'll pitch well enough to remain with the Dodgers all
season. He's 2-1 with a 4.62 ERA, and his ERA is 3.07 in his last
three outings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did it not because the team asked me to do it but because I
have to do it,'' Perez said before Monday's game with Atlanta.
``They pay me to work and I have to pay them back.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone said the players
association was aware of the agreement and won't question it,
particularly because it benefits the player.
</P>
<P>
   If Perez didn't agree to it, the Dodgers were prepared to send
him to Triple-A Albuquerque prior to Saturday's deadline, a team
official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives us more flexibility and it helps us, at least through
the month of May,'' Malone said. ``It's a nonissue right now
because of the way he's been pitching, so I think we'll deal with
it when it gets closer. Now, we have all of (May) to continue to
evaluate his progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez is scheduled to start Wednesday's series finale with the
Braves and pitch again May 9 in Arizona. But three off days in the
next two weeks make it so the Dodgers won't need a fifth starter
again until May 20, when Perez is tentatively scheduled to pitch in
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   If Perez falters, the Dodgers are prepared to send him to the
minor leagues and put right-hander Orel Hershiser in the starting
rotation. The possibility also exists that if Perez pitches well
into late May, he and the Dodgers could extend the agreement
longer.
</P>
<P>
   __ Spring-training funding: A bill that would allocate funding
to upgrade or acquire spring-training facilities in Florida,
particularly Dodgertown in Vero Beach, was passed by that state's
House of Representatives on Monday and is expected to breeze
through the Senate today.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which could produce $7 million of funding to keep the
Dodgers in Vero Beach, would then be placed on Gov. Jeb Bush's desk
Wednesday. Bush then has 30 days to sign the bill or veto it.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush signs off on the bill, it also strengthens the Dodgers'
bargaining position with Las Vegas, which is trying to lure several
teams for an extravagant spring-training complex.
</P>
<P>
   __ Off his Rocker: Atlanta closer John Rocker, whose insensitive
comments during the offseason offended nearly every walk of life,
was greeted with mixed reaction before the game.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker was booed by the few thousand fans in the ballpark about
45 minutes before the game, but when he walked to the bullpen
moments before the national anthem, the stadium was filled with
jeers and cheers.
</P>
<P>
   __ Odds and ends: Wanting to get the maximum amount of starts
out of Kevin Brown, the right-hander will start Friday's series
opener against Houston and push everyone back a day because of
Thursday's day off. That allows Brown to pitch the series finale
May 10 in Arizona. . . . The Dodgers got a scare during batting
practice when left fielder Gary Sheffield stepped on a ball near
the batting cage and collapsed. Sheffield turned his already
injured right ankle. He hobbled off the field but was in the
starting lineup for the 25th time in 25 games. . . . Lefty Onan
Masaoka might not be returning to Los Angeles any time soon.
Masaoka, sent to Triple-A Albuquerque to find his arm strength,
can't find the plate. He walked eight in his last outing and has 19
walks in 10 innings. . . . Johnson spoke to rehabbing right-hander
Antonio Osuna to let him know the Dodgers are thinking about him.
Osuna hasn't allowed a run in 4 innings with Albuquerque.
</P>
</TEXT>
