<HEADER>
A3034 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-CHRONICLE-TRIAL-SFCHR     05-02 1321
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRONICLE-TRIAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON OPENING DAY OF TRIAL, EXAMINER PUBLISHERS ACKNOWLEDGES 
 `HORSETRADING'
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By WILLIAM CARLSEN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ The publisher of the Examiner testified Monday
that he conveyed to Mayor Willie Brown his willingness to
``horsetrade'' favorable treatment in the Examiner's editorial
pages in exchange for the mayor's support of the Hearst
Corporation's purchase of The Chronicle.
<P>
   The revelation came in testimony by Timothy O. White, editor and
publisher of the Hearst-owned Examiner, and was used to show the
lengths to which the company was willing to go to defuse political
and legal opposition to The Chronicle deal.
</P>
<P>
   White was the lead-off witness in an unprecedented federal
antitrust trial challenging Hearst's proposed purchase of The
Chronicle and the acquisition of the Examiner by the Fang family,
publishers of the free, thrice-weekly Independent.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed by former mayoral candidate Clint Reilly,
claims that the Fang family's acquisition of the Examiner is a
``sham'' that is doomed to failure, which would leave San Francisco
with a single daily newspaper _ a Hearst-owned Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, which is being heard by U.S. District Judge Vaughn
Walker, is the first to challenge an attempted dissolution of a
joint operating agreement, an exemption to federal antitrust law
that allows competing newspapers like The Chronicle and the
Examiner to share printing, advertising and distribution functions
but remain editorially independent.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly's lawyer, Joseph M. Alioto, sought to show through
White's testimony and the introduction of confidential memos,
letters and e-mails that both The Chronicle and the Examiner are
currently profitable under the JOA and were planning to compete
head-to-head in 2005, when the JOA expires.
</P>
<P>
   The testimony by White, who was questioned by Alioto for more
than three hours, was filled with colorful revelations about
backroom maneuvering at The Chronicle and Examiner and power plays
at City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   White testified that he met Brown for lunch Aug. 30 _ several
weeks after the Chronicle sale to Hearst had been announced _ and
conveyed to the mayor that his support for the sale would result in
``more favorable treatment'' for the mayor in the Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he (Brown) was beating up on us,'' White wrote in an e-mail
describing the meeting to Hearst executives in New York, ``it would
be difficult being out there championing (Brown's) initiatives like
muni and the stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked by Alioto if he was ``horsetrading,'' White answered,
``Yes.'' But the publisher immediately qualified his answer, saying
that any favorable treatment would be in the Examiner's editorial
pages _ and not the paper's news pages.
</P>
<P>
   In an e-mail describing his lunch with the mayor to top Hearst
executives, White wrote: ``I asked him how I would justify to my
superiors in New York wanting to support him and cooperate with him
when he was seeming to go out of his way to make our lives
difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time Brown talked with White last year, he was running
for re-election as mayor against Reilly, a former political
consultant and wealthy San Francisco real estate investor.
</P>
<P>
   The Examiner endorsed Brown for mayor. White testified, however,
that the endorsement was based solely on the candidates' merits and
not linked to The Chronicle deal.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Hallings, the Hearst Corporation's attorney, argued in his
opening statement to Walker that Hearst can close the Examiner
because it is a failing newspaper. He said that without revenues
from the JOA, the Examiner would lose millions of dollars yearly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can shut it down,'' he said, under current antitrust law,
``or give it away.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We can certainly give it away with a subsidy,'' he said,
referring to Hearst's announcement in March that the corporation
would give the Fangs $66 million over three years to take over the
operation of the Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst has admitted that it offered the Fangs the subsidy after
no one stepped forward last year to buy the Examiner and to satisfy
U.S. Department of Justice concerns.
</P>
<P>
   But Alioto told Walker that Hearst knows that the Examiner will
fold after the subsidy runs out, leaving a Hearst-owned Chronicle
with a monopoly in San Francisco in violation of federal antitrust
laws.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst corporation can not claim the Examiner is failing, he
said, because last year it took $23 million in profits out of the
JOA and is projecting profits of $25 million in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   He argued that the Examiner and The Chronicle were preparing for
head-to head competition in 2005 when the JOA ends and that
antitrust laws require that such competition be preserved.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto questioned White closely about a number of internal
Hearst memos, e-mails and meetings early last year in which the
company told The Chronicle that it intended to shift the afternoon
Examiner to morning publication in 2005 _ or before _ and compete
directly with The Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   In one letter dated March 13, 1999, a Hearst Corp. executive,
George Irish wrote that White was sent to San Francisco in January
with the job of assuring that the Examiner will be in a strong
position in 2005, adding that they would acquire the best people
and content to ``give us a sustainable, competitive edge.''
</P>
<P>
   In a March e-mail outlining the Hearst's ``strategic
initiatives'' for competing with The Chronicle, White wrote that
the goal was: ``Strengthen the Examiner's franchise prior to 2005
in every possible way. Use every medium available. Seek every
partnership/alliance and affiliation that will hasten and
strengthen Hearst's presence in the Bay Area. Continue to
communicate Hearst's commitment for the long haul to (Chronicle
Publishing Chief Operating Officer John) Sias and the Chronicle.''
</P>
<P>
   One document described ``talking points'' for a meeting that
White and Irish scheduled in April to discuss the future of the two
papers with Sias.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know it is our intent to stay and publish, independent of
the (JOA),'' they planned to tell Sias.
</P>
<P>
   ``Were you telling the truth to Mr. Sias?'' Alioto asked.
</P>
<P>
   White answered that Alioto would have to ask Hearst
Corporation's Chief Executive Officer Frank Bennack. ``We wanted to
create that impression with Mr. Sias.''
</P>
<P>
   White conceded that he was assigned the role of coach to rally
the team at the Examiner and to try to hire the best columnists in
the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm out here to get (the staff) to run down the field against
tackles and guards twice their size.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that many of the moves were meant to bring The Chronicle
to the bargaining table so Hearst could negotiate buying the paper.
</P>
<P>
   He said that because the Examiner was less than one-quarter the
Chronicle's size, it faced ``extinction'' when the JOA ended. He
called it the ``blowfish'' strategy, meaning that Hearst was trying
to puff up large enough to scare the family that owns The Chronicle
into selling the paper.
</P>
<P>
   White also described the crazy political minefield he was
stepping through to complete The Chronicle deal.
</P>
<P>
   In August, he said, he received a ``fairly bizarre'' phone call
from Warren Hinckle, a columnist for the Independent. Hinckle put
on Jack Davis, the controversial and flamboyant political
strategist for Mayor Brown and a close friend of the Fang family.
</P>
<P>
   White quoted Davis as saying: ``I'll bet before this is over
there will be a lawsuit from an advertiser, a lawsuit from a
subscriber, and a lawsuit from a competitor.''
</P>
<P>
   White said he didn't recall feeling threatened, although in
later testimony he described it as a ``thinly veiled threat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was disjointed, from a noisy bar in the background. It was
kind of hard to paste it all together.''
</P>
<P>
   White is scheduled for cross-examination when the trial resumes
at the Federal Building in San Francisco Tuesday. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
