A3035 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v PM-BUDGET-NYT     05-02 2761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 PM-BUDGET-NYT 
 (sw) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For TUESDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Tuesday, May 2.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S.-TRADE (Undated) _ Two members of Congress were back
in Washington Monday after one of the most expensive lobbying
efforts ever undertaken by the Clinton administration, if measured
on a per-vote basis. Hoping to sway legislators who remain
undecided on whether to grant China permanent normal trade
relations, President Clinton set aside funds earlier this year to
fly wavering lawmakers to China where they could gauge trade and
human rights conditions for themselves. But when the group left
last week, there were only two undecided congressmen. So began the
education of Rep. Gregory Meeks, D-N.Y., and Rep. Ruben Hinojosa,
D-Texas. By Craig S. Smith.
</P>
<P>
   CHECHNYA-DOCTOR (Mozdok, Russia) _ When Dr. Hasan Baiyev was
summoned to his hospital in the Chechen town of Alkhan-Kala on Feb.
1, he quickly learned that it was not for an ordinary case. As
Russian troops tried to take the capital, Grozny, Chechen rebels
had begun on Jan. 31 to fight their way out. Now hundreds of
bloodied militants were waiting for treatment in Baiyev's village
southwest of Grozny. They included Shamil Basayev, the most
notorious of the Chechen warlords, who was wounded as he led his
fighters through a Russian minefield. After administering a local
anesthetic, Baiyev, a surgeon, amputated Basayev's right leg. And
soon after that, the rebels whisked their leader to safety in the
Caucasian mountains. Baiyev's life has not been the same since. By
Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-FISH (Listvyanka, Russia) _ Almost any resident of this
village can tick off the seemingly endless string of superlatives
about the great lake _ inland sea, really _ that laps insistently
against the town docks. Lake Baikal is the biggest, the oldest, by
far the deepest, the clearest lake on earth. But press a resident
to say what he loves most about Baikal, and he may cast his lot
with the nondescript, gray, oily, foot-long fish that dwells
therein. Siberians love the lowly omul. They love it fried, dried,
smoked, baked, grilled, salted, stuffed, with internals and without
internals, with and without scales. Residents of the eastern shore
even like it slightly decayed _ ``with odor,'' they call it. By
Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT14,15) have been sent to NYT photo clients.
Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-ENVOY (United Nations) _ On the wall behind Ambassador
Volkan Vural's desk at the Turkish mission here is a reproduction
of a 1923 Time magazine cover featuring Mustafa Kemal Ataturk, who
forged modern Turkey out of the wreckage of the Ottoman Empire.
This summer, Vural is scheduled to return to Ankara to take up a
new post that presents a challenge almost as daunting. His job will
be to demonstrate to the European Union that Turkey merits
membership and to convince his countrymen that joining the club is
worth the painful admission price. By Douglas Frantz.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-POLLUTION-CREDITS (Albany, N.Y.) _ The New York state
legislature has passed a bill that would radically reduce the
amount of air pollution that has for years drifted from Midwestern
and Southern states into New York. The bill would bar New York
companies from selling pollution credits they earned by cleaning up
their own smokestacks to polluters in other states. The legislation
directly challenges the 1990 Clean Air Act, which set up a
marketplace in which companies could trade the right to pollute in
the form of credits, as a commodity. Gov. George Pataki is expected
to sign the measure, which would make New York the first state to
ban these exchanges. By Raymond Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT-CENSUS (Detroit) _ For a decade, Detroit has feared that
it could become the first American city of more than 1 million
people to have its population fall below that number. The city,
long dogged by its image as a rusting auto giant, barely made it
over the million marker in 1990, and then only after a recount.
Staying at a million is a point of pride. Census anxiety runs so
deep here that Mayor Dennis Archer began drafting his battle plan
four years ago. By Nichole M. Christian.
</P>
<P>
   NY-LEVY-SCHOOLS (New York) _ If the school system's top
officials did not have enough to worry about, with Harold Levy, the
interim chancellor, pushing them to be more efficient and
accountable, now he wants them to be more thoughtful, too. Music
and poetry are among the more esoteric parts of his plan to raise
the internal level of debate on education policy, he says. That
means focusing less on administrative minutiae, and adding
intellectual rigor to the often tedious board meetings. Some board
members are not thrilled. By Abby Goodnough.
</P>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH-DEVELOP (Pittsburgh) _ For this city's strong-willed
mayor, 61 old downtown buildings and 125 merchants in them are
standing in the way of the downtrodden area's renewal and should be
torn down. But the National Trust calls his plan `the most
wrongheaded revitalization proposal to appear anywhere in this
country in the last 30 years.'' In these economic boom times, many
downtowns are undergoing revitalization, but none are creating as
big a political fight. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT19-28) have been sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphic and locator map have been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
