   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DISNEY-TIMEWARNER (Undated) _ Millions of television viewers
found themselves without access to ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire'' and many other popular television programs Monday as
the country's two biggest media companies, Time Warner and Walt
Disney, fought over the cable television rights to stations owned
by Disney's ABC network. The dispute has its roots in an argument
over how much money Disney should receive for carrying its channels
on Time Warner's cable systems, but it involves larger issues
dealing with the distribution of media content _ including the
longstanding antipathy between the cable and broadcast industry,
the growing competition between cable and satellite companies and
Disney's opposition to the proposed merger between America Online
and Time Warner. It also concerns how much power the new company
will wield in a television industry that is merged with the
Internet. By Bill Carter.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ Fighting to defeat the
government's proposal to break the company in two, Microsoft plans
to ask the trial judge next week for broad authority to obtain
hundreds of pages of government records on the case, and for
permission to bring a collection of witnesses to court who will
argue that the proposal is unwarranted and out of bounds. By Joel
Brinkley and Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-INTERNET (Jakarta, Indonesia) _ In a country dominated
by corporate dynasties, Edward Soeryadjaya is famous as the scion
who broke his family's bank and cost his family the car company his
father founded in 1957, Astra International. Now, Soeryadjaya has
returned to the corporate stage as a high-technology entrepreneur
planning to build a stable of dot-coms and turn Jakarta's old
airport into Indonesia's Silicon Valley. In the process, he wants
not only to resurrect a fallow property investment but also to
prove that he was an unwitting pawn of politics. By Wayne Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   MARKETS-MERGE (Frankfurt, Germany) _ In the most dramatic step
yet toward creation of a pan-European stock market, the London and
Frankfurt stock exchanges plan to announce a merger on Wednesday,
according to officials familiar with the discussions. The deal
would unite Europe's two biggest securities exchanges, creating an
entity that would far outweigh the alliance proposed between the
Paris, Brussels and Amsterdam exchanges. By Edmund Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   BEN&AMP;JERRYS-MARKETPLACE (New York) _ When the founders of Ben &AMP;
Jerry's Homemade Inc. finally agreed to sell their company to
Unilever last month, people involved in the talks credited the
relationship that had developed between the founders and a Unilever
executive, Richard Goldstein, who heads the company's North
American business. On Monday, as the three gathered in New York to
discuss Ben &AMP; Jerry's future, there was an element of awkwardness
in the air. And no wonder: Now that the deal is done, Goldstein
isn't going to be around anymore. By Constance L. Hays.
</P>
<P>
   CHICKEN-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ Cliff Freeman and Partners _ known
for offbeat commercials like ``Where's the Beef?'' for Wendy's
International and ``Pizza! Pizza!'' for Little Caesar's Pizza _ is
now serving up a television campaign for Church's Fried Chicken
that comically depicts the gritty dinner hour of working-class
families, with a sarcastic twist.
</P>
<P>
   DISNEY-REACT (Undated) _ Looking at how viewers in metropolitan
New York, Los Angles and Houston are reacting to the blackout of
their ABC stations.
</P>
