<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE TIMES (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FIRST-HUMANS (undated) _ Genesis mentions three of Adam and
Eve's children: Cain, Abel and Seth. But geneticists, by tracing
the DNA patterns found in people throughout the world, have now
identified lineages descended from 10 sons of a genetic Adam and 20
daughters of Eve. The human genome is turning out to be a rich
archive for historians and pre-historians. Explorers of the
archives have recently found evidence for a prehistoric human
migration from Europe to North America; identified the people who
seem closest to the ancestral human population; and given weight to
whispers that Thomas Jefferson fathered a family with his slave
mistress Sally Hemings. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PROSTATE-TEST (Undated) _ Mayor Giuliani urged all men to
have the P.S.A. test after announcing that he had prostate cancer.
But experts are divided on the value of the test for the
slow-advancing cancer. In some cases, the test forces men to endure
painful therapy that is not always merited. But in other cases, the
test clearly allows early intervention to prevent what is some
cases becomes deadly. By Kenneth Chang.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-QUANTUM-PHYSICS (Undated) _ Experiments described in three
forthcoming papers in the journal Physical Review Letters show how
Einstein's thought experiments on quantum mechanics missed their
mark. The studies showed again that that measuring one particle
could instantaneously change the properties of another particle, no
matter how far apart they were (known as entanglement) was true.
But it also demonstrated that the process might be used to create
unbreakable codes for the secure transmission of bank transactions
and diplomatic communiques. By James Glanz.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ARMPIT-EFFECT (Undated) _ Experiments in golden hamsters
show strong evidence for the ``armpit effect,'' in which animals,
and perhaps even humans, screen out potential breeding partners,
eliminating by smell those whose odors are closest to their own.
Thus, they eliminate possible mates from the same genetic lines and
improve the chance of advancing their own genes. Experiments also
seem to show that the animals do it based on their own scents, not
those of family members they were raised with. By Carol Kaesuk
Yoon.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FROZEN-METEORITE (Undated) _ A meteorite that was
refrigerated by a quick-thinking local resident may give scientists
fresh insights into the primordial solar system. Although the fiery
journey through the atmosphere heated up the outside of the
surviving rocks, the inside would have remained cold, giving
researchers hope that delicate organic molecules trapped within the
meteorite remained intact. By Kenneth Chang
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PARTICLE-PHYSICS (Undated) _ The United States, long a
leader in particle physics, is losing its edge in the field, with
the demise of the superconducting super collider. Soon, serious
American physicists will need to travel to Geneva or elsewhere to
conduct cutting edge research, and this at a time when the essence
of dark matter is being discovered, giving scientists insight to
the beginning of time. By Michael Riordan.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ News and notes on science: Items on vinyl
discs can be used for X-ray microscopes, the number of discordant
sounds that render a song incomprehensible, the Newton's
gravitational constant. By Henry Fountain.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FUCHS-ECONOMICS (Undated) _ A conversation with Dr. Victor
Fuchs, an economist who also sees himself as a humanist, a person
who is interested in values and who inquires how economics can help
people to think about social problems and arrive at solutions.
Economics, he explains, is about choice. It asks how people respond
to incentives, how they respond to constraints. And so, Fuchs
observes, ``economics is the quintessential policy science.'' He
discusses managed care and proposed changes. By Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BREAST-GENE (Undated) _ The mechanism by which the BRCA gene
works. By Denise Grady.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ELIAN-PSYCH (Undated) _ Long after the courts untangle Elian
Gonzalez' future, mental health professionals may still be
pondering the meaning of their own involvement in the Cuban boy's
American odyssey. Psychiatrists and psychologists have taken an
active part, advising government officials, voicing their opinions
on talk shows and in news accounts, escorting Elian on his plane
ride to Washington and even, in one case, assisting Diane Sawyer in
her interview with him on ``Good Morning America.'' By Erica Goode.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DOMINO-TRANSPLANTS (Undated) Domino organ transplants are
just beginning to occur in the United States, with one patient
receiving organs but passing on others because of a rare condition.
Only a handful have ever been done in this country, while about 40
have been done around the world, mostly in Europe. By Eric
Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ The personal health column: Some
doctors are getting more personal in taking medical histories, and
this is a positive sign. But still other questions need to be asked
about healthful habits like exercise, diet and stress. By Jane E.
Brody.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ A science question answered: Why do cats
periodically run around madly as if they were chasing a fire
engine? By C. Claiborne Ray.
</P>
