r a BC-CABLE-ABC-LADN     05-02 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CABLE-ABC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGRY VIEWERS MISS SHOWS DUE TO DISNEY-TIME WARNER DISPUTE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(EDITORS: Los Angeles Daily News Staff Writer David Kronke
contributed to this story.) 
By VALERIE KUKLENSKI 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ About 350,000 homes in the Los Angeles area lost
their ABC and local KABC programming Monday in the Disney-vs.-Time
Warner dispute, missing out on the second part of ``Arabian
Nights,'' the celebrity studded ``Who Wants To Be a Millionaire''
and other popular programs.
</P>
<P>
   In the west San Fernando Valley, about 120,000 subscribers were
affected by the blackout that comes just a few days into the highly
competitive -- and commercially critical -- May ratings sweeps
period. Another 20,000 were affected in Canyon Country.
</P>
<P>
   While frustrated viewers blamed both companies, executives and
attorneys for two of the most powerful companies in the
entertainment industry blamed each other while developing legal and
public relations strategies.
</P>
<P>
   No one from either camp was willing to predict how long the
standoff might continue. But it appeared likely to be protracted
since both the Disney-owned KABC (Channel 7) and Time Warner cable
system planned end runs to get the network signal back into homes.
</P>
<P>
   Starting Wednesday, KABC will offer free DirecTV satellite
dishes and installation to all Time Warner subscribers in its
viewing area ``so they can get off Time Warner forever,'' said
Arnold J. Kleiner, the affiliate's president and general manager.
</P>
<P>
   When the network's Houston affiliate made that offer last
February, 18,000 subscribers accepted. Details of the Los Angeles
rebate plan had yet to be ironed out late Monday.
</P>
<P>
   KABC also teamed with its sister radio station, 790 KABC-AM, in
a simulcast of ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' Monday and
tonight. Selected ABC programming will be available on the radio
station, as well as the TV station's Web site, www.kabc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner, meanwhile, is offering free switches to customers
that will enable them to switch to an antenna to watch ABC
programming.
</P>
<P>
   The two media powerhouses have been mired in a nationwide
contract dispute since late last year over how much Time Warner
must pay for Disney's networks -- including ABC, owned affiliates
such as KABC and WABC in New York, ESPN and the Disney Channel --
and other terms. The existing agreement lapsed in December but had
been extended several times.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, ABC ran a message during prime time saying Time
Warner would continue to carry ABC programming through May 24 --
the end of sweeps -- while the issues are resolved.
</P>
<P>
   But Time Warner discontinued its ABC feed just after midnight
and put up a slate advising viewers that ``Disney-owned Channel 7
has pulled its programming off of Time Warner'' and, to further
insult its adversary, said it will be carrying C-SPAN2 in its
place.
</P>
<P>
   KABC's Kleiner said that statement is false.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're telling our viewers they need to call Time Warner to
complain,'' he said. ``Time Warner took us off and only Time Warner
can put us back on.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Time Warner Communications spokesman Michael Luftman
blamed Disney, saying it would have been illegal for the cable
operator to continue to carry ABC without an agreement in effect.
</P>
<P>
   Angry or confused viewers who called KABC Monday were
transferred to a recorded message stating the network's position
and encouraging them to voice their complaints to Time Warner, the
nation's largest cable service. At Time Warner's Chatsworth office,
the customer service line was chronically busy. When calls did make
it through, they were passed to a recording and a long wait for the
chance to talk with a real person.
</P>
<P>
   William Croasdale, a veteran broadcast advertising buyer with
Western International Media, said, ``What happens will depend on
how ABC fares with the overnight ratings. If there is a marked
falloff in viewers, and most of them are in major metropolitan
areas, I think you'll see a quick settlement. If not, this thing
could drag out for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Miereanu, a travel agent and Time Warner subscriber who
lives in Woodland Hills, is one of the viewers who will affect
those numbers. ``We happen to be a Nielsen family, and it's
tough,'' she said. ``Boy, is it going to be skewed.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she had hopes of watching the celebrity ``Millionaire''
shows as well as the conclusion of ``Arabian Nights.'' She also
routinely watches KABC's ``Eyewitness News,'' ``20/20'' and ``Good
Morning America.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just annoying that the consumer is being left in the
lurch, as usual,'' Miereanu said.
</P>
<P>
   Disney chief Michael Eisner was the target of Beth Locicero's
ire. The 47-year-old Northridge waitress was furious and vowed to
carry a sign through her neighborhood reading ``Boycott Disney.''
Locicero said she is annoyed about having to unplug her cable jack
and rehook her antenna to watch her favorite soap opera.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many senior citizens, how many children, how many people
in hospitals will have to crawl to the TV to get Channel 7?'' she
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-00 0139EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
