u s BC-BBN-METS-GIANTS-NYT &LR;      05-02 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-GIANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS CRUSH METS, 10-3 
</HEADLINE>
   By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It was the kind of inning the Mets fear with
Bill Pulsipher, the kind when the left-hander allows little
problems to morph into bigger ones.
</P>
<P>
   Pulsipher was making his season debut with the Mets on Monday
night, joining the rotation until Bobby J. Jones can come back from
a calf strain. One reason the Mets promoted their former top
prospect was because he had shown better concentration in his
starts at Class AAA Norfolk; he could recover from adversity.
</P>
<P>
   But the San Francisco Giants beat Pulsipher on Monday night,
10-3, at the new Pacific Bell Park, and they did not have to try
too hard. Trailing 1-0 in the fourth inning, Pulsipher walked the
Giants' third and fourth hitters, Barry Bonds and Jeff Kent. After
a sacrifice bunt and a run-scoring single, Pulsipher hit J.T. Snow
to load the bases.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Estalella then singled in two runs, and as Pulsipher
returned to the mound after backing up the plate, catcher Todd
Pratt patted him, offering encouragement. Pulsipher stalked ahead,
without acknowledging it. The Giants starter Shawn Estes squared to
bunt, but Pulsipher walked him on four pitches, all of which missed
the strike zone badly.
</P>
<P>
   That was it for Pulsipher, who allowed four runs on three hits
and four walks in three and one-third innings. He was making just
his second start for the Mets since 1995, a promising season that
ended when elbow problems shut him down. That was ominous for
Pulsipher, who was then 21 years old. He would miss most of the
next two seasons while attempting to come back from elbow surgery.
He made just one start for the Mets in 1998 before they traded him
to Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   Pulsipher's counterpart, Estes, allowed two earned runs in seven
innings to beat the Mets for the fifth time in seven decisions. But
a impressive as he was, Giants fans will remember the game for
something else.
</P>
<P>
   Facing Rich Rodriguez in the sixth inning, the Giants star Barry
Bonds lofted a towering fly that landed in San Francisco Bay, 418
feet from home plate. It was the first ball hit into the water
outside Pacific Bell Park, and it touched off a celebration among
the 40,930 fans, who stood and screamed until Bonds popped from the
dugout, waving his arms to acknowledge the cheers.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Figone, a groundskeeper at the Giants' former home, the
blustery 3Com Park, was the luckiest fan of all. Powering a dinghy
decorated with a Giants flag, Figone outraced a motorboat to the
ball, swooping the prize with a net as the boats bumped together.
Later, Figone raised a bottle of champagne, toasting his fortune.
</P>
<P>
   That homer put the Giants up by 9-0, but the Mets had managed
some celebrating of their own before the game unraveled.
</P>
<P>
   With two outs in the third inning, center fielder Jay Payton
raced to his right in pursuit of a deep fly by Bill Mueller. In
front of the 382-foot sign in the left-center-field gap, Payton
leaped and stretched his glove just above that of a fan, his
shoulder crashing into the padded wall and he made the catch.
Payton then grabbed the ball with his right hand, holding it aloft
in excitement as he jogged from the warning track.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets were playing the game with only one healthy catcher; to
make room for Pulsipher, they had optioned reserve catcher Vance
Wilson to Class AAA Norfolk. Mike Piazza, who hyperextended his
right elbow in a home plate collision on Friday, was still feeling
discomfort on Monday and was planning to begin throwing again on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had emergency options _ Matt Franco, Melvin Mora, Jon
Nunnally and Todd Zeile _ and for a moment it seemed they would
need one. With the bases loaded in the fourth, first baseman Zeile
fielded a grounder and fired it home to catcher Pratt, who was
touching home plate with his right foot for the force out.
</P>
<P>
   Snow, trying to score from third, slid hard into Pratt's knees,
knocking him off his feet for a hard landing on his backside. Pratt
got up and motioned toward Snow, barking at him, and the umpire
Mark Wegner quickly came between the players as both benches
emptied.
</P>
<P>
   But no punches were thrown and Pratt limped away from the fray.
He was examined by a trainer and stayed in, inviting heavy booing
from a crowd that has reason to be enthusiastic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
