<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-INDIANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES NIP INDIANS, 2-1 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND, May1 _ Opportunity is running out for Shane Spencer,
like grains of sand plunging through an hourglass. He does not know
how much time he has left to show he can play, but he has been
around the Yankees long enough to know that any losing streak leads
to change.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer is building credentials, however. His two-run double
produced the Yankees' runs as they edged Cleveland, 2-1, on Monday
night at Jacobs Field. Ramiro Mendoza disguised his lack of raw
stuff, deceiving the Indians for six innings before the Yankees'
bullpen took over in seventh. Rain delayed the start of the game
for 2 hours 44 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Adding another to their list of dramatic victories, the Yankees
escaped a two-on, no-out situation in the bottom of the ninth.
David Justice led off with a single and moved to third when Jim
Thome doubled into the right-field corner. With Alex Ramirez in as
a pinch-runner for Thome, Mariano Rivera struck out Richie Sexson
swinging for the first out.
</P>
<P>
   Travis Fryman, who was 3 for 3, fell behind no balls and two
strikes before lining out to left field. Ramirez took off toward
third, assuming the ball would drop, and was doubled off second
when Spencer threw to Derek Jeter to give Rivera a very shaky
eighth save. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Indians loaded the bases against Jeff Nelson and Rivera in
the bottom of the eighth, but with two outs, Rivera retired Manny
Ramirez on a weak grounder; Ramirez is 0 for 10 in his career
against the Yankees' closer. The Yankees' bullpen has an earned run
average of just 1.44 over the last 10 games.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' record will go a long way toward determining how
much time Ricky Ledee and Spencer are given to prove themselves,
Manager Joe Torre said before Monday night's game. The Yankees have
won two-thirds of their 24 games, and although they have not played
all that well, they can afford to wait before determining what
trades they need to make to augment their roster for the final
months of the regular season and the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Ledee's average is plummeting far below .200, a decline that is
resulting in a grimace on his face, his head hanging down.
Spencer's average has been hovering above .200, but he seems much
less bothered than Ledee does about the uncertainty of his
situation _ not surprising, one member of the organization
remarked, for Spencer spent almost a decade in the minors
overcoming the perception that he was not good enough to play in
the majors. There were several seasons in his career when he faced
the possibility of being released if he did not produce.
</P>
<P>
   Torre maintains that nothing has changed for Spencer and Ledee,
but there has been a subtle adjustment in how Torre is handling the
two. Ledee was the left fielder and Spencer the designated hitter
for much of the first month. But last week, Torre began using
Spencer in left and Ledee at designated hitter so that he would be
in a better position to counter a move if the opposing manager
called on a left-handed reliever to face Ledee late in games; this
way, Torre could use someone like Jim Leyritz to pinch-hit for
Ledee without worrying about who would play the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   If Ledee were hitting the way he did at the end of spring
training, however, then Torre would not be pinch-hitting for him.
</P>
<P>
   Back to playing in the field, Spencer had two hits Sunday,
including a two-run homer, and on Monday night he propelled the
Yankees into the lead. Jaret Wright, nearly traded to San Diego for
Sterling Hitchcock on the eve of the season opener, had an
overpowering fastball, and he shut out the Yankees through four
innings, matching Mendoza.
</P>
<P>
   Tino Martinez lined a single leading off the fifth, however, and
Jorge Posada dumped a double down the left-field line and into the
corner, Martinez stopping at third. Wright challenged Spencer,
throwing a 98-mile-an-hour fastball that Spencer swung through to
make the count no balls and two strikes. Spencer fouled off a
fastball and two sliders as the count went to 1-2.
</P>
<P>
   Wright tried another slider, a pitch that confounded Spencer
last year. Spencer pulled a grounder down the third-base line,
hesitating for a split second, thinking it might go foul. And this
is where the Yankees got a little lucky.
</P>
<P>
   Fryman, the Cleveland third baseman, moved over to field the
ball as Martinez sprinted homeward, and Spencer's grounder hit the
base and bounced over Fryman's head. Martinez and Posada scored,
and Spencer rambled into second base, fortunate only because he had
given himself a chance with his persistent at-bat against Wright.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
