r a BC-DRACULA-BRADBURY-LADN     05-02 0501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRACULA-BRADBURY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHOR RAY BRADBURY TESTIFIES FOR HIS MENTOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JESSE HIESTAND 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If not for ``Dr. Acula,'' legendary science
fiction author Ray Bradbury testified Monday he might never have
penned such classics as ``The Martian Chronicles'' and ``Fahrenheit
451.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradbury said he was 17 when he met Forrest J. Ackerman -- later
known as ``Dr. Acula'' -- who invited him to join a group of
science fiction devotees at Clifton's Cafeteria in downtown Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't be sitting here today if I didn't meet him when I
was in high school in 1937. I was a man who was a writer but had no
place to go,'' Bradbury told the Van Nuys Superior Court jury.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a recent illness, Bradbury made his way by wheelchair
into the courtroom to testify on behalf of Ackerman, who is suing a
former employer for trademark infringement and defamation. The
civil suit centers on the cult magazine Famous Monsters of
Filmland, which Ackerman edited from 1958 to 1982, signing
editorials as ``Dr. Acula.''
</P>
<P>
   Ackerman seeks to defend his legacy as the real ``Dr. Acula,''
but the magazine's new owner, Ray Ferry of North Hills, has
insisted he owns all of the magazine's trademark phrases.
</P>
<P>
   In court Monday, Bradbury backed Ackerman's claim that he has
used the pen name ``Dr. Acula'' for some 60 years and is inexorably
linked to the character.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is it -- there's no one else in the world that represents
the totality of science fiction and fantasy,'' Bradbury said.
</P>
<P>
   The 79-year-old author said he was surprised anyone would
challenge Ackerman's association with ``Dr. Acula,'' a play on
Dracula.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wouldn't dare -- I'd get after them,'' Bradbury said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradbury said he has long associated Ackerman with ``Dr. Acula''
because the two men have joked for decades over how to pronounce
it.
</P>
<P>
   As for Ackerman's claim that his battle with Ferry has damaged
his reputation, Bradbury said he has heard no feedback in the
industry about that.
</P>
<P>
   Bradbury portrayed Ackerman as a tireless champion of all things
ghoulish, especially as caretaker of the world's largest collection
of science fiction and horror memorabilia, now at his Los Feliz
house.
</P>
<P>
   Bradbury said he was a dirt-poor newspaperboy in 1937 when he
posted a note on the bulletin board of a Hollywood science fiction
bookstore.
</P>
<P>
   To the amazement of the Los Angeles High School student,
Ackerman saw the note and wrote back, inviting him to Clifton's.
</P>
<P>
   The imagination-rich teen immediately went to work writing for
Ackerman and two years later, with Ackerman's financial backing,
launched his own magazine, Futuria Fantasia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helped establish me among simple fans -- people who just
love writing,'' Bradbury said.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, Ackerman also acted as his literary agent. ``My
stories were not very good, but he tried his best and achieved some
success,'' Bradbury said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-00 0151EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000502.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 01:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3044 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLA     05-02 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATLANTA ROCKS DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Los Angeles Dodgers bolstered their offensive
numbers against Cincinnati and Florida, but until the powers of
balance change in the National League, the measuring stick is the
Atlanta Braves.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the Dodgers' offense doesn't measure up well to the best
pitching staff of the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   After getting shut down during a three-game sweep last week in
Atlanta, the Dodgers generated little offense in a 2-1 loss in the
opening of a three-game series Monday at Dodger Stadium, but the
28,790 in attendance let Braves closer John Rocker know exactly how
they felt.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker pitched the ninth inning for his sixth save and survived
a few scary incidents. On his run in from the bullpen, several fans
threw things at Rocker, just missing him.
</P>
<P>
   And with two outs in the ninth a fan ran onto the field, stopped
between first and second base, and gestured toward Rocker in a foul
manner. He was escorted away by security.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Elster then kept the game going by singling in Todd
Hundley to pull the Dodgers within 2-1. But Geronimo Berroa struck
out as Rocker recorded his sixth save.
</P>
<P>
   It brought an end to the Dodgers' three-game winning streak
while Atlanta's won a club record 14 in a row.
</P>
<P>
   An offense that scored 25 runs in sweeping three games from
Florida over the weekend managed six singles against the Braves.
Kevin Millwood recorded the win, allowing five hits in seven
innings, and Rudy Seanez pitched a scoreless eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta got a third-inning homer from Quilvio Veras' to
right-center with one out. Other than that, Dodgers right-hander
Eric Gagne was brilliant in facing the Braves for the second time
in five days.
</P>
<P>
   Gagne's looking for his first win of the season to go against to
losses. He's allowed five homers in four starts. Gagne yielded four
hits, walked two and struck out six in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers reliever Matt Herges saw his streak of shutout ball
stopped at 15 innings when the Braves made it 2-0 in the top of the
eighth. Of course, Herges wasn't aided by the Dodgers defense.
</P>
<P>
   Veras led off the eighth with a single and should have been
erased on Andruw Jones' grounder to second. But Veras stopped
running so he wouldn't be tagged out by Mark Grudzielanek, who in
turn threw to first to get Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Karros' throw to second was late and Veras was safe.
Chipper Jones lined to short for the second out, but Herges looked
like he could get out of the inning when Andres Galarraga took a
close pitch with two strikes.
</P>
<P>
   It was called a ball and Galarraga grounded a ball that Adrian
Beltre fielded deep behind third base. Karros couldn't handle
Beltre's errant throw, which bounced behind the bag and allowed
Veras to score. Beltre's team-leading eighth error allowed the run
to score. Herges pitched a perfect ninth and is yet to allow an
earned run in 17 innings.
</P>
<P>
   It's the second time in five days Millwood bested Gagne.
Millwood (3-0) allowed five hits and an unearned run in beating the
Dodgers last Wednesday in Atlanta. When the Dodgers were swept in
Atlanta, it came after a 1-0 loss to the Mets but on the heels of
scoring 36 runs in a three-game sweep of Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Momentum didn't carry over last time, and it certainly didn't
against Millwood this time, either.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers had runners in scoring position in each of the first
four innings but couldn't deliver the hit to score a run. In the
first inning, Shawn Green was picked off first with Gary Sheffield
on third and two out. An inning later back-to-back one-out singles
by Todd Hundley and Adrian Beltre were wasted when Millwood struck
out Kevin Elster and Gagne.
</P>
<P>
   Veras, who drove in the lone run in the Braves' 1-0 win over the
Dodgers last Tuesday, gave the Braves a 1-0 lead in the top of the
third with his second homer of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Millwood was in trouble in the third inning again as
Grudzielanek singled with one out and Gary Sheffield walked, but
Green struck out and Karros flied out to center to end the inning.
It was the beginning of string in which Millwood retired 10
consecutive batters. He didn't allow another hit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-00 0152EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
