   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   KENT-STATE (Undated) _ On May 4, 1970, National Guardsmen at
Kent State University shot and killed Jeffrey Glenn Miller, Allison
B. Krause, William K. Schroeder and Sandra Lee Scheuer. The
shootings marked the end of four lives, the end of an impromptu
demonstration against the Vietnam War, and the beginning, for
Professor Jerry M. Lewis, of a life wrapped around the legacy of
crazy force, a blurred picture of shouting teenagers caught on the
government's own killing ground. Lewis was 33 years old, a
sociology professor on campus. Now, he is coordinating close to 60
events marking the anniversary of the Kent State killings. By
EDVINS BEITIKS.
</P>
<P>
   GAY-MURDER (Sacramento, Calif.) _ When someone called Robert
Rosenkrantz a ``faggot'' at his high school graduation party and
exposed his homosexuality to his father, the 18-year-old went into
a panic, bought an Uzi and, a week later, put 10 bullets into the
man who outed him. Now, after 15 years in prison for second-degree
murder, Rosenkrantz's case is the center of yet another political
fight between California Gov. Gray Davis and fellow Democrats in
the Legislature, many of whom believe Rosenkrantz should be set
free after becoming a model prisoner. By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   ROSIE-RIVETER (Richmond, Calif.) _ She wore a red polka-dot
bandanna, flexed her biceps and proclaimed, ``We Can Do It!'' She
inspired millions of women to work on the home front during World
War II, graced postage stamps and posed as a cover girl for the
Smithsonian magazine. Her name is Rosie the Riveter, a character
immortalized by posters supporting the war effort and a wartime
song by the same name. A new monument pays tribute to Rosie _ or
rather, to the women whose work at home was vital to the war
effort. By PETER PHOTIKOE.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BREAST-CANCER (Delmar, N.Y.) _ Mara Ginsberg didn't waste any
time wondering ``why me?'' when she was diagnosed with breast
cancer in 1996. Since then, she has beat her cancer, quit her job
as a lawyer, and started To Life!, a vocal advocacy group for women
and their families affected by breast cancer. By SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT(``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-GEPPETTO (Undated) _ Drew Carey, ABC's most prominent face
before Regis Philbin came along, proves he's still the network's
most versatile performer in a ``Wonderful World of Disney'' musical
production of ``Geppetto.'' And, yes, Carey can in fact carry a
tune. By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   DRAMA-REVIEW-BLONDE (New York) _ ``It isn't what I do, but how I
do it,'' Mae West used to say. ``It isn't what I say, but how I say
it, and how I look when I do it and say it.'' Claudia Shear doesn't
follow that dictum very well in ``Dirty Blonde,'' her popular new
play about the bawdiest of American stage and screen legends. Which
is all to the good. By ROBERT HURWITT.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   EXAMINER-SALE (San Francisco) _ The publisher of Hearst Corp.'s
San Francisco Examiner testified that he offered Mayor Willie Brown
favorable editorials in exchange for the mayor's support of
Hearst's plan to buy the San Francisco Chronicle. By SETH
ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PAN-AM-GAMES (San Antonio) _ The Brazilian city of Rio de
Janeiro, known for its seaside beauty, romance and party spirit,
will compete against San Antonio for the right to host the 2007 Pan
American Games. By JERRY BRIGGS.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Like most Americans, for weeks
I've been avoiding thinking about Al Gore and George W. Bush. On
the whole, I'd rather think about Cream of Wheat or rice pudding.
But suddenly, out of the mushiness of the two presumptive nominees'
presumptive campaign (that is, we presume there's a campaign)
appears an intelligent, strong-willed, articulate woman. By ROB
MORSE.
</P>
