<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOYS OF DUCT TAPE  
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Being home-repair impaired, my favorite tool is, and always has
been, duct tape.
</P>
<P>
   If I'm too lazy or too stupid to fix something right, which is
most of the time, I simply cover the problem with duct tape. This
signals to my wife that the task is ``over my head'' and that it's
time, once again, to consult the yellow pages.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, by sheer accident, my duct-tape repairs work. While
hanging Christmas lights last year, I inadvertently created a
ganglion of extension cords so heavy it threatened to pull down all
the lights. By cleverly spinning a few turns of duct tape around
the cords, the gutter, the chimney and possibly the pug dog, I was
able to keep the lights aloft.
</P>
<P>
   (The problem came later when I tried to peel off the duct tape,
one of the stickiest substances known to man. I wound up having to
use scissors and cutting the wires of several expensive sets of
icicle lights. The duct tape, I'm happy to report, is still
intact.)
</P>
<P>
   There are dozens of sites devoted to duct-tape use on the World
Wide Web and authors Tim Nyberg and Jim Berg have published three
books on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Besides hanging Christmas lights, you can use duct tape to fix a
shoe, a raincoat, a lawn chair or a seat cushion. It's good for
hurricane protection, splinting a finger and removing hair. The
fashion set might use duct tape for a dress form, an emergency
necktie or as a particularly daring type of thong swimsuit. (Refer
to earlier section on hair removal.)
</P>
<P>
   But of the hundreds of duct-tape usages that I've seen, none
matches the creativity employed by Gemini Wink, 26, of Louisville,
KY. While visiting friends in Tampa, Wink set out into a nearby
swamp to photograph alligators. Naturally, being a guy, he brought
along a roll of duct tape that he planned to use like bread crumbs
to mark his trail.
</P>
<P>
   Incredible as it may sound, this strategy didn't work and Wink
became lost in waist-high water with night falling.
</P>
<P>
   Using the kind of ingenuity that only veteran duct-tape users
possess, Wink clambered 40 feet up a tree and taped himself to the
trunk to avoid being eaten by alligators.
</P>
<P>
   (It is a well-known fact that alligators hate the taste of duct
tape, even when it is wrapped around a succulent young tourist from
Louisville. I think the stuff gets stuck between their teeth. The
duct tape, that is.)
</P>
<P>
   But duct tape or no duct tape, sleep comes hard when you're
taped to the trunk of a tree 40-feet above swampy ground teeming
with alligators.
</P>
<P>
   Wink's yells for help were heard by someone at a nearby house
who called sheriff's deputies. Using a helicopter and police dogs,
Wink was finally located and freed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll definitely visit again, but I'll probably stay out of the
swamps,'' Wink told the Tampa Tribune.
</P>
<P>
   Or at least remember to bring along a bigger roll of duct tape.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. The Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-00 1119EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000502.0045 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 11:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3181 &Cx1f; ttg-z
u a BC-BROWN-COMPUTER-COLUMN     05-02 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROWN-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK EXPLAINS COMPUTER MYSTERIES  
</HEADLINE>
   By LONNIE BROWN   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're the type who does poorly with a computer, but does
well when reading a textbook, there may be hope lurking in
``Computer Friendly!''
</P>
<P>
   This 96-page book is written in easy-to-understand language. It
shuns computer terms until it can explain what they mean to the
reader.
</P>
<P>
   Every so often, it has a little exercise so readers will know if
they're getting things right. One example: ``When would you use the
following options? Shut down; restart; stand by.''
</P>
<P>
   If you can correctly answer those situations, know how to remove
and copy files, and can change desktop options, you'll probably
find Computer Friendly a little too friendly for your skill level.
</P>
<P>
   If, on the other hand, you'd like to make better use of the
control panel _ or understand why it's there in the first place _
Computer Friendly can provide the guidance to find out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The course assumes the reader never had any computer
experience,'' said a publicist for the author, Raymond Steinbacher.
He's a 34-year-old Web page designer and former manager of a
software department for a retail chain. While selling software one
day, Steinbacher found himself talking to Ernest Weckesser,
president of Green Tree Press Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``Raymond combined the two elements of genuine helpfulness I'd
been seeking for years: simple explanations and plain English,''
wrote Weckesser in the forward to the book published by Green Tree.
``It was just a matter of time until I realized that here was the
one guy most qualified to write and develop a truly basic computer
course; something we'd been wanting to publish here at Green Tree
for several years.''
</P>
<P>
   The book was published in February 1999 and has sold nearly
500,000 copies. It's available directly from the publisher for
$15.95, shipping included. For more information: Green Tree Press,
3603 W. 12th St., Erie, Pa. 16505. Tollfree: 800-834-3888.
</P>
<P>
   HOAX BUSTER
</P>
<P>
   No, it isn't true that the Federal Communications Commission is
going to end religious broadcasting on radio and television. No, it
is not true that you need to forward the e-mail about Petition
Number 2493 to all the people you know.
</P>
<P>
   Any time you see the words ``to all the people you know,'' or
``to as many people as possible,'' or ``everyone in your address
book,'' think: Hoax.
</P>
<P>
   This hoax about the FCC and religious broadcasts has been going
on for nearly 25 years. And while there indeed was a petition
numbered 2493, it did not have anything to do with banning
religious broadcasts. And the petition was not filed by atheist
Madalyn Murray O'Hair, who disappeared mysteriously in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The petition was filed by two attorneys (neither were connected
with O'Hair or any of her followers) who asked the FCC to
disqualify religiously affiliated organizations and institutions
from broadcasting on channels reserved for noncommercial education.
The petition was turned down in August 1975, with the FCC saying it
could take no position on religion.
</P>
<P>
   That was the end of it. But the FCC still receives a dozen or so
protests a day against the petition _ a number that increases
around Easter and Christmas, when the e-mail makes its rounds on
the Internet and into conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is it true that the Cat4'lic church is trying to collect
signatures against the petition.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things take on a life of their own,'' a church spokesman
told a reporter last year. ``I'm sure anybody who passes the (FCC
rumor) on, they mean well ... It's just that they've fallen prey to
a hoax.''
</P>
<P>
   (Lonnie Brown is associate editor of The Ledger in Lakeland,
Fla. He can be reached by e-mail at LonnieB001(AT)aol.com. The
Ledger is a member of the New York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
