<HEADER>
A3184 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0503-CO     05-02 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0503-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The high price of campaigning
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Isn't it wonderful living in a country where
anyone can grow up to be President _ as long as he or she has
access to more money than it would take to buy a small country and
feed everyone in it for a generation?
</P>
<P>
   George W. has already spent $63 million _ more than twice as
much as any previous presidential candidate, and the election is
still six months away. Gore trails with close to $34 million.
Elizabeth Dole dropped out at $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   So what's all this yammer I've been hearing about campaign
finance reform? And what does that mean, anyway? I've tried to
figure it out, but it's like reading ``War and Peace'' without a
tearsheet listing the cast of characters _ impossible to tell who's
saying what. It does help to frequently remind myself that both are
fiction based only loosely on reality.
</P>
<P>
   There's also been a lot of talk about ``soft'' money
(contributions given to the party rather than the candidate) and
how it ought to be regulated. Good idea but a waste of time. Before
Congress could ever get together on a reform bill, the candidates
would have found a way around it and be back to business as usual.
</P>
<P>
   The money politicians spend in their bids for election is
staggering, once it sinks in, and that takes a while. Average folks
like us don't think in esoteric terms of millions or billions.
While we can relate to mortgage payments and gasoline prices, we
cannot identify with the astronomical numbers in a candidate's war
chest _ like the almost $20 million W. has spent on the media, and
another $11 million on fundraising.
</P>
<P>
   In real life (as opposed to political life), these are absurd
numbers that call for an equally absurd solution. And that's what
I'm good at. My suggestion is to give each candidate fifty bucks
and see how much ground he can cover with it. Whoever's left come
November 7th, gets my vote.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of my no-spend theory have tried to convince me that
money spent by the candidates is dumped back into the economy and
eventually comes back to me. Sure. I've heard that one before. The
only trickle down I know of is tomato soup on my chin when the
saltines get in the way.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Shmoe doesn't get a check from NBC when Gore drops some big
bucks with them. Hell, we never even got a kickback from the Brushy
Creek BBQ House when W. spent $6,438 there. The route of the
trickle is too circuitous to ever wind up back in my pocket.
</P>
<P>
   But what do we get for our money? Well, we have one candidate
who by now believes he invented the Internet, and that Erich Segal
</P>
<P>
   wrote his book ``Love Story'' about his wife and him, and
another who goes around saying stuff like: ``Laura and I really
don't realize how bright our children is sometimes until we get an
objective analysis.''
</P>
<P>
   Presidential candidates are not the only ones blowing a bundle.
How much do you think a Senate seat might be worth? Take a guess.
</P>
<P>
   To Hillary and Rudy it's apparently worth plenty. Watchdog
groups have made an educated guesstimate that by election day these
two campaigners will have topped the $100 million mark. That's a
whole lot of desire to ``serve'' the citizens of New York _
particularly for the candidate who is still unpacking.
</P>
<P>
   Then comes November 7th. The last vote is in and the war chest
is empty. Now it's payback time. Watch for the lines of folks with
their hands extended, queing up around the winners. Trust me,
they're not there to shake; they've come to collect on their
investments.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get what you pay for,'' is as true in politics as it is in
diamonds, and that's what scares me. I couldn't afford to buy a
single candidate this year.
</P>
<P>
   (Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(at)nwonline.net)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
