   AUTOMOTIVE NEWS
</P>
<P>
   COXNET WHEELS PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet WHEELS page for the current week. This
layout is available now.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET WHEELS 0502 _ For 2000, few compact pickups can match the
Mazda B-Series when it comes to permutations and consumer group
endorsements. Thank Ford for that. Although Mazda has been selling
pickups in the United States since 1971, they are built by Ford in
New Jersey, so the mechanicals and virtually everything else
duplicate the features of Ford's Ranger. (DeVault, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) Art includes a 4-column color photo of the
2000 Mazda B3000.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   AT A GLANCE _ Fact box previewing the 2000 Mazda B3000.
</P>
<P>
   SHARP DRIVING _ Into my driveway comes one of Honda's cute
little S2000 sports cars. The day is made for convertibles. I can
hardly wait to put the top down and take to the flower-lined
roadways. Except I can't start the car or figure out how to release
the fuel door. (Sharp, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). Includes
1-column color photograph of columnist.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   HOME AND GARDEN
</P>
<P>
   SLOANE-DESIGN _ ATLANTA _ Her clients include New York rap
mogul/Atlanta restaurant owner Sean ``Puffy'' Combs, rap artist and
neighbor Queen Latifah, Disney, BET, Sony. But equally high on
Courtney Sloane's list of people to take care of are young black
designers in search of role models. ``I never had one, but I've
been blessed with good luck and have worked hard, so I've been able
to accomplish a great deal in virtually a short period of time,''
the New York designer said from her studio, Alternative Design.
Since forming the company eight years ago, the 36-year-old has been
on the fast track in a white-male dominated industry in which fewer
than 3 percent of designers are African-American. Her success,
designing mostly offices and homes for music industry leaders and
professional athletes, surprises even Sloane, who speaks today at
the Atlanta Decorative Arts Center to a sold-out audience of
designers and clients shopping the spring market. (Flanders,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   OLDNEW-HOUSE _ ATLANTA _ The Atlanta Symphony Decorators'
Showhouse is a study in old and new: A 1930s house updated, then
expanded with 21st-century amenities. A woody estate enhanced by
outdoor rooms and young gardens. A blue-blooded neighborhood
integrated with the nouveau riche. A designer cast of 32 veterans
mixed with rising talent. Inside, you won't find the dramatic color
palette of past show houses but an emphasis on warm neutrals, even
monochromatic color in some rooms. Story includes decorating tips
from the experts, rooms not to miss and event information. The
house is open through May 21. Last year's show house raised
$300,000 for the symphony. (Flanders, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.)
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed for Thursday, May 4.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT-ARTS
