<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 11:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3189 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-MONEYTALK03-COX     05-02 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Financial gift a wise choice for graduates
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Millions of young Americans will don their caps and
gowns in the next few weeks, graduating for high school or college
and starting the next chapters in their lives.
</P>
<P>
   They will have plenty to celebrate, including the gift-giving
that their successes have earned.
</P>
<P>
   For some families, a lot of money is involved, paying for cars,
vacations, electronics or perhaps jewelry. Others will spend much
less, but they will be searching for something important enough to
be a reward for years of work and the passage through one of life's
milestones.
</P>
<P>
   Here's an idea: How about giving something of lasting and even
increasing value? How about a financially oriented gift, one that
recognizes the approach of adult responsibilities and helps a
youngster start dealing with them?
</P>
<P>
   Parents or grandparents could pour some cash into a short-term
savings plan, with goals such as paying college tuition or, later
on, paying off college loans.
</P>
<P>
   Family members might also lean towards buying stocks or shares
in a stock mutual fund, perhaps in a Roth IRA. With those
longer-term arrangements, the goal is to encourage young people to
start soon on their investment plans, so they can benefit from the
power of compounding.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're encouraging your children to make conscious choices
about money, like all adults have to do,'' said certified financial
planner Elizabeth Jetton.
</P>
<P>
   Gifts need not be hugely expensive, like bright red cars, or
trips to the Caribbean, or giant slugs of stock in Disney or
Microsoft. There are cheaper alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   The choice will vary with each family's circumstances. For a
high school graduate, for example, the financially savvy gift might
be money for a freshman college year. Call it tuition money, pizza
money or whatever seems most rewarding.
</P>
<P>
   For college graduates, the most important financial goal might
be immediate -- graduate school or setting up a new household --
rather than far-off things like retirement plans.
</P>
<P>
   It's important to focus on the graduate's actual needs, rather
than the parents' yearnings for their children. ``You can't just
say, 'This is for your benefit, dear,''' Jetton observed.
``Graduates have to feel that there is some fairly immediate
advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   It may also be important to build in incentives. ``We've
suggested dollar-for-dollar matching programs,'' said Lewis J.
Walker, a certified financial planner in Norcross. That would hold
for short- or long-term savings plans.
</P>
<P>
   In his own family, Walker decided not to buy his daughter a car.
Instead, he made the down payment. ``I wanted her to have car
payments, to feel that her dad helped her start it and she helped
pay for it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another useful tactic could be splitting your gift money between
immediate gratification and future-oriented savings plans. ``One
thing we tell parents is that if you're giving money, rather than
blow it all on a car, put some into an investment,'' said Jetton.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you split your gift, putting only half into an S&AMP;P 500
index mutual fund, the growth would be impressive. After 10 years,
an investment of $10,500 could be expected to grow to $30,906.
Based on long-term trends and the power of compounding, the
investment would come to nearly $91,000 in 20 years and $267,800 in
30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Results like that should make it easy to sell young people on
the rewards of achieving financial independence.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some ideas for financially rewarding gifts:
</P>
<P>
   --- Open a Roth IRA. If your graduate has as much as $2,000 in
earnings, you can make a gift in that amount into a retirement
plan. Left to grow without taxes, the increased value could be
huge.
</P>
<P>
   While this makes good sense financially, some planners believe
retirement is a goal too far away to hold a young person's
interest. That raises the possibility of cashing out the IRA
quickly, for whatever need comes along.
</P>
<P>
   --- Stick with basic green. That could include money for
college, for buying a first home or some other or even paying down
college loans or other debts.
</P>
<P>
   Be careful with that last one. ``That's tricky,'' Jetton said.
``Until a person has reached a certain amount of maturity, having
no debt just frees them up to go into more debt.''
</P>
<P>
   Incentives may be particularly useful. You might offer to pay
down a portion of school debt when a new graduate gets his or her
first job, for example.
</P>
<P>
   --- Buy stocks or mutual funds. For long-term investments,
stocks tend to appreciate faster than bonds, certificates of
deposit or other such conservative investments. Ibbotson
Associates, which has gathered a massive database on investment
results since 1926, reports that large-company stocks held for any
15-year period have never lost money. The best annual return was
18.9 percent from 1985 through 1999. The worst was 0.6 percent,
from 1929 through 1943.
</P>
<P>
   Walker suggests buying mutual funds, especially for young people
with no experience in picking stocks. He favors stock funds, and
particularly focussed funds -- those that concentrate their
investments in a small number of stocks.
</P>
<P>
   --- Use low-cost, easily accessible investment vehicles. If you
are buying mutual funds, that means picking the ones that don't
charge more than about 1 percent sales fees and that have low
annual expenses. You might also shop for a fund that accepts
additional investments in small amounts, to encourage your graduate
to keep on putting money in.
</P>
<P>
   If you are buying stocks, lean towards discount brokers, like
Schwab. You could also look at www.netstockdirect.com or
www.buyandhold.com, which allow very small purchases for very low
commissions.
</P>
<P>
   --- Help your graduate learn. Some parents high financial
coaches to tutor young people on the basics of budgeting, saving
and financial planning. You could also buy financial planning
software, such as Quicken, to get them started.
</P>
<P>
   A number of good books are available for beginners. Among them
are ``The Green Magazine Guide to Personal Finance,'' by Ken
Kurson, and ``The Rookie's Guide to Money Management,'' by Carolina
Edwards and Ray Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
