<HEADER>
A3208 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-COLD-CAN-COX     05-02 0262
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLD-CAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Self-chilling beverage can sounds cool, but won't be cheap
 &HT;    By Don Fernandez
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Envision a day at the beach, sun beating down mercilessly and
throat parching in the heat. You reach for a soft drink can boiling
in the sand. With a click of a button, the drink converts from
feverish to frigid.
</P>
<P>
   A Bradenton, Fla., firm wants to make that sun-drenched mirage a
reality. Tempra Technology has created a self-refrigerating
beverage can that drops a drink to 35 degrees in minutes and keeps
it there for more than an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Crown Cork &AMP; Seal Co., which produces more than 30 billion cans
a year, agreed to mass produce the chilling device and is trying to
entice one or more of the big beverage makers to put it on the
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has the potential to be one of the most interesting
innovations in some time,'' said Dan Abramowicz, a Crown executive.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the can is a filament coated in a water-based gel. Push a
button and a vacuum mechanism in the base of the can sucks the
moisture in the gel into the bottom. That drops the temperature of
the filament, which then acts as an ice cube of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   Convenience is costly: A self-chilling can of soda will cost
about a dollar. But experts say it could appeal to a niche market.
</P>
<P>
   ``This can is interesting,'' said John Sicher, editor and
publisher of Beverage Digest. ``Crown has a lot of manufacturing
expertise and a lot of industry customer contacts.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
