<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 12:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3210 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-WRESTLING-MEDIA-COX     05-02 1255
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRESTLING-MEDIA-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   MEDIA GIANTS
</P>
<P>
   The wrestling industry is generating millions of dollars in
profits by packaging and distributing their products in many ways
</P>
<P>
   By John Allen
</P>
<P>
   Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere you turn in this media-crazed world, professional
wrestling is there. And in many cases, they blazed the trail for
other non-wrestling companies to follow.
</P>
<P>
   A Saturday Night Live episode scored the show's highest ratings
of the year. Why? Because the World Wrestling Federation's The Rock
was the host with the most; the top-rated cable show of the year,
WWF's Monday night ``Raw is War;'' The top selling books on the New
York Times bestsellers list are wrestling autobiographies. Hottest
selling vide
</P>
<P>
   o games, you guessed it, pro wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere you turn in this media-crazed world, professional
wrestling is there. And in many cases, they blazed the trail for
other non-wrestling companies to follow.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at what they have done, what they are doing now
and what you can expect in the future:
</P>
<P>
   TELEVISION
</P>
<P>
   The tube was the reason behind the growth of professional
wrestling in the 1980s and has become the key to wrestling's
current success. This time, though, it is carrying cable television
profits to new heights. The last Monday in April was a good
example. WWF's ``Raw is War'' show earned a 7.1 rating, it's
highest in head-to-head competition with World Championship
Wrestling's ``Nitro'' program. Meanwhile, ``Nitro,'' which had been
slumping over the past year, earned one of its highest ratings in
six months at 3.1. That mark is good enough to be one of the top 10
watched cable shows for the week. When the NFL is not in season,
``Raw is War'' is almost always the top-rated cable television
show.
</P>
<P>
   The WWF's 18-month long headlock as the top cable television
show has drawn interest from CBS. CBS is in the process of
mergering with Viacom. When that deal is complete, they are
expected to move the ``Raw is War'' show from the USA Network to
The Nashville Network (TNN) _ owned by CBS. USA network has filed a
court injunction in an attempt to stop the WWF from moving.
</P>
<P>
   CBS is expected to include a deal for the WWF's new business
venture, the spring football league XFL, as part of its package.
That would leave Extreme Championship Wrestling (the third most
popular organization) looking for a home for its program that is
the highest rated show on TNN. They could very well end up on USA.
</P>
<P>
   The WWF, WCW and ECW have also dominated the pay-per-view
market. With almost 30 events per year, the trio attract nearly 15
million additional viewers.
</P>
<P>
   The wrestlers' appeal is not just limited to their shows. Steve
Austin, Triple H, Chyna, Tommy Dreamer, New Jack, The Big Show and
Mick Foley are just a few of the wrestlers who have made guest
appearances on shows such as ``Nash Bridges,'' ``3rd Rock from the
Sun,'' ``Boy Meets World.'' Austin, who has appeared on four
episodes of Nash Bridges, may play a recurring character.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES
</P>
<P>
   While Warner Brothers and WCW are trying to earn box office
dollars with the recently released ``Ready to Rumble'', movies and
pro wrestling have not worked well. Ready to Rumble grossed about
$12 million during its first month, and will be out of most
theaters soon.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the documentary ``Beyond the Mat'' has received
critical acclaim, but not box office success. Despite the limited
showing in theaters, when it hits the video stores later this year,
the movie should find a very strong cult following.
</P>
<P>
   As for the future, the only movie you'll see wrestlers in will
be ``The Mummy II,'' where The Rock will have a guest star role.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   While the average John Q. Public thinks wrestling fans can't
read, Mick Foley helped prove otherwise. Foley's autobiography
``Have a Nice Day'' climbed up The New York Times bestsellers list
until it reached No. 2. On the heels of that success, The Rock took
his book, ``The Rock Says,'' to No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Such success has made writers out of Diamond Dallas Page
(''Positively Page'') and Bret Hart (''The Best there is, the Best
there was, the Best there ever will be'') and has made book deals
for 'Stone Cold' Steve Austin, The Fabulous Moolah and Rena Mero
(a.k.a. Sable).
</P>
<P>
   As for the future, wrestling superstars such as Ric Flair, Hulk
Hogan, Shawn Michaels, Kevin Nash, Sting, Lex Luger and Triple H
could all have No. 1s in their futures.
</P>
<P>
   VIDEOS
</P>
<P>
   Wrestling has learned how to make more of their pay-per-views by
releasing videos of each event months later. Those videos along
with special compulation tapes on stars like The Rock, Mick Foley,
Hulk Hogan and Sting have allowed professional wrestling to
dominate the sports video market (they had 12 of the top 20 selling
videos for the month of March).
</P>
<P>
   According to Billboard magazine, results from this past week's
recreational video sales lists the WWF with the top 6 spots, and 7
of top 9. An ECW video is 10th. Of note, the video of Super Bowl
XXXIV is 8th.
</P>
<P>
   Videos are also the way startup groups like ECW have been able
to merchandise their product. When ECW was new, they did not have
weekly television shows, so many road shows were strung together to
form videos that are now considered classics by wrestling video
conneseurs.
</P>
<P>
   As for the future, the sky is the limit. Expect the past to come
alive again. ``Classic'' matches from the 1970s and early 1980s are
in demand and will continue to grow in popularity. When one website
can be devoted to strictly selling wrestling videos and have a
library of thousands, it's big.
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO GAMES
</P>
<P>
   While this is an area that wrestling was slower to get involved
in that other entertainment industries, they have definitely made
up for lost time. WWF and WCW each have produce four different
games and expect to have more for 2000. ECW introduced its first
game with the help of Acclaim and it became one of the top selling
games in the video game maker's history.
</P>
<P>
   According to PCdata.com, the top selling video game for Sony's
Playstation for March was ``WWF's Smackdown 2000.'' In March, the
4th best-seller for Nintendo was WWF's ````Wrestlemania'' 2000.''
Also the 5th best-selling Nintendo game for 1998 was ``WCW/NWO
Revenge.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the future, more games, more violence and more swearing.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC
</P>
<P>
   Of all the multimedia arenas, this has been the least
successful. Grouping together a bunch of wrestling intros has not
translated into big sales and probably never will. However, the
WWF's ``The Music Vol. 4'' went platinum on Dec. 16, according to
Billboard magazine.
</P>
<P>
   A gold record is given when a CD sell 125,000 copies. Platinum
is issued when sales reach 250,000.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere is wrestling hotter than on the Internet. Web sites
exist for wrestling organizations, wrestlers, news groups and fan
clubs. Yahoo current lists 646 professional wrestling Websites (218
are devoted to wrestlers), up nearly 100 from last June.
</P>
<P>
   These Websites can tell you everything you want to know about
your favorite wrestler, sell you their merchandise, tell you when
they are coming to your town, get you tickets, to when you can see
them on television, and let you in on the latest gossip and rumors.
</P>
<P>
   As for the future, expect to see the number of sites dwindle,
but the ones who survive will be among the best on the Internet for
innovations.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
