<HEADER>
A3213 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-TV-GEPPETTO-HNS &LR;      05-02 0364
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GEPPETTO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     VERSATILE DREW CAREY CARRIES A TUNE IN ENTERTAINING
`GEPPETTO' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK McGUIRE   
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Drew Carey is no singer. He just plays one on television.
</P>
<P>
   But Carey _ ABC's most prominent face before Regis Philbin came
along _ proves he's still the network's most versatile performer in
a ``Wonderful World of Disney'' musical production of ``Geppetto''
(7 p.m. EDT Sunday).
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, Carey can in fact carry a tune. He's no Burl Ives, but
he's game, and that's enough.
</P>
<P>
   If Disney's ``Geppetto'' doesn't come close to the level of its
near-perfect TV musical ``Annie'' of last fall, this reworking of
the Pinocchio story from the toy maker's point of view is certainly
entertaining family fun.
</P>
<P>
   And that is squarely because of Carey, who before
``Millionaire'' was the one ABC talent with shows on two nights
(``The Drew Carey Show'' and ``Whose Line is it Anyway?'').
</P>
<P>
   There's no denying Carey's earnestness, an innate everyman
quality that comes from being a regular guy in real life. Here he's
a schlub playing a schlub with a Herman's Hermits haircut. You want
to root for him.
</P>
<P>
   Brent Spiner, without the pancake makeup of his years as Data on
``Star Trek: The Next Generation,'' is properly manic as the evil
and borderline psychotic puppeteer Stromboli. Seth Adkins, best
remembered as the kid Leonardo DiCaprio saves in the hallway of the
sinking Titanic, is properly unruly as the wooden boy who just
wants to have fun.
</P>
<P>
   Julia Louis-Dreyfus plays the Blue Fairy, the wish-granter who
puts the toy-to-boy transformation into motion. She's so over the
top _ like Glinda the Good Witch on hash _ that your fillings will
ache.
</P>
<P>
   She has to be putting us on; but that touch of ``Seinfeld''
irony never comes. I understand playing big for kids, but
Louis-Dreyfus is going Godzilla here.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, kids like Godzilla. They should also like
``Geppetto.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His electronic mail
address is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
