<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 12:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3215 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-BREAST-CANCER-HNS &LR;      05-02 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BREAST-CANCER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BREAST CANCER SURVIVOR WORKS TO BOOST AWARENESS, CARE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SYLVIA WOOD  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DELMAR, N.Y. _ Mara Ginsberg didn't waste any time wondering
``why me?'' when she was diagnosed with breast cancer in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother and aunt both died of the disease at age 44.
</P>
<P>
   With such a family history, Ginsberg had known for years that
she was at risk. ``It made me vigilant,'' she said. ``I started
having mammograms at 23.''
</P>
<P>
   If anything, getting the diagnosis sent Ginsberg, then a
37-year-old lawyer for the New York attorney general's office, into
high gear, gathering information about the disease and potential
treatments. She recalled when the radiologist called her at work to
deliver the news about her malignant lump.
</P>
<P>
   When she hung up the phone, she relayed the news to her
officemate, who promptly asked how she was feeling and whether she
shouldn't go home. ``I said, `What am I going to do at home?'''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Ginsberg has beat her cancer, quit her job, and
started To Life!, an advocacy group for women and their families
affected by breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The nonprofit group, based in a small office in suburban Albany,
will mark its second anniversary in October and shows no sign of
losing momentum as it hires its first part-time employee and plans
for its annual fund-raising gala later this month.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the group reached hundreds of women in the area
around Albany, the state capital, with a series of educational
forums and weekly support group meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Ginsberg has earned national recognition for her work. In
October, she won a You Can Make a Difference Award from the Kellogg
Co. and Susan G. Komen Breast Cancer Foundation, which also
presented her in July with the Local Hero Award.
</P>
<P>
   Next month, she is slated to be honored by the Albany-Colonie
Chamber of Commerce in a ceremony recognizing 100 Women of
Excellence.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a tremendously energetic person with a good idea every
30 seconds,'' said Paula Steigman, a breast cancer survivor and
close friend of Ginsberg's for the past 15 years. ``She's
developing contacts in the field all around the country.''
</P>
<P>
   To Life! wasn't a late-night brainstorm. Ginsberg, now 41, said
her decision to start the group was an evolutionary process that
began with her diagnosis. She had chosen to get her care in New
York City, in part because she already knew a doctor there.
</P>
<P>
   But she also learned that New York City was miles ahead in its
approach to breast cancer, whether it was the availability of
support groups or human hair wigs to help camouflage the effects of
chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the resources available to patients there and what
wasn't available to patients here,'' she said. ``I thought there
were things missing.''
</P>
<P>
   To Life! has been an effort to fill in those gaps, with weekly,
not monthly, support group meetings, a mentoring program to pair up
newly diagnosed women with survivors, and even a special beauty
shop to help fit women with wigs and prosthetic breasts.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Lanoue, the service line manager at Northeast Women's
Health, believes such services have helped make a difference to the
women she sees. ``The patients who have gone to Mara have spoken
very highly of it,'' she said. ``From my perspective, it's another
resource I can give the patient. It's another avenue I can steer
them down.''
</P>
<P>
   Ginsberg says her mission is simple: ``To help people through
the process in a positive way, no matter what the outcome.'' She
acknowledges that part of her commitment comes from having watched
her own mother, who also was a lawyer, suffer with the disease in
relative silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was completely alone,'' Ginsberg said. ``In the '60s, when
she was diagnosed, you never talked about cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   And adults certainly didn't talk to their children about the
illness. ``I learned about it when I was 13,'' she said, recalling
how a playground bully taunted her with, ``Your mommy had her
breasts cut off.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was diagnosed,'' Ginsberg said, ``the first thing I did
was find a way to tell my children. It was important for me to tell
them because I was left in the dark.''
</P>
<P>
   Her two children, now 11 and 8, have grown up hearing about To
Life! a translation of the Hebrew phrase ``La chiam.''
</P>
<P>
   Ginsberg has since written a book, and is looking for a
publisher, for ``Mommy Has Breast Cancer, Please Tell Me What That
Means.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although Ginsberg's main goal is to give women as much
individual attention as possible, she acknowledges that another
part of her mission is to help raise the standard of medical care
by encouraging women to educate themselves and voice their concerns
with their physicians.
</P>
<P>
   So far, that strategy seems to be working. Over the past 16
months, To Life! has hosted more than a dozen educational programs
on topics such as innovations in breast cancer biopsies and healthy
cooking.
</P>
<P>
   ``A well-educated patient knows what to ask and that's the most
effective weapon for dealing with and treating their disease,''
said Dr. Debbie Kennedy of Albany Plastic and Reconstructive
Surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, who often does reconstructive surgery on patients after
mastectomies, believes groups like To Life! not only have an impact
on the medical community but also on government, in determining how
state and federal dollars are spent on research.
</P>
<P>
   And while To Life! hasn't entered into the lobbying arena yet,
Kennedy believes Ginsberg has the potential to influence change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mara is a bundle of energy,'' she said. ``She's the kind of
person who makes things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Ginsberg's motivation, however, remains very personal and very
tied to her mother. ``I'm doing this, in part, for her and all the
people who suffered silently alone,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Considering her family history, she's also acutely aware that
her own 11-year-old daughter, Barbara, is at risk of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is my fervent hope that with all the changes going on, that
many of the issues will be a thing of the past,'' she said. ``I do
feel in some sense I'm completing a mission.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (For more information about To Life! and its services, including
times of support group meetings, please call 518-439-5975.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
