u k BC-COLUMN-MURRAY03-COX     05-02 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLUMN-MURRAY03-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   DISPATCHES FROM DREAMSVILLE: Magical times on the family farm
</P>
<P>
   (''Dispatches from Dreamsville'' is an occasional series in
which readers share with Cox Newspapers senior writer Joe Murray
their memories of growing up in small-town America. Back then, or
at least the way we remember it, life was like a dream.)
</P>
<P>
   By Joyce B. Barnes
</P>
<P>
   Special to Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   CATAWBA, Ohio _ I was not a true farm kid, but my grandparents'
farm had been our main vacation spot all during my childhood.
</P>
<P>
   At spring break, my brother Gene and I, grumbling about being
slave labor, were put to work helping with the spring cleaning.
</P>
<P>
   In summer, we'd come to the farm to celebrate the Fourth of
July, bringing a box of all kinds of fireworks to shoot off in the
meadow.
</P>
<P>
   At Christmas, a big tree would be cut from their back property,
lighted with grandma's dainty tapers and adorned with treasured
ornaments from the attic.
</P>
<P>
   I remember, too, Aunt Dorothy's delicious yuletime cookie and
candy concoctions and the family's simple gifts, often homemade, as
well as the mysterious packages our parents had packed into the
trunk of the car.
</P>
<P>
   Amiable and easygoing, my grandpa, Charlie Coe, was not one for
shiny new tractors. He let others lead the way to modern
efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   He did drive a little tan Ford Model A with a rumble seat that
Gene and I enjoyed, but everything else stayed the same.
</P>
<P>
   Grandpa loved to work the farm with his mules and Old Billy, his
horse.
</P>
<P>
   I swear it was the world's largest horse. When I rode him, his
restless shifting had me hanging onto the saddle horn for dear
life.
</P>
<P>
   The gentle snorting of Guernsey cows were part of the farm life,
as well as the contented clucking of grandma's hens and,
occasionally, their raucous squawks when Duke the dog made
mischievous forays into their midst.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the time came when grandpa and grandma could no
longer go it alone, and our dad moved us to the farm.
</P>
<P>
   When we protested having to leave our school and become a part
of rural life, he said: ``Would you rather be a little frog in a
big puddle or a big frog in a little puddle?''
</P>
<P>
   We accepted the inevitable, not that we really had a choice.
</P>
<P>
   And it turned out wonderfully in that beautiful little community
nestled in rolling green hills dotted with grazing horses and
cattle. All of it was like magic.
</P>
<P>
   Gene and I found our future mates in Catawba, and life was
uncomplicated and fun _ until that fateful windy March night when
our beautiful home went up in flames.
</P>
<P>
   We were thankful, of course, to escape with our lives, but we
lost everything we had.
</P>
<P>
   Years later when I returned to visit the site, I realized that
even if fire had not claimed our home, the farm itself long ago
would have succumbed to the overpowering movement known as
agri-business.
</P>
<P>
   Grandpa Coe's acerage would have been combined with adjoining
land, and the farm I had known would have disappeared regardless.
</P>
<P>
   I know that's progress, and I remind myself how much more
efficient it is now, this strange, alien turf. But in my heart,
it's difficult to understand.
</P>
<P>
   Joyce B. Barnes lives in Springfield, Ohio, about 25 miles from
Catawba.
</P>
<P>
   (If you have a story to share, send it to ``Dispatches from
Dreamsville,'' c/o Joe Murray, Cox Newspapers, P.O. Box 151108,
Lufkin, Texas, 75915; email, jmurray(at)txucom.net. If your article
is used, you will receive $25. For other Dreamsville stories, visit
http://www.coxnews.com/newsservice.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
