u e BC-COLUMN-POP-BOS &LR;      05-02 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLUMN-POP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUCY PEARL IS JUST WHAT THE SOUL DOCTOR ORDERED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   R &AMP; B ain't what it used to be.
</P>
<P>
   Once there was Curtis and Chaka, Otis and the O'Jays, Lady Soul
and the Godfather of Soul. There were the Spinners, Stylistics,
Commodores, Earth Wind &AMP; Fire, and the Isley Brothers. Marvin Gaye
sang ``Got to Give It Up,'' and we happily acquiesced. Al Green
said, ``Let's Stay Together,'' and we did. Gladys Knight and the
Pips hopped that ``Midnight Train to Georgia,'' and she had us
waiting at the station.
</P>
<P>
   Now, we have Sisqo's silly ``Thong Song,'' which is just
thong-thong-thong-thong-wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Little wonder then that there's been so much buzz surrounding
the new band Lucy Pearl, which has been touted as R &AMP; B's first
supergroup. Formed last year, Lucy Pearl is the phoenix that rose
from the ashes of three of the best R &AMP; B and hip-hop groups of the
1990s _ Raphael Saadiq of Tony Toni Tone (``Feels Good'' ``If I Had
No Loot''), Dawn Robinson of En Vogue (``Free Your Mind,''
``Something He Can Feel''), and Ali Shaheed Muhammad of A Tribe
Called Quest (``Award Tour'' ``Scenario,'' ``Bonita Applebum'').
</P>
<P>
   With such a pedigree, Lucy Pearl's eponymous CD is nearing its
May 23 release date laden with expectations that this talented trio
deliver us from R &AMP; B mediocrity and help mend the hole in R &AMP; B's
soul. But Saadiq maintains he isn't feeling the heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure I feel is the pressure I like, and the pressure I
need,'' he said in a telephone interview during a brief respite
from preparations for the band's first tour, due to kick off in New
York later this month. They'll also make their national TV debut
this week on ``The Tonight Show With Jay Leno.''
</P>
<P>
   Saadiq has been friends with Robinson and Muhammad for years,
but Lucy Pearl happened almost by accident. Saadiq and Muhammad had
worked together on projects for their former bands (Saadiq was a
member of Tribe's production unit, the Ummah), and they'd always
talked about doing something more. They originally envisioned their
then-unnamed band as an all-male trio, but when Robinson's name
came up, both Saadiq and Muhammad rethought their new group.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson was one of En Vogue's funky divas and the standout
voice on such songs as ``Hold On,'' ``Giving Him Something He Can
Feel,'' and ``Don't Let Go (Love).'' She left to pursue a solo
career in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew she was available,'' Saadiq said, ``and we thought it
would be a great idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucy Pearl arrives in the midst of the so-called ``neo-soul''
sound, which, for all intents and purposes, Tony Toni Tone helped
launch back in the late-1980s. It's a genre that, while employing
hip-hop stylings, jeep beats, and new jack swing, finds its heart
in the traditional R &AMP; B prevalent in the 1960s and 1970s. The
music features glorious vocals (yes, kids, once upon a time R &AMP; B
singers could actually sing), sultry grooves, and ace musicianship.
</P>
<P>
   It's a movement being championed by such artists as Macy Gray,
Angie Stone, Erykah Badu, Maxwell, Meshell Ndegeocello, and
D'Angelo, whose recent hit, ``Untitled (How Does It Feel),'' was
co-written and co-produced by Saadiq. Lucy Pearl is the first band
of neo-soul, although Saadiq shrugs off the title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been doing it since the Tonys back in '88, so I don't
know if there's anything new about it,'' he said. ``I don't call it
new soul. When (the Tonys) were doing it, it wasn't new. We were
just doing what people before us _ like Cameo and Midnight Star _
were doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the trio briefly considered the name Disciples of Soul,
until Lucy Pearl popped into Saadiq's head. ``It had that ring I
wanted,'' he said. ``It sounded unique.''
</P>
<P>
   In Lucy Pearl, Saadiq and Robinson share vocals. Saadiq plays
guitars and bass; and Muhammad, Tribe's former mixmaster, handles
the turntables, loops, drum machines, and adds his own touches on
bass. (When's the last time you saw an R &AMP; B group that played its
own instruments?) From the biting guitars of ``Hollywood,'' to the
unbelievably sultry first single, ``Dance Tonight,'' Lucy Pearl
often measures up to what Saadiq proclaims in the intro to the CD's
first song, ``Ask of You'': ``It's a new revolution.'' Much in the
way that the Tonys, Tribe, and En Vogue stood out from the pack in
their time, Lucy Pearl is unlike anything else on urban radio _
which is perfectly fine with Saadiq.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're definitely not a part of that, but we don't knock it,''
he said. ``Everybody seems to want to do the same thing. People
should go out and try to do different things, but some people don't
know how to do anything else. They're making a great living out of
it, so who's to say?
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, there's people getting rich selling horse manure,
too. They're bagging that and selling it by the load, so I guess
they figure, why wouldn't somebody sell music like that?'' he
asked. ``But we have some pride in our product. We're doing what we
like. They have their niche, we've found our niche, and our niche
happens not to be what's on the radio.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Renee Graham covers the pop scene for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
