<HEADLINE>
POLAROID PUTS FINGER ON SECURITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Polaroid Corp. wants to make it cheaper to get to know you.
</P>
<P>
   While the Cambridge, Mass. company is primarily a camera-maker,
it is also trying to lower the cost of computer security
identification systems. At a trade show in Florida this week it
planned to announce partnerships with 11 other companies to produce
keyboards and other devices using a modest Polaroid-built
fingerprint reader that costs around $50 a copy.
</P>
<P>
   That's a big markdown from existing scanners that sell for
$1,000 or more, and Polaroid bets computer users will want to
substitute a thumb or forefinger for the multitude of passwords
they now must remember to log on to computer networks or access
their voicemail.
</P>
<P>
   Users might include banks, airlines, and other large companies
that control access to sensitive databases. Manufacturers that buy
devices from Polaroid say they are in talks to sell tens of
thousands of keyboards, with the Polaroid device installed, to
customers such as Continental Airlines, TRW, and Bausch &AMP; Lomb.
</P>
<P>
   So far, these customers have been slow to embrace fingerprint
systems, partly for fear employees would regard them as intrusive.
</P>
<P>
   But Phil Bruno, vice president at keyboard maker Key Source
International in Hayward, Calif., says many businesses are warming
to the idea, privacy concerns notwithstanding. ``We have major
corporations calling us and saying, `It's time, we're ready,' ''
Bruno said.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of Polaroid's devices is an optical scanner that
analyzes a half-inch section of a person's finger or thumb pressed
against a optical-glass window.
</P>
<P>
   The skin is illuminated by two small diodes, and the image
captured by a chip that functions as a digital camera. Software
then analyzes the image and places a marker at each point at which
the lines in the fingerprint stop or split.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a two-dimension map that Polaroid says is the
equivalant of a 300-digit password.
</P>
<P>
   The cameras are known as ``optical scanners.'' Some devices made
by competitors like Veridicom Inc. in Santa Clara, Calif., require
users to touch a finger directly onto a sensitive surface attached
to a semiconductor. The systems then use electrical signals to
measure the difference between the fingertip's ridges and valleys
to create a similar identifying code.
</P>
<P>
   Systems using the latter method can be smaller than the
three-inch-long box that houses Polaroid's optical scanner, and
produced at similar prices. Polaroid says its devices are simpler
to make and more durable. Vendors like Biometric Identification
Inc. of Sherman Oaks, Calif., buy both types of sensors for
different situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've got an outdoor environment, where you might have
water on the screen, then you might want to use Polaroid,'' said
Biometric manager Julie Web.
</P>
<P>
   In an office, where many different people might use the same
fingerprint scanner, devices that use electrical signals sometimes
are more versatile, she said.
</P>
<P>
   At the trade event, the CardTech/SecureTech show in Miami, her
company will show off software systems that can integrate both
types of sensors.
</P>
<P>
   Polaroid came to the fingerprint-scanning business through its
identification unit, which mostly produces drivers licenses and
voting and Social Security cards for 37 states and foreign
governments such as the Republic of South Africa. (Polaroid
equipment also will be used by the Massachusetts Registry of Motor
Vehicles starting in October.)
</P>
<P>
   The company began using fingerprint readers to authenticate
voters in Third World elections, but found the readers bulky and
expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Philip J. Scarfo, Polaroid's vice president of biometrics,
decided the company would produce its own scanners at the start of
1999. The company has made just a few thousand test copies to date.
But by 2001, he said, it could be making a ``a few million'' at an
assembly plant in Norwood. Chips for the scanner are produced by
Atmel Corp. in San Jose, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   At least one gunmaker is considering buying the print-scanner as
part of a ``trigger-lock'' system, Scarfo said. But the biggest
market, he expects, will be desktop computers at companies that do
business via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Ross Kerber is a member of the Globe staff. He can be reached by
e-mail at kerber(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
