<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 13:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3236 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-EXAMINER-SALE-HNS &LR;      05-02 1397
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXAMINER-SALE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PUBLISHER TESTIFIES HE OFFERED FAVORABLE EDITORIALS FOR MAYOR'S
SUPPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SETH ROSENFELD  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The publisher of the San Francisco Examiner has
testified that he offered Mayor Willie Brown favorable newspaper
editorials in exchange for the mayor's support of the Hearst
Corp.'s plan to buy the competing San Francisco Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Examiner Publisher Timothy O. White, testifying Monday in an
antitrust case that seeks to block the purchase, said the
editorials would favor some of Brown's programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't affect the journalism side,'' White added. ``It
would affect the editorials.''
</P>
<P>
   White made the statements under questioning by Joseph M. Alioto,
the lawyer for Clint Reilly, who filed the antitrust lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued later Monday, the Hearst Corp. said, ``It
is not now, nor has it ever been, a policy of the San Francisco
Examiner to trade favorable editorial coverage for any gains,
including political influence. The newspaper's coverage of the
mayor, and his policies, stands on its own merit.''
</P>
<P>
   White said in the statement, ``I was tired and confused by the
question. The implication of my answer that the pages of the
Examiner can be influenced, under any circumstances, is absurd.''
</P>
<P>
   The first day of the trial shed light on Hearst's efforts to
acquire the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly contends Hearst's plan to buy the Chronicle for $660
million and sell the Examiner to the publishers of a free newspaper
will result in Hearst owning the only metropolitan daily paper in
San Francisco, allegedly an illegal monopoly that would reduce
competition for news, advertisements and subscriptions.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly, a former candidate for mayor who has criticized the
Examiner's coverage of him and has tried to buy the paper, is
asking U.S. District Judge Vaughn R. Walker to bar Hearst
permanently from buying the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to settle the lawsuit failed Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst has denied Reilly's allegations and says he lacks legal
standing to bring the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Halling, a Hearst lawyer, said the afternoon Examiner
cannot support itself outside of a joint operating agreement under
which it splits profits with the larger San Francisco Chronicle,
which publishes in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Examiner is an economically failing company, Hearst
could buy its rival Chronicle and close or sell the Examiner
without violating antitrust laws, Halling said. That has happened
in cities across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Despite an extensive sales effort, no one was willing to pay for
the Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one wanted to take it for free,'' Halling said in his
opening statement. ``The marketplace has spoken. This is not a
viable business.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Hearst agreed to transfer the Examiner to the Fang
family and to give them a $66 million subsidy for publishing costs.
</P>
<P>
   White answered Alioto's questions about his contacts with Brown
after Walker overruled Halling's objections that they were hearsay
and irrelevant to antitrust law.
</P>
<P>
   The questioning focused on several internal Hearst Corp.
communications obtained by Alioto.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who has complained about critical coverage in the
Examiner, was one of several San Francisco politicians who opposed
Hearst's initial plan to buy the Chronicle and close the Examiner
if no buyer could be found, saying he wanted the city to have
competing dailies.
</P>
<P>
   White testified that he made the offer of editorial support to
Brown at a Sept. 1, 1999, lunch, at the height of the mayor's
re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In an e-mail written later that day, White reported on the
meeting to George B. Irish, head of Hearst's newspaper division.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked Willie how I was going to justify to my superiors in
New York wanting to support him and cooperate with him when he was
seeming to go out of his way to make our lives difficult,'' White's
e-mail said.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto asked White if he was trying to suggest to Brown that the
Examiner might be more supportive if the mayor backed Hearst's bid
for the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not that specifically,'' White replied. ``We had talked
earlier about working together on a number of priorities for the
city that we shared.''
</P>
<P>
   White said the shared priorities included reforms of the city's
public transportation system. He said the Examiner's support would
come from its editorial pages, not its news reporting.
</P>
<P>
   ``You were doing a little horse-trading yourself,'' Alioto
asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' White said.
</P>
<P>
   And the trade was that the Examiner would not be so hard on the
mayor in editorials if he supported Hearst's purchase of the
Chronicle, Alioto asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the implication,'' White testified.
</P>
<P>
   According to White's Sept. 1 e-mail, Brown also told White that,
although he had written U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno expressing
concern about Hearst's acquisition of the Chronicle, he did it to
placate the city's governing Board of Supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   Also at the lunch, according to the e-mail, Brown said he had
only one complaint about his coverage in the Examiner: that he was
being judged ``guilty by association with some really bad people''
who were the focus of an FBI investigation of the city's handling
of minority contracting.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor added that he appointed an independent panel to
investigate the matter, in response to the FBI case and ``our
relentless reporting,'' White said in the e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   In the Hearst statement issued Monday, Examiner Executive Editor
Phil Bronstein said he was at the lunch with White and Brown, and
that there was ``no negotiation of press coverage of any kind.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   White, previously the publisher of the Hearst-owned Times Union
in Albany, N.Y., also testified that he was sent to San Francisco
to rally the Examiner's smaller staff and to persuade the Chronicle
Publishing Co. to sell the Chronicle to Hearst.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1965, the Chronicle and the Examiner have had a joint
operating agreement in which they share printing, advertising and
circulation. The newspapers split all revenue evenly after joint
costs, but then use their respective shares to pay for their
independent editorial staffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle's owners refused to extend the agreement beyond
2005, so Hearst faced the daunting and expensive task of competing
directly with the Chronicle after that, competition that could have
killed the Examiner, White testified.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem, he said, was that outside of the joint
operating agreement the Examiner would lose millions of dollars
annually.
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle refused to participate in promoting Examiner
subscriptions, which Hearst believed was an effort to weaken the
Examiner further, White testified.
</P>
<P>
   White said he told Chronicle representatives that Hearst meant
to compete, although ``I didn't believe that we could go
head-to-head.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a March 13, 1999, e-mail to Irish titled ``Strategic
Initiatives,'' White outlined several strategies, including:
</P>
<P>
   _ Exploring alliances with Dean Singleton's Alameda Newspaper
Group or the Gannett Co.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Openly analyzing'' the division of printing presses and
other physical assets shared with the Chronicle under the joint
operating agreement.
</P>
<P>
   White testified that the plans were intended to make the
Chronicle owners think Hearst meant to engage them in a costly
newspaper war and that it was better for them to sell the Chronicle
to Hearst.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called this the blowfish theory,'' White testified. ``It is
what it is, but it is as big as it can be made to look.''
</P>
<P>
   White said Hearst was trying to convince the remaining one-third
of the Chronicle's owners who did not want to sell the newspaper to
Hearst.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were going to come out of the bushes screaming, whether
we're holding spears or not,'' he said of the strategy.
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle Publishing Co. agreed in August 1999 to sell the
San Francisco daily to Hearst. The company also decided to sell
some other properties to other companies.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto is trying to show that the Examiner could compete as an
economically independent newspaper and that Hearst's plan to close
it or sell it to the Fangs violates antitrust laws.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-00 1317EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
