u e BC-TV-DISNEY-BOS &LR;      05-02 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-DISNEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEHIND THE LINES IN TIME-WARNER VS. DISNEY WAR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (e and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the surface, the acrimonious stalemate between Walt Disney
Co. and Time-Warner Inc. _ which deprived 3.5 million homes of
Regis Philbin's smiling face Monday night _ involves only the
narrow question of how much Time-Warner must pay Disney for the
right to carry its cable channels.
</P>
<P>
   But a larger battle is also taking place, one with possible
implications for the proposed megamerger of Time-Warner and AOL and
for the digital, broadband future that television is moving toward.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one behemoth clashing with another for positioning,''
said Joseph Turow, a professor of communications at the Annenberg
School for Communication at the University of Pennsylvania. ``It's
a tango of sorts, positioning themselves for the new media
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``tango'' involves two huge corporations that may be viewed
with little sympathy by the public, especially now that Time-Warner
has upped the ante by blacking out programs from Disney-owned ABC,
including Philbin's blockbuster ``Who Wants To Be a Millionaire''
on cable systems in such major markets as New York City, Los
Angeles, Houston, and Raleigh-Durham.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the Iran-Iraq war: You root for them both to lose,''
said Tobe Berkovitz, a communications professor at Boston
University. Added Tom Wolzien, a media analyst at Sanford C.
Bernstein &AMP; Co. in New York: ``Remember John Belushi in `Animal
House' yelling `Food fight!'? This is sort of the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is a deeper issue percolating beneath the arguments
over how much Time-Warner should pay Disney for such channels as
Toon Disney and a soap-opera channel, and whether the Disney
Channel should be part of the basic cable package on
Time-Warner-owned systems, rather than a premium service for which
customers pay extra.
</P>
<P>
   An ABC spokeswoman, Julie Hoover, brands it an ``abuse of
power'' for Time-Warner to black out ABC programs in the middle of
a crucial ``sweeps'' month. Then she cut to the heart of the
matter: ``If this is the way Time-Warner behaves when they are a
gatekeeper of cable systems, how will they behave when they are a
gatekeeper not only of cable systems but of the Internet? People
won't even know they are losing access to alternative services;
they will be cut off at the pass.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Kane, president of WABC-TV in New York, wasted no time in
labeling the pulling of the ABC signal from Time-Warner in New York
a ``frightening foreshadowing of the implications of the
Time-Warner/AOL merger.''
</P>
<P>
   Time-Warner, for its part, says this is no more than a dispute
between two large corporations. ``They've been trying to wrap this
around the AOL merger from the beginning,'' a Time-Warner official
said. ``We felt we had a deal, and suddenly the ground rules
changed from the Disney perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Tellingly, both sides have invoked the Federal Communications
Commission to bolster their positions. Time-Warner insists that
under FCC rules, it is not allowed to continue to carry a network's
signal without a transmission agreement in place. (The deal with
Disney has expired.) Disney, however, contends that FCC regulations
do not allow a cable operator to stop airing a broadcast station
during a sweeps period.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts speculate that Disney may be playing hardball in an
effort to slow the AOL-Time Warner merger by persuading federal
regulators to look at the competitive and consumer issues involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could be hoping someone will come in and set some rules
on how much you can own,'' said Dan Amundson, research director at
the Center for Media and Public Affairs. ``Even if they don't stop
the Time-Warner/AOL merger, maybe they can tie them up for a while
by persuading the Justice Department that there's too much
concentration of power.''
</P>
<P>
   Turow added: ``Disney does not own cable systems, and that can
potentially put Disney and other companies, like News Corp., in a
difficult position when negotiating with cable firms. . . .
Time-Warner clearly has control over the exhibition arena into
people's homes. Disney wants to get its (product) into those homes,
and in order to do that, it has to have leverage.''
</P>
<P>
   That leverage may be the fact that federal regulators are
looking closely at everything Time-Warner does, especially actions
that might be seen as anticompetitive. ``Disney may be thinking
`AOL is under scrutiny in Washington, so maybe the atmosphere is
better for us,' '' Wolzien said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from Disney and Time-Warner met Monday with staff
members of the Federal Communications Commission, but at day's end,
the stalemate had not been resolved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
