<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-COMMENT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIMING AT CARROLL, GRIER SANK HIMSELF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ If you bury the old coach, don't expect the
new coach to embrace you.
</P>
<P>
   That's the lesson to be learned from the firing of Patriots vice
president of personnel Bobby Grier by Bill Belichick.
</P>
<P>
   When Pete Carroll was in his final days last season, the rats
deserted the ship. So did Grier, a normally quiet man who
apparently was overwhelmed by the possibility of facing
unemployment himself and unknowingly took steps to assure it.
</P>
<P>
   When Grier began to tell every microphone and pen he could find
that Carroll and his assistants had talent enough to win but hadn't
properly developed it, he revealed a long-running beef he'd had
with Carroll over the use of the talent Grier had imported for him.
</P>
<P>
   The timing couldn't have been worse, and when Grier began to be
heavily criticized in this corner as disloyal, he tried to back
away from his own words and claim he'd never meant to criticize
anyone, just point out his faith in his draft picks and a
philosophical difference with Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the more he talked, the more Grier hanged himself. Who will
ever forget his explanation of failed No. 1 draft choice Chris
Canty? Grier could have had Sam Madison, who has become a Pro Bowl
cornerback in Miami, but opted for Canty, who was described in this
space on draft day as ``a slow dwarf,'' which turned out to be
exactly what he was.
</P>
<P>
   After Canty proved to be a bust in New England and was released
last year, Grier claimed he'd never intended for Canty to be a
starter; he merely had drafted him as a backup, he said. Who uses
No. 1 draft choices to select backups?
</P>
<P>
   Nobody, if they know what they're doing, which more and more it
began to seem Grier did not. At least not as well as a man he
helped drive out of the organization: Charley Armey.
</P>
<P>
   Once Grier worked for Armey, but Bill Parcells and owner Bob
Kraft shook up the organization several years ago and jumped Grier
ahead of Armey even though it was Armey who set the draft board in
the good days when the Patriots took Curtis Martin and Ted Johnson
and Ty Law and Lawyer Milloy.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, according to sources inside the Patriots' organization,
Grier began to undermine Armey now that he was his superior,
finally embarrassing him in his final days in New England when he
was a lame duck by sending him home when the draft meetings were
held. The implication was that the most honest man in that
organization might reveal trade secrets to his future employers,
the St. Louis Rams.
</P>
<P>
   Well, what goes around comes around some day, and this was one
of those days. While Armey sits in St. Louis with a promotion to
general manger, a new multiyear contract extension, and a Super
Bowl ring partly the product of the talent he brought in the past
three years (including MVP Kurt Warner), Grier is unemployed.
</P>
<P>
   After what he did to Carroll and his staff when they were
already down, he may be in that condition considerably longer than
Armey was.
</P>
<P>
   But what really doomed Grier were two things: his disastrous
1997 draft and his near-total waste of the six high draft picks the
Patriots acquired from the New York Jets as ransom for losing
Parcells and Martin to them.
</P>
<P>
   When Belichick announced his decision to ax Grier and his
assistant Dave Uyrus, he said, ``This is an unpleasant thing for me
to do. I recognize that Bobby Grier has made significant
contributions to the New England Patriots over many years, in
various capacities, as has Dave Uyrus. I enjoyed a good working
relationship with Bobby in preparation for the recent draft, as I
did in 1996. This decision is unrelated to any specific event,
performance or personal relationship. It is more a reflection of my
general feeling to proceed in a new direction with regard to the
structure and operation of our personnel department.''
</P>
<P>
   Belichick was not being disingenuous. The sacking of Grier did
not relate to any specific event or performance, it related to a
string of them. Primarily, it related to the players he drafted
since taking over from Armey and Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   It also related to the hiring of longtime Belichick confidant
Scott Pioli, who came with him from the Jets as ``assistant''
personnel director. If Bobby Grier understood anything about how
the NFL works, he knew Pioli wouldn't be his ``assistant'' for
long.
</P>
<P>
   What he should have known as well was that the minute he
publicly flogged Pete Carroll, he had to hope the man who replaced
him didn't come in the way Belichick did _ with the power to fire
him.
</P>
<P>
   You don't keep Sammy ``The Bull'' Gravano around if you're John
Gotti, and you don't keep Bobby Grier around if you're Bill
Belichick.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
