<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVENTS PLUNK TEAMS RIGHT INTO THE MIDDLE OF A RIVALRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Brushbacks. Knockdowns. Hit batsmen. Emptied benches.
Intimidation. Enforcers. Suspensions.
</P>
<P>
   Even on a day when the Patriots finally fired their de facto
general manager, Pedro Martinez's Sunday war with the Indians was
Sports Topic No. 1 around Greater Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro lit the match when he dusted Tribe catcher Einar
``Cameron'' Diaz, and it was a raging blaze by the time the Red Sox
flew out of Ohio Sunday night. Cleveland newspapers called Pedro
``chicken'' for staying in the dugout during the nonfight, and Red
Sox general manager Dan Duquette returned fire when he said, ``The
Indians can't beat him within the rules of the game. They have to
look at alternative ways to beat Pedro Martinez. This isn't
anything new, but our guys stayed within the rules. Pedro was doing
his job in terms of pitching inside. Pedro has beaten Cleveland
consistently and they've tried different strategies _ stepping out
of the batter's box, taking a long time when they are hitting.
Those things are all designed to upset Pedro because they can't
beat him within the rules.''
</P>
<P>
   In Cleveland, Indians general manager John Hart declined to
respond to Duquette's remarks, but he told the Cleveland
Plain-Dealer, ``You have to give Pedro his due, but the only thing
that took the edge off is that I think he threw a pitch that was
way too close to Einar's head. That was a dangerous pitch. It was
just too much of a coincidence. I just think Pedro Martinez is
better than that. He threw right at Einar's head.''
</P>
<P>
   It's like the Elian Gonzalez case and the Reggie Lewis trial.
Everyone has an opinion . . .
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Was the pitch to Diaz an effective ``purpose pitch'' or designed
to maim? . . . Should Jose Offerman have charged the mound when he
was hit by Charles Nagy? . . . Will there be any suspensions handed
down by Frank Robinson? . . . Was Pedro chicken for staying in the
dugout when the benches emptied? . . . Was it poor judgment to risk
blowing a game by retaliating or did Pedro's plunking of Roberto
Alomar serve to further galvanize the Boston clubhouse? . . . What
happens next time the Sox meet the Tribe (June 8)?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(unitals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This much is certain: The Sox have come a long way since the
days of ``25 players, 25 cabs'' and Joe Price's solo charge up San
Juan Hill when none of the other Sox came out of the dugout for a
would-be fight in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette said the Sox had been in communication with Robinson's
office (one of the great plate-crowders, Frank is now in charge of
doling out the suspensions). The Duke said he expected no
suspensions. Pedro said he warned Offerman that he would be hit,
and told his countryman/teammate not to charge the mound. Cleveland
manager Charlie Manuel said Pedro started the whole thing.
Shortstop Omar Vizquel said Pedro should be suspended.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette is right about one thing: Pedro is 7-0 lifetime against
Cleveland and has hurled 20 consecutive scoreless innings against
the Tribe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's not a big secret he can beat us,'' said Vizquel.
``I know for sure he can beat us, but I think it's pretty
(expletive) that a guy who is dominating the game the way he is,
and the guy who got two hits off him, he's got to go up and in on
him at his chin. I don't know for what. He should be suspended just
for what he did. Just like any other player.''
</P>
<P>
   Manuel added, ``He deliberately hit the guy (Alomar). Not only
that, watch the game, somebody must have a film, but if you watch
Diaz get two hits off him and after he got the second double he
turns around on the mound and stands there and stares at him, kind
of mockery at him. Then when he comes up again, he throws two balls
at him right at his face. To me, without a doubt he's throwing at
him. I mean, he started it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pedro was still claiming to be little more than an innocent
bystander, just doing his job with no emotions attached.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I should get suspended for that,'' he said.
``I'm not worried, either, but I don't think I should. (Throwing
inside) has been going on for as long as the game has been going
on. Suspend me? Why? I didn't fight. I just do what I have to do
for my team.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the ace of this staff I'm out to say that I'm going to
protect my hitters. I understood what I have to do and I told Offy
not to come out if he gets hit. And if they hit him, what am I
supposed to do? I'm not going to change a thing. There's no
discipline to be issued. There was no fight. This is all part of
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Diaz is a catcher. He knows that pitching inside is part of
the game. He is just a rookie. He should take his place and
understand that after he gets two knocks on changes away, he has to
expect something in to try to get him out.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be a ton said and written about this when the Sox and
Indians play again next month and especially when they host the
baseball-palooza (five games in three days) at Fenway in September.
</P>
<P>
   And what about the playoffs, folks? How great will this be
when/if Pedro toes the rubber at the Jake again in October? Pedro
has infuriated Cleveland. The Duke has said they can't beat him
without cheating. The Indians say he's gutless. Red Sox-Indians
could be as good as Sox-Yankees. Maybe better.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist; Gordon Edes of the Globe
staff contributed to this column from Cleveland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-00 1321EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
