<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-NEWENGLAND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHATEVER YOU'D LIKE TO SEE OR DO, NEW ENGLAND'S GOT IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The grass may seem greener elsewhere, but there's nothing wrong
with discovering your own backyard.
</P>
<P>
   New Englanders have so much to enjoy, especially in summer, that
it almost makes no sense to travel afar. Within a couple of hours
of Boston, one can be in the mountains or wilderness, vacation at
the ocean or a lake, stay on a farm, a luxurious resort, or an
island, live it up in a world-class city, savor great dining and
great art, relax, or enjoy an adventure.
</P>
<P>
   Few other areas in the country offer as much diversity of
vacation options _ especially ones packed with fun, history, and
discoveries.
</P>
<P>
   Just scanning the list of happenings throughout New England
proves there's too much to do in one season. So plan on ``doing''
New England again and again.
</P>
<P>
   Even the experts at Yankee Magazine agree. Carol Connare,
associate editor of this year's Travel Guide to New England, notes:
``When I was younger, I traveled to every corner of North America,
including living for a time in Alaska. I had a notion that to `see
the world' I had to go far away, but I was always drawn back to New
England. I've learned that some of the greatest treasures are in
your own backyard.''
</P>
<P>
   Need proof? Then just hit the road; you'll find treasures in
every part of New England.
</P>
<P>
   Some of my best vacation experiences were on an island off the
coast of Maine. It was a seven-hour drive to get there, but worth
every minute. It was Maine living at its best. Fresh lobsters right
off the boat, great island life, a wonderful hidden sandy beach on
the ocean (sure, the water was freezing, but it'd do for a dip once
a year; otherwise we'd head for the old quarry where the water was
perfect). It was a wonderful change of pace.
</P>
<P>
   Then we started moving. First to Orange, Mass., just a 1
1/2-hour drive from Boston but a world away. This was Hidden
Massachusetts, the state's most rural county, where I realized that
one didn't have to drive seven hours to escape city life _ it was
within commuting distance. Laurie Bongiormo, innkeeper of
Kennybunkport, Maine's, wonderful White Barn Inn, would tease me by
noting he could reach Boston in less time than it took me to drive
from Orange.
</P>
<P>
   Now that I live in the Blackstone Valley area that encompasses
parts of Rhode Island and Massachusetts, I'm making new discoveries
even closer to Boston. Providence, for example, is a delight. Get
off Interstate 95 and within a few blocks on College Hill are
beautiful homes dating to the early 1800s, and on the other side of
95 is Federal Hill, filled with taste-tempting Italian restaurants.
Why, the actual city is even more interesting that the TV series
``Providence.''
</P>
<P>
   Rhode Island may be small but it has a lot to offer. Newport,
already known for its grand ``cottages'' _ those palatial former
summer homes of some of the then richest people in America, will
soon have another grand mansion to tour.
</P>
<P>
   Rough Point, the home of Doris Duke, a woman of mystery and
great wealth, will open for limited tours in May. What makes this
105-room mansion along the Cliff Walk special is Duke herself. The
home, which has been closed since her death in 1993, will appear
just as she left it after living there for 70 years. While Duke was
a very private person, she is responsible for maintaining Newport's
Colonial era. She founded The Newport Restoration Foundation and
paid millions to buy and restore some 84 Colonial-era houses in the
city. The foundation now owns and rents the homes.
</P>
<P>
   Boston, though, is still my town. And, what a summer it is
planning. The John F. Kennedy Museum offers ``Jacqueline Kennedy:
Travels Abroad'' beginning May 27, highlighting her travels as the
first lady to Paris, India, Pakistan, Rome, and London. Then on
June 2 the museum opens an exhibit on JFK's love of the sea and
sailing.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Museum of Science has two blockbusters. ``Secrets of
Aging,'' now on view, is the first comprehensve exhibit on the
topic of aging. More than 500,000 people are expected to view it.
Opening June 22 is the ``T Rex Sue Exhibition'' featuring a cast of
the largest and most complete T Rex specimens ever found.
</P>
<P>
   The Museum of Fine Arts will serve up a stunningly beautiful
show, ``Van Gogh: Face to Face,'' begins July 2 through Sept. 24.
It showcases more than 70 of the artist's finest portraits.
</P>
<P>
   And, for a real spectacular, see Tall Ships 2000. The July 10-21
festival will feature 70 ships from 30 countries. There will be a
grand parade, public boarding of ships, and fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   This is but a small sample of what New England has to offer.
Other activities include white-water rafting, hiking, sailing on a
windjammer, going on a whale watch, and lots more.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
