<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-NOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWPORT: A CITY OF FIRSTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Newport, R.I., is filled with ``firsts.'' Among other things,
this historic and colorful city was:
</P>
<P>
   --The first to have a ferry service (1657).
</P>
<P>
   --The first to pass a traffic ordinance (1687).
</P>
<P>
   --The first to host a circus in this country (1774).
</P>
<P>
   --The first of the 13 colonies to declare independence from
England (May 4, 1776).
</P>
<P>
   --The first to have gas-illuminated streetlights (1803).
</P>
<P>
   --The first to host the International Polo Match (1886), Open
Golf Tournament (1895), and National Lawn Tennis Championships
(1899).
</P>
<P>
   --And the first place in the United States where an arrest was
made for an auto violation (1904). The driver was charged with
going an astonishing 15 miles an hour!
</P>
<P>
   (For more information on this city of firsts, call the Newport
County Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau at 401-849-8048, write to the
bureau at 23 America's Cup Ave., Newport, RI 02840, or visit
www.gonewport.com.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Trivia: Which New England state was once an independent
republic? (Answer at end of column.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
And the winner is . . . Congratulations to Ellen Sahl of Sharon,
winner of the Wacky Shorts Contest. She and her husband, Scott,
will get a free Boston-Bermuda cruise aboard the Norwegian Majesty
for submitting a photo of the wackiest pair of Bermuda shorts,
chosen from more than 125 entries. And those shorts, designed by
Sahl and her 11-year-old daughter, Vicki, are wacky indeed, with
foil accents and bananas, too. For a photo, see Page XXX. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quotable: ``A friend told me she visited a little shop in Maine and
asked the saleslady if she carried a certain commodity. `We used to
stock them,' she replied in a perfectly rational tone, `but we
always sold out right away, so we stopped ordering them.' '' _
Joseph Gallagher. &QL; 
 &QL; 
In a name: You may know or surmise that Boston's Beacon Street was
named for a beacon once located there. But did you know that the
beacon was actually a bucket of tar? The bucket was mounted atop a
65-foot pole and was to be lighted to warn of any enemy approach.
But it was never lighted, and today a 60-foot column topped with an
eagle to commemorate the War of Independence is in its place.
What's more, in the 17th century the street was called Poor House
Lane because it was near an almshouse. Nobody would use the word
``poor'' in connection with Beacon Hill today. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Today's loopy law: New Hampshire forbids selling the clothes you
are wearing to pay a gambling debt. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Old friend: All states have official flowers or birds, but
Connecticut has a state fossil, too. It's called eubrontes
giganteus, a large, three-toed impression in the Connecticut Valley
that dates to early Jurassic days, some 200 million years ago. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel bookshelf: Boston's North Shore is really a special place
(and not just because I live there). Just how special becomes
readily apparent when reading ``Hidden Treasures on Boston's North
Shore'' by Harriet Webster (Commonwealth Editions, $12.95). In
addition to describing the many attractions and events in
communities from Lynn to Newburyport, the book offers clues to a
literal treasure worth $3,000 _ a limited-edition Millennium Clock,
provided by Descenza Diamonds in Peabody. Following those clues
will lead you to a document that proclaims you the winner. Monthly
hints to interpret the clues will be given at the Descenza store
and on the publisher's Web site, www.commonwealtheditions.com.
Happy hunting. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? Vermont.
</P>
