<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF THE MIGHTY CAN LOSE THEIR SHIRTS, SO CAN YOU 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In his new book about day trading, ``Dumb Money,'' Joey Anuff
recounts the moment when he realized he had to quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came to day trading looking for a way out of the choas of
blind betting, of surprise swings that could make or break me,'' he
says. ``But when the crucial moment comes _ and it comes every day
_ the sheer unknowability of the future gets in the way.''
</P>
<P>
   George Soros can probably sympathize with Anuff. So can Julian
Robertson. The two, among the most legendary hedge fund investors
of our time, have been humbled of late by the ``unknowability'' of
the financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson shut down his hedge fund in March after heavy losses
and investor withdrawals. Soros isn't quitting, but he said Friday
that he is scaling back his operation and reducing risk after a
string of disappointments. Two of his top deputies quit altogether.
</P>
<P>
   At first blush, the news might cheer average investors the way
average golfers are heartened when they watch Tiger Woods flub a
shot. ``See, even the best of the best screw up.'' But upon closer
examination, investors probably ought to take a different lesson
away from the troubles of Mssrs. Soros and Robertson.
</P>
<P>
   The duo's woes suggest that investing is hard and humbling and
risky _ words that generally have not been associated with the
stock market in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   Soros' Quantum fund racked up incredible gains over the past 30
years, making big bets on interest rates and currencies. In 1992 he
earned a profit of $1 billion by betting successfully against the
British pound.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two years, however, Soros' luck has soured. In 1998
he lost big when the Russian economy collapsed. More recently he
bet wrong on the euro. He thought it would strengthen against the
dollar; instead it has plunged to new lows.
</P>
<P>
   Soros' chief lieutenant, Stanley Druckenmiller, invested heavily
in biotech and tech stocks last year. The strategy worked until
April, when both groups lost ground in a huge sell-off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I screwed up,'' Druckenmiller told The New York Times. ``I
overplayed my hand. I should have sold in February.'' As day trader
Joey Anuff writes in ``Dumb Money,'' ``To be a day trader is to
make regret into a lifestyle.''
</P>
<P>
   Robertson's Tiger Management funds had a great run for 18 years,
turning in annual gains of 30 percent. But in the last 18 months,
Robertson has stumbled badly. He lost money betting on the Japanese
yen and on Russian bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Druckenmiller, he avoided technology stocks, preferring
to stick with old economy names like General Motors and US Airways.
When those stocks lost value in 1999 and early this year, investors
headed for the exits and Robertson had to sell to meet redemptions.
</P>
<P>
   It should be pointed out that another legendary investor, Warren
Buffett, has taken his lumps sticking with old economy names like
Gillette and Coke. Shares in Buffett's company, Berkshire Hathaway,
are trading below where they were two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line: there are lots of ways to lose money.
</P>
<P>
   Both Soros and Robertson have suggested they are victims of a
changing market. With so many investors and so much information, it
is hard today, they argue, to find the inefficiences they once
exploited. Robertson also blamed the herd mentality behind the
runup in technology stocks. ``We are in a market where reason does
not prevail,'' he groused.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that is true. But maybe it is just sour grapes. The
history of Wall Street is the history of booms and busts, euphoria
and gloom. The time between the ups and downs may have shrunk, but
otherwise it is hard to see that things have changed very much.
</P>
<P>
   What tripped up Soros and Robertson was the ``unknowability of
the future.'' How could they know the Russian economy would tank?
Or that tech stocks would go straight up for months only to go
straight down again? Or that the euro would be worth 92 cents, not
$1.10?
</P>
<P>
   They couldn't. And neither can the rest of us. That doesn't mean
we need to drain our stock funds and keep all our savings in
certificates of deposit.
</P>
<P>
   It does mean, however, we should be mindful of the risks
inherent in investing. It means we should make small bets, not big
ones, diversify our holdings, maintain a long-term perspective and
always have some cash around for a rainy day. It is boring advice
to be sure, but advice worth keeping in mind.
</P>
<P>
   If the giants can lose their shirts, so can we little guys.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com
</P>
</TEXT>
