<HEADLINE>
THE NEXT HOT SECTOR: CONVERGENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Looking for a sector that still excites venture capitalists?
Here's one: It's a foggy place full of entertainment and
possibility _ somewhere between cyberspace and your living room
couch _ where TV and the Web mingle.
</P>
<P>
   They call it ``convergence'' (because all things Web-related
must have strange monikers) and it's the catch-all term for a
burgeoning industry looking to squeeze more profits out of tube
watchers everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, advertisers already spend $45 billion a year peddling
their brands and products on television. But as the TV moguls and
Web gurus see it, there's a whole new world in linking the data
flow of the Web and the television set.
</P>
<P>
   Advertisers want to better target their audiences, the players
in this business say. They want to lead ready buyers to the Web to
spend money. As for TV viewers, they may want to sort through
programming options more efficiently, and even be able to pause a
show midstream to grab a beer. Some may want to communicate with
other fans of their favorite shows.
</P>
<P>
   Does that mean people are going to be sitting around watching TV
on a computer screen? Well, some might. But that's not the main
point of the convergence game. Larry Namer, founder of E!, the
television show and online entertainment news site, says: ``You're
going to give me something in a postage stamp-sized box, and expect
me to get excited about it?''
</P>
<P>
   Namer's Steeplechase Media Inc. in Los Angeles is a partner with
Boston's MarkeTVision in a venture called Television.com. They're
approaching the convergence arena from the standpoint of giving TV
watchers a reason to love TV more, and to log onto related Web
sites.
</P>
<P>
   The company produces, for example, 30-minute programs aimed at
specific groups of people. They market the program intensely, on
the Web and elsewhere, and then try to lure viewers to make
purchases.
</P>
<P>
   MarkeTVision chief executive Andrew Miller gives the example of
a half-hour Grateful Dead video for VH1. Fans of the band watched
the show, then jumped on the Web. The show spurred the sale of
15,000 CDs in one week, he says.
</P>
<P>
   The key to success, Miller argues, is not only the product but
being able to market the concept itself. Thus the name
Television.com. ``With all the dot-com clutter that's out there,''
he says, ``we decided brand had to come first.'' His company is
also helping back sites such as Telephone.com and Sportsfan.com.
</P>
<P>
   Other players are working on ``video streaming,'' to improve the
look of video on the Web. Still others are making digital tuner
cards for computers, so they can work like TVs. Cable companies are
building boxes to put on your TV that will be much smarter than the
old ones.
</P>
<P>
   The flurry of activity around convergence is based on the idea
that all those TVs and computers in 100 million households each
around the country have got to be more useful together than apart.
The tube is turned on seven hours a day in the average home,
according to Nielsen Media Research. People are on the Internet an
average of just 30 minutes a day, Nielsen says.
</P>
<P>
   But Internet use is climbing, and some of that could be driven
by TV watchers. Steeplechase's Namer says his own kids, young
teens, come home from school and watch MTV; then they go to an AOL
chat room to chat with friends about what they're watching. It's
possible to do all that on one screen, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Only about 1 million people currently have the technology set up
at home to interact with their TVs, Namer says. But industry
followers predict that could rise to 40 million within a few years.
</P>
<P>
   There's already interactive Judge Judy on the Web. There are
sites like TVparty.com and jumptheshark.com, which are online
communities for television trivia aficionados.
</P>
<P>
   And even if you're not the type to go online to yak about
``Seinfeld'' reruns, you might like your TV to alert you to any
Bogart films or sports shows running this week. Namer also foresees
your own stocks strolling across the screen when you watch the
business news, instead of random Dow or Nasdaq stocks. Even the
weather or news reports could be tailored to individual interests.
</P>
<P>
   It's all about making your TV work harder for you, Namer says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care about the weather in Paris this weekend. I'm not
going there.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Beth Healy is a member of the Globe staff. She can be reached by
e-mail at bhealy(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
