<SLUG> BC-TECHNO-ROUNDUP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEAUTIFUL PROFITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE STOUGHTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't add Chris Ambler's voice to the chorus of
bricks-and-mortar merchants complaining about the online
competition.
</P>
<P>
   In an ironic twist, Internet retailers are sending business to
his store, Frame Smart in Chestnut Hill. More than a year ago, the
store manager began noticing that customers in this highly wired
locality were bringing in more prints and posters purchased from
Internet sites such as eBay.com.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first to be framed was a print of a colorful Keith
Haring painting. Since then, FrameSmart has welcomed a steady
stream of prints, paintings, and even cereal boxes into its store.
And it's more than eBay. Sellers now include art.com, iwant.com,
and antiques sites.
</P>
<P>
   Ambler estimates that FrameSmart has picked up an extra $500 in
sales each week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Web has definitely helped us,'' he said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Losing weight on the Web &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The idea of managing weight loss while blobbed out in front of a
computer may elicit a few giggles. But Web firms like Inner Workout
Inc. of Boston say they're serious about helping consumers slim
down.
</P>
<P>
   Like a fitness center, innerworkout.com charges consumers an
annual membership fee of $100. The only problem is that the package
doesn't include a Stairmaster or weights. (And forget about squash
courts.)
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Web site offers ``learning themes'' and personal
storytelling with tips from experts in nutrition, exercise
physiolog,y and women's psychology. Women are given tools to learn
``InnerSkills'' to help them identify and change behavior ``from
the inside out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's incredible to see the difference when you address a
weight problem at the root-cause level,'' gushes Michelle Toth,
chief executive of Inner Workout.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to critics, the company attached a Brown University
study that shows Internet weight loss programs may help reduce the
public health burden on obesity.
</P>
<P>
   But wouldn't it be more effective to tell consumers to log off
and take a walk? That's not likely to happen. Weight management
sites are no different than any other Web businesses: They want to
keep consumers from clicking off. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Divided by sound systems &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As a vice president at Hifi.com and HerHifi.com, a sister
consumer electronics store that targets women, Roger Sullivan
should have known better than to buy a stereo system without
consulting his wife.
</P>
<P>
   But there he was last fall, merrily hauling the boxes into their
new Marblehead home, only to be greeted by his wife's stony stare.
</P>
<P>
   In the consumer electronics business, a gaping gender divide
exists. Research shows men view sound systems as a purchase of the
heart, and they want all the bells and whistles, including extra
power. Women tend to be more practical, aiming for visually
appealing equipment that doesn't take up too much space.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't need jets roaring overhead,'' joked Laurie Nova,
HerHifi.com's program manager.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan now agrees. His wife, Ada, told him that the stereo did
not fit into the home decor, so the couple decided on a more
compact model.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really does make a difference,'' he said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Loyalty only goes so far &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A new research report questions whether e-commerce companies'
loyalty programs create loyal shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   More than 75 percent of online consumers said they take part in
loyalty programs that give incentives to frequent buyers, according
to a survey of 1,200 Internet shoppers by Jupiter Communications
and NFO Interactive.
</P>
<P>
   Few shoppers, however, said incentive programs were important in
motivating them to step up their purchases, the survey showed.
Instead, online consumers placed higher values on easy returns,
customer service and product selection.
</P>
<P>
   Even travel e-commerce sites, early innovators in developing
aggressive incentive programs, ``have yet to extend their retention
and loyalty efforts to the Web effectively,'' Jupiter analysts
wrote.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
