<SLUG> BC-TECHNO-MIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIT GRADS HAVE MADE A PLACE FOR THEMSELVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ATHERTON, Calif. _ Snickering about snow in Boston, more than
200 graduates of the Massachusetts Institute of Technology gathered
beneath a balmy California sunset last week to reflect on their
good fortunes _ and not just in regard to the weather.
</P>
<P>
   There was Bill Porter, MIT class of '67 and founder of ETrade,
who is about to launch an online securities exchange for stock
options. Steve Kirsch, class of '78, was also there, still glowing
from the sale of Infoseek Corp., a search engine he founded and
sold to Walt Disney Co. last year for more than $1.7 billion.
Nearby was Kevin J. Kinsella, who busied himself after graduating
from MIT's Sloan School of Management in 1967 by starting 53
software and biotech companies.
</P>
<P>
   These are the ``nerdtrepreneurs'' that have made MIT famous in
Silicon Valley as the school that keeps pumping out technologically
astute eager beavers with a penchant for starting their own
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with William R. Hewlett, MIT class of '36, who
cofounded Hewlett-Packard Co. in Palo Alto in 1939, the list of
Silicon Valley companies founded by MIT graduates has grown to
include Intel Corp., National Semiconductor, Genentech, and Cirrus
Logic, to name a few.
</P>
<P>
   A 1995 survey by BankBoston counted 287 companies in Northern
California founded by MIT graduates. These companies had sales of
$66 billion and worldwide employment of 287,000. They accounted for
one-quarter of the manufacturing jobs in Silicon Valley, and 29
percent of the area's electronics jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the MIT family of companies has further swelled with
the addition of the ``dot com'' babies. Some have become familiar
names, like Webvan Group Inc., started by Louis Borders, a one-time
MIT graduate student and founder of Borders Books. But many others
are just arriving on the scene, hoping to become the next ETrade.
These include Portfolio Corner Inc., Smartbasket.com, Xporta,
Quova, and Embark.com.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these companies' founders were at the MIT reception last
week at the Menlo Circus Club, noshing on caviar, smoked duck and
truffled mousse pate. All were instructed by their invitations to
dress in ``uptight East Coast business attire,'' and most complied,
looking slightly awkward in their navy blue suits, many of which
haven't been worn in years.
</P>
<P>
   The hosts of the event were Richard Schmalensee, dean of the MIT
Sloan School of Management and a member of the MIT class of '65,
and Kenneth P. Morse, a '68 graduate and managing director of the
school's Entrepreneurship Center. Both wore chunky school rings
featuring the MIT beaver _ nature's star engineer.
</P>
<P>
   Morse, who helped found 3COM, also sported a tie with beavers
busily chopping down trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the Stanford tree,'' joked Morse in reference to a
decades-old friendly rivalry between MIT and Stanford University,
whose official seal features a tall tree.
</P>
<P>
   There are 7,000 MIT alumni in Northern California, most of them
in Silicon Valley, said Schmalensee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Silicon Valley has the third-largest concentration of MIT
alumni after Boston and New York,'' he said. Asked why MIT grads
are drawn to the Valley, he replied: ``MIT is about innovation, and
so is Silicon Valley.''
</P>
<P>
   The reception, meant to recognize distinguished alumni, is also
a vehicle for the school to cultivate potential donors. Porter of
ETrade has donated $25 million to the Sloan School, while Kirsch's
$2.5 million donation has resulted in an auditorium at the school
named after him.
</P>
<P>
   Kinsella, who founded 53 companies and has promised $1 million
to MIT in his will, reflected on the effect the school has had in
his endeavors and how it distinguishes him from the masses.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no substitute for the underpinnings in science and
technology that the school gives you,'' said Kinsella. ``Without
that, you'd be easily bamboozled by technology. We know how to ask
the right questions.''
</P>
<P>
   David Weitz, a partner with Silicon Valley law firm Wilson
Sonsini Goodrich &AMP; Rosati who graduated from MIT in 1987 with a
bachelor's degree in chemistry, summed it up this way: ``What's our
legacy here? We're the underrecognized builders of Silicon
Valley.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Alex Pham is a Globe reporter covering Silicon Valley. She can
be reached by e-mail at pham(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-00 1329EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
