<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3254 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-02 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BUSH FIRES BACK WITH A WEAPON NAMED RICE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ What presidential race?
</P>
<P>
   Like most Americans, for weeks I've been avoiding thinking about
Al Gore and George W. Bush. On the whole, I'd rather think about
Cream of Wheat or rice pudding.
</P>
<P>
   But suddenly, out of the mushiness of the two presumptive
nominees' presumptive campaigns appears an intelligent,
strong-willed, articulate woman.
</P>
<P>
   Is it relevant to add that she's black and beautiful, as well as
an expert on Russia?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it is relevant, because Condoleezza Rice is working as a
top adviser for Bush, who needs the votes of women and minorities.
When she rebuts a speech by Gore, as she did the other day, voters
wake up, take a look and do some listening.
</P>
<P>
   You can disagree with Rice on matters of foreign policy, or
whether America should invest billions in questionable technology
to counter a missile threat that doesn't exist. But you have to
agree she's livened things up.
</P>
<P>
   Rice attacked Gore on behalf of Bush on Sunday, but she's also
Bush's anti-Quayle device, a counterweight to Bush's lack of
weightiness.
</P>
<P>
   Gore once said Bush is ``noticeably blank'' on foreign policy.
Bush filled in the blank with Rice, a former Stanford University
provost and political science professor, and a member of the
National Security Council under Bush's father.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview, Bush the Younger called her a ``brilliant
person (who) can explain to me foreign policy matters in a way I
can understand.''
</P>
<P>
   You can almost hear it now.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see, W, it's like a football rivalry. China, Russia and
the United States are like Yale, Princeton and Harvard. They'll
always be rivals, no matter what their standings or academic
exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we always have to be ready to counter threats from small
rogue powers like Iraq and North Korea _ in Ivy League football
terms, the equivalents of Columbia and Brown.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice is a big football fan and served on the search committees
for two Stanford coaches, so I'm sure she could come up with even
better football analogies for international affairs, ones that W
could understand, of course.
</P>
<P>
   A friend of mine asked, ``If Condoleezza Rice is so smart, why
is she working for George W. Bush?''
</P>
<P>
   I think the question should be reversed. If George W. Bush is so
dumb, why does he have Condoleezza Rice working for him?
</P>
<P>
   Think about it. When Rice cut loose against Gore, there were a
couple of messages.
</P>
<P>
   She accused Gore of misrepresenting Bush as an out-of-touch cold
warrior when it comes to Russia and China, and it was pretty
effective. Where Gore had linked Bush to an extremist like Sen.
Jesse Helms of North Carolina, Bush was fighting back with an
expert of the stature of Rice.
</P>
<P>
   That's quite an implicit message: Bush trusts an intellectual
black woman to go out front for him, and she believes in him enough
to do it.
</P>
<P>
   If I were Al Gore, I'd be getting nervous. In fact, to judge by
Gore's idiotic pandering on the matter of Elian Gonzalez, I think
he is getting nervous.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is a reasonably smart guy (or so we are told) who is
impossible to listen to. Bush is a regular guy (or so we are told)
who also is impossible to listen to. But he may be smart enough to
pick good people to speak for him.
</P>
<P>
   Where Clinton stole all but a few planks of the Republican
platform, Bush is sneaking in and capturing some core Democratic
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Several polls show that the new environmentally friendly,
educationally cuddly Bush has pulled ahead of Gore, particularly in
education policy, where he has made a ringing call to wipe out
illiteracy. The Los Angeles Times even reported Bush has pulled
ahead of Gore among women.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that Texas has a terrible record on health care and
the environment, and that Gov. Bush of Texas is an executioner, fan
of concealed weapons and opponent of abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   Image is everything, I guess. Gore persists in having an
irritatingly blank image, and when he tries to shed that image he
tends to shout, exaggerate or pander. Meanwhile, Bush is playing
nice guy, shedding the ghost of Bob Jones, and taking advice from
people like Condoleezza Rice.
</P>
<P>
   Her image is everything, too. When she speaks of the 1972
Anti-ballistic Missile Treaty as a ``historical artifact'' that
stands in the way of deploying a nuclear missile defense system,
she sounds more credible than Bush would.
</P>
<P>
   It's doubtful he knows what ``ABM'' stands for, or could
reliably pronounce the word ``artifact.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's all very expensive baloney. Tests of anti-missile
missiles all have failed miserably. Hitting a warhead in space, one
that can come from points as distant as North Korea or Iraq, is
like trying to hit a needle in midair with a rock.
</P>
<P>
   The mythical missile defense system is an expensive boondoggle,
one that still threatens the Russians because it is, in fact, an
offensive weapon in terms of nuclear game theory _ if it were
possible to build such a weapon, that is.
</P>
<P>
   It's really just an offensive weapon for Republicans and
Condoleezza Rice to use against Al Gore, and he's on the defensive.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
