<SLUG> BC-PAN-AM-GAMES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SAN ANTONIO, RIO DE JANEIRO EARLY COMPETITORS FOR PAN AM
GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JERRY BRIGGS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ The Brazilian city of Rio de Janeiro, known for
its seaside beauty, romance and party spirit, will compete against
San Antonio for the right to host the 2007 Pan American Games.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Krier, president of the Greater San Antonio Chamber of
Commerce, said Rio de Janeiro will provide stiff competition. The
Pan American Sports Organization (PASO) is expected to announce the
2007 host city in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are a strong candidate,'' Krier said, ``and they will
have the strong backing of the national government. But, they do
not have a local organizing committee yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Rio de Janeiro's candidacy had been rumored since February after
Brazil dropped out of contention for the 2008 Summer Olympics. That
bid became official on April 27 when Rio made its plans known on
the first day of the PASO meetings in San Jose, Costa Rica.
</P>
<P>
   Also at that meeting, U.S. Olympic Committee President Bill Hybl
formally announced San Antonio's 2007 candidacy for the Pan
American Games. No other city made an official statement, though
Guadalajara, Mexico, appears to be interested, Krier said.
</P>
<P>
   Rio, stretched across a coastal plain and on slopes of coastal
mountains at Guanabara Bay on the Atlantic Ocean, is legendary for
its picturesque location.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Frost Jr., the chairman of the San Antonio Sports
Foundation, said it's important to be in the same race with Rio. He
is not intimidated by the battle for the games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it means we're an international city like
Rio,'' Frost said, ``but we do feel we can host the games as well
or better than Rio. It's exciting to be in a competition with them.
It's important for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Krier said he was one of nearly 20 people from San Antonio in
Costa Rica. The city sent five delegates to the PASO meetings. The
rest were members of the San Antonio Free Trade Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we walked into the reception with 18 or 19 people, that
was impressive,'' Krier said. ``I think we're off to a pretty good
start.''
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the PASO meeting, Krier said it appears certain
that the Dominican Republic will be able to host the 2003 Games, as
planned. It had been rumored that the Dominican Republic might not
be able to stage the event because of economic concerns stemming
from damages caused by Hurricane Georges in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I'm concerned, all doubts have been erased,'' Krier
said. ``They made a big presentation and the gist of it is, 'We are
looking forward to having you.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Pan American Games are held every four years in the year
preceding the Summer Olympics. Athletes from nations in the Western
Hemisphere will participate.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Olympic Committee considers it the third biggest event
on its calendar behind the Summer and Winter Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Jerry Briggs can be reached by e-mail at
jbriggs(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
