 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The Chronicle offers readers the recipe
for an outstanding dish at a Bay Area restaurant, plus the chef's
secrets for making it a success. Tips and recipe follow in optional
trim. 
 
 SECRETS OF SUCCESS: Charanga's Cool Sangria: Citrus, apples and 
 wine combine to make a refreshing drink  By Michael Bauer  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Charanga is the type of Pan-Latin restaurant that
wants to make you reach for a glass of sangria. It's little wonder,
then, that this Mission District hot spot serves the best in the
city.
<P>
   Most versions are watered down or lightened up, but chef
Gabriela Salas, who hails from Costa Rica, uses only fruit and
sugar to flavor the red wine.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the blend is a simple mix of Taylor Hearty Burgundy, a
Valencia orange, Granny Smith apple, lemon and sugar. It's potent
stuff and goes well with the food at this innovative restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   The name Charanga comes from a Cuban style of music and dance.
Partner Rita Abraldes is Cuban-American, and both women bring their
heritage to the restaurant. Much of the food has a little kick,
making the sangria all the more popular. While the interior is bare
bones and noisy, the food is excellent and prices are under $10.
</P>
<P>
   At home, the sangria is ideal for outdoor barbecues or any
robust dish with a dash of spice. For a real splash, try it with a
curry dish.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Charanga, 2351 Mission St. (between 19th and 20th streets),
San &LR;   &LR; Francisco; (415) 282-1813. Dinner Tuesday-Saturday. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SECRETS OF SUCCESS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Taylor Hearty Burgundy. &LR;  It's true. Of all the inexpensive
box wines on the market this has the most character. It's smooth
and not too tannic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ The citrus fruit. &LR;  The whole diced fruit, pith and peel
included, intensifies the flavor.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; RUBY RED SANGRIA
</P>
<P>
   This sangria will keep in the refrigerator for several days.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 Valencia orange, unpeeled, cut into 1/2-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   1 Granny Smith apple, cored and cut into 1/2-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   1 lemon, unpeeled, cut into 1/2-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   3 bottles (750 ml each) California Burgundy wine, preferably
Taylor Hearty Burgundy
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Divide the fruit and sugar between 2 pitchers. Add the wine and
stir until the sugar dissolves. Chill well before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6 to 8.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 250 calories, &LR;   &LR; 1 g protein, 17 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 0 fat, 0 cholesterol, 15 mg sodium, 0 fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-00 1415EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
