<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 BEST WAY: Storing Lettuce   By Noel Advincula 
 &HT;     c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; There is nothing more frustrating than getting
ready to fix a wonderful salad, only to find out that the lettuce
and greens in the refrigerator have wilted and turned brown.
<P>
   To find out how to prevent that from happening, The Chronicle
Food department tested five ways of storing iceberg lettuce and
mesclun greens mix in the refrigerator. We used the refrigerator's
crisper drawer because it has higher humidity intended to help keep
greens fresh. As a control, we left a head of lettuce and some
unwashed mixed greens out on a shelf in the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   The three storage mediums used were self-sealing plastic bags,
self-sealing plastic bags perforated with holes for air circulation
(We imitated the perforated vegetable bags that are no longer
available in grocery stores by poking holes in self-sealing plastic
bags), and moist paper towels that were changed daily. We also put
a head of lettuce and some mixed greens directly into the crisper,
without any wrapping.
</P>
<P>
   We also cored, washed, drained and placed one head of iceberg
lettuce in a self-sealing plastic bag while keeping the other heads
intact.
</P>
<P>
   We checked the produce after one, two, three and five days.
After day one, there was no appreciable difference between the
condition of the head lettuce and the mixed greens in any of the
tests.
</P>
<P>
   After the second day, all the produce stored in the crisper
drawer looked fresh and had a crisp texture and mild, sweet taste.
The head of lettuce stored on the shelf had started to wilt and the
leaves showed signs of frostbite. The mixed greens on the shelf,
which were put in an open plastic container, had wilted
significantly.
</P>
<P>
   On the third day, the lettuce and greens on the refrigerator
shelf were ready to be thrown out. The head of lettuce and mixed
greens left unwrapped in the crisper were also showing signs of
decline. The rest of the samples still looked good _ especially the
head of lettuce and mixed greens wrapped in moist paper towels.
</P>
<P>
   By the fifth day, the mesclun mix had started to taste bitter.
The cored and washed lettuce was still crisp, but the part where
the core was removed was brown and unappetizing. The lettuce and
greens in the perforated plastic bags had brown edges.
</P>
<P>
   After the fifth day, the only lettuce that wasn't wilted,
bruised or discolored was the head that was stored in an airtight
self-sealing plastic bag. The best mixed greens were those wrapped
in moist paper towels and those stored in self-sealing plastic
bags.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Best Way &LR;
</P>
<P>
   To get the best results, store the head of lettuce in a
self-sealing non-perforated plastic bag in the crisper drawer. Do
not core or wash it if you intend to keep it for more than two
days. Remember to wash the lettuce before using it.
</P>
<P>
   The mixed greens should be rinsed and either wrapped in moist
paper towels or placed in a self-sealing non-perforated plastic
bag. It is key to handle the mixed greens as little as possible
before storing to prevent bruising.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-00 1415EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
