A3283 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-LEARN-PASTA-SFCHRON &LR;      05-02 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEARN-PASTA-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Every other week, The Chronicle features ``Learning
to Cook'' by Marion Cunningham, a cooking teacher and cookbook
author best known for her revisions of the Fannie Farmer cookbooks.
This column is intended for novices in the kitchen. &HT;     
 LEARNING TO COOK: Pasta and Chiles Trigger a Fusion   By Marion Cunningham  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; In the last few years a new word has been added to
our California cuisine, ``fusion food.'' This usually describes a
hybrid Asian/Western dish, but my experience has been that most
attempts at fusing don't fuse. You may have had better luck than I.
<P>
   This intriguing idea has prompted me to attempt fusing, but with
Italian and Mexican ingredients. You might well ask why, but I can
only suggest you try the following recipe for Spaghetti with Green
Sauce.
</P>
<P>
   The spaghetti, of course, is Italian; the Green Sauce, most
definitely, is not. The sauce is a spirited blend of garlic,
cilantro leaves, a touch of hot or mild chile, some onion and those
marvelous lemony-tasting tomatillos that are so common in Mexican
salsas, sauces, stews and braises.
</P>
<P>
   If this doesn't fuse for you, you can always use the Green Sauce
on beans, fish or on an avocado salad.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; SPAGHETTI WITH GREEN SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   3 quarts water
</P>
<P>
   21/2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound spaghetti
</P>
<P>
   Green Sauce
</P>
<P>
   4 large garlic cloves
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup cilantro leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 mild Anaheim pepper or 1 jalapeno pepper (found in produce
section of the market)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 medium-size yellow onion, peeled
</P>
<P>
   8 tomatillos (miniature-sized green tomatoes covered with a
green or brownish paperlike husk. Also found in produce section of
markets)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound Parmesan cheese (don't buy grated cheese; it loses
flavor)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; Cooking the Spaghetti:  &LR; Put the water in a large pot, add
the salt and stir. Put the pot on high heat until the water begins
to boil. Put the spaghetti in the boiling water, stir for a good
minute so the strands don't stick together.
</P>
<P>
   Turn the heat down, but keep the water boiling; set the timer
for 12 minutes. When the timer rings, fish a strand of spaghetti
out with a fork, run it under cold water and if it is tender and
not firm or hard, it is ready.
</P>
<P>
   If you haven't finished preparing the sauce, just turn off the
heat under the pot of spaghetti and let it stay hot until you
finish the sauce.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Preparing the Green Sauce:  &LR; Remove the papery outer skin from
the garlic cloves; set the cloves aside. Remove the cilantro leaves
from the stems, measure 1/3 cup; set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Whichever pepper you decide to use, cut off the stem and split
the pepper lengthwise. Scrape out the seeds and veins and discard.
Cut the pepper into 1/4-inch strips. Holding the strips in a
bunched up pile, cut into 1/8-inch pieces crosswise. Set aside.
( &UR; Note: &LR;  You may want to wear rubber gloves to do this if you are
using a jalapeno pepper. The oils can burn your skin.)
</P>
<P>
   Place the onion half flat-side down on a cutting board. Holding
the half firmly with one hand, make about seven vertical slices
into the onion, from stem end to root end; don't slice completely
through the root end. Next, slice crosswise. Repeat with the
remaining onion half.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the papery outer skin of the tomatillos. Cut off the stem
tops and discard. Cut each tomatillo into 1/4-inch slices from the
stem end down. Holding each sliced tomatillo together, slice into
small pieces crosswise.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Finishing the Green Sauce:  &LR; Put the chopped garlic, cilantro
leaves, pepper, onion and tomatillos in a small saucepan; set
aside. Just before you drain the spaghetti, warm the green sauce.
This isn't to be cooked, just barely warmed so the spaghetti stays
hot.
</P>
<P>
   Grate about 3/4 cup cheese so it is ready to sprinkle over the
spaghetti and green sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Toss the drained spaghetti with the warmed green sauce. Top with
the Parmesan. You may serve this family-style in one large bowl and
pass to each person, or portion onto individual plates.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 3.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 680 calories, &LR;   &LR; 43 g protein, 72 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 24 g fat (14 g saturated), 59 mg cholesterol, 1,424
mg sodium, &LR;   &LR; 2 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-00 1416EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
