<DOCNO> NYT20000502.0084 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 14:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3284 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-POTPOURRI-SFCHRON &LR;      05-02 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POTPOURRI-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;      
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, wine editor Gerald Boyd discusses a
variety of wine topics. 
 
 WINE POTPOURRI: Frozen North Produces Gold-Medal Ice Wines  By Gerald D. Boyd  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; In the world of rare wines, the sweet nectar known
as eiswein stands out. Months after the end of the regular harvest
in Germany and Austria, some intrepid vintners gamble with nature.
Winter comes early in Northern Europe and by late December/early
January, a hard freeze has turned the grapes to frozen green
marbles. When the conditions are just right _ and it doesn't happen
every year _ the frozen grapes are rushed to the winery and pressed
while still solid, thus concentrating the sweetness of the juice.
<P>
   Eisweins always have been a rarity in Europe. In recent years,
Canadian wineries, mainly in Ontario and the Okanagan Valley of
British Columbia, have moved to the head of the list of quality ice
wine producers because conditions there are right just about every
year for ice wine.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian ice wines scored big in recent U.S. wine competitions.
Jackson-Triggs, Okanagan Valley, won four gold medals at the
Pacific Rim International Wine Competition, three for ice wines.
Earlier, Jackson-Triggs ice wines won two gold medals at the Grand
Harvest Awards.
</P>
<P>
   One of the key developers of Canadian ice wines is Inniskillin,
located in Canada's Niagara Peninsula wine region, about an hour's
drive from Toronto. Inniskillin was founded in 1975 by Donald
Ziraldo and Karl Kaiser. Ziraldo is the son of Italian immigrants,
and Kaiser, an Austrian winemaker, is regarded as an expert in
cool-climate grape growing. Kaiser and Ziraldo started making ice
wines from Riesling and Vidal, a French-American hybrid grape,
releasing the first commercial ice wine in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Long after the grapes in other North American wine regions were
crushed, Inniskillin's Riesling and Vidal grapes are still hanging
on the vines, protected from birds with a sweet tooth by heavy
netting. When the temperature drops to 7 degrees Fahrenheit, and
the natural sugar is between 38 and 46 percent by volume, the
grapes are frozen and ready to harvest.
</P>
<P>
   Inniskillin produces a range of ice wines, including one that is
oak-aged and one that is sparkling. These are relatively
low-alcohol wines, 9.5 to 10.5 percent is common, with residual
sweetness levels of about 200 to 240 grams per liter, or 20 to 25
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The following wines were tasted recently and still are available
in select stores and through  &LR; WineShopper.com &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   Inniskillin 1998 Niagara Peninsula Riesling Ice Wine, ($65 for a
375 ml bottle), a bright silky blend of apricots and nectarines,
with a touch of honey balanced by good acidity; Inniskillin 1997
Niagara Peninsula Oak Aged Vidal Ice Wine, ($80 for a 375 ml
bottle), an intriguing blend of toasted oak, vanilla and ripe
apricots that lingers in the mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Serve these wines as dessert or with fresh fruit.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Ice Wine or Late Harvest? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   One of the key differences between ice wine and late-harvest
wines is the absence of botrytis, a beneficent mold at harvest in
most botrytized or late-harvest wines. Ice wine derives its
sweetness from long grape-hang time, concentrating the grape
sugars. Many late-harvest wines also benefit from long hang time,
but much of their distinctive character and complexity is the
benefit of botrytis, or noble rot.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Changes Afoot &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Niebaum-Coppola Estate, producers of Rubicon, a Napa Valley
Bordeaux red blend has announced that it will not produce a 1998
Rubicon. The reason given by Francis Coppola and winemaker Scott
McLeod is that 1998 was a difficult vintage and grape quality did
not come up to their standards for Rubicon.
</P>
<P>
   Sonoma's Lou Preston, a master vintner and bread baker, is
adding to the Preston Vineyards line, with Preston of Dry Creek.
The new line, anchored on Zinfandel and Sauvignon Blanc, is made
from estate grapes.
</P>
<P>
   Far Niente partners Gil Nickel, Dirk Hampson and Larry Maguire
announce the formation of a new winery, named Nickel &AMP; Nickel, in
the Napa Valley. Located on a 40-acre site across from the Robert
Mondavi Winery, Nickel &AMP; Nickel will specialize in small lots of
vineyard-designated wines.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; May Wine Events &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Women for WineSense World Conference will be held May 4-6 at
the Doubletree Hotel in Rohnert Park, Sonoma County. The theme is
``Wine at America's Table: Maintaining Wine Heritage in a Dot-Com
World.'' For details, call (800) 204-1616, or visit the Web site at
 &LR; www.womenforwinesense.org &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   _ Beringer Vineyards Spring Wine Opener, an opportunity for wine
fans to taste newly released and limited-edition wines, will take
place May 12, from 5 to 8 p.m. at Beringer Vineyards, 1000 Pratt
Ave., St. Helena. Tickets are $100 and the proceeds will benefit
Napa Valley schools. For ticket information, call (707) 963-8989,
Ext. 4443.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Wine Basics &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Interest is mounting for value-related Spanish red wines,
especially those from La Rioja and Ribera del Duero. As with other
imported wines, Americans often don't understand the label language
on Spanish wines.
</P>
<P>
   Although various Denominacion de Origen (Denomination of Origin)
in Spain have different requirements for wine aging terms, the
following basics are the same for all Spanish red wines:
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Ciranza: &LR;  This term is reserved for wines aged in wood and
bottle for at least two years, six months of which must be in oak
barrels.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Reserva: &LR;  Red wines must be aged a minimum of 36 months in
wood and bottle, at least 12 months in oak casks. For white and
ros &LR; e &LR;  wines, the minimum period is 24 months, six of them in oak
casks.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Gran Reserva: &LR;  Used for red wines that have been aged for at
least 24 months in oak casks, followed by 36 months in bottle prior
to release. For white and ros &LR; e &LR;  wines, the minimum period is four
years; six months must be in wood.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Aussie Wine Holiday &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Planning a vacation to Australia this year, with maybe a few
winery visits? The Australian Wine Bureau in New York is offering
the Australian Wine Holiday Guide, a handy pocket guide with wine
facts, a winery directory and a fold-out map of Australia's wine
regions. It's free! For a copy, call (212) 351-6585 or e-mail:
 &LR; awb.usa &LR; austrade.gov.au &LR; . To learn more about Australian wines
visit  &LR; www.wineaustralia.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
