<SLUG> BC-TASTE-CHIPS-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The San Francisco Chronicle's panel of
professional tasters tries a different product available in
supermarkets.  
 
 TASTER'S CHOICE: Thin and Crispy Wins in Potato Chip Picks   By Robin Davis  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  It's been more than 10 years since The Chronicle's
panel sampled full-fat, full-salt potato chips. Since then, many
new chips have come out. Today's panel sampled 12 brands, not
including any that specified ``dark cooked,'' low-salt or low-fat.
<TEXT>
<P>
   One brand ranked significantly higher than the others, but was
not a unanimous favorite. Panelists agreed that personal
preferences are strong _ some like thick, substantial chips while
others prefer them thin and crisp.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lay's &LR;  (7.5 ounces, $2.89-$2.99 at many supermarkets) placed
first. Four panelists picked it as their favorite for its light
texture and ``classic'' flavor. The dissenter thought it was too
flimsy. Four would buy it, and one might.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Ruffles &LR;  (13.25 ounces, $3.19 at Safeway) came in second, with
one panelist picking it number one _ ``a good basic chip.'' Another
thought it was a good ``middle-ground'' chip, although it looked
overly processed. Three would buy it, one might buy it and one
would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Idaho &LR;  (6 ounces, $1.99 at Safeway) came in third. Several
panelists noted a greasiness, but two liked the texture. One
thought it would be good for dipping. Two would buy it, one might
buy it, and two would not.
</P>
<P>
   Panelists were decidedly divided over  &UR; Barbara's &LR;  (5 ounces,
$1.85 at Rainbow). One described the flavor as artificial, but
another thought it had great potato flavor. One panelist thought
the chip wasn't ``snappy enough,'' but two others particularly
liked the thin crispiness. One would buy it, two might buy it, and
two would not.
</P>
<P>
   Fifth place went to  &UR; Boulder &LR;  (5 ounces, $2.29 at Whole Foods
and Andronico's). Two panelists thought the chip was too thick and
tough, but liked the potato flavor. Another thought it was too
greasy and lacked salt. Two would buy it, one might buy it, and two
would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Kettle Chips &LR;  (5 ounces, $1.69 at Whole Foods) came in sixth.
Most tasters liked the dark brown color, but one thought they were
too dry. All decried the lack of salt. Two would buy it, one might
buy it, and two would not.
</P>
<P>
   The panel also tasted Trader Joe's, Hawaiian, Granny Goose,
Tim's Cascade-Style, Cape Cod and Pringles Original, but they
scored too low to rate.
</P>
<P>
   Panelists were Shelley Handler, consultant and food writer;
Donna Katzl, chef-owner, Cafe For All Seasons, San Francisco; Julia
McClaskey, chef, Dine in San Francisco; Kim Severson, Chronicle
staff writer; and Kirk Webber, chef-owner, Cafe Kati, San
Francisco. All products are tasted blind.
</P>
</TEXT>
