<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 14:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3291 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-WINECHEF-SFCHRON &LR;      05-02 3779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINECHEF-SF </SLUG>
 CHRON  
 Winemakers in the Kitchen: Tradition view with eclecticism as
two  master blenders don their aprons to prepare dinner. 
 &HT;     By Janet Fletcher 
 &HT;     c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; They spend most of their working day thinking
about taste, aroma, balance and texture. They obsess about
ingredients and tinker with technique. Their practiced palates can
tell a mountain Cabernet from a valley-grown version. But can
winemakers cook?
<P>
   Many Napa Valley winemakers have reputations as amateur cooks _
among them Marco Cappelli of Swanson Vineyards and Art Finkelstein
of Judd's Hill. On separate nights, they each prepared a
dinner-party menu of their own invention while sharing some
thoughts on the pleasures of the table. Although their cooking
styles could hardly be more different, the two men hold remarkably
similar views about the ingredients for an enjoyable evening.
</P>
<P>
   In chef terms, Cappelli is the Paul Bertolli of the kitchen,
Finkelstein the Wolfgang Puck. Like Bertolli, chef at Oakland's
Oliveto, Cappelli reveres tradition, simplicity and the dishes his
Italian mother and grandmother made. Like Puck of San Francisco's
Postrio, Finkelstein's multicultural kitchen embraces the whole
California experience, from barbecued ribs to pasta to sushi.
Sesame oil, saffron and Thai chile sauce _ telltale signs of a
culinary adventurer _ all share space in his pantry.
</P>
<P>
   Authenticity, not adventure, was on Cappelli's mind when the
39-year-old consulted his mother about his menu. She agreed to
bring him baby artichokes from her home in Carmel and told him
that, no, he couldn't serve veal after pasta with tuna sauce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Italians have these traditions,'' says Cappelli, shrugging.
Pasta with fish sauce should be followed by fish. He had forgotten
this unwritten rule, but it's ingrained in him now.
</P>
<P>
   In his modest U-shaped kitchen in Rutherford _ he lives next to
the winery _ Cappelli expertly trims the artichokes as he relates
experiences that have shaped his food views. A slim man with a
youthful face, a lush mane of jet-black hair and graceful manners,
Cappelli was raised in Carmel after his Italian-born father retired
from the U.S. Army. His mother was a good cook, but family life
didn't center around food. She prepared the simple dishes of her
region, the Marches, and mealtimes unfolded in the Italian order:
soup or pasta, followed by a meat course with salad.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents were not teetotalers, but close,'' recalls
Cappelli. They didn't serve wine, but they didn't forbid it, and he
grew up with no interest in it.
</P>
<P>
   But as a freshman at University of California at Davis, where he
enrolled because a friend did, Cappelli met an enology student who
introduced him to dorm-room mead. Fascinated by fermentation, he
took a quarter off to work at Louis Martini Winery, then returned
to Davis to earn a degree in enology.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fell in love with the whole business,'' he says, ``with
being able to see that grape-y character in your wine. It's like
making jam. Winemaking is preserving.''
</P>
<P>
   After graduation, Cappelli headed for Italy with assurances of a
three-week job in Chianti Classico. Before long, one of Tuscany's
top winemaking consultants took the young Italian-American under
his wing, arranging stints for him at such prestigious wine
properties as Castello di Volpaia and Badia a Coltibuono.
</P>
<P>
   Like others pilgrims that have preceded and followed him,
Cappelli returned home with a profound respect for how Italians
live, work and eat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every bit of land is producing for them in some way,''
Cappelli says. An Italian doesn't plant a lawn if he can grow a
crop instead. In some regions, even the highway medians were
planted with wheat, he recalls. ``My friends couldn't believe that
there were fruit trees among the grape vines, and wheat between the
rows.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Cappelli returns to Italy each year to visit family and
friends and to strengthen ties to a culture he loves. These annual
trips have shaped his thoughts about food and the place of wine on
the table.
</P>
<P>
   ``The women on my mother's side are extremely good cooks,'' says
the winemaker. ``Their food isn't fancy at all; they rely on the
ingredients being good _ good pasta, good Parmesan, good olive
oil.''
</P>
<P>
   Great oil is fundamental, he says. The better the oil _ he
trades Swanson wine for McEvoy Ranch extra virgin olive oil _ the
more simply you can cook.
</P>
<P>
   His pasta sauce _ a quick simmering of chopped fresh tomato,
anchovy and olive oil _ proves his point. He doesn't peel the
tomato; he adds no garlic, no cheese, no herb except parsley. Yet
this straightforward pasta dish is hard to stop eating, the sauce a
melding of compatible flavors with no extraneous note.
</P>
<P>
   When guests come for dinner, this bachelor's menu is likely to
be equally unfussy: pasta with a tomato-based sauce, roast chicken
with rosemary and garlic, roast potatoes, a sauteed green vegetable
like broccoli or chard and perhaps a green salad. For dessert?
Grappa, perhaps, or another high-proof fruit brandy.
</P>
<P>
   Cappelli dismisses the notion that a dinner party needs to be an
orchestrated wine-and-food dance. ``Wine is almost an afterthought,
to tell the truth,'' says Cappelli about his own entertaining.
Guests usually bring bottles they want to share; he rarely serves
his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Italy, wine is like the bread,'' says the winemaker. ``It's
always on the table, but it's not something you focus on. The
reason we're not a wine-drinking nation is because we worry too
much about what it tastes like.''
</P>
<P>
   Cappelli's simple tastes are evident in the rest of his menu, a
classic preparation of veal scaloppine bathed in a lightly
thickened Marsala sauce. He painstakingly trims the thin-sliced
meat of every scrap of connective tissue and fat, then pounds the
slices even thinner, flours them lightly and sautees them quickly
in butter and oil. A splash of Marsala goes into the pan and is
quickly reduced to make the aromatic sauce.
</P>
<P>
   To accompany the veal, Cappelli trims and quarters his
hand-delivered artichokes, then braises them with white wine, olive
oil and crushed garlic. Dessert, which he rarely serves, is
refreshing and different, a mixed-fruit salad macerated in anise
liqueur.
</P>
<P>
   Chief among the lessons he learned in Italy is that ``cooking is
nothing to be afraid of. I have friends who can't do anything
without a recipe.'' Buy good ingredients, he might advise them;
then keep it simple.
</P>
<P>
   Art Finkelstein, like Cappelli, is unintimidated in the kitchen
and equally untethered to recipes. A fearless cook who once invited
Madeleine Kamman to dinner (she came), he also regularly mans the
grills at his Napa synagogue's fund-raisers and estimates that
1,000 people have eaten his barbecued salmon. A year-round charcoal
griller, he owns three Webers for those occasions when he and his
wife, Bunnie, invite the whole staff of Tra Vigne to dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to Cappelli, the 58-year-old Finkelstein is a much more
adventurous cook, with eclectic tastes that span the globe and no
fear of fusion. ``I like to wing it,'' he says, ``and I don't feel
bound to make authentic dishes.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly. His menu for the evening includes barbecued baby back
ribs in an Asian marinade, followed by a grilled quail salad with a
curry dressing and a fish soup that suggests bouillabaisse by way
of Tokyo. He cooks with a vast supporting cast of Eastern and
Western oils, vinegars, sauces, spices and condiments _ the palette
that fuels his culinary imagination.
</P>
<P>
   A former architect, Finkelstein considers cooking another outlet
for his long-standing impulse to build. He has cooked since college
days, when he left his strictly kosher Illinois home for the
University of Southern California. There, his older brother
introduced him to Los Angeles' ethnic restaurants; together they
explored an unimagined world of Greek, Indian, Thai and Chinese
establishments. When Finkelstein liked a dish, he wanted to make
it, and he developed a cooking-class habit that continues today.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1970s, he and Bunnie moved to Napa Valley, where
Finkelstein and his surgeon brother opened Whitehall Lane Winery.
They later sold it, but in 1989, Art and Bunnie launched their own
label _ Judd's Hill, named for their son. The following year they
designed and built a home over their small Conn Valley winery; from
the glass-walled dining room, guests can look directly into the
cellar.
</P>
<P>
   Given the drama of their high-ceilinged great room, the kitchen
is surprisingly humble, a small square room with a butcher-block
work table in the center. Finkelstein has no fancy cookware, no
professional-quality stove. ``I don't like `things,' '' he says.
``I don't need cars, jewelry, fancy dogs. I like to celebrate life
with friends, to eat and drink and have a good time.''
</P>
<P>
   For this evening, he has invited Hiro Sone and Lissa Doumani,
the owners of Terra restaurant in St. Helena, and their two
visiting Japanese guests. Art Finkelstein, Doumani says, is just
about the only person in the valley who will cook for her and her
chef husband.
</P>
<P>
   Before his guests arrive, Finkelstein pre-cooks the ribs,
marinates the quail, makes his barbecue basting sauce and whisks up
a salad dressing. He chops vegetables for his fish soup and starts
to soften them in olive oil. When it is time to light the coals in
the first of two grills he will use this evening, he grabs the
bottle of extra virgin olive oil and heads outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate liquid fire starter,'' he says, drizzling olive oil
over the coals, which are piled on newspaper. A match starts the
pile smoking immediately.
</P>
<P>
   The ribs, first baked in a slow oven to release their fat and
tenderize them, go on the grill with hickory chips and a basting of
sauce. Forty-five minutes later they are crusty, dark and
smoky-finger food to serve with cocktails and sparkling wine.
Bottles of Judd's Hill Merlot and Mason Sauvignon Blanc appear on
the table with the first course, grilled quail salad with mango and
citrus curry dressing. The meal proceeds, the bottles keep coming:
Pinot Noir with the fennel and saffron-scented seafood broth and
glazed sea bass; two Cabernet Sauvignons and Lustau sherry with the
cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to what one might expect, the conversation barely
touches on wine all evening, and the many bottles are poured and
passed without ceremony. As at Cappelli's table, the focus is on
conviviality, not on the intricate interplay of wine and food.
Nobody asks for or offers an opinion about which wine goes best
with the quail. If anyone is analyzing the wine and food pairings,
they don't do so out loud.
</P>
<P>
   It's not hard to imagine why Cappelli and Finkelstein find
satisfaction in cooking. The gratification is almost immediate; you
don't have to wait months or years to know if the ``recipe''
worked. You can throw out the mistakes and start over. And you have
an almost limitless world of ingredients to play with, not just
grapes and oak.
</P>
<P>
   But the kitchen's main appeal for these two winemakers may be
less tangible. Good food brings people around a table and provides
a context for sharing wine, which is reason enough for them to keep
on cooking.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; MARCO CAPPELLI'S MENU &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Spaghetti with Tomato-Anchovy Sauce
</P>
<P>
   _ Veal Scaloppine with Marsala
</P>
<P>
   _ Braised Baby Artichokes
</P>
<P>
   _ Italian Fruit Salad with Anise Liqueur
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SPAGHETTI WITH TOMATO-ANCHOVY SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2-ounce tin anchovy fillets in olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon hot red pepper flakes, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   4 large, ripe tomatoes, chopped (no need to peel or juice)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 pound spaghetti
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Bring a large pot of salted water to a boil for the pasta.
</P>
<P>
   While the water heats, warm the olive oil, anchovies (no need to
chop) and the oil from the anchovy tin over moderately low heat,
stirring until the anchovies dissolve. Add the hot pepper flakes
and saute briefly to release their fragrance. Add the tomatoes,
raise heat to moderately high and cook, stirring, until they
collapse into a coarse sauce. Simmer briefly to thicken sauce to
desired consistency, then stir in the parsley. Taste and adjust
seasoning.
</P>
<P>
   Cook the pasta until al dente. Drain and transfer to a warm
serving bowl. Add the sauce and toss.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 595 calories, &LR;   &LR; 19 g protein, 91 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 17 g fat (2 g saturated), 20 mg cholesterol, 534 mg
sodium, 2 g &LR;   &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
VEAL SCALOPPINE WITH MARSALA
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 pound very thinly sliced veal scaloppine
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   All-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup dry Marsala
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Trim the veal rigorously, removing any membranes or external
fat. It is OK to cut a slice in two if necessary to trim away
internal membrane. Using a rolling pin or wine bottle, pound the
veal gently until it is 1/16-inch thick. Season with salt and
pepper. Just before cooking, lightly flour both sides of each
slice, shaking off excess.
</P>
<P>
   Heat two large skillets over moderately high heat, or work in
batches if necessary. Divide the butter and oil between the two
skillets. When the fat is hot, add the veal. Sear on one side, then
turn with tongs and cook on the other side until the veal is
lightly colored, about 2 minutes total. Transfer the veal to a
large warm platter and pour off the fat in the skillets. Return the
veal to the skillets along with the Marsala, dividing it evenly.
Cook until the Marsala reduces to a lightly thickened sauce that
just bathes the veal. Transfer the veal to warm platter and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 360 calories, &LR;   &LR; 24 g protein, 3 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 23 g fat (5 g saturated), 96 mg cholesterol, 100 mg sodium, 0 &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; BRAISED BABY ARTICHOKES
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   20 baby artichokes
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons white wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, peeled and lightly crushed
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   Approximately 1/3 cup white wine, or more as needed
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; Trim the artichokes:  &LR; Remove the tough outer leaves until
you reach the pale yellow-green heart. Cut about 1/2-inch off the
tip of the artichoke and trim the base of any dark green parts.
Quarter artichoke hearts and trim away prickly leaves in the
center, if any. Drop the artichokes into a bowl of water acidulated
with the wine vinegar to prevent browning.
</P>
<P>
   Drain the artichokes. Heat the olive oil in a skillet over
moderate heat. Add the garlic and saute briefly to release its
fragrance. Add the artichokes and season with salt. Add 3
tablespoons wine. Cover and cook until the artichokes are tender,
adding a little more wine if the skillet threatens to cook dry. At
the end, there should be no liquid in the skillet and the
artichokes should be slightly browned in parts. Transfer to a bowl
and serve hot or at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 170 calories, &LR;   &LR; 5 g protein, 23 g carbohydrate,
7 &LR;   &LR; g fat (1 g saturated), 0 cholesterol, 140 mg sodium, 17 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ITALIAN FRUIT SALAD WITH ANISE LIQUEUR
</P>
<P>
   This marinated fruit salad can adapt to what you find at the
market. You may peel the thin-skinned fruits such as peaches and
pears, but it's not necessary. Serve with Asti Spumante.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 nectarine, diced
</P>
<P>
   1 orange, peeled, pitted and diced
</P>
<P>
   1 plum, diced
</P>
<P>
   1 apple, cored and diced
</P>
<P>
   1 pear, cored and diced
</P>
<P>
   banana, peeled and diced
</P>
<P>
   1 mango, peeled and diced
</P>
<P>
   6 strawberries, sliced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup blueberries
</P>
<P>
   Grated zest and juice of 1/2 lemon
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup anise liqueur, such as sambuca
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Combine all ingredients in a large bowl and stir gently. Cover
and refrigerate for 8 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4 to 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 155 calories, &LR;   &LR; 1 g protein, 33 g carbohydrate,
1 &LR;   &LR; g fat (0 saturated), 0 cholesterol, 2 mg sodium, 5 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; ART FINKELSTEIN'S MENU &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Asian-Style Smoked Baby Back Ribs
</P>
<P>
   _ Grilled Quail &AMP; Mango Salad with Citrus Curry Dressing
</P>
<P>
   _ Soy-Glazed Sea Bass and Shellfish in Seafood Broth
</P>
<P>
   _ Kinta's Cornmeal Cookies &AMP; Sorbet of choice
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ASIAN-STYLE SMOKED BABY BACK RIBS
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 racks baby back ribs, halved lengthwise by the butcher
</P>
<P>
   Garlic salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   8 large handfuls hickory chips
</P>
<P>
   Sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup hoisin sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup plum sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons white vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons dry sherry
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Asian sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   3 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon Thai chile sauce, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 250 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Season the ribs with garlic salt. Wrap them loosely in
heavy-duty aluminum foil and place in a baking dish. Bake until
very tender, about 3 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Soak hickory chips in water to cover for 2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   To make the sauce, whisk together all ingredients. Taste and add
more chile sauce if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare a moderate charcoal fire. When the coals are ready,
divide them into two piles on either side of the grill. Put 3
handfuls of chips on each pile. Top with the grate.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange the ribs on the grate, not directly over the coals; they
should cook by indirect heat. Brush with sauce, cover and cook
until the ribs are crusty and browned, about 45 minutes, brushing
again with sauce halfway through. Add another handful of chips to
each pile if necessary to keep the coals smoking.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer the ribs to a cutting board and let rest a few minutes
before cutting between the ribs.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8 to 12.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 180 calories, &LR;   &LR; 9 g protein, 1 g carbohydrate,
10 &LR;   &LR; g fat (4 g saturated), 36 mg cholesterol, 795 mg sodium, 0 &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; GRILLED QUAIL &AMP; MANGO SALAD WITH CITRUS CURRY DRESSING
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   Quail Marinade
</P>
<P>
   1 cup soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons Asian sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground ginger
</P>
<P>
   8 semi-boneless quail
</P>
<P>
   Salad
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons orange juice
</P>
<P>
   11/2 teaspoons rice vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon curry powder
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   8 handfuls baby salad greens
</P>
<P>
   1 ripe mango, peeled and diced
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Marinate quail:  &LR; Whisk together the soy sauce, lemon juice,
brown sugar, sesame oil and ginger. Add the quail and turn to coat
with marinade. Cover and refrigerate 2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Make salad dressing:  &LR; Whisk together the olive oil, orange
juice, rice vinegar, sugar, lemon juice, curry powder and salt.
Taste and adjust seasoning.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare a medium-hot charcoal fire.
</P>
<P>
   Cook the quail directly over the coals, with the grill lid on
but the vents open, until browned on both sides, about 5 minutes
per side. Transfer the quail to a platter and let rest while you
toss the salad.
</P>
<P>
   Toss the greens in a large bowl with just enough dressing to
coat the leaves lightly. Divide among salad plates. Scatter the
mango over the greens. Cut the quail in half. Put 2 halves on each
plate.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 300 calories, &LR;   &LR; 22 g protein, 7 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 20 g fat (5 g saturated), 0 cholesterol, 61 mg sodium, 1 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &QL;  &LR; 
 &LR; The calories and other nutrients absorbed from marinades vary &LR; 
 &LR; and are difficult to estimate. Variables include the type of &LR; 
 &LR; food, marinating time and amount of surface area. Therefore, &LR;   &LR; the
marinade is not included in this analysis. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; SOY-GLAZED SEA BASS &AMP; SHELLFISH IN SEAFOOD BROTH
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   Broth
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup coarsely chopped carrots
</P>
<P>
   1 celery rib, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 leek (white and light-green part only), well rinsed and
chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup coarsely chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   1 large garlic clove, chopped
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon dried oregano
</P>
<P>
   4 cups fish stock or best-quality bottled clam juice
</P>
<P>
   1 cup white wine
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon powdered saffron
</P>
<P>
   11/2 teaspoons ground fennel
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   8 Chilean sea bass fillets, about 6 ounces each
</P>
<P>
   Asian sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   Seasoning salt, such as Lawry's
</P>
<P>
   8 teaspoons kabayaki sauce (available at Japanese markets)
</P>
<P>
   11/2 pounds sea scallops
</P>
<P>
   11/2 pounds shrimp, peeled and butterflied
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; Make broth:  &LR; Heat the olive oil in a large pot over
moderate heat. Add the carrots, celery, leek, parsley, garlic and
oregano and saute until slightly softened, about 5 minutes. Add the
fish stock, wine, saffron, fennel and sugar. Bring to a simmer,
adjust heat to maintain a gentle simmer and cook about 10 minutes
to boil off the alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat broiler.
</P>
<P>
   Coat the sea bass lightly with sesame oil, then season with
seasoning salt. Put the fish on a rack in a baking dish and broil
until almost done. Brush each fillet with 1 teaspoon kabayaki sauce
and return to the broiler until the fish just flakes.
</P>
<P>
   While the fish cooks, add the scallops to the simmering broth.
Cover and simmer until they are about half-done, about 1 minute,
then add the shrimp. Cover and simmer briefly, just until the
shrimp and scallops are done. Taste the broth and adjust seasoning.
</P>
<P>
   Spoon some of the broth, shrimp and scallops into warmed serving
bowls. Using a spatula, transfer a sea bass fillet to each bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 410 calories, &LR;   &LR; 62 g protein, 8 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 12 g fat (2 g saturated), 280 mg cholesterol, 558 mg sodium, 1 &LR;   &LR; g
fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
KINTA'S CORNMEAL COOKIES
</P>
<P>
   Bunnie Finkelstein got this recipe from Kinta Clark, former
owner of Deer Park Winery in St. Helena.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup softened butter
</P>
<P>
   1 cup light brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 egg
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   11/4 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 cup yellow cornmeal
</P>
<P>
   11/2 teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 cup finely chopped walnuts or pecans
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Using an electric mixer, cream the butter and sugar until
fluffy. Add the egg and vanilla and beat well. Sift together the
flour, cornmeal, baking powder and salt. Add to the sugar mixture
and beat just to blend. Add the nuts and beat just to blend. Divide
the dough into thirds. Shape each third into a 12-inch log. Wrap in
wax paper and chill several hours or overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 375 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Slice the dough into 1/4-inch-thick rounds. Arrange on ungreased
cookie sheets. Bake until golden brown, 8 to 10 minutes. Cool on
wire racks.
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 10 dozen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER COOKIE: &LR;   &LR; 33 calories, &LR;   &LR; 0 protein, 4 g carbohydrate, 2 g &LR; 
 &LR; fat (1 g saturated), 5 mg cholesterol, 24 mg sodium, 0 fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
