<HEADER>
A3304 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-KENT-STATE-HNS &LR;      05-02 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENT-STATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PROFESSOR CAN'T ESCAPE MEMORIES OF KENT STATE'S FATEFUL DAY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By EDVINS BEITIKS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   On May 4, 1970, Ohio National Guardsmen at Kent State University
shot and killed Jeffrey Glenn Miller, Allison B. Krause, William K.
Schroeder and Sandra Lee Scheuer.
</P>
<P>
   The shootings marked the end of four lives, the end of an
impromptu demonstration against the Vietnam War, and the beginning,
for Professor Jerry M. Lewis, of a life wrapped around the legacy
of crazy force, a blurred picture of shouting teen-agers caught on
the government's own killing ground.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis was a young sociology professor the day the soldiers went
into a momentary, three-stage shooting spasm, killing the four and
wounding nine others.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Lewis, the last professor left on campus willing to
talk about what happened 30 years ago, worked to coordinate close
to 60 events marking the anniversary of the Kent State killings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be very beautiful that day, just the way it
was,'' Lewis said by telephone. ``Except for the wind, it looks
exactly the same. So gorgeous. Bright sunlight.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, 63, sighed. ``What happened here that day, it's my hair
shirt,'' he said. ``Every time I walk out there ... not so much
around the pagoda, but that hill's getting higher and higher ...
and to see those markers in the parking lot, where they died ...as
I'm talking now I can look at three memories, three different
positions I took up that day.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my colleagues noted I'm recently getting more and more
emotional in my presentation at the memorials. It's true. I
remember a lot. It's painful.''
</P>
<P>
   A round, clean hole made by an M-1 bullet fired by some
gas-masked Guardsman is still there, sliced through the left-side
heart of the steel pagoda at one corner of Taylor Hall on campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The memory that is most with me,'' Lewis said, ``the one that
never goes away, is watching Allison Krause coming down the hill
... on that gurney. I was pretty sure she was dead, dying, and I
grabbed two young women standing there and pulled them to my chest
and said, `You don't want to see this.'
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time after that I dreamed about the shooting, about
once a week ... always the Guard turning and firing. At least once
a week. ...''
</P>
<P>
   Slowly retracing his steps 30 years later, Lewis said, ``Right
before noon I was walking through the rally, went up on the
sidewalk there and a friend joined me just as the guards started
coming across. We were all going past Taylor Hall, a marshal kept
shouting, `Don't go on the practice football field, it's closed!'
and I went out to give some first aid to a student who'd been hit
by tear gas.''
</P>
<P>
   He returned to the parking lot, Lewis said. ``And as I stood
there looking up the hill, I saw the guard walking rapidly to the
pagoda, saw the right rear echelon of eight to 10 guys turn, knew
something was going to happen, and I just dove to my right, jumped
about 10 steps behind a bush. ... It's what I learned in the Army.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then came the shots and I said to myself, `What should I do?'
and a student came over and asked me, `Dr. Lewis, those were
blanks, weren't they?' and I pointed to Sandy Scheuer's body ...
about 15 yards away from me ... and I said, `You must leave. Those
are real bullets.'''
</P>
<P>
   Since that day, Lewis said, he has made it a personal crusade to
underline the uncompromising use of force at Kent State. While
others may see the 30th anniversary as another self-serving media
opera, Lewis said, ``I take a different position. I don't think
it's heavy-handed at all. I think Kent State is about the use of
force, and every chance I get I'm going to spread that word.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the Elian custody situation _ the feds haven't learned
a damned thing. Force. Tear gas. Guns. For what?
</P>
<P>
   ``Kent State is the federal government firing into a crowd, with
the government never apologizing,'' he said. ``That's one reason I
continue to talk. That's just wrong, period. I'm a patriot, I
believe in the American dream, I vote every year, but I have a
profound distrust in my federal government.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It did end the war,'' Lewis said of Kent State. ``Many
historians are saying it speeded up the withdrawal of troops. The
ones who say it was the end of the anti-war movement, well, that's
just empirically wrong. I went to an awful lot of rallies after
that. The huge, mass rallies died after Washington, D.C., that's
true, but the activism didn't stop.''
</P>
<P>
   And the most important legacy, Lewis said, may be the public's
insistence since Kent State ``on having a check on social-control
forces. Look at the outcry that took place after Elian. That was a
good show of what's changed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
