<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 14:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3320 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     05-02 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 PERSONALS: Advice From the Man Who Knows How  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The wit and wisdom of San Francisco Mayor  &UR; Willie Brown &LR;  _ in
pronouncements made at DreamWorks' post-Oscar party, is shared in
George magazine, which was standing by while Brown ``was holding
court at the bar'':
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were  &UR; Al Gore &LR; ,'' said the mayor, ``I'd have been sitting
next to  &UR; Annette &LR;  and  &UR; Warren &LR;  tonight. A billion people watching!
No one would have a problem except  &UR; Bob Jones &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   Brown had some ideas for award-winner Beatty, too, who he said
``would love to do something political. It's in his system. It's
too bad he doesn't live in my town. I'd use him, hell, yeah. Chair
the police commission.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor fit right in with the entertainment crowd. ``As a
politician, you're only as good as your last win,'' he said. ``As
an actor you're only as good as your last movie. You're toast if
you're not relevant, interesting and timely.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S.  &UR; Steve Talbot &LR; , who's making a ``Frontline'' documentary on
``The Battle Over School Choice'' (to be broadcast May 23 by PBS),
watched Gore deliver a speech on education last week to the
National Conference of Black Mayors.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas Mayor  &UR; Ron Kirk &LR;  gave the candidate a rousing
introduction, and  &UR; Stevie Wonder &LR;  music was struck up as Gore
entered, ``looking good, stage left. He's smiling, he's
confident,'' he's getting lots of hugs. And then he begins to
speak, says Talbot, ``and proceeds to suck every ounce of life out
of that energized room. ... By the end of Gore's speech, several of
his staunchest supporters had dozed off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Afterward, the mayors, their wives and aides crowded around
Gore. The vice president seemed particularly impressed by Willie
Brown's pinstriped suit, checking the designer label on the inside
coat pocket, as our mayor laughed.''
</P>
<P>
   FLASH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Personals has received word of the San Francisco Bay Area
Conference on Customer Service, which includes seminars on all
sorts of things that will strike familiar notes with consumers who
have treasured the hours they've spent waiting on hold or tripping
along the merry byways of voice mail:
</P>
<P>
   ``Hidden gold: How to turn complaints into profits''; ``How to
deal with demanding, angry or unreasonably customers _ and still
feel good!''; and ``The difference between the hard `no' and the
customer-friendly `no.' ''
</P>
<P>
   _ Director  &UR; Guy Ritchie &LR; , father of  &UR; Madonna &LR; 's forthcoming
baby, likes to tell people he's always been poor, says the Sunday
Telegraph of London, but his father was an advertising executive
and he grew up in a 17th century house owned by his stepfather.
``In art, as in life,'' said the Telegraph, ``Ritchie's real talent
lies in myth-making. But who cares? His Mockney act keeps Madonna
happy.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
THE KOSHER NATURAL? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hebrew National has asked the Los Angeles Dodgers' newest star,
Jewish right fielder  &UR; Shawn Green &LR; , to endorse its line of all-beef
hot dogs, reports Los Angeles magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Green told the magazine that when he came to bat one Sunday in
Milwaukee last season, when he was playing for Toronto,  &UR; Jesse &LR; 
 &UR; Levis &LR; , who was playing for Milwaukee, was catching, and the umpire
was  &UR; Al Clark &LR; . All are Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was right after Rosh Hashanah,'' he said, ``and, after
greeting each other with a laughing round of `Hey, Yids,' we wished
each other a happy New Year.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Muscle &AMP; Fitness magazine editor &UR; Jim Rosenthal &LR;  says that
former Giant  &UR; Rod Beck &LR; , who's now pitching for the Boston Red Sox,
has the flabbiest physique in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   P.P.S.  &UR; Wilson Lewis &LR;  calls the flotilla outside the new
ballpark's McCovey Cove ``McCovey's Navy.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WHO SAID WHAT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Caps and bridges and Lee Press-On teeth would appear to have
made dentures a thing of the past. Quel drag! Dentures were one of
the main sources of entertainment available to me as a youngster.
... If (my Dad) sneezed, his gnashers would hit the floor before
you could say Gesundheit. He once sneezed them across the front
yard, where they landed under his oily motorbike. My sister and I
consider this to be one of our most treasured childhood memories.
What are the dentures of today? Botox, breast implants? Will kids
scream with laughter when mummy's collagen slips or if her
acid-peel turns nasty? Which minor afflictions will provide the
happy memories of tomorrow?''
</P>
<P>
   _ Simon Doonan  &LR; in the New York Observer. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
