   Green told the magazine that when he came to bat one Sunday in
Milwaukee last season, when he was playing for Toronto,  &UR; Jesse &LR; 
 &UR; Levis &LR; , who was playing for Milwaukee, was catching, and the umpire
was  &UR; Al Clark &LR; . All are Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was right after Rosh Hashanah,'' he said, ``and, after
greeting each other with a laughing round of `Hey, Yids,' we wished
each other a happy New Year.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Muscle &AMP; Fitness magazine editor  &UR; Jim Rosenthal &LR;  says
former Giant  &UR; Rod Beck &LR; , who's now pitching for the Boston Red Sox,
has the flabbiest physique in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Caps and bridges and Lee Press-On teeth would appear to have
made dentures a thing of the past. Quel drag! Dentures were one of
the main sources of entertainment available to me as a youngster.
... If (my Dad) sneezed, his gnashers would hit the floor before
you could say Gesundheit. He once sneezed them across the front
yard, where they landed under his oily motorbike. My sister and I
consider this to be one of our most treasured childhood memories.
What are the dentures of today? Botox, breast implants? Will kids
scream with laughter when mummy's collagen slips or if her
acid-peel turns nasty? Which minor afflictions will provide the
happy memories of tomorrow?''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Simon Doonan &LR;  in the New York Observer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
