 &UR; WEDNESDAY, May 3, &LR;  of particular interest:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `i' news category)
</P>
<P>
   IVORYCOAST-MILITARY (Abidjan) _ In the four months since an
initially popular coup, the army is everywhere _ traffic cop,
soccer coach, gym teacher. The military is in total control in a
country that for decades had been one of the few African nations
not to have experienced military rule and still stands as the
richest in French-speaking Africa. By Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-DMZ (Panmunjon, South Korea) _ For American and South
Korean soldiers stationed in the demilitarized zone that divides
the two Koreas, days begin with a blast of martial music and
Communist propaganda blaring from gigantic loudspeakers that North
Korea has erected just across the heavily fortified border. Despite
all the talk of movement between North and South, nothing has
changed here. By Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; UNITED STATES &LR;  _  &UR; General &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' news category)
