 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
 (Repeating)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR TUESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Tuesday, May 3:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   DISNEY-TIMEWARNER (Undated) _ Developments in the clash between
Time Warner and Disney. More details on the negotiations; the
possibility of FCC action and a look at the extent to which
consumers pay when a programmer seeks more money from a cable
system. By Bill Carter.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   DISNEY-MEDIA (Undated) _ How each side in the dispute is using
the media, as well as its own media, to get its point of view
across. By Felicity Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   Related stories as appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T-OUTLOOK (New York) _ AT&AMP;T says earnings this year will be
less than expected, and its shares fall as much as 14 percent. The
company cites slower growth in its long-distance phone operations
and says it plans to cut 6,200 jobs by 2001. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ Developments in the Microsoft
antitrust case. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-EUROPE (Cambridge, England) _ How the proposed breakup
of Microsoft is being viewed in Europe. The views of regulators,
entrepreneurs and rivals of Microsoft. By Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-SALES (Detroit) _ Auto makers report United States sales of
vehicles in April. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stocks were lower in early trading. At 10:55
a.m., the Dow Jones industrial average was off 66 points, or 0.61
percent, dragged down by AT&AMP;T, which accounts for nearly 29 points
of the Dow's decline. The S&AMP;P 500 was down 0.65 percent and the
Nasdaq composite index was down 1.03 percent. Treasury prices were
slighty lower. European stock markets, back from their Monday
holiday, were largely higher, with Frankfurt up 1.63 percent; but
London was down 0.03 percent. The Nikkei closed up 0.20 percent,
and the Hang Seng index ended up 1.92 percent.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TRAVEL (Undated) _ The business travel column. By Nancy
Sharkey.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-TELECOMS (Frankfurt, Germany) _ Germany begins an
auction of next-generation mobile phone licenses. Twelve bidders,
including Deutsche Telekom and MCI Worldcom, enter, in a sale that
generate $50 billion, more than Britain's recent auction. By Edmund
L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-ECON (Geneva, Switzerland) _ Looking at a U.N. survey of
Europe that predicts average GDP growth for Western Europe will
exceed 3 percent for the first time since 1990. By Elizabeth Olson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MANAGEMENT PAGE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   JACOBS-MANAGEMENT (Evanston, Ill.) _ No one has had a greater
effect on management education in the United States than Dr. Donald
P. Jacobs, dean of the Kellogg Graduate School of Management at
Northwestern University, say his peers at schools around the
country. In 25 years at the helm, he created the prototype of the
modern business school, management experts say, fostering a boom in
M.B.A.'s. And Jacobs has become something of a model manager
himself. Unlike many academic institutions, Kellogg acts quickly,
putting in place pilot programs and taking time later to decide
whether they deserve a permanent place in the curriculum. ``He
pushes constant change,'' a colleague says. By David Leonhardt.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KAPLAN-MANAGEMENT (Undated) _ Seth Kaplan, founder and managing
director of Informatics East China Inc.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S.-TRADE (New York) _ Samuel Berger, the national
security adviser, is at Columbia to give what the White House says
will be an important speech on China trade and national security.
By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   IVORYCOAST-MILITARY (Abidjan) _ In the four months since an
initially popular coup, the armys is everywhere _ traffic cop,
soccer coach, gym teacher. The military is in total control in a
country that for decades had been one of the few African nations
not to have experienced military rule and still stands as the
richest in French-speaking Africa. By Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-DMZ (Panmunjon) _ For American and South Korean soldiers
stationed in the demilitarized zone that divides the two Koreas,
days begin with a blast of martial music and Communist propaganda
blaring from gigantic loudspeakers that North Korea has erected
just across the heavily fortified border. Despite all the talk of
movement between North and South, nothing has changed here. By
Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-HOLOCAUST (Jerusalem) _ At 10 a.m., the siren goes off to
announce Holocaust Remembrance Day. All of Israel freezes, gets out
of their cars and pauses for a moment, except the ultra-Orthodox.
The reasons are complicated, not surprisingly, and have to do not
just with how one should remember the Holocaust, but also what
should be remembered. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT7.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY-REPUBS (Washington) _ From citizenship proposals to
the plan for a hearing on the raid, Republicans have talked very
tough about Elian, but, so far, have ended up doing very little. By
Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTONS-TEENS (Washington) _ Bill and Hillary Clinton hold a
daylong conference on teen-agers, with the title ``Raising
Responsible and Resourceful Youth.'' By Marc Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   PHILLY-CONVENTION (Philadelphia) _ After 52 years, Philadelphia
prepares for another presidential convention, having rushed to add
4,500 hotel rooms in the past four years to build itself into a
first-line hospitality city. An old Democratic bastion with a fresh
gleam has won the Republicans' favor, thanks to the vision of Ed
Rendell, former Mayor who must watch the summer fun from afar in
his new role as Democratic national chairman. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-CRIME (Atlanta) _ Trying again to solidify his appeal in
the center, Gore offers some proposals on crime, with a focus on
dealing with drug problems of prisoners. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-PRIMARIES (Washington) _ A Republican group has proposed
a primary system that would end front loading, perhaps decreasing
the importance of early money in the presidential nominating
system. The Democrats are wary, but have plenty of time to respond.
By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-ECON (Washington) _ Bush economics experts add detail to
his economic proposals and rebut accusations by the Gore campaign.
By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ News from the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-BONFIRE (College Station, Texas) _ A commission
investigating the collapse of the Texas A&AMP;M University Bonfire,
which killed 12 people, issues its findings today concerning what
went wrong. Unknown is whether the commission will place blame on
the students who build the huge bonfire structure, or if they will
place any blame at all. This report will be critical when A&AMP;M
President Ray Bowen is expected to decide later this spring whether
Bonfire will continue. By Jim Yardley.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT3.
</P>
<P>
   ARK-EXECUTE (Undated) _ Arkansas to execute a woman for the
first time. She is a mother who killed her two children. The
execution is schudeled at 10 p.m. EDT. By Emily Yellin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-LYME-DISEASE (Undated) _ Three congressmen are calling for
an investigation into allegations that federal and state health
officials have inappropriately taken sides and shown scientific
bias in an unresolved but bitter medical dispute over how to treat
Lyme disease. Aides to lawmakers from Connecticut, Pennsylvania and
New Jersey _ three states that are among those with the highest
incidence of the disease in the nation _ say they will ask for a
probe of charges that federal agencies misallocated research funds
that were to have been devoted to a better understanding of the
long-term effects of the still baffling disease that many patients
say has left them with serious neurological problems that can only
be treated with long-term antibiotics. By Holcomb B. Noble. (2000
words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Paul Krugman's ``Reckonings'' and Maureen Dowd's ``Liberties.''
</P>
