<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3370 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-LONDON-MAYOR-BOS &LR;      05-02 1211
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONDON-MAYOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VETERAN OF LABOR'S OLDER WARS, DEFYING BLAIR, MAY WIN LONDON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ If the bookies are right, and they usually are, Ken
Livingstone, a maverick left-wing member of Parliament, will become
London's first elected mayor on Thursday, and Tony Blair's worst
nightmare will have been realized.
</P>
<P>
   Blair, the immensely popular prime minister, has mostly had his
way since he led his Labor Party to a landslide general election
victory in May 1997. Blair enjoys the biggest majority in
Parliament in nearly two centuries, allowing him to push through
virtually any legislation he wants. He has re-branded stodgy old
Britain as Cool Britannia and has positioned himself and Britain as
the bridge between the United States and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition Conservatives are at an all-time low in the
polls, posing no threat to Blair's popularity. He has gotten rid of
the rare check on his power, the conservative peers who inherited
their titles in the House of Lords. And, at 46, Blair is a few
weeks away from becoming a father for the fourth time, the first
prime minister to have a child born at 10 Downing St. in 150 years.
</P>
<P>
   But then there's ``Red Ken.''
</P>
<P>
   Livingstone, a dyed-in-the-wool left-winger, is everything that
Blair and the new Labor Party leadership deplore. Blairites thunder
that it was Livingstone and other ideologically rigid left-wingers
who were so beholden to unions and extremist causes that they made
the Labor Party unelectable for 18 years and allowed Margaret
Thatcher and her reactionary Tories to run roughshod over Britain
for a generation.
</P>
<P>
   Blair and his top aides, who undid the Tory lock on power by
moving Labor toward the center and making it more
business-friendly, were determined not to let Livingstone be
Labor's candidate in the mayoral election. But their heavyhanded
tactics backfired, offending Londoners' sense of fair play and
fueling Livingstone's improbable campaign as an independent.
</P>
<P>
   He was expelled from the Labor Party but is heavily favored to
win. The most recent poll has him with 51 percent of the vote, 34
percent ahead of his closest rival.
</P>
<P>
   A maverick and something of a loner, Livingstone is a darling of
the left-wing press but is derided as loony by the right, which
consider him a communist-loving, self-loathing Englishman and an
IRA apologist. Conservatives say Livingstone is a self-aggrandizing
publicity hound, an ideologue incapable of making the compromises
and pragmatic decisions required of a mayor of a city of more than
7 million people.
</P>
<P>
   London has been run by the national government for 14 years.
Livingstone headed the Greater London Council, the city's last
local government, when Thatcher abolished it in 1986 after its
liberal leaders attacked her conservative policies. The council was
something like the Cambridge City Council in Massachusetts, where
no cause was too far to the left to merit a fawning resolution. In
the London council, Sinn Fein, the political wing of the Irish
Republican Army, was treated fondly even while the IRA was bombing
London.
</P>
<P>
   Even some of those who deplored the Labor Party's efforts to
keep Livingstone out of the mayor's race are wary of him regaining
the power he once wielded. Simon Jenkins, a columnist for the
Evening Standard, argued passionately that Livingstone deserved a
chance to run, but he is appalled at the prospect of him winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``His proposed four-year freeze on train and bus fares is
financial madness,'' Jenkins said. ``His vulnerability to any lobby
that can gain his ear promises a return to the old mayhem.
Interesting he may be, incompetent most certainly.''
</P>
<P>
   But most Londoners, especially minorities who feel cut off from
the establishment, seem to love him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ken's a Londoner,'' said Fiona Shaw, 30, an Irish-born hotel
receptionist, bestowing what is apparently the highest praise one
can lavish. ``He cares about ordinary people, people who ride The
Tube.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tube is London's creaky, crumbling subway system, also known
as The Underground. It's overcrowded, it often breaks down, and its
escalators in many of its cavernous stations are broken.
Livingstone wants to freeze fares and float bonds to improve it.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, it was Blair who made Livingstone's return to power
possible, pushing for London's first elected mayor as part of his
push to decentralize power and to bolster local government.
</P>
<P>
   ``This contest has done exactly what the prime minister
intended. It has rekindled interest in local government,'' said
Patrick J. Dunleavy, a professor of government at the London School
of Economics. ``But Livingstone winning will present Blair with all
sorts of headaches and challenges.''
</P>
<P>
   While turnout in local elections in Britain is typically about
25 percent, Dunleavy predicts that the mayoral race could bring out
50 percent of the 5 million voters, handing whoever wins the
biggest single mandate in Europe, where parliamentary systems mean
that individuals, even prime ministers, are elected by relatively
small constituencies.
</P>
<P>
   Dunleavy said the London mayor will have limited powers, and
will be unable to raise taxes or dictate spending, but will have
authority to levy fees on those driving into London. The mayor will
have influence over the two institutions that matter most to
Londoners: public transportation and the Metropolitan Police.
</P>
<P>
   More significantly, Dunleavy said, the mayor, overnight, will
become a celebrity and a national and international figure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever wins will be the leader of one of the three or four
truly international cities in the world,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Livingstone's opponents have had trouble matching his ability to
generate publicity, especially Frank Dobson, Blair's handpicked
candidate. In the most recent polls, Dobson is struggling to hold
onto third place.
</P>
<P>
   Bearded, paunchy, and described as reserved by friends and as
downright dull by critics, Dobson is by most accounts a competent
administrator. He served as health minister before being drafted,
some would say forced, by the party leadership to challenge
Livingstone. Dobson has failed to stir passions.
</P>
<P>
   The Conservative candidate, Steve Norris, who is running a
distant second in the polls, has stirred passions, but in a James
Brown sort of way. When questioned about his repeated infidelities,
Brown, the Godfather of Soul, once said, ``I simply have got to
have lots of ladies.'' Norris made virtually the same admission
after his myriad affairs were gleefully catalogued by the British
tabloids.
</P>
<P>
   Put off by his philandering, Conservatives chose Jeffrey Archer,
a roguish novelist, as their candidate. But he was forced to quit
the race in November after it emerged that Archer had lied in a
libel case in which he successfully sued two newspapers that had
said he had spent a night with a prostitute in a seedy hotel.
Norris became the candidate by default.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, it made little difference. Most everybody agrees
that come Thursday, Ken Livingstone, flashing his trademark
Cheshire cat grin, will be mayor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Kevin Cullen, the Boston Globe European correspondent, is based in
London.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
