<SLUG> BC-GAY-MURDER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PAROLE CASE PITS GOVERNOR AGAINST FELLOW DEMOCRATS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ When someone called Robert Rosenkrantz a
``faggot'' at his high school graduation party and exposed his
homosexuality to his father, the 18-year-old went into a panic,
bought an Uzi and, a week later, put 10 bullets into the man who
insulted him.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after 15 years in prison for second-degree murder, the
Rosenkrantz case is at the center of a political fight between Gov.
Gray Davis and fellow Democrats in the Legislature, many of whom
believe Rosenkrantz should be set free because he has been a model
prisoner.
</P>
<P>
   The case is jeopardizing a Davis appointment to the state Board
of Prison Terms, which has refused to find Rosenkrantz suitable for
parole, despite an unprecedented court order requiring them to do
so.
</P>
<P>
   Of about 2,100 inmates reviewed for parole since Davis became
governor in 1999, the prison board has recommended parole only 18
times, and the governor has rejected every one, including
Rosenkrantz.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ought not to have a system that runs on automatic pilot in
these kinds of cases,'' said state Sen. Richard Polanco, a Los
Angeles Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   The Rosenkrantz case is widening a political split between Davis
and Senate President pro tem John Burton, a San Francisco Democrat
who is the state's most powerful lawmaker.
</P>
<P>
   Against the governor's wishes, Burton has blocked the
appointment of the parole board's former chairman, James W.
Nielsen, after allegations that disabled prisoners were being
ignored at hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenkrantz, now 34, was convicted of second-degree murder and
sentenced to 17 years to life after the June 1985 killing in the
Los Angeles area.
</P>
<P>
   Then 18, he was headed to college and was host for a graduation
party at his parent's beach house when his brother and one of the
brother's friends, Steven Redman, burst into the party screaming
``faggots'' and attacked the party-goers. Rosenkrantz's nose was
broken.
</P>
<P>
   Redman later told Rosenkrantz's father that his son was gay,
prompting Rosenkrantz to be disowned. (The father has since
embraced his son.)
</P>
<P>
   Rosenkrantz bought an Uzi submachine gun, went to a firing range
to practice and confronted Redman a week after the party. When
Redman refused to recant his statement, and called him a ``faggot''
again, Rosenkrantz shot him 10 times and drove away.
</P>
<P>
   Since his conviction, Rosenkrantz has earned a college degree
and started tutoring other inmates.
</P>
<P>
   Prison officials say he is a model inmate who has not received a
single citation for discipline problems.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous psychologists say he is fit to be released. Prosecutors
in his case, the trial judge and detective who worked on the case
say he should be released. Redman's grandmother, the victim's last
surviving relative, thinks Rosenkrantz should be paroled.
</P>
<P>
   An appeals court ruled on April 27 that the parole board had
abused its discretion when it found Rosenkrantz unsuitable for
parole.
</P>
<P>
   The court ordered a new parole hearing within 30 days. The
appeals panel was supporting a Superior Court judge who last year
ordered a release date for Rosenkrantz, saying he no longer
remained a danger to society.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's never happened before. There has never been a court
order that the board must find someone suitable for release,'' said
Rowan L. Klein, Rosenkrantz's Los Angeles-based attorney. ``The
parole board can't have an across-the-board policy. That just makes
all cases automatically the maximum sentence. ... They're supposed
to be given due consideration.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
