<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 15:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3374 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SCI-INFECT-BOS &LR;      05-02 1673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-INFECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH OFFICIALS BATTLE A RISING TIDE OF DISEASES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boston is 190 miles from New York City as the crow flies _ and
that's the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Crows are a favorite target of the West Nile virus, the latest
``new'' human disease organism to appear in North America. The
viral import, which most closely resembles a strain found in the
Middle East but might have come from Africa, Europe or Asia, killed
seven people last summer in the New York metropolitan area. It
caused serious but nonfatal brain infections in 62 older
individuals, and infected perhaps 2,000 others who didn't fall ill.
</P>
<P>
   Now health officials fear West Nile encephalitis may soon hitch
a ride to southern New England in the blood of a crow.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't take a flock of crows to seed virus into an area,''
said Ralph Timperi, director of the Massachusetts Health
Department's State Laboratory Institute. ``One infected bird could
do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of crows died of West Nile virus disease last summer
and fall in New York, New Jersey, Connecticut and, in one known
case, Baltimore. The crows picked up the virus from a mosquito
species called Culex that especially likes to breed and bite in
urban areas.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists don't know why crows are exquisitely sensitive to the
West Nile virus strain that popped up last season. But they do know
that infected crows develop remarkably high blood levels of the
virus before they sicken and die, providing opportunity for
mosquitoes to amplify the virus across the landscape. And while
crows don't migrate, they do range 200 miles or so from their home
territory.
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't have to be a crow, either. Federal health officials
have tracked West Nile virus in 18 bird species so far.
Massachusetts health officials and their counterparts along the
Eastern seaboard are worried that robins and starlings, two common
species that roost like crows, could also spread the virus in the
coming months. Hawks and chickens are also susceptible.
</P>
<P>
   But state and federal health officials acknowledge that they
have no idea whether West Nile virus will cause significant human
disease this season, or where. ``We're looking at the whole state
as potentially at risk,'' said Dr. Bela Matyas, medical director of
the state health department's epidemiology program.
</P>
<P>
   The unfolding West Nile encephalitis story is yet another
illustration of the entire globe's rising vulnerability to emerging
infections. It's an alarming trend, health researchers say, that
offers fresh examples almost every month.
</P>
<P>
   ``After almost a decade of battling emerging infections, it
seems that the factors supporting their occurrence have only become
more common and complicated,'' infectious disease expert Michael T.
Osterholm notes in the current New England Journal of Medicine.
``Our task is a lot like trying to swim against the current of a
raging river.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in highly developed nations with the world's best public
health infrastructure, microbes old and new are often winning
battles in a war that not long ago society seemingly had almost
won. Infectious-disease mortality in this country has increased
during the last two decades after 80 years of dramatic and steady
decline, according to Dr. Steven Ostroff of the US Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   If AIDS deaths are counted, Ostroff said, the US
infectious-disease mortality rate increased 58 percent since 1980.
Even removing AIDS from the tally, the nation has experienced a 22
percent rise in infectious disease deaths during that period.
</P>
<P>
   A common denominator of many emerging diseases, health
authorities say, is the vast and rapid traffic of people, food
products, and animals across increasingly permeable international
boundaries. ``Infectious diseases can move rapidly and cause
enormous health problems these days,'' Timperi said. ``If something
is happening anywhere, it's a concern to us.''
</P>
<P>
   West Nile virus, for instance, is thought by many scientists to
have arrived on these shores in the blood of a bird, or perhaps an
infected mosquito, most likely from the Middle East. Genetic
analysis of the virus showed it most closely resembled a strain
that killed a goose in Israel in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   That means, the CDC's Ostroff said, that humans inadvertently
enabled the virus to leap to New York City, either in an airplane
or a ship's cargo hold. He noted that the sentinel cases in last
year's West Nile encephalitis outbreak arose within a few miles of
Kennedy International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Besides its predilection for crows, robins, chickens, hawks and
other common bird species, West Nile virus has another feature that
worries public health authorities. The ``vector'' that carries it
between birds and humans is the Culex mosquito species that thrives
in urban areas and feeds all night. By contrast, the Aedes mosquito
species that carries deadly Eastern equine encephalitis prefers
swampy areas and feeds only at dusk and dawn, limiting human
encounters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Culex comes out at dusk but it stays out all night seeking
blood meals,'' said Timperi, the Massachusetts health official.
``Also, Culex will go into homes; not all mosquitos will. It's
probably the one that's buzzing in your ear at night.''
</P>
<P>
   In public health terms, however, West Nile virus's dependence on
Culex is also an opportunity. Mosquito abatement is a strategy
about which health officials know a thing or two. The task is vast:
Think about all those stagnant pools, ditches, clogged gutters,
backyard wading pools and bird baths where Culex larvae lurk. But
it is straightforward.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we all proactively and aggressively eliminate breeding
opportunities for these mosquitos, we can make a real difference in
our exposure to them,'' Matyas said. ``Change the water in your
birdbath regularly. Make sure your gutters aren't clogged. If you
have a swimming pool, you can get little briquettes called Mosquito
Dunks that contain a nonchemical pesticide that kills the larvae
with no effect on any animal. Don't let water stand in old tires or
garbage cans.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Massachusetts, with a $2.7 million grant from the
CDC, is hiring more personnel to track bird die-offs and trap
mosquitos, especially as Culex populations build in late June and
July. If West Nile virus begins to show up, officials will move
into higher gear, sowing bacterial larvicide in catch basins and
stepping up public education.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible, however, that nothing may happen this season,
either because of public health efforts or because the Old World
virus may behave unpredictably in its New World setting. ``West
Nile may not necessarily cause a flare-up over the next several
months,'' said the CDC's Ostroff, ``because we know it's there,
we're doing very intensive monitoring to determine where and when
it emerges, and there will be aggressive efforts to reduce mosquito
populations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My concern,'' he added, ``is that, if not much happens, people
will rapidly lose interest, not do the same thing next year, and
then we'll see the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
FOUR CASES SHOW A WIDESPREAD, DIVERSE PROBLEM
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The New England Journal of Medicine offers four detailed case
studies of emerging infections that illustrate both the global
sweep and the biological diversity of the phenomenon: &QL; 
 &QL; 
Case one &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of Malaysian pig farmers and others who had close
contact with the animals fell ill last year with encephalitis in an
outbreak that killed one-third of the cases and left another 15
percent with long-lasting brain damage. That epidemic was caused by
the recently discovered Nipah virus.
</P>
<P>
   Osterholm, a former Minnesota health official who now runs an
Internet company that purveys infectious disease information, noted
that the outbreak resulted from ``the unprecedentedly large
populations of closely confined animals, particularly pigs and
chickens'' that characterize ``our new global food supply.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Case two &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A 12-year-old Nebraska farm boy recently suffered an intestinal
infection that turned out to have been caused by a strain of
salmonella bacteria resistant to 13 different antibiotics,
including ceftriaxone, a mainstay for treating salmonella
infections.
</P>
<P>
   The boy apparently acquired the infection _ the first such
highly resistant salmonella strain that has arisen in this country
_ through his contact with antibiotic-fed cattle.
</P>
<P>
   The findings suggest ``that the use of antimicrobial agents in
livestock is the dominant source of resistance'' in salmonella, the
Nebraska researchers said. They warned that dangerously resistant
salmonella infections ``could become more common in the United
States.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Case three &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A bowel infection nearly killed a diabetic 12-year-old Atlanta
boy who had eaten chitterlings, or pig intestines, contaminated
with a bacterium that normally does not cause disease in developed
countries. The boy required extensive surgery to remove damaged
portions of his intestine.
</P>
<P>
   Because the boy's poorly controlled diabetes predisposed him to
the unusual infection, Osterholm warned that the case ``reminds us
of the increased potential for infectious diseases'' among the
growing number of people with chronic diseases and poor immune
function. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Case four &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A 1997 outbreak of intestinal illness among 1,566 students and
teachers at two primary schools in northern Italy was caused by a
bacterium called Listeria, which only recently has been known to
cause gastrointestinal symptoms. Nearly 300 victims required
hospitalization.
</P>
<P>
   Italian researchers traced the Listeria outbreak to contaminated
canned corn. ``With a global food supply, we worry less about the
possibility that Grandmother's potato salad will affect 80 percent
of the people attending a church picnic than about the prospect
that hundreds of thousands of people in many countries will be
exposed to a single contaminated product,'' Osterholm commented.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
