<HEADLINE>
LOOKING UP THE DISTANCE BETWEEN EARTH AND THE PLANETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Is there a formula or chart to determine how far away all the
planets are in relation to the Earth at any given time?
</P>
<P>
   R.S., N. Quincy, Mass. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The answer really depends on how well you want to know the
distances. Lots of astronomy books will give you average distances,
which may be good enough for many applications. Relatively easy
formulas also are possible and can be worked out from the
information in many texts, if you know a bit of physics and math
and are willing to approximate the orbits of the planets about the
sun as circles or ellipses all lying in a plane. If you want lots
of detail, you can look in the Astronomical Almanac published by
the US Naval Observatory each year. It takes a bit of work to get
the numbers you want out of it, and you'll need to know what a
vector is, but it's all there for you.
</P>
<P>
   You might be better off getting some software that runs on a PC
instead of a book. It's more efficient to do things that way, just
as it's more efficient to have a calculator work out trig functions
and logs than it is to keep huge tables.
</P>
<P>
   The MICA, or Multiyear Interactive Computer Almanac, also from
the US Naval Observatory, will give you lots of information about
where interesting things in the sky are at any time from 1990 to
2005. You can find out more about how to get this program from the
Web at http://aa.usno.navy.mil/AA/software/mica/micainfo.html.
</P>
<P>
   Another useful book is ``Planetary Programs and Tables -4000 to
+2800'' from Willmann-Bell Inc. The website is at
http://www.willbell.com/math/mc11.htm.
</P>
<P>
   You can find a book and a collection of programs there.
</P>
<P>
   There's quite a lot of software out there, and Dr. Knowledge
would be happy to hear from any of you who have any favorites.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail drknowledge(at)globe.com; or send fax to: 617-929-9263, or a
letter to Dr. Knowledge, in care of The Boston Globe,
Health/Science Section, Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107. Please include
your initials and hometown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-00 1518EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
