<HEADLINE>
GETTING TO P'TOWN, SPEEDILY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Provincetown is moving closer to Boston. No, the tip of Cape Cod
is not physically moving, but a new ferry service will cut the time
getting there almost in half.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Harbor Cruises will begin a ``fast'' ferry service
between Boston's Rowes Wharf and Provincetown's MacMillan Wharf
begins Saturday with daily service beginning May 12. The new
service will take 90 minutes, using a high-speed catamaran that can
travel at up to 40 miles an hour with up to 350 people on board.
</P>
<P>
   At present the fastest service to Provincetown takes two hours
on Bay State Cruises. The company has another vessel that takes
three hours.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Harbor Cruises vessel will offer a full snack bar,
cocktail service, and a state-of-the-art sound system. The one-way
service will cost $25 for adults, $22 for students and seniors, and
$20 for children. Round-trip fares are $39 adult, $35 students and
seniors, and $30 children. Included in the price is admission to
The Whydah Museum on MacMillan Wharf. The museum contains a
collection of pirate artifacts and offers a look into the history
of buccaneers. The line is also offering bike rentals in
Provincetown.
</P>
<P>
   The new service should prove a boon to tourism in Provincetown,
and to marine life. The catamarans are said to reduce the potential
of underwater strikes at marine life because they use no underwater
shafts or propellers, just water jets for power.
</P>
<P>
   For more information call 617-227-4321 or visit www.
</P>
<P>
   bostonharborcruises.com.
</P>
<P>
   For information on Bay State Cruise trips to Provincetown call
617-457-1428.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Free rooms &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the third year in a row, Stowe, Vt., will provide free rooms
and a variety of activities to moms and their families on the
Saturday of Mother's Day, May 13. The event is intended to help
mothers celebrate the holiday in Stowe with their families, and
also generate funds for breast cancer research. The weekend benefit
is a joint effort by the town of Stowe and the Breast Cancer
Network. Stowe lodges donate up to 500 rooms for free occupancy for
May 13 (there still are a few vacancies; call 800-24-STOWE).
Requests for specific lodges cannot be accommodated. A $50
reservation fee will be charged to hold each room. When guests
arrive, they may choose to donate the fee to BCN, or to simply
cancel the charge. In addition to free rooms, Stowe area businesses
provide a number of free activities and tours.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Cape by rail &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On June 18, a Day Cape Codder will depart Boston's South Station
at 8 a.m. for a day trip to Cape Cod, crossing the vertical-lift
railroad bridge at Buzzards Bay and traveling on to Hyannis with
time for a harbor cruise and an exploration of the village of
Sandwich. The trip by the Mystic Valley Railroad Society is $65 a
person. For information, write to MVRS, PO Box 365486, Hyde Park,
MA 02136 or call 617-361-4445.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Maritime Days &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The seventh annual Cape Cod Maritime Days, May 16-21, will
celebrate the centuries-old seafaring and fishing heritage of the
Cape. More than 40 events are planned. Cape lighthouses with open
houses will be at Chatham, Highland (Truro), Nauset (Eastham),
Nobska (Woods Hole), Race Point (Provincetown), and Three Sisters
(Eastham). Other events include a concert, ``A Millennium of Sea
Songs,'' on May 19; harbor cruises; sunset lighthouse cruises;
historic tours of towns and boatyards; and presentations on topics
ranging from ship building to Cape sea captains. For complete
information and a brochure, call the Cape Cod Commission at
508-362-3828 or visit www.
</P>
<P>
   capecodcommission.org. Maritime Days is part of the year-round
Heritage Cape Cod celebration. For more information on the 2000
program, write to the Cape Cod Chamber of Commerce at Box 790,
Hyannis, MA 02602 or call 508-862-0700.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
May breakfasts &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   May Breakfasts are a tradition in Rhode Island. This year an
estimated 25,000 residents and visitors will enjoy breakfast at one
of the 37 places in 21 communities. Each menu offers bountiful
breakfast fare and generally includes Rhode Island jonnycakes.
</P>
<P>
   Among breakfasts this year where reservations are not necessary
are: Friday _ Rhode Island School for the Deaf, Providence (23d).
Saturday _ Quonset Air Museum, North Kingstown; Church of the
Redeemer, Providence; Congdon Street Baptist Church, Providence
(14th); Jamestown Rotary Club, Jamestown (35th); Pawtuxet Baptist
Church, Cranston (74th); Shawomet Baptist Church, Warwick (63d);
Smithfield Avenue Congregational Church, Pawtucket (25th); St.
James Episcopal Church, Woonsocket (80th); St. Mark's Church,
Warren; Wesley United Methodist Church, Lincoln (35th); Bristol
Volunteer Fire Department's Ladies Auxiliary, Bristol (22d). Next
Sunday _ Snug Harbor Volunteer Fire Association, South Kingston;
St. Mary's Episcopal Church, East Providence. May 21 _ Johnston
Lions Club, Johnston (21st).
</P>
<P>
   For more information on these and breakfasts where reservations
are necessary, call 800-556-2484.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Steamy fun &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Small Towns, Steamy Movies'' is the theme of the first annual
Camden (Maine) Film Festival, Friday through Sunday. Camden was
where the racy and controversial New England novel ``Peyton Place''
was filmed in 1957. Not only will that film be shown, but also
``Picnic,'' ``The Postman Always Rings Twice,'' and ``Cat on a Hot
Tin Roof.'' Some of the stars of ``Peyton Place'' will attend the
festival. For information, call the Camden-Rockport-Lincolnville
Chamber of Commerce at 207-236-4404.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Kruger reopens &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kruger National Park in South Africa is again fully operational
following the floods that struck in February. South African Tourism
reports that damage to the park's infrastructure has been repaired,
and while the floods were destructive, the rains have had a
positive effect on the park's natural environment. The floods
cleared waterways of years of silt buildup and dense vegetation
along riverbanks. The soft, muddy ground left in the wake of the
floods has created a boon for wildlife viewing as lions, giraffes,
and bull elephants are seen congregating on the roads. Rangers
believe this is due to the tar roads being firmer and offering more
support, making them preferable for the animals. For information
write to South African Tourism, 500 Fifth Ave., Suite 2049, New
York, NY 10110; telephone 800-822-5368 or visit www.satour.org. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Gardens to view &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Looking for some gardens that are open to the public? ``The
Garden Conservancy's Open Days Directory: The Guide to Visiting
Hundreds of America's Best Private Gardens'' (Abrams, $14.95)
offers gardens that are open to the public on select weekend days
through October. This year 17 cities were added to the book,
including destinations in New Hampshire and Long Island's North
Shore. The book can be ordered ($14.95 plus $3.50 shipping) by
writing to the Garden Conservancy, PO Box 219, Cold Spring, NY
10516 or calling 888-842-2442.
</P>
