<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACING-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWITCH PULLED WITH `EXCHANGE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Trainer D. Wayne Lukas was determined to go into the Kentucky
Derby holding three cards. So with True Confidence out, thrown into
the pile of slow horses, Lukas picked up Exchange Rate and tucked
him into his hand.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas, who has saddled the most Derby starters (35, including a
record five in 1996), has High Yield, who is legitimate, and
Commendable, who is highly questionable, ready to go. He was trying
to work True Confidence, who has only a maiden victory in nine
starts, into the mix. But True Confidence, who gave way badly to
finish 13th in the Arkansas Derby at Oaklawn April 15, was too
dismal, even for Lukas. The trainer gave him one more chance, but
after he finished eighth and last in the Derby Trial at Churchill
Downs last Saturday, Lukas pulled the plug.
</P>
<P>
   However, up popped Exchange Rate, who had finished ninth in the
Wood Memorial at Aqueduct April 15. Lukas sent him out for a gate
work at Churchill Sunday, and _ voila! _ Exchange Rate was headed
for the Derby. It is no coincidence that True Confidence and
Exchange Rate are both owned by Padua Stable, a key Lukas outfit
that wants to be represented in the Rose Run. At least Exchange
Rate has won three races (7-3-2-0), including a stake, the Risen
Star at Fair Grounds Feb. 20.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas has competed in the last 19 runnings of the Derby, but
this marked the first time he had worked a horse from the gate in
preparation for the race. Exchange Rate, a son of Danzig, went 5
furlongs in 1:00 flat under jockey Calvin Borel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I had to do a little more with him because I don't
think he got anything out of the Louisiana Derby (finished fourth)
and Wood Memorial. If he's doing as well as I think he is doing, we
will go in, and Calvin will ride him.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, True Confidence, a son of Storm Cat, will go to
either the Illinois Derby, the Preakness, or the Riva Ridge (on the
Belmont Stakes undercard).
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of options,'' said Lukas. ``True Confidence
caught a quarter (kicked his front foot with his back foot) in the
Trial, but he's fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Commendable is another who has won only a maiden race (6-1-0),
but the son of Gone West is owned by Bob and Beverly Lewis, who won
last year's Derby with the Lukas-trained long shot Charismatic. The
Lewises own a piece of High Yield, but Commendable is all theirs.
Commendable has run fourth three straight times, in the San Rafael
and San Felipe at Santa Anita in March, and in the Lexington at
Keeneland April 21. He worked 6 furlongs Sunday at Churchill in
1:12 3/5 with exercise rider Stacey Maker aboard.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas, who has won the Derby four times (Winning Colors, 1988;
Thunder Gulch, '95; Grindstone, '96; and Charismatic), is eager for
Derby Day to arrive. He knows he has one true threat, High Yield,
the winner of the Blue Grass at Keeneland April 15, who will be
ridden by the King of Churchill, Pat Day. Another son of Storm Cat,
High Yield has an excellent career record of 12-4-4-3, and has
captured three Grade I races while earning nearly $1.2 million. He
drilled six panels in 1:13 3/5 Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to run this thing now,'' said Lukas. ``We're ready.
We have been able to do everything we wanted to do since we got
here. I think all you can do is get your horses as good as you can
possibly get them, and then see what happens. The last piece of the
puzzle was Exchange Rate working well. We are at the point with
High Yield and Commendable that they had very good weeks. I've
looked around (at the opposition), and I feel comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``High Yield has been very durable, very tough. He probably has
more bottom in him than most of them at the track that a lot of the
media are mentioning. He has endured the two-turn races, the Grade
I competition, and moved forward off every one of them, in my
opinion. I had him out on the lawn, and I couldn't beleive the
muscle tone and the weight he is carrying. I'm pleased with his
overall condition. Whether he is good enough to win the Kentucky
Derby, nobody knows. But I wouldn't want to change anything.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cruise control
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Presumptive favorite Fusaichi Pegasus had his final Derby
workout at Churchill Sunday and it was uneventful. When he worked
last Wednesday, Fusaichi Pegasus suddenly reared, threw exercise
rider Nuno Santos to the ground, and fell himself, landing on his
right hip. Fortunately, both horse and rider were unscathed. This
time, he just cruised around, going 6 furlongs in 1:14 3/5 before
galloping out 7 in 1:27 under Andy Durnin. ``He wasn't given his
head until 100 yards from the finish,'' said trainer Neil Drysdale.
``His last quarter was :23 and change, and he galloped out another
eighth in :12 and change. I'm very satisfied. He went well. It was
exactly what we asked for, a standard work. He behaved well. He
played around a little bit, with a few bucks. This horse looks good
going over the ground, and I'm happy to see him doing so well.''
From now untillthe race, Fusaichi Pegasus will gallop only to keep
fit . . . Suffolk will host a 14-race doubleheader Saturday. Gates
will open at 10:30 a.m., with first post at noon. Full-card
simulcating will be offered from Churchill Downs, where post time
will be 11:30 a.m. Suffolk will offer ``price shopping,'' meaning
bettors can wager on the Derby through the New England pool at
Suffolk, or through the national pool at Churchill. Advance
wagering on the Derby will be offered, through the Suffolk pool
only, beginning at noon Friday. A Derby cocktail glass, always a
popular item, will be given away with each paid admission, while
supplies last.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Material from the publicity departments at Churchill Downs and
Suffolk Downs was used to prepare the this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
