<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WARTIME ICON OF WORKING WOMEN HONORED IN CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By PETER PHOTIKOE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   RICHMOND, Calif. _ She wore a red polka-dot bandanna, flexed her
biceps and proclaimed, ``We Can Do It!'' She inspired millions of
women to work on the home front during World War II, graced postage
stamps and posed as a cover girl for the Smithsonian magazine.
</P>
<P>
   She has been a familiar face for more than 50 years, most
recently appearing in an advertising campaign for Tampax.
</P>
<P>
   Her name is Rosie the Riveter, a character immortalized by
posters supporting the war effort and a wartime song by the same
name.
</P>
<P>
   A new monument pays tribute to Rosie _ or rather, to the women
whose work at home was vital to the war effort _ along the
waterfront at Marina Park in Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   What started in 1997 as a local project honoring women who
worked in shipyards during World War II has received congressional
attention. There has been one setback, as the monument was to have
been completed on Labor Day 1999 but rising construction costs
postponed the project.
</P>
<P>
   Still, plans are under way to create a national park in
recognition of women workers and the entire U.S. home-front effort.
</P>
<P>
   The idea came from a former Richmond city councilwoman, Donna
Powers, whose aunt and mother-in-law had talked with her about
their own work during the war, said project manager Donna Graves.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an important moment in American history that was
relatively overlooked,'' Graves said.
</P>
<P>
   Then several California lawmakers and the National Park Service
got involved, creating the Rosie the Riveter/World War II Home
Front National Historic Park in Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   The Richmond shipyards produced 747 ships, said Kathleen Rupley,
curator for the Richmond Museum of History.
</P>
<P>
   ``People came from all different parts of the country'' to work
at the shipyards, Rupley said. ``People who had never built a ship,
who had never worked in industry, all of a sudden learned to work
as a team and build a ship.''
</P>
<P>
   The shipyards at Richmond were collectively known as the Kaiser
shipyards, named after industrialist Henry Kaiser, who pioneered
social programs for workers, Graves said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He addressed how people balance their home lives and
careers,'' Graves said. ``He started things like 24-hour day care
and hot meals at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Richmond was not ready for the population boom, going from
20,000 residents before World War II to 100,000 by war's end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing was ready. The streets weren't ready, the sewers
weren't ready, the schools weren't ready,'' Rupley said. ``And
still people came.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those people to migrate to Richmond was Matilda Foster,
then 27 years old. Now in her 80s, she still calls Richmond home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came to Richmond to help win the war and to make money,''
Foster said. ``They were paying good money. This yard that I worked
at paid $1.05 an hour, eight hours a day, and you get a two-week
vacation.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucy Cortes, 83, was also attracted to the well-paying job as a
ship welder. She liked it so much that she kept her job for 25
years, long after most women had left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really liked everything about welding, but after the war,
there was nothing for ladies to weld,'' Cortes said. ``I stayed on
to do repairs and things like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Drawing from that Richmond shipyard experience, Cortes offers
this advice for staying happy at work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the people and I like the work, that's the main thing
at a job,'' Cortes said. ``You like everybody around you, everybody
treat each other the same, and then you're all right. If you're
not, there's no reason to stay there and work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
