<HEADLINE>
LET'S HEAR IT FOR TAKE YOUR SPOUSE TO WORK DAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA FRAZIER ANDERSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thursday was Take Your Daughter to Work Day, which has evolved
into Take Your Child to Work Day. I like the idea that my children
can see me at work doing what I do everyday. I think it adds value
to my labor just like a father watching his wife deliver their
child adds value to the birthing process.
</P>
<P>
   However, I have a suggestion. Why don't we have Take Your Spouse
to Work Day?
</P>
<P>
   Now, now, I know you're thinking, ``He/she gets on my nerves
during those five hours we spend together each week night, why on
earth would I want to take him/her to work with me?''
</P>
<P>
   Don't you see that the reason we annoy each other in the
evenings is that most of us have no idea how truly stressful and
complex our spouse's duties are each day?
</P>
<P>
   Just imagine the possibilities. A hard-working woman in
corporate America takes her equally hard-working husband to work
with her one morning. With indulgent smiles, they climb into her
SUV and the drama unfolds:
</P>
<P>
   She says: Don't change the radio station, I like that morning
team.
</P>
<P>
   He says: They talk too much. Let's listen to sports radio.
</P>
<P>
   She bites her tongue and continues applying lipstick in the
rearview mirror.
</P>
<P>
   Him: Keep your eyes on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Her: I do manage to make it to work every morning without
instructions from you.
</P>
<P>
   They arrive at the giant tower that contains layer upon layer of
cubicles enclosed in glass and take the elevator to her floor. She
greets a young man who hands her a cup of coffee and several
messages.
</P>
<P>
   Him: Who's that guy?
</P>
<P>
   Her: That's my new administrative assistant.
</P>
<P>
   Him: That guy who looks like Denzel Washington is your
secretary? You never mentioned him to me.
</P>
<P>
   Her: Yes, I did. That's Gene. Does he look like Denzel? Hmmm, I
hadn't noticed.
</P>
<P>
   Him: Look at him, he's typing with two fingers.
</P>
<P>
   Her: He probably hurt his hands lifting weights at the gym. He's
a body builder, and I'm pretty sure he can type, too. Anyway, he
makes great coffee.
</P>
<P>
   At 10 a.m. they go to a meeting in the boardroom. Two and a half
hours later, the meeting finally ends.
</P>
<P>
   Him: I thought I was going to die in there. That guy went on and
on about nothing, and you guys all sat there like he was reciting
the secret to life.
</P>
<P>
   Her: It's his company, I just work here.
</P>
<P>
   Him: Yeah, but you worked on that presentation all weekend, and
he shot down all of your ideas like they were ducks in the sky. Who
in their right mind would put up with that? Doesn't that make you
angry?
</P>
<P>
   Her (smiling): Yes, as a matter of fact it does, honey. There's
nothing I like better than smiling and being pleasant while someone
essentially calls me a moron.
</P>
<P>
   Back at her office, she grabs her organizer and laptop and they
hit the road. They spend the afternoon meeting with potential
clients. She's standing most of the time, giving PowerPoint
presentations. She smiles a lot and patiently answers the same
questions over and over. She never eats anything. Two of the three
presentations end with the phrase, ``I'll think about it.'' The one
firm commitment leaves her needing three more to reach her quota
before the month ends. That's two days away.
</P>
<P>
   Him: It's 5 o'clock and you haven't eaten a thing. Tell me you
don't do this everyday. All the meetings and rushing from one place
to the next. I'm tired and all I did was watch you.
</P>
<P>
   Her: Actually, it was a typical day for me but I usually manage
to grab a sandwich at some point. Sorry, I didn't even think about
food. If I don't make my quota, I'll have plenty of free time to
eat.
</P>
<P>
   The next year she goes to work with him.
</P>
<P>
   A gorgeous woman smiles as they enter. The woman hands him a
doughnut and coffee.
</P>
<P>
   Him: I know. She looks like Cindy Crawford, right?
</P>
<P>
   Her: Actually, she looks just like the woman I saw on America's
Most Wanted. They said she gets in good with her bosses and then
she poisons them.
</P>
<P>
   Now, can't you see the value in Take Your Spouse to Work Day?
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a wife, mother and dentist in
Arlington, Texas. You can call her at (817) 548-5564, or write in
care of the Arlington Star-Telegram at 1111 W. Abram St.,
Arlington, TX 76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on
the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
