<DOCNO> NYT20000502.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 15:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3418 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT &LR;      05-02 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOFU TAKES TO CURRY AS ONIONS TAKE TO BROWNING 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARK BITTMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   One process that can never be rushed is browning onions. Slow
cooking caramelizes their natural sugars, building a complex base
for hundreds of dishes. This browning is especially important for
curries: their flavor comes from the onions almost as much as from
the spice mix, even in a dish with many other ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   Many curries are made the same way, although the meat or other
protein may differ. After the onions are browned, the spice mix, or
just curry powder, is toasted in the same skillet. A flavorful
liquid is then added. And after that, just about any meat, poultry
or other protein can be cooked in the sauce to give the dish heft.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike traditional Western stews, curries are built on their
sauces. The protein is almost interchangeable.
</P>
<P>
   And so, while chicken, shrimp and pork are some of the usual
choices for curry, I had another idea. Over the years, almost
despite myself, I have become increasingly fond of tofu. The flavor
is so subtle as to be almost nonexistent, especially in a
full-flavored dish like this one. But the texture is incomparable:
silken and creamy. Tofu also needs no real cooking, which makes it
even more appealing for a fast curry.
</P>
<P>
   Tofu is light, so I wanted to make the sauce as substantial as
possible. I used canned coconut milk with my caramelized onions.
Like heavy cream, coconut milk will thicken a sauce, making it
luxurious in almost no time. Then, to add contrasting texture, I
decided to use nuts as well. Both walnuts and cashews do splendidly
here.
</P>
<P>
   Because tofu really needs only to be heated through, all the
time and work in this dish are in the making of the sauce, starting
with those onions. (If you decide to use chicken, shrimp or pork
instead, cut half-inch cubes and cook them in the sauce for about
five minutes.)
</P>
<P>
   But the bottom line is the onions: they really must be browned
carefully and thoroughly, without burning. The trick is to use oil
(not butter) and have the heat high enough that the onions brown in
about 10 minutes, and no more than 15. I use medium-high heat, but
all stoves are different, so you may have to adjust yours. The oil
should be bubbling but not smoking, and you must stir the onions
every minute or so. After three or four minutes, they should begin
to brown; they are done when their edges are quite dark and their
interiors somewhat darkened.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CURRIED TOFU WITH SOY SAUCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Time: 30 minutes &LR;
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons peanut, canola or grape seed oil
</P>
<P>
   1 large onion, peeled and chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon curry powder, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 cup roughly chopped walnuts or unsalted cashews
</P>
<P>
   1 can (12 to 14 ounces) unsweetened coconut milk
</P>
<P>
   1 block (about 1 pound) tofu, cut into roughly }-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons soy sauce, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   Salt and cayenne pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   1. Put oil in a 10- or 12-inch nonstick skillet and turn heat to
medium-high. A minute later, add onion and cook, stirring
occasionally, until edges of onion pieces are well-browned, about
10 minutes (for best flavor, onions must brown but not burn). Add
curry powder and cook, stirring, for 30 seconds or so; add nuts and
cook, stirring occasionally, for about a minute.
</P>
<P>
   2. Add coconut milk. Stir, bring to a boil and reduce heat to
medium. Add tofu, stir and let tofu heat through for about 3
minutes. Stir in soy, then taste and adjust seasoning with soy,
salt and/or cayenne as necessary. Serve over white rice.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
