<HEADER>
A3419 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-ELLE-EDITOR-ART-NYT &LR;      05-02 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLE-EDITOR-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FASHIONISTA TURNS A PAGE FOR ART'S SAKE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: NYT Photo 10 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ROBIN FINN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In her black Gap leather jacket, black Prada skirt,
beige Prada sandals, fashionably bare legs and surprisingly bare
toenails, Elaina Richardson, in her next life as the president of
the country's most famous arts colony, still looks the part of her
old life.
</P>
<P>
   She is a fashion editor in chief, the kind who makes being a
slave to style (bare legs all winter!) look like a fun option. She
looks as if she has never had a bad hair day, looks as if she
discovered her cascade of ethnic jewelry (she favors ``glorious
fakes'') somewhere exotic, say, Istanbul.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, her jewels were a shopping find in Turkey, but looks, as
they say, can be deceiving. Better to scotch the temptation to
stereotype this self-possessed Glasgow export who has hovered atop
Elle magazine's masthead for four years as just another smug
fashion plate in a city brimming with well-dressed platters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have been just as happy if it had been Scientific
American _ it didn't have to be fashion,'' she recalls of her segue
into American publishing, made 12 years ago when she landed her
first editorial spot (at In Woman, now defunct) as a matter of
fiscal survival.
</P>
<P>
   Now she is not certain whether to attribute it to millennial
wanderlust or fear of typecasting _ the Oxford-educated Richardson
never planned to turn into a trend-setter/spotter at an industry
glossy _ but in a career about-face that seems heretical in a
for-profit dot-com decade, she has resigned her top spot at Elle to
do a highbrow disappearing act. She is going upstate (no more bare
legs in winter) to run the iconic Yaddo, a nonprofit artists colony
founded in 1900.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think as I wandered my way into publishing, that was never
about money, either,'' says Richardson, a printer's daughter who
grew up in a council flat in Glasgow and snagged her first
journalism job at The Evening Standard there when she was 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``It never occurred to me that being a writer was a way to make
money. It felt like a way to have a kind of life that I was curious
about, and this felt like the same thing,'' she said. ``I don't
have those fears about money that some women talk about, their
bag-lady fears, that they'll end up with nothing. Because I grew up
in sort of a striving but working-class environment, I've always
thought that, well, you work, that's what you do. I've worked since
I was 13.''
</P>
<P>
   She suspects this new job ``will change the quality'' of her
life, and took it for the same reason she veered away after college
at Edinburgh and Oxford from what she feared might become a static
life of letters in academia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to feel as if I'm on autopilot,'' she said. ``In
terms of what I wanted to achieve at Elle, I felt I'd done it. I
thought that no woman now would only talk about her appearance, I
mean, only an idiotic woman. Magazines that cover the fashion part
of your life, if they don't also get into culture and current
events, it's like sitting next to a dinner partner who's a dud.''
</P>
<P>
   With Elle safely delivered from dud-dom, what now? ``I was
definitely thinking, `Is there a next chapter?''' Richardson
admits.
</P>
<P>
   So last month, in a jolting genre jump, she handed in her
fashionista badge (and that prime perk, a generous clothing
allowance) to assume the reins of Yaddo, the retreat that sprawls
across 400 acres of Gothic glory in Saratoga Springs, N.Y. From now
on, instead of free Prada, Richardson will have to content herself
with free poetry.
</P>
<P>
   The trade-off does not seem to scare her: a scholar who
specialized in 18th-century dissident writers and poets, she has
been known to write a poem or two. Not that she is at Yaddo to
reawaken the artist slumbering within: ``The search committee was
very careful, and I was very careful, not to romanticize this move:
you absolutely do have a connection to the artists, but the job is
administrative. I think I would define it as taking care of all the
details, everything from if the roof's solid to if the endowment's
secure.''
</P>
<P>
   At 38 she is the youngest and, with a resume jammed with
short-lived jobs at pop culture publications, perhaps most
surprising applicant to win the Yaddo presidency, traditionally a
post for tweedy arts aficionados plucked from the ivory tower, not
the 44th floor of a Manhattan skyscraper. Richardson is also the
first president to bring a child to Yaddo: she and her husband,
Kevin, a political writer working on a memoir of his Louisiana
boyhood, and their 9-year-old daughter, Caitlin, will move into the
president's residence, a secluded colonial called Southwoods, in
September.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, whose entourage includes a black Labrador retriever
and a pony, warned Yaddo's executive board that her child is not
the type to tiptoe around the hallowed grounds where Edgar Allan
Poe (he frequented an on-site tavern some 50 years before the Trask
family created the arts colony), and later John Cheever, James
Baldwin, Aaron Copland and countless others craved and found
artistic isolation. She recalls her family's first visit, when a
subtle ``Beware of the Bats'' sign elicited yips of delight from
her daughter.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yaddo search committee was smitten by Richardson's
``intelligent, lively seriousness and real love of the arts'' said
Linda Collins, the committee chairwoman. And they do not hold her
fashion savvy against her. After all, Yaddo's president will be
spending 10 days each month in Manhattan, attending cocktail
parties, openings and fund-raising events. Nice to know she already
dresses the part.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-00 1553EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
