<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXASATLARGE-CHAPMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU CAN FIND SOME OF THE MOST POPULAR EATING PLACES INSIDE
CHURCHES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the church bulletin calls for a ``covered-dish'' or
``potluck'' supper, the food is going to be good. The stakes are
too high to take anything but the most proven and popular family
dish to a church function.
</P>
<P>
   So it shouldn't be surprising to find a couple of the state's
most popular eating sites inside the stained-glass windows of local
sanctuaries.
</P>
<P>
   The first, and easily the best known, is the Church of the Holy
Barbecue in Huntsville.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, that's a little irreverent. The church is the New Zion
Missionary Baptist Church in Huntsville. Annie Mae Ward, a
parishioner there, started cooking barbecue almost 20 years ago
when her late husband painted the church buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Ward cooked over an outdoor pit and people just started stopping
by and asking to purchase the delicious ribs and brisket. The
health department asked her to move out from under a tree and
indoors, and church members helped her move into a home adjacent to
the sanctuary. She, and the restaurant, have gained statewide
popularity.
</P>
<P>
   New Zion gets a percentage of the profit. Ward and her crew of
six get the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Now, there is a second church-cafe making a reputation for
itself. Mirinda Jacko and the Christian Faith Soul Food Kitchen in
Port Arthur are the new names being scribbled on bulletins and
tithe envelopes statewide. Newspapers in Port Arthur and Houston
have featured Jacko. Members of the Christian Faith Church are
spreading the word.
</P>
<P>
   The 36-seat soul food cafe started about six months ago. Sister
Jacko, as she is known to her congregation, was forced to retire at
49 when she had a neck injury.
</P>
<P>
   Out of work for the first time in her life, she found that doing
nothing was something she was not good at. Her health improved and
she became antsy. She turned to her pastor for help.
</P>
<P>
   Pastor J. Barrington Minix decided that opening the cafe would
not only give Sister Jacko something to do with her time, but it
would also provide a new source of badly needed income to the
church.
</P>
<P>
   Jacko bought an entire commercial kitchen _ pots and pans, stove
and all _ from a closed smokehouse restaurant and went to work.
</P>
<P>
   The daily specials vary, but generally they include ribs,
meatloaf and the almost always present stuffed bell peppers. Side
orders include black-eyed peas, red beans, pinto beans, cole slaw
and macaroni and cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Two items that appear daily _ pig's feet and oxtail soup.
</P>
<P>
   The two dishes are Southern staples, she said. You might not
find them in every restaurant, but, in every Southern town, pig's
feet and oxtail soup are being made in someone's home.
</P>
<P>
   Jacko explained the dishes in one of her newspaper articles. She
said she starts out with a roux, similar to one used to make gumbo,
and boils the oxtails for a long time to make them tender. Pig's
feet start out with a roux, too, ``but it's a lighter roux, and I
put vinegar in it. Those people, they just like to suck on those
pig's feet,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jacko said she learned much of her cooking skills at the side of
her grandmother and a great-aunt who lived in Lafayette, La.
</P>
<P>
   Religion aside, the Christian Faith Church hasn't reached the
level of New Zion Missionary Baptist. The Christian Faith Soul Food
Kitchen hasn't been extremely profitable.
</P>
<P>
   But Jacko isn't worried. With a portable tape player ringing
gospel music in the background, she said the restaurant is God's
plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been wanting to do this all my life,'' she said. ``I've
been wanting to open a kitchen, a small restaurant. I never thought
of doing it in a church, but that's were the Lord led me.''
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes a weekly column on things Texan. You can
call him at (817) 390-7422, or e-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
