<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 15:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3422 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SHOW-WORLD-REBIRTH-AR     05-02 1319
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOW-WORLD-REBIRTH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW ON STAGE AT TIMES SQUARE SEX EMPORIUM: LIVE THEATER, FULLY
CLOTHED 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT9 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SHAILA K. DEWAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Live girls! Live girls! Live girls are back at Show
World!
</P>
<P>
   The barker got right to the point, and, as he tells it, he made
sure that his siren song was heard through the red and black,
low-ceilinged rooms of the Times Square sex emporium.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran employees stuck their heads in the Go-Go Bar, grinning
hopefully. Curious video booth customers left ``A Week in the Life
of Kristi Myst'' and ``The Best of Raylene'' to investigate. Live
girls. Live girls? Live girls!
</P>
<P>
   But then, in the interest of full disclosure, someone would have
to explain: these girls were members of a theater company. They
were going to perform Shakespeare. With their clothes on.
</P>
<P>
   Oh.
</P>
<P>
   In a city where enforced morality and rents are both on the
rise, it amounts to a meeting of endangered minds: sex
entertainment and fringe theater.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to dodge the city's efforts to rid Times Square of
sex entertainment establishments, Show World Center, which
burlesque historians say was once a widely imitated model for the
industry, has undergone a gradual but thorough transformation,
giving over a vast tract of mirror-tiled, runway-lighted acreage to
theater productions that are Off Off, but not so far from,
Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   While Show World, which opened on Eighth Avenue in 1975, still
has banks of video peep show booths and an adults-only sex shop
that is as brightly lighted as a surgery room, more than 80 percent
of the floor space in the multilevel complex has been de-porned.
</P>
<P>
   In the former Big Top Lounge, which once housed carousel horses
ridden by topless dancers, two downtown theater companies are
running an ``Urban Fairytale Festival'' of short plays. In the
Go-Go Bar, on a stage still graced by a golden pole, one can now
see Chekhov's ``Vaudevilles.''
</P>
<P>
   Show World first dipped a toe into the theater business as a
landlord. In 1997, it leased the former Triple Treat Theater to
three actors who started Pantheon Productions.
</P>
<P>
   But Show World's current theatrical enterprise has its roots in
zoning regulations for sex shops and strip clubs that took effect
in 1998. The regulations, which would have forced Show World to
close, apply to any business that devotes more than 40 percent of
its space to sexual entertainment or merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   To comply, Show World got rid of its live topless dancers and
peep show ``booth babies'' and began looking for alternative uses
for its space. Soon, independent filmmakers were showing short
films every weekend, and an Off Off Broadway theater company,
Collapsible Giraffe, was presenting a play called ``Three
Virgins.''
</P>
<P>
   In July 1999, Aaron Beall, the artistic director of Todo Con
Nada, a Lower East Side theater company and presenting
organization, came looking for a venue for a theater festival. Show
World asked him to become artistic director of a joint venture now
called Nada Show World. The theater companies do not pay rent, but
Show World shares in proceeds from ticket sales.
</P>
<P>
   He could do anything he wanted, Beall said he was told by Show
World's management. Only, please: no nudity. The risk for a
business still fighting in court to stay open was too great. That
meant that what Beall might be able to pull off downtown would not
fly here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Show World,'' Beall said, ``is our chaste space.''
</P>
<P>
   For Beall, the promise of an affordable space was enough to lure
him almost anywhere. In its two other spaces on Ludlow Street, Todo
Con Nada, like many performing troupes, struggles to pay rent. But,
Show World was more than a cheap option of last resort. There was
also the sleaze factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great environment for the creation of art,'' Beall
said. Instead of trying to steer clear of pornographic taint, the
companies that perform at Nada Show World revel in the atmosphere
of the demimonde, using it as a draw for curious audience members.
</P>
<P>
   It has even been an artistic inspiration: the schedule has
included ``God of Vengeance,'' a play about a Jewish brothel whose
owner tries to keep his daughter pure; ``Perviverse,'' a
``sweet-tempered comedy,'' according to Beall, about the London
fetish subculture; and perhaps most significant, ``The Show World
Reunion Show,'' a takeoff on Shakespeare's ``Measure for Measure''
performed as if by Show World's disc jockeys, dancers and customers
of yore.
</P>
<P>
   The show was performed in a workshop in mid-March, and will
reopen for a full run this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Its creators, Diane Paulus and Randy Weiner of Project 400, a
theater company best known for its disco-era spin on ``A Midsummer
Night's Dream,'' saw ``The Show World Reunion Show'' as a chance to
expand their audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought, God, if we can just get the people that want to
see live girls, and then get the Shakespeare buffs, we can have a
huge sampling of the market for popular entertainment,'' Weiner
said. So Weiner, who played the barker, said he gave it all he had
when he shouted, ``Live Girls!''
</P>
<P>
   But more important than the chance to draw in new patrons, the
company saw itself in league with Show World against what both
artists and sex-industry leaders often complain is the
Disneyfication of New York. Project 400 had long been considering a
production of ``Measure for Measure,'' whose plot involves an
attempt to rid Vienna of its prostitutes and immoral citizens.
</P>
<P>
   When the co-directors heard that Show World was housing plays,
they thought the location would be a perfect way to draw a parallel
between Shakespeare's plot and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's cleanup of
Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket sales for Nada Show World's three performance spaces
vary, but ``The Show World Reunion Show,'' at $12 a ticket, brought
in about 75 people each night, Paulus said.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Thursday, billed as ``An Evening of Short and Nasty
Theater,'' Viveca Gruen, a market researcher, was among the crowd
of about 20. ``It was a little scary coming in,'' she said.
``Someone hit on me. But once I found it, it was fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Paulus sees a fine line between theater and sex entertainment.
``The question became, when do we acknowledge these things as part
of our human nature, and when do we say this is immoral and should
be shut down?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the show, the actors performed lap dances (without
nudity, Paulus said) and accepted tips. A ``flyer guy,'' modeled
after the ones who solicit customers for sex shops, passed out
leaflets advertising ``live girls.''
</P>
<P>
   The show was conceived with one particular audience member in
mind.``Our fantasy would be that Giuliani would show up,'' Paulus
said. ``He couldn't shut it down, because it would be this
Shakespeare play.''
</P>
<P>
   Herald Price Fahringer, Show World's lawyer, said he liked the
idea of Show World's being used as a platform to criticize the
mayor. ``You have a great deal of freedom criticizing the
administration,'' Fahringer said. ``The greatness of this city has
been due to a high level of tolerance for all forms of
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can do anything, you can see anything, and that gives
people a high sense of self-esteem.''
</P>
<P>
   To those familiar with the sex industry, the irony is not so
much that Show World is showcasing theater, it is that Show World,
known for its broad appeal and once called ``the McDonald's of the
sex industry'' by William Daly, the director of the mayor's Office
of Midtown Enforcement, has chosen alternative theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's more like a Broadway house, in a way,'' said
Rachel Shteir, a theater historian whose book on the history of
striptease is forthcoming from Oxford University Press. ``It was
trying to mass produce sex shows.''
</P>
</TEXT>
