u a BC-NY-REICH-BAITING-NYT &LR;      05-02 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-REICH-BAITING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAZI IMAGES: EVEN THE MAYOR CAN'T RESIST 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLYDE HABERMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Say what you will about the Nazis _ and no doubt a
lot will be said Tuesday, a day set aside by Jews to recall the
Holocaust _ they managed to perform one useful service. They
provided some of the most enduring metaphors for evil we are ever
likely to see.
</P>
<P>
   You can try calling someone you hate a Bolshevik, but the word
doesn't pack quite the wallop that it used to. Labeling your enemy
a fascist carries a punch, but you probably ought to check his
ethnicity first to stay out of trouble. Remember Sen. Alfonse
D'Amato's lachrymal performance eight years ago, when he turned
``fascist'' into an anti-Italian slur? (By the same token, you may
want to avoid shouting ``quisling'' at a Norwegian.)
</P>
<P>
   Uber alles _ sorry, over all _ invoking Hitler and his crew is
hard to beat for getting really nasty about an opponent. Maybe
that's why so many people seem unable to resist the temptation,
including politicians who claim to know better and find Nazi
imagery to be deplorable when it is aimed at them. Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani comes to mind.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor went to town last week with the phrase ``storm
troopers.'' That is what he repeatedly called the federal agents
who had grabbed Elian Gonzalez in Miami and returned him to his
father.
</P>
<P>
   When objections were raised _ by the Federal Law Enforcement
Officers Association, the Anti-Defamation League and members of the
New York congressional delegation, among others _ Giuliani stood
his ground.
</P>
<P>
   It may be useful to note that the real storm troopers _
Sturmabteilung, in German _ were the muscle behind Hitler's ``beer
hall putsch'' of 1923 and his rise to power 10 years later. Details
can be found in the Encyclopedia of the Holocaust, compiled by Yad
Vashem, the Holocaust museum in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Sturmabteilung members, the encyclopedia says, ``were drafted
into the auxiliary police, and as such they arrested, tortured and
terrorized political, ideological and personal enemies in abandoned
barracks or factory yards that became known as concentration
camps.''
</P>
<P>
   Does that sound to you like an apt description of the men and
women who reunited a little Cuban boy and his papa?
</P>
<P>
   As protests over his remarks continued, Giuliani allowed that he
did not mean to attack the agents themselves, but rather President
Clinton and Attorney General Janet Reno. That, by extension, would
seem to make Clinton and Reno equivalent to Hitler and Hermann
Goering. True, the president once had a cabinet secretary named
Reich. But does that put him in the Nazis' class?
</P>
<P>
   An interesting twist to this political spat is that it is
usually the mayor who ends up on the receiving end of over-the-top
Nazi imagery. Understandably, he has not liked it one bit.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters have carried placards caricaturing him with a
Hitlerian mustache. His emergency crisis center downtown has been
derided as his bunker. Comparisons between him and the Third Reich
are amply suggested in an exhibition at the Whitney Museum of
American Art.
</P>
<P>
   A show like the Whitney's, Giuliani complained, cheapens the
Holocaust and its meaning. Last year, when he was likened to Hitler
during protests over the police killing of Amadou Diallo, he had
this to say: ``Invocations of Adolf Hitler are despicable no matter
who it is. Nobody should participate in it, and nobody should do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the appeal of this imagery remains strong, going well beyond
the mayor and his critics.
</P>
<P>
   An angry Mike Jarvis, the basketball coach at St. John's
University, recently compared the National Collegiate Athletic
Association to the Gestapo. Ted Turner has likened Rupert Murdoch
to ``the late Fuehrer.'' You no doubt remember Jerry Seinfeld's
Soup Nazi, as though the problem with the Nazis was that they could
be grumpy.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, this imagery can be inadvertent, as it was in 1998
when Commissioner Jason Turner of the city's Human Resources
Administration defended his welfare-to-work program by saying,
``Work makes you free.'' It seems to have eluded Turner that those
very words _ ``Arbeit macht frei,'' in German _ appeared on the
gates of Nazi concentration camps.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, Nazi imagery can be as dopey as it is offensive. We
have in mind a West Side woman who was so enraged by a Parks
Department crackdown on lawbreaking dog owners that she said with
trembling hands, ``I'm beginning to understand how Jews felt in
Nazi Germany.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe we need some new adult education courses, to explain the
world of difference between a pooch and a putsch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
