<SLUG> BC-POUNDCAKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BEARABLE LIGHTNESS OF BEATING 
</HEADLINE>
   By MELISSA CLARK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Poundcake is like brownies: a baker's challenge that
sounds like child's play. The name itself is traditionally half the
recipe _ a pound each of butter, eggs, sugar and flour _ but the
technique is critical to producing a cake that is so tender it can
stand alone but still sturdy enough to hold up under a fruit
compote, ice cream or sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Chefs around New York all have their own secrets to perfecting
poundcake, which is turning up on menus with all manner of fruit.
Because traditional poundcakes have no leavening like baking powder
or baking soda, their lightness comes from beating air into the
batter. Classic recipes call for beating together butter and sugar
until they are fluffy, but the trick is not to overbeat, which
heats the butter and makes the cake greasy.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Haimowitz at Morrell's Wine Bar and Cafe uses half
shortening, which makes the batter easier to whip so that it
reaches a perfect consistency before the butter has a chance to
break down. It also creates a lighter poundcake as moist as chiffon
cake, which is made with oil. It works well as a base for a compote
of dried mixed fruit, like apricots, figs, cherries, cranberries
and currants, marinated in muscat.
</P>
<P>
   Using less butter, though, means less buttery flavor. Steven
Picker, the chef at Good in Greenwich Village, uses all butter in
his coconut poundcake (served with caramel ice cream and
caramelized bananas) but takes extra care with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``After making hundreds of poundcakes, I guess I discovered what
everyone ends up discovering,'' he said. ``The two most important
things seem to be the temperature of the ingredients, which should
be at room temperature, and the amount of time you beat the butter
and sugar.'' If the butter is at the right temperature, it usually
takes three to four minutes of beating with the sugar in an
electric mixer to get it airy and creamy enough to leaven the cake.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Murphy, pastry chef at Gotham Bar and Grill, uses another
technique, similar to the preparation of a genoise, for the almond
poundcake he serves with strawberry-rhubarb compote, roasted
strawberries and sour cream ice cream. He melts the butter first,
beats eggs and sugar together until they are very thick, then
whisks in cake flour, almond flour and the butter. Although the
proportions are the same as for any other poundcake, the result is
almost spongy, with a fine crumb.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy's variation might be too weightless for poundcake
enthusiasts who like the traditional chewiness. They might prefer
Sarabeth Levine's cakes at Sarabeth's in the Chelsea Market, in
chocolate, lemon, poppy seed and other flavors. ``A good poundcake
can be dense and light at the same time,'' she said. And so for
many of her cakes she uses a high-fat cultured dairy product, like
sour cream or cream cheese, which adds even more butterfat to the
recipe. More butter, she explained, ``would just make it feel
greasy.'' She also prefers superfine sugar, which dissolves faster
than granulated sugar and adds to the moistness of the cake.
</P>
<P>
   As light as they are, the results bear out her warning: ``You
never want to use the word fluffy with a poundcake.''
TOASTED-ALMOND POUND CAKE WITH PAN-ROASTED STRAWBERRIES &QL; 
AND STRAWBERRY-RHUBARB COMPOTE Adapted from Gotham Bar and Grill &QL; 
Time: 1 hour 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 cup (2 sticks) plus 1 tablespoon unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   5 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   1} cups sugar plus more to taste
</P>
<P>
   11/3 cups almond flour
</P>
<P>
   1\ cups cake flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon grated tangerine zest
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons sliced almonds
</P>
<P>
   3 pints strawberries, hulled
</P>
<P>
   4 cups trimmed, sliced rhubarb.
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Grease and flour a loaf pan. In
a small saucepan, melt butter. Set aside to cool.
</P>
<P>
   2. Using an electric mixer fitted with whisk attachment, beat
eggs and 1 cup sugar until thick and pale, about 3 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   3. In a bowl, sift together almond flour, cake flour and zest.
Fold 1/3 of the flour mixture into eggs until thoroughly combined.
Fold in rest of flour in 2 batches. Fold in all but 2 tablespoons
of the melted butter. Scrape batter into pan, and sprinkle almonds
on top. Brush remaining butter over almonds.
</P>
<P>
   4. Bake cake until a tester inserted into middle comes out
clean, 40 to 45 minutes. If top of the cake seems to be getting
overly browned before center is set, cover with foil and continue
baking. Let cool on a rack before inverting.
</P>
<P>
   5. Meanwhile, make the compote. In a medium saucepan, combine 1
pint of the strawberries, the rhubarb, } cup sugar and \ cup water.
Bring mixture to a simmer and cook, stirring occasionally, until
fruit breaks down into a puree. Let mixture cool, then taste and
add more sugar if desired.
</P>
<P>
   6. Just before serving, place remaining strawberries in a large
skillet, and sprinkle with sugar to taste. Cook strawberries over
high heat until they release their juices and sugar dissolves.
Serve slices of the pound cake surrounded by strawberry-rhubarb
compote and topped with strawberries. Yield: 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   VANILLA BEAN POUND CAKE WITH MUSCAT-MACERATED FRUIT  &QL; 
Adapted from Morrell's Wine Bar and Cafe &QL; 
Time: 90 minutes  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   { cup butter, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   { cup shortening, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   4 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   { vanilla bean, split lengthwise and center scraped with tip of
a knife
</P>
<P>
   1} cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   } teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   Muscat-macerated fruit (see recipe).
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Grease and flour a loaf pan.
Using an electric mixer, cream butter, shortening and sugar until
very fluffy, about 3 to 4 minutes. Whisk together eggs, vanilla
extract and vanilla bean scrapings (reserve bean for fruit sauce).
Gradually add egg mixture to butter mixture, beating well.
</P>
<P>
   2. Sift together flour and salt. Add half the flour mixture to
batter, and beat to combine. Add remaining flour, gently folding it
in with a spatula. Scrape batter into prepared pan, and smooth the
top.
</P>
<P>
   3. Bake cake until a tester inserted into middle comes out
clean, about 1 hour and 10 minutes. If top of cake seems to be
getting overly browned before center is set, cover with foil, and
continue baking. Let cool on a rack before inverting.
</P>
<P>
   4. Serve slices of pound cake topped with macerated fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 8 to 10 servings.
</P>
<P>
   MUSCAT-MACERATED FRUIT  &QL; 
Time: 10 minutes, plus cooling time  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1\ cups mixed dried fruit, like apricots, figs, cherries,
cranberries and currants
</P>
<P>
   } cup muscat wine, like Beaumes-de-Venise
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons honey
</P>
<P>
   3 allspice berries
</P>
<P>
   1 cinnamon stick
</P>
<P>
   1 vanilla bean (saved from cake recipe).
</P>
<P>
   In a small saucepan, combine all ingredients with } cup water.
Bring mixture to a simmer, and cook for 2 minutes, stirring to
dissolve sugar. Turn off heat, and let mixture cool. Remove vanilla
bean and cinnamon stick before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 3 cups.
</P>
</TEXT>
