<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Vermont affirms gay family values
 &HT;    (EDs: This is an editorial from Wednesday's Atlanta
Constitution.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's not hard to imagine why a same-sex couple from,
say, Georgia might take the trouble to travel to Vermont to
register their relationship as a civil union. Even though that bond
has legal standing only within the confines of the Green Mountain
State, it has powerful symbolic significance beyond its borders.
</P>
<P>
   This is more than just a formal commitment between two
individuals. Vermont's innovative statute, signed into law last
month by Gov. Howard Dean, will create pioneers in a legal and
societal sense _ the first homosexual Americans to be joined in a
state-sanctioned union crafted especially for them, with its
attendant responsibilities and rights.
</P>
<P>
   Set to go into effect on July 1, Vermont's civil union law
provides a good model for legislators in other states to follow.
The Vermont law recognizes that committed life-partners of the same
sex ought to be able to _ as married couples do _ get joint health
coverage, make medical decisions for each other when one is
incapacitated, be treated as the next of kin in crisis situations,
inherit property without complicated legal preparations, etc. This
isn't ``special'' treatment; it's simply fair.
</P>
<P>
   Many Americans will say they disapprove of Vermont's unique
statute on moral grounds, but they ought to ask themselves this:
</P>
<P>
   Is making life and the law difficult for homosexuals the decent
thing to do or, for that matter, an effective way to keep their
numbers at a minimum?
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, if Americans truly embrace family values, what is
wrong with a law that encourages gays to affirm monogamy,
faithfulness and stability _ their way?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
