 YOUNG LAWYERS' STOCK RISES WITH INTERNET  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE WILMSEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Mike Kendall was 28 and just a few years out of law
school in 1997 when his firm, Boston's Goodwin Procter &AMP; Hoar,
asked him to work with a Harvard business student, Stig Leschley,
who needed help making his e-commerce idea a reality.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall soon became the firm's main contact for the young
entrepreneur, who grew his start-up into Exchange.com, an Internet
retail site that fetched $200 million when Amazon.com bought it
last year. The young lawyer not only offered Leschley legal advice,
he talked him through setbacks and celebrated his successes with
him. They went to parties together.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an extraordinary thing when you think about it,'' Kendall
says now. ``It was me, a fourth-year associate, who developed that
relationship, not an established partner.''
</P>
<P>
   In the old economy, the chances of junior lawyers like Kendall
having such close contact with a client were virtually nonexistent.
An associate's lot in life was to do legal research and support
senior lawyers in the hope, after seven or eight years, of becoming
a partner in a firm. But in the new economy, where 20-somethings
often head dot.com companies, law firms now see young lawyers like
Kendall as a crucial resource in attracting legal work from the
Internet world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of these companies are being run by young people, and
when they go looking for a lawyer, they want somebody with the same
energy level, the same excitement for what they're doing and
similar comfort with computers and the Internet,'' says William
Lee, managing partner at Hale and Dorr in Boston. ``It's usually
not older lawyers they want.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, many associates are being liberated from the staid
confines of law libraries to take on business-getting roles, in a
reversal of the traditional law-firm hierarchy in which a select
group of partners serve as rainmakers. To win their services, firms
are offering huge salaries, fast-track career paths and perks that
range from Palm Pilots to stock options in the high-tech start-ups
the young lawyers represent.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, even after an associate completed the grueling
apprenticeship to become a partner, it could take years to develop
a client roster. But more than ever before, law firms are running
on Internet time, relying on some on their youngest lawyers to woo
high-tech companies, the fastest growing sector of corporate legal
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have people who are six, seven, eight months out of law
school out there networking and bringing in business from emerging
companies,'' says Charles Dougherty, a senior partner at Boston's
Hill &AMP; Barlow, which is offering associates large bonuses and the
possibility of making partner in five years for wooing companies
into its ``incubator'' program for startups.
</P>
<P>
   Dougherty said that the firm's associates ``are members of every
entrepreneurial group and technology-related council that exists,''
and that many have classmates who are involved in start-ups. ``We
are encouraging an entrepreneurial approach for the associates, and
it is enormously successful,'' Dougherty said.
</P>
<P>
   Most firms where associates are taking a larger role in wooing
clients still keep a seasoned partner on those accounts to handle
tough legal issues and to help manage the work. But firms have
found that emerging high-tech companies need hand-holding as much
or more than they need experienced lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want people they know will care about what they're
doing,'' Dougherty says. ``They see these young lawyers as
co-entrepreneurs who are working with them and are there for them.
A lot of these guys are learning how to run a business as they go,
and they need people to brainstorm with and toss around ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason young lawyers have been put in charge of those
accounts is, simply, that they are often about the same age and
connect more readily with fledgling entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   But, as with all things in the lottery-like universe of the
Internet, it's the lure of sudden riches that's driving such
geologic shifts in law firm protocol. Firms want to inexpensively
establish as many relationships with infant Internet start-ups as
possible _ betting that a few will turn into giants with steady
needs for legal services and healthy budgets to spend on them.
Armies of associates can forge more of those relationships at a
lower cost than senior partners whose time is worth more money,
firms say.
</P>
<P>
   It's also an attempt to hang on to young lawyers, who recently
have fled big firms in droves to become in-house lawyers for
Internet companies _ a gamble for more exciting careers while
possibly hitting it big with portfolios of stock options.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the big dream for lawyers right now,'' says Brian
Lenihan, a seventh-year associate at Hill &AMP; Barlow who has built
his own client list of some 50 high-tech and venture capital
companies under the firm's ``incubator'' program. ``Everyone talks
about that as their end-game: Go to work for a dot-com and get the
options. Everybody's thinking about the brass ring.''
</P>
<P>
   Attempting to counter the siren song of the Internet, some
Boston firms have upped starting salaries for first-year associates
to as much as $155,000, up from last year's standard of $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Others, like Hill &AMP; Barlow, have launched incentive programs
that give associates bonuses of up to half their salaries for
bringing in new clients and racking up billable hours. To further
sweeten the pot, the firm has begun taking ownership interests in
start-up clients and offering a stake in the companies to
associates. In addition to money, Hill &AMP; Barlow lets the most
successful associates trim two years off the standard track to
being a partner in the firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want them to realize they don't have to climb some long
ladder in order to do interesting work and get somewhere in the
firm,'' Dougherty says.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts say it's too early to tell whether the strategy
will work for law firms or even whether it will last. With the
unnerving tumble of the Nasdaq Composite stock index in recent
weeks and the resulting shakeout of marginal Internet companies,
some now wonder whether the dot-com gold rush will soon cease,
ending law associates' moment of glory.
</P>
<P>
   But most believe that whether or not the frenzied pace of the
past two years continues, the old order has been abolished by the
Internet age.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a momentum there that's not going to be thwarted,''
Dougherty says. ``The world has changed, and this is definitely the
model of the decade that law firms will have to follow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
