<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 16:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3434 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-DRAMA-REVIEW-BLONDE-H     05-02 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRAMA-REVIEW-BLONDE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PLAY TAKES A DELIGHTFUL LOOK AT MAE WEST, SOCIETY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT HURWITT  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``It isn't what I do, but how I do it,'' Mae West
used to say. ``It isn't what I say, but how I say it, and how I
look when I do it and say it.''
</P>
<P>
   Claudia Shear doesn't follow that dictum very well in ``Dirty
Blonde,'' her popular new play about the bawdiest of American stage
and screen legends. Which is all to the good. How she looks when
she does it and says it is pretty fantastic. But what she says and
does is every bit as important.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Mae West so famously said: ``When I'm good I'm very, very
good, but when I'm bad, I'm better.'' In fitting tribute to her
subject, Shear's at her best when she's baddest, pushing the sexual
propriety envelope and transgressing restrictive norms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blonde,'' an Off Broadway hit since it opened in January at
New York Theatre Workshop (the original home of ``Rent''), has
moved on up to the Great White Way where West broke into the big
time in 1927 with her first play, ``Sex'' (the title, as much as
the content, landed her in jail for indecency, which she adroitly
exploited to boost her career). The NYTW production of ``Blonde''
opened Monday _ ``Mae Day,'' as it were _ at Broadway's Helen Hayes
Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   It is not, Shear fans should be advised, a one-woman show. Nor
is it autobiographical, as was Shear's widely popular 1993 solo
``Blown Sideways Through Life'' (which also originated at NYTW), a
comic and affecting tour through her 64-job search for happiness.
</P>
<P>
   Developed over the course of three years with director and
frequent Sondheim collaborator (``Passion,'' ``Into the Woods,''
``Sunday in the Park with George'') James Lapine (who suggested the
idea to Shear and edited and helped shape the result), ``Blonde''
is a multicharacter, three-actor, 100-minute play.
</P>
<P>
   It's about Mae West, to be sure. But it's also about obsession.
It's about women's roles and sexuality in a society that places
strict, hypocritical limits on both. It's about the abyss between
the public persona and the private self. It's about cross-dressing
and just plain dressing up. And it's a love story about a gal and a
guy who are both obsessed with Mae West.
</P>
<P>
   Shear, who also plays West at various stages of her life, is Jo,
an aspiring actress who has developed a mania for the original
blonde bombshell. Big, portly Kevin Chamberlin, who also plays some
of the (many, many) men in West's life, principally appears as
Charlie, a film librarian who has idolized West since his student
days _ to the point that he actually made a pilgrimage to meet her
in Beverly Hills, and became an annual visitor until her death,
receiving one of her gowns for his devotion.
</P>
<P>
   Tall, lean Bob Stillman, who doubles as the show's musical
director and very capable piano accompanist, plays some of the
other important men in West's life: Her early vaudeville partner
and hapless husband, Frank Wallace; Ed Hearn, her effete longtime
dresser who helps create her famous look and develop the
groundbreaking gay characters for her second play, ``Drag''; Joe
Frisco, the sardonic, wise-cracking companion of her later years.
</P>
<P>
   The two stories run on parallel tracks, enlivened by plentiful,
well-chosen quips from West's sketches, plays and films. We follow
West's career from the lower echelons of vaudeville _ developing
her shimmy, testing the limits of what she could get away with - on
to Broadway and the creation of the corseted, ``dangerous curves''
persona immortalized in life vests and crullers as well as on film
(a successfully brazen response to the slim, flat flapper look then
in vogue).
</P>
<P>
   The story is told chronologically, but also not. Through
Charlie's pilgrimage, we meet the elderly West _ a remarkable
combination of doddering conceit and ingrained dignity in Shear's
performance _ long before she moves on to Hollywood. Meanwhile, Jo
and Charlie meet cute at West's tomb in her (and Shear's) native
Brooklyn. The progress of their romance is tantalizingly awkward,
impeded by mutual shyness and Jo's doubts about his sexual
orientation, especially when she discovers his habit of dressing up
as West.
</P>
<P>
   Shear's script and Lapine's seamless direction make the
transitions not only easy to follow but a large part of the joy of
the piece. It all takes place within the storybook confines of
Douglas Stein's hot-pink, forced-perspective box of a set, the rear
wall opening to reveal film library or apartment windows, as David
Lander's lights cast cell-block or palm tree shadows to suggest
changes of scene.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Hilferty's deftly suggested quick-change costumes help
keep the story lines straight and take on a central role, first as
we watch West transform herself into her indelible image, then as
Jo and Charlie follow suit. Above all, it's the lightly but sharply
etched portraits created by the actors that keep ``Blonde'' on its
delightful track.
</P>
<P>
   Stillman inhabits his various characters with a vaudevillian's
soft-shoe flair. Chamberlin, so affectingly guarded and vulnerable
as Charlie, deftly takes on a variety of other roles, wonderfully
impersonating an embittered W.C. Fields for a blistering exchange
of savagely comic put-downs with West on the set of ``My Little
Chickadee.''
</P>
<P>
   Shear so carefully defines Jo, and so brightly portrays West's
stance, manner and throaty Brooklyn-accented sensuality, that
there's never the slightest doubt which character she is at the
moment _ even as both grow and develop; even when Jo adopts full
West drag. West _ as she often said, and as Shear sings _ was
certainly ``no angel.'' But she proves a very good muse.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Claudia Shear's ``Dirty Blonde'' is at the Helen Hayes Theatre,
240 W. 44th St., New York, N.Y., 800-432-7250, 212-239-6200.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
