u f BC-EUROPE-ECON-NYT &LR;      05-02 0364
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. STUDIES FORESEE STRONG ECONOMIC GROWTH FOR EUROPE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ A U.N. survey predicts that the average economic growth
for Western Europe will exceed an annual pace of 3 percent if
current economic conditions hold. Western Europe has not had such
growth on average since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Improvement in East European and the Baltic countries is also
foreseen by the 2000 Economic Survey of Europe, which is prepared
annually by the U.N. Economic Commission for Europe. Eastern Europe
is expected to grow an average 4 percent, while the Baltic states
are expected to have 3 percent growth.
</P>
<P>
   Driven by rapid expansion of exports in Western Europe, the
Continent is forecast to fare better than it did in 1999. Paul
Rayment, director of the body's economic analysis division,
however, warned that uncertainties over oil prices and European
monetary policy as well as ``the possibility of a crash in
overvalued equity prices in the United States is a serious risk to
the current outlook.''
</P>
<P>
   In Western Europe, Italy and Germany could experience a stronger
rate of growth than predicted. The business climates in the two
countries improved markedly in early 2000.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Western Europe growth is expected to increase to a
3.2 percent pace this year, up from 2 percent in 1999. Of its
largest countries, France is forecast to rise to 3.5 percent from
2.7 percent last year. Germany's growth is predicted to reach 2.8
percent, up from 1.5 percent last year. Britain is expected to
reach 3 percent, up 1 percentage point from 1999. Italy is forecast
to grow at a 2.5 percent pace, up from 1.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Among the smaller countries, Finland, Norway, Switzerland and
Turkey are anticipated to have the greatest economic expansion in
2000, according to the report, which is based on data from the
Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development as well as
national statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Many economies in Eastern Europe are more uncertain, Rayment
noted.
</P>
<P>
   Short-term recovery in Russia is also uncertain, especially
because of its vulnerability to external factors, like a fall in
oil prices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
