<SLUG> BC-FOOD-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOD QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MELISSA CLARK    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When to Use Grape Seed Oil
</P>
<P>
   Q. I can't find grape seed oil. Is there a substitute?
</P>
<P>
   A. Grape seed oil, a light-bodied flavorless oil pressed from
the pits of wine grapes, can generally be replaced by other neutral
oils, like safflower, canola or vegetable.
</P>
<P>
   Since grape seed oil is extracted via the cold press method (as
are top quality olive oils) it has a clean flavor without any of
the undesirable ``processed'' notes in some other oils. While these
notes are undetectable in robust dishes, they might show up in
subtly seasoned preparations, like mild vinaigrettes, dressings and
mayonnaise, so it is better to use grape seed oil for these.
</P>
<P>
   Grape seed oil is also preferable sometimes because it has a
high smoking point. At the smoking point, oils break down, giving
foods an ``off'' flavor, or even burning them. This makes grape
seed oil especially good for deep fat frying.
</P>
<P>
   Grape seed oil is available in some supermarkets and at most
specialty shops. Prices vary, from $8 to $12 for 26 to 32 ounces.
</P>
<P>
   Bowls That Don't Interact
</P>
<P>
   Q. When a recipe tells you to mix something in a nonreactive
bowl, what does that mean?
</P>
<P>
   A. A nonreactive bowl is made from glass, ceramics, plastic or
stainless steel, which are inert materials. A reactive bowl is one
made from unlined copper or unlined aluminum. Cast-iron cookware is
also reactive.
</P>
<P>
   Reactive materials can interact with the liquid in a recipe,
especially acidic liquids like tomato juice, lemon juice or
buttermilk, which can negatively affect the flavor and color of the
mixture. Most bowls sold today are nonreactive.
</P>
<P>
   There is one instance in which a cook might prefer a reactive
bowl. When egg whites are beaten in an unlined copper bowl, the
eggs' proteins bond with acids in the copper, creating a stronger,
more stable egg-white foam than can be achieved in a nonreactive
bowl. (A similar reaction can be produced in any bowl, however, by
adding a pinch of cream of tartar to whites as you beat them.)
</P>
<P>
   A Primer on Creme Fraiche
</P>
<P>
   Q. What, exactly, is creme fraiche?
</P>
<P>
   A. Creme fraiche is a cultured dairy product made from heavy
cream. In France, it is typically made by letting unpasteurized
cream slowly ferment and thicken at room temperature until it
acquires a complex, buttery flavor with a characteristic sour tang.
In the United States, creme fraiche is made by introducing
bacteria, like that in yogurt, into pasteurized cream.
</P>
<P>
   Creme fraiche has several uses in cooking. When whipped until it
holds peaks, it makes a lush topping for desserts, fruit or blini.
It can be added to sauces and soups to thicken and enrich them, and
unlike sour cream, will not curdle when heated. It can also be used
as an ingredient in baked goods.
</P>
<P>
   Creme fraiche can be found in most specialty food shops and many
large supermarkets. But you can also easily make it at home. Simply
mix one cup heavy cream (preferably not ultra-pasteurized) with two
tablespoons buttermilk, which contains the required bacteria, and
let the mixture sit, loosely covered, at room temperature until it
thickens. This can take anywhere from 12 to 36 hours. Homemade
creme fraiche will keep for about 10 days in the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   Low-Fat Cream Sauces
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am always looking for ways to make low-fat, low-cholesterol
versions of recipes, and I'm having a problem with cream sauces. In
place of cream I've been substituting evaporated skim milk.
Although the taste is fine, the sauces seem to separate or curdle.
What am I doing wrong?
</P>
<P>
   A. You are probably overheating your sauces. Bringing the sauce
to a simmer, which is commonly called for in recipes using heavy
cream, won't work with lower-fat dairy products like milk or
yogurt. This is because heat encourages the proteins in all dairy
products to clump together and curdle, forming solid little
nuggets. Heavy cream has enough fat to coat the proteins, keeping
them separate and flowing in a smooth, creamy liquid, but skim milk
does not. Therefore, only recipes using heavy cream can safely be
brought to a simmer.
</P>
<P>
   That said, there is a simple way to substitute low-fat milk for
cream: add starch. Starch will both thicken the sauce and keep it
from curdling. A good rule of thumb is to blend two to four
teaspoons of cornstarch, arrowroot powder or potato starch with one
cup evaporated skim milk (or regular skim milk), then add it to the
saucepan. Bring the sauce to a simmer, and cook for a minute or
two, until it thickens.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to salvage an already curdled sauce, try whirling it
in the blender to recombine it. This will work with most separated
sauces, as long as you serve it quickly so that it doesn't have a
chance to separate again.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about food and cooking can be sent to Food Chain, the
Dining section, The New York Times, 229 West 43rd Street, New York
10036-3959, or by e-mail to dining(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
