<HEADER>
A3447 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-SLOANE-DESIGN0503-COX     05-02 0626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLOANE-DESIGN0503-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Creative role model: Designer blazing a trail for others
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Her clients include New York music mogul/Atlanta
restaurant owner Sean ``Puffy'' Combs, entertainer and neighbor
Queen Latifah, Disney, BET, Sony.
</P>
<P>
   But equally high on Courtney Sloane's list of people to take
care of are young black designers in search of role models.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never had one and suffered such a learning curve without
one. But I've been blessed with good luck and have worked hard, so
I've been able to accomplish a great deal in a short period of
time,'' the New York designer said from her studio, Alternative
Design.
</P>
<P>
   Since forming the company eight years ago, the 36-year-old has
been on the fast track in a white-male dominated industry in which
fewer than 3 percent of designers are minorities. Her success,
designing mostly offices and homes for music industry leaders and
professional athletes, surprises even Sloane.
</P>
<P>
   For Sloane, the key has been a multidisciplinary approach to
design, taking on everything from interiors to products with a
racially and ethnically diverse staff of 10. That mix, she said,
breeds a healthy exchange of ideas that knows no barriers.
</P>
<P>
   But outside her office, the lack of diversity concerns her.
``Across the country, the number of blacks enrolling in design
school is declining,'' Sloane said.
</P>
<P>
   It's unknown how many minorities are practicing design. The
industry's largest national organization, the 30,000-member
American Society of Interior Designers, doesn't track them. But the
national Organization of Black Designers, which includes 5,100
interior, fashion and graphics designers, estimates all minorities
make up less than 3 percent, said David Rice, the group's founder.
About 1,500 members are interior designers, including about 200 in
the Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta clothing and interior designer Knox Clayton, who is
black, said it was ``unheard of'' 27 years ago when he opened his
clothing store, F'Alonso, in a white upper-class area of Atlanta.
``But then, I've always kind of stood alone and did whatever I
wanted to do, without any real influences in my career,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, opportunities in Atlanta have never been greater for
black interior designers because of the influx of wealthy athletes
and recording artists, Clayton said, yet few are taking advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Sloane explained why.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why aren't more blacks entering the design profession?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``I think they get discouraged because they want to be in
career paths where they can see people like them, and there's just
not a lot of us that are visible.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: How were you able to accomplish so much without a black role
model?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``I really, really wanted design as a career. In college, I
majored in marketing before studying interior design at the Fashion
Institute of Technology so I learned how to sell myself, which in
this industry is so important.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's being done to encourage young designers?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``A lot of the old guard here in New York who have been
practicing 30 years are winding down their careers, so
opportunities are coming along for a new generation. I'm on the
advisory board for the interior design department at the Pratt
Institute and get a lot of calls from design students, wanting to
know how to get started, how to get into the magazines. I'm also
helping to establish the African-American Archives at the Hewitt
Institute here in New York, a place where we can submit photos
about our work and champion our accomplishments. Our hope is that
other people will in some way draw inspiration from it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
