 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Wednesday, May 3. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S.-TRADE (New York) _ President Clinton and his national
security adviser warned Tuesday that failure to extend new trading
rights to China would be a self-inflicted wound, compromising
America's global leadership as it undermined Chinese reformers. In
sometimes dire language that seemed to reflect the administration's
nervousness about prospects for congressional approval of the China
trade measure, Clinton said that even beyond economic benefits, the
legislation is important to American national security. By Joseph
Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-HOLOCAUST (Jerusalem) _ At 10 a.m., the siren goes off to
announce Holocaust Remembrance Day. All of Israel freezes, gets out
of their cars and pauses for a moment, except the ultra-Orthodox.
The reasons are complicated, not surprisingly, and have to do not
just with how one should remember the Holocaust, but also what
should be remembered. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT7.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-SUICIDES (East Haddam, Conn.) _ No one in this town, not
their families, not their teachers, not their personal therapists,
believes Jeff Barton and Michael Dombrowski would kill themselves
the way they did. Early Monday morning, after speaking with several
of their eighth-grade friends by cell phone, the two boys stole
Michael's father's Ford Bronco and drove it into a large Norwegian
spruce a mile south of their school. The spruce, which grew in
front of the First Church of Christ here, was also the scene of a
deadly car accident in November that killed Michael's 17-year-old
brother, Daniel. Friends of the two boys said Tuesday that Michael
killed himself so that he could be with his older brother. By Paul
Zielbauer.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   PHILLY-CONVENTION (Philadelphia) _ After 52 years, Philadelphia
prepares for another presidential convention, having rushed to add
4,500 hotel rooms in the past four years to build itself into a
first-line hospitality city. An old Democratic bastion with a fresh
gleam has won the Republicans' favor, thanks to the vision of Ed
Rendell, the former mayor who must watch the summer fun from afar
in his new role as Democratic national chairman. By Francis X.
Clines.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DISNEY-TIMEWARNER (New York) _ Time Warner restored ABC's signal
shortly before 3:30 p.m. EDT on seven stations after agreeing to an
extension of its current agreement with Disney through mid-July.
Time Warner had originally sought an eight-month extension. The
change came after the Federal Communications Commission gave
indications that it would rule in favor of Disney's request to
force Time Warner to restore the signal until after the sweeps
ended. By Bill Carter.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ AT&AMP;T Corp. shares fell 15 percent,
their biggest drop in 13 years, after the largest U.S.
long-distance telephone company said this year's profit will be
less than expected and first-quarter earnings fell. AT&AMP;T also plans
to cut 6,200 jobs by 2001, about 4.2 percent of its work force,
though it will end the year with more employees because of
acquisitions. Profit for 2000 will be $1.87 to $1.92 a share before
items, about 2 cents less than previous forecasts. Sales will grow
7-8 percent, rather than the 8-9 percent AT&AMP;T forecast in December.
(Summary from wires) By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-LYME-DISEASE (Undated) _ Three congressmen are calling for
an investigation into allegations that federal and state health
officials have inappropriately taken sides in an unresolved but
bitter medical dispute over how to treat Lyme disease. The
congressmen say they also want an investigation into charges that
federal agencies misallocated research funds targeted toward Lyme
research, staff aides said Tuesday. By Holcomb B. Noble.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT17.
</P>
