<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-KHANNOUCHI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD MARATHON RECORD HOLDER GAINS U.S. CITIZENSHIP AT LAST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Texas, Ill., Pa., Mass.)   By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Khalid Khannouchi, who holds the world record in the marathon,
became a U.S. citizen on Tuesday, making him eligible to compete
for a slot on the U.S. team going to the Olympic Games in Sydney,
Australia, in September.
</P>
<P>
   The Moroccan-born runner, who now lives in Ossining, N.Y., took
his citizenship oath in Houston after being interviewed by an
official of the Naturalization and Immigration Service and passing
a test on American history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm extremely happy that my quest for U.S. citizenship has
been successful,'' Khannouchi said, according to The Associated
Press. ``I look forward to competing in national and international
championship events as an American citizenship.''
</P>
<P>
   Khannouchi came to the United States in 1993 to run in the World
University Games. He settled in New York, believing that the
Moroccan athletic federation was not supporting him sufficiently,
and later married another marathon runner, Sandra Natal, who is a
naturalized U.S. citizen. He applied for permanent residency status
more than three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But Khannouchi's application was delayed after the immigration
official who interviewed him was accused of taking bribes in other
cases and quit, leaving no paper record of the interview. The
runner's file was frozen and he had to start the application
process all over again.
</P>
<P>
   After his wife took a job last month with an American firm in
Madrid, Khannouchi became eligible for citizenship under a law that
allows spouses of Americans working overseas to become citizens
without having to meet a three-year residency requirement.
</P>
<P>
   Khannouchi, 28, broke the world record at a marathon in Chicago
last October when he covered the 26-mile-385-yard course in 2
hours, 5 minutes and 42 seconds. On April 16, he ran the London
Marathon in 2 hours, 8 minutes and 36 seconds, finishing in third
place with hamstring and ankle pain.
</P>
<P>
   Khannouchi is considering whether to run in Pittsburgh's hilly
marathon on Sunday, only three weeks after the London race that
left him hobbling, or to bide his time until the 10,000 meter
trials for the U.S. Olympic team in Sacramento, Calif., in July. He
is expected to discuss his plans at a news conference in New York
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   It is unusual for elite runners to do more than two marathons a
year, which Khannouchi has already done.
</P>
<P>
   The runner must also secure Morocco's permission to compete for
the United States under an Olympic rule that requires an athlete to
wait three years to represent a new country unless his former
country agrees.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Khannouchi's bid for citizenship was supported by two members of
Congress: Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., and Rep. Sue Kelley,
R-N.Y., who represents the Westchester County district where the
runner now lives.
</P>
<P>
   Khannouchi was also backed by New Balance, the Boston-based
footwear company whose running shoes Khannouchi has endorsed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
