<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROEPER-COLUMBINE-VIDEO-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TRAINING VIDEO FOR THE FIRE DEPARTMENT? WHAT WERE THEY
THINKING? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Tuesday, May 2, or thereafter)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of the ROEPER column.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.2000 The Chicago Sun-Times  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The bodies have been removed, replaced by yellow cards
indicating the names of the victims.
</P>
<P>
   A textbook is open on a desk, forever frozen. Walls and windows
are strafed with bullet holes. Computers have been shot to
smithereens, their electronic guts spilling out. The trophy case is
a poignant mess. Abandoned bookbags and knapsacks are everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Robotically unaware of what has transpired, an electronic sign
in the cafeteria continues to flash messages such as, ``Good Luck
Spring Sports Teams...''
</P>
<P>
   Blood congeals in dark patterns on the carpet in the library.
</P>
<P>
   And while we're seeing this, we're hearing pop tunes. First
``Columbine, Friend Of Mine,'' then Cheryl Wheeler's ``If It Were
Up to Me,'' then Sarah McLachlan's ``I Will Remember You.''
</P>
<P>
   This is Columbine High School, as you've never seen it before.
</P>
<P>
   It's perhaps the most bizarre medley of raw footage I've ever
seen. If ever there's a show called ``World's Most Macabre Home
Videos,'' this could be the showcase segment.
</P>
<P>
   Spurred by a judge's order, authorities in Jefferson County,
Colo., released the Littleton Fire Department so-called training
video that includes 3 1/2 hours of overhead footage taken by
KCNC-TV's news helicopter, unedited footage taken by news crews on
the ground and a 25-minute segment that shows the interior of the
high school in the immediate aftermath of the shootings that left
15 dead and several others seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
   County officials were selling copies of the tape for $25 _ but
their initial 80-copy supply has already run out, and copyright
challenges may prevent further distribution of the tape. The music
companies representing Wheeler and McLachlan have strenuously
objected to the unauthorized use of their songs.
</P>
<P>
   And well they should. Since when does a training video look like
an audition tape for MTV?
</P>
<P>
   I haven't seen the entire video, but the segments I watched had
absolutely nothing to contribute in the way of lessons learned or
safety guidelines to follow should a similar flash of chaos occur
someday.
</P>
<P>
   What I saw was irrelevant, tasteless and strange, and would
undoubtedly be deeply upsetting to anyone with a personal
connection to the Columbine tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the music, we get all sorts of home video auteur
stuff: Dramatic zooms so we can focus on the blood, dissolves from
the ravaged cafeteria to the funereal library, pans across
particularly dramatic bullet holes in windows. It's creepy and
ghoulishly voyeuristic.
</P>
<P>
   Even more disturbing are the pictures of victims loaded into
ambulances. Some are gesturing; others' faces have already been
covered. We hear random, unidentified voices, including a woman who
says, ``Are you all parents? We're trying to get parents to go to
(the) elementary school.''
</P>
<P>
   Beth Nimmo had two children who attended Columbine. Son Craig
Scott, now 17, somehow survived the shootings. Daughter Rachel
Scott did not.
</P>
<P>
   ``When (my son) was in the library, he didn't hear music playing
in the background,'' Nimmo said Wednesday after viewing the tape.
``For the first time today, I saw my daughter being dragged over to
the fire engine. I don't need to see that and nobody else needs to
see that.''
</P>
<P>
   I'd like to ask the ``author'' of this videotape a simple
question: What were you thinking?
</P>
<P>
   Then again, I already know the answer. The answer is,
``Nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Richard Roeper (rroeper &LR; suntimes.com) is a columnist for the
Chicago Sun-Times and the author, most recently, of ``Urban
Legends: The Truth Behind All Those Deliciously Entertaining Myths
That Are Absolutely, Positively, 100% Not True!'' Roeper is also a
commentator for Fox News in Chicago and has appeared on programs
such as ``Nightline,'' ``The CBS Evening News with Dan Rather,''
``Oprah'' and ``The Drudge Report.'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on the
RICHARD ROEPER column and other features. &QL;
</P>
