<HEADER>
A3456 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-PALIN-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      05-02 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PALIN-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HEMINGWAY ADVENTURE' : A TRAVELOGUE FROM BIRTHPLACE TO GRAVE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Fla., Idaho, Cuba, Kenya, Spain, Uganda)  (Eds: Broadcast notes appear at end of review. Time, channel are
for New York area. Check local listings.) 
 By RON WERTHEIMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Michael Palin's Hemingway Adventure'' is an engrossing
travelogue. But there are two things it is not. Even though Palin,
the program's host and writer, is an alumnus of the Monty Python
comedy troupe, this is no manic Pythonian romp. Nor is it a
colloquy on the life and work of Ernest Hemingway.
</P>
<P>
   In the spirit of Palin's two earlier globe-trotting series, this
four-hour ``Adventure'' _ which PBS is showing in two chunks,
Wednesday night and next Wednesday _ gives Palin wide latitude (not
to mention longitude) for his wry observations. They are often
delightful. That's lucky because while the series visits
Hemingway's birthplace, grave and many of the places that were most
significant in between, he remains a shadowy presence along the
way.
</P>
<P>
   You will hear some memorable factoids about the great man: he
once shot himself while fishing; he loved cats; he hated underwear;
he ate Spam; he and Orson Welles once bashed each other with
chairs. But to seek his essence as a man or a writer, you'll have
to book another kind of passage. Or pass time with a book.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, you can enjoy the trip that Palin is
conducting. He is an imaginative tour guide, both knowledgeable and
curious about the places through which he leads you. He has a knack
for creating the illusion of intimacy as he speaks wittily to you
and to the people he meets along the way, rarely acknowledging the
film crew that is shadowing him and capturing dozens of memorable
images, from the snows of Kilimanjaro to Palin's own farewell to
arms after he tries firing a pistol and shotgun.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, after recalling his delight in discovering
Hemingway's books as a teen-ager, Palin is off to Spain: to
Pamplona, where Hemingway described the annual running of the
bulls, and to Valencia, where he started his first novel, ``The Sun
Also Rises.'' At a bullring, Palin makes the first of many
discoveries of his own distaste for things Hemingway loved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I know better what drew Hemingway to the bullfight,''
he says. ``For him, to confront death was to experience life at its
most intense. For me, well, it's a Spanish thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night's other stops include Kenya, where, instead of
hunting, Palin views animals with rangers who protect them, and to
Hemingway's birthplace in Oak Park, Ill., where Palin learns that
he shares a hometown _ Sheffield, England _ with Hemingway's
maternal grandfather.
</P>
<P>
   Next week's jaunt includes stops in Key West, Fla., for the
annual Hemingway look-alike contest; Uganda, where he survived two
plane crashes within 48 hours; and Venice, where he gleefully read
in The Daily Mirror of New York that he had died in the second
crash. Before reaching Ketchum, Idaho, site of Hemingway's suicide
in 1961, Palin stops in Cuba for the series' best sequence.
</P>
<P>
   He visits Hemingway's favorite hotel room in Havana and his
house outside the city, both lovingly maintained as shrines. At the
house, ``every object is cleaned religiously,'' including
Hemingway's record collection, ``which can never be played, as
they've run out of needles.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end, when he concludes that Hemingway has been a good
traveling companion, you will think the same of Palin. He has
gamely failed in his attempts at Hemingway-style fishing, shooting
and drinking. But except for a moment's jotting in a notebook, he
is never shown trying that most Hemingwayesque pursuit, writing.
Maybe that's why Papa never quite comes into focus.
</P>
<P>
   Besides his scripts, Palin has written several books, including
a novel called ``Hemingway's Chair,'' which he never mentions.
Still, he was probably wise to keep such efforts off screen. If you
have ever seen someone actually writing, you will know: It is not a
pretty sight.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `MICHAEL PALIN'S HEMINGWAY ADVENTURE'
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. ET Wednesday on PBS
</P>
<P>
   Produced by Prominent Television Productions for the BBC and
PBS. Martha Wailes, series producer; David F. Turnbull, director;
Anne James and Edward Mirzoeff, executive producers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-00 1705EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
