<DOCNO> NYT20000502.0148 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3457 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-TV-PARTY-REVIEW-SFCHR     05-02 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PARTY-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE `PARTY'S' OVER, BUT SKIP THE TEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Check local listings for time and channel.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Will the last Salinger to leave San Francisco please turn out
the light?
</P>
<P>
   In Wednesday's series finale of ``Party of Five,'' it seems the
worst fate that could befall any member of the Salinger clan is to
be ``stuck'' in dreary San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Damned ingrates.
</P>
<P>
   After six seasons on Fox, ``Party of Five'' closes shop with a
syrupy two-hour finale in which almost everyone wants to get out of
town.
</P>
<P>
   Yep, the old Hewitt maneuver. Jennifer Love Hewitt left the show
a year ago to live in New York, and what good came of that?
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, her former boyfriend Bailey Salinger (Scott Wolf) now
wants to earn a business degree from the University of
Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey's sister Julia (Neve Campbell) has been offered an
internship by the National Organization for Women in Washington,
D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Their sister Claudia (Lacey Chaubert) has been accepted at
Stanford University, but the heck with that. She wants to go to
Juilliard in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was safe, and completely doable,'' she says of Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   That part I like. In fact, I believe that's the Stanford school
motto: ``Safe, and completely doable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's going to stay with me and Charlie if you all go?''
wonders little Owen (Jacob Smith), the youngest member of the
orphaned Salinger family.
</P>
<P>
   Eldest sibling Charlie (Matthew Fox) seems to be wondering the
same thing. ``Now I'm the only one who's left,'' he grouses. ``I
don't know what I'm going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, thinking of his deceased parents, Charlie delivers
another love letter to San Francisco. ``If they were alive,'' he
says, ``we all would have left years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Good grief, one bad 49ers season and you'd think the whole burg
was Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of the episode, the fleeing family members have
second thoughts. Not that they really want to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always the one that backs down,'' Bailey complains. ``I'm
always the one that gets (set ital)stuck(end ital) here.''
</P>
<P>
   There's also the matter of the Salinger shack. Actually, their
mansion at Broadway and Fillmore, with a bay view. Charlie doesn't
want it; too many stairs.
</P>
<P>
   So the house is at risk, too. In the final episode's single
startling moment of realism, Charlie figures the real estate market
is hot and the place would fetch a fair sum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Party of Five'' dies as it lived, in a pool of sentiment deep
enough to drown a giraffe.
</P>
<P>
   There are half a dozen or so flashback scenes, with the
Salingers pulling at heartstrings. Most of it is accompanied by
maudlin piano music.
</P>
<P>
   Die-hard viewers, those who stayed with ``Party of Five'' to the
end, probably wouldn't want it any other way. Their favorite
fictional family bucked the odds, kept together, grew, laughed,
cried.
</P>
<P>
   OK, mostly cried.
</P>
<P>
   For the rest of us, the ``Party's'' been over for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-00 1711EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
