<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3459 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-CLINTON-TEENS-ART-530     05-02 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TEENS-ART-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT WHITE HOUSE CONFERENCE ON TEENS, CLINTONS RELATE THEIR
EXPERIENCES 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos NYT4 and 16 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By MARC LACEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Chelsea Clinton was away at Stanford University on
Tuesday, finishing up her junior year, but her ears must have been
burning from a conversation that was occurring back at home.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, her mother was using her as Exhibit A in the
first-ever White House Conference on Teen-agers, a day-long session
that brought together academic experts, activists, parents and
young people to discuss the challenges of growing up in this age of
school shootings, body piercings and Internet pornography.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president and I speak, of course, with great authority _
having just graduated from being the parents of a teen-ager to
being the parents of a 20-year-old and having survived it,'' said
Hillary Rodham Clinton as she began the conference.
</P>
<P>
   Although Mrs. Clinton called the event ``more than a trip down
memory lane or an exercise in nostalgia for us,'' she spoke from
personal experience as she talked about the challenges of balancing
work and family, and of the disconcerting feeling that parents face
when their teen-agers would rather spend time with friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to hang around just in case they'll deign to say
something to you,'' said Mrs. Clinton, prompting the president,
whom she called the ``co-parent'' of the household, to roar in
laughter. The Clintons have been extremely protective of their only
child, who was 11 when they moved into the White House. But they
appear quite proud that she has emerged from an unusual childhood
into an accomplished young woman.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton said it was in the small kitchen in the White House
residence where familial bonding occurred in the Clinton household.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before our daughter left for college, the three of us made it
a priority to share at least one meal together a day,'' said Mrs.
Clinton. ``With our hectic schedules, it wasn't always easy and,
occasionally, wasn't possible. But we sure tried.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton called those half-hour or hour-long meals ``my
favorite part of the day,'' and one of the most important, too. To
spread the word about the importance of sharing meals, or any time
at all, with teen-agers, she announced a new public education
campaign on the issue by the National Partnership for Women and
Families.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill and I were very convinced that we wanted to convey to our
daughter a simple message, one that we hoped she would carry away
to college: that whenever she does need someone to talk to or ask
for advice, or just wants to say hello, we will be available and
eager to listen,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton said what she knows as a parent is right in line
with new research from the National Institute of Mental Health that
shows teen-agers' brains go through a second wave of development,
not unlike the quick growth of the brains of toddlers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember the very wise advice I got from a friend of mine,
when my daughter was very small, and she was raising three
teen-agers,'' said Mrs. Clinton. ``And she said, you know, the two
times in a child's life that seem most similar to me are those
toddler years and the teen-age years. It's when we need to give so
much more attention to our children.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   These days, giving that attention is tougher than ever for the
Clintons.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton is busy campaigning in New York for a Senate seat.
President Clinton has a vigorous travel schedule of his own. For
her part, Chelsea, who has a boyfriend and a full load of classes,
is not exactly sitting by the phone waiting for a call from Mom and
Dad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, with 3,000 miles between us, the three of us try to talk
on the phone as often as possible,'' Mrs. Clinton wrote in a column
on being a parent in Newsweek magazine. ``Of course, it isn't quite
the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite their official travel schedules over the years, the
first couple effectively worked at home as they were raising
Chelsea, increasing the opportunity for interaction. And Bill
Clinton was the top boss, meaning if he decided to attend one of
her high school ballet recitals, the rest of the federal government
obliged.
</P>
<P>
   But the president, acknowledging that other federal workers face
tougher times, signed an executive order Tuesday barring
discrimination against parents in the federal workforce. ``The goal
of this order simply says, `no glass ceiling for parents,''' he
said. ``The job they're doing at home is more important, anyway.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
