<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3468 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT03-COX     05-02 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MICROSOFT MOUNTS ANTITRUST COUNTERATTACK
 &HT;    560&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Microsoft Corp. mounted a broadly based campaign
Tuesday to derail the government's effort to break up the company.
</P>
<P>
   On the legal front, Microsoft's next move will be to seek more
time to show the judge who tried the case that the desired
punishment does not fit the purported antitrust failings.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Cullinan, a company spokesman, said Microsoft would seek to
subpoena the government's economic consultants to find out how the
Justice Department came up with its ``Draconian and overbearing''
proposals.
</P>
<P>
   In political arena, Microsoft sought to persuade opinion makers
that the plan to divide the software giant into two companies, one
selling Windows and the other applications such as Office, would be
unpopular with consumers and economically unsound.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's two top leaders, chairman Bill Gates and chief
executive Steve Ballmer, railed against the breakup proposal filed
last Friday by the Justice Department and 17 states with U.S.
District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to key customers, business partners and
shareholders, they said: ``We believe the government's extreme
regulations would be a major setback for consumers, the
high-technology industry and the American economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing in the lawsuit against Microsoft justifies the harsh
restrictions that the government is now seeking to place on
Microsoft's innovation and product design,'' they added.
</P>
<P>
   Ballmer also appears in a 30-second TV commercial implicitly
criticizing the proposed corporate divorce and promising that, for
Microsoft, ``the best is yet to come.'' The ad is being widely
aired in the nation's top 50 media markets, mainly during
newscasts.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Microsoft's top lawyer, William Neukom, previewed the
counter-brief that Jackson will get on May 10.
</P>
<P>
   Although Jackson ruled April 3 that Microsoft maintained an
illegal monopoly that harmed consumers and competitors, Neukom
noted that ``the court did not find that Windows and Office became
popular because of any wrongful conduct by Microsoft.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There has never been a court-ordered breakup of a unitary
operating company,'' he said. ``The evidence and law applicable to
this case fell far short of providing the basis for such a drastic
and unprecedented remedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft does not plan, at least at this stage, to offer a
counter-proposals of its own. There is no need to do so, the
company believes, since it expects Jackson's guilty verdict to be
overturned on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of factual and legal assertions in the
material ... that is going to require a good deal more thought,''
said C. Boyden Gray, counsel to the Association for Competitive
Technology, a Washington-based trade group that plans to file its
own pro-Microsoft brief with Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that I find utterly mystifying,'' Gray
added, ``is what's happening in the browser market,'' which the
government once placed at the center of its antitrust charges.
</P>
<P>
   Gray noted that America Online Inc. recently announced plans to
drop Microsoft's Internet Explorer for its own 22 million customers
and substitute the Navigator browser, a product built by Netscape
Communications, which it acquired last year for $10 billion.
Jackson found that Netscape was a victim of Microsoft's illegal
dealings.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, in releasing a new trial version of its Windows Media
Player, Microsoft sent a signal that it does not intend to be cowed
by its legal woes.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Fester, a Microsoft marketing executive, said the software,
which plugs directly into the operating system, offers enhanced
audio and video quality and customization features that ``open the
door to digital media for millions of consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's stock, which had rebounded Monday after having
plummeted to a 17-month low, lost ground again on Tuesday. It
closed at $69.88, down $3.56, or 4.85 percent, on volume of
48,233,000 shares. The drop came after a Microsoft analyst at
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter said she thought the stock would trade
in the $60 range for the foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: microsoft.com/freedomtoinnovate/default.htm
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-00 1722EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
