<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-00 1722EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000502.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3470 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-PUERTORICO-VIEQUES-05     05-02 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUERTORICO-VIEQUES-0503-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TAKING VIEQUES WON'T BE EASY, PROTESTERS EXPECT NUMBERS TO GROW
IF ACTION TAKES PLACE
 &HT;    (725&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    EDs: This story may have to be updated if the protesters are
evicted tonight.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIEQUES, Puerto Rico _ The U.S. Marines have been storming
ashore this tranquil island for decades, hitting the beaches for
live-fire war games, with aircraft roaring overhead and huge ships
with massive guns looming just offshore.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Marines may be coming again, but this time their
operation won't be make-believe.
</P>
<P>
   Their job will be to secure a perimeter around a U.S. Navy
bombing range located on the far eastern tip of this tiny island
just off Puerto Rico's east coast. Protestors have occupied the
range for the past year in an effort to end 60 years of U.S.
military presence on Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   The job of rounding up and arresting the demonstrators will fall
to U.S. Marshals, FBI agents and possibly other federal law
enforcement officers, according to press reports. Coast Guard and
Navy ships and the Marines will try to keep more protestors from
taking the place of those already arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday passed with no word of when the operation would take
place, although protesters braced for a showdown after press
reports indicated the action might come this week.
</P>
<P>
   Protest leaders warn that the operation could trigger
demonstrations on the main island of Puerto Rico, where most of the
political leadership and public sentiment are firmly in support of
the Vieques protestors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any action to remove us will be the beginning, not the end of
the protests,'' said Ruben Berrios, head of the Puerto Rican
Independence Party, who has illegally camped on the bombing range
for the past year. ``If they arrest us, they can expect a million
people to protest because this issue has united Puerto Ricans of
all political persuasions as never before.''
</P>
<P>
   Some leaders predict there will also be protests in New York and
New Jersey, where hundreds of thousands of Puerto Ricans live.
</P>
<P>
   Vieques seems an unlikely spot for a high-profile showdown. A
sleepy island about 20 miles long and 5 miles wide, it lies about 7
miles off the Puerto Rican coast. It is only about 15 miles from
Roosevelt Roads, a large U.S. Navy base where any eviction
operation might be based.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the island has enjoyed a tourism boom, with
several small guesthouses and hotels opening. The snorkeling and
diving are excellent, and there are miles of deserted beaches.
Narrow roads criss-cross the island's center, with cows and horses
grazing on the shoulders. There are no high-rise condominiums or
casinos, and most of the hotels lack televisions or telephones in
the rooms, catering to visitors seeking to get away from it all.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing range dates back to World War II, when the military
condemned two-thirds of the island's 33,000 acres. Farm workers and
landowners were moved off their plots on the east and west ends of
Vieques to the island's center, concentrated in the small villages
of Esperanza and Isabel Segunda. Today, about 9,000 people live on
Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy property on the two ends of the island is cut off from
the island's populated center by high metal fences that stretch
from the south coast to the north coast.
</P>
<P>
   There is little activity at the western tip of Vieques, which is
home to a naval munitions detachment. The larger, eastern end is
called ``Camp Garcia,'' and it takes up nearly half of Vieques, but
has only a small permanent contingent of Navy personnel and
civilian workers.
</P>
<P>
   The controversial bombing range is on the far eastern tip, about
9 miles from the nearest civilian home. The range is about two
square miles of rough hills, covered with thorn bushes and small
trees. It is dotted with old warplanes, tanks and military vehicles
used as targets by Navy pilots.
</P>
<P>
   The range is also dotted by the protest camps, with several
separate encampments run by a wide range of Puerto Rican groups _
teachers, ministers, labor unions, students and Berrios' political
party.
</P>
<P>
   Dirt roads wind through Camp Garcia to the bombing range, but
drivers must first pass through a gate protected by security
guards. The protestors reach the range by boat, hitching rides with
fishermen who support their cause and ferry out supplies on a daily
basis.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the protest camps on the range, other protestors
have set up a permanent site directly in front of the main gate.
Any law enforcement action would have to clear both sites.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Protest leaders at the main gate believe Puerto Rican police may
try to block the roads leading to the gate to stop more
demonstrators from coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're concerned that people might come to the roadblocks and
there might be some sort of confrontation,'' said Roberto Rabin,
one of the leaders of a coalition of protest groups. ``So we've
asked people to go the main plaza in Isabel Segunda if that happens
so they will have a place to express themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Protest leaders have been preaching non-violent civil
disobedience for months, telling people that active resistance
would be futile and dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   But if the arrests happen, some believe other protestors will
rush to the range by boat, or try to cut the fence and reach the
bombing zone by land. The boats would presumably be turned back by
the Coast Guard and Navy vessels, while the fence might be
patrolled by Marines.
</P>
<P>
   But even if all the protestors are swiftly rounded up, leaders
say they won't suffer a complete defeat. They believe any
law-enforcement action will trigger new protests in San Juan and in
American cities with large Puerto Rican populations, and they hope
political pressure will keep away the Navy bombs as successfully as
the protest camps have done for the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Removing the protestors ``will be a great shock to the Puerto
Rican people,'' said Rev. Juan Franco, a United Church of Christ
minister who has protested on the range. ``This is happening in a
moment when there is a fast-growing sense of national identity in
Puerto Rico. The people feel very strongly about this, and this
would only make them feel that much stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   (Mike Williams' email address is: mikew(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-00 1725EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000502.0155 </DOCNO>
