<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3473 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER0503-COX     05-02 2422
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0503-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Crime fighting at the ywca
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Al Gore unveiled a comprehensive anti-crime package at a YWCA in
Atlanta today that includes $1.3 billion in spending for new police
officers and crime-fighting technologies. He proposed the federal
government provide funds to help local communities hire 50,000 new
police officers, a constitutional amendment guaranteeing victims'
rights in the criminal justice system, new anti-gang laws, and a
requirement that prisoners be free of drugs before being released
from prison. From Atlanta, Gore heads to Atlantic City, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   GUBERNATORIAL SHOOTOUT IN CAROLINA . . .
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen candidates vied in North Carolina today for the chance
to succeed retiring Gov. Jim Hunt, with Democrats sparring over
education programs and Republicans challenging each other's
conservative credentials. Hunt is barred by state law from seeking
another term. The two leading Democrats seeking his seat, Lt. Gov.
Dennis Wicker and state Attorney General Mike Easley, argued over
how best to strengthen education programs with money from a
not-yet-approved state lottery. The leading Republicans fought over
who was more conservative. Ex-Charlotte Mayor Richard Vinroot and
state Rep. Leo Daughtry criticized each other's conservative record
on spending and abortion, while debating whether to use attack ads.
Former state Rep. Chuck Neely avoided most of that fight.
</P>
<P>
   . . . AND ANOTHER BACK HOME IN INDIANA
</P>
<P>
   Rep. David McIntosh and a lawyer touring Indiana in a red school
bus battled for the nomination to challenge first-term Democratic
Gov. Frank O'Bannon, who has no opposition. Indianapolis attorney
John Price, who promised to visit all 92 counties in his red bus,
trailed McIntosh in recent polling. Conservative three-termer
McIntosh's decision to run for governor set off a scramble to
represent his east-central Indiana district, which includes Muncie.
Among the 11 candidates were former radio talk show host Mike Pence
and Republican state Rep. Jeff Linder.
</P>
<P>
   START WITH THE LITTLE GUYS, WORK UP
</P>
<P>
   Smaller states would vote first and others would follow
according to their size in a primary-election plan proposed today
by a Republican advisory group chaired by ex-Sen. Bill Brock of
Tennessee. The plan is aiming for more voter participation in
different states. Brock said a primary process that lengthens the
decision period while reducing the influence of money would be
healthy. The current system is driving the nominating process
toward a national primary day somewhat like Super Tuesday this year
when all states crowd up to a deadline. Under the plan unveiled
today, smallest states would vote on the first Tuesday in March,
with three more groups voting on the first Tuesdays of subsequent
months, ending in June.
</P>
<P>
   PLATFORM PROTECTION FROM THOMPSON
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush put a staunch abortion foe, Wisconsin Gov. Tommy
Thompson, in charge of the platform committee for the Republican
National Convention in Philadelphia. The appointment suggests the
party is unlikely to step away from its blanket opposition to
abortion, a stance that prompted dissension from GOP moderates
before the 1996 convention in San Diego. Bush opposes abortion
except for in cases of rape, incest or when the life of a mother is
endangered. The platform has no such exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   THREAT COMING FROM THE RIGHT
</P>
<P>
   A day after a former congressman from Westchester County, Joseph
DioGuardi, announced he would seek the Conservative Party
endorsement to run for the Senate in New York, Rudy Giuliani
declared that he, too, wanted the party's endorsement. So
Giuliani's aides sought for the first time to set up a meeting. The
prospect of a credible conservative candidate in the race is a
matter of clear concern to Giuliani's aides, since DioGuardi,
running on the right, presumably would draw votes away from
Giuliani to the advantage of Hillary Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   CLOSE HORSERACE _ WITH BUSH BY A NOSE
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush and Al Gore are locked in a close race for
president: 49 percent for Bush, 44 percent for Gore, in a new
CNN-USA Today-Gallup poll. The five-point difference is within the
poll's 5 percentage point margin of error for the 499 likely voters
surveyed. Among registered voters, Bush led 46-45 percent. In this
same poll three weeks ago, Bush led 50-41 percent among likely
voters. In a four-way matchup with third-party candidates Pat
Buchanan and Ralph Nader, Bush had 47 percent and Gore 41 percent
among likely voters. Buchanan and Nader split the remainder about
evenly.
</P>
<P>
   SHAKY FOOTING IN SOME KEY STATES
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore is performing worse than expected in some states carried
by Democrats since 1988, a sign that his political base needs
shoring up in the race for the 270 electoral votes required to win
the White House. In Iowa, Minnesota, Oregon, Washington and
Wisconsin _ all carried by Democratic presidential candidates in
the last three elections _ the most recent polling showed Gore
trailing or tied with George W. Bush. ``This is obviously troubling
for Gore. Those are states he should have in his pocket right
now,'' said Democratic consultant Dane Strother.
</P>
<P>
   LOG CABIN TO HEAR FROM THEIR CANDIDATE
</P>
<P>
   John McCain will address leaders and top donors of the Log Cabin
Republicans, the leading gay Republican organization, at the
group's annual meeting May 17-20 in Washington. ABC reports that
the group expects 50 of the Log Cabin's leaders and top donors, to
attend. Several GOP members of Congress, including backers of
George W. Bush, also will address the gathering. Bush met recently
with a group of gay Republicans, but froze out Log Cabin leaders,
who supported McCain in the primaries.
</P>
<P>
   IT'S WHAT YOU SEE ON THE SCREEN THAT REALLY COUNTS
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after his campaign plane touched down at Laredo
International Airport in Texas last week, George W. Bush waved
grandly to his left and his right as he walked down the steps to
the tarmac. No one waved back. The only people watching were
campaign staffers, a handful of television camera operators and
security officers. Most of the people Bush waved to _ including the
TV crews _ had been with him on the plane from Austin. The Dallas
Morning News noted that similar scenes have played out several
times lately. Bush has been chatty with reporters, but he met few
everyday people during his last campaign swing.
</P>
<P>
   OPEN LETTER INSTEAD OF PLATFORM FIGHT
</P>
<P>
   Forgoing a platform fight, Pat Buchanan has agreed to make his
case against abortion through an ``open letter'' should he become
the Reform Party presidential nominee, said party chairman Pat
Choate. The letter would affirm Buchanan's positions on such social
issues as abortion and gay rights while leaving untouched the
paty's platform, which concentrates on trade, immigration and
foreign policy. The party, in turn, acted to quell a rebellion in
some state affiliates that have been hostile to Buchanan's
candidacy by threatening to withhold their credentials at the
national convention. ``We're just telling people that if they play
games, their delegations will not be recognized,'' Choate said.
</P>
<P>
   HIM? OH, JUST AN OLD FRIEND
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush can only hope his meeting next week with John
McCain goes as well as McCain's meeting with Al Gore. McCain met
Sunday for 20 minutes with Gore at the Naval Observatory in
Washington, the vice president's official residence. Both were
appearing on CNN's ``Late Edition,'' being filmed there. When Gore
learned that McCain would be under his roof the next day, he called
him and invited him to come over early for a private chat. ``We're
friends,'' Gore told reporters later, noting that the two had
served in the House and Senate together. ``It's not that
complicated.''
</P>
<P>
   PROBABLY DIDN'T DISCUSS THE CORVAIR, EITHER
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocate and Green Party candidate Ralph Nader
discussed an endorsement with leaders of the United Auto Workers
union, which broke with the AFL-CIO last October. Nader said he
didn't directly ask for the union's backing, and added that it will
not endorse a candidate until after a congressional vote expected
this month on providing permanent normal trade relations with China
_ which Nader, the UAW and other major labor unions oppose. Instead
of asking for endorsements, Nader said: ``I just tell people what
we're doing.'' Union officials were unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   CONSERVATIVE COALITION THROWING WEIGHT
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-six national conservative organizations have formed a
coalition to lobby at the national party conventions for the
adoption of conservative platform planks. The group is led by the
American Conservative Union Foundation and includes Americans for
Tax Reform, Christian Coalition, Citizens Against Government Waste,
Competitive Enterprise Institute, Independent Women's Forum,
National Rifle Association, National Right to Life PAC, National
Taxpayers Union and the Southeastern Legal Foundation. ``We have
been quite successful in the past,'' said Donald Devine, chairman
of the Committee for a Conservative Platform, ``primarily at
Republican conventions.''
</P>
<P>
   SOMETIMES, YOU JUST GET TIRED OF GIVING
</P>
<P>
   Soft-money donations to the political parties are on a pace to
set a record this year, but more and more large corporations have
quietly stopped giving them. In some cases, senior executives say
they want to distance themselves from what they describe as the
capital's unseemly culture of cash and influence, while others
acknowledge that their companies are simply not getting a bang for
the buck. Thirty-one corporations that in each previous election
cycle since 1993-94 contributed at least $100,000 in soft money
have not donated any soft money this time around, according to a
computerized study of Federal Election Commission records by the
New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   THE PLAY'S NOT THE THING THIS TIME
</P>
<P>
   Without mentioning her husband by name, Donna Hanover, actress
wife of Rudy Giuliani, said she's postponing her performance in the
sexually suggestive off-Broadway play ``The Vagina Monologues'' due
to family circumstances. Giuliani, who is running for the Senate
against Hillary Clinton, has early-stage prostate cancer. Hanover
was scheduled to appear May 30 through June 11 with Kirstie Alley
and Hazelle Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN AIN'T REALLY TEXAS
</P>
<P>
   Austin, the Texas capital, hasn't exactly rolled out the welcome
mat for George W. Bush and his presidential campaign, favorite son
or not. The Washington Post reports there's a cultural divide there
between the city's bohemians and new residents from the Bush team.
And the Bush people themselves don't dispute their
fish-out-of-water status. ``I can't say (Bush) is a favorite son of
Austin,'' campaign aide Joe Allbaugh admits. Says state Rep. Glen
Maxey, a Democrat: ``He's sort of like a temporary resident in this
government-funded house. I think by and large most of the people
who think of Austin wouldn't say this is a George Bush kind of
town.''
</P>
<P>
   PRIME TIME FOR TV AD BUCKS
</P>
<P>
   Television stations are scarfing up money under the deluge of
election-year advertising. Between candidates and lobbying groups,
political spots have become a $600 million windfall for TV, edging
out fast food as the third-highest sector in airtime consumption,
according to the Washington Post. Consequently, broadcasters aren't
leading the charge for campaign finance reform and the free TV air
time it could bring. ``The industry has a sweetheart deal and is
not interested in making any moves to open the door to make it work
better,'' said Fred Wertheimer, president of Democracy 21, a
nonprofit group working for campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   WE'D RATHER SEE DAVE THOMAS FOR WENDY'S
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina has a well-deserved reputation for particularly
nasty political campaigns. But that could change. A newly passed
state law aimed at reducing negative campaigning stipulates that
any candidate who mentions an opponent in a radio or television
spot must personally appear in the ad. Advocates of the law say
it'll force politicians to tone down their attacks and help restore
a more polite political atmosphere. North Carolina is the first
state to enact such a measure, according to National Public Radio.
</P>
<P>
   NOT IN SHAPE TO RUN
</P>
<P>
   Former Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin seemed to reject the idea
of being a possible running mate for Al Gore, calling it ``a
curious notion.'' Rubin said that while he has been around politics
for many years, including a stint as a Democratic fund-raiser, he
viewed running for and serving in office as a special field,
``something unto itself.'' Rubin suggested that it was unwise to
choose a nominee who has not been tested by other campaigns. ``You
don't want somebody in a presidential campaign, which is the
ultimate of political experience in this country, who hasn't been
tested by running before.''
</P>
<P>
   ENOUGH'S ENOUGH FOR BABBIT
</P>
<P>
   There has been considerable speculation in Arizona that once
Bruce Babbit finished his tour as secretary of the interior, he
would return to the state to run for governor, a job he held from
1978 to 1986. But Babbitt says he has other plans. He told the
Arizona Republic that he would return to Arizona, but not to run
for governor. He didn't say what he planned to do, but he made it
clear that he was tired of Washington's ``witch-hunting
mentality,'' referring to the 19- month investigation into his
handling of permits for Indian reservation casinos.
</P>
<P>
   LITTLE GUY EYES BIG RUN
</P>
<P>
   Former child actor Gary Coleman is entering politics, saying he
intends to seek a California Senate seat. The 4-ft.-8 ex-star of
television's ``Diff'rent Strokes,'' now 32, told the Fox News
Channel that he has yet to decide upon his party affiliation, but
``I'm such a radical . . . I might have to run independent.'' He
said he selected California over New York to run because ``New York
is just too far'' and he didn't wish to be compared to Hillary
Clinton, ``representing a state I don't know anything about.''
Coleman has worked most recently as a security agent.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
