<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: The following text accompanies the weather map for Wednesday,
May 3, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York Times News
Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The warmest spell in the Northern states so far this year will
spread from the northern Plains into most of the East in the next
few days. Meanwhile, a slow-moving disturbance will produce
recurrent heavy rain as it drifts into the lower Mississippi
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   A persistent flow of moisture from the western Gulf of Mexico
will set the stage for local flooding over parts of eastern Texas
and western Louisiana. Rainfalls up to 3 inches in a few hours will
occur in areas where weak winds aloft favor sluggish thunderstorms.
</P>
<P>
   Humid air will spread north into the Ohio Valley. Thundershowers
will move east across the region Wednesday night. After a chilly
dawn, ample sun will promote mild conditions over most of the
Northeast. Onshore breezes will keep the coast cool. In the West, a
cool front with showers will reach the northern coast.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: DECEIVING AVERAGES
</P>
<P>
   While monthly averages are an important tool for climatological
comparisons, they can mask significant weather variations. The
average temperature last month in North Platte, Neb., was only 0.2
degree below normal. But, most days were unusually warm and most
nights were uncommonly chilly. Daytime highs averaged 3.2 degrees
above normal while nights were 3.7 degrees cooler than average.
Frequent sunny days and clear nights led to many instances with
exceptionally large diurnal temperature ranges.
</P>
</TEXT>
