<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3476 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-JAZZ-MALONE-LADN &LR;      05-02 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAZZ-MALONE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOK WHO'S PLAYING
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients. Embargoed until May 5.) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
When he was 4, Russell Malone received a plastic four-string
guitar. It was a gift that put him on a career path.
</P>
<P>
   Now a well-known jazz guitarist with an elegant, blues-tinged
tone, Malone played for several years with jazz singer/pianist
Diana Krall before leaving to promote his solo albums.
</P>
<P>
   Malone recalls the years spent with the Grammy Award-winning
Krall as slightly frustrating.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started to feel like I was being typecast,'' he said.
``There's more to my playing than what was heard in that setting.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone's just-issued fifth and latest album, ``Look Who's Here''
(Verve), includes three originals along with interpretations of
tunes by Burt Bacharach/Hal David (``Alfie''), Cole Porter (``Get
Out of Town''), Stevie Wonder (``You Will Know'') and Neal Hefti's
theme from ``The Odd Couple.'' The disc was produced by Verve Music
Group Chairman Tommy LiPuma, who also oversaw Malone's
well-received previous effort, 1998's ``Sweet Georgia Peach''
(Impulse!).
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other instruments such as piano and saxophone, the
guitar's role in jazz has yet to be fully defined. While legends
like Wes Montgomery and Charlie Christian laid the ground rules,
much of the guitar's potential is still evolving in the hands of
modern-day six-string explorers like Malone, Bill Frisell and Pat
Metheny.
</P>
<P>
   Malone's straight-ahead style is steeped in jazz tradition but
also infused with a soulfulness that hints at his background in
r&AMP;b, country and pop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love jazz, but I'm not narrow,'' Malone, 36, said from his
home in New York. ``I like many different styles of music. I'm not
worried about living up to someone else's idea of the perfect jazz
guitarist or what's considered to be cutting-edge. I'm committed to
being the best musician I can be.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone started studying the guitar after seeing B.B. King
perform ``How Blue Can You Get'' on TV as he was growing up in
Georgia. That led him to discover George Benson, Montgomery and
country players like Chet Atkins and Johnny Cash, who were
influences along with the church spirituals he heard in his
childhood.
</P>
<P>
   Breaking into live performance with soul-jazz organist Jimmy
Smith in 1988, Malone joined up with Harry Connick Jr., playing
with the singer's orchestra from 1990 to 1994. Recording sessions
with Branford Marsalis, Benny Green and Roy Hargrove followed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing with Jimmy (Smith) was a great experience,'' Malone
recalled. ``That's a guy who doesn't tell you what to do on stage.
He just leaves room for you to solo. That's how I approach my own
band members.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone's new disc is his first to feature his touring band of
the past two years _ Anthony Wonsey (piano), Richie Goods (bass)
and Byron Landham (drums).
</P>
<P>
   ``I really enjoy playing with those guys,'' Malone said. ``It
makes a big difference recording with the guys you've been touring
with. You play music together, you eat together, you hang out. It
makes for a very comfortable recording experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone cut his self-titled debut album in 1992 for Columbia
while playing with Connick. His second effort, ``Black Butterfly,''
came the following year. Two years later, he released ``Wholly
Cats'' on Japan's Venus label.
</P>
<P>
   While pursuing his solo career, Malone hit the road with Krall,
playing in both duet and band settings with the popular
singer-pianist. Malone ended that gig last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing with Diana was good for me, but I also contributed a
lot to her music,'' the guitarist said.
</P>
<P>
   Malone's ``Look Who's Here'' opens with two upbeat originals:
the funky ``The Angle'' and the swinging title track which he
describes as ``a fun tune for the whole band to blow on.'' Then,
the album settles in for a gorgeous reading of ``Alfie.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone says he's loved the famous Bacharach/David movie theme
``ever since I was a kid. I love the melody and the changes are
great to play on. The song itself is so well-constructed that you
don't even need to solo on it.''
</P>
<P>
   On Hefti's ``Odd Couple,'' Malone unleashes melodic as well as
angular lines. The album's third original is ``Soulful Kisses,'' a
catchy tune that melds classic soul sensibilities with gutbucket
blues.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we play this in a live setting, we get a great
response,'' Malone says, describing the tune as ``downhome and
funky.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his personal favorite, Malone chooses Porter's ``Get Out
of Town,'' which starts with a groove that wouldn't be out of place
in a spaghetti western.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took chances with this song,'' he explained. ``We threw
caution to the wind. I stretched out and showed another side to my
playing that hasn't been heard on my own recordings.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone also covers the Wonder standard ``You Will Know'' and
ends the album with a rare vocal performance on Irving Berlin's
``Be Careful, It's My Heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone said he heard Frank Sinatra do the tune, but it wasn't
until Lorraine Gordon, owner of New York's Village Vanguard, gave
him a tape of a Cuban vocalist singing it that he considered coming
up with his own interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like going to the Vanguard and talking about tunes with
Lorraine because we both love good songs,'' Malone said. ``So I
called her one day and sang my version to her. She said, `You've
got to record that.' Now, I don't think of myself as a singer, but
I respect singers and I love lyrics and melody.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone's current disc was cut in just two days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so easy to make,'' he said. ``I like being prepared
before going into the studio. Because as a band we were so
well-oiled, we just went in and hit.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
