<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREASURIES MIXED AS INVESTORS FAVOR SHORTER-TERM MATURITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Prices of U.S. Treasury securities were mixed on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Treasuries with shorter maturities were higher as investors
moved money out of stocks, which were declining, for the favorable
return on interest-bearing instruments. The price of longer-term
Treasuries was lower, however, amid concern that the Federal
Reserve would move to raise interest rates, driving bond prices
lower.
</P>
<P>
   By late in the day, the benchmark 30-year bond was down 15/32,
to a price of 103 6/32. Its yield, which moves in the opposite
direction from the price, increased to 6.02 percent from 5.99
percent on Monday, exceeding 6 percent for the first time in six
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The mixed feelings about the Fed's next move have created some
consternation in the bond markets, said Michael P. Maurer, a
fixed-income strategist at A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons. ``Strong economic
data forced the reassessment of conventional market wisdom last
week as the consensus for the fed funds target rate became less
certain.'' He said market participants were divided between
expectations of a quarter-percentage-point increase and a steeper
rise of half a percent. Until recently, it had seemed fairly
certain that the central bank would continue its pattern of gradual
rate increases.
</P>
<P>
   Donald J. Fine, chief market analyst at Chase Asset Management,
is among those who say that many market participants expect a
half-point tightening at the May 16 meeting of the Federal
Reserve's policy-setting committee, as economic growth led by
strong consumer spending continues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fed seems poised to move aggressively in its pre-emptive
strikes against inflationary forces,'' he said. ``Simply put, the
risk of economic momentum being sharply curtailed by an aggressive
move to a less accommodative posture is considerably less at this
juncture than the risk of having an undesirable inflationary bulge
result from a somewhat sluggish monetary policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Maurer of A.G. Edwards said, ``There are several major
announcements due this week, which could shake up the markets.''
The data include the Treasury's quarterly refunding on Wednesday,
first-quarter productivity and cost figures on Thursday, and April
employment figures on Friday. Expectations are for nonfarm payrolls
to rise 350,000 and for the unemployment rate to drop to 4 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
