<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    1999 A&AMP;M BONFIRE: Key dates
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _
</P>
<P>
   Important events before and after the 1999 Aggie Bonfire
collapse.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nov. 24, 1998
</P>
<P>
   Eight senior and eight junior construction chiefs, all known as
redpots, are selected for the 1999 bonfire.
</P>
<P>
   _ Spring 1999
</P>
<P>
   Fund-raising starts for bonfire.
</P>
<P>
   _ April 1999
</P>
<P>
   Bonfire leadership training class.
</P>
<P>
   _ Aug. 30
</P>
<P>
   Contract signed for cut site.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sept. 28
</P>
<P>
   First safety class for students on how to cut down trees.
</P>
<P>
   _ Oct. 29
</P>
<P>
   Center pole arrived at bonfire site.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nov. 5
</P>
<P>
   Center pole erected; construction of the log stack begins.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nov. 11
</P>
<P>
   Push to complete the bonfire begins.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nov. 15
</P>
<P>
   Construction crane reported to have hit bonfire crossties, which
are attached to the center pole. Later, the investigation report
indicates that the impact did not contribute to the collapse.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nov. 18
</P>
<P>
   Bonfire collapses. Twelve people are killed and 27 are injured.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nov. 22
</P>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M announces five-member commission to investigate the
collapse.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nov. 25
</P>
<P>
   Date bonfire was to have burned in anticipation of the annual
A&AMP;M-University of Texas football game.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nov. 26
</P>
<P>
   Aggies win annual A&AMP;M-UT football game, 20-16.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nov. 27
</P>
<P>
   Houston construction executive Leo Linbeck Jr. named chairman of
special investigating commission.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dec. 5
</P>
<P>
   Two bonfire victims reported to have been legally drunk at the
time of the collapse; alcohol had long been a bonfire concern.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dec. 11
</P>
<P>
   Commission hires McKinsey and Co., an international management
consulting company, to assist the commission's work.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jan. 4
</P>
<P>
   The investigating commission meets for the first time and begins
hiring consulting firms to help in the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jan. 12
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M President Ray Bowen says he would resign if investigation
shows that the collapse was the product of poor administrative
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   _ April 14
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M freshman John Comstock of Richardson, is the last person to
be released from a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tuesday
</P>
<P>
   Investigation commission lists six physical factors and four
behavioral factors that contributed to the collapse. The nearly
four-month investigation, which had a $2 million budget, is
estimated to have cost $1.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
