<DOCNO> NYT20000502.0162 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3486 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-OLDNEW-HOUSE04-COX     05-02 1619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLDNEW-HOUSE04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Decorator house mirrors Atlanta's changing tastes
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, May 4.
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If you think a decorator show house is simply a place
for the have-nots to drool _ or in some cases, gasp _ take a closer
look at the Atlanta Symphony Associates' 30th rendition.
</P>
<P>
   This show house is a study in old and new: A 1930s house
updated, then expanded with 21st-century amenities. A woody estate
enhanced by outdoor rooms and young gardens. A blue-blooded
neighborhood integrated with young nouveaux riches. A designer cast
of 32 veterans mixed with rising new talent.
</P>
<P>
   The metro area's most popular show house, open now through May
21 in Buckhead's prestigious Tuxedo Park, is unique in that it
features an addition that more than doubles the home's size.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's real unusual for us to do this much of a renovation,''
said Liz Troy, event chairwoman.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, you won't find the dramatic color palette of past show
houses but an emphasis on warm neutrals, even monochromatic in some
rooms. The surprise is that the 24 rooms flow together as if
organizers planned it.
</P>
<P>
   And, perhaps reflecting Atlanta's changing tastes, there's a
greater mix of traditional and contemporary furnishings _ fine
antiques paired with funky artwork, rustic natural materials
complemented by sleek metal and glass.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, the event, which last year raised $300,000 for the
Atlanta Symphony Orchestra, is chock-full of design ideas, and many
of the furnishings and accessories are for sale.
</P>
<P>
   But as you meander through the house, don't become so consumed
by the details that you miss the Woodlands, as the owners have
named the setting. The event offers a rare opportunity to take in
one of development-crazed Buckhead's rapidly disappearing spots.
Its tranquil spring and pond nestled in a wooded valley will make
you think you're in the Georgia mountains, not in north Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Enjoy it while it's there.
</P>
<P>
   The history
</P>
<P>
   Woodlands was built in 1932 as a brick and shingle-sided New
England Colonial-style house. It was designed by Atlanta architects
Charles Frazier and Daniel Bodin for Robert Pegram, vice president
of Southern Railway System, and his wife, Susan.
</P>
<P>
   The house was later sold to Charles and Helen Jagels and finally
to Ray and Sara Moore, who developed its extensive gardens while
maintaining the pristine surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   Neighborhood residents cherished the property so much that three
years ago when it was sold to a developer and divided into three
lots, they raised the money to purchase the corner parcel. The lot
was placed in a public trust, which protects it from development.
Peter Lloyd and Gene Lashley bought the lot with the house and
began renovations. The third parcel behind it remains for sale.
</P>
<P>
   The owners
</P>
<P>
   Last year, as the Symphony Associates scouted sites for this
year's show house, Woodlands was back on the market. ``We were
looking at the house as is,'' event co-chairwoman Suzy Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Nashville transplants Robert and Jill Crowder have
agreed to buy the house but delayed moving in to allow the show to
go on.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really unusual for us to work with two sets of owners on
a show house,'' Smith said _ let alone one undergoing such
extensive renovation.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison Design Associates designed and built a new kitchen and
master suite, expanding the house from 3,500 to 8,000 square feet.
Robert Crowder, an apartment developer, and his wife, Jill, have
had input in the additions through Atlanta interior designers
Essary &AMP; Murphy, which will redecorate the house for the owners
after the event.
</P>
<P>
   The renovation
</P>
<P>
   Bill Harrison, whose Atlanta architectural firm designed the
1998 Neiman Marcus/Southern Accents Holiday House, has taken the
house from casual Cape Cod to a more formal English manor style.
Oversize handmade brown brick, a slate roof and a limestone portico
give the structure a new facade. On one side is the new master
suite; on the other is a two-story kitchen and media room.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison shifted the entrance to the right to make the design
more symmetrical. A new entry and library took the place of the old
dining room, and a stair hall and powder room now stand in the old
foyer. Though the changes allow visitors to see from one end of the
house to the other, the large number of both old and new rooms
almost creates a mazelike flow.
</P>
<P>
   Small windows were replaced with French doors, which help
brighten the dark house and blend it with the new expansive
additions and beyond. New outdoor spaces include a motor court
garden, a stacked-stone cabana and a cantilevered terrace with a
pool featuring a vanishing-edge waterfall.
</P>
<P>
   The designers
</P>
<P>
   The 32 interior and landscape designers were selected by
inviting both previous participants and new referrals to an open
house. Designers then applied to decorate a room. A review
committee looked at portfolios, and those with show house
experience were given priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want high-profile designers involved because they produce
the things people talk about,'' Smith said, citing Dilger Gibson's
moss-covered bed in 1998 as an example.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, new talent is sought to keep the event fresh.
</P>
<P>
   The only room not assigned is the kitchen, which because of the
expense of outfitting, is handled through bids between owner and
designer.
</P>
<P>
   The designers, who must submit plans to the committee for
approval, can do nothing to the walls or ceilings that can't be
undone. Floors cannot be changed or painted.
</P>
<P>
   And while participants sometimes know a little about what their
neighbor is planning, there's no coordination among the spaces.
``That's why it's really interesting how well the colors seem to
flow together from room to room this year,'' said Vicki Gillis of
Diane Johnson &AMP; Associates Interior Design, which designed the
foyer and entry hall.
</P>
<P>
   The decor
</P>
<P>
   There are two stories here _ neutral tones and a mix of
traditional and contemporary.
</P>
<P>
   Warm earth colors extend from the limestone kitchen to the
creamy master suite. Look for an emphasis on off-white, tan, taupe
and sage throughout the house.
</P>
<P>
   The master bedroom features cream-on-cream tones and softly
patterned fabrics that complement the focal point _ a wide view of
the woodlands valley. ``The owner loves creams and taupes and
neutrals, and we wanted to create a really sexy, seductive look,''
said Bill Murphy, who designed the space with Jim Essary.
</P>
<P>
   Interiors also are more eclectic than in the past. The house is
still traditional, reflecting Atlanta tastes, but furnishings and
artwork are more contemporary.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a lot of money in Atlanta being young, I think you'll see
a lot of the designs aimed at young professionals,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   In the guest suite, done in soft monochromatic taupes and golds,
Pineapple House Interior Design plays classic European antiques
against pieces with glass and steel. A contemporary painting hangs
above a 19th-century French commode. ``I think that's what makes
things interesting,'' designer Michelle Doughtie said, ``a touch of
the old with the new.''
</P>
<P>
   ENCORES
</P>
<P>
   Scenes that leave you wanting more
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Guests will never leave: The guest suite, with its sitting
area, should please any weekend company. Pineapple House Interior
Design uses a pedimented, hand-rubbed Grecian relief, salvaged from
a New Hampshire opera house, to create a dramatic bed headboard.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Can't beat clean livin': Tranquillity reigns in the sun room,
where Guyton Design Group, displaying amazing restraint, makes the
garden view the focal point. A pair of Louis XV lounge chairs, an
ottoman and a library table are the main furnishings in this
inviting space, done in tones of white with black accents. Don't
miss the ceiling, washed in a brushed sage.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Why leave your room? Designers Stanley Ellis and David Erhardt
of ellis/erhardt have combined so many warm, inviting textures in
the master sitting room you want to curl up by a fire with a good
book. The eclectic room includes an acrylic tea table as well as
polished Biedermeier pieces and velvet upholstery.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A real closet case: Imagine having a convenient place to store
your luggage, let alone open a suitcase. Closets &AMP; More and Expo
Design Center give the gentleman of the house just that in the
master closet, which contains dresser and countertops wide enough
to pack for the next business trip.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  At your (bare) feet: The things they do with tile these days
never seem to end. Check out the mosaic tile ``rug'' in the
poolside cabana, by Kelly Sparra Interior Design.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1940s macho: Clean, sleek lines and chocolate and camel
furnishings turn the upstairs study into a masculine retreat.
Designer Craig Duncan juxtaposes a pair of leather club chairs with
a wall-hung antique quilt.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Symphony Associates
</P>
<P>
   30th Annual Decorators' Showhouse
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Where: 3671 Tuxedo Road N.W.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  When: Through May 21. Hours: 10 a.m.-3:30 p.m.
Mondays-Saturdays (also 6-8 p.m. Thursdays); noon-5 p.m. Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tickets: $20.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Parking: Phipps Plaza, near the Phipps Drive/Lenox Road
(formerly known as Buckhead Loop) intersection, where free shuttles
will run to and from the house. (No parking available at the
house.)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Events: Food and Wine Experience (samples and entertaining
tips by Atlanta chefs), 6-8:30 p.m. Thursdays; Designer Lecture
Series (topics, schedule vary).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: 404-733-4935 or www.atlantasymphony
</P>
<P>
   .org.
</P>
<P>
   Danny C. Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
