<HEADER>
A3487 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-PARTY-OF-FIVE03-COX     05-02 0478
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARTY-OF-FIVE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Party of Five' ends six-year run on Fox
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ``Party's'' over.
</P>
<P>
   After tonight, the Salingers of ``Party of Five'' will never
again take arms against another crisis, furrow another brow, fall
in love or bed or both. Fox sends them off after six years in a
two-hour finale that has more thorough closure than a chastity
belt.
</P>
<P>
   Who killed ``Party of Five''? It was more or less mutual between
Fox and the fans. Ratings had evaporated this season, down a
whopping 40 percent from last. Neve Campbell was eyeing her movie
career, and Jennifer Love Hewitt, who joined in Season 2 and became
the biggest name in the cast, was spun off to her own series,
``Time of Your Life.'' (It tanked earlier this season, but will be
back in the summer.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Party'' had won its awards (Golden Globe, Humanitas), built
(and lost most of) its buzz, and it was time to move on. So move on
the Salingers do tonight.
</P>
<P>
   The show combines lots of clips from past seasons (the only time
Hewitt appears) and a regular episode. Claudia (Lacey Chabert) is
itching to go off to Juilliard. Bailey (Scott Wolf) wants to head
to business school in Pennsylvania. Julia (Campbell) has an
internship waiting with the National Organization for Women. That
leaves Charlie (Matthew Fox) stuck with raising little Owen, and
none too tickled about it.
</P>
<P>
   Can the Salingers rise above their tensions and do what's right
for the family one last time? What do you think?
</P>
<P>
   When ``Party of Five'' debuted in 1994, it attracted a small,
loyal audience that grew. Although its core was mostly young
females, some middle-aged moms found it a safe haven to watch with
their daughters, as the five Salinger kids, orphaned when their
parents were killed in a wreck, negotiated a world that teetered
between reality and ``it's only television.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Party'' probably peaked in popularity sometime in Season 3.
That was when Bailey's alcoholism became a long-running story line.
In Season 4, Charlie was diagnosed with cancer, and Internet fans
began complaining that the series had gotten too dark. Then in
Season 5, Julia not only got an abusive boyfriend, Ned, but stayed
with him far too long for some viewers' tastes. Rosie O'Donnell
took to ranting about Julia getting away from this guy, and while
there's the theory that there's no such thing as bad publicity,
there was also a feeling that ``Party of Five'' was trying the
patience of many of its fans.
</P>
<P>
   If you are, or were, a fan, don't worry about going back to
those dark places tonight. The finale doesn't throw any nasty
curves, just piles on the bittersweet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Party of Five''
</P>
<P>
   8 tonight on Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
