<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3492 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-HOLOCAUST-ART-     05-02 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-HOLOCAUST-ART-1025(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL'S MOST OBSERVANT JEWS MAKE A POINT OF NOT OBSERVING
HOLOCAUST DAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT7 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ At precisely 10 a.m. on Tuesday, air-raid sirens
sounded throughout Israel and the country froze in its tracks for
two minutes to remember the victims of the Holocaust. Drivers stood
at attention beside their cars, shopkeepers stepped onto the
sidewalk and pedestrians halted in mid-stride, their heads bowed or
defiantly upright.
</P>
<P>
   But this did not happen in Mea Shearim or other strictly
Orthodox neighborhoods. In Mea Shearim, as if the call of the siren
were a car alarm, religious Jews in black frock coats and black
felt hats did not pause, or interrupt conversations, or stop their
shopping.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where does this thing of the siren come from?'' said Shai, a
young Hasidic Jew with long strawberry-blond side curls, who would
not give his last name. ``It's someone else's custom _ the English,
the goyim,'' or non-Jews. ``What we as Jews do is recite religious
texts. And not just today, but every day. To stand silent, like
goyim, is to insult the name of those burned to death for their
beliefs.''
</P>
<P>
   A woman out shopping, dressed in a long skirt, her head covered
with a tight scarf, agreed. ``God thinks it's a goyish holiday,''
she said of Holocaust Remembrance Day, which is a somber national
holiday in Israel, when restaurants, theaters and nightclubs shut
down and schools, radio and television stations devote themselves
to Holocaust education. ``They have their customs,'' she said,
nodding toward secular Israel in general. ``We have God.''
</P>
<P>
   For many Israelis, the shunning of Holocaust Day by
ultra-Orthodox Jews rubs extra salt in the wounds of a divided
society. The haredim _ the word means those who tremble before God
_ also do not observe Israel's Independence Day or its Memorial
Day. But many Israelis consider the Day of the Shoah, as it is
known here, to be the one time when the Jews of Israel should stand
_ literally _ together.
</P>
<P>
   ``The haredim have set up parallel institutions for
everything,'' said Efraim Zuroff, a Holocaust historian, a modern
Orthodox Jew and the local director of the Simon Wiesenthal Center.
``But one would have hoped that the Holocaust would be the one
exception. What did the Holocaust teach us, if not that Jewish
unity was essential?''
</P>
<P>
   The matter is actually a complex internal Jewish dispute, not
only about the way that the Holocaust should be remembered but
about Holocaust history itself. In the haredi world, a string of
new books, films and museum projects are sketching out an
alternative to the official account of the Holocaust that is taught
in Israeli schools and featured at Yad Vashem, the national
Holocaust memorial.
</P>
<P>
   That mainstream account, by their reckoning, over-emphasizes the
physical heroism and martyrdom of nonreligious Jews who resisted
the Nazis. It glorifies the fighters, they say, just as Zionists in
Israel exalt the soldiers of the national army in which most
haredim, who believe they serve the country by keeping strictly
observed Jewish traditions alive, do not serve.
</P>
<P>
   The date for Holocaust Remembrance Day, in fact, was fixed by
Israel to commemorate the Warsaw ghetto uprising of 1943, in which
the underground Jewish Combat Organization led Polish Jews in a
four-week revolt against their deportation to Nazi concentration
camps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do we give more importance to the physical fighters?''
said Rabbi Menachem Mendel Taub, a Holocaust survivor who is known
as the rebbe of Kaliv, for the Hungarian city whose Hasidic Jewish
community he and five generations of ancestors led. ``What about
the rabbis and yeshiva students who clung to the religious
commandments until the end? Did they not defend the soul of the
Jewish people? Are they not as important to Israel today as F-16s
and A-bombs?''
</P>
<P>
   More pointedly, in a haredi weekly, Moshe Gorelick, an article
called ``Even in Israel They Deny the Holocaust'' said that the
official Holocaust Day explicitly disdains those who ``kept their
godly souls until the last minute'' as ``going like lambs to the
slaughter.''
</P>
<P>
   It is well known here that many haredim avoid Yad Vashem, which
almost every other Israeli visits regularly as schoolchild and
soldier. Most often, they cite religious objections to the nude
photographs of skeletal Holocaust victims. A deputy mayor of
Jerusalem, an ultra-Orthodox Jew, created a stir several years ago
when he threatened to cut off funds to Yad Vashem if the
``immodest'' pictures were not taken down.
</P>
<P>
   But ultra-Orthodox rabbis say that the real problem is
ideological. The museum, they say, does not sufficiently pay
tribute to ``religious martyrs,'' among them rabbis who had visas
that would have allowed them to emigrate but stayed in Europe to
lead _ and die with _ their followers.
</P>
<P>
   Taub is one who is working to append the official history. He
has published two volumes of a Holocaust encyclopedia filled with
the stories of Jews who observed Jewish law against all odds in the
ghettos and the concentration camps. And he is raising money to
build an alternative Holocaust museum in Jerusalem, for which the
cornerstone has already been laid. Another museum project, by a
separate organization, is also under way in Bnei Brak.
</P>
<P>
   After the Holocaust Remembrance ceremonies began on Monday
night, the rabbi was interviewed in Bnei Brak, a religious
community near Tel Aviv, through his personal secretary. Taub, who
is the seventh-generation rabbinical leader of Kaliv, does not take
questions from women; his secretary posed the questions. His
assistants placed a large picture frame between the rabbi and a
female reporter so that his view would be blocked. He talked to the
ceiling, alternating English from his 17 years in the United States
with Hebrew and Yiddish. At the end, he offered a blessing, both
verbally and in the form of a small plastic pouch containing a
10-agorot coin, worth a few pennies.
</P>
<P>
   ``When somebody is in jail for dozens of years, he promises to
himself that when he is released, he will do good things,'' the
rabbi said. ``Usually his good intentions fade. I promised myself
the day that I survived the Shoah, that I would think about this
day and night. What does a single day, Holocaust Day, mean?''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   To Holocaust survivors and to many of the participants in the
official ceremonies, it means a great deal. About 230,000 Israelis
once lived under Nazi rule, according to Israeli statistics
released on Tuesday, and the population of survivors is dwindling.
Some 20,000 have died since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Ehud Barak and other government officials took
part in an annual tradition on Tuesday, reading, with breaking
voices, the names of Jews killed in the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   In an editorial, a haredi newspaper, Hamodia, said
``God-fearing'' Jews still use ``these same names, in the same
books, in the same customs, and in the same tradition that the
opinion-makers in Israel would wish to put in a museum.'' Some
religious Jews believe that they themselves are recreating the
European Jewish village life that was wiped out during the
Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   Zuroff, author of a new book, ``The Response of Orthodox Jewry
in the United States to the Holocaust'' (Yeshiva University Press),
said he thinks that the haredim have a hard time dealing with
Holocaust history.
</P>
<P>
   The very fact that the Holocaust happened is difficult for them,
he said, as are some of the mistakes made by their leaders. Some
Hasidic rabbis, for instance, ordered their followers to stay in
Europe and not to flee, he said. And while some rabbis perished
with their communities, others fled themselves.
</P>
<P>
   But ultra-Orthodox leaders disagree, and, in the streets of Mea
Shearim Tuesday morning, it came down to something more basic:
Holocaust Day is a secular event, dictated by the secular
authorities of Israel. And the haredim obey what they consider to
be the higher authority of the Torah.
</P>
<P>
   Holocaust Day falls during the Hebrew month of Nissan, a month
of celebration, when strictly Orthodox Jews are barred from public
expressions of mourning. Modern Orthodox Jews believe that it is
literal-minded to think the ban should apply to Holocaust Day.
</P>
<P>
   Strictly observant Jews, however, say that Judaism marks tragic
events in the life of Jewish people on Tisha B'Av, a day of fasting
and mourning that commemorates the destruction of the First Temple
in 586 B.C. and the Second Temple in the year 70. Other Jews, they
say, have allowed the Holocaust to dominate their worldview.
</P>
<P>
   ``All Jewish history does not begin and end with the
Holocaust,'' said Jonathan Rosenblum, a haredi spokesman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-00 1750EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000502.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3494 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-GOP-PRIMARIES-HNS &LR;      05-02 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-PRIMARIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GOP PRIMARY PROPOSAL WOULD PUT SMALLER STATES AHEAD OF
CALIFORNIA, N.Y. 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Filed in ``w'' and ``p'' categories)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAN FREEDMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A Republican task force on Tuesday recommended a
four-tiered primary balloting schedule that would put small states
first, and push giants such as California and New York to the back
of the line.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP commission headed by former Sen. William Brock of
Tennessee was assembled by Republican National Committee Chairman
Jim Nicholson last July to figure what to do about
``front-loading,'' the process in which states clamor for attention
from presidential candidates by scheduling their primaries earlier
and earlier.
</P>
<P>
   This year, California and New York moved their primaries from
their historic positions late in the political calendar to March 7
_ Super Tuesday _ in an effort to get more attention from
candidates. The two states send a total of 263 delegates to the GOP
convention, nearly a quarter of the delegates needed to win the
party's presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Interest in favoring smaller states accelerated this year when
both parties' winners emerged by early March, before half the
states had held primaries or caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   To address this perceived imbalance, Brock unveiled the Delaware
Plan, named for its originator, Delaware GOP Chairman Basil
Battaglia.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, states would be grouped in four tiers
according to population. The most populous _ California, New York
and Texas among them _ would go into the fourth tier of states that
are barred from holding their primaries any earlier than the first
week of June.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller states such as Delaware, New Hampshire and North Dakota
would have the first crack, holding their primaries the first week
in March.
</P>
<P>
   The next tier would go no sooner than the first week of April.
This bloc would include states such as Arkansas, Iowa, South
Carolina and West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   The third tier would hold primaries no sooner than the first
week of May. This group includes Arizona, Missouri, Washington and
Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   The final tier of large states also includes Florida, Michigan,
Ohio and Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats last week considered a similar plan and rejected
it, according to a statement from the Democratic National
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democrats had serious reservations about the lack of diversity
in the small states that would go first'' in the Delaware Plan, DNC
Rules and Bylaws co-chairman Jim Roosevelt said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
   New York and California were reliable supporters of President
Clinton in the last two presidential elections and Democrats are
not anxious to anger the party faithful in those states.
</P>
<P>
   The Delaware Plan is to be reviewed by the GOP's rules committee
in Indianapolis next week. If approved, the entire Republican
National Committee would vote on the plan at the party's convention
in Philadelphia in August.
</P>
<P>
   The aim, Brock told a news conference here, is to restore
smaller states and their Main Street politics to their leading role
in the nominating process. Front-loading the primary schedule with
larger states turns the race into a chase for money and soundbites,
with little real debate, he added.
</P>
<P>
   This year, six GOP contenders dropped out of the race before the
first ballots were cast in Iowa and New Hampshire because of
because they could not raise enough money to compete in the big
states, where candidates must spend more on advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe there's value in retail politics,'' Brock told
reporters. Concentrating on small states early would give
candidates a chance to ``wrestle through'' the issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't need a lot of money to run in Wyoming,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   While the Brock plan groups Iowa and New Hampshire into their
appropriate population categories, it does not close the door to
their traditional standing as the first states to cast ballots.
</P>
<P>
   The plan immediately drew fire from Republicans in larger states
such as New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``For parochial reasons, we don't like the Delaware Plan,'' said
Jeffrey Buley, general counsel to the New York Republican Party.
The primary schedule should produce ``the best possible nominee
with the best chance of winning in November,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Delaware Plan, he added, ``will produce a protracted battle
(and) a broke and bloodied nominee at the convention.''
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address dan(at)hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-00 1750EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000502.0171 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3496 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-TEENS-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      05-02 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-TEENS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN ON TV, PUBERTY CAN'T LAST FOREVER 
</HEADLINE>
   By BERNARD WEINRAUB    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ For decades on television shows about teen-agers,
sex was unmentioned, divorced parents were out of the question, and
families lived in an all-white suburban world that seemed frozen in
time. The biggest issues facing television teen-agers of the '50s,
'60s and '70s seemed to be borrowing the family car or finding a
date for the prom.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the Fox shows ``Beverly Hills 90210,'' which is
reaching its television finale on May 17 after 10 years, and
``Party of Five,'' whose last episode will be seen Wednesday night
at 8.
</P>
<P>
   Though the characters on these two series could not be more
dissimilar, ``Beverly Hills 90210'' and ``Party of Five'' have
transformed the way teen-agers are depicted on television,
presenting them as far more complicated, thoughtful and sexy than
the innocent, perky and sometimes goofy young people on earlier
series like ``The Many Loves of Dobie Gillis,'' ``The Patty Duke
Show,'' ``My Three Sons'' and ``The Adventures of Ozzie and
Harriet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Beverly Hills 90210,'' the longest-running drama series on
American television and nothing less than a cultural phenomenon
abroad, enjoyed far greater success than ``Party of Five.''
``90210'' was initially about a Minnesota family, Jim and Cindy
Walsh and their twin teen-agers, Brenda (Shannon Doherty) and
Brandon (Jason Priestley), who move to opulent Beverly Hills. At
fictional West Beverly Hills High (patterned after Beverly Hills
High School and some private schools in Los Angeles) the twins
encounter a sun-bleached world of money, glamour and, even by
Southern California standards, unreasonably perfect looks and
bodies.
</P>
<P>
   The show itself was never taken seriously by critics or even
rival television executives; in fact it was scorned as shallow. In
his review of the ``90210'' premiere in The Washington Post, Tom
Shales wrote of the show's makers: ``They've created a vacuum, a
perfect void, a black hole in the already vast and empty TV
schedule. Not so much a black hole actually as a beige one.''
</P>
<P>
   But despite the obvious fantasy elements of the high school, the
series dealt, in its own glossy way, with subjects as serious as
date rape, alcoholism, suicide, AIDS and drug abuse. Thus the
series stood out from contemporaries like ``Ferris Bueller'' and
``Parker Lewis Can't Lose.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Party of Five,'' which made its debut in 1994, was about five
siblings raising themselves after the deaths of their parents at
the hands of a drunken driver.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Simon, the curator at the Museum of Television and Radio in
Manhattan, said that what was especially novel about ``90210'' and
``Party of Five'' was their focus on the teen-agers outside the
standard family context. Previous shows were characterized by major
story lines involving parents because networks and advertisers
wanted to draw on as large a demographic group as possible.
</P>
<P>
   But the splintering of the television audience, the growth of
cable and the end of the dominance of the once-powerful three major
networks led advertisers and networks to target a specific segment
of the audience: in this case, teen-agers themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past the comic struggles of the teen-agers on
television were always in the context of the family,'' said Simon.
``They didn't reflect the hidden truths and confusions of what it
meant to be a teen-ager. These shows tried to reflect that.''
</P>
<P>
   The striking success of ``90210'' fostered the creation of the
WB network, which was marketed specifically for the kinds of
teen-age audiences generated by ``90210'' and ``Party of Five.''
(Movies, on the other hand, have often dealt with teen-agers in a
more straightforward way; 45 years ago the Nicholas Ray film
``Rebel With a Cause,'' which made James Dean a star, served as one
of the earliest and most serious depictions of alienated
teen-agers.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Our show opened the way on television,'' said Chris Keyser,
who created ``Party of Five'' with his partner Amy Lippman. ``It
was really the first of its kind to specifically deal with serious
relationships among teen-agers and those in their early 20s.''
</P>
<P>
   `` `Party of Five' said to network executives and advertisers
that there's an important demographic in teen-agers, and shows
about them can be successful,'' Keyser said. ``It's fair to say
that the show, as well as a show like `My So-Called Life,' treated
teen-agers and those in their early 20s as something beyond just
soap opera.''
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Spelling, one of the executive producers of '`90210,''
whose extraordinarily successful career has been stamped by shows
like ``Charlie's Angels'' and ``Dynasty,'' said that for all the
critical abuse the show took, its success was based on several
factors: as the cast grew older and went on to college, the
audience grew older, too, and kept returning; the show never
preached or seemed strident as it dealt with serious issues in a
setting that seemed quite unserious; and it was dreamlike in its
lush surroundings and gorgeous people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intent changed,'' said Spelling. ``In the beginning it was
just to have fun with kids in high school. You know, cheerleaders
and football games and pom-poms and all that. We hung on by our
teeth.''
</P>
<P>
   (MORE)  &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   But then Fox, in an unusual move in the summer of 1991, decided
to broadcast new episodes instead of reruns. They dealt with summer
vacations and playing at the beach, which gave the young cast
members the chance to take off their clothes and stroll around in
bathing suits. The episodes turned Priestley and Luke Perry into
television stars and lured a large audience of young women to the
show.
</P>
<P>
   After that ``90201'' began tackling what were then unusual
subjects for a seemingly frivolous teen-ager series. ``We had shows
about racism, we had shows about condom use, we had a show about a
kid accidentally killed by his father's gun left in a drawer,''
said Spelling. ``We had shows about violence at school. Remember
this was years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Rosin, an executive producer of the series in its first
five years, said these breakthroughs went unnoticed by critics.
``We broke ground on many different levels,'' he said. ``Our lead
characters were sexual. In our ninth episode we dealt with AIDS.
They were computer-literate as far back as 1993. We would scour
what was going on in the culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, there was style and facade. But underneath we dealt with
a whole jangle of anxieties and insecurities back then which we
take for granted today. We took teen-agers seriously, their
melodramas and relationships and problems. Television shows back
then didn't do that, except for heavy after-school specials which
dealt with the problem of the week.''
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, ``Party of Five'' was developed as a replacement
for ``90210,'' which was then in its fourth year. Keyser and
Lippman, who had met years before in a writing class at Harvard,
said that the idea for ``Party of Five'' came from Sandy Grushow,
now chairman of the Fox Television Entertainment Group.
</P>
<P>
   Grushow, then a high-ranking Fox television executive, said he
was concerned about how long the Beverly Hills show would last. He
said he and several other executives discussed a series about
teen-age empowerment and struck on the idea of a family of
teen-agers who lost their parents in an accident. Keyser and
Lippman turned the show into one that was more serious than Fox
intended.
</P>
<P>
   `` `90210' was initially a straight-down-the middle soap opera,
whereas `Party of Five' was conceived by Chris and Amy to be a more
serious contemporary drama,'' said Grushow. ``I probably conceived
it somewhere in the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   At least at the outset the two shows would have been unthinkable
on ABC, CBS and NBC. ``The idea that any of those three networks
would do a show about teen-agers and for teen-agers was absurd,''
said Grushow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Party of Five,'' was never in the same ratings league as
``90210.'' But because it followed the Beverly Hills show on
Wednesday nights on Fox, the more somber show was buoyed by the
success of ``90210.'' Still, ``Party of Five'' was never among
television's Top 20 shows, and its situation has been dicey over
the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   Recently Fox moved the show to Tuesday nights at 9, against
NBC's ``Will and Grace'' and ABC's ``Dharma and Greg.'' Some of the
stars of ``Party of Five'' had either left or were reducing their
number of episodes. More important, most of the show's characters
were now young adults. As a result Fox decided to end the show.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the two teen-age dramas faded because their stars had
grown older, and the longevity of the two series, especially
``90210,'' may have made them a little tired. At the same time the
growth of cable networks like MTV, VHI and E! and the appeal of the
Internet have splintered the teen-age audience.
</P>
<P>
   But these shows' impact remains considerable. WB's ``Dawson's
Creek,'' ``Felicity,'' ``Popular,'' ``Angel'' and ``Roswell,'' and
even NBC's acclaimed but canceled high school comedy, ``Freaks and
Geeks,'' owe a debt to the two Fox series that took teen-agers and
their issues seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Though many of those connected with ``90210'' and ``Party of
Five'' say the series gave them a career boost, some writers and
actors said they were concerned that the shows had typecast them,
and that they were seeking to reach beyond the teen-age genre.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Wolf, one of the stars of ``Party,'' was on Broadway last
year in ``Side Man.'' He has recently worked at several repertory
theaters and is actively pursuing a film career.
</P>
<P>
   Before the series, ``I was sort of bopping around, getting work
in commercials, doing whatever I could get my hands on,'' said
Wolf, 31. ``This has radically changed my life.'' He said he was
convinced that the show succeeded because it was so different from
conventional television series about teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly Ian Ziering, a star of ``90210,'' said that no matter
how glamorous or even unreal the characters on the show seemed at
times, audiences related to the series because there was an
underpinning of seriousness.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was only a show about hair styles, it would not have
survived,'' Ziering said. ``It was a show about young people
growing up together, living with the cards that life dealt them.
And a lot of people, young and not so young, related to that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
