<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3498 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r l BC-L.A.-LOFTS-LADN &LR;      05-02 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-L.A.-LOFTS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOFTY L.A.
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below; `today' refers to Sat., May 6) 
By ANGELA LEMIRE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Toss out the notion loft-living in old industrial buildings is just
some spartan lifestyle for struggling artists in New York, Boston
or Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   It's on the rise here in Southern California and in other parts
of the country, officials say, as more professionals are trading
trees and yards of sprawling suburbia _ and long daily commutes _
for interior space to create urban live-work environments.
</P>
<P>
   The Southland boom is strongest in downtown Los Angeles _ where
today and Sunday one such community, The Brewery Art Complex, opens
its loft doors to the public for tours and an art sale. Lofts have
been thriving downtown since the mid-1980s and many communities,
including the Brewery complex, still have waiting lists.
</P>
<P>
   Now other areas like Hollywood and some industrial zones are
following suit, says Don Spivak, an urban planner with the Los
Angeles City Redevelopment Agency.
</P>
<P>
   More cities now see loft communities as both a revitalization
tool and a way to support growing arts communities, Spivak says,
noting that lofts are popular in Denver, Houston and San Francisco.
In Southern California, his research shows the trend has hit San
Diego, Santa Monica, Venice, Anaheim and Hollywood, while other
arts experts point to lofts cropping up in Santa Ana, Fullerton and
Pomona.
</P>
<P>
   City planners in Glendale and Ventura also are considering lofty
proposals to revitalize commercial or industrial zones, but are far
from final decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a modern-day trend,'' said Jim Glaser, Glendale's
assistant director of planning. ``It's not only the single-family
homes in the suburbs that are the typical model for housing
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Earlier in the century, there was a tendency to separate
zoning and business uses, but now people are beginning to rethink
that concept.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result of zoning changes passed last summer, several
projects are under way in downtown Los Angeles to convert vacant
office buildings into loft apartments. Spivak says the goal is
create more downtown pedestrian neighborhoods and consumer bases.
</P>
<P>
   And he's confident there's a market for loft-style housing in
urban centers, which have average monthly rents of $1 to $1.50 per
square foot.
</P>
<P>
   Established loft complexes in downtown Los Angeles have had
waiting lists for years, including lofts on Eighth and Spring
streets, throughout the Artists' District, which encompasses
roughly 2,500 lofts between Alameda Street and the Los Angeles
River, the Santa Fe Art Colony on Long Beach Boulevard, and the
Brewery complex at North Main Street _ named after former occupant
Pabst Blue Ribbon Beer.
</P>
<P>
   There's already a waiting list to fill all 250 lofts currently
transforming downtown's old banking district. The developer, Los
Angeles-based Gilmore Associates, is renovating vacant financial
buildings with new wiring to support modern technology in hopes of
enticing wide array of self-employed professionals.
</P>
<P>
   Brewery loft-dweller Nathan Swift _ a 30-year-old architect with
2,000 square feet of live-work space, concrete floors and a 23-foot
ceiling _ no longer commutes to work two hours daily on clogged
freeways.
</P>
<P>
   He also was able to open his own business without the extra
expense of a separate office. But unlike a suburban home office, he
has ample parking and equally business-friendly, arts-minded
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Spread over a dozen brick and concrete buildings, the Brewery's
300 units are filled with art and antique dealers, painters,
photographers, designers, musicians, welders, writers, film
technicians, performance artists, furniture makers, yoga masters
and the like.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an energy here that's hard to find in other places,
especially the suburbs,'' said Swift, who also holds gallery
openings in his loft with girlfriend and partner architect, Gloria
Lee.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a sense of community that's unparalleled in the
city,'' agreed neighbor Ted Meyer, a designer, teacher, writer and
painter whose specialties include model prints of clients' body
scars. ``I can knock on my neighbors' doors at 11 o'clock at night
and ask them what they think of a painting I'm working on.''
</P>
<P>
   Meyer added, ``It's like living in a college dorm where
everyone's room is the size of a house and everyone's 30 _ or at
least has that maturity level.''
</P>
<P>
   He's not surprised artists are now regarded as solutions to
struggling areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know artists are the only people who would move into some
place that everyone else thinks is gross and make it really nice,''
laughed Meyer.
</P>
<P>
   The City of Ventura, which has been redeveloping its downtown
and waterfront, is studying artists' proposal to revamp old oil
refinery properties on the city's blighted west side into live-work
lofts, said Rochelle Margolin, a city economic development
associate.
</P>
<P>
   And in Glendale, a task force has suggested loft living in
vacant commercial and industrial zones as one of many solutions to
encourage community arts.
</P>
<P>
   But Glaser, the Glendale city planner, predicts there will be
several tough hurdles to clear before such projects are possible,
including enacting zoning changes, securing funding and finding
developers.
</P>
<P>
   And, depending on factors such as zoning and financing
provisions, Spivak says live-work loft complexes usually restrict
tenants to artists, or target various self-employed professionals.
</P>
<P>
   Brewery resident Mat Gleason, an art magazine publisher and
gallery manager, says he generally approves of cities' efforts to
create new loft communities for artists, if the intention indeed is
to encourage the arts and not use artists for a quick-fix.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do cities want more art museums and places for arts patrons to
go, or do they just want a reliable source to come in, and fix it
up, so it's nice enough for a Starbucks to move in next year?''
Gleason asked, then added with light-hearted resignation, ``But
hey, I guess those 10 to 15 years it takes to fix it up could be
fun.''
</P>
<P>
   _____ &QL; 
What: The Brewery Spring 2000 Artwalk &QL; 
Where: Main Street at the 5 Freeway at the north edge of downtown
Los Angeles. &QL; 
When: 11 a.m.-6 p.m. today and Sunday. &QL; 
Admission and parking: Free. Call (213) 694-2911 for information.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
