u f BC-ROBERDS-LIQUIDATION05     05-02 0448
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBERDS-LIQUIDATION0503-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Great deals for shoppers in Ohio and Georgia
 &HT;    By Meredith Moss
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The bad news for shoppers is that Roberds is
closing its doors.
</P>
<P>
   The good news for shoppers is the store's going-out-of-business
sale.
</P>
<P>
   It may mean great deals on refrigerators, stoves, televisions,
beds, stereos, lamps, tables and chairs.
</P>
<P>
   Roberds has engaged a liquidator to sell the inventory of its
Ohio and Georgia stores, a sale expected ``to begin in the near
future and conclude within 90 days,'' the company said. The
liquidation firm has not been named.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Sturdavant, a liquidator for United American in Columbus,
said the point of such sales is to turn all assets into cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``A company typically checks with two or three liquidators and
then takes the best money offered,'' he said. ``They walk away free
and clear.''
</P>
<P>
   Then it's up to the liquidator to get as much as it can for the
stock. Everything down to the bare walls is sold. Often, Sturdavant
said, two liquidation firms are involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, the merchandise people do their gig,'' selling the
store's inventory, he said. ``Then the fixture people take over _
selling visuals, shelving.''
</P>
<P>
   Stock may at first be offered at 10 percent off the original
price, then be reduced further. Customers begin getting really good
deals, he says, when merchandise is marked 50 percent off.
Depending on the sale, markdowns may eventually go as low as 90
percent.
</P>
<P>
   A liquidation sale puts the responsibility on the customer, who
must haul the merchandise away. Stock is sold ``as is'' so it's
important to examine it carefully. There are no exchanges or
returns, though warranties are frequently dealt to other stores.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Lunsford of National Content Liquidators in Springboro
says the Roberds liquidation will be of national scope because of
its size. ``You're talking about millions of dollars worth of
inventory,'' he said, even though the company already has
liquidated the contents of its stores in Florida and California.
</P>
<P>
   He also explained that the liquidation firm is likely to bring
in additional inventory from other sources and keep stocking the
sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our minds, it's not a true liquidation sale, but it's a
nice deal for Roberds because they make a percentage of revenue
from what these guys bring in,'' Lunsford said.
</P>
<P>
   Sturdavant says all kinds of shoppers show up at liquidation
sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll see corporations, entrepreneurs, lots of people just
looking for a good buy,'' he said. ``It's really a hodgepodge.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
