<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TEENS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON BARS FEDERAL JOB DISCRIMINATION AGAINST PARENTS
 &HT;    360&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton issued a ban Tuesday on
employment discrimination against parents by the federal
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe it or not, there are still some employers who are
reluctant to hire or promote employees who have children at home,''
Clinton said at the White House Conference on Teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   At the day-long meeting, experts, parents and teens spent much
of their time discussing ways for busy parents to keep close
relationships with busy adolescents.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's tough to be a teenager today, it's probably tougher to
be a parent,'' said first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton. ``More and
more parents are working outside their homes (and) struggling to do
right by their families and their jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   The president said his executive order sends those who recruit,
refer, hire, promote or discharge federal employees this message:
``No glass ceiling for parents. The job they are doing at home is
more important anyway, and if they can do your job, you ought not
to stop them.''
</P>
<P>
   While he ordered the Office of Personnel Management to set
guidelines for federal agencies, he stipulated that his order sets
a goal, rather than giving anyone the right to sue the federal
government.
</P>
<P>
   His order, which doesn't require congressional approval, is
based on a much stronger bill that would give parents the right to
sue public or private employers who discriminate against them.
Congress has yet to act on the bill, which was proposed by Clinton
in January 1999 and introduced on his behalf in November by Sens.
Chris Dodd, D-Conn., and Edward Kennedy, D-Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is about eliminating bias, not about guaranteeing
accommodation,'' said Dodd, who emphasized that parents would still
have to fill any job performance requirements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thus, an employer may discipline an employee who is late
because of child-care issues,'' Dodd said. ``Similarly, an employer
may reject an applicant for a job that requires extensive travel if
that applicant is unwilling to travel because of his or her
responsibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows)
</P>
<P>
   At the teen conference, which included a three-hour discussion
led by Mrs. Clinton in the East Room of the White House, the more
than 200 participants learned of several new polls and studies
concerning teens.
</P>
<P>
   Many were intrigued by a contrast between answers of 200 parents
and of 200 children aged 12 to 15 in a poll (with a margin of error
of plus or minus seven percentage points) that was conducted in
April for the YMCA of the USA:
</P>
<P>
   _ A strong 61 percent of the parents, but only 41 percent of the
children, said they talk frequently with each other about values
and beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   _ The top concerns listed by parents about their teens were
drugs, alcohol and violence, but the top concerns listed by the
children were education and ``not having enough time together''
with parents.
</P>
<P>
   _ While 78 percent of the children said they ate eight or more
meals with at least one of their parents during a normal week, only
61 percent of the parents said they ate that many meals with their
teens.
</P>
<P>
   Another study by Clinton's Council of Economic Advisers found
that teenagers who had dinner with their parent or parents five
nights a week were more likely than other teens to avoid smoking,
drinking, violence, suicide and drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The council reported that it couldn't tell whether sharing
family meals helps teens avoid risk, or whether risk-taking teens
avoid family meals.
</P>
<P>
   The emotional and physical health of children is affected not so
much by the amount of time parents spend with their teenagers as by
the teens' perceptions of the warmth and closeness of their
relationship with their parents, according to research cited by
Robert Blum, an adolescent health researcher at the University of
Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Galinsky, president and co-founder of the Families and
Work Institute, said that in her surveys of the children of working
parents, ``Kids said they wish their parents were less stressed and
less tired.''
</P>
<P>
   But, in her surveys of employers, she found, ``Unfortunately,
only 12 percent are doing something specifically to help the
parents of teenagers.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: New federal site for teens, www.americasteens.gov;
White House, www.whitehouse.gov.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Mollison's e-mail address is andym(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
