<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-TURNER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUTH D. TURNER, 85; WAS EXPERT ON SHIPWORMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ruth Dixon Turner, a professor at Harvard University and curator
of malacology at the school's Museum of Comparative Zoology known
affecionately as ``Lady Wormwood'' for her wide knowledge of
shipworms, died Sunday in Meadow Green Nursing Home in Waltham. She
was 85.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Turner was a leading expert on teredos, bivalve mollusks
sometimes called shipworms that cause widespread destruction by
eating wood in ocean environments. Teredos led to the loss of all
of Christopher Columbus's ships on his fourth voyage to the New
World and are the reason why there was so little wood left on the
wreck of the sunken ocean liner Titanic when it was located by
Robert Ballard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The impact of these borers on the history of man is difficult
to estimate,'' Miss Turner said in a story published in the Globe
on Nov. 16, 1961, ``but it has certainly been tremendous.''
</P>
<P>
   She said accounts of the early voyagers such as Cooke and Drake
made it clear that they dreaded shipworms as much as the they did
scurvy.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Turner speculated that many of the explorers who had set
sail and were never heard from again may have gone down because of
shipworms.
</P>
<P>
   Sailors weren't the only ones threatened by the worms. In 1730,
they riddled the wooden-faced dykes in the Netherlands with holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows,'' Miss Turner said in 1961. ``Maybe the legendary
little Dutch boy who saved the dyke by plugging a hole with his
finger was actually stopping up a seaworm hole.''
</P>
<P>
   During her 50-year career, Miss Turner worked closely with the
UN Food and Agriculture Organization and the Navy's Office of
Oceanography, which funded much of her research.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to participating in expeditions throughout the
world, she maintained a laboratory in Puerto Rico and also did
research at Northeastern University's marine laboratory in Nahant,
Mass. and the marine biological laboratory at Woods Hole, Mass.,
where she used the Deep Submergence Research Vehicle to study the
sea.
</P>
<P>
   She was born in Melrose, Mass. and graduated from Bridgewater
(Mass.) Teachers College. She earned a master's degree at Cornell
University and a doctorate at Radcliffe College.
</P>
<P>
   She leaves two sisters, Winifred Garrity of Sudbury, Mass. and
Lina MacNeill of Wayland, Mass.
</P>
</TEXT>
