<HEADER>
A3527 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-MISSILE-DEFENSE-HNS &LR;      05-02 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSILE-DEFENSE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RUSSIAN SAYS MISSILE SYSTEM COULD IGNITE NEW `COLD WAR' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Three Russian lawmakers warned Congress Tuesday
that if the White House follows through on plans to build a
national missile defense system, the U.S.-Russia relationship would
be severely undermined.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Shabanov, deputy chairman of the Duma's foreign
relations committee, said the missile defense program could spark
``another Cold War,'' and he warned of ``very dangerous''
repercussions. The Duma is Russia's lower house of parliament.
</P>
<P>
   He said that if the United States deploys such a system _ which
Russia views as a threat to its nuclear deterrent _ Moscow might
not feel bound by top-priority defense arrangements, such as a
joint effort to stem the flow of nuclear weapons and missile
technologies to nations that Washington considers international
pariahs.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a joint gathering of Russian and U.S. lawmakers on
Capitol Hill, Shabanov added that a national missile defense system
would further isolate Russia from the United States and Europe,
forcing Moscow to form alliances with countries unfriendly to the
Americans and Europeans. ``Leaving Russia on its own is very
dangerous,'' he said through an interpreter.
</P>
<P>
   Konstantin Kosachev, also a deputy chairman of the Duma's
foreign relations committee, said Moscow is angered that the United
States is moving ahead on missile defense ``unilaterally without
taking into account the Russian position.''
</P>
<P>
   Kosachev said that Washington has backed Moscow into a corner,
forcing Russia either to agree to changes in the 1972
Anti-Ballistic Missile treaty to allow for the deployment of such a
defense system or threatening to abrogate the treaty altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Kosachev said that the fast pace of proposed changes to such a
fundamental arms control treaty was unnecessary. ``We shouldn't
hurry on this matter,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The stated reason behind the U.S. push to deploy national
missile defense is the alleged threat posed by North Korea, which
U.S. intelligence asserts is developing a long-range missile
capable of striking U.S. territories.
</P>
<P>
   But Vladimir Ryzhkov, a Duma member, challenged U.S.
intelligence estimates. He said the threat from North Korea ``is
highly exaggerated.'' Shabanov added that Russia has determined
that North Korea lacks the economic wherewithal to develop a
long-range missile.
</P>
<P>
   R. James Woolsey, former director of the Central Intelligence
Agency, countered Russian assessments of the North Korean threat.
The Russians have ``bum dope and are badly in need of accurate and
complete information,'' he said, adding that North Korea has
achieved many technical milestones in its missile program.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at the same conference, Sen. John Kyl, R-Ariz., said it
was certain that the United States would eventually deploy a
missile defense system, despite Russian objections. ``There will be
a deployment of NMD by the United States,'' Kyl said.
</P>
<P>
   The missile system is supported by the White House and both Vice
President Al Gore, the likely Democratic presidential nominee, and
Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the presumptive Republican nominee.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton is scheduled to make a decision about whether
to deploy the national missile defense system no earlier than this
fall. The United States and Russia have entered preliminary
discussions about renegotiating the 1972 missile treaty, and
Clinton is scheduled to travel to Moscow next month to meet with
Russian President Vladimir Putin to discuss the topic.
</P>
<P>
   But Moscow objects to amending the ABM Treaty because it is
viewed as a stabilizing force between two giant nuclear arsenals.
Russia's view is that by prohibiting national missile defenses,
each side is ensured that it could destroy the other, thus
deterring the other from launching a first strike.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials have stressed that national missile defense would
be ``limited,'' aimed at defeating a dozen or so missiles launched
from countries such as North Korea or Iran and that it in no way
could defeat Russia's nuclear arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow, however, is concerned that the proposed U.S. missile
defense system would soon be enlarged where it could defeat
Russia's missiles, thus disrupting the strategic balance between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
   The technology for such a missile system still has not been
perfected. The results so far have been mixed with another key
missile test scheduled for next month. The system could be
completed by 2015.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Rosenberg can be reached at 202-298-6920 and by e-mail at
eric(at)hearstdc.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
