<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Wednesday, May 3 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-PRIMARIES (Washington) _ A Republican group has proposed
a primary system that would end front loading, perhaps decreasing
the importance of early money in the presidential nominating
system. The Democrats are wary, but have plenty of time to respond.
By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   With photo NYT15 and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S.-TRADE (New York) _ President Clinton and his national
security adviser warned Tuesday that failure to extend new trading
rights to China would be a self-inflicted wound, compromising
America's global leadership as it undermined Chinese reformers. In
sometimes dire language that seemed to reflect the administration's
nervousness about prospects for congressional approval of the China
trade measure, Clinton said that even beyond economic benefits, the
legislation is important to American national security. By Joseph
Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   DISNEY-TIMEWARNER (New York) _ Time Warner restored ABC's signal
shortly before 3:30 p.m. EDT on seven stations after agreeing to an
extension of its current agreement with Disney through mid-July.
Time Warner had originally sought an eight-month extension. The
change came after the Federal Communications Commission gave
indications that it would rule in favor of Disney's request to
force Time Warner to restore the signal until after the sweeps
ended. By Bill Carter.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-REENTRY (Tokyo) _ For returning Japanese who have spent
time abroad, re-entry into Japanese society is painful and
sometimes nearly impossible. They find themselves isolated, shunned
and confused about how to fit into a society that seems to be
becoming more insular, rather than more open, as it struggles to
deal with a declining population and a shrinking world. By Howard
W. French.
</P>
<P>
   WOOING-STUDENTS (Undated) _ The period from April 1 to May 1 is
a time unlike any other in the college admissions season, when
roles reverse. The students become the admissions officers,
screening potential candidates against a yardstick of their own
idiosyncrasies. And the officers are reduced to mere applicants,
trying to put their schools in the best light _ they routinely ply
top candidates with free plane tickets and fawning letters from
professors _ while bracing for rejections from hundreds of
desirable students, who will ultimately choose to attend college
elsewhere. By Jacques Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT18.
</P>
<P>
   VEEP-SELECTION (Dateline to kum, Calif.) _ A look at strategies
in the selection of a vice president. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
