<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRIER SPENDS TIME WITH PATRIOTS OWNER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Deposed vice president of player personnel
Bobby Grier had a final meeting with Patriots owner Robert Kraft at
Foxboro Stadium Tuesday, presumably to get a handshake and perhaps
a severance package.
</P>
<P>
   There was no word on whether Kraft offered Grier a job within
the organization, as the Red Sox did when Lou Gorman was replaced
by Dan Duquette.
</P>
<P>
   Grier, 57, isn't ready to retire, but the timing of his
departure will make it very difficult to hook on elsewhere for the
2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   The timing, in fact, raises the question that if Belichick and
the Krafts didn't care for Grier's draft selections, why did they
put off firing him until after the draft?
</P>
<P>
   Rainbow Sports, a watchdog group that promotes diversity in
professional sports, watched closely the firing of Grier, an
African-American, as it did the firing of Ray Rhodes as Green Bay
coach this year. It asked for and received a satisfactory
explanation from the Packers, who fired Rhodes after one 8-8
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Belichick has every right to hire and fire as the new
head coach of the New England Patriots,'' said Charles Farrell,
director of Rainbow Sports. ``All that we're concerned about is
hoping that Mr. Belichick will consider an African-American, a
Latino, a woman as a replacement for the position. All we ask for
is equal footing.''
</P>
<P>
   Farrell said Grier's firing ``took us by surprise. He is a
well-respected football executive with 18 years of experience.
That's rare for an African-American in the sports business. Our
hope is that Mr. Grier will land on his feet in another position in
the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   Farrell said his group will look into the Grier firing but in no
way was he suggesting that it was racially motivated.
</P>
<P>
   ``As positions open up, we remind teams to embrace diversity and
emphasize that diversity is good for everyone in business,'' said
Farrell.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick is looking around for more of his loyalists to round
out the personnel staff. With Scott Pioli the main assistant in
charge of pro personnel, look for Belichick to hire a director of
college scouting or someone with expertise in that area.
</P>
<P>
   A number of scouts and executives with the Jets and Ravens have
ties to Belichick and may find their way here. Among them are Jets
scouts Lionel Vital, who worked with Pioli in Baltimore and then
with Pioli and Belichick in New York, and Trent Baalke. Hingham's
Terry McDonough, an assistant with the Ravens, is another, as is
Phil Savage, the Ravens' director of college scouting, though he
recently signed a new deal.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick certainly has not been shy about cleaning house; the
only question is where will he stop. Several employees of the team
are wondering who's next.
</P>
</TEXT>
