   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LOCKERBIE-TRIAL (Zeist, Netherlands) -- Two Libyan men charged
with killing 270 people go on trial more than 11 years after Pan Am
Flight 103 was blown out of the sky over Lockerbie, Scotland. By
Kevin Cullen. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-VIETNAM (Halifax, N.S.) _ Canada breaks off diplomatic
relations with Hanoi after the execution Saturday of a
Canadian-Vietnamese woman, a former boat person, on drug charges.
By Colin Nickerson. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   NATO-CLARK (Stuttgart, Germany) _ Gen. Wesley K. Clark hands
over US military command in Europe, and is to turn over NATO
supreme command and go on what the Pentagon calls ``termination
leave'' in the United States. By John Donnelly. 750 words. (i and a
coding)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (w) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PRIMARIES-NH (Washington) _ New Hampshire's position as the
first-primary state could be endangered under a GOP plan that
deletes a guarantee that the state would go first and instead sent
the matter to the party's Rules Committee and national convention.
By Michael Kranish. (w and a coding)
</P>
<P>
   TEENS-CLINTONS (Washington) _ First White House conference on
teens, presided over by President Clinton and Hillary Rodham
Clinton, features time-tested advice, plus research showing early
teen years are a crucial step in brain development. By Mary
Leonard. 1100 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS (p) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GORE-CRIME (Atlanta)_ Al Gore outlines his anti-crime program,
which calls for spending $500 million a year _ with the states
matching the money _ to fight drugs in prisons. By Susan Milligan.
900 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-CONSERVATIVE (New York) _ As if Mayor Giuliani didn't have
enough reasons to second guess his senate race, the conservative
party has decided to proceed without him, nominating an
anti-abortion conservative who can be expected to paste Giuliani as
much as Hillary Clinton. By Fred Kaplan. 700 words.
</P>
<P>
   MA-ANTIBIOTICS (Boston) _ Massachusetts health officials are
trying to take a hard line with doctors who they say routinely
overprescribe antibiotics, contributing to the global problem of
drug resistance. By Richard Saltus. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ATT-REVAMP (Undated) _ AT&AMP;T's stock plunges as the company
issues its first profit warning under chief executive C. Michael
Armstrong, fueling worries about whether his radical remake of the
nation's largest long-distance company will succeed. By Peter Howe.
900 words.
</P>
<P>
   BIOGEN-MULLEN (Undated) _ James C. Mullen, named president of
Biogen after James Tobin left over apparent disagreements with
chairman Jim Vincent, will now become chief executive officer of
the biotechnology company. By Ronald Rosenberg. 500 words.
</P>
<P>
   MEN-FAMILIES (Undated) _ While most polls have portrayed
American men as more concerned about power, prestige and money than
their families, new findings by the Radcliffe Public Policy Center
indicate younger men are more likely to put family matters first.
By Diane E. Lewis. 700 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FBN-PATRIOTS (Foxborough, Mass.) -- Deposed vice president of
player personnel Bobby Grier has a final meeting with Patriots
owner Robert Kraft at Foxboro Stadium, presumably to get a
handshake and perhaps a severance package. By Nick Cafardo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
