<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3538 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-GOP-PRIMARY-1STLD-WRI     05-02 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-PRIMARY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GOP PRIMARY PROPOSAL WOULD PUT SMALLER STATES AHEAD OF
CALIFORNIA, N.Y. 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (ATTN: Examiner; adds quote from Calif. GOP)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAN FREEDMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A Republican task force on Tuesday recommended a
four-tiered primary balloting schedule that would put small states
first, and push giants such as California and New York to the back
of the line.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP commission headed by former Sen. William Brock of
Tennessee was assembled by Republican National Committee Chairman
Jim Nicholson last July to figure what to do about
``front-loading,'' the process in which states clamor for attention
from presidential candidates by scheduling their primaries earlier
and earlier.
</P>
<P>
   This year, California and New York moved their primaries from
their historic positions late in the political calendar to March 7
_ Super Tuesday _ in an effort to get more attention from
candidates. The two states send a total of 263 delegates to the GOP
convention, nearly a quarter of the delegates needed to win the
party's presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Interest in favoring smaller states accelerated this year when
both parties' winners emerged by early March, before half the
states had held primaries or caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   To address this perceived imbalance, Brock unveiled the Delaware
Plan, named for its originator, Delaware GOP Chairman Basil
Battaglia.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, states would be grouped in four tiers
according to population. The most populous _ California, New York
and Texas among them _ would go into the fourth tier of states that
are barred from holding their primaries any earlier than the first
week of June.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller states such as Delaware, New Hampshire and North Dakota
would have the first crack, holding their primaries the first week
in March.
</P>
<P>
   The next tier would go no sooner than the first week of April.
This bloc would include states such as Arkansas, Iowa, South
Carolina and West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   The third tier would hold primaries no sooner than the first
week of May. This group includes Arizona, Missouri, Washington and
Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   The final tier of large states also includes Florida, Michigan,
Ohio and Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats last week considered a similar plan and rejected
it, according to a statement from the Democratic National
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democrats had serious reservations about the lack of diversity
in the small states that would go first'' in the Delaware Plan, DNC
Rules and Bylaws co-chairman Jim Roosevelt said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
   New York and California were reliable supporters of President
Clinton in the last two presidential elections and Democrats are
not anxious to anger the party faithful in those states.
</P>
<P>
   The Delaware Plan is to be reviewed by the GOP's rules committee
in Indianapolis next week. If approved, the entire Republican
National Committee would vote on the plan at the party's convention
in Philadelphia in August.
</P>
<P>
   The aim, Brock told a news conference here, is to restore
smaller states and their Main Street politics to their leading role
in the nominating process. Front-loading the primary schedule with
larger states turns the race into a chase for money and soundbites,
with little real debate, he added.
</P>
<P>
   This year, six GOP contenders dropped out of the race before the
first ballots were cast in Iowa and New Hampshire because of
because they could not raise enough money to compete in the big
states, where candidates must spend more on advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe there's value in retail politics,'' Brock told
reporters. Concentrating on small states early would give
candidates a chance to ``wrestle through'' the issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't need a lot of money to run in Wyoming,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   While the Brock plan groups Iowa and New Hampshire into their
appropriate population categories, it does not close the door to
their traditional standing as the first states to cast ballots.
</P>
<P>
   The plan immediately drew fire from Republicans in larger
states.
</P>
<P>
   California's March 7 primary this year was ``the first time for
many of us that our vote counted in the presidential selection
process,'' said Stuart DeVeaux, spokesman for the California
Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   The plan ``definitely would be a situation that would not excite
Republicans in California,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For parochial reasons, we don't like the Delaware Plan,'' said
Jeffrey Buley, general counsel to the New York Republican Party.
The primary schedule should produce ``the best possible nominee
with the best chance of winning in November,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Delaware Plan, he added, ``will produce a protracted battle
(and) a broke and bloodied nominee at the convention.''
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address dan(at)hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
