<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-ROADTRIP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOM GREEN, TALKING DOG WILL HAVE YOU TRIPPING
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Breckin Meyer, the star of this summer's designated keg-party
movie ``Road Trip,'' has never actually taken a road trip himself,
which he admits is pretty pathetic. Then again, if the road trips
he was to take turned out anything like the one in the movie, he'd
be better off locking his doors and staying at home.
</P>
<P>
   The gross-out comedy ``Road Trip'' has Meyer and some buddies
driving from Ithaca, N.Y., to Austin, Texas, to retrieve a
videotape that Meyer's college friend accidentally sent to his
long-distance girlfriend. The tape features proof of a night of
drunken infidelity, hence the urgency to recover it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The movie's got everything a summer movie needs,'' Meyer says.
``Sperm banks, tainted french toast, infidelities, naked girls _
emphasis on the naked girls _ and a talking dog. Oh, and Tom Green
eats a mouse.''
</P>
<P>
   Green, MTV's resident guerilla freak, plays Meyer's roommate.
Director Todd Phillips says Green's tribulations with the mouse are
among the movie's funniest moments, but he also wants people to
know that his comedy isn't entirely geared toward adolescent (in
body and/or spirit) males.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women seem to like it, too,'' Phillips says. ``I mean, it
treats women in an interesting way, showing that the girl has a lot
of power in most situations. The women here are very proactive, and
they win in the end. I think it shows that it's OK for women to be
sexually aggressive and make the first move.''
</P>
<P>
   Hmmm, proactive, sexually aggressive women. Isn't that every
adolescent male's fantasy, particularly if the emphasis is, as
Meyer says it is, on them being naked?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I guess it is,'' Phillips admits. ``Did I mention we
have a talking dog?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-00 1831EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
