<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-IRENE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S DOUBLE TROUBLE: BROTHERS TAKE RISK FOR KILLER COMEDY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every new Farrelly brothers movie has its defining moment, a
scene that has the filmmaking duo wondering if this time they've
taken their brand of wacky humor just a little too far.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our comedy is pretty risky,'' says Bobby Farrelly, who writes
and directs with brother Peter. ``I mean, that hair gel scene in
'There's Something About Mary' could have ended Cameron Diaz's
career.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't, of course. And chances are their new movie, ``Me,
Myself and Irene,'' won't do anything to dim Jim Carrey's star
power. In fact, after his two rather somber turns in ``The Truman
Show'' and ``Man on the Moon,'' ``Irene'' promises audiences the
goofy Carrey they came to know and love in movies like the
Farrellys' early hit, ``Dumb and Dumber.''
</P>
<P>
   Here, Carrey plays split personalities, and they're both in love
with the same woman, Irene (Rene Zellweger). Coincidentally (or
perhaps not so much so), Carrey and Zellweger fell in love during
the making of the film.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not ``Irene's'' defining moment. What is? We'd best
let Bobby explain:
</P>
<P>
   ``Early on, Jim's wife runs off with an African-American little
person, leaving him with her three illegitimate sons. The story
starts when they're born and continues through high school. We had
no idea if it was going to fly, but it turns out to be the funniest
part of the movie. It really gives the story some heart. Really.''
</P>
<P>
   History bears him out. Now we'll just have to see if the
brothers' latest effort holds together and, um, jells.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-00 1832EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
