<DOCNO> NYT20000502.0202 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3553 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-MOVIE-ROCKYBULL-LADN &LR;      05-02 0271
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-ROCKYBULL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEY ROCKY, WATCH ME PULL A MOVIE OUT OF MY HAT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The world has changed a great deal since we last saw those Cold
War cartoon heroes Rocky and Bullwinkle, and it would be pretty
easy to dismiss the goofy moose and his diminutive squirrel pal as
passe. But that old-hat perception is precisely one of the reasons
acclaimed theatrical director Des McAnuff thought it'd be fun to
revisit the animated icons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've parachuted them into the present day and given them full
room to ply their smart-aleck brand of humor,'' McAnuff says. ``One
thing it does is show you just how much our world has changed and
how cynical we've become about things.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Adventures of Rocky and Bullwinkle'' pits the animated
heroes against their traditional flesh-and-blood counterparts.
Jason Alexander and Rene Russo play spies Boris and Natasha, and
Robert De Niro plays the fiendish Fearless Leader. These days, the
Leader is a media mogul with designs on world domination.
</P>
<P>
   De Niro may seem like an unlikely candidate for this material,
but apparently he was so happy with the screenplay by his ``Analyze
This'' collaborator Kenneth Lonergan that he signed on to produce
the movie as well. He even pokes fun at his ``Taxi Driver'' persona
with a ``You talkin' to me?'' routine.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a good sport about that,'' McAnuff says. ``I hesitated
to even suggest the idea, but I think he's at a point in his career
where he really enjoys this kind of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Fearless, indeed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
