 PERSONALS: Standing on the Corners Watching  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A mural incorporating a  &UR; Lawrence Ferlinghetti &LR;  poem, painted by
graffiti artists two years ago on the outside of the Black Cat, a
restaurant at Kearny and Broadway in San Francisco, was painted
over last week. Poetry fans who contacted Personals are upset by
what they see as the loss of ``an unpublished original poem by our
poet laureate'' in the restaurant's attempt to ``attract the
Financial District lunch crowd,'' but the poet himself is unfazed
and the Black Cat's owner,  &UR; Reed Hearon &LR; , has an explanation.
</P>
<P>
   Ferlinghetti, who wrote the untitled poem in exchange for free
meals, says he's not upset because his words were barely legible on
the wall. He hopes, however, that Hearon reinstates the poem on his
menu, where it used to be printed.
</P>
<P>
   Hearon says the work will be honored in a more profound medium
than the menu, when a permanent tile version is installed in about
six weeks. Hearon had the mural removed, he said, because police
told him about an Alcoholic Beverage Control Department ruling that
requires bar owners to remove graffiti; and because the
mural-bearing wall had ``turned into a graffiti magnet.''
</P>
<P>
   Charges that he is trying to attract a Montgomery Street crowd
are unfounded, he said. ``Most of the people I've seen from the
Financial District are visiting other establishments on Broadway
during the day.''
</P>
<P>
   _ A historic marker unveiled about a year ago at Webster Street
and Atlantic Avenue in Alameda, Calif., near the confluence of
Walgreens, Starbucks and Kinko's, notes that it was ``Donated by
Browman Development to the Housing Authority of the City of
Alameda.''
</P>
<P>
   The plaque marks the ``Site of the former Rosefield Packing Co.,
incorporated on August 24, 1926.  &UR; Joseph Rosefield &LR;  was the
inventor of hydrogenated peanut butter. Before this process was
developed, peanut butter would separate and quickly spoil. Mr.
Rosefield received a patent for his process in 1923 and three more
patents as he improved the process over the next seven years. Under
Mr. Rosefield's guidance, his packing company in Alameda became the
largest peanut butter manufacturer in the nation, with up to 90
employees working three eight-hour shifts, seven days a week. The
product was sold under the name of Skippy Peanut Butter. Tours of
the facility were enjoyed by generations of Alameda schoolchildren.
The Alameda plant closed in 1974. The Skippy brand continues to be
popular today.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; FLASH &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Donna Hanover &LR; , wife of New York Mayor  &UR; Rudolph Giuliani &LR; ,
has announced that she's postponing her appearance in ``The Vagina
Monologues'' ``due to personal family circumstances.'' Giuliani
announced last week that he has prostate cancer. Reader
 &UR; Steve Blasberg &LR;  notes, for the record, that Hanover, who was born
 &UR; Donna Kofnovec &LR; , is a graduate of Fremont High School in Sunnyvale
and Stanford University.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Camilla Parker Bowles &LR;  has not been invited to a June 21
party at Windsor Castle to celebrate the 100th birthday of the
 &UR; Queen Mother &LR; , and her boyfriend,  &UR; Prince Charles &LR; , is ``resigned
and disappointed,'' said the Daily Mail.
</P>
<P>
   _ When raindrops started falling on the large unsheltered crowd
at Foreign Cinema on Monday night, in the middle of an outdoor
screening of the new movie ``Luminarias,'' faces turned to the sky,
hands were extended palms up, rustling was heard ... but the movie
continued and no one left. The credits included a thank you to Our
Lady of Guadalupe, who must have had a hand in stopping the rain
after a few minutes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; WHAT THEY'RE READING IN ACADEMIA &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The publisher of  &UR; Ward Connerly &LR; 's anti-affirmative action
memoir, ``Creating Equal'' (Encounter; $24.95), is crowing about
the amazon.com notation that the book is ``popular in: University
of California: Office of the President,'' specifically, No. 9 on
the office of the president's best-seller list. Scurrying right to
that list, Personals found:
</P>
<P>
   The top three books were Harry Potters. No. 4 is ``Dr. Atkins'
New Diet Revolution''; No. 5, possibly a backlash to No. 4, is
``Julia and Jacques Cooking at Home.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``People are mostly attracted to the familiar and comfortable in
life. ... We are less and less tolerant of challenge. I'm concerned
that nobody thinks.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Richard Chamberlain &LR; , who opened Tuesday in San Francisco in
``The Sound of Music.'' Chamberlain was not, apparently, discussing
the show; he was discussing his paintings, which are on exhibit at
the Hanson Gallery in San Francisco in conjunction with the show.
</P>
