<DOCNO> NYT20000502.0211 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3565 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CLINTON-LABELLA-HNS &LR;      05-02 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LABELLA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LABELLA SAYS CLINTON SHOULD BE INVESTIGATED IN 5 AREAS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The former Justice Department prosecutor who
investigated possible campaign finance violations told Congress
Tuesday that Attorney General Janet Reno should have appointed a
special prosecutor to probe ``five areas'' related to President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Labella, who headed the Justice Department's campaign
finance task force from September 1997 to July 1998 when he left to
take over as interim U.S. attorney in San Diego, declined to go
into the ``nuts and bolts'' of his still-confidential 1998 memo to
Reno.
</P>
<P>
   The memo summarized his recommendations after his investigation
into possible illegal campaign fund raising in the 1996
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   LaBella, who testified under subpoena before a panel of the
Senate Judiciary Committee, said disclosing the contents of the
memo would ``cause a chill among every Justice Department attorney
who would fear their internal debates which they rely on'' would
become public.
</P>
<P>
   Although he refused to discuss specific details of his memo,
LaBella did reveal at least one of the five areas during
questioning from Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., who read the memo
Monday night after the Justice Department turned over the document.
</P>
<P>
   While LaBella did not specifically talk about the area, he
confirmed that passages from the memo read by Specter were
accurate.
</P>
<P>
   Quoting from the memo, Specter said that LaBella had sought an
investigation of the president and the head of Loral Corp. because
of $1.5 million in donations by the business executive to the
Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Loral later obtained a waiver from the Clinton administration
allowing the company to do satellite business with China.
</P>
<P>
   Specter also revealed parts of the memo referring to Vice
President Al Gore. The senator said LaBella wrote that ``the vice
president may have given false statements'' to Justice Department
prosecutors and FBI agents when he denied knowing that some of the
money he was raising from his office was put in ``hard money''
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   It's illegal to use government offices or phones to raise money
for specific political campaigns, money referred to as ``hard
money.'' In contrast, ``soft money'' refers to contributions made
to political parties for general issue advertising or so-called
``party building'' activities.
</P>
<P>
   Specter asked LaBella whether he remembered writing in his memo
that Gore's answers on the ``hard money'' accounts were
``reminiscent of the lack of recollection of the Buddhist temple
matter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like a phrase I used,'' LaBella answered.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has said that he didn't know that an event he attended at a
Buddhist temple in Hacienda Heights, California was a fund-raiser,
saying initially that he thought it was an act of community
outreach.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the more than $100,000 in donations from the temple
event were illicit contributions from people who were reimbursed
for their donations by the temple, which is barred from making
political contributions because it is a tax-exempt religious
institution. In the memo, LaBella reportedly accused top Justice
Department officials of using ``intellectually dishonest'' double
standards by endorsing independent counsels to investigate
Cabinet-level officials _ while opposing the appointment of
Clinton, Gore, first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton and former White
House aide Harold Ickes.
</P>
<P>
   Ickes is a top adviser to Mrs. Clinton's Senate campaign in New
York. Reno, while avoiding comment on specific charges in the memo,
has downplayed LaBella's strong language and his questioning of the
motives of her top aides.
</P>
<P>
   During his Tuesday testimony, LaBella said Ickes was involved in
a number of the areas that he investigated. ``He touched on a lot
of investigations,'' LaBella said.
</P>
<P>
   Reno's refusal to appoint an independent counsel for campaign
fund-raising has drawn intense fire from Republicans who charge she
is covering for the administration.
</P>
<P>
   But LaBella defended the attorney general, saying: ``She made no
decision to protect anyone. She listened to the advice of other
people and took that advice.''
</P>
<P>
   However, LaBella acknowledged that he and Reno never had a
``detailed'' discussion of his memo and that his relationship with
the department is ``quite cool.''
</P>
<P>
   LaBella resigned from the Justice Department in 1999 after
Clinton nominated another candidate for the regular San Diego post.
He is now senior managing director of Decision Strategies/Fairfax
International, an investigative and consulting firm in Fairfax, Va.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-00 1852EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
