<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3572 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-BANKRUPTCY-REFORM-HNS     05-02 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKRUPTCY-REFORM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LIBERAL DEMOCRATS SAY BANKRUPTCY REFORM GOES TOO FAR 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AUSTIN ZALKIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Four liberal Democratic lawmakers joined labor and
consumer advocates Tuesday to denounce a bankruptcy reform bill
they say excessively punishes debtors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The debate has been unfairly slanted towards the credit card
companies and the banks at the expense of vulnerable Americans,''
said Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass. ``This Congress should (not pass
a bill that comes) at the expense of large numbers of citizens who
the bankruptcy laws are supposed to help, not hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Russell Feingold, D-Wis., called the legislation ``an
anti-consumer bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of bankruptcy reform say the current law makes it too
easy for debtors to escape their obligations, even if they are able
to repay some of what they owe.
</P>
<P>
   To make it more difficult for a debtor to declare bankruptcy,
the House passed a bill that would require a debtor to pay some
debts if the debtor's income after important living expenses
totaled more than $1,200 a year over five years. A Senate bill
would set the threshold at $2,000 a year. Both bills are pending in
a Senate-House conference committee.
</P>
<P>
   Liberal critics of the bills say the changes go too far.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jerrold Nadler, D-N.Y., said people hit with large medical
bills from catastrophic illness should not be held responsible for
the costs they incur.
</P>
<P>
   ``A middle class family suddenly hit by half a million dollars
in medical bills didn't deliberately undertake debt except in
(saying yes to) the heart transplant,'' he said. Nadler asked
rhetorically, ``That's voluntarily undertaking debt?''
</P>
<P>
   A study by Harvard University law professor Elizabeth Warren
indicated that one-third of all personal bankruptcies filed last
year were related to substantial medical costs of the filer or a
family member.
</P>
<P>
   ``People under certain circumstances should have the opportunity
for a fresh start,'' Nadler said. ``They shouldn't be burdened with
impossible debt for the rest of their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers who oppose the bill also found fault with
provisions that would allow creditors to dip into debtors' pensions
and would strip tenants who declare bankruptcy of the right to stay
in their homes even if they are behind on rent. Currently, all
pension plans are untouchable to creditors.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bankruptcy bill has the potential to be one of the great
injustices of the 106th Congress,'' Wellstone said.
</P>
<P>
   He claimed a ``small victory'' when he announced that other
senators he had spoken with were willing to remove what he termed
the ``pension grab.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers also envisioned poor people being thrown out on
the street because their landlords would be allowed to evict them
easier under the bankruptcy bill's rules.
</P>
<P>
   Wellstone said the provision ``takes away from the tenant the
right not to be summarily evicted'' when they declare bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Wellstone and the other lawmakers charged that bill supporters
were favoring large lending institutions over the public. Wellstone
said he works in ``a Senate of, by and for credit card companies.''
</P>
<P>
   House Republican leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, told reporters that
passing a bankruptcy bill is ``a high priority for this Congress
and for me.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Austin Zalkin can be reached at 202-298-6920 or
dart(at)hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-00 1858EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000502.0216 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3573 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-EDUCATE-BOS     05-02 0466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-EDUCATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOCUS ON SCHOOLCHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   US senators have a choice. As the Capitol Hill debate on public
education turns serious Wednesday, senators can try to make
political points or they can do something to help the nation's
schoolchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Oddsmakers aren't hopeful. In a presidential election year,
partisanship is the easy path. So Republicans are likely to insist
stubbornly on block-grant proposals that shift too much discretion
to the states and encourage high-risk voucher programs, while
Democrats, if their more sensible programmatic proposals don't
prevail, are threatening to muddy the bill with gun-control
amendments.
</P>
<P>
   The better course would be cooperation on specific steps,
tightly focused on classroom improvements that have already shown
promise.
</P>
<P>
   Senators would do well to remember that the Elementary and
Secondary Education Act was originally passed in 1965 specifically
to supply help to districts where students were receiving poor
educations because their states had let them down. What progress
there has been in closing the gap between poor districts and
wealthier communities is largely attributable to federal aid.
</P>
<P>
   When the law was last reauthorized in 1994, Congress took a
crucial step by requiring states to set high standards for all
students, eliminating longstanding disparities in many states under
which less was expected of poor children, so they were taught less.
</P>
<P>
   The bill before the Senate would take a step backward with its
block grant approach. This would not, as advertised, give local
districts, parents, and teachers more control. It would merely
shift direction from Washington to the states, which have proven
themselves notoriously variable.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the proposals to be advanced by Democrats  &UR; today &LR;  are
far more promising, focusing on hiring new, well-trained teachers,
repairing school buildings, and supporting after-school programs.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, however, Senator Edward M. Kennedy is threatening
to offer an amendment that would restrict gun purchases at gun
shows. Kennedy is understandably frustrated that this provision,
which passed the Senate last year, has been stuck in a conference
committee that hasn't met for eight months. Still, it has no
business in the education bill, which should be fought on its
merits.
</P>
<P>
   Political infighting would be the easy course for both parties.
But the irony is that a strictly partisan debate, while clearly
betraying the educational needs of a generation, might not produce
political advantage either. Voters hate gridlock.
</P>
<P>
   If the Senate can do the hard work of bipartisan compromise, it
will regain a measure of public respect and help the nation's
future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
