<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-DISNEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTLE OF MEDIA GIANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Time Warner and Disney are locked in a serious tussle over the
costs of cable programming and access. This clash of the media
titans is viewed by many as competition on a grand scale. But it
could just as well be a grand conspiracy. There's nothing like a
celebrity ruckus to attract attention, and everyone knows that in
show business, publicity is the name of the game (just spell the
name right!)
</P>
<P>
   The battle is nasty enough to inspire a legion of Hollywood
scriptwriters. Disney, the parent of the ABC television network,
wants Time Warner to include its channels in the basic package the
cable giant offers to its subscribers. But Time Warner says Disney
charges too much for its popular programming. No deal, no place on
Time Warner's cable network, and 3.5 million households around the
country were blacked out Monday night, looking at nothing but an
eerie, dare we say Orwellian, message from Time Warner: ``Disney
has taken ABC away from you.''
</P>
<P>
   Late Tuesday ABC was back on again, and negotiations had been
extended until July. So millions of Americans will be able to see
Saturday's Kentucky Derby after all. And the latest quiz craze,
``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire,'' won't be zapped. But viewers
already know who wants to be a zillionaire.
</P>
<P>
   The game of corporate chicken left consumers either belligerent
or bemused, depending on how much they wanted to watch people vie
for big bucks for remembering which letter comes between A and C.
But there is a more serious portent to all the media
conglomeration, especially as Time Warner looks to merge yet again
with America Online, the Internet provider.
</P>
<P>
   We have already seen how a cable giant is capable of blocking
access to programming in an economic dispute. The aggregation of
vast power in a limited number of hands also aggregates control.
What is to prevent some media mammoth from keeping unfavorable
content _ an expose of one of its subsidiaries, for example _ off
the air?
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission ought to step in soon with
some ground rules. Otherwise, consumers will be like the victims in
the old fable: When the elephants fight, only the grass gets
trampled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
