<HEADLINE>
RACE A RAW NERVE IN US, PROFESSOR TELLS PRESS GROUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Calling the issue of race ``America's rawest nerve,''
Cornel West says the nation will not heal its racial wounds without
a fuller examination of the ``dark side'' of its history.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a deep legacy of white supremacy,'' said West, a
professor of Afro-American studies at Harvard. ``And it's a history
that's often held at arm's length.''
</P>
<P>
   West was on a panel of Harvard officials Tuesday that included
Anthony Appiah, an Afro-American studies professor; William Julius
Wilson, the Lewis P. and Linda L. Geyser university professor ; and
Henry Louis Gates Jr., chairman of the Afro-American studies
department, as the International Press Institute's World Congress
moved to the Harvard campus.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the hundreds of IPI journalists visiting Boston
attended seminars on international diplomacy and the changing media
universe. Tuesday, the discussion shifted to two of this nation's
hot-button social issues _ race and gender.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Gilligan _ who is Harvard's Patricia Albjerg Graham
Professor of Gender Studies and moderated the second panel _ echoed
West when she suggested that society had failed to come to grips
with the reality of changing gender roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're in the midst of a remarkable social and cultural
transformation on the subject of gender,'' she said. ``And I think
it's one of the least talked about subjects.''
</P>
<P>
   The unifying theme of Gilligan's panel was the matter had moved
well past traditional calls for equality of the sexes. The idea is
``not simply to repopulate the heirarchy, but to rethink the
heirarchy itself,'' said panlist Lani Guinier, the first black
woman to become a tenured Harvard Law professor.
</P>
<P>
   To prove that point, Guinier _ best known as President Clinton's
unsuccessful nominee to head the Justice Department's civil rights
division _ recounted how the height requirement for the New York
City Police Department had been modified because it discrimated
against women. More important than the new standard, she said, was
that female officers were able to patrol dangerous housing projects
by non-traditional means, proactively reaching out to potential
trouble makers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point here, is to think about the women's approach to
conflict resoultion as perhaps a functional way for all police
officers to think about dissipating conflict,'' Guinier said.
</P>
<P>
   Panelist Swanee Hunt, director of Harvard's Women and Public
Policy Program, discussed the ``Women Waging Peace'' initiative,
which hopes to use grass-roots women's groups to forestall or
ameliorate local armed conflicts by capitalizing on their ``ability
to connect and organize at a very personal level.''
</P>
<P>
   While Guinier and Hunt talked about the struggle to incorporate
women's voices into society, West lamented a ``pigmentocratic''
society unable to confront its racist past. ``It's very difficult
for the American empire of the 21st century to look closely,
candidly, critically, at its dark side,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks, Wilson traced racial tensions to two decades of
economic decline and federal retreat from American cities. The
solution, he said, may rest with ``metropolitanism,'' the idea that
cities and suburbs are ``economically interdependent'' and vital to
each other's survival.
</P>
<P>
   ``The future of metro regions in the United States, as a well as
the social inclusion of its residents, ... may well depend on the
success in eliminating the urban-suburban divide,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
