<DOCNO> NYT20000502.0220 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3579 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-SANTA-BARBARA-ART-2TA     05-02 1378
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SANTA-BARBARA-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUSH WINE FROM A PACIFIC BREEZE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(Eds: See also TASTINGS, a list of recommended wines.) By ERIC
ASIMOV   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOMPOC, Calif. _ The Santa Ynez Valley stretches west through
central Santa Barbara County, reaching toward this small city and
the Pacific Ocean beyond. It's a land of relaxed beauty, where
narrow roads curl through the knobby, windswept Santa Rita Hills,
through rows of walnut trees and strawberry fields, past acres of
cabbage and broccoli and, here and there, a few sparse vineyards.
It's certainly not Burgundy, where grapevines are planted to the
edge of the highway, or Napa Valley, where the wineries are as
densely packed as a suburb of split-levels, but make no mistake:
This is wine country.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few years, the Santa Barbara wine region has grown
astonishingly. Since 1997, the amount of land planted with grapes
has shot up to more than 18,000 acres, from about 10,000, and the
number of wineries in the county has almost doubled in the last
decade, to about 50. Most of that acreage was planted by big
wineries like Beringer, Robert Mondavi and Kendall-Jackson, which,
recognizing the quality of Santa Barbara grapes and the relative
affordability of the land, bought up huge tracts in the Los Alamos
Valley and the Santa Maria Valley to the north.
</P>
<P>
   But the true measure of excitement here is focused a little
farther south, on the western Santa Ynez Valley, where smaller
parcels of land, ranging from just a couple of acres to a few
hundred, have been planted with pinot noir and chardonnay grapes.
Growers expect these Burgundian varietals to flourish in the cool
climate that is moistened by fogs blowing in almost daily off the
Pacific Ocean, and the first wines, made from vines planted three
years ago, show excellent potential. The chardonnays are almost
crisp with citrus flavors, while the pinot noirs, flamboyant in
their youth, should achieve elegance as the vines mature.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to see some brilliant wines coming out of Santa
Barbara,'' said Alan Phillips, the winemaker and general manager of
both Foley Estate and LinCourt Vineyards, which have planted about
250 acres, mostly of chardonnay and pinot noir, on undulating
slopes facing south and west. ``The cool climate wines are
absolutely stunning.''
</P>
<P>
   Equally exciting are the passionate young winemakers like Steve
Beckmen, 31, of Beckmen Vineyards and Andrew Murray, 28, of Andrew
Murray Vineyards, who have seized on Rhone varietals, particularly
syrah, and have planted new hillside vineyards in the warmer
central part of the valley.
</P>
<P>
   The best Santa Barbara syrahs are rich and complex wines,
layered with nuances as in the northern Rhone Valley of France,
syrah's home territory, rather than lightly likable, as so many
California syrahs have been.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started making syrah, I think there were four other
people in the state who were doing it,'' said Bob Lindquist of
Qupe, who made his first syrah for Zaca Mesa in 1982 and who saw
the potential for Rhone grapes early on in the Santa Ynez Valley.
``Now, I think there are 25 syrah makers in Santa Barbara County
alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Santa Barbara is not the only booming region in California. San
Luis Obispo County, the Monterey Bay region and Sonoma County have
all experienced similar rapid development. But this sleepy county
about 100 miles north of Los Angeles may be the most unlikely
California region to be joining the top echelon of wine producers.
It's far better known for the relaxed city of Santa Barbara, for
its beautiful hills that have offered refuge to the likes of Ronald
Reagan and Michael Jackson and for its 18th-century adobe missions.
The missions were the first in the county to make wine, a sweet and
sturdy beverage that no doubt had its secular as well as its
sacramental uses. Wine was made in the county right up through
Prohibition but seemed to die out after World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Not until the late 1960s and early '70s, well after the
California wine industry began to take off, did Santa Barbara again
try its hand at grape growing and winemaking. Pioneers like
Firestone Vineyards, Zaca Mesa and Sanford &AMP; Benedict arrived, with
little idea of what grapes to plant and where.
</P>
<P>
   Many early arrivals planted cabernet sauvignon in areas ill
suited for the grape, producing weedy, vegetal wines. Others
planted chenin blanc and riesling, noble grapes that have never
achieved much popularity in California. But some got it right
almost immediately. The 130-acre Sanford &AMP; Benedict vineyard, the
first planted in the western part of the Santa Ynez, has been a
superior source of pinot noir and chardonnay grapes for 25 years,
while the 900-acre Bien Nacido vineyard, first planted 30 years
ago, graces the labels of many of the county's finest bottles.
</P>
<P>
   By the mid-'80s, acclaimed wineries like Au Bon Climat, Qupe,
Babcock Vineyards and Sanford Winery were firmly established, soon
to be joined by others like Foxen Vineyard, the Lane Tanner Winery
and Fess Parker Winery and Vineyard. Big organizations like
Beringer had begun to make inroads, but the winemakers were largely
a small, close-knit community, many of whom had learned their craft
together, and the county reflected their irreverence.
</P>
<P>
   By most accounts, Jim Clendinen of Au Bon Climat, an
iconoclastic winemaker who wore long, shaggy hair after it had been
stylish and a goatee before goatees came back, worked feverishly to
draw attention to Santa Barbara wines, traveling the world to tout
their quality. In Santa Barbara County, he and Lindquist of Qupe
had a cooperative agreement to share production facilities at the
Bien Nacido vineyard, an arrangement that has set a collegial
standard for the county.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim Clendinen has been huge, as far as his ambassadorial role
in bringing attention to the area and paving the way for others to
follow, and to illustrate what the potential of Santa Barbara
County could be,'' said Greg Brewer, 31, of Brewer-Clifton, one of
the county's hottest winemakers today. ``In the late '80s and early
'90s, he was a larger-than-life figure here.''
</P>
<P>
   Though they had eked out a reputation for seductive, elegant
pinot noirs and ripe yet nicely acidic chardonnays as well as a
scattering of good syrahs, Santa Barbara wines were still largely a
footnote in California.
</P>
<P>
   But that made Santa Barbara all the more attractive to wealthy
wine lovers in Southern California, who saw greater opportunities
to make an immediate mark in the wine industry nearby, rather than
in Northern California, where they would be greeted with yawns, if
they were noticed at all. That and the fact that prime Santa Ynez
vineyard sites are a relative bargain, under $20,000 an acre,
compared with $35,000 to $45,000 an acre in the Carneros district
of Napa Valley, by one winemaker's estimate.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Melville, who owns a securities firm in Los Angeles,
actually bought land in Napa Valley before settling on several
hundred acres in the Santa Rita Hills, where he built Melville
Vineyards and Winery. He hired Brewer to oversee his operations.
Melville will release its first bottles, from the 1999 vintage,
later this year. The families of both Beckmen and Murray moved up
from Los Angeles, choosing Santa Barbara over Northern California
to build wineries. Fess Parker, the Hollywood actor who played Davy
Crockett and Daniel Boone in the '50s and '60s, opted for elbow
room and wide open spaces in Santa Barbara County in the late '80s,
over densely populated Northern California.
</P>
<P>
   Like many in the county, Parker points to great untapped
potential in the region, and with recent purchases in both the
western Santa Rita Hills and the central Santa Ynez, he is doing
his best to tap it. He owns hotels in Santa Barbara and in Los
Olivos, a quiet town of cafes, galleries and wine-tasting rooms,
where Parker is trying to develop a world-class restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goals here are not modest,'' he said. ``I want this to be
the French Laundry of Santa Barbara County. Napa Valley wasn't any
fun until the restaurants came in.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Parker's winery, a sprawling ranch-style building with a
rambling veranda, is on Foxen Canyon Road, a winding country lane
of stunning vistas of hills and valleys, sprawling coastal oak
trees and wild flowers, with hawks and vultures drifting overhead.
While most of the small wineries on this route that links the Santa
Ynez Valley with the Santa Maria Valley welcome visitors, Parker's
is one of the few equipped to handle big groups, complete with a
large tasting room, a gift shop where you can buy wines, local
foods and of course, coonskin caps.
</P>
<P>
   Such an operation sends cold chills through many in the county,
who see wineries as harbingers of the kind of large-scale
development they detest.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Traffic jams are unknown in Santa Ynez, short of the tourists
who slow to gawk at the twirling windmills in the town of Solvang,
where the main draw is not wineries but a quaint and kitschy
Scandinavian theme with plenty of clogs and shoppes.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   ``This is kind of where Napa was 25 years ago,'' said Gary Burk,
a marketing and production executive with Au Bon Climat and Qupe,
who incidentally makes very good pinot noirs and chardonnays under
his own label, Costa de Oro. ``Are we going to stay a little
country place that makes wines, or are there going to be wine
trains and bed-and-breakfasts all up and down Foxen Canyon Road? I
don't know if everybody wants that. Some people will welcome that,
I think especially the newer people. The older people prefer making
wines in a more casual environment.''
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to slow development, the county has put up numerous
regulatory hurdles _ ``the madness,'' Phillips, the Foley
winemaker, calls it. Well-financed concerns like Foley Estate can
battle their way through the obstacles, but some smaller winemakers
are opting out.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer-Clifton, which makes minute quantities of pinot noir and
chardonnay from purchased grapes, is moving its winemaking
operation to a warehouse in the city of Lompoc, which is within the
county lines but is not bound by its rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lompoc is a funny town that's screaming for business,'' Brewer
said. ``Santa Barbara County is very resistant to more wineries
going in. There are all kinds of regulations, permits and delays.
It's a long, arduous process.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Though the regulatory tensions are bound to continue (the latest
debate was over a rare salamander that received an emergency
listing as an endangered species, grinding several winery projects
to a halt), one thing the wineries seem to be figuring out is to
how to use the climate for the maximum advantage of each particular
grape.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   The Santa Ynez Valley is blessed with long growing seasons with
plenty of sunshine, offset by natural, fog-induced maritime
air-conditioning, a product of the east-west valleys that are a
peculiar feature of the jutting coastline below Santa Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a unique combination,'' said Lindquist of Qupe. ``We're
far enough south so that we don't get hit by the rains that come
down from the northwest, and yet because the coastline is turned
around we have this tremendous cooling effect. The soils are
important, but not nearly as important as the climate.''
</P>
<P>
   That moderate climate, Murray of Andrew Murray Vineyards said,
is what gives the Rhone varietals such potential in the central
Santa Ynez. ``Too warm and you might get a more insipid-style
syrah,'' he said. ``Too cool and it might be too lean. Somewhere
right in the middle, you get your darkest, richest wines,
full-bodied but still elegant.''
</P>
<P>
   Other places in California make good syrahs, too, Murray
admitted, but he believes that the long Santa Barbara growing
season is a definite advantage. ``We were picking syrah at the end
of November,'' he said. ``That's when you can really eke out not
only those fruit flavors, but those flavors of earth and spices and
violets, the real pretty side of syrah, which you find often in the
syrahs of this area.''
</P>
<P>
   The California wine boom has sent the demand for grapes soaring,
forcing many winemakers to seek new supplies or to grow their own.
Chris Whitcraft, who has been buying grapes to make small
quantities of pinot noir and chardonnay since 1985, had to get his
pinot noir from Sonoma County in 1999. When the demand exceeds the
supply, the small winemakers are the first to lose out, one of the
reasons that Beckmen of Beckmen Vineyards feels more secure with
his own supply of grapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, having 80 acres of syrah, I get calls every day
asking if I have syrah grapes available to sell,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some fear that the expansion can be too rapid, and that a fall
will be inevitable. ``Will there be a home for all these grapes,
especially if the economy takes a dip?'' Lindquist asked. ``Both
'98 and '99 were small crop years. But in '97, there were more
grapes than we could handle. A lot of winemakers have short
memories.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as the wines themselves are concerned, a Santa Barbara
signature has been elusive. The future looks very good for syrahs,
which can be spicy, nuanced and elegant. Some optimistic winemakers
even expect that the eastern end of the Santa Ynez, the warmest
part of the valley, will one day produce good Bordeaux varietals
like cabernet sauvignon and merlot, grapes that have failed
miserably in other parts of the valley.
</P>
<P>
   But most people agree that the county's greatest successes have
been its richly textured, sweet pinot noirs and its chardonnays,
some of which resemble Chablis in their blend of citrus and mineral
flavors.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For some like Brewer, who can sound almost mystical discussing
how Brewer-Clifton wines reflect the soil from which the vines
emerge, this is a noble challenge. Others like Richard Dore, an
owner of Foxen Vineyards, seem to say, slow down and catch your
breath.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been doing this for 30 years, and we're just figuring
out where to plant stuff, let alone how to make it,'' Dore said.
``In Burgundy they've had 3,000 years to get it right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-00 1903EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
