<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-REENTRY-820(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPANESE WHO HAVE LIVED ABROAD FIND TROUBLE FITTING IN BACK HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ When Ayako Shima first returned to Japan after spending
her secondary school years in South America, she found herself
reveling in a newfound power to make decisions and express
opinions, abilities that set her apart in classrooms where no one
ever seemed to volunteer to speak.
</P>
<P>
   But as fellow students began to shun her and it became harder to
make friends, she, like many other Japanese who have lived long
stretches outside their country, gradually began to perceive that
the sense of freedom that had become second nature abroad could be
a major handicap back home.
</P>
<P>
   Before long, Shima, who is a 21-year-old college student in
Tokyo, was biting her tongue instead of speaking out, masking the
fact that she spoke two foreign languages fluently and making her
speech vague with the maybes, perhapses and other hedging
expressions that pepper conversational Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is frustrating not to state my feelings, but people here
call you bossy and get angry at you when you do,'' Shima said. ``In
Japan I've discovered that you always have to express yourself in a
very careful way.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Japanese started to live in the West and travel there
in large numbers in the 1970s, people have been predicting dramatic
changes for one of the world's most insular societies. But in a
country already famous for keeping foreigners at arm's length,
returning Japanese say that the taint of other cultures is often
enough for them to be regarded as somehow no longer fully Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   This phenomenon, experienced by many Japanese expatriates, is
perhaps the most dramatic measure of the challenge this nearly
ethnically homogeneous nation faces as it struggles to come to
terms with the pressures of globalization.
</P>
<P>
   In a reaction that is being called the ``U-turn phenomenon'' by
sociologists, Japanese who are frustrated by their reception back
home and are no longer willing to put up with the society's many
strictures are often going back overseas as fast as possible.
</P>
<P>
   The problems they encounter, many say, go far beyond the simple
use of language, encompassing the whole range of human relations,
from the stressful rhythms of daily life and workplace politics to
a mechanical educational system and affairs of the heart.
</P>
<P>
   Strikingly, many overseas Japanese say that the adjustment
required to fit back into their society is often more traumatic
than the adaptations required in moving abroad.
</P>
<P>
   School-age returnees, for example, say they are often taunted as
``gaijin,'' a mildly derogatory word for foreigner, by their
schoolmates. Many young people also say they feel saddened and
empty by the emotional reserve that is the norm here: eye contact
is rare in Japan, hugging and touching are far less common than in
Western cultures, and simple gestures like smiling or holding the
door for strangers are almost unheard of.
</P>
<P>
   Companies hiring new recruits often frown on Japanese with
foreign high school or college educations as insufficiently
socialized into the ways of Japan, which place an emphasis on
outright acceptance of directives from above and preserving group
harmony.
</P>
<P>
   And even managers sent overseas by their own companies are
routinely assigned to back-office jobs until their superiors can be
sure that their foreign ways have dissipated.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first returned, after eight years in the United States,
my boss would tell me flatly that America had spoiled me, and kept
me in a position where I would have really limited contact with
customers,'' said Toyokazu Matsumoto, 51, a manager with a major
Japanese corporation.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a meeting in Japan you are not supposed to react to things
quickly,'' Matsumoto said. ``I still find it difficult not to show
some reaction.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of experiences like these, many returning adults,
including Matsumoto, are opting to send their children to
international schools in Japan, where they can escape the heavy
rote learning that prevails in Japanese schools and maintain their
individuality without being made to feel like oddities.
</P>
<P>
   With its population dwindling more rapidly than any other
industrialized country, Japan has recently begun to debate the
extent to which it will need to attract workers from other
countries to work in this country. The experiences of expatriate
Japanese suggest, however, that even before it comes to terms with
new immigrants, this country will first have to learn how to better
accommodate its own citizens who have lived abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kind of assimilation pressure here is very strong,'' said
Kazuhiro Ebuchi, a professor of cultural anthropology at the
University of the Air, in Tokyo. ``Even people who speak good
English are teased here because Japanese should speak English in
the Japanese way. Japanese people like to say that we appreciate
cultural differences, but this is only lip service. In fact, there
is not much place for difference here.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   According to official statistics, the number of Japanese
studying overseas increased nearly tenfold over 15 years, to
186,827 in 1999. From 1988 to 1998, the number of Japanese
officially working overseas increased from 80,000 to 298,000.
</P>
<P>
   Recent opinion polls here have shown that by a substantial
margin, Japanese expatriates are happier overseas than they are
back home. This is particularly true for women, and especially so
for those who have lived in Western countries.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the factors cited in these polls are obvious, such as
the more spacious homes and lower cost of living that are typical
in the West. But the polls have also revealed more subtle reasons.
Some cited, for example, the habit of people in Japan to identify
themselves strongly with groups, such as their company or school,
instead of the individualism practiced elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Females often cite the lower status of women in Japan than in
many other developed countries.
</P>
<P>
   When Makiko Okada, who is 48, returned from the United States in
the early 1960s, people like her were so unusual that she was
turned away by public schools. ``It was very traumatic, because
there were no other returnees around me,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The sheer volume of Japanese living overseas has reduced the
oddity factor considerably since then, but in many ways Okada, who
is now the director of a program for returning students at
International Christian University High School in Tokyo, says the
adjustments she has felt compelled to make as an adult are even
more frustrating.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was always uncomfortable with the groupism in Japan, but as
I have matured, I find what bothers me most is the nonegalitarian
ways of this society,'' she said. ``Japan is a much more male
oriented society than the United States, although I think that is
changing a bit. Still, as a female, I constantly have to tone down
my views when I give an opinion, and work very hard not to
intimidate my peers.''
</P>
<P>
   Other women told of having to remember not to smile too freely
around men in the workplace, lest they take it as a sexual advance,
or relearning the habit of keeping their voices in the high, dulcet
tones still commonly adopted by working women.
</P>
<P>
   Chihiro Shiono, a 22-year-old law student at Tokyo University,
spent much of her childhood in England, Wales and Malaysia,
returning home for brief stints before her family moved overseas
again. Even from an early age, she said, the intense social
pressures to conform grated her.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a little girl I was teased a lot at school,'' she said.
``People called me a boy because in England I had learned to sit on
the floor with my legs crossed.''
</P>
<P>
   To ease her adjustment when she returned to Japan briefly for
secondary school, Shiono's parents deliberately selected a school
where returnees were common. But even there, when she spoke to
another returnee in English in one of her first days at the school,
she was bluntly warned by the girl that to do so placed her at risk
of becoming an outcast.
</P>
<P>
   ``That really frightened me,'' Shiono said. ``I never spoke
English like that again.''
</P>
<P>
   As she grew older, Shiono became more at ease with her
international identity, but the chafing sensation of her
separateness never completely faded. In junior high school, girls
teased her cruelly for having boys for friends, as was common in
England, but rare for that age in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   She also felt odd in subjects like literature, where students
were expected to recite the teacher's interpretations of whatever
was being read rather than expressing their own views. Later,
entering college, she felt uncomfortable during the near compulsory
college rounds of bottoms-up beer drinking, known as icki-icki.
</P>
<P>
   For Shiono, like for many other returnees, the impact of
experiences like these has often made her itch to return to a life
overseas. ``I don't want to remain in Japan for the rest of my
life. I came back to Japan to understand Japanese values, but I
want to return overseas sometime soon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
