<HEADLINE>
MULLEN NEW BIOGEN CHIEF EXECUTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The line of Jims continues in the chief executive officer's
suite at Biogen Corp.
</P>
<P>
   James ``Jim'' Mullen was named the company's CEO Tuesday. Mullen
became the Cambridge, Mass. company's president 17 months ago after
the abrupt departure of James ``Jim'' Tobin.
</P>
<P>
   Mullen's promotion, which will take effect at Biogen's annual
meeting on June 16, was announced by Jim Vincent, the company's
long-time chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Mullen, 41, raised Biogen's international profile by registering
and launching the company's multiple sclerosis treatment Avonex in
Europe. He was vice president of international operations when
Tobin was president and CEO.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin's surprise decision to leave Biogen in December 1998, over
uneasiness that Vincent was second-guessing his decisions, led to
Mullen replacing him as president and chief operating officer.
Vincent, who was chairman when Tobin left, returned temporarily as
chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   Vincent, 60, will remain Biogen's chairman when he relinquishes
the chief executive's role next month. He said he has known Mullen
for 11 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite frankly, I would have made him president when I started
the search for a president six years ago,'' Vincent said. ``But he
just needed more management experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Vincent, who ran Biogen from 1985 to 1997 when Tobin took over,
is credited with turning a troubled company into one of the
nation's most successful biotech firms.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin, who is now president and chief executive of Boston
Scientific Corp. in Natick, Mass., said Mullen is ``one of the best
young managers and I am glad he is getting the recognition.''
</P>
<P>
   Mullen said he has a solid relationship with Vincent.
</P>
<P>
   ``When questions and problems arise, we talk them over and kick
ideas around,'' Mullen said. ``In the nearly year and a half since
Jim (Tobin) left, we have reorganized the management team, expanded
the pipeline and moved a lot of (Avonex) product. Biogen is
becoming a global marketing company''
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts applauded Mullen's promotion. They said
Biogen remains one of the nation's most solid biotech companies,
dominating the multiple sclerosis drug market with Avonex, which
last year had sales of $621 million.
</P>
<P>
   But the company also stumbled last fall when it stopped six
clinical trials that used Antova, one of its most promising
experimental drugs, after some patients suffered blood clots.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been doing intensive research over the last six months
to learn what happened,'' said Mullen.
</P>
<P>
   Biogen's shares closed at $58.9375, up 75 cents in Nasdaq
trading.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
