</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOCERBIE-TRIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER 11-YEAR WAIT, FAMILIES SEE LOCKERBIE TRIAL BEGIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZEIST, Netherlands _ The trial of two Lybians charged with
planting the bomb that brought down Pan Am Flight 103 opens
Wednesday at a site so out of the way that Jim Swire bought a
second-hand bicycle for $35 in order to save on cab fare.
</P>
<P>
   Swire, a courtly British physician who is one of the leaders of
the families of Pan Am 103's victims, figures it was money well
spent, since he will be monitoring the sessions at the isolated
former US airbase for what could be a year or more.
</P>
<P>
   After waiting more than 11 years for the trial take place,
neither Swire nor most of the other families of the 270 victims are
complaining about the remote setting. But many of the relatives of
the victims are reserving judgment on whether justice will be
served by the trial, which is being held here under Scottish law as
the result of an elaborate compromise between Libya and the British
and American governments.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Swire's daughter Flora, those on board the
London-to-New York flight when it was blown out of the sky over
Lockerbie, Scotland, were 189 Americans _ including many college
students heading home for the Christmas break _ 44 Britons, and
passengers from 20 other countries. In addition, 11 residents of
Lockerbie were killed by the debris that rained down on the
Scottish countryside the night of Dec. 21, 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Swire has abandoned his practice in England to monitor the trial
and taken a year's lease on an apartment in this sleepy town 32
miles southeast of Amsterdam. Some newfound Dutch friends painted
and decorated it for him.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the American families whom Swire has befriended plan to
attend the proceedings more occasionally. Dozens of Americans,
including Jack and Kathleen Flynn of Montville, N.J, whose son John
was killed, have come over for the trial's opening. Swire, the
Flynns, and the other relatives are antsy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just want to get on with it,'' said Swire.
</P>
<P>
   A 100-acre section of Camp Zeist has been legally declared
Scottish soil for the duration of the trial, and nearly $20 million
has been spent converting it into a high-security, high-tech
criminal justice center.
</P>
<P>
   The two suspects _ Abelbasset Ali Al Megrahi, 48, and Al Amin
Khalifa Fhimah, 44 _ are held in a specially-built jailhouse that
has four-foot-thick walls that can withstand bombs and tank fire.
They are guarded by a contingent of 200 Scottish police and prison
officers.
</P>
<P>
   When prosecutors call the first of more than 1,000 witnesses,
the Lybians will walk to the court room through an underground
tunnel and sit behind bullet-proof glass.
</P>
<P>
   A huge gynmasium has been converted into a media center to house
the hundreds of journalists from more than 200 news organizations
who have descended on the area.
</P>
<P>
   It took Herculean judicial and political maneuvering to get this
far. The two suspects were indicted more than eight years ago. They
insisted they were innocent, and Libyan leader Moammar Khadafy
refused to turn them over to western authorities, accusing the
Americans, in particular, of being on a witchhunt.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, in an attempt to break the impasse, the United Nations
Security Council imposed sanctions on Libya, but for years the
Libyan leader refused to budge. Wanting to end the international
isolation of his country, and after considerable persuasion by the
likes of UN Secretary General Kofi Annan and South African
President Nelson Mandela, Khadafy finally allowed the suspects to
be extradited to the Netherlands in April of last year.
</P>
<P>
   Some relatives, including Susan Cohen of New Jersey, whose
20-year-old daughter Theodora was among those on the flight, worry
that the two suspects are scapegoats and that those who
orchestrated the bombing will never be held accountable. Cohen and
her husband, who wrote a book critical of way the families have
been treated, are far from alone in fearing that the geopolitical
stakes are so high that the trial will avoid pointing the finger at
high-ranking officials in the Middle East who ordered the bombing,
and at others in Washington and London who may have failed to
prevent it.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors will try to convince a tribunal of three Scottish
judges sitting without a jury that the two suspects were Libyan
intelligence agents and planted the bomb in retaliation, most
likely, for US warplanes' bombing of Tripoli in 1986. That bombing
was in turn ordered by President Ronald Reagan in retaliation for a
terrorist attack on a West Berlin disco frequented by US soldiers,
which Washington blamed on Libya.
</P>
<P>
   The Scottish lawyers defending the two suspects will try to
raise doubts by citing the other theories that prosecutors pursued
before settling on the two Libyan suspects. Specifically, defense
lawyers will argue that the bomb was planted by a convicted
terrorist named Mohammed Abu Talb, an Eyptian-born Palestinian who
led a Syrian-based terrorist group that was intially the prime
suspect. Talb is serving a life sentence for an unrelated attack on
a synagogue in Copenhagen.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution, lead by Colin Boyd, the Lord Advocate of
Scotland, will bank heavily on its star witness, Abdu Maged Jiacha,
a Libyan intelligence agent who defected to the CIA. Jiacha claims
that the two suspects used their covers as employees at Libyan Arab
Airlines at Malta's airport to slip the bomb into a suitcase on a
flight to Frankfurt. From there, the suitcase was sent onto London
and loaded onto Pan Am Flight 103 at Heathrow Airport, bound for
John F. Kennedy Airport in New York.
</P>
<P>
   It exploded while the airliner was 31,000 feet above Lockerbie.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation into the bombing was one of the most extensive
in history. The forensic case is, according to independent
observers, rock solid. There seems little doubt that the bomb was
made of Semtex, the Czech-made explosive that can be undetectable,
and was hidden in a Toshiba radio-cassette player, a device used
before by terrorists in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Less conclusive, however, is the evidence that it was the two
suspects who planted the bomb, and even less conclusive is the case
that they were anything but low-level operatives, put up to the job
by far more senior people.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution's case has taken a beating in recent months. A
key witness who had initially claimed to have sold to the Libyan
government the sort of electronic timer used to detonate the bomb
has since begun to waffle. An FBI agent who argued that his
colleagues were going down the wrong path by pursuing Talb and
helped steer the investigation toward Libya has since been charged
with tampering with evidence in other cases.
</P>
<P>
   Boyd tried to get a postponement last week, saying the defense
had sprung a last-minute list of surprise witnesses. But the
presiding judge, Lord Ranald Ian Sutherland, would have none of it.
Sutherland believes the prosecution, which will outline its case
for months before the defense makes its case, has had plenty of
time to prepare.
</P>
<P>
   Lord Sutherland, Jim Swire, the Flynns, and the Cohens likely
agree on one thing: After nearly 12 years, it's time to get on with
it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
