<SLUG> BC-CANADA-VIETNAM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANADA SHOCKED TO LEARN OF EXECUTION IN VIETNAM  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALIFAX, Nova Scotia _ On April 24, shortly before dawn in
Hanoi, a 43-year-old Canadian seamstress named Nguyen Thi Hiep _
convicted of attempting to smuggle heroin out of Vietnam _ was
blindfolded, gagged, and tied to a wooden stake in a field near the
Xuon Phuong detention center in the communist capital of Hanoi.
</P>
<P>
   There was no one there except the firing squad and a few passing
prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Nguyen's family nor the Canadian government had been
alerted _ indeed, officials in Ottawa and the woman's kin in
suburban Toronto were under the impression that the execution had
been postponed indefinitely after Canadian police furnished Vietnam
with new evidence suggesting the woman was innocent.
</P>
<P>
   But at 6 sharp, the six executioners raised their rifles and
fired a single volley, according to a prisoner who witnessed the
execution and later described it to her family. An hour later, her
husband _ in Hanoi to visit Nguyen _ was hustled to the killing
ground and shown the bullet-torn post and the place where she was
buried.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was blood all over the ground,'' Tran Hieu told
reporters in a call home to Brampton, Ontario. ``The last shot was
to her head. They already had a hole dug and had a box ready to put
her body in. . . My wife is dead, they killed her.''
</P>
<P>
   As Vietnam celebrates the 25th anniversary of its military
victory over the United States, once-warm relations between the
regime and Canada _ which opposed the Vietnam war and threw its
doors open to American draft dodgers _ have been cast into
diplomatic disarray by Nguyen's execution.
</P>
<P>
   Her case is quickly becoming a cause celebre as Canadians react
with horror to the brutally lethal punishment for a crime hardly
proven beyond a reasonable doubt. Even as the US basks in
dramatically improved relations with the old foe, Canada's ties
with Vietnam are being strained to the snapping point.
</P>
<P>
   ``We deplore this absolutely unacceptable conduct of the
government of Vietnam,'' Prime Minister Jean Chretien said shortly
after Ottawa announced that it had withdrawn its ambassador to
Hanoi and suspended other diplomatic contacts. It also this week
halted millions of dollars in development aid to the impoverished
Southeast Asian nation.
</P>
<P>
   The sentence, carried out in secret and revealed last week to
stunned Canadian authorities, seemed an almost perverse slap at
Canada's attempts to win pardon for Nguyen and her 74-year-old
mother, still incarcerated in the rat-infested Hanoi facility. The
execution squad opened fire just four days before Vietnam released
12,500 prisoners, including convicted murderers, in a mass amnesty
to mark the victory celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say we are shocked is too mild,'' said Reynald Doiron, a
spokesman for Canada's Ministry of Foreign Affairs. ``This Canadian
citizen was shot dead . . . after we were given assurances in
writing that she would be spared at least until we could present
new information.''
</P>
<P>
   The execution came only weeks after Canada offered Vietnam new
material from the Toronto Metropolitan Police supporting Nguyen's
claim that she was the unsuspecting dupe of Canadian-based heroin
smugglers. Right to the end, she refused to sign a confession and
adamantly maintained her innocence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, evidence suggests she was guilty of minor greed and
major bad judgement,'' said a Canadian diplomat, requesting
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The execution came almost precisely four years after Nguyen and
her mother, Tran Thi Cam, were arrested at Hanoi's Noi Bai
International Airport on April 25, 1996 while preparing to fly
home. It was their first visit to Vietnam since fleeing as part of
the huge post-war exodus of boat people.
</P>
<P>
   Nguyen was caught with 12 pounds of heroin, worth $3.4 million,
concealed in decorative frames of lacquer paintings in her
suitcase. Her mother, also on the trip, was charged as an
accomplice.
</P>
<P>
   Mother and daugher said Ngueyn had been paid $100 by the
neighbor of a relative in Canada to carry the artwork back home
from Vietnam as a sort of paid favor.
</P>
<P>
   The explanation has been branded a lie by Vietnamese officials.
But Nguyen won surprising support from Toronto police, whose drug
investigators believe she and her mother were unsuspecting mules
tricked by drug smugglers. Toronto police even made a highly
unusual offer to send detectives to Hanoi to plead her case.
</P>
<P>
   The modus operandi was identical to that one used with another
Vietnamese woman recruited by the same man to carry heroin-packed
artwork back to Canada. That woman was apprehended at a Toronto
airport within days of Nguyen's arrest, but released after
detectives became convinced she had been hoodwinked into doing a
``favor'' and had no idea she was carrying narcotics.
</P>
<P>
   Nontheless, Nguyen was sentenced to death by a Vietnamese court,
and her elderly mother was handed a life sentence. The only details
of the case that Hanoi has provided Ottawa are in a confusing
eight-page document whose main point seems to be that Nguyen at
first lied about receiving the $100.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, Canada gave Vietnam details of the case
involving the second woman and other evidence indicating Nguyen was
not a knowing trafficker.
</P>
<P>
   Family members who visted Nguyen over the years said she was
kept in shackles in a squalid cell overrun with rats, cockroaches,
and other vermin. In Brampton's close-knit Vietnamese immigrant
community she had the reputation of a hardworking seamstress whose
life revolved around family, especially her two sons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now our only hope is that her remains can be released for
cremation in accordance with Buddhist custom,'' said one of the
sons, Tu Le. ``She suffered so badly in this life we need to
perform the ceremonies to help her gain good fortune in the next
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Vietnam, like several other nations in Southeast Asia, imposes
the death penalty in almost every case involving narcotics
trafficking. The execution of Nguyen marks the first time a
Canadian citizen has received the death penalty on a foreign drug
charge.
</P>
</TEXT>
