<HEADER>
A3595 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-IVORYCOAST-MILITARY-2     05-02 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVORYCOAST-MILITARY-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IVORY COAST JUNTA CHIEF HINTS THAT HE MAY SEEK ELECTION AS
PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABIDJAN, Ivory Coast _ Since staging this West African country's
first military coup last Dec. 24, the army has not shied away from
trying on new roles besides politics.
</P>
<P>
   There was the time a couple of months ago when it tried its hand
energetically, if somewhat too energetically, at coaching soccer.
Ivory Coast's national team, the Elephants _ made up mostly of
Ivoirians who play for high-paying European teams and reluctantly
took time off to participate in the African Nations Cup in Ghana _
performed so spiritlessly that they failed to qualify for the
quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly angered, the country's military rulers forced the
players to make an unexpected detour on their way back to Europe _
to a military camp in Abidjan. Stripped of their passports and
their freedom, not to mention their cell phones, the soccer stars
spent two days at the base taking lessons in civics and patriotism,
and doing pushups.
</P>
<P>
   Then recently soldiers driving sports-utility vehicles bearing
no license plates began patrolling a 25-mile stretch of highway
between Abidjan and Grand-Bassam, a beach resort popular among
expatriates. Bad drivers have been summoned to appear in sweats at
a nearby military base, where they have been lectured and forced to
jog _ and to pay a $7 fine.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic cop, soccer coach, gym teacher _ the army is control in
Ivory Coast, a country that for decades had been one of the few
African nations not to have experienced military rule and still
stands as the richest in French-speaking Africa. More than four
months after an initially popular coup, it remains unclear when the
army will relinquish power _ though most assume that it will happen
eventually.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the uncertainty stems from Gen. Robert Guei, the leader
of the junta, who only a few months ago had declared in an address
to the nation that, ``Contrary to what we have seen in many
countries in the sub-region, power does not interest me.'' In
recent months, Guei has eschewed such clarity in favor of coy
comments that suggest that he is, in fact, interested in power.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guei is behaving more and more like a candidate,'' said one
Western diplomat.
</P>
<P>
   As the Ivoirian political class and Western diplomats have come
to believe that the general is preparing to present himself as a
presidential candidate, the possibility is likely to complicate
further the country's year-long political crisis. The trouble led
to the overthrow in December of President Henri Konan Bedie, whose
party had been in power since independence from France in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In Bourbana, a slum sprawling on a hill next to a lagoon across
from the skyscrapers of downtown Abidjan, Guei's rise was cheered
in December. The residents of Bourbana, mostly northerners or
immigrants who had become targets during Bedie's increasingly
xenophobic administration, still spoke well of the general.
</P>
<P>
   The putrid smell from the lagoon wafted up the hill through the
labyrinth of narrow alleys that criss-cross Bourbana. Women cooked
and sold small items; stagnant water had collected in many alleys,
and pedestrians stepped around them with great difficulty.
Nevertheless, life had improved in Bourbana, said a group of
jobless young men milling around in one of the few open spaces. The
police, they said, no longer harassed them and did not stop them
from setting up small commercial stands along the nearby highway.
</P>
<P>
   Even in this slum, however, some expressed worry about the
repercussions of the candidacy of a man who had seized power
through the gun.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Guei becomes president, it would please us,'' said Seydou
Ouattara, 68, the traditional chief of this community. ``I don't
know how to read or write, so I am not sure, but he's a military
man. And if he becomes president, the whites will not give us
money.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Almost all foreign aid to the Ivory Coast has been suspended
because of the coup. And as the junta delays announcing whether it
will hold elections by October _ the original timetable, which
seems less and less likely now to be respected _ most programs go
unfinanced.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. State Department last month came out strongly against a
possible candidacy by Guei, describing it as ``inappropriate,'' and
any electoral outcome as clouded from the start. Officials from
France and the European Union, however, would be more likely to
countenance his candidacy, diplomats here said.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor expected to influence how a Guei candidacy is
accepted abroad is the lack of any other presidential candidate who
is popular nationwide. The leaders of two of the three main parties
are divisive figures, each for different reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The question over the eligibility of Alassane D. Ouattara, a
former deputy managing director of the International Monetary Fund,
contributed to the December coup; a constitutional referendum that
will essentially decide whether he can run has already been
postponed. Whatever the outcome, Ouattara's base is mainly among
Muslim northerners.
</P>
<P>
   The deposed president, Bedie, stirred up hatred against
northerners and immigrants by claiming that some were more Ivoirian
than others. Since the coup, Laurent Gbagbo, another potential
candidate, has taken up that strategy through a newspaper close to
his party, Notre Voie.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Whoever becomes the next president will have a hard time
restoring the luster to a country whose commercial capital,
Abidjan, was once called the Paris of Africa.
</P>
<P>
   With the economy worsening, banditry has risen. The military
government has responded by increasing summary executions. In
April, Guei announced that 66 bandits had been executed in the
first three months of the year, compared with 33 for the previous
three months.
</P>
<P>
   The Ivoirian League of Human Rights denounced the extra-judicial
killings, saying in a statement that there was nothing to ``boast''
of in this ``sad record.''
</P>
<P>
   Attacks against journalists, which occurred in the previous
government, have been notable in several instances. The randomness
of the attacks by soldiers, apparently uncoordinated, have also led
to suggestions that Guei does not have full control over the
military.
</P>
<P>
   Young soldiers began the insurrection in December, displeased
that they had not been paid money owed to them. A mutiny erupted at
a military camp in western Ivory Coast over the same issue in
March, and one soldier was killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will do what we can for the young soldiers, but they cannot
resort to blackmail,'' Guei said in an interview with Radio France
International at the time. Recently, the general has been pointedly
avoiding the media.
</P>
<P>
   Le Jeune Democrate, an independent daily, and Le National, a
newspaper that was close to the toppled government, have both been
targets in recent months, leading the Committee to Protect
Journalists to protest to Guei.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never had freedom of speech in the Ivory Coast, but it's
the dimension of the current repression that is cause for worry,''
said Jules Toualy, an editor at Le Jeune Democrate who was held for
five hours by two soldiers after he wrote about the March mutiny.
Toualy, who revealed the identity of his source after he was
tortured, has now become a sportswriter.
</P>
<P>
   Soldiers raided Le National twice after the paper published
articles critical of the general. One time they fired shots into
the ceiling and forced journalists to do push-ups.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is that soldiers do whatever they wish,'' said
Theodore Brouhaud, an editor at Le National. ``They go wherever
they want.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   When soldiers visited his newsroom, Brooss said, they asked each
journalist to do 100 push-ups. ``They would force us onto our knees
or outside the office so that we would be in the sun for 15
minutes,'' he said. ``Then they would let us under the shade and
then back again under the sun. It was a game for them. It lasted
two hours. We had marks on our wrists from all the push-ups.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
