   NY-PATAKI-TRIPS (New York) _ The New York State Ethics
Commission has found that Gov. George Pataki and his aides did not
violate the law in allowing a non-profit group largely financed by
companies with business before the state, including Philip Morris,
to pay for Pataki's visits to Hungary in 1995 and 1996. But the
commission concluded that the trips did raise ``ethical concerns''
because the non-profit group, the Hungarian-American Chamber of
Commerce U.S.A., solicited money from the companies specifically
for the trips. By Clifford J. Levy.
