<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3606 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AUTO-SALES-1000-NYT &LR;      05-02 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-SALES-1000-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNTERING PREDICTIONS, AUTO SALES REMAIN STRONG 
</HEADLINE>
   By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Rising interest rates, a volatile stock market and
higher gasoline prices were expected to be slowing the American
economy by now, including the highly cyclical auto industry. Yet at
car dealerships across the country, business is still booming, with
every big domestic and foreign automaker announcing on Tuesday that
April sales exceeded last year's brisk pace.
</P>
<P>
   The buyers are people like Frank DiBernardino, a 52-year-old
human resources consultant in Glen Mills, Pa., who bought a huge
blue GMC Yukon for $42,300 last month. The Federal Reserve's
interest rate increases did not affect him, he said, because he
wrote a check for the full-sized sport utility vehicle, using the
proceeds of some stock he sold in February. Nor was he troubled by
the price of gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a certain size requirement we needed for the family,''
he said, including three grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   For the last several months, economists and auto executives have
been predicting that auto sales would slow significantly, but that
has not happened. While sales slowed very slightly in April from
the record-setting pace of the first quarter of this year,
adjusting for seasonal variations, they were still up 10.5 percent
from the extremely strong level of April last year. It was the auto
industry's best April ever, according to Ward's Auto Infobank.
</P>
<P>
   Other economic indicators are also showing surprising strength.
The Commerce Department said that new home sales leaped 4.5 percent
in March, while the Conference Board in New York announced that its
index of leading indicators rose a tenth of a percent in March
after edging down in February.
</P>
<P>
   The auto sales report is a clear sign that robust growth
continued into the second quarter. Auto executives and economists
said the biggest reason is that buyers still feel confident about
the economy and still have money to spend. ``Real wages are really
strong and it's hard to stop this train,'' said Diane C. Swonk, a
senior vice president and chief economist at Bank One Corp. in
Chicago. ``You don't need any more gains from the stock market.''
</P>
<P>
   Another reason is that automakers are still piling on rebates,
discounted interest rates and other incentives in a frantic
struggle for market share even as sales boom. Automakers are using
their enormous profit margins to subsidize prices and keep monthly
payments from rising for the 80 percent of their customers who use
car loans or leases instead of paying cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fly in the ointment is the incentives for everybody are
very tough,'' said James Holden, the president of DaimlerChrysler's
Chrysler subsidiary. ``With interest rates escalating, trying to
hold payments constant is getting expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Ballew, GM's general director of global market and industry
analysis, said that the company actually hoped that auto sales
would slow soon, because factories were struggling to keep up with
demand, and so many sales now might subtract from sales in the
future. ``We would like and expect to see some moderation _ it's
not in our interest to have an exaggerated cycle,'' said Ballew,
the Federal Reserve's top expert on the auto industry in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few signs that the pace of sales might be cooling.
Frank Ursomarso, a dealer with franchises in Wilmington, Del., said
that he had noticed a slightly slower tempo and had charted a
pattern over the last 44 years in which sales tended to precede the
overall industry's increases and declines. ``The floor traffic has
been trending down a little each month,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler announced on Friday that it was reducing
production slightly of the Jeep Grand Cherokee, which faces growing
competition in the market for mid-sized sport utility vehicles.
Holden said the company had decided that it was better to lose a
little market share than to keep increasing incentives.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the industry is running at $2,000 incentives, which is
creating this hyper industry, sometimes you take a few losses,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   GM's market share was 28.3 percent in April, down from 30.6
percent a year ago. But almost all of the decline reflected the
company's continued weakness in the unprofitable small car market,
in which it faces growing competition from low-cost Korean imports.
GM has been gaining in the profitable market for full-sized sport
utility vehicles, as recently redesigned models like the Chevrolet
Suburban and the GMC Yukon have enjoyed vibrant sales.
</P>
<P>
   GM reported a smaller increase in sales than any other big auto
maker last month, a 2.2 percent gain overall as a 7.1 percent gain
in sales of sport utilities, pickup trucks and vans more than
offset a 2.5 percent decline in car sales. GM's arch-rival, the
Ford Motor Co., reported a different pattern, as a 15.4 percent
increase in car sales led the company to an overall increase of
12.1 percent, while its sales of so-called light trucks _ sport
utilities, pickups and vans _ were up 9.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Ballew said that this might be the first full year in which
light truck sales inch ahead of car sales, although this has
already happened in a few months during the last three winters.
Market share gains for light trucks have slowed sharply from the
mid-1990s, and are increasingly the result of rising sales of
all-wheel-drive wagons, like the Chrysler PT Cruiser and Toyota
RAV4, that the auto industry chooses to classify as light trucks
because of preferential regulatory treatment for vehicles not sold
as cars.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler's sales rose 5.3 percent, led by ever-popular
sport utilities, pickup trucks and Mercedes cars.
</P>
<P>
   Among other automakers announcing results today, Asian
automakers thrived last month, with Honda's sales rising 14.7
percent from a year ago, Toyota's up 15.7 percent, Nissan's up 31.8
percent, and Mitsubishi's up 49.2 percent. European automakers also
prospered, with BMW posting a 12.1 percent increase while
Volkswagen reported a gain of 14.7 percent. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-00 1930EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000502.0239 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3610 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-STEWART-PROTEST-NYT &LR;      05-02 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEWART-PROTEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRODUCERS TURN TO UNION IN DISPUTE WITH PATRICK STEWART
</HEADLINE>
  By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The producers of the Broadway play ``The Ride Down
Mount Morgan'' have filed charges with the stage actors union
against the show's star, Patrick Stewart, citing a speech he made
from the stage on Saturday accusing the producers of failing to
promote the play adequately.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint of unprofessional conduct, filed with the Actors
Equity Association, could result in Stewart's expulsion from the
union, which would be a professional blight but would not bar him
from Broadway productions. The union rarely expels a member, but
Stewart could be reprimanded or fined if the union agrees with the
producers.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart and one of the producers will each have the opportunity
to speak before a hearing committee of four Equity actors. The
hearing has yet to be scheduled. Under Equity rules, agreeing to
this procedure means that the producers have waived their right to
take other legal action.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart declined through a spokeswoman to comment on the charges
Tuesday. The spokeswoman, Kelly Bush, said that Stewart had not yet
been notified of the action.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Schoenfeld, chairman of the Shubert Organization, along
with the other producers of the show, said simply, ``In our opinion
we thought the matter should be brought to Equity's attention.''
Schoenfeld said that the producers had spent more than $1 million
on advertising and promotion.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart's speech _ which he made on behalf of himself and the
play's author, Arthur Miller, nine days before Tony nominations are
to be decided _ stunned Broadway, not only because a precedent
could not be recalled, but because Stewart publicly took on the
powerful and legendarily tough-minded Shuberts, as the organization
is commonly known.
</P>
<P>
   The actor, who agreed to take a lower salary than usual for
``Mount Morgan'' in exchange for a percentage of the show's
profits, had until then had a close relationship with Schoenfeld,
having worked with him on ``A Christmas Carol'' and ``The
Tempest,'' both of which were produced in Shubert theaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mount Morgan,'' which received positive reviews, has been
running at nearly full capacity, according to Variety, but most of
the tickets have been heavily discounted, selling for about $40,
down from the top ticket price of $80. As a result the play has
been taking in 61 percent of its optimum gross. The producers would
not say how much revenue the show needed to take in to make money.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview on Monday, Stewart said that Schoenfeld had
rejected requests to meet with him and Miller and that Stewart's
agent, Sam Cohn, relayed a message from Schoenfeld demanding a
written apology. ``Of course I have no reason to make an apology of
any kind,'' Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was driven to deliver his statement _ which he made
standing alone onstage after the curtain call at Saturday's matinee
and evening performances _ because he felt that the concerns he had
voiced to Schoenfeld were being ignored. ``It's not as if I were
trying to create a controversy around a failed production,''
Stewart said. ``The production is a success. The reviews are
excellent. But people are not being told that.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart said he believed that other nonmusicals like ``The Real
Thing'' and ``A Moon for the Misbegotten'' were being advertised
more aggressively. ``We are all in competition for audiences and
for awards and nominations when they come around,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart said he had received assurances from Schoenfeld last
week over the telephone that an advertisement for the play would
run the following Sunday in the Arts &AMP; Leisure section of The New
York Times. The ad appeared in less than half of the copies _
700,000 of 1.8 million, advertising personnel at The Times said,
because it arrived at the Times after the deadline. He also said he
had assurances that the exterior of the Ambassador Theater would be
decorated with signs quoting the positive reviews, but that these
never materialized.
</P>
<P>
   Schoenfeld said the signs would be forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart said that before he made the speech, he alerted Miller;
the play's director, David Esbjornson; Bush, his spokeswoman; and
the rest of the cast. The actors declined through a secret ballot
to join Stewart onstage.
</P>
<P>
   Although Stewart had initially vowed to continue making his
speech, he said he changed his mind because of the wide attention
his comments attracted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a disturbing thing for an audience to experience that,''
Stewart said. ``And I was disturbed at having to do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
