u f BC-STATES-BIGDIG-NAT     05-02 0638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-BIGDIG-NAT </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  McCAIN TO PROBE BIG DIG INSURANCE PROGRAM, FEDERAL FUNDING
</P>
<P>
   By Alex Canizares
</P>
<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, May 2 - In a Senate hearing to probe the Big Dig's
cost overruns, Senator John McCain will examine the project's
discredited funding schemes today, and seek assurances that no
additional federal money will be used if costs rise further.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who chairs the Senate Commerce committee, will focus on
the Big Dig's controversial $800 million insurance fund and other
federal funds that a recent US Transportation Department audit
found to be illegitimate sources to help pay for the Central
Artery, a Senate aide said.
</P>
<P>
   Senator John Kerry, who is also on the committee, has received
assurances from the former presidential candidate and Arizona
Republican that the Big Dig would not be made into a ``political
football,'' spokesman David Wade said.
</P>
<P>
   And Senator Edward Kennedy said he approved of the hearings and
downplayed any political firestorm. ``I don't there's any time
bombs in this,'' he said in an interview yesterday. ``I think,
hopefully at the end of the hearing there will be an even greater
sense of support for continuing to move ahead in a timely way and
complete the project.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet McCain will grill witnesses, including Big Dig chief Andrew
Natsios, to explain the project's insurance scheme, which the
project has attempted to use as a source of funding as well as
insurance reserves.
</P>
<P>
   The insurance fund has been called a ``fiction'' by the US
Transportation Inspector General Kenneth Mead, who will testify
today.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said he would re-offer an amendment from last fall
designed to strip $150 million from the trust fund if the program
is retained, a Senate aide said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would drop it again,'' the aide said. ``We are in regular
contact with the (Inspector General) on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts and federal highway auditors are separately
grappling with a way to pay for the project -- which will cost
between $13.4 billion and $13.6 billion -- and both have called for
scrapping the insurance program.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is expected to grill Richard Thomas, senior vice
president of the American Insurance Group Inc., to explain
allegations of a conflict of interest.
</P>
<P>
   US Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater and Matthew Wiley,
project manager of Bechtel/Parsons Brinckerhoff, the join venture
that handles the Big Dig's daily operations, will also testify.
</P>
<P>
   Natsios, who replaced James Kerasiotes as the state's Turnpike
chairman last month, will pledge his complete cooperation with
overseers in Washington to restore the project's credibility, said
spokesman Joe Landolfi. ``We need to reach a certain comfort level
with Congress and federal highway officials,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to probing past mistakes, McCain will seek
assurances that no additional federal funding is at risk beyond the
$8.5 billion already promised in highway money.
</P>
<P>
   Transportation Inspector General Kenneth Mead is expected to say
the Big Dig's most recent finance plan drafted under Kerasiotes
could raise the federal share to $9.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Although the finance plan has been rejected by the state and its
delegation in Washington, McCain's aides disagreed that federal
funds are legally protected, and said Slater would be asked about
an informal cap on the Big Dig. ``There is no cap,'' the aide said.
``The cap exists in somebody's mind''
</P>
<P>
   The Big Dig is currently limited to an informal cap of $8.5
billion in federal funds, according Federal Highway Administrator
Kenneth Wykle, in a ``hand-shake'' agreement that is not written
into law.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts congressional aides dismissed any notion that
McCain, whose committee doesn't handle the Big Dig's funds, would
take any action that could affect the project's finances. l. z
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
