<SLUG> BC-ROBERDS-SIDE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Roberds customers left holding receipts
 &HT;    By Jim Bohman and Laura A. Bischoff
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Roberds Inc. customers drove up to locked stores
Tuesday, clutching receipts and wondering when or how they would
get the sofas, refrigerators or chairs they paid for weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Or could they get their money back?
</P>
<P>
   ``They were still taking orders up until the end of last week,''
said Sandy Hack, angry that she and husband Jim spent $1,600 in
March on an upholstered chair and loveseat and don't have the
furniture.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they knew there was a problem, they should not have taken
cash or credit cards or whatever from customers,'' Mrs. Hack said
in front of the silent, sun-baked store in suburban Beavercreek.
</P>
<P>
   ``It aggravates me that so many people are going to get burned
because of this,'' said Hack, a retired General Motors employee.
The couple put down $400 in cash and placed the balance on their
Roberds credit card. Mrs. Hack, a New Jersey native, declared that
she won't pay those charges unless she gets her furniture.
</P>
<P>
   Simegnish Hunegnaw, a native of Ethiopia who described himself
as a loyal Roberds customer for 20 years, drove up to the
Beavercreek store in a pickup truck hoping to get the refrigerator
he ordered for $793.24. He, too, placed the purchase on a credit
card.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, we will get something,'' Hunegnaw said. ``We don't
want to lose our money.'' He said he would be in line, receipt in
hand, when the liquidation sale begins.
</P>
<P>
   Hunegnaw said the company seemed to change, and not for the
better, as it grew. When Roberds had only the West Carrollton
store, he said, the selection was great and delivery, always free,
was superb.
</P>
<P>
   ``One time we bought a recliner, and we were unhappy with it,''
he said. ``They came back and replaced it and it was no problem.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the company may have become overly ambitious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they wanted to get big in a short period of time,''
said the Dayton resident, who furnished much of his home with
merchandise from the original store. ``We were satisfied customers.
But now they've got stores all over. Maybe they've stretched too
much.''
</P>
<P>
   Chuck and Becky Smail of Springfield were perplexed. They put
$450 down on a $990 sofa, and don't know how to get the
merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I owed them,'' Chuck Smail said, ``they'd be right on my
doorstep.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
