u p BC-GORE0503-COX     05-02 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE0503-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore stumps in Atlanta, pitches crime proposal
 &HT;    By Peter Mantius
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Vice President Al Gore delivered a major policy speech
on crime Tuesday, detailing a package that includes funding for
50,000 new police officers and an amendment to the U.S.
Constitution to expand crime victims' rights.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in casual slacks and a tan polo shirt, Gore outlined his
plan at an Atlanta YWCA in front of about 250 uniformed police
officers and local and state public officials.
</P>
<P>
   The audience broke in with applause more than a dozen times
during the approximately 45-minute address. One of the loudest
rounds came after Gore called so-called racial profiling of
suspects an unjust practice. ``It is unfair and inconsistent with
the idea of community policing that has worked so well,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of the speech, Gore's remarks turned overtly
political as he blasted his Republican presidential opponent, Texas
Gov. George W. Bush, for proposing a $2 trillion tax cut that would
inevitably dry up funding for Gore's planned police positions. Gore
said he favored a Senate plan to create a budgetary ``lock box'' on
that police funding now.
</P>
<P>
   ``George W. Bush is preparing to pick the lock with his tax cut
giveaway,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Attorney General Thurbert Baker, a Democrat who
attended, said Gore's plan increases pressure on Bush to deliver
his own anti-crime agenda. The Bush campaign faxed a three-page
response to Gore's speech about an hour after he finished speaking.
</P>
<P>
   To Gore's claim that prison inmate recidivism in Texas had risen
nearly 25 percent during Bush's term as governor, Bush spokesman
Dan Bartlett shot back:
</P>
<P>
   ``If Al Gore is willing to attack Texas where violent crime is
at a 20-year low and the largest prison drug treatment program in
the country is located, we're also expecting attack on Texans for
defending the Alamo.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's decision to deliver the major anti-crime speech in one of
Atlanta's trendy and heavily Democratic neighborhoods signals his
determination to make Georgia a presidential battleground, said
Merle Black, a political scientist at Emory University.
</P>
<P>
   Gore hopes to avert a Republican sweep of the South by focusing
time, energy and money in both Florida and Georgia, Black said.
``Gore wants to split the South,'' Black added. ``If Gore wins
Georgia, it's hard to see how Bush wins the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   The anti-crime package he outlined includes:
</P>
<P>
   _ Increased drug testing of prisoners, parolees and probationers
to help reduce the number of drug addicts released from prison back
onto the streets.
</P>
<P>
   _ An amendment to the U.S. Constitution to expand the rights of
crime victims by allowing them to participate in trials and by
notifying them of criminals' release from prison.
</P>
<P>
   _ 50,000 new police officers. The program would be a follow-up
to President Clinton's 100,000-police officer initiative in 1994.
The Clinton slots are all funded, but only 60,000 of the 100,000
positions have been filled.
</P>
<P>
   _ New federal legislation to empower local communities to break
up violent teen gangs.
</P>
<P>
   _ More after-school programs for teens to cut down on juvenile
crime committed in the afternoon when parents are still at work.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
