<HEADER>
A3622 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-HONGKONG-AUCTION-900(     05-02 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONGKONG-AUCTION-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE BIDDER BUYS RELICS FOR CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIK ECKHOLM with MARK LANDLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ The confrontation between Chinese authorities and Hong
Kong's premier auction houses over the sale of looted imperial
treasures has been defused, for now at least, by an unlikely
source: a giant Chinese state-owned corporation that became the
winning bidder on three of the four contested objects.
</P>
<P>
   The company, China Poly Group Corp., which until last year was
owned by the People's Liberation Army and is best known for its
global weapons sales, recently established a small antiquities
museum here with an emphasis on ancient bronzes. Part of its
mission is to buy choice Chinese relics abroad and bring them back
to the motherland, and as was clear in recent days, it has very
deep pockets.
</P>
<P>
   In Hong Kong auctions at Christie's on Sunday and at Sotheby's
on Tuesday, the Poly Group bought the three objects, bronze animal
heads that once helped form a zodiac fountain at the Old Summer
Palace north of this city, for a total of $4 million, far above the
expected price.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided to buy these things because they belong to us,
they're part of the Chinese people's national treasure,'' said the
assistant curator of the new Poly Art Museum, Jiang Yingchun.
``Since the attempts to halt the auction or even bring the relics
back by legal means or persuasion had failed, we had to resort to
commercial means.''
</P>
<P>
   The fourth object, a Qing dynasty vase also believed to have
been stolen from the Old Summer Palace when it was pillaged by
invading British and French troops in 1860, was sold at Sotheby's
Tuesday afternoon for an equally astounding $2.7 million to an
unidentified Beijing antiquities company.
</P>
<P>
   Because the objects all appear to be returning to China, albeit
at premium prices, the immediate tensions seem to have dissipated.
But left hanging for the auction houses, and more generally for the
booming global market in Chinese antiquities, is a major question:
How serious is the government's new aggressiveness over the
international trade in Chinese relics, many of which were
originally stolen or smuggled out of the country?
</P>
<P>
   This week's disputed items were, to be sure, in a special
category. The Old Summer Palace, known in Chinese as Yuanmingyuan,
or Garden of Perfect Brightness, is idealized here, and the story
of its sacking is taught to every schoolchild as the ultimate
symbol of national humiliation.
</P>
<P>
   Built by 17th- and 18th-century Qing emperors as their summer
residence and fantasyland, the palace was actually a vast estate of
landscapes, lakes and finely crafted traditional buildings, and
even included a cluster of rococo marble palaces designed by
European Jesuits. The estate was stocked with China's finest arts
when it was burned and looted as invading colonial powers forced
China to accept the opium trade.
</P>
<P>
   During its 27 years in Hong Kong, Sotheby's has sold other
relics from the Old Summer Palace without any objections from the
Chinese government, said Carlton Rochell, the managing director of
the China and Southeast Asia division for the auction house.
</P>
<P>
   But since Hong Kong officially became part of China in 1997,
while maintaining a separate legal system, public awareness about
relics has increased. After seeing the four items openly marketed
as Old Summer Palace treasures, some Chinese officials began to
complain last month.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese State Relics Bureau stepped in last week, sending a
letter to Christie's and Sotheby's asking them not to auction the
items in Hong Kong, saying that it would be a deep insult to the
Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
   The auction houses decided to hold their ground, and much to
their relief, the Poly Group and the unidentified Beijing dealer
apparently decided to win back the objects at almost any price.
</P>
<P>
   For years the Poly Group was the chief global arms seller in
China. It attracted attention a few years ago in the West when a
subsidiary was caught smuggling assault rifles into the United
States for sale, and later when its chairman, Wang Jun, became
known as the Chinese arms dealer who was brought to a White House
meeting of political fund-raisers in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The Poly Group was forced to separate from the military last
year because of a new national policy to end military involvement
in business. The company says that its operations are now
concentrated in real estate, industry, high technology and tourism.
</P>
<P>
   Following the model of American corporate philanthropy _ a new
concept in China _ the company decided to improve its image by
doing visible good and established the museum in central Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Ma Baoping, the assistant director of the museum and a former
military officer, said that as company executives traveled
overseas, they noticed how many premier Chinese relics were in
foreign hands. ``We felt that if we could bring some of these
objects back to China, it would be a patriotic act,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Until now the collecting of the Poly Art Museum had focused on
ancient bronzes and other relics. The decision to buy the three
comparatively recent bronze animal heads this week was made only on
Sunday, just before the Christie's auction began, museum officials
said. They declined to say whether they had consulted with
government officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of Chinese national dignity and self-respect, you
can't measure the importance of these objects in money alone,''
said the Poly curator, Jiang.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At the auction Tuesday, Sotheby's sold its first disputed item,
an intricately decorated 18th-century hexagonal vase, for more than
double the estimated value.
</P>
<P>
   As the bidding began, a man at the rear of the ballroom shouted,
``It is shameful to sell off national treasures of China!'' He was
removed without incident, and the bidding quickly narrowed to a
duel between the Beijing company and a collector from Taiwan with
ties to an art museum there. The vase has a twin that sold at
Sotheby's in Hong Kong in 1988 and now belongs to the Taiwanese
museum.
</P>
<P>
   The second piece, a bronze tiger's head from a zodiac fountain
that is believed to have been designed by a Jesuit artist who lived
in China, sold for $2 million, more than three times its estimated
value of $580,000, with the price driven up by an unidentified
telephone bidder.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The bronze ox and monkey heads sold by Christie's on Sunday,
taken from the same fountain, each sold for about $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   China's overall position on sales of Chinese relics is unclear.
A relics bureau representative said that the goal was simply to get
the auctions out of Hong Kong and Chinese territory.
</P>
<P>
   But a Beijing newspaper quoted a senior official at the relics
bureau Tuesday as saying that international precedent and law
required that objects plundered during wartime must be returned no
matter how much time has passed, an opinion that, even if not
rooted in international law, could presage more conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say that no international agreements mandate the return
of items stolen so long ago. Still, a more assertive China could,
at a minimum, make life difficult for auction houses and dealers
hoping to do business on the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   When objects have been stolen more recently and proof exists,
the situation is different: many countries, including China, have
signed a 1970 UNESCO treaty requiring their return.
</P>
<P>
   Institutionally Christie's has kept a poker face throughout the
dispute, but on Tuesday, executives at Sotheby's said they were
relieved by the outcome of the auctions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a great resolution because mainland Chinese were able
to purchase these things, which clearly the nation was very
passionate about having back,'' said Rochell of Sotheby's.
</P>
<P>
   Rochell defended the practice of auctioning relics, even those
from historically symbolic places like the Old Summer Palace.
</P>
<P>
   ``If these objects weren't traded openly and freely at auction
they might have remained underground, and the people from Beijing
wouldn't have had the opportunity to buy them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he acknowledged that the criticism from China surprised
and shook the house.
</P>
<P>
   In future cases of relics involving particular historical or
emotional significance, he said, Sotheby's will discuss the sale
with the Chinese government in advance, although to what end is
unclear.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was from a known place that was sacked, we'd want to be
more careful,'' Rochell said. ``One has to be very sensitive about
the objects that are in an auction.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
