<HEADER>
A3635 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-STEPPENWOLF-THEATER-2     05-02 1227
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEPPENWOLF-THEATER-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEPPENWOLF AND LONG WHARF, WHERE THE ENSEMBLE IS THE STAR 
</HEADLINE>
   By BRUCE WEBER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The Steppenwolf Theater Company, which will celebrate
its 25th birthday next season, has become known, somewhat
paradoxically, for both its ensemble ethos and the stars that have
emerged from its ranks.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand the company is, in many ways, emblematic of the
thriving and close-knit theater world here, a city where a
surprising number of actors manage to work and live without making
the pilgrimage to either coast and where a de facto performance
style has arisen as a result. Chicago actors tend to be less
career-oriented offstage and thus less audience-oriented on. They
play to one another here; they do not mind turning upstage. Actors
here speak of this as liberating, a license to challenge their
colleagues with a vigor that isn't necessarily appreciated
elsewhere. The physically robust quality that many critics have
attributed generally to Chicago actors is a manifestation of this.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the fame and reputation of Steppenwolf rests
largely on the individuals who have leapt from here to celebrity:
John Malkovich, Gary Sinise, Laurie Metcalf, John Mahoney and Joan
Allen are among the company's 33 current members, many of whom no
longer live in Chicago. Even though most return periodically for
company productions, the traditional definition of an ensemble
troupe is not really applicable to Steppenwolf any longer;
star-studded ensemble is something of an oxymoron.
</P>
<P>
   Two current productions provide an interesting illustration of
this peculiar dynamic at work. One is at Steppenwolf, where Sinise,
a founding member of the company, is starring as McMurphy in Dale
Wasserman's adaptation of the Ken Kesey novel ``One Flew Over the
Cuckoo's Nest.''
</P>
<P>
   The other is at the Long Wharf Theater in New Haven, where
Martha Plimpton, a Steppenwolf member for the last two years, is
performing the title role in ``Hedda Gabler.'' Both lead actors are
giving ensemble-oriented performances in roles that are often
played as tours de force. Why ``Cuckoo's Nest'' is the more
satisfying has to do with the productions that contain them.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Doug Hughes, the Long Wharf's artistic director,
from his own script adaptation, this ``Hedda'' is a chilly one.
Played against a curving ice-blue wall conspicuously in need of a
paint job, with minimal furnishings and only the ominous portrait
of Hedda's military father as a decorative touch, the production is
devoid of the sumptuous affluence that Hedda, the manipulative and
unsatisfiable new wife, insists on exhibiting in her new home and
that her weak-kneed scholarly husband, Tesman, cannot afford. The
directorial idea _ a home that is warmthless and barren _ puts
obvious emphasis on Hedda's tortured sexuality, but it also places
huge demands on all the actors, leaving an enormous vacancy onstage
for the characters to fill with their collective anxieties.
</P>
<P>
   The production, which is scheduled for a reprise at Steppenwolf
next season, begins with Plimpton, wraithlike in a long white
dress, entering alone, running back and forth across the stage as
if in flight from an invisible demon. It's an effective
introduction to the powerlessness Hedda can neither escape nor
abide. She's a trapped rat in an oversize maze, and for the rest of
the play, you can not forget the image; her wheedlings and
plottings loom as an ever more desperate search for an exit. The
best moment of this production is the first.
</P>
<P>
   But from then on, with the entrance of the other characters, the
production creaks like uncarpeted floorboards. These are tough
roles in any case, with inbred ambiguities that should swell as the
play proceeds. But here, only Quentin Mare as Lovborg, Tesman's
rival scholar and a self-destructive, charismatic man with a
discomforting hold on Hedda's heart, has found the weight in his
character that can command the stage.
</P>
<P>
   Graham Winton plays Tesman as a man oblivious to the most
evident innuendo; Jenny Bacon, as Thea Elvsted, the woman who has
fallen for Lovborg, seems purely feckless. By the end, after
Lovborg's death, they seem remarkably untouched by the action
around them, simply getting out of the way so Hedda can get on with
her suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Best known as a film actress, Plimpton has nonetheless
established her stage chops; as Pegeen Mike in ``The Playboy of the
Western World'' and Laura in ``The Glass Menagerie,'' both at
Steppenwolf during the last two seasons, she demonstrated a
wide-ranging gift. But with her reedy voice and slight build, as
Hedda she never exudes real potency, never swells to a near
triumph. Hedda's feigned self-possession is unpersuasive; she's
straining to assume authority rather than creating a mask and
hiding behind it, and as a result, Hedda's self-inflicted demise is
no dramatic fall, just a closing event. In the end, this is a
production that could have used, from her, a bit more diva.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, here in ``Cuckoo's Nest,'' which is the city's
hottest ticket right now, Sinise is being buoyed and challenged by
a company of actors in strong character turns, and by a director,
the Steppenwolf member Terry Kinney, who has made sure his star
never has to seek the spotlight. It's a mediocre play _ the stage
version extracts the theme of righteous rebellion against injustice
without the Faulkneresque darkness of the Kesey novel _ but the
production is a crowd pleaser, played in the first act for laughs
and the second for tears. It will travel to London for a brief
sojourn this summer, and, with a commercial producer, Fox
Theatricals, behind it, Broadway may beckon, particularly if Sinise
is willing to stick around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cuckoo's Nest'' is the story, of course, of Randle Patrick
McMurphy, a gregarious prisoner who is transferred to a mental
asylum, where he becomes a doomed messiah, bringing life and hope
to the inmates as he disrupts the emasculating ward routine.
Sinise, a burly man with a natural swagger (he's physically closer
to the Kesey description of the character than was Jack Nicholson,
who won an Oscar for the role in Milos Forman's 1975 film), exudes
here the capability of physical threat and an instinctive sympathy
for the downtrodden.
</P>
<P>
   He plays the part for the melodrama the play insists on _ the
renegade with the heart of gold _ and it is a winning performance,
not least because it isn't overdone. In an admirably modest star
turn, he's willing to share the stage, and happily, he has worthy
colleagues here.
</P>
<P>
   Nurse Ratched, his nemesis, is played here with stony
unrufflability by Amy Morton, one of many Steppenwolf actors of
deserving local renown in the cast. They include Mariann Mayberry
as a riotously salacious prostitute McMurphy smuggles into the
ward; Rick Snyder as Cheswick, a patient who behaves, a pathetic
and hilarious amalgam of bravado and retreat; and K. Todd Freeman
as a doctor caught between McMurphy's charm and Nurse Ratched's
punishing authority. They are joined by Ross Lehman, marvelous as
the patient Harding, whose erudition is no salve for his crippling
sexual inadequacy, and Eric Johner, well cast as the stammering,
suicidal Billy Bibbit; his gentle good looks make Billy's
unbearable insecurity especially touching.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-00 1951EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
