<DOCNO> NYT20000502.0256 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3636 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-STEPPENWOLF-THEATER-N     05-02 0269
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEPPENWOLF-THEATER-NYT </SLUG>
 
CHICAGO: especially touching.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perhaps the play's most difficult role is that of Chief Bromden,
the belittled Indian giant who feigns being deaf and dumb to
survive on the ward and whose long-buried sense of self is restored
by McMurphy. He is played with effective lumbering sadness by Tim
Sampson, an Oklahoman whose father, Will, played the part in the
film. But it's a role that suffers in translation from page to
stage.
</P>
<P>
   In the novel, it is the chief who narrates; his strange and
moving voice combines shrewd observation with the deranged
fantasies of a man who wants only to hide in plain sight. This is
what the play misses, the sense of organic misery that soaks the
ward and that gives the novel its earned tragedy. The Chief's
paranoid inner monologues are illustrated here with interludes of
stagecraft: the Chief standing and speaking in a shaft of light,
with huge projections of machineworks on the white institutional
walls and steel-latticed windows of Robert Brill's set. The
projections, by Sage Carter, are dramatic, but anyone who has read
the novel will feel them as a makeshift ploy.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the actors are the heart of the production. Their
firm characterizations seize the sympathy of the audience without
ever stealing its attention, allowing Sinise to play off them
without undue clamor. Though there are moments when Kinney calls
the jittery energy on the ward to an awkward halt to allow McMurphy
to linger in the spotlight, this is, by and large, a highly
successful example of ensemble power. It's what Steppenwolf has
always done best.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
