A3637 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MA-ANTIBIOTICS-BOS &LR;      05-02 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-ANTIBIOTICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY UNCOVERS MUCH OVERUSE OF ANTIBIOTICS IN BAY STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Prompted by the rise of drug-resistant ``superbugs''
that are not killed by standard antibiotics, Massachusetts
officials and insurers have begun questioning doctors' prescribing
practices and warning that overuse and misuse of drugs may be
breeding the next generation of superbugs right here.
</P>
<P>
   Early state findings suggest that some doctors may be
contributing to overuse of drugs by prescribing them without seeing
the patient, or by giving in to patients' demands for antibiotics
even when they're not needed. Overuse of antibiotics increases the
chance that bacteria can breed new strains able to survive the drug
onslaught, rendering it ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   A survey carried out by the state agency that oversees Medicaid
showed that 44 percent of prescriptions written for 76,000 mostly
low income Mass Health members in 1999 were given without seeing
the patient in an office visit, said Dr. Annette Hanson, director
of the state Division of Medical Assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Most of these prescriptions were for ear infections in children,
which are often caused by so-called ``streptococcus'' bacteria that
are increasingly resistant to standard antibiotics, said Hanson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some doctors said the patients wanted the antibiotics `just in
case,' and others said the patients felt the doctor didn't care
about them unless they were given a prescription,'' Hanson said
Tuesday at a conference on the antibiotic resistance problem.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, part of an elaborate study on antibiotic resistance
being funded in Massachusetts by the federal government, also
showed that 90 percent of antibiotics were prescribed without a lab
test to determine what type of bacteria were involved. This
practice can lead to prescribing an unecessary or wrong antibiotic,
although for many childhood infections like those of the ear, it's
difficult to obtain a sample to test.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jonathan Finkelstein, a Harvard Medical School physician who
is principal investigator of the study, said the researchers will
take bacteria samples from patients around the state to determine
how widespread and serious the problem of drug-resistant bugs is.
That information, together with further surveys of how doctors are
prescribing antibiotics, will then be funneled into a plan to
educate doctors and consumers about how to use antibiotics
properly.
</P>
<P>
   The study, which received funding in January, comprises
researchers from Harvard Medical School, the Harvard School of
Public Health, the state Department of Public Health,
Harvard-Pilgrim Health Care and a number of other HMOs, said
Finkelstein.
</P>
<P>
   Although the ``miracle drugs'' like penicillin began
encountering resistant bugs almost as soon as they started saving
lives in the 1940s, the trend has worsened in recent years.
According to the ``antibiotic paradox,'' named by Dr. Stuart Levy
of Tufts University, organizer of the conference, the more
antibiotics are used the more likely they are to kill susceptible
bacteria, but encourage the growth of random mutants that aren't
vulnerable to the drug.
</P>
<P>
   Levy described the continuing appearance of drug-resistant
bacteria in hospitals and among the public, but said, ``I don't
think antibiotic resistance is inevitable'' if the drugs are used
wisely.
</P>
<P>
   Globally, the resistance problem is only beginning to be
measured, said Rosamund Williams, head of drug resistance
containment at the World Health Organization in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're horribly short of global data,'' said Williams, but she
mentioned some particularly worrying trends:
</P>
<P>
   -- Up to 70 pecent of streptococcus bugs are
penicillin-resistant in South Korea, while the
penicillin-resistance rate is 56 percent in the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
   -- Cure rates of malaria in Thailand have dropped steeply within
a few years after each new malaria drug has been introduced.
</P>
<P>
   -- The bug that causes gonorrhea has become resistant to
penicillin in the Western Pacific countries.
</P>
<P>
   The results are not only that infections become harder to treat,
but more expensive drugs are necessary, which many in developing
countries cannot afford. Consequently, said Williams, a cost
increase ``means no treatment, or treatment with the wrong drug.''
</P>
<P>
   Other factors worsening the problem are unregulated sales of
antibiotics in many countries, giving the wrong drug or dose or for
the wrong length of time, as well as people self-medicating with
drugs they accumulate or buy over-the-counter. Paradoxically she
said, ``30 percent of the world lacks access to essential
antibiotics like penicillin or chloramphenicol, but at the same
time, in the United States and Canada, 50 percent of outpatient
prescriptions for antibiotics are unnecessary.''
</P>
<P>
   And both of those statistics, she said, contribute to the
resistance problem.
</P>
<P>
   The conference, ``Antibiotic Resistant Infections: A Global
Problem with Local Solutions,'' was sponsored by the Mass DPH, the
Massachusetts Medical Society, the Alliance for Prudent Use of
Antibiotics and the American Association for World Health.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
