<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3639 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CAMPBELL-SENATE-HNS &LR;      05-02 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPBELL-SENATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     A LONGSHOT, CAMPBELL BELIEVES HE CAN WIN CALIF. SENATE SEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAN FREEDMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Behind in California's all-important money chase
and statewide polls, Republican Senate candidate Tom Campbell still
believes he can beat two-term veteran Dianne Feinstein.
</P>
<P>
   If his own polling shows a close race this fall, and ``it's a
good year for Republicans, I win,'' he told reporters at a luncheon
here.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell's dream scenario? Vice President Al Gore, the
presumptive Democratic presidential nominee, selects Feinstein to
be his running mate. ``That is a gift from heaven if it occurs,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The 47-year-old House member whose district runs through the
Silicon Valley said he intends to make to make foreign policy a
major fault line in his uphill bid to unseat Feinstein.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein backed the Clinton administration in its conduct of
the NATO air campaign over Serbia and Kosovo last year. Campbell, a
former Stanford University law professor, opposed it as an
unconstitutional exercise of the president's war-making powers.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell led a failed bid to put the House on record as either
declaring war or calling for an end to the air war.
</P>
<P>
   The United States had no business intervening in what was
essentially a ``civil war,'' Campbell said. Atrocities by the Serb
forces of Slobodan Milosevic were exaggerated and, he said, the
ethnic Albanians in Kosovo were also guilty of mass killing.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell also said the effort to halt international drug
trafficking has proven ineffective and more attention should be
paid to domestic demand for narcotics. While he supports
prosecution of drug traffickers, Campbell said he is open to making
drugs available to addicts and permitting marijuana for medicinal
use.
</P>
<P>
   The congressman said he opposes permanent normal trade relations
with China, known as PNTR in the world of Washington acronyms. A
decisive vote in the House is three weeks away.
</P>
<P>
   With a doctorate in economics from the University of Chicago,
Campbell argued that normalizing trade relations with China would,
in essence, give an OK to Chinese government subsidies of commerce
and industry.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Congress must renew trade privileges for China each
year.
</P>
<P>
   Approval of permanent trade relations would weaken Washington's
ability to police possible unfair trading practices by China,
Campbell said. Feinstein, in contrast, is a strong supporter of
giving China permanent trade status and has led the fight to get
China admitted to the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Most statewide polls show Feinstein leading Campbell. In the
March 7 primary _ when Democrats and Republicans appeared
side-by-side on the ballot _ Feinstein won 51 percent overall,
Campbell won 23 percent. He was the top Republican vote-getter in a
crowded field of GOP contenders.
</P>
<P>
   But Campbell said his last poll prior to the primary put him at
42 percent against Feinstein's 48 percent in a one-on-one matchup.
``That's really good,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the incumbent leads on the money front. From Feb. 17 to
the end of March, Feinstein took in $988,000, spent $360,000, and
reported about $2.2 million in the bank. In the same period,
Campbell raised $565,000 and spent nearly $700,000, leaving a
balance of $615,000.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, speaking Tuesday, said he has raised about $2.5
million. But it takes a minimum of $10 million to $12 million to
run a statewide campaign in huge state such as California, where
personal campaign appearances take a back seat to advertising on
television and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Campbell is planning a district-by-district approach to
campaigning, counting on local media coverage to get his message
across to voters. And he said he hopes to do well enough in
fund-raising to be competitive on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have tremendous room to grow,'' he said, a boyish grin
lighting up his face. ``She (Feinstein) really doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address dan(at)hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
