u w BC-PRIMARIES-NH-BOS &LR;      05-02 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIMARIES-NH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP PANEL WON'T GUARANTEE NEW HAMPSHIRE FIRST PRIMARY STATUS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A Republican Party advisory commission declined
Tuesday to guarantee that New Hampshire should hold the nation's
first presidential primary and also recommended switching the
Massachusetts vote from March 7 to May.
</P>
<P>
   Both moves drew immediate protests, and the proposal faces a
possible fight on the Republican convention floor this summer.
Massachusetts Secretary of State William Galvin called the
commission report ``an absurd proposal that will never be
approved'' by the full Republican National Convention. The report
calls for four rounds of primaries in which the smallest states go
first and the largest go last. Galvin has backed an alternative
plan to rotate regional primaries, which the commission rejected.
</P>
<P>
   The final decision also could be influenced by the party's
all-but-certain nominee, Texas Governor George W. Bush, who lost
the New Hampshire primary this year and has much sway over the
convention delegates. There has been concern about whether Bush
would use his influence with the advisory commission to end New
Hampshire's status of voting first, according to Galvin. But Bush
spokesman Ari Fleischer said, ``The governor didn't do that,''
noting that Bush has supported New Hampshire's first-in-the-nation
role.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Party so far has not tried to change New
Hampshire's status, creating the possibility that the state could
hold primaries for each party on different days.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican's 10-member Advisory Commission on the
Presidential Nominating Process, chaired by former Senator Bill
Brock of Tennessee, did not include any people from New England.
The proposal's fate will debated by the party's Rules Committee
next week in Indianapolis and is likely to be decided by delegates
to the Republican National Convention, where large states that
oppose the plan have much more power.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire Secretary of State William Gardner said he had not
been informed by the commission that the state's first-primary
status was left unprotected by the panel. Indeed, he cited a draft
report by the panel that guaranteed New Hampshire and the
first-caucus state of Iowa would lead the way as usual.
</P>
<P>
   The draft report, according to Gardner, said the panel was
``recognizing the tradition of Iowa and New Hampshire. We would
allow Iowa and New Hampshire to go first.''
</P>
<P>
   But the final report, released Tuesday afternoon, was changed.
``The Advisory Commission does not believe that the Iowa-New
Hampshire issue needs to be decided in conjunction with a reform
model; in fact, the majority of the commissioners feel that the
issue should be voted upon separately,'' the final report said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commission does not single out Iowa and New Hampshire for
either special treatment nor special inclusion,'' said RNC
spokesman Larry Purpuro.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is the brainchild of Basil Battaglia, chairman of the
Delaware Republican Party. Battaglia bombarded GOP officials with
100-page documents outlining what became known as the ``Delaware
plan.'' He said the commission chairman, Brock, ``fell in love with
the idea because it makes so much sense,'' and he predicted that
the Rules Committee would adopt it. Brock did not return a call
seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Battaglia said that he thought New Hampshire's effort
to retain its first-primary status ``is in trouble'' with the Rules
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Battaglia became a familiar player in the primary wars after he
fought with New Hampshire officials in 1996 about Delaware's effort
to trump the first-primary state. New Hampshire officials won a
promise from most of the presidential candidates not to campaign in
Delaware that year because Delaware wouldn't abide by New
Hampshire's demand for a week-long break between the first and
second primaries.
</P>
<P>
   The effort to revamp the primary schedule has been the subject
of debate for years and took on an added urgency as a result of
this year's primary schedule, when the nominees of both parties
were all but certain by March 7, leaving a months-long campaign
vacuum until the national conventions this summer. Many states
jockeyed to hold early primaries, resulting in a bunched-up
schedule that favored the best-financed candidates.
</P>
<P>
   California, which had been holding its primary in June, voted on
March 7 this year in order to have more impact on the race. But
under the plan California would once again be relegated to a June
vote. That upset California Secretary of State Bill Jones, who
served on the advisory commission but was unable to persuade his
colleagues to support the regional rotating primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't spend all that time moving California to the front
just to be in the back permanently,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of the commission plan said it would be fair because
it would encourage more ``retail'' politics in small states during
the early stages of the primaries, providing a boost to candidates
who initially have fewer resources. That would give longshot
candidates a better chance of using momentum in early primaries to
collect funds for the later and most expensive stages of the
campaigns in larger states.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would leave 47 percent of the delegates to be chosen in
June, an effort to address concerns that the race would be over
before the largest states participate.
</P>
<P>
   But representatives of larger states said the plan was
unworkable because it would require candidates to travel across the
nation to an array of small states and permanently put larger
states at the end of the process, when the race is more likely to
be meaningless.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
