<DOCNO> NYT20000502.0260 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3644 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-ROBERDS-MAIN0503     05-02 1235
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBERDS-MAIN0503 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Financially plagued Roberds closes its doors
 &HT;    By Tim Tresslar
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST CARROLTON, Ohio _ Strapped for cash and struggling to keep
its stores filled with merchandise, home furnishings retailer
Roberds Inc. on Tuesday closed stores and distribution centers in
the Dayton and Atlanta areas and prepared to go out of business.
</P>
<P>
   Roberds, a West Carrollton-based retail chain that first sought
bankruptcy protection from creditors in January, filed a petition
Tuesday with the U.S. Bankruptcy Court calling for it to cease
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Closure of the chain's 15 stores in Ohio, Indiana and Georgia
will cost 1,300 jobs, including 650 in Roberds' Dayton market,
store officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Roberds closed the stores so employees can take inventory and
prepare for a liquidation sale. Though the retail chain hasn't
selected a liquidator or determined when the sale will begin, the
company hopes to conclude the liquidation sale within 90 days.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Executive Melvin H. Baskin assured customers waiting for
purchased items that Roberds would try to provide them with either
merchandise or refunds. But he also asked customers to be patient
as management decides how to handle these claims. He hopes to have
more information for consumers within the next few weeks, he said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Baskin, however, stopped short of pledging that all Roberds
customers will get either the money or goods owed to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no guarantee,'' he said. ``There is likelihood,
strong likelihood.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberd's announcement Tuesday ended speculation about the
company's future that surfaced after it postponed its annual
shareholders meeting Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Baskin said cash-flow problems and an inability to get furniture
and appliances from suppliers forced Roberds to abandon its
reorganization efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Turning around the financially beleaguered company hinged on
attracting shoppers back to the stores and getting them the
merchandise they wanted, Baskin said. Since the bankruptcy filing,
though, vendors have been reluctant to supply the chain with
merchandise, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The inability to reach credit terms with vendors so Roberds
would have merchandise to sell has been one of the most frustrating
aspects of the reorganization, Baskin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Vendors) were very cautious,'' Baskin said. ``We were quite
surprised that they did not stand behind us to the level that we
thought they would.''
</P>
<P>
   Baskin said the Roberds board voted unanimously Thursday to
close the company. They had exhausted all other options, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The genuine bottom line is we ran out of cash,'' he said. ``We
simply did not have any more money. So that left us with no
alternative.''
</P>
<P>
   Baskin said the arrival of Best Buy, Circuit City and Rhodes
Furniture into the Dayton market made it more competitive and
contributed to Roberds' struggle.
</P>
<P>
   However, he would not blame Roberds' problems on a single
factor, including his management.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a series of events over a number of years that have
brought this company to where it is right now,'' said Baskin, a
former Federated Department Stores executive. ``My presence was an
attempt to turn the business around so that this would not happen.
I think that speaks to some degree for itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberds has seen annual revenues dip from $342 million in 1996
to $287 million in 1999. The company also has experienced four
consecutive years of net losses. Sales for stores opened a year or
more have declined over the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   When Roberds filed for Chapter 11 protection in January,
executives announced plans to exit the money-losing Cincinnati and
Florida markets, concentrating instead on Dayton and Atlanta.
Initially, management had hoped to turn the company around and
emerge from bankruptcy within 90 days. The company in January
listed assets of $142.5 million and debts of $117.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, executives met with employees to announce Roberds'
impending closure and to hear worker concerns about issues such as
medical benefits. Baskin said the decision to close the stores was
a difficult one, but he considers watching out for the employees to
be a top priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurts a lot,'' he said, his eyes moist. ``These are
people's lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Baskin said the company has tapped officials in Ohio, Indiana
and Georgia to supply workers with help as they lose their jobs. He
declined to discuss employee severance benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Employees at the company's headquarters and its flagship store,
both in West Carrollton, declined comment as they left Tuesday's
meeting. Uniformed security guards patrolled the store's parking
lot, turning away customers who wanted to know about undelivered
merchandise or refunds.
</P>
<P>
   Baskin was unsure how much Roberds owes in furniture or refunds.
Some of the credit card purchases have been paid back, he said.
Still, the company has several million dollars in outstanding
merchandise due to customers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot predict how much cash we will generate from the
going out of business sales or from sales of our various
properties,'' Baskin said. ``We therefore cannot predict at this
time how much money will be available to pay our various creditors
or whether any funds will be left for shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are confident, however, that our current course of action
is the best option available under these circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Barkin, an assistant U.S. Bankruptcy Trustee said,
customers, along with taxes and administrative expenses, typically
are considered priority creditors.
</P>
<P>
   In the Dayton market, Roberds closed stores in Beavercreek,
Piqua, Springfield, Vandalia, West Carrollton and Richmond, Ind.,
as well as a distribution center in Fairborn. The company also will
close seven stores and a distribution center in Georgia. The
company already had planned to close a store in Atlanta, Ga., as
part of its reorganization effort.
</P>
<P>
   Creditors had hoped Roberds would emerge successfully from
bankruptcy proceedings, said Lawrence Walter, co-counsel for the
unsecured creditors committee. But he lauded Roberds' decision to
close before it exhausts all of its assets and can no longer pay
creditors, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they've made the appropriate decision, no matter how
lamentable that may be,'' he said. ``I can't fault them.''
</P>
<P>
   He looks for the creditors to still get some of their money
back, though he is unsure how much.
</P>
<P>
   Roberds executives said Tuesday they look for Nasdaq to remove
Roberds' stock from the exchange's small cap market. Trading of
Roberds' shares (NASDAQ:RBDSQ) halted in January after the company
filed for reorganization protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not know what market, if any, will exist for our
stock,'' Baskin said.
</P>
<P>
   Those holding the company's 6.2 million shares of common stock
are considered unsecured creditors and whether they can recoup any
of their investment remains in question. Shareholders include
Chairman Don Wright, Deborah Fletcher, widow of Roberds co-founder
Kenneth Fletcher, Baskin and a handful of high-profile Dayton
business executives.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Roberds' recent problems, Baskin said the company made
its mark in the local retail industry by offering strong customer
service.
</P>
<P>
   ``With that, Roberds leaves a powerful legacy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
