<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BONFIRE-PROBE (College Station, Texas) _ A commission
investigating the collapse of a giant bonfire at Texas A&AMP;M blames
the deadly accident on weak oversight of the building of a
``complex and dangerous structure.'' The collapse killed 12
students and injured 27 others. By JOHN WILLIAMS.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-LABELLA (Washington) _ Former federal prosecutor Charles
LaBella, who headed a Justice Department task force to investigate
possible campaign finance violations, outlines why he urged the
appointment of an independent counsel to investigate President
Clinton and Vice President Al Gore. By MARK HELM. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   MISSILE-DEFENSE (Washington) _ Three senior members of the
Russian legislature warn U.S. lawmakers that if the White House
follows through on plans to build a national missile defense
system, the U.S.-Russia relationship will be severely destabilized.
One lawmaker, Alexander Shabanov, said the missile defense program
could spark ``another Cold War,'' and he warned of ``very
dangerous'' repercussions. By ERIC ROSENBERG. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TRADE (Washington)  &Cx1f; _ Despite divisions in Congress, the
vote on permanent normal trade relations for China is likely to be
a done deal. The trade status, sought by Beijing and the Clinton
administration, would give Chinese goods the same low-tariff access
to U.S. markets as products from most other nations. Under existing
law, Congress must renew these trade privileges for China each
year. By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   BANKRUPTCY-REFORM (Washington) _ Four liberal lawmakers join
labor and consumer advocates in denouncing a bankruptcy reform bill
they say punishes working Americans hit by catastrophic illness.
Sens. Paul Wellstone, D-Minn., Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., and Russell
Feingold, D-Wis., and Rep. Jerrold Nadler, D-N.Y., say the bill
would make it more difficult for borrowers in financial trouble to
avoid paying off their debts by declaring bankruptcy. By AUSTIN
ZALKIN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GOP-PRIMARIES (Washington) _ A Republican Party commission
headed by former Sen. Bill Brock is recommending an overhaul of
primary elections. Under the plan, smaller states would vote first
in primaries staggered from March 1 to June 1. The plan would put
larger states such as California and New York back at the end of
the line. By DAN FREEDMAN. (Also filed in the ``w'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-CRIME (Atlanta) _ Vice President Al Gore proposes a
crime-fighting measure that would give states money to conduct drug
tests on parolees and probationers. He also calls for using federal
money to hire more police officers. By BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPBELL-SENATE (Washington) _ Behind in California's
all-important money chase and statewide polls, Republican Senate
candidate Tom Campbell still believes he can beat two-term veteran
Dianne Feinstein. If his own polling shows a close race this fall,
and ``it's a good year for Republicans, I win,'' the congressman
from the Silicon Valley says. By DAN FREEDMAN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   Marianne Means in on vacation. Her column will resume Monday,
May 15.
</P>
