<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BURCH-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIGER OPTING FOR NELSON NOT A SNUB TO COLONIAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ By Friday, the worst-kept secret on the PGA
Tour will become public knowledge. Tiger Woods, barring unforeseen
circumstances, will commit to play in next week's GTE Byron Nelson
Classic for a fourth consecutive year.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the uncomfortable comparisons will resume for MasterCard
Colonial officials.
</P>
<P>
   Folks in Fort Worth have known since February that Woods, the
lone golfer capable of elevating a tour event into a civic
happening, would be jetting off to Germany during Colonial week
(May 18-21) to defend a title at the Deutsche Bank-SAP Open on the
European Tour. For those keeping score, that's three consecutive
misses on the Tiger trail for the guys in plaid jackets, while
their Nelson counterparts continue to bat 1.000 in landing the
world's top-ranked golfer.
</P>
<P>
   That fact, compounded by rumor and innuendo, has convinced some
local golf fans that Woods has scratched Colonial from his PGA Tour
schedule for the next millennium. They envision a permanent Woods
boycott, turning the 54-year-old invitational event into the John
Deere Classic or B.C. Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I've heard that, too,'' said Clark Martin, a member of
the Colonial board of governors and a former club president.
</P>
<P>
   Martin punctuated his response with a wry smile and a roll of
his eyes. That's because such sentiment is in direct opposition to
feedback Colonial officials have received from Woods'
representatives. Those exchanges have centered on scheduling
conflicts, rather than negative perceptions about the tournament,
as reasons why the PGA Tour's top gate attraction has not set foot
in Fort Worth since 1997. That's why Colonial officials envision a
return engagement. And soon.
</P>
<P>
   Colonial tournament chairman Phil Thomas spoke confidently about
the possibility of Tiger sightings at ``Hogan's Alley'' in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would come close to betting that Tiger would be in this
field next year, unless he wins again in Germany,'' Thomas said,
noting that a repeat triumph probably would trigger another
European title defense during the week of the 2001 Colonial. ``I'm
not concerned about him \Rnever\S coming back. I don't think we're
on his bad list. I firmly believe he'll be here next year, and we'd
love to have him.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect Woods to tip his hand about scheduling plans. He
has yet to commit to the 2000 Nelson, much less the 2001 Colonial.
It's his policy not to acknowledge upcoming tournament appearances
until the Friday before the event, the minimum advance notice
required under PGA Tour rules.
</P>
<P>
   Little wonder, then, that Woods was noncommittal when asked
about a possible return to Colonial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see,'' he said. ``Maybe some day, I'll be able to put my
name on that trophy.''
</P>
<P>
   What does that mean? Only Tiger knows.
</P>
<P>
   The only certainty about Woods and Colonial is that there were
hiccups in their initial encounter, which occurred at the apex of
the ``Tigermania'' craze during his rookie season. Colonial
officials began circulating Woods' name on their unofficial]
commitment list a month before the 1997 tournament, raising
eyebrows from agents who preferred a last-minute release of such
information.
</P>
<P>
   Once in town, Woods was greeted by a national media contingent
interested in chronicling his pretournament meeting with Fuzzy
Zoeller, who had uttered racially insensitive remarks in an
ill-advised attempt at humor after Woods' victory at the Masters.
Colonial officials went public with a suggestion that the two play
a bury-the-hatchet practice round, which never materialized. From
all indications, the idea was better received by Zoeller than
Woods.
</P>
<P>
   During the final round, Woods surrendered a share of the lead
with double bogeys at No. 9 and No. 17, ending his three-event
winning streak. Afterward, he refused interview requests.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, Woods said, the off-course distractions he faced
during his six-event winning streak this season were ``not as bad,
or anywhere close, to what it was \Rlike\S at Colonial in 1997.
That was interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Against this backdrop, some surmise that Woods has written off
Colonial. I disagree.
</P>
<P>
   Truth be known, both Woods and Zoeller expressed gratitude to
club officials for their professionalism in handling their
clear-the-air luncheon summit in 1997. And, until proved otherwise,
I'll buy scheduling conflicts as an ongoing reason for Woods
skipping Colonial. Here's why:
</P>
<P>
   Woods vowed to significantly vary his 1998 schedule from events
he played as a rookie to placate the tournaments he skipped in
1997. In doing so, he skipped the 1998 Colonial. Last year, he
accepted a $750,000 appearance fee to play in Germany during
Colonial week, then won the event. This year, he's defending that
title. Perfectly reasonable, up and down the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we've ever been told, in terms of Tiger, is that he's had
scheduling conflicts,'' said Scott Corpening, a tournament
committee member. ``I'd be absolutely amazed if he has an ax to
grind with Colonial.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Colonial deserves the benefit of the doubt in the saga
of the missing Tiger. But if Woods loses in Germany and skips Fort
Worth in 2001, it's time to start searching for that ax.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
