<HEADER>
A3653 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-WOOING-STUDENTS-ART-2     05-02 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOOING-STUDENTS-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER MAKING ADMISSIONS OFFERS, COLLEGES VIE FOR SELECT STUDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT18 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JACQUES STEINBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Albert Dixon III, 18, thought he was dreaming when he was
awakened at 7 on a March morning by an admissions officer calling
from Williams College. She informed him that a thick letter
announcing his acceptance was on its way, as was a free round-trip
ticket to the campus, just to check out Williams one more time.
</P>
<P>
   Making his decision more difficult, Dixon, an aspiring history
teacher from San Francisco, had already received a more attractive
offer of free tuition from Morehouse College, a historically black
institution in Atlanta. (Williams had offered him only loans.)
</P>
<P>
   And then there was Wesleyan University, which had used a softer
sell _ a call of good wishes from a current student _ but had urged
him to attend a celebration last month for accepted seniors. He
left the campus in Middletown, Conn., smitten with the thick french
fries in the cafeteria and moved by an impromptu discussion of the
Holocaust that began after a videotape snapped in the middle of a
history class.
</P>
<P>
   For Dixon, who had spent the better part of a year pleading with
colleges to accept him, the role reversal was jarring.
</P>
<P>
   The 30 days from April 1, when such offers are generally
proferred, to May 1, when such decisions are due, is a time unlike
any other in the college admissions season, at least for a select
group of several thousand students. They become the
decision-makers, screening potential candidates against a yardstick
of their own idiosyncrasies, while the officers are reduced to
supplicants, promoting their schools as they brace for  &QL; 
rejections from many of those they wanted most.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a courting period,'' said Rafael Figueroa, an associate
dean of admissions at Wesleyan. ``You're telling them, `This could
go places. We could have a great thing, you and me.' Then they turn
around and tell you, `Have a nice life. I'm going to Brown.'''
</P>
<P>
   Little wonder, then, that Dixon _ who is black and whose high
College Board score of 1480, out of 1600, belied his B average _
felt like a prized athlete throughout April, so often was he plied
with messages from admissions officers, professors and students at
the six universities where he was accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Only the most sought-after candidates to top colleges receive
plane tickets from faraway places, but, as is the case at dozens of
colleges, all 1,850 students accepted to Wesleyan were to have
received at least one follow-up call, if not several, because a
letter of admission is no longer regarded as sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   This admissions season was the most competitive for the nation's
elite colleges, including Wesleyan, a lush-green liberal arts
college where enough students applied to fill the 715-member Class
of 2004 10 times. Flooding the class was an especially long
pipeline of high school graduates, many of them convinced that
attending a selective institution provided a guarantee of success
in life.
</P>
<P>
   But the proliferation of good applicants did not mean that
Wesleyan could let the responses just roll in. Hedging their bets,
many seniors like Dixon had applied to more than 10 colleges, which
only served to elevate the students' anxiety _ and the
institutions' _ as the students deliberated throughout April.
</P>
<P>
   The admissions officers, at Wesleyan as elsewhere, were uneasy
because they were intent on engineering a student body that was a
little better than last year's, to say nothing of those of rival
schools _ with ``better'' defined to include students with high
College Board scores, roots in minority communities, leadership
skills, science aptitude and the ability to play the oboe or second
base.
</P>
<P>
   Colleges like Wesleyan reason that assembling such a class can
only elevate the experiences of students and faculty, while
providing fringe benefits like a prouder alumni body (which may
give more money) and perhaps a higher ranking in closely read
guidebooks like those by U.S. News &AMP; World Report.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it often seemed to admissions officers at Wesleyan, as
at Amherst and Williams, that they were pursuing many of the same
1,500 teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   One of them is Jordan Goldman, 17, an aspiring writer from New
York City's Staten Island who has already collaborated with the
novelist Richard Price. Throughout the year, Goldman asked himself
if he needed the imprint of an Ivy League institution like Brown,
or whether he would be happier at a smaller, though still
prestigious, university like Wesleyan.
</P>
<P>
   He also could not dismiss an alluring proposition from New York
University, which dangled four trips to Europe as part of a
study-abroad program.
</P>
<P>
   And Jannely Almonte, 18, a resident of the South Bronx who
attends a prep school on scholarship in New Jersey, had to sift
through nine acceptance letters from selective colleges, as well as
their financial aid packages.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the unending flurry of e-mail messages from
professors and undergraduates that left her most confused: when she
returned from a trip to Columbia University last week, she found a
phone message from someone at Wesleyan encouraging her to call with
any questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like a Michael Jordan trading card from his rookie
season,'' Almonte, who wants to study biology, said during a visit
to Wesleyan last month. ``The schools are putting in a lot of
effort to get me while I'm in mint condition.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All the attention makes me feel good,'' she said. ``But I feel
bad. I have to think of some way to let them down easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the seniors worried that picking the wrong college might
darken the rest of their lives, with some waiting until Monday
night, within hours of the midnight deadline, to mail out their
answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really see this decision as monumental,'' said Stephen
Singer, director of college counseling at Horace Mann School in New
York. ``You say to them, `There's no way you can screw this
decision up.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes them feel better,'' he added. ``For a minute.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Wesleyan had been hoping to persuade 650 to 675 of the students
it accepted to attend, leaving room to take as many as 50 others
off the waiting list in May and June. (By Tuesday, deposits from
656 were in hand, with perhaps two dozen more expected in
Wednesday's mail.)
</P>
<P>
   Those taken off the waiting list will be chosen, in part, to
``correct imbalances'' in the class, whether on the football team,
in science laboratories or among the ranks of Asian-American or
Hispanic-American students, when their representation in the new
class is compared with last year's, said Gregory Pyke, the senior
associate dean of admissions.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   To insure that its acceptances were accepted, Wesleyan employed
gestures as large as a phone call from a department chairman, to
jottings as small as ``Come to Wes!'' and ``Yes!'', which the dean
of admissions, Nancy Hargrave Meislahn, scribbled on all 1,500
letters of acceptance mailed out in late March. (About 350 other
students had been accepted early.)
</P>
<P>
   The officers plotted every detail, including when a dean might
contact a desirable student to make a pitch. (If the call came too
early, would Wesleyan appear desperate? If it was too late, would
Swarthmore have already gotten there?)
</P>
<P>
   They even hired a recent graduate _ his job is so new he does
not have a title _ to make e-mail contact on behalf of Wesleyan
with ``hot prospects,'' making sure, for example, that a student
who identified himself as Jewish knew how to reach the campus
rabbi.
</P>
<P>
   To help the students deliberate, Wesleyan created a list-serve _
a mass e-mail directory in which a message posted by one registered
applicant is automatically sent to all _ in which the accepted
students counseled each other, joined by the occasional Wesleyan
undergraduate.
</P>
<P>
   Reading the dispatches on the list-serve, in which 200 high
school seniors posted as many as 400 messages a day, was like
looking through a microscope. Late at night from home, the high
school seniors dissected Wesleyan, along with Brown, Amherst,
Williams, Vassar and Dartmouth, seeking to determine whether the
number of Nobel laureates on the faculty (none at Wesleyan) was as
important as whether dogs are permitted in residence halls (they
are not.).
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Goldman, the budding screenwriter, used the list-serve to hash
out his own decision, agonizing for eight long pages on April 17
over whether he should choose Wesleyan, ``Ivy U,'' ``Big City U,''
or a college he identified as ``Unnamed Gorgeous Small Liberal Arts
School.''
</P>
<P>
   In the final sentence, he revealed his decision: Wesleyan.
</P>
<P>
   What impressed him most, Goldman said, was that the university
had allowed students to put up posters during the celebration for
accepted applicants that took issue with the weekend being
alcohol-free _ not because they supported underage drinking, but
because they felt students might be getting a sanitized portrait.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman wrote that he was struck by the ``absolute free
expression'' and that ``you won't find that an Ivy League school.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldman _ who was accepted by Johns Hopkins and Vassar, but not
Brown or the University of Pennsylvania _ was so persuasive that at
least 25 seniors reported that his dispatch had made the difference
in their own decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can retire,'' Figueroa said. ``Jordan can take over from
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Almonte, the prep school student in New Jersey by way of the
Bronx, managed in early April to jettison Trinity, Union College,
the University of Rochester, Connecticut College and Haverford,
leaving only Columbia and Wesleyan.
</P>
<P>
   Because her mother is a home health aide with a spare salary,
she had expected to go with the best financial offer. Though
Wesleyan and Columbia were close, Wesleyan was offering more money
up front, with Columbia tying up more aid in loans.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike Goldman, Amonte, a Dominican whose parents did not
attend college, decided that an Ivy League education was too
important to pass up.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother, my grandmother, my aunts and uncles, they always
expect me to choose the best,'' she said. ``And according to their
mind, Ivy League is the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Wesleyan also lost out on Katie Stockhammer, a straight-A soccer
captain from Florida, who had impressed the admissions committee in
March by maintaining her grades while being treated for cancer. She
chose Swarthmore, outside of Philadelphia, in part because it was
closer to a big city.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Dixon felt like a three-pronged wishbone tugged by Morehouse,
Williams and Wesleyan?
</P>
<P>
   Though Morehouse's offer of a free ride would have eased the
financial burden on his father, an executive at a software company,
Dixon and his dad agreed that the education he'd receive at
Williams or Wesleyan would be superior.
</P>
<P>
   But which one?
</P>
<P>
   A week ago Sunday, over a slice of the special lemon pound cake
that his mother had prepared for his birthday, Dixon summoned his
parents to the kitchen table.
</P>
<P>
   ``Williams is a school that most parents and teachers think is
great, simply because it's rated high academically,'' Dixon
explained. ``But socially, it's out in the middle of nowhere. And
it's really conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   Wesleyan, he concluded, was not only more liberal and diverse,
``but in the classes I attended, even the kids I thought wouldn't
be smart or intelligent in a conversation ended up having some
pretty good things to say.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there were those Wesleyan french fries, which his dad
remembered as fondly as he did.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Dixon decided to head back for four years' worth of
second helpings.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ADMISSIONS MAZE
</P>
<P>
   Admission to elite colleges is more competitive than at any time
in history. The New York Times asked Wesleyan University in
Middletown, Conn., to give a reporter full access to its selection
procedure. It did so, permitting him to read applications and
attend admissions meetings, on the condition that applicants'
identities not be revealed during the process. This is the third,
and last, of the articles. The previous articles can be found on
the Web at
http://www.nytimes.com/yr/mo/day/national/index-education.html.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
