<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3655 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e BC-TV-SHELFLIFE-SPI &LR;      05-02 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SHELFLIFE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY THE NETWORKS DON'T SMELL IT WHEN SHOWS GO BAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The answer is term limits. And the question has nothing to do
with Strom Thurmond.
</P>
<P>
   No indeed. It has to do with the shelf life of TV shows.
Specifically, a statute of limitations. Should a series be produced
with a termination date already in mind? And should networks offer
a warning when they introduce their new shows? Something like:
``Welcome to `ER.' We hope you enjoy the 44 episodes that we plan
to produce over the next two seasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Think about it. If shows came stamped with an expiration date,
like a gallon of milk, we'd avoid the sour-smelling puddle of ennui
that seeps out from under the TV table whenever a show starts to
get long in the tooth. This feeling of detachment, characterized by
an uncontrollable urge to see what else is on, varies from one show
to the next. But, aside from the occasional exception like ``The
Simpsons,'' it's pretty much inevitable. With ``Ally McBeal,'' it
happened early in the second season. With ``ER,'' it was season
four. Or maybe five.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever. It's as predictable as green on cheese. Like it or
not, a TV show is perishable, just like broccoli. It eventually
becomes unappetizing, and ultimately unconsumable. At this point,
we tend to throw the food out. But networks will serve the rank,
the stale and the moldy without a moment's hesitation.
</P>
<P>
   It's because no one is checking to see when a good show has gone
bad, least of all the viewers. We get hooked when things are good,
when the show is crackling with witty dialogue, clever plot twists
and great chemistry. We expect it to remain good because no one
told us that the last decent idea the show ever had was used up a
couple seasons back, just before the original writers and producers
departed to start another series. That's why last week's plot
seemed remarkably like one that ran during the show's second
season, only with different characters in the key positions.
</P>
<P>
   In other countries, long-running shows _ the kind that go on for
five, six, seven seasons _ are scarcer than homely people on The
WB. In England, for instance, no one really worries about a series
overstaying its welcome, because they don't stay long. Two or three
seasons, maybe four, and it's on to something else.
</P>
<P>
   That probably would have been a suitable life expectancy for an
ensemble series like ``Party of Five,'' which ends its six-season
run Wednesday night on Fox. I ceased being a regular watcher two
seasons ago after Charlie, flush with his victory over Hodgkin's
disease, met a stripper and got her pregnant. It seemed that the
writers were reaching, grasping, clawing to keep the story of the
orphaned Salinger siblings viable. I remember thinking at the time
that no family could possibly experience as much melodrama in a
year as the Salingers did in 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Rosie O'Donnell, who claims to have seen every episode of
``Party of Five,'' I packed it in just about the time Julia got
back into Stanford. I missed, thank heaven, Julia's newest
ill-starred relationship, Charlie's proposal of marriage to Kirsten
(she said yes), Bailey's proposal of marriage to Sarah (she said
no), Charlie and Kirsten's wedding, and Claudia's losing her
virginity. Eeew. I'd rather remember Claudia as the
wiser-than-her-years moral compass who kept the rest of the gang
centered.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is, you'll never get a producer to admit that a show has
lost its edge. As long as the studio is willing to pay a handsome
sum _ usually in the mid to high six figures each season _ not too
many producers would have the artistic courage to follow along when
his muse decides to take a sabbatical.
</P>
<P>
   And so greatness, or near-greatness, begets mediocrity, as good
shows peter out after passing what should have been their natural
expiration dates. Granted, it's impossible to know exactly when a
show will lose it. But doesn't it make sense to decide up front
that a show will have a finite run of, say, three or four seasons?
That way, the ending might come before the wheels start to fall
off.
</P>
<P>
   The inherent lunacy of term limits is that you just don't cancel
a show, no matter how tired, if people are still tuning in. ``ER''
is rarely hitting on all cylinders these days, but it remains the
favorite drama series in America because viewers have simply become
conditioned to tuning in on Thursdays at 10. Still, I can think of
several new shows that are infinitely more appealing right now,
notably ``The West Wing,'' ``Roswell'' and ``Once and Again,'' but
NBC recently renewed ``ER'' through the 2003-2004 season, assuring
it of at least a 10-year run.
</P>
<P>
   ``ER'' is the exception to a rule that requires most series to
disappear after a brief time in the spotlight. So the idea of
predetermining a show's lifespan is counterintuitive in an industry
set up to perpetuate an economic model that anticipates a large
failure rate. Without this model, the industry would collapse under
the weight of too many successful shows preventing new pilots from
getting on the air.
</P>
<P>
   But these successes are measured in quantity, not quality. Once
a show gets four seasons in, it has enough episodes to be
syndicated, which is where the real money is. If some network
executive were to decree that the premise of a certain show seems
doable for only three seasons before it runs out of steam, the
whole syndication bonanza is out the window.
</P>
<P>
   That's the biggest problem with term limits, and the reason
it'll never happen in this country until the networks put art
before the dollar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
