<HEADLINE>
NEW CHIEF NAMED IN POWER SHIFT AT POP POWERHOUSE
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a long-expected power shift, Antonio Reid was
formally named Tuesday as the new chief executive of Arista
Records, the 25-year-old pop powerhouse that for months has been
bracing for the departure of its founder and longtime leader, Clive
Davis.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement by the record label's parent, BMG
Entertainment, ended what had been a long-running and uncommonly
public struggle over the replacement of Davis, 67, an old-fashioned
music industry titan who nurtured artists like Janis Joplin, Barry
Manilow, Whitney Houston and Carlos Santana.
</P>
<P>
   Reid, 43, chief of his own Atlanta-based label, LaFace Records,
said Tuesday that he had discussed his appointment with Davis. It
remained unclear what sort of role Davis would play in a
transition.
</P>
<P>
   Davis was noticeably muted Tuesday in his comments about his
replacement, who will take over in early July after Davis' own
contract ends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though I regret the imposition of the Bertelsmann retirement
age policy, it's time now to turn to a new and vital chapter in
this fast-changing world of music,'' Davis said in a statement he
issued after declining to be interviewed. He added that he was
looking at offers to start his own record label, including a
potential deal with BMG.
</P>
<P>
   BMG Entertainment said that LaFace Records would be consolidated
with Arista through BMG's purchase of the remaining 50 percent of
LaFace that it did not own.
</P>
<P>
   Consolidation could lead to expansion because of plans to
increase Arista's reach into genres like Latin music, said Reid and
Strauss Zelnick, chief executive of BMG Entertainment. ``Neither
one of us expects to go through the unfortunately typical process
of roster reduction and consolidation that new label presidents
often go through,'' Zelnick said.
</P>
<P>
   With gross revenues of about $425 million, Arista is expected to
achieve record profits by the end of its fiscal year in June,
partly on the strength of Santana's best-selling album
``Supernatural.''
</P>
<P>
   But Reid said that Arista could probably improve its
performance. ``We intend to make Arista the home for many Latin
artists, record producers and Latin superstars,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Reid, the son of a Cincinnati seamstress who got his musical
start as a drummer for a group called the Deele, helped create
LaFace Records 11 years ago, cultivating Atlanta's thriving hip-hop
and urban music scene with performers like Toni Braxton, TLC, Usher
and OutKast. He founded that label with Babyface Edmonds, a
left-handed guitarist from the Deele. Edmonds is to head his own
record label, which will be called Joe Lies Music. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
