r s BC-BBA-RANGERS-NOTES-TEX     05-02 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ As the Rangers prepare to negotiate with
Las Vegas officials, the Florida House of Representatives passed a
bill Monday that would provide $75 million in tax money to upgrade
the state's spring training facilities. The bill must still be
passed by the Senate and signed by Gov. Jeb Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' facility in Port Charlotte, Fla., is among those
that would receive financing. Charlotte County officials recently
asked the Rangers for a wish list of improvements that would keep
them there after their lease expires next year.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers vice president John McMichael said the club is looking
for increased storage space in the major-league clubhouse, a
permanent weight room in the minor-league facility, meeting rooms
and a renovated press box.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers and five other teams _ Los Angeles Dodgers, Tampa
Bay Devil Rays, Baltimore Orioles, Houston Astros and Toronto Blue
Jays _ are considering moving their spring training facilities to
Las Vegas in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still working on that,'' McMichael said. ``We're talking
among ourselves, and they're still looking at projections,
revenues, how much everything will cost. We're preparing to
negotiate with them, and they're preparing to negotiate with us.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Rangers stay in Port Charlotte and use state money to
upgrade the facility, the bill requires that they sign a 15-year
lease and agree to pay for half the costs of improvements.  &QL; 
Palmeiro returns
</P>
<P>
   Rafael Palmeiro returned to the Rangers' lineup last night, even
though he's still bothered by a strained left hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've missed enough games,'' Palmeiro said. ``I'm sure I'm
risking something, but anytime you go out there, you're risking
something.''
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Danny Wheat said Palmeiro played with a strained
hamstring early last season and only missed one game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He went back out there while it was still bothering him, but
after a couple of games, he was fine,'' Wheat said. ``He's shown me
he knows how to protect it and play.''  &QL; 
Other injury news
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Justin Thompson played catch in the outfield and felt no
pain in his left shoulder. He'll test the shoulder again today with
a throwing session in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Greer, on the disabled list after undergoing ankle
surgery, has begun running in the outfield and hitting balls off a
tee. He reported no problems with the ankle, but his hamstring is
not quite 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Catalanotto (torn groin muscle) is walking without pain
but is still limited in his workouts. He's going to be out awhile.
 &QL; 
Big start for Clark
</P>
<P>
   Manager Johnny Oates does not hide the fact that tonight is a
big start for Mark Clark. The Rangers' fifth starter has allowed 11
runs in 61/3 innings over his past two starts, and Oates is
considering starting a left-hander _ either Doug Davis or Matt
Perisho _ against Oakland on Sunday. In that scenario, Rick
Helling, who normally would pitch Sunday, would be moved to Monday
against Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time, we have to make decisions,'' Oates said. ``I'd like
nothing better than Mark to pitch well and earn a chance to go back
out there in four or five days. It makes us a better ballclub if he
pitches well.''  &QL; 
Early work for Mateo
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers held extra early batting practice yesterday for the
second time on the road trip. Ruben Mateo was there, as he was
Friday in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to work out early, the first day in a city,'' Mateo
said. ``I want to keep on doing what I'm doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Mateo went into last night's game with eight hits in his past 21
at-bats, raising his average to a season-high .281.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to say I'm not happy, but I would feel better if
the team was winning,'' Mateo said. ``It doesn't matter if you're
doing well ... it would be much better if the team was winning and
I was putting up numbers.''  &QL; 
Canseco likely to miss series
</P>
<P>
   Jose Canseco was scratched from the Tampa Bay lineup yesterday
because of tightness in his right calf muscle. Canseco has been
bothered by that and a strained left hamstring muscle since spring
training. He is not expected to play in any of the three games
against the Rangers.
nn
</P>
