<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-THIRD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS USING PLATOON AT THIRD BASE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ The Rangers are trying to find a way to
get their pitching staff down to 11 pitchers and keep Mike Lamb and
Tom Evans as a platoon at third base for the entire season.
</P>
<P>
   Much depends on what they do with pitchers Mark Clark and Matt
Perisho. But having Evans and Lamb share third-base duties seems to
be the Rangers' best answer at a troubling position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to Johnny \ROates\S about something along those
lines,'' general manager Doug Melvin said. ``If we can get down to
11 pitchers and keep pitching effectively, it would be nice to have
that extra bat.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangers third basemen went into last night's game hitting .224
with one home run and eight runs batted in. Lamb, a left-handed
hitter, and Evans, a right-handed hitter, have been platooning at
third since Frank Catalanotto went on the disabled list with a
strained groin muscle.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had 11 pitchers and both those guys on the team, you'd
have one guy \RLamb\S known for his bat and another \REvans\S known
for his glove,'' Melvin said. ``It would be nice to have both on
the team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have some time to make that decision because
Catalanotto is expected to need at least two more weeks before he's
ready to return. That gives Lamb and Evans time to catch Oates' eye
and prove they belong in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, they're both going to get a chance to play as much
as possible,'' Oates said. ``It will depend on if I need a 12th
pitcher more than a backup third baseman.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the Rangers haven't needed 12 pitchers. Going into
yesterday, their starters had worked 1541/3 innings, second in the
American League behind the Anaheim Angels. That gives the Rangers
hope they might be able to drop a pitcher when Catalanotto
returns..
</P>
<P>
   Right now, Lamb is getting most of the playing time at third. He
has started seven of eight games since being called up from the
minor leagues, all against right-handers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just one of those things,'' Evans said. ``I understand.
When I was in there against right-handers, I didn't produce the way
they wanted. So right now I've got to out there in batting practice
and work that much harder and focus more, because I'm not going to
be in there that often. Games that I am in, I've got to be prepared
for.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Oates: ``Both have a chance to play at the big-league
level.Eventually you'll have to make a decision on who will play
every day. Not right now.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, the Rangers go with a platoon.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
