<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: A TALE OF TWO BILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MAUREEN DOWD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Bill East was always going to be a star. He had the
drive. He had the smarts. He had the ingenuity to know which ideas
to claim as his own and which to dump.
</P>
<P>
   Bill West was always going to be a star. He had the drive. He
had the smarts. He had the ingenuity to know which ideas to claim
as his own and which to dump.
</P>
<P>
   ``Opportunity and responsibility,'' Bill East preached.
</P>
<P>
   ``Embrace and extend,'' Bill West preached.
</P>
<P>
   Bill East was greatly underestimated by the old guard, George
Bush and Bob Dole. He upended them and became, heaven help us, the
poster boy for his generation, dominating the '90s. His rise was
relentless, leaving a trail of enemies behind, using any means at
his disposal to rule.
</P>
<P>
   Bill West was greatly underestimated by the old guard, the
mainframers at IBM. He upended them and became, heaven help us, the
poster boy for his generation, dominating the virtual '90s. His
rise was relentless, leaving a trail of enemies behind, using any
means at his disposal to rule.
</P>
<P>
   Bill East, who had an adolescent streak, knew he was being
scrutinized for his reckless behavior but was too arrogant to pull
back.
</P>
<P>
   Bill West, who had an adolescent streak, knew he was being
scrutinized for his reckless behavior but was too arrogant to pull
back.
</P>
<P>
   There was blood in the water.
</P>
<P>
   Jealous rivals lobbied for the downfall of Bill East, and ran to
the prosecutor with tales of his nasty deeds.
</P>
<P>
   Jealous rivals lobbied for the downfall of Bill West, and ran to
the prosecutor with tales of his nasty deeds.
</P>
<P>
   Bill East stonewalled and dissembled, giving them nothing and
figuring it would blow over.
</P>
<P>
   Bill West stonewalled and dissembled, giving them nothing and
figuring it would blow over.
</P>
<P>
   The chief executive from this Washington and his prosecutor came
from different worlds. They started in mutual mistrust and worked
themselves up to true loathing.
</P>
<P>
   The chief executive from the other Washington and his prosecutor
came from different worlds. They started in mutual mistrust and
worked themselves up to true loathing.
</P>
<P>
   The case built and Bill East was clearly in trouble. It would
have helped if he could have shown some humility and remorse. But
he was petulant and bitter.
</P>
<P>
   The case built and Bill West was clearly in trouble. It would
have helped if he could have shown some humility and remorse. But
he was petulant and bitter.
</P>
<P>
   The Bills spent millions of dollars and hours with high-priced
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Some punishment was in order. But the prosecutors overreached,
pushing for penalties that seemed radical and even bizarre.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the zealous pursuit within the Beltway _ or maybe
because of it _ Bill East remains very popular.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the zealous pursuit within the Beltway _ or maybe
because of it _ Bill West remains very popular.
</P>
<P>
   Had prosecution become persecution?
</P>
<P>
   Too hard on Bill East and, more important, too hard on us. He
had gone over the line, certainly, but he was far from being the
only politician who behaved like a cad. We are, after all, a nation
obsessed with sex.
</P>
<P>
   Too hard on Bill West and, more important, too hard on us. He
had gone over the line, certainly, but he was far from being the
only capitalist who behaved like a bully. We are, after all, a
nation obsessed with money.
</P>
<P>
   How quickly the two Bills went from dominant to dejected,
kicking around their big Washington houses, screening movies,
playing golf, wistful about their waning power. Their less
charismatic No. 2s have stepped into the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   Bill East is intent on repairing his image and plotting his next
act. History will show, he insists, that his nightmare with the
Clinton Justice Department was all the doing of his enemies.
</P>
<P>
   Bill West is intent on repairing his image and plotting his next
act. History will show, he insists, that his nightmare with the
Clinton Justice Department was all the doing of his enemies.
</P>
<P>
   There is even a wave of Bill nostalgia. When you look at the
alternatives, these guys start to look pretty good. For better or
worse, they're originals.
</P>
</TEXT>
