<DOCNO> NYT20000502.0278 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3667 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-HEALTHEON-EARNINGS050     05-02 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTHEON-EARNINGS0503-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ambitious company facing competition on several fronts
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier and Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The mission: Turn the Internet into the medium for 30
billion health care transactions each year, make it the place where
consumers, doctors, hospitals and insurers go for information, the
forum in which they do business.
</P>
<P>
   It is a giant undertaking, but the payoff could be stunning.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based Healtheon/WebMD plans to become the one company
that achieves those goals, reaching from one end of the health care
system to the other and connecting it all via the Net. With tens of
billions of dollars at stake _ investors have already pumped well
over $1 billion into Healtheon/WebMD _ the atmosphere has been
rarefied, but the path has been a bit bumpy.
</P>
<P>
   Healtheon got its start in Silicon Valley, founded by Netscape
founder Jim Clark. WebMD was founded in Atlanta entrepreneur Jeff
Arnold, now 30. The two companies seemed headed in the same
direction _ each convinced that the trillion-dollar health care
economy would inevitably move to the Net, each with huge ambitions
to shape and dominate the transition.
</P>
<P>
   Last May, the two merged.
</P>
<P>
   The deal formed an online health care conglomerate _ if such a
thing can be said about a young company far from turning a profit.
The stock market valued the new Atlanta-based company at more than
$19 billion. It started an impressive run of partnerships and
acquisitions, capped by a flurry earlier this year:
</P>
<P>
   In January, Janus Capital bought 15 million shares of
Healtheon/WebMD at $62 a share, an investment of $930 million.
</P>
<P>
   In January and February, Healtheon/WebMD agreed to buy Envoy,
OnHealth Network and CareInsite for stock that was worth, at the
time of the deals, almost $10 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Healtheon/WebMD hired the head of ABC Television,
Patricia Fili-Krushel, and Steven Grant, a vice president with
American Express. Grant is the new chief operating officer,
replacing Mike Long, who remains co-chairman. Fili-Krushel, the
first woman to run a major television network, oversees WebMD
Health, which includes WebMD TV, a joint effort by WebMD and Fox
Television. The channel is expected to be launched this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Other news has been less impressive.
</P>
<P>
   And Healtheon/WebMD's stock has suffered as a result. Shares of
Healtheon traded above $60 when those deals were made earlier this
year. The stock even crested above $100 when the merger with WebMD
was announced last spring. The stock closed Tuesday at $20, up 25
cents.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason for the stock's slide lies with Healtheon's
performance. The company's first-quarter earnings, reported in
March, underwhelmed analysts and started the stock on a downward
slide. But competition also has something to do with it.
Healtheon/WebMD's marketing message is that it wants to ``make
health care ... healthier.''
</P>
<P>
   A few of the companies are showing signs of healing themselves.
</P>
<P>
   In March, insurance companies and drug makers said they
considering forming an Internet venture to link doctors, patients
and insurers.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna U.S. Healthcare, Cigna, WellPoint Health Systems, Oxford
Health Plans, Foundation Health Systems and PacifiCare Health
Systems said they wanted to make the Internet the place doctors,
for example, checked whether a patient was eligible for health
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Some ``push back'' from other quarters _ many of them with deep
pockets _ was predictable, said Elizabeth W. Boehm, an analyst with
Forrester Research. ``Healtheon/WebMD had come at them with a very
arrogant message _ that health care was fouled up and they were
going to fix it. The message (from insurers) is that existing
insurers don't necessarily want another player to come between them
and their members, between them and their clients.''
</P>
<P>
   The effort could pose a threat to Healtheon/WebMD, which is
trying to do the same thing. In mid-April, the challenge grew more
ominous. Five major health care product distributors said they were
creating Web sites to preserve their place in the supply chain.
</P>
<P>
   AmeriSource Health, Cardinal Health, Fisher Scientific
International, McKesson HBOC and Owens &AMP; Minor said they would
invest $100 million to create NewHealthExchange.com. The venture is
designed as an Internet marketplace for physicians with one place
for information about medical products, pricing and availability.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge is not only competition but a fragmented health
care sector where it is hard to be all things to all people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the shine has come off Healtheon/WebMD in the past few
months,'' Boehm said. ``The question is whether they can do all of
it well if they are going to do so many different things. Execution
is a lot harder than it looks.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors are a key to Healtheon's ability to link insurers,
patients and hospital groups.
</P>
<P>
   The cliche is that doctors resist technology. Physicians are
increasingly coming online, but most practices lack Internet
access. The percentage of doctors using the Web rose from 20
percent in 1997 to 37 percent in 1999, according to a December
study by the American Medical Association. Some 58 percent said
they plan on acquiring access to the Web in the next six months.
</P>
<P>
   The percentage of doctors who use a computer stayed flat, at 41
percent, according to the study.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors use the Web, according to the study, to send and receive
e-mail, to find medical information and for travel information.
They are not yet converts to the ``new economy'' _ at least not at
work.
</P>
<P>
   Citing the AMA study, a report from Forrester says that much of
the buzz about getting doctors connected rests on fallacies. For
example, consumers will not quickly force doctors online. Yet
Forrester predicts that after a nasty shakeout of weaker players,
Heatheon/WebMD will be one of the survivors.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
