<DOCNO> NYT20000502.0280 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3670 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-SLOVAKIA-POLITICS-NYT     05-02 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLOVAKIA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWER STRUGGLE AT ROOT OF FORMER SLOVAKIAN LEADER'S ARREST
</HEADLINE>
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRATISLAVA, Slovakia _ Bold or bizarre, the violent arrest of
former Prime Minister Vladimir Meciar may finally, the government
hopes, put an end to his extraordinary influence over Slovak
politics.
</P>
<P>
   On April 20, masked commandos from the organized-crime unit blew
down the back door of Meciar's villa with dynamite and took him
away at gunpoint for questioning. He was quickly released. But the
raid raised new questions about a bruising politician who, polls
show, may be both the most popular and the most unpopular in
Slovakia.
</P>
<P>
   Populist, nationalist and hyperbolic in his language, Meciar, a
former boxer, ran Slovakia from its independence in 1993, after the
divorce from the Czech Republic, until September 1998, when he was
defeated by a coalition of four diverse parties.
</P>
<P>
   His government was widely considered illiberal, discriminatory
and corrupt, practicing crony politics. So much so that Slovakia
became a pariah, left out of the first round of NATO expansion and
shunned for entry negotiations by the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   But only a year ago, Meciar won 43 percent of the vote in the
presidential election, losing to a former Communist, and his party
remains the most popular, winning 25 percent support in polls.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, despite difficult economic times _ including an
unemployment rate of 22 percent _ because of long-delayed
restructuring and reform, Meciar's popularity has been dropping
enough that the government of Prime Minister Mikulas Dzurinda was
able to quietly sanction the raid on Meciar's villa.
</P>
<P>
   The day after his arrest, several thousand supporters rallied
here to protest and scream epithets at Dzurinda.
</P>
<P>
   Meciar was seized because he refused to cooperate with
investigators. Although he was quickly released, he is being
investigated for paying $350,000 in ``illegal bonuses'' to cabinet
members, and he faces questioning about the kidnapping of the son
of the president of Slovakia in 1995. The kidnapping is widely
believed to have been carried out by the secret police on Meciar's
orders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The case is formally about the bribes but informally about the
kidnapping,'' said Grigorij Meseznikov, president of the Institute
for Public Affairs, a research group. ``Everyone knows he was
involved in this.''
</P>
<P>
   Meciar's party had dropped, from 32 percent in the polls to 25
percent, Meseznikov said, and the criminal accusations will hurt
him. ``I don't think he can return to power,'' Meseznikov said.
``It's hard to imagine that any of the democratic parties will go
into coalition with him.''
</P>
<P>
   He paused and added: ``Of course, since 1990, people have been
saying that Meciar was finished. But he keeps coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   Dzurinda is widely admired in the West for trying to bring
Slovakia back, as quickly as he can, to the prescribed route of
reform for former Communist states. With a smart young economist,
Ivan Miklos, as deputy prime minister, he has moved rapidly to cut
the budget, trade deficits and foreign debt and to restart a more
open process of privatization that will include banks, energy and
telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   But ``because of Mr. Meciar, we've lost time, nearly 10 years,''
Miklos said. ``The Meciar legacy is lack of investor confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   That is most visible in comparison with the Czech Republic,
which has some of the same problems of cronyism and corruption.
Last year, the Czech Republic attracted $4 billion in direct
foreign investment; Slovakia, just $350 million. And as usual,
restructuring has led to higher unemployment and a drop in the
government's popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Dzurinda has also promised new respect for human rights and a
fairer deal for Slovakia's Gypsies, who make up 8 percent of the
population and who face widespread discrimination and joblessness.
He is pushing Slovakia for the next round of NATO expansion,
whenever that will come, and trying to get President Clinton to
stop here next month.
</P>
<P>
   Slovakia is about to join the Organization for Economic
Cooperation and Development, and the European Union has invited the
new government to talks.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Dzurinda expressed some concern over the
cohesion of his broad coalition. His center-right party is itself a
merger of five smaller parties. A new populist party called Smer,
or Direction, run by a young lawyer and former Communist, Robert
Fico, has quickly emerged from nothing to become the second most
popular party.
</P>
<P>
   Fico is described by experts and diplomats here as purposefully
vague, making broad populist comments that criticize crime,
corruption, the Russian and Slovak mafias and the Gypsies, but
maintaining a pro-European stance and saying he will never
cooperate with Meciar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hold the door open for Fico,'' Dzurinda said. ``On the one
hand, I'm not so happy with his party. He's a bit populist. But
he's not Meciar.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
