A3671 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-GAPAC-NEWADS0503-COX     05-02 0482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAPAC-NEWADS0503-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ga.-Pacific reaching out to consumers with new ads
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ In its broadest image-building move ever,
Georgia-Pacific plans to unveil TV ads today that emphasize it's
more than just a paper and wood products company.
</P>
<P>
   The new branding campaign reminds consumers the Atlanta-based
manufacturer is an integral part of home life.
</P>
<P>
   In one ad previewed Tuesday at the annual shareholders meeting
in Augusta, there are flashes of household activities and little
reminders of where Georgia-Pacific fits in. A family unpacks
groceries at a kitchen table, and the word ``here'' pops up on a
package of Angel Soft bathroom tissue and also on a wooden table
leg. ``Not here'' appears on aluminum foil that a young girl plays
with nearby.
</P>
<P>
   In another segment, ``yesses'' are superimposed on parts of a
deck and windswept sheets of paper that youngsters scramble to
grab. The tagline is ``We make the things that make you feel at
home. ``We want Georgia-Pacific to be widely known as more than a
collection of building products and paper products,'' Chairman and
Chief Executive Pete Correll told shareholders. ``Ultimately, we
want to make the Georgia-Pacific name a preference-driving vehicle
for all of our products.''
</P>
<P>
   For years Georgia-Pacific has been stamping its name on stacks
of lumber and other building products, but only recently has the
company best known for pulp and plywood tried to push its name
closer to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, its logo began appearing on the front of Sparkle paper
towels and Angel Soft tissue packages. The company's new liquid
hand soap, Pacific Garden, also carries the logo.
</P>
<P>
   The new TV spots were created by Fallon McElligott New York
City. Framed in a ``letterbox'' cinematic style with upbeat,
acoustic music in the background, the ads aim to reach homeowners
rather than Georgia-Pacific's base of commercial customers.
</P>
<P>
   The switch in marketing mind-set came after Georgia-Pacific made
its timber-growing business a separate operating group from its
manufacturing operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the years, we built our company on a philosophy of
looking at the resource, determining what we could manufacture and
then driving that product to the market,'' Correll said. Now the
marketing perspective has turned away from two-by-fours and other
commodities to a focus on consumer products, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now must become a company that talks to our customers,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The ads will start running Thursday on national cable networks
such as Home &AMP; Garden Television and the Food Channel. They'll also
run on network stations in regional markets where Georgia-Pacific
has a strong presence.
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street, Georgia-Pacific's stock rose $1.25, closing at
$38.25.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-00 2022EDT &QL; 
