<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3672 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-AT&AMP;T-MARKETPLACE-NYT &LR;      05-02 1146
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: DESPITE PROGRESS, AT&AMP;T FINDS INVESTORS IMPATIENT 
</HEADLINE>
   By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After a day like Tuesday, it is easy to see that C.
Michael Armstrong, chairman of AT&AMP;T, may have the toughest job in
Corporate America.
</P>
<P>
   It was the worst day for AT&AMP;T's investors in more than a dozen
years, and Armstrong probably has not had such an unpleasant
professional experience since he took over the company in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T announced quarterly financial results that met analysts'
expectations. But the company also warned that its earnings and,
perhaps more important, its revenue growth for the full year would
be lower than anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   The shortfalls are slight. Rather than earning $1.89 to $1.94 a
share before special charges, the company now expects to earn $1.80
to $1.85. Revenue after acquisitions had been expected to grow by 8
to 9 percent, but the company cut that projection to 7 to 8
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, AT&AMP;T's shares fell 14 percent, or $6.8125,$41.9375,
on the New York Stock Exchange. It was the biggest percentage
decline in AT&AMP;T's stock, one of the most widely held in the nation,
since the stock market crash of 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps adding some psychological pain to the financial burn,
AT&AMP;T ended a trading session for the first time with a lower market
value than one of its Baby Bell progeny _ $134 billion to SBC
Communications Inc.'s $144 billion _ according to Thomson Financial
Securities Data, a research firm.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking AT&AMP;T's top job after three decades at IBM and a
stint running General Motors' Hughes Electronics unit, Armstrong
has been a whirlwind of activity trying to reinvigorate AT&AMP;T and to
take advantage of the revolution in digital communications. He has
committed more than $90 billion of his shareholders' money to build
the nation's biggest cable television operation. He has spent
billions more building the company's torrid wireless division. He
is intent on making AT&AMP;T the biggest provider of high-speed
Internet service to American consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Tuesday's vertigo-inducing selloff, all these
initiatives are going well. But AT&AMP;T simply has not been able to
escape its deteriorating legacy as a long-distance telephone
carrier and is running out of chances with impatient investors who
are hoping that AT&AMP;T's future is now.
</P>
<P>
   With defiance in every word, Armstrong defended his legacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a lot of speculation or comment on whether we can
we grow the businesses that we've invested in and acquired,'' he
said Tuesday in a telephone interview. ``Take wireless and
broadband. We're redefining the AT&AMP;T circuit-switched network to
one that is both optical and broadband. These are the businesses
that we have invested in for the future, and this year they're
going to grow over 12 percent and their growth rate is
accelerating. Three years ago, we were growing at 1.7 percent and
we had a domestic long-distance voice business.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news about today's results,'' he added, ``is that it
is a confirmation that the growth businesses are growing. They are
meeting all of their underlying metrics.''
</P>
<P>
   However, AT&AMP;T said Tuesday that its core consumer long-distance
telephone business is shrinking even faster than the company had
previously led analysts to believe and that its unit that serves
business customers had mismanaged some of its biggest accounts.
Forbearance was not in the air.
</P>
<P>
   Until Tuesday, AT&AMP;T had guided stock analysts to expect that
revenue for its consumer unit, which is dominated by long-distance
telephone sales, would shrink by 3 to 5 percent this year. Tuesday,
the company said the unit would shrink by 5 to 7 percent, a victim
of the growing popularity of wireless phones and of low-cost
calling plans like its own flat-rate long-distance plan for 7 cents
a minute. (AT&AMP;T added that if a regulatory plan to which it has
agreed takes effect, the decline would actually be 6 to 8 percent.)
</P>
<P>
   That was not a killer for AT&AMP;T. Just about everyone on Wall
Street and in the communications business knows that AT&AMP;T's
consumer unit is shrinking and if the pace is accelerating, well,
perhaps that is to be expected.
</P>
<P>
   What was not expected was the problem in the company's business
services unit, which has been consistently robust in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   In the first quarter, AT&AMP;T transferred almost 300 of its biggest
corporate accounts to its Concert joint venture with British
Telecom. The company also moved 1,200 big accounts into a different
internal organization that Armstrong believed enjoyed better
executive leadership.
</P>
<P>
   In the shuffle, some customers were neglected, if not lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really shuffled too many people too fast across accounts,
broke a few relationships,'' Richard Roscitt, the new chief of
AT&AMP;T's business-services unit, said Tuesday in a conference call
with financial analysts. ``It is a set of accounts where we frankly
did not pay enough attention to the high end.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the company said that the business-services unit
would grow by about 8 percent, instead of the previously expected 9
to 11 percent. (By comparison, AT&AMP;T's wireless unit is expected to
grow by 25 to 30 percent, and the company's cable unit by 12 to 14
percent.)
</P>
<P>
   As in the consumer unit, the shortfall in the business-services
operation did not appear huge. In fact, judging strictly by the
numbers, a strong case could be made that the magnitude of
Tuesday's sell-off was an overreaction.
</P>
<P>
   But when investors have the jitters about a company, as they do
about AT&AMP;T, it is rarely all about the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's people anticipating another shoe dropping,'' said
Richard G. Klugman, an analyst for Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette.
``It sounded like these were not blips on the radar screen. It
sounded like there are fundamental issues that the company will
have to deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   Discounting special charges and some outside investments, AT&AMP;T
met analysts' expectations by earning 53 cents a share, or $1.7
billion, in the last quarter, down from 61 cents a share, or $1.7
billion, a year earlier. Revenue after acquisitions increased by
5.8 percent, to $15.8 billion, from $15 billion during the
comparable period of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Including all charges, investments and acquisitions, AT&AMP;T earned
54 cents a share, or $1.7 billion, up from 38 cents, or $1.1
billion, during the comparable period last year. Reported revenue
increased by 12.3 percent, to $15.8 billion from $14.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Continuing its cost-cutting drive, AT&AMP;T said it would cut 6,200
jobs, or about 4 percent of its work force, by the end of the year.
The company declined to provide more specific information about the
cuts, but more than 1,000 jobs could be lost in New Jersey, home to
AT&AMP;T's headquarters, according to an executive close to the
company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
