<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: TALKS CONTINUE
</P>
<P>
   After inconsequential meetings with Ulster's Catholic and
Protestant political leaders at 10 Downing Street, Prime Minister
Tony Blair and his Irish counterpart, Bertie Ahern, scheduled more
talks in Belfast on Thursday. The sessions are seeking to restart
the power-sharing government suspended by Britain, which said it
acted because of the failure of the Irish Republican Army to make
expected moves on disarmament.
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND: BODY SEARCH
</P>
<P>
   Working with new information from the Irish Republican Army,
diggers searched in County Louth for the remains of Jean
McConville, a mother of 10 who was killed by the IRA in 1972 after
she comforted a wounded British soldier. Digging for the bodies of
nine IRA victims from the 1970s began at the end of last May; three
bodies were found before excavation was suspended.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: EXTRADITION ORDER
</P>
<P>
   A court ordered the extradition of two Egyptians to the United
States to face charges of conspiring with the Saudi dissident Osama
bin Laden in the 1998 bombings of the American embassies in Kenya
and Tanzania. Ibrahim Hussein Abdel Hadi Eidarous and Adel Mohammed
Abdul Almagid Bary can appeal the order, a Bow Street Magistrates'
Court official said.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: NEW CHIAPAS BISHOP
</P>
<P>
   Felipe Arizmendi Esquivel, 60, the new bishop in a turbulent
diocese in Chiapas state, said he is opposed to the armed tactics
of the Zapatista guerrillas but also warned that poverty and
inequality breed violence. Thousands of Indian worshippers thronged
San Cristobal de las Casas when Bishop Arizmendi took over from
Bishop Samuel Ruiz Garcia, who retired after 40 years. Ruiz was
revered by many Indians but was accused by the government of
preaching Marxism.
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA LEONE: U.N. SOLDIERS SEIZED
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen U.N. peacekeepers from India and Kenya were taken
hostage in northern and eastern Sierra Leone by rebels who have yet
to disarm despite a nine-month-old peace accord. Negotiations with
the rebel leader Foday Sankoh were under way to obtain the release
of the hostages. Meanwhile, a Nigerian officer died from wounds
received in a clash with rebels on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE: COMMONWEALTH CONDEMNATION
</P>
<P>
   Seeking increased diplomatic pressure on President Robert
Mugabe, Britain won support from the 54-nation Commonwealth in
condemning political violence, lawlessness and the occupation by
squatters of white-owned farms in Zimbabwe. A statement from an
influential Commonwealth panel in London coincided with reports
that a 15th opponent of Mugabe had died in violence linked to
coming elections.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: REBELS FREED
</P>
<P>
   The government continued to release jailed leaders of the
Hurriyat Conference, an alliance of anti-India groups in Kashmir.
Shakeel Bakasi of the Jammu and Kashmir Liberation Front was the
latest to be set free. Home Minister L.K. Advani said India is
willing to engage Hurriyat in talks aimed at ending a decade of
strife.
</P>
</TEXT>
