<HEADLINE>
KRONE IS FIRST WOMAN IN RACING HALL OF FAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Jockey Julie Krone, who took her final ride a
year ago at Lone Star Park at Grand Prairie, became the first woman
to be elected into the Thoroughbred Racing Hall of Fame, hall
officials announced yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Also elected were trainer Neil Drysdale, 1992 Horse of the Year
A.P. Indy, 1988 Kentucky Derby winner Winning Colors and 1956
Kentucky Derby winner Needles.
</P>
<P>
   Krone's 3,545 victories are the most by a female jockey and she
is the only female jockey to win a Triple Crown race (aboard
Colonial Affair in the 1993 Belmont Stakes). Krone, 36, cried when
she talked about how her mother, Judi, helped her achieve her
dreams. Her mother died in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   When she told her mother she wanted to be a jockey, her mother
took her to Churchill Downs. But Julie Krone couldn't get in the
barn area because she was 15, a year too young. So Judi Krone went
to a store across the street and changed the date on the birth
certificate.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom had a sense of adventure,'' Krone said. ``She told me
when someone shuts a door on you, they left open a window.''
</P>
<P>
   The induction ceremony is scheduled Aug. 7 in Saratoga Springs,
N.Y.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
