<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3684 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-TEXAS-BONFIRE-ART-NYT     05-02 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-BONFIRE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAULTY CONSTRUCTION, LAX SUPERVISION BLAMED IN BONFIRE COLLAPSE
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT3 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic
is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ In a highly critical report, a
commission investigating the fatal collapse of a traditional Texas
A&AMP;M University bonfire tower concluded Tuesday that students made
fundamental mistakes in building the huge structure and that
university officials failed to properly control the student-led
project.
</P>
<P>
   The accident on Nov. 18 killed 11 students and 1 former student
and injured 27 others. The five-member commission determined that
construction flaws and a sloped surface caused the lowest tier of
logs to break and set off the collapse of the 59-foot structure.
Yet in assessing responsibility, the commission pointed not to
current students and administrators but to an insular university
culture developed over decades that was resistant to change and
outside criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``This failure has roots in decisions and actions by both
students and university officials over many, many years,'' said the
commission chairman, Leo Linbeck Jr., a Houston construction
executive. ``It created an environment where a complex and
dangerous structure was allowed to be built without controls.''
</P>
<P>
   For Texas A&AMP;M, known for the intense devotion and loyalty of
students and alumni, the accident has prompted much public
soul-searching over whether to continue the 90-year-tradition of
the bonfire. Every year, students spend two months harvesting
thousands of trees and erecting the tower in anticipation of the
school's annual football game with the University of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Ray M. Bowen, the university president, said he would decide
the fate of the tradition within six weeks after reviewing the
commission's 2-inch thick report and consulting with student
leaders, faculty members, university officials and alumni. In
recent weeks, more than 6,000 students have signed petitions in
favor of continuing the tradition, known on campus simply as
Bonfire. About 3,000 people, mostly students, attended Tuesday's
final commission meeting at the school's basketball arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not made up my mind,'' Dr. Bowen said at a news
conference after the commission meeting. ``It may be that we will
continue to have a bonfire, it may be that we will not.''
</P>
<P>
   For months, speculation had swirled about the accident. News
accounts and documents released by the university revealed that
students had failed in several instances to follow a safety
handbook. The tower exceeded the allowed 55-foot height. Freshmen
and sophomores, who were considered inexperienced, were working on
the structure's top levels despite safety guidelines that
prohibited them from doing so. A crane operated by a student had
struck the tower. The guiding pole had snapped at least three
times. And toxicology reports indicated that 2 of the 12 victims
were legally drunk.
</P>
<P>
   The commission did find evidence of drinking, horseplay and
hazing but said none of those activities contributed to the
collapse. The commission also minimized the impact of the incident
involving the crane and the actions of the students atop the stack,
and it ruled out sabotage.
</P>
<P>
   The bonfire is a student-run activity with a faculty adviser and
a university committee, neither of which monitors the structure's
design.
</P>
<P>
   Veronica Callaghan, a commission member, portrayed a loose
atmosphere in which the tower was built ``with no written
guidelines.'' Upperclassmen known as Red Pots and Brown Pots are
expected to train the thousands of students who take part, but
Callaghan said student leaders lacked the proper knowledge to
safely construct the tower.
</P>
<P>
   The ``bonfire was never built the same way twice,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Callaghan also blamed university officials, saying the school
``addresses risk in student organizations reactively.'' She said
there several warning signs of problems: The tower collapsed in
1957 and again in 1990, though no one was injured. Injuries related
to the bonfire had risen to 59 in 1998 from 32 in 1996. Yet she
said university officials had ``tunnel vision'' in failing to
recognize that such problems could foretell a structural and
cultural problem. Other universities, she said, are much more
aggressive in monitoring student-led activities.
</P>
<P>
   In explaining the physical cause of the collapse, Hugh Robinson,
a commission member who runs a Dallas engineering firm, noted that
the tower had evolved over many decades from a pile of trash to a
complicated, engineering project that weighed more than 2 million
pounds. Despite this evolution, Robinson noted that university
officials took a very limited role in the building of the bonfire.
</P>
<P>
   After an exhaustive engineering review, the commission traced
the problem to the lowest tier of the wedding cake shaped tower,
Robinson said. Since 1994, students had wrapped steel cables around
this lowest tier of logs for extra support, he said. He compared
the cables to the strips of metal that encircle a wooden barrel.
But this year, students did not use the cables, partly because they
wrongly believed that the cables made the wooden stack burn faster.
In addition, students used inadequate wiring to bind individual
logs together, Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said students also improperly wedged the second tier of
logs into this lowest tier. Students thought doing so would provide
more stability and create a tighter foundation, but Robinson said
the opposite occurred: The pressure from the wedged logs helped
push the lower tier apart. Finally, a sloped ground surface
contributed to the instability as did the excessive size of the
second tier.
</P>
<P>
   ``A combination of factors and not any one factor led to the
collapse,'' Robinson said. Still, he noted that using the steel
support cables ``would have greatly reduced the likelihood of
collapse.''
</P>
<P>
   The one piece of solace for family members of the victims is
that the accident apparently occurred in an instant. ``This
collapse happened very quickly,'' Robinson said. ``Eyewitnesses
were stunned.``
</P>
<P>
   In his news conference, Dr. Bowen admitted that his heart told
him to carry on the bonfire tradition. But he quickly added that he
would make his decision with his head. ``If we do continue to have
Bonfire,'' he said, ``there will be appropriate changes to the
culture. That's essential.''
</P>
<P>
   Wade Countryman, 22, a senior who is a member of the school's
military-styled Corps of Cadets, listened to the commission's
presentation from the bleachers of the basketball arena. ``I think
we'll have it next year,'' he said. ``I think it will change, but I
think it was an accident. I don't know how much you could prevent
it. Accidents happen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tragic,'' he added. ``Planes crash, things happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-00 2033EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
