<DOCNO> NYT20000502.0289 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3685 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-HEART-FILM-ART-$ADV07     05-02 1294
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEART-FILM-ART-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEST FRIENDS ON BEST FRIENDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By DANA KENNEDY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first-time writer-directors Anthony Stark and Sean Smith,
best friends since high school, are in a difficult position when
they talk about their new movie, ``Into My Heart'' _ a dark story
about two men, best friends since childhood, whose relationship
takes a tragic turn after they grow up and get married. (The film
opens May 5.)
</P>
<P>
   At first, Stark and Smith, both 39, best friends since they met
in 1977 at the Browning School on Manhattan's Upper East Side,
insist there is ``only a little autobiography'' in the story of Ben
and Adam, two sons of affluent East Coast families who are ``like
two olives in a martini,'' according to Adam's father, yet very
different.
</P>
<P>
   Stark and Smith's reluctance to admit that their art may imitate
life could be more than the usual insistence by writers that their
creation is a work of fiction, not real life. The character of Ben,
played by Rob Morrow, the chief instigator in the movie's twisted
quadrangle, raises uncomfortable questions about betrayal and
infidelity and whether so-called nice, normal people can commit
destructive, hurtful acts.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who see it focus on Ben as this monolith of evil,''
Stark said. ``Many people just don't want to believe that good
people can do bad things. We wanted to show the moral hypocrisy of
that and ask who can presume you couldn't do what these people
did.''
</P>
<P>
   On a more mundane level, Stark and Smith will admit to being
part of an upper-middle-class social circle like that of the WASPy
young adults in the film. The movie's characters spend weekends at
Adam's family's country house in the Berkshires and play word games
like the ``name game''; Stark has been a frequent guest at Smith's
family's weekend house near the Berkshires and the name game is one
of their favorites. And Stark said he modeled Adam's wife on a
woman he knows well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're a lot more like Ben and Adam than they
claim,'' said Morrow, 37, who signed on for the low-budget film
after being won over by the script. ``I've heard them talk about
the movie and pass it off as if it isn't their story. But you hear
the characters of Ben and Adam come out of their voices.''
</P>
<P>
   The character of Ben is restless, cynical, ambitious _ and a
veteran of bad relationships. Adam, played by Jake Weber, described
as a ``golden boy'' in the film, is romantic, loyal _ and happily
married to Nina, the love of his life, a woman he meets in college.
Nina, played by Claire Forlani, becomes the catalyst that shatters
the friendship between Ben and Adam forever.
</P>
<P>
   Cut to a table at the Algonquin Hotel recently, where Stark and
Smith are explaining their own lives _ over two glasses of Jack
Daniels apiece. The very likeable but often cynical Stark, the son
of Art Stark, a television producer who produced NBC's ``The
Tonight Show'' until 1969, is divorced and claims he would like to
be in a stable relationship with one woman, ``but I've blown so
many opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I decided to get married it was to the sweetest woman in
the world,'' he said. ``There was nothing wrong with her at all. I
just got bored and had to blow something up.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Smith, the son of a poet and a schoolteacher, who
has a calm, contained manner, has been married for 10 years to his
``first love,'' a woman he met 20 years ago in college. They have
two young children. ``I think I was very lucky,'' said Smith of his
wife, Virginia Keeny, a civil rights attorney in Los Angeles. ``I
found a really special person. I loved her instantly. And I still
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Stark said he and Smith, who have written several movies
together but never directed before, rarely argue over personal
issues, but they have a longstanding disagreement over people who
remain stuck in unhealthy relationships. ``Sean can't understand
why supposedly smart people stay in bad relationships,'' he said.
``As someone who has stayed in more than his share of bad
relationships for far too long, I don't understand why he can't
understand it.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith smiled at Stark indulgently. ``It's not that I don't
understand it _ to a point,'' he said. ``It's just that in
Anthony's case it seems to go on and on.''
</P>
<P>
   Stark does not seem to mind such statements, which mirror
spirited exchanges between Ben and Adam in ``Into My Heart.'' But
perhaps more tellingly, when it comes to his writing partner's
long, seemingly idyllic relationship with his wife, Stark does not
seem to harbor the sort of unspoken envy Ben has of Adam.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're like a perfect family,'' Stark said of Smith's wife
and children. ``But I'm not jealous. I've had a lot of chances but
I've blown them and it's almost always my fault. If I can't commit
myself, who else is there to blame?''
</P>
<P>
   So while the contrasting personalities of the two best friends
in ``Into My Heart'' eventually lead to tragedy, Stark and Smith
have managed to profit from their own admittedly ``good cop, bad
cop'' friendship by translating it into professional success.
</P>
<P>
   Both men now live in Los Angeles but spent considerable time
apart after graduating from high school. Stark went to Columbia and
later studied at the London Film School. Smith attended Harvard and
got his doctorate in modern British history at Stanford. He spent a
year supposedly doing doctoral research in London but said he ended
up hanging around Stark in his film classes.
</P>
<P>
   Smith later moved to Los Angeles, where he waited on tables and
worked as a freelance film journalist until Stark joined him there
and they started collaborating in 1991. After writing what Smith
called ``pretty stupid genre movies'' like ``Dogfighter'' (1996)
and ``Art of Murder,'' which will be released straight to video
later this year, they decided to write the kind of movie they liked
to watch and came up with ``Into My Heart.''
</P>
<P>
   The script wound up in the hands of Jean Doumanian, the veteran
producer of eight Woody Allen movies, when an associate in Los
Angeles recommended it to her. Jean Doumanian Productions is
opening the movie for a two-week run at the Quad with the intent of
getting wider distribution. ``I think it strikes at something
universal,'' Doumanian said. ``When two couples are friendly or
double-date I think at one time or another they are attracted to
the other. I knew two couples that ended up married to each other's
spouses.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Into the Heart,'' however, does not have such a happy ending.
In the movie's pivotal scene, Ben, who is by now married himself
(his wife is played by Jayne Brook), kisses Adam's wife and sets in
motion the smashing of all four people's lives. Stark is happy to
go on the record and declare that he has never once kissed Smith's
wife. Smith, for his part, said, ``I wouldn't kill myself if he
did, I would kill him.''
</P>
<P>
   That occasion seems unlikely. After first talking about doing a
movie together in high school, Stark and Smith have finally gained
a foothold in Hollywood and are planning more scripts together as
well as solo projects. They are almost done writing their next
movie, a comedy that Smith called ``the best thing we've done so
far.''
</P>
<P>
   While the ending of ``Into My Heart'' is given away in the
opening scene, Stark and Smith conclude the interview with a twist
of their own. When asked if either one can envision doing something
as destructive as Ben does, Stark, the bad cop, immediately says
``No.'' Smith says ``Yes,'' apparently surprising even himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should not have said that,'' he said, laughing. ``Can I take
it back?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
