<HEADER>
A3687 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-REPUBS-PRMARIES-ART-N     05-02 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-PRMARIES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP PANEL PROPOSES NEW PRESIDENTIAL NOMINATING SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
  (With text box, REPUBS-STATES) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A high-level Republican committee on Tuesday
proposed a new presidential nominating system intended to build
suspense and interest from March through June, with smaller states
voting first and larger states casting the decisive final votes.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal comes as a sharp reaction to the current system, in
which both party nominations were effectively decided by March 7,
the first big primary day, before millions of Americans knew much
about the candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Brock, a former senator from Tennessee and a former party
chairman, who led the committee that offered the plan, said, ``Too
many people in too many states have no voice in the electoral
process that names our candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Nicholson, the Republican national chairman, said he
expected the plan to be adopted, although Republicans in the past
have been reluctant to impose national rules on state parties, and
some big states will be concerned that the nomination could be
decided before they hold their primaries.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican willingness to scrap the current nominating
system seems likely to open up a debate about the system in both
parties, althoughthe Democratic Party's reaction on Tuesday was
that since the present system had elected Bill Clinton twice, ``at
this point, there is little incentive to change.''
</P>
<P>
   But if Republicans adopt the plan at their convention in August,
Democrats might be ready to negotiate changing the primary process
after the election. One key provision would give the Republican
National Committee the authority, which it now lacks and the
Democratic committee has, to alter delegate selection rules between
conventions.
</P>
<P>
   James Roosevelt, co-chairman of the Democratic Rules and By-Laws
Committee, said, ``If the Republicans can get that kind of
flexibility, then between cycles we could have some real
substantive discussions about this.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, the 12 smallest states, the District of Columbia
and the territories would be allowed to hold primaries or caucuses
no earlier than the first Tuesday in March. Another group of 13
slightly larger states, including Connecticut and New Mexico, could
go on the first Tuesday in April. Thirteen middle-size states,
including Kentucky and Massachusetts, could go on the first Tuesday
in May.
</P>
<P>
   The rest, including New York, California, Texas, Florida and New
Jersey, could have primaries on the first Tuesday in June. Any
state could go later, and in the early stages, some might do so to
get a Tuesday that is less crowded. The plan makes no allowance for
early votes in Iowa and New Hampshire, but that might be adjusted
by the Republican National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   State legislatures would have to vote to adopt new primary
dates. To pressure them, the Republican National Committee would
have the power to deny state parties between 50 percent and 90
percent of their delegates.
</P>
<P>
   That degree of central control may be an issue, at the
convention if not earlier, at next week's meeting of the Republican
rules committee.
</P>
<P>
   John Deardourff, a Republican consultant whose first primary was
in 1964, said on Tuesday, ``The unwillingness to impose
Washington-based decisions and the unwillingness to accept them is
pretty strongly ingrained in Republican theology, and whether it's
the government doing it, or the party, it just doesn't sit well.''
</P>
<P>
   Deardourff, however, said he supported the plan. ``Anything
would be better than the current system, and that view may be
sufficiently widely held to produce some change.''
</P>
<P>
   The first hurdle is clearly within the party.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Jones, secretary of state in California, said the plan was
``absolutely not'' in his state's best interest because it would
mean California always came in the last group. He said the majority
of the Brock commission, on which he served, was mistaken in its
belief that because nearly half the delegates would not be chosen
before June that a contest would be keep going.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who had pushed to move the California primary up to March
7 this year, said he did not think the suggested changes would be
enough to overcome the current way of nominating a candidate, which
he called ``raise a lot of money, get it over quick.'' He said he
thought a system of regional primaries, in which different regions
each got their chance to go first, would be better.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the presumptive Republican
presidential nominee, could play a decisive role in deciding
whether the plan is adopted at the convention. But his campaign had
no comment on Tuesday night, saying he looked forward to studying
the report.
</P>
<P>
   The Brock commission report was issued on the day when North
Carolina and Indiana, the 11th and 14th largest states, held
presidential primaries that drew virtually no interest.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the campaign turnout was high, at least among
Republicans, but by March 7, known as Super Tuesday, two-fifths of
Republican delegates and one-third of Democratic delegates had been
picked.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Gans, head of the Committee for the Study of the American
Electorate, who cheered the Brock report as ``the best thing since
sliced bread,'' said turnout since March 7 ``has been abysmally low
and the citizens in the states which were after Super Tuesday have
felt left out of the process.''
</P>
<P>
   The Brock Commission, whose undisclosed vote was not unanimous,
did offer a fallback proposal of rotating regional primaries _ a
plan suggested by the National association of Secretaries of State.
They said that proposal would allow a different region to go first
every four years, and believed it would reduce front-loading.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
