<SLUG> BC-FUNDRAISING-CONGRESS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSECUTOR HAD SOUGHT INQUIRY OF CLINTON AND PARTY DONOR 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Pa.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT12 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic
is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A Republican senator said at a hearing Tuesday that
the former head of the Justice Department's campaign finance unit
had unsuccessfully urged the appointment of an independent
prosecutor to investigate President Clinton and a top executive of
the Loral aerospace company.
</P>
<P>
   The senator, Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania, made his comments
during the questioning of Charles La Bella, the former Justice
Department official. La Bella responded obliquely to Specter's
questions, but did not dispute that he had recommended an outside
inquiry of Clinton and Bernard L. Schwartz, chairman of the Loral
Space and Communications Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Loral officials had no immediate reaction to Specter's
disclosure Tuesday. Previously, they have defended Schwartz's
actions and said that company officials did nothing wrong in their
dealings with scientists in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz has been one of the Democratic Party's largest donors
and had contributed $1.5 million during the 1996 election campaign.
His contributions have continued even as his company became the
subject of a separate Justice Department investigation into whether
it broke the law by providing important technological help to
China's rocket program. At the same time he was contributing money
to the Democratic Party, Schwartz's company was seeking government
approval for satellite launches in China.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear Tuesday whether La Bella had referred in his memo
to any specific evidence suggesting that either Clinton or Schwartz
had engaged in improper conduct. Other officials said that they had
never established any reason to question the legality of Schwartz's
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the officials who have read the memorandum written by La
Bella to Attorney General Janet Reno in 1998 said that he did urge
her to seek the appointment of an independent prosecutor to
investigate the matter, in part because of the appearance that the
Justice Department could not credibly investigate the president on
its own.
</P>
<P>
   The issue arose Tuesday at a hearing of a Senate Judiciary
subcommittee when Specter referred to passages in La Bella's
still-confidential memo, whose existence and conclusions have been
the subject of reports by a number of news organizations. In the
memo La Bella strongly recommended the appointment of an
independent counsel to investigate allegations of fund-raising
abuses in the 1996 election.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a section of your report which deals with Loral on the
technology transfer from Loral to the People's Republic of China,''
Specter said. ``And there was a recommendation as to proceeding as
to an investigation for the chief executive officer of Loral,
Bernard Schwartz, who had contributed some $1,500,000 to the
Democratic National Committee.''
</P>
<P>
   Specter then said that the memorandum indicated that if the
Justice Department opened an investigation of Schwartz, it should
also begin an inquiry of Clinton, who was subject to the
independent counsel statute.
</P>
<P>
   La Bella, accepting Specter's account, replied,
``Hypothetically, if you're going to investigate the person who
gave the contribution because you think something was wrong with
that because they were seeking a quid pro quo, then it seems to me
that part of the area of investigation would be the person who
received the contribution.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno rebuffed La Bella, who wrote his memorandum as he was
departing after a sometimes fractious tenure as head of a high
profile investigation into possible campaign finance irregularities
stemming from the 1996 election.
</P>
<P>
   Reno never discussed La Bella's memo with him and, ultimately
she decided against seeking an independent counsel to investigate
Clinton or Vice President Al Gore, whose fund-raising activities,
according to La Bella's memo, also raised enough questions to
warrant investigation by an outside prosecutor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
