<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-AGENCY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT OPPOSES SHIFT IN MEDICARE OVERSIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration said Tuesday that
proposals to create an independent agency to run the Medicare
program or to administer prescription drug benefits for the elderly
were unwise and probably unconstitutional because the new entity
would not be accountable to the president.
</P>
<P>
   Most Republicans in Congress and many Democrats want to reduce
the authority of the agency that now runs Medicare, the Health Care
Financing Administration. In carrying out laws passed over the last
three decades, they say, it has become a heavy-handed regulator.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the leading proposals in Congress for Medicare coverage
of prescription drugs would create a quasi-independent board, which
would hire private entities to administer drug benefits under
guidelines set by the government. Many lawmakers would like to give
the board additional powers over Medicare in the future.
</P>
<P>
   But the Justice Department said such proposals ``would
constitute an unwarranted and unwise erosion of the president's
authority to oversee the functioning of the executive branch'' of
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``The proposed legislation raises serious constitutional
concerns'' and ``poses a serious threat to the core constitutional
values of political accountability and coordinated executive branch
policy-making,'' the Justice Department said in a letter to Sen.
John D. Rockefeller IV, D-W.Va., . He asked the department for its
views in February.
</P>
<P>
   If the Clinton administration persists in its opposition to an
independent board, it could seriously complicate Congressional
efforts to offer drug benefits to the 39 million people on
Medicare. Support for such a board appears to be growing on Capitol
Hill. Many lawmakers have said they fear that if the Health Care
Financing Administration is responsible for new drug benefits, it
may eventually try to regulate drug prices as it has regulated
doctors' fees and hospital payments under Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department expressed its views in a critique of
legislation introduced by Sens. John Breaux, D-La., and Bill Frist,
R-Tenn.. The Medicare board in their bill was modeled, in part,
after the Federal Reserve Board and other independent agencies.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Breaux said he saw no basis for the Justice
Department's concerns. The Medicare board, he said, would be
outside the Department of Health and Human Services, but it would
still be in the executive branch, like the Social Security
Administration, which was removed from the department by a 1994
law.
</P>
<P>
   As envisioned in the Breaux-Frist bill, the Medicare board would
be ``an independent agency of the United States.'' It would
generally supervise the Medicare program and manage a competitive
market in which health insurance plans vie with one another, and
with the original fee-for-service Medicare program, to provide
coverage to people who are elderly or disabled.
</P>
<P>
   The board would have seven members, appointed by the president
for seven-year terms. The president could remove a member ``only
for neglect of duty or malfeasance in office,'' the bill says. The
Justice Department strenuously objected to this restriction on the
president's power to dismiss board members.
</P>
<P>
   Breaux said, ``It's easy to construct a Medicare board that
would meet constitutional requirements.'' If necessary, he said,
the bill could be revised so board members would serve at the
pleasure of the president.
</P>
<P>
   Rockefeller, like the Clinton administration, opposes the idea
of an independent Medicare board, saying it would create a new
bureaucracy that is not accountable to either beneficiaries or
taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot pass the buck,'' Rockefeller said. ``Removing
Medicare from the accountability of Congress and the president
amounts to an abdication of duty that would risk the health care of
millions of America's seniors.''
</P>
<P>
   But aides to Breaux and Frist said they had been assured by
lawyers at the Congressional Research Service that the proposed
Medicare board would not violate any provision of the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Proposals for Medicare drug benefits have already become an
issue in many election campaigns this year. But Rep. Bill Archer,
the Texas Republican who is chairman of the Ways and Means
Committee, said Tuesday, ``We want to work with President Clinton
in a bipartisan fashion to make a prescription drug benefit under
Medicare a reality, not a political bumper sticker.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-00 2044EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
