<DOCNO> NYT20000502.0293 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3691 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-CUBAN-BOY-REPUBS-(TRI     05-02 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-REPUBS-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESSIONAL GOP PULLING BACK FROM CALLS FOR HEARINGS ON ELIAN 
</HEADLINE>
   By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After a barrage of fiery talk critical of the
Justice Department's raid to retrieve Elian Gonzalez, Senate and
House Republicans are now distancing themselves from the case,
agreeing they are no longer sure that hearings are warranted.
</P>
<P>
   Descriptions of ``jack-booted thugs'' and ``storm troopers''
have been all but muted in the last few days, replaced by a
cautious call for answers, maybe even just written ones, from the
Justice Department about its decision to send heavily armed agents
into a private home.
</P>
<P>
   While several prominent Republicans, including Sen. Trent Lott,
the majority leader, still want to publicly delve into the Elian
case, many others have come to realize that doing so could be a
grand political miscalculation.
</P>
<P>
   Those Republicans, who range from conservative to moderate, have
counseled taking a more measured approach and have helped tone down
the rhetoric surrounding the Justice Department's raid on the Miami
house of Elian's great-uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   In part, members of Congress are heeding public opinion surveys
showing that most Americans agree with Attorney General Janet
Reno's decision to raid the house; disagree with the boy's Miami
relatives who seek to prevent his return to Cuba; and scorn
Congress' desire to dredge up the details of the raid once again.
The members also recognize the political danger of hearings, which
tend to become overly partisan and often paint Republicans as
overzealous.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be turned into political theater, and I don't think
anyone wants that,'' said Sen. Don Nickles of Oklahoma, the
second-ranking Republican in the Senate, who does not routinely shy
away from investigating the Clinton administration. He added, ``I'd
like to get some answers to some questions, but I don't think we
need a big show.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Olympia Snowe, a moderate Republican from Maine, echoed
several colleagues' comments when she said she worried that
hearings would be viewed as just more political posturing on a case
that many feel has already been overpoliticized. So far, the
political fallout for Republicans in siding mostly with Elian's
Miami relatives, who have been seen by the public as intransigent,
has been minimal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would look like a lot of political grandstanding and I
would be concerned about that,'' Snowe said. ``This could be done
without hearings.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In his weekly news conference, Rep. Dick Armey, the House
majority leader, seemed to search for the mildest characterizations
he could find to talk about both the Elian case and the possibility
of hearings. After calling the photograph of a federal agent with
the submachine gun removing Elian from a closet in the Miami house
``frightening,'' Armey said that members needed ``to sit down and
talk about'' hearings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know the answer to whether or not a hearing will be
necessary,'' he said. ``Depends on how forthcoming they are to any
inquiries our guys make.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Mayor Rudolph Giuliani of New York, who had referred to the
agents who seized Elian as ``storm troopers,'' has lowered the
volume as he considers a run for the Senate. At a speech to more
than 1,000 fellow Republicans in Saratoga Springs, N.Y., on Friday,
he refrained from calling the raid ``unconscionable,'' as he
previously had; nor did he lay blame for the raid, as he did
earlier last week, on ``Fidel Castro, Bill Clinton and Janet
Reno.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   John Kingdon, professor emeritus of political science at the
University of Michigan, said Republicans may have initially misread
the Elian case, especially the level of outrage about the raid and
the photograph of the agent with the gun. They also appeared to
underestimate the power of another set of photographs, those of a
beaming father and son.
</P>
<P>
   Their calculations also shifted after Reno and her deputies
appeared on television numerous times to discuss the case and
defend their actions. While Republicans say a number of legitimate
questions remain unanswered, the Justice Department has already
tried to address concerns about cost and the search warrant. And
Reno has spoken of the events leading up to the raid.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have really miscalculated the political benefits,''
Kingdon said of the Republicans.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At this point, Senate hearings would most likely last one or two
days and focus on whether the raid was legal and proper, Lott said.
The House has said it will begin a ``preliminary inquiry.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican retreat began last week when Sen. Orrin Hatch of
Utah, the chairman of the Judiciary Committee, who had hastily
called a hearing for this Wednesday, postponed it because the
Justice Department had failed to produce the information he sought.
On Sunday, Hatch raised the possibility that his committee might
not hold hearings if the department documents adequately explain
its decision.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Tuesday, Hatch said he was still waiting for the
department to turn over the requested documents. He also criticized
Reno for making television appearances in the midst of pleading for
more time to collect the documents.
</P>
<P>
   From the start of the case in November _ when Elian was rescued
in the Atlantic Ocean after a vessel carrying Cuban emigres sank,
claiming the life of his mother _ many Republicans were quick to
side with Cuban-Americans in Miami who fought to keep the boy in
the United States, even if it meant separating him from his father
in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Top Republicans leaders, including presidential candidates,
unleashed sharp attacks on Castro and argued that the boy's case
should be heard in a state family court, even though it has no
jurisdiction over an immigration case.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, treading carefully, broke with the
Clinton administration and also suggested that the case was best
left to the courts.
</P>
<P>
   In January, with Congress just back from its recess, Republicans
pushed for a bill to make Elian a citizen. But in another retreat,
Republican leaders dropped the effort, without saying so outright,
after it became clear they lacked the votes in their own party to
push the bill.
</P>
<P>
   A number of Republicans viewed the Elian case as a family issue
_ a son being kept from his father _ and found it difficult to
support any measure that suggested the two should not be reunited.
They were not the most vocal, but their influence was considerable.
</P>
<P>
   At stake is a crucial group of Cuban-American voters, which
leans Republican but helped deliver Florida to President Clinton in
1996. Some analysts say Republicans were just trying to help George
W. Bush, the presumptive Republican presidential nominee, win
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``Utlimately, it's a Florida issue,'' said Brian Kennedy, a
Republican political consultant. ``Some would suggest that if Gore
can deny Bush Florida, Gore would be hard to beat. Republicans want
to remind people that it was the Clinton administration that came
in and pointed guns to take this boy back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-00 2045EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000502.0294 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3692 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w BC-TEENS-CLINTONS-BOS &LR;      05-02 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEENS-CLINTONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE CONFERENCE OFFERS ADVICE TO PARENTS WITH TEENS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It may take a village to raise a child, but as most
parents know, that pales next to the time, patience, and
perseverance required to rear a healthy teenager.
</P>
<P>
   To explore the issue, Hillary Rodham Clinton Tuesday hosted the
first White House Conference on Teenagers, which assembled experts,
activists, adolescents, and even actors who offered more counsel to
concerned parents than criticism of the teenage culture.
</P>
<P>
   There was common-sense advice (eat meals with your teenager);
new research (the brain's gray matter expands at puberty); and an
executive order aimed at ending discrimination against parents in
the federal workplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe it or not, there are still some employers who are
reluctant to hire or to promote employees who have children at
home,'' said President Clinton, who was introduced by Mrs. Clinton
as her ``co-parent.'' The president said he signed the executive
order to say, ``No glass ceiling for parents. The job they are
doing at home is more important anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   The daylong event followed the teenage killings at Columbine
High School by a year and the teen shooting of seven children at
Washington's National Zoo by a week. It also comes in the thick of
the political season when pollsters see work-family pressures
emerging as a potent issue, especially among women voters, and when
Mrs. Clinton is running for the US Senate in New York as an
advocate of families and children.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady said she understands that it's hard being an
adolescent today _ harder than when she was a girl - and that the
teen years can be times of great stress, alienation, and confusion.
But, speaking as the mother of a daughter just-turned-20, Mrs.
Clinton said her heart goes out to parents of teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents are worried about the movies their children are
seeing, the Web sites they are visiting, the music they are
listening to,'' said Mrs. Clinton, who moderated two panels for
several hundred guests in the East Room of the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of worry that all those heart-to-heart talks
and those efforts to communicate, which are sometimes so awkward
and difficult, about values and good behavior, are getting drowned
out by a popular culture filled with gratuitous sex and violence,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton shared some personal observations. One was that
even with their hectic schedules, she and the president always
tried to eat at least one meal a day with Chelsea before she went
to college. And Mrs. Clinton admitted the reason the First Couple
didn't plunge into the Washington social scene during the first
term was because they needed to stay in the White House, ``hanging
around, waiting for a (Chelsea) sighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, when you have one (teenager) in your home, you want
to hang around with the hope that just maybe they'll deign to say
something to you,'' Mrs. Clinton said. ``Occasionally it worked,
but not always.''
</P>
<P>
   A survey released Tuesday by the YMCA of the USA showed
teenagers are concerned about the lack of time they spend with
their parents and the depth of their communication. In responses
from 200 parents and 200 teens, the poll found that 61 percent of
parents say they talk frequently to their children about values and
beliefs, but only 41 percent of the teens report having those
conservations.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Galinksy, head of the Families and Work Institute in New
York, said her studies show teenagers want strong relationships
with their parents and value quality over quantity time. They wish
their parents weren't always so tired and under stress, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Psychological connectedness'' of parents to children _ talking
to them on the phone, leaving notes on the refrigerator, assigning
them responsibilities and chores _ is the best prescription for
lowering the risk of unhealthy teen behavior, said Dr. Robert Blum
of the University of Minnesota. Access to weapons in the home, peer
drug use, and sexual victimization all raise the risk, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jeffrey Brown, pastor of Union Baptist Church in
Cambridge and co-founder of the Boston's Ten Point Coalition to
check youth violence, said Blum's message of making teenagers
responsible was one he would carry home. Brown said the message he
himself brought to the conference was that ``building a dialogue
between families and teenagers relates to transforming
neighborhoods and communities.''
</P>
<P>
   Three teenagers, all success stories, spoke about the strength
of their family bonds. Edwin Speaker, 17, of Los Angeles, said he
was nervous _ ``How many kids get to fly six hours and stand right
next to the first lady?'' _ but not afraid to speak up about his
relationship with his single father: ``It takes a man to raise a
man,'' Edwin said.
</P>
<P>
   Actor Danny DeVito, the father of three teenagers, said parents
need to tell children ``they weren't always so perfect, like they
are now.'' DeVito and his wife, Rhea Perlman, are leading a group
called the After School Alliance, which aims to provide quality,
after-school care in all of the nation's elementary schools by
2010.
</P>
<P>
   The president said his 2001 budget request to Congress includes
doubling the funds to $1 billion for after-school and summer-school
programs. He has also called for expanding the Family and Medical
Leave Act to include more firms and purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said a new report by his Council of Economic Advisers
presented a mixed picture of today's teenager. ``The good news is
that teenagers are far healthier, more prosperous, and look forward
to more promising lives than ever before in our history,'' he said.
But he cited ``a significant opportunity gap'' between white and
minority students, and he said the incidence of teen smoking, drug
use, pregnancy, and gun violence remain ``too high.''
</P>
<P>
   The conference, aimed at giving attention to what experts say is
an understudied social issue and getting the family-advocacy
community energized, explored everything from Internet technology
(many teenagers know more than their parents, Mrs. Clinton said),
to new adolescent brain research.
</P>
<P>
   According to Dr. Jay Giedd of the National Institute of Mental
Health, preliminary data from sophisticated new scanners indicates
that while the brain is 95 percent formed by the first grade, there
is a second growth spurt during puberty. The implication is thicker
gray matter, Giedd said, and it suggests teenagers can ``use it or
lose it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-00 2048EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
