<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3694 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-JACOBS-MANAGEMENT-ART     05-02 1414
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACOBS-MANAGEMENT-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KELLOGG'S JACOBS, THE DEAN OF BUSINESS SCHOOL DEANS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass., Ill., Pa., N.J., Germany, Hong Kong, Israel and
Thailand)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT11 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DAVID LEONHARDT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EVANSTON, Ill. _ Donald P. Jacobs jumps into a swimming pool
every day at 6:30 a.m. and spends 45 minutes doing laps. During
rainstorms, he sometimes dashes without an umbrella between
buildings on the Northwestern University campus here, even as the
wind off Lake Michigan musses his hair. When he gives public
speeches, he often wears a sweatshirt. When he finds something
funny, he throws his head back, crosses his arms over his chest as
if to hug himself and guffaws.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs has a rather loose style for a business school dean,
especially one who passed the traditional retirement age seven
years ago. But nothing is frivolous about his accomplishments: No
one has had a greater effect on management education in the United
States than he has, say his peers at schools around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Few of them can remember when he was not around. This spring,
Jacobs is celebrating his 25th anniversary at the helm of the
Kellogg Graduate School of Management at Northwestern. He has held
his job longer than any current major university president or other
business school dean, higher education experts say. When he took
over, Cal Ripken Jr. was playing high school baseball and Pope John
Paul II was still Karol Wojtyla, archbishop of Cracow.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Jacobs created the prototype of the modern
business school, management experts say. Well before many of its
rivals, Kellogg interviewed all its applicants, published students'
evaluations of its professors' teaching skills and encouraged
students to help design the curriculum.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Kellogg caters to its students as if they were
customers. It unabashedly considers the teaching of skills like
teamwork and social networking as central to its mission, and seeks
students who agree. ``If you think you are that kind of person, you
fit,'' Jacobs recently told a group of accepted applicants. ``If
not, this is the time to get the hell out,'' he added, as the room
burst into laughter.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the changes _ many of which once seemed heretical in
the world of higher education _ and to the recruitment of ambitious
young professors, the school that once had little respect on its
own campus steadily climbed the national rankings, securing a solid
spot in the top five and forcing more prestigious schools to
imitate it.
</P>
<P>
   Professors say Jacobs is the symbol for the business school boom
that over the last quarter century has tripled, to 100,000, the
number of MBA's awarded each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has quite done what Don has done,'' said Rajat Gupta,
the managing partner of McKinsey &AMP; Co., who sits on advisory boards
at Kellogg, Harvard and the universities of Chicago and
Pennsylvania. ``Which is to transform an average school into a
top-five school and keep it there for some time.''
</P>
<P>
   In a business world that craves speed and flexibility, Jacobs, a
tall, jovial, blunt-speaking economist, has also become something
of a model manager himself, his colleagues say. Kellogg, with a
relatively small administrative staff, relies on its version of
factory-floor employees _ its students _ to study many of its
problems and suggest solutions. Unlike many academic institutions,
it acts quickly, putting in place pilot programs and taking time
later to decide whether they deserve a permanent place in the
curriculum. ``He pushes constant change,'' said Robert Duncan, a
professor of leadership who has taught at the school since 1970.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, for example, reacting to student criticism that
Kellogg had not devoted enough attention to the Internet and risked
falling behind its peers, Jacobs and a few faculty members drew up
plans for an e-commerce major that includes 16 courses. It is
already the third-most popular major at the school. Kellogg also
now offers an executive education class on the Internet every
month.
</P>
<P>
   At the core of Jacobs' strategy has been strengthening the ties
between the ivory tower and a business world that sometimes views
intellectuals as eggheads. Over the skepticism of other
Northwestern officials, he built an executive education center 20
years ago that now brings in $93 million a year and has inspired
similar versions at Stanford, Pennsylvania and other schools. He
was also among the first deans to encourage professors to make
international trips a part of actual classes.
</P>
<P>
   He himself continues to teach every year, both the full-time day
students and the executives who pass through. Between 1975 and
1979, he served as the chairman of Amtrak and has also been a
director for First Chicago, Commonwealth Edison and Hart Marx, the
high-end clothing company. (One of his board stints, on a
meat-packing company, turned him into a vegetarian, he said, after
he had learned the details of the industry's operations.)
</P>
<P>
   A competitive man whose sometimes fiery temper has cooled only
recently, friends say, and who needs little provocation before
lobbing insults about the nearby University of Chicago, Jacobs says
Kellogg makes a legitimate claim to be the nation's top business
school. More removed experts call that wishful thinking, if only
barely. Given the choice, most students enroll at Harvard or
Stanford over Kellogg, for example. After building a top-notch
business faculty, Kellogg has lost a few academic stars to rival
schools in the last three years whom it has failed to replace with
researchers of the same rank, professors say.
</P>
<P>
   What most management experts agree on, however, is that few
graduate schools of any kind have come as far as Kellogg has over
the last 25 years, and few institutions bear the mark of their
leader as much as this one. ``His personality really infuses the
place,'' said Mike Miles, the former chairman of Philip Morris who
heads the school's advisory board.
</P>
<P>
   Some students and professors worry that Kellogg's biggest
problem is that Jacobs has not surrounded himself with strong
candidates to replace him, even though he says he will definitely
retire, and spend more time teaching, within the next few years.
``There's nobody that is a natural successor to Jacobs within the
school right now,'' said James Schlesinger Jr., the former editor
of the student paper, who will graduate this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs grew up as the son of bakers on the far west side of
Chicago, three blocks from the suburb of Oak Park that Frank Lloyd
Wright was making famous. Until junior high school he suffered from
what doctors would now call dyslexia and, he said, is still
terrible at remembering names. He enlisted in the Navy at the age
of 17, just weeks before Japan surrendered in World War II. He
returned home and attended Roosevelt University in Chicago, where
an economics professor encouraged him to take up the subject.
Jacobs eventually earned a doctorate in economics at Columbia. ``I
never, ever thought of being anything but a professor,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He got his first job at City College but, not wanting to raise
children in New York, began looking around in the mid-1950s.
Northwestern's business school was the next place to offer him a
position, Jacobs said. The dean at the time, Richard Donham, son of
the founding dean of Harvard Business School, said Jacobs could
have a job if he promised to teach in the executive education
program, a forum that many faculty members considered
intellectually weak. Donham ``wouldn't have hired me if I wouldn't
do it,'' Jacobs said.
</P>
<P>
   The experience changed his view of business education and,
eventually, remade Kellogg.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next two decades, Jacobs taught finance, took regular
sabbaticals in Washington and, in 1974, found himself on a search
committee to find a replacement for John Barr, the former chief
executive of the giant retailer Montgomery Ward who was then
stepping down as head of Northwestern's business school. The
committee offered the job to a French diplomat and to
administrators at both Princeton University and the University of
Pennsylvania. All three said no.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then the search committee,'' said Duncan, another
committee member, ``almost in desperation, said: `Enough is enough.
Somebody's got to be dean.'''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs, as the senior faculty member on the committee, was the
choice, and he set aside his academic career to accept the post.
``He wasn't thrilled about it,'' Duncan said. ``I don't know that
anyone was thrilled about it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jacobs threw himself into the job. On his first day, a
Monday, he told the outgoing dean that he wanted the school to
focus, in part, on the teaching of business people who were in
their 30s and 40s and no longer interested in attending school
full-time. By Friday, he was meeting with James Allen, a founder of
Booz Allen &AMP; Hamilton, to pitch his idea to build a separate
executive education center for weeklong and monthlong classes. The
following Monday, Allen agreed to finance much of the project, and
the planning began.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs' idea was hardly met with unanimous enthusiasm. ``The
university thought he was crazy,'' said Meyer Feldberg, now the
dean at Columbia, who was the center's first director. More
prestigious schools like Harvard already had thriving programs, and
with the U.S. economy mired in an inflation-induced funk, companies
were not rushing to make large new investments.
</P>
<P>
   When the center, named for Allen, opened in 1979, the corporate
landscape was starting to change. The globalization of markets and
the acceleration of technological change had made doing business
more complicated. The Allen Center had little trouble filling its
seats, and Northwestern professors soon had the advantage of being
in constant contact with their core audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our faculty were good theorists,'' Jacobs said, ``but they
honestly understood the problems businesses really faced. It was
one of the things that made us different.''
</P>
<P>
   The Allen Center also became an unofficial advertisement for
Kellogg, as the school became known in 1979 after a gift from
relatives of the cereal company family who were largely unconnected
to the business. After a few weeks of study in Evanston, executives
went home more willing to consider Northwestern graduates as well
as the Harvard, Pennsylvania and Chicago MBA's that they had long
hired.
</P>
<P>
   ``His strategy was absolutely clever,'' said Robert Hamada, dean
of Chicago's Graduate School of Business, offering a rare
compliment for the local competition. ``He was the first of the
major deans _ and he wasn't even a major dean at the time _ to
think in terms of marketing.'' After years of ignoring the market,
Chicago itself began offering executive classes a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, Kellogg burnished its reputation as a real-world
business school that emphasized teamwork. ``The notion that people
work cooperatively is almost un-American,'' Jacobs said. ``We've
built a culture that is contrary to people's idea of business
education.''
</P>
<P>
   The dean also signed alliances with schools in Germany, Hong
Kong, Israel and Thailand in an effort to overcome Northwestern's
reputation as a heartland school lacking an international outlook.
The school has never achieved the academic prestige of its rivals _
no faculty member has ever won a Nobel Prize, for instance _ but
among applicants and recruiters, it remains as popular as any other
school.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs' biggest headache now is how to exit gracefully and allow
a smooth transition. It is a problem the students in his corporate
governance classes study in detail but one that he says is
difficult to solve at a university, where a successor must be
chosen by a search committee rather than groomed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question of succession drives me crazy,'' Jacobs said. ``A
well-run organization probably would have gotten rid of me by
now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-00 2051EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000502.0298 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3696 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-BIOWAR-NYT     05-02 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BIOWAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT LINKS U.S. SUPPORT FOR RUSSIAN LABS TO POSSIBLE GERM
WEAPONS 
</HEADLINE>
  By JUDITH MILLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the Clinton administration seeks a tenfold increase in money
for Russian-American biological cooperation, the General Accounting
Office has concluded that American support could inadvertently help
Russian scientists and former weapons labs make germ weapons.
</P>
<P>
   In a new report to be published this week, the GAO presents no
evidence that Moscow is conducting such illegal research or making
germ weapons. Nor does the report state that American assistance to
Russian labs and scientists is being diverted for military
purposes. But Congress' independent auditing agency said that
despite the administration's efforts to reduce the risks of such
misuse or diversion, there is no way to prevent Russian scientists
from ``potentially using their skills or research outputs to later
work on offensive weapons activities at any of the Russian military
institutes that remain closed to the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The report, a copy of which was obtained by The New York Times,
says that such concerns have been intensified by Russia's
unwillingness to open four military labs to inspection or visits by
foreign scientists. It also chides Moscow for retaining the ``Cold
War leadership'' of the germ weapons complex in key posts,
including Gen. Yuri T. Kalinin, who heads Biopreparat, an
organization that once directed the Soviet Union's germ warfare
program.
</P>
<P>
   In a written response to the GAO's concerns, the administration
argues that the risks of not helping 15,000 impoverished Russian
bio-weaponeers at some 50 institutes throughout the former Soviet
Union far outweigh the risks of doing so. Scientists desperate for
employment would likely find work with rogue states like Iran, the
administration argued.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can stay home and wish the problem away, or we can confront
it head on at the source,'' one administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, officials cite what they call quiet breakthroughs in
scientific cooperation with the Russians that have enhanced their
confidence that Moscow is getting out of the germ weapons business.
For instance, a team of Russian scientists that once made a deadly
strain of anthrax gave their American counterparts at the Centers
for Disease Control and Prevention in Atlanta two rare anthrax
strains last week as part of a long-awaited exchange program.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials also cite some progress in efforts to
open up Russia's closed military germ labs. A group of Russian
military scientists has agreed to visit American
chemical-biological defense centers this summer as part of another
exchange program, officials disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO report is likely to help fuel a long-simmering debate
over whether Russia is still making germ weapons or conducting
illegal research and development, as the Soviet Union did after
signing a 1972 treaty that banned germ weapons. Former President
Boris N. Yeltsin declared in 1992 that Russia had ended its germ
warfare program and told Washington he would dismiss General
Kalinin, a former intelligence officer. But the general still heads
Biopreparat, which, even though it has been reborn as a state-owned
drug company, still controls many key Russian institutes, though it
no longer finances them. Russian officials and the general have
denied that Russia is making germ weapons or conducting illegal
research.
</P>
<P>
   To help prevent the spread of deadly scientific knowledge from
Russia to Iran, Iraq, and other potentially dangerous states, the
administration has provided about $20 million between fiscal 1994
and 1999 to support collaborative research projects in Russia that
redirect former germ weapons scientists to peaceful research
activities. Between fiscal 2000 and 2004, the administration plans
to spend at least $220 million to expand efforts to engage former
Soviet germ weapons institutes.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Floyd D. Spence, the Republican chairman of the House Armed
Services Committee, said Tuesday that the GAO report ``reinforces
my concern that the administration's plans to increase assistance
to Russia could exacerbate the risk of a renewed Russian offensive
biological weapons effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Several experts disagreed. Amy E. Smithson, a defense expert at
the Henry L. Stimson Center in Washington who toured some of the
six labs that the GAO team visited, said that the report contained
considerable evidence that the administration's program was
effective.
</P>
<P>
   She noted, for instance, that the report says that American
support has prompted former Soviet scientists at some 15 labs to
reject an offer to cooperate with states like Iran. ``The American
auditing of its grants is usually very tight,'' Smithson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the State Department finds evidence that a scientist has
gone astray, the institute loses its grant. Whenever the U.S. has
placed that choice before a Russian scientist or lab, the answer is
always: `We're on your team,''' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
