<SLUG> BC-RAC-DERBY-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW MEMBERS TAKE SAME HALLWAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. - The Kentucky Derby is central to the stories
of four of the five new Racing Hall of Fame members introduced
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Neil Drysdale has favorite Fusaichi Pegasus and
contender War Chant in Saturday's 126th running of the Derby.
Drysdale-trained A.P. Indy (elected in the ``contemporary-male''
category) became one of the great what-ifs when he had to be
scratched from the 1992 Derby with a foot injury. Winning Colors
(``contemporary female'') won the Derby in 1988. Needles (``horse
of yesteryear'') won it in 1956.
</P>
<P>
   The other 2000 inductee will be jockey Julie Krone, and although
she never finished better than 11th in the Derby, she gets
emotional thinking about how her career began here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not usually much of a crier,'' said Krone, who is the
first woman jockey elected to the Hall of Fame at Saratoga Springs,
N.Y. ``But flying here (Monday), I ended up crying on the airplane,
thinking about being 15 years old and driving to Churchill Downs
with my mother to begin my career as a jockey.''
</P>
<P>
   Krone's mother, Judy, died of cancer last year at Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've almost dialed her phone three times (to say), `Mom, I
made the Hall of Fame!' '' Krone said. ``She'll have to be watching
from heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   Krone won 3,545 races, including the 1993 Belmont Stakes aboard
Colonial Affair, in a 19-year career that ended in 1999. She is
developing a broadcasting career, including intertrack-TV race
analysis at Hollywood Park.
</P>
<P>
   She downplayed the first-woman angle, saying, ``Just being in
the Hall of Fame itself, that's the cake, the frosting, the
sprinkling, the candles and everything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Clocking The Deputy: Santa Anita Derby winner The Deputy went 5
furlongs in 1:00 under Chris McCarron on a Churchill Downs track
rated ``fast'' despite light rain Tuesday morning. That's the time
the official clockers recorded, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Jenine Sahadi said she timed the work in 1:00 1/5.
McCarron said he got it in 1:00 2/5. McCarron is the rare jockey
who clocks workouts while riding them. He said that unless his
mount is pulling hard, his hands are together on the horse's neck,
so punching the buttons on his digital wristwatch isn't difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of riders say they have a clock in their heads. Well, I
have one on my wrist,'' said McCarron, who won the Derby with
Alysheba (1987) and Go for Gin (1993).
</P>
<P>
   Snuck out: Arkansas Derby runner-up Snuck In will skip the Derby
and aim for the May 20 Preakness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
