<HEADLINE>
REPORT LINKS U.S. SUPPORT FOR RUSSIAN LABS TO POSSIBLE GERM
WEAPONS 
</HEADLINE>
  By JUDITH MILLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the Clinton administration seeks a tenfold increase in money
for Russian-American biological cooperation, the General Accounting
Office has concluded that American support could inadvertently help
Russian scientists and former weapons labs make germ weapons.
</P>
<P>
   In a report to be published this week, the GAO presents no
evidence that Moscow is conducting such illegal research or making
germ weapons. Nor does the report state that American assistance to
Russian labs and scientists is being diverted for military
purposes. But Congress' independent auditing agency said that
despite the administration's efforts to reduce the risks of such
misuse or diversion, there is no way to prevent Russian scientists
from ``potentially using their skills or research outputs to later
work on offensive weapons activities at any of the Russian military
institutes that remain closed to the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The report, a copy of which was obtained by The New York Times,
says that such concerns have been intensified by Russia's
unwillingness to open four military labs to inspection or visits by
foreign scientists. It also chides Moscow for retaining the ``Cold
War leadership'' of the germ weapons complex in key posts,
including Gen. Yuri T. Kalinin, who heads Biopreparat, an
organization that once directed the Soviet Union's germ warfare
program.
</P>
<P>
   In a written response to the GAO's concerns, the administration
argues that the risks of not helping 15,000 impoverished Russian
bio-weaponeers at some 50 institutes throughout the former Soviet
Union far outweigh the risks of doing so. Scientists desperate for
employment would likely find work with nations like Iran, the
administration argued.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can stay home and wish the problem away, or we can confront
it head on at the source,'' one administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, officials cite what they call quiet breakthroughs in
scientific cooperation with the Russians that have enhanced their
confidence that Moscow is getting out of the germ weapons business.
For instance, a team of Russian scientists that once made a deadly
strain of anthrax gave their American counterparts at the Centers
for Disease Control and Prevention in Atlanta two rare anthrax
strains last week as part of a long-awaited exchange program.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials also cite some progress in efforts to
open up Russia's closed military germ labs. A group of Russian
military scientists has agreed to visit American
chemical-biological defense centers this summer as part of another
exchange program, officials disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO report is likely to help fuel a long-simmering debate
over whether Russia is still making germ weapons or conducting
illegal research and development, as the Soviet Union did after
signing a 1972 treaty that banned germ weapons. Former President
Boris N. Yeltsin declared in 1992 that Russia had ended its germ
warfare program and told Washington he would dismiss General
Kalinin, a former intelligence officer. But the general still heads
Biopreparat, which, even though it has been reborn as a state-owned
drug company, still controls many key Russian institutes, though it
no longer finances them. Russian officials and the general have
denied that Russia is making germ weapons or conducting illegal
research.
</P>
<P>
   To help prevent the spread of deadly scientific knowledge from
Russia to Iran, Iraq, and other potentially dangerous states, the
administration has provided about $20 million between fiscal 1994
and 1999 to support collaborative research projects in Russia that
redirect former germ weapons scientists to peaceful research
activities. Between fiscal 2000 and 2004, the administration plans
to spend at least $220 million to expand efforts to engage former
Soviet germ weapons institutes.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Floyd D. Spence, the Republican chairman of the House Armed
Services Committee, said Tuesday that the GAO report ``reinforces
my concern that the administration's plans to increase assistance
to Russia could exacerbate the risk of a renewed Russian offensive
biological weapons effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Several experts disagreed. Amy E. Smithson, a defense expert at
the Henry L. Stimson Center in Washington who toured some of the
six labs that the GAO team visited, said that the report contained
considerable evidence that the administration's program was
effective.
</P>
<P>
   She noted, for instance, that the report says that American
support has prompted former Soviet scientists at some 15 labs to
reject an offer to cooperate with states like Iran. ``The American
auditing of its grants is usually very tight,'' Smithson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the State Department finds evidence that a scientist has
gone astray, the institute loses its grant. Whenever the U.S. has
placed that choice before a Russian scientist or lab, the answer is
always: `We're on your team,''' she said.
</P>
