<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Time Warner and Disney Agree to Temporary Truce
</P>
<P>
   Under increasing pressuring, Time Warner restored the signals of
ABC television stations to 3.5 million homes after agreeing to a
temporary truce with Walt Disney. The settlement ended a 39-hour
blackout and put off until July 15 a deadline for Time Warner and
Disney to come to terms on how Disney would be compensated by the
cable company for use of its network stations on the cable systems.
</P>
<P>
   Auto Sales Boom Despite Naysayers
</P>
<P>
   Economists and auto executives have been predicting for the last
several months that auto sales would soon slow significantly. That
has not happened. Adjusting for seasonal variations, sales were up
10.5 percent from the extremely strong level of April last year.
</P>
<P>
   Adventure, the Chinese Way
</P>
<P>
   In business school, you write your thesis on how to manage
for-profit schools. After more research, you take your idea and a
20-year plan to a developing country on the other side of the
planet. Are you crazy? Many thought he was, says Seth Kaplan, who
is in Shanghai, with 16{ years left to go on his plan to develop a
chain of universities in China. ``In China, you must be ready to
create and take opportunities the Chinese way,'' he says. His
stories bear him out.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T Comments Send Stocks Down
</P>
<P>
   Stocks fell broadly yesterday after AT&AMP;T delivered a cautious
profit outlook and investors took profits from a three-day rally in
technology shares. The Dow Jones industrial average fell 80.66
points, to 10,731.12. The Nasdaq composite index slipped 172.63
points, or 4.4 percent, to 3,785.45. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index dropped 21.96 points, or 1.5 percent, to 1,446.29.
</P>
<P>
   A Power Shift at Arista Records
</P>
<P>
   In a long-expected power shift, Antonio Reid was formally named
the new chief executive of Arista Records, the 25-year-old pop
powerhouse that for months has been bracing for the departure of
its founder and longtime leader, Clive Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton Focuses on China Trade Bill
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and his top aides, acknowledging that they
lack enough votes to pass a crucial China trade measure later this
month, increased pressure on Congress by emphasizing national
security issues.
</P>
<P>
   New-Home Sales Up 4.5 Percent in March
</P>
<P>
   Sales of new single-family homes unexpectedly rose 4.5 percent
in March, to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 966,000 units
after falling 0.6 percent in February. The sales rate was the
largest since the 995,000 units reported in November 1998. The
median price of a new home rose 3.1 percent, to $165,000 in March
from $160,000 a month earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Media Service Agencies to Merge
</P>
<P>
   B Com3 is merging its media services agencies, Starcom Worldwide
and Mediavest Worldwide, to form a media planning and buying
behemoth, Starcom Mediavest Group.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate Jets Make a Comeback
</P>
<P>
   The corporate jet business has come back at full throttle,
thanks to a booming economy, a reaction against the delays and
frustrations of commercial airlines, and a pronounced change in
attitudes as corporate managers justify the expense of a company
plane as a business tool.
</P>
<P>
   Gannett's Succession Plans Set
</P>
<P>
   The chief executive of Gannett, John Curley, is stepping down in
June but will remain chairman until he retires next year. Douglas
McCorkindale, who has been the company's president since 1997, will
succeed him.
</P>
</TEXT>
