<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3705 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r BC-CAR-MAYFIELD0503-COX     05-02 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-MAYFIELD0503-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Illegal fuel: Mayfield team busted
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After more than two weeks of delay, the NASCAR police
on Tuesday finally caught up with Jeremy Mayfield and the rest of
his race team.
</P>
<P>
   The sport's governing body found the Ford No. 12 team guilty of
using an illegal fuel additive at Talladega on April 16 and issued
one of the most severe penalties in Winston Cup history.
</P>
<P>
   Owner Michael Kranefuss was fined $50,000 and stripped of 151
owner points. Crew chief Peter Sospenzo was suspended for four
races. Jeremy Mayfield had 151 driver points wiped out, which
dropped him from No. 7 to 14th in the Winston Cup points standings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mistakes were made and there were certainly some grave errors
in judgment,'' Kranefuss said in a prepared statement. ``Needless
to say, we accept the penalty, we have taken disciplinary action
within our team, and we apologize to our fans, our sponsors, NASCAR
and the other teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayfield also released a statement on Tuesday, saying, ``We're
all embarrassed and we're all going to make sure nothing like this
happens again.'' NASCAR said the team had not appealed the
penalties as of Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in NASCAR history, a team was subjected to
three different penalties for one infraction: a fine, a suspension
and the deduction of both driver and owner points.
</P>
<P>
   ``NASCAR obviously felt like (this fuel situation) was severe
enough that they had to set someone as an example,'' driver Ward
Burton said.
</P>
<P>
   The Ford No. 12 team still faces punishment for failing
post-race inspections after Mayfield won last Sunday's NAPA 500
Auto Parts 500. NASCAR determined that the car's roof was too low,
but it also conceded that it ``most likely'' occurred when Mayfield
repeatedly jumped on the roof in the winner's circle.
</P>
<P>
   Racing officials said Sunday that the team would be able to keep
the win _ the second of Mayfield's career _ but that it faces more
penalties this week.
</P>
<P>
   The Talladega controversy began when Mayfield's engine was torn
apart after the DieHard 500. Mayfield won the pole two days
earlier, but the engine breakdown was delayed because the No. 12
team decided to use the same motor in the race.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR Chief Operating Officer Mike Helton said that more than
60 fuel samples, including one from Mayfield's tank, were taken
after qualifying and that all passed inspection.
</P>
<P>
   Through an extensive series of interviews with team members in
the ensuing weeks, Helton said, the ruling body was convinced that
the illegal fuel additive was added during the race by an crew
member who acted alone and without the knowledge of any others
within the organization.
</P>
<P>
   The incident was reported to have occurred during the final pit
stop, which happened with around 25 laps remaining. Mayfield
climbed as high as fourth after leaving the pit, but ended up in
14th place.
</P>
<P>
   Under NASCAR rules, the crew chief is ``responsible for the
actions of crew members during a race'', hence Sospenzo's
suspension. Kranefuss declined Tuesday to identify the crew member
but said disciplinary actions have been taken within the team.
</P>
<P>
   Mayfield and Kranefuss were given 126 points after the car's
finishing position at Talladega. NASCAR took away those points on
Tuesday , and added a 25-point deduction because of the serious
nature of the infraction, which was tampering with fuel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've related this to when you were young and your father
pulled off his belt -- at least it was that way when I was young,''
Helton said. ``The first two whacks were from what I did (wrong),
and the last one was to make sure I didn't do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   The theory behind the illegal fuel additive, which was
oxygen-based, was to add more horsepower to the motor.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
