<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAINER DRYSDALE SUCCEEDING WITH CAUTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. - After Fusaichi Pegasus reared, threw his
exercise rider and toppled over on the Churchill Downs track in a
rambunctious moment one morning last week, somebody joked that
trainer Neil Drysdale would be forced to scratch the favorite from
Saturday's Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus hasn't been injured. But he had gotten dirty.
How could Drysdale put up with such imperfection?
</P>
<P>
   Drysdale is so different from the typical Derby trainer, he is
being portrayed as the mad genius of this Derby week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neil is unique,'' said an owner who has horses with him.
</P>
<P>
   He's better educated (University of Barcelona). He's more
worldly (he managed a stud farm in Venezuela). He sounds a lot more
like Alistair Cooke than Shug McGaughey (does a transplanted
Englishman who still says ``Darby'' deserve to win America's
greatest thoroughbred race?).
</P>
<P>
   And he might be the most cautious trainer ever actually to get a
horse to the track. A hair out of place, to exaggerate only
slightly, and a Drysdale horse will not run.
</P>
<P>
   It's no coincidence that despite the accomplishments that earned
the 52-year-old Drysdale election to the Racing Hall of Fame on
Tuesday, the most famous move of his quarter-century career was the
decision to scratch a sore-footed A.P. Indy from the 1992 Kentucky
Derby on the morning of the race.
</P>
<P>
   Drysdale says that was a ``black-and-white decision'' and will
admit to not the slightest regret or disappointment, even though
A.P. Indy's subsequent victory in the Belmont Stakes and Breeders'
Cup Classic suggested he would have been the best horse in the
Derby.
</P>
<P>
   That's Drysdale, who rejects reporters' touchy-feely questions
and tries to take emotion out of horsemanship, refusing to dream of
victory in his first Kentucky Derby because ``my job is not to
fantasize - (it's) to get the bloody horses into the gate.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if, sometimes, it appears he'd rather find an excuse to
keep them safely in their stalls.
</P>
<P>
   Drysdale has two horses in Saturday's 126th running of the
1-mile race: Japanese-owned Fusaichi Pegasus, undefeated in 2000
with three victories at Santa Anita and a romp in the Wood Memorial
at New York's Aqueduct racetrack; and War Chant, 3 for 4 after his
second-place finish to The Deputy in the Santa Anita Derby.
</P>
<P>
   They embody the Drysdale style. Each was brought along more
slowly than the textbook Derby contender, each racing only once as
a 2-year-old, War Chant because Drysdale adjusted for his late
birthdate (May 22), Fusaichi Pegasus because the trainer wanted
time for the colt to grow into his huge frame.
</P>
<P>
   Thus Drysdale defies Derby history, which shows that Proud
Clarion in 1967 was the last horse to win after failing to win a
race at 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had pushed on with them, they might not be here now,''
Drysdale said while leaning against a rental car outside Churchill
Downs' barn 41 Tuesday morning. ``My feeling is I've come here with
talented horses. If I have to choose between talent and experience,
I'll take talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus and War Chant generally do not set stopwatches
aflame in their workouts, another element of the Drysdale approach
that distinguishes him from speed-crazy American trainers eager to
please Racing Form-reading American owners.
</P>
<P>
   That's his European background at work, and the influence of the
late Hall of Famer Charlie Whittingham, whom Drysdale assisted for
four years he refers to as ``a graduate course'' in training.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neil doesn't train for owners. He trains for himself,'' said
Jeff Siegel, who was among the owners of Drysdale-trained Breeders'
Cup Turf winner Prized in 1989 and is here with The Deputy. ``He's
not obnoxious about it. He listens. But it doesn't change the way
he trains.''
</P>
<P>
   His fastidiousness, his emphasis on patience and planning might
frustrate owners and drive away potential clients. But it's hard to
argue with his results: five champions, including 1992 Horse of the
Year A.P. Indy, and five Breeders' Cup winners.
</P>
<P>
   Because Drysdale8Ac
</P>
</TEXT>
