<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA TRADE BILL GAINING IN HOUSE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton warned Tuesday that it would be a
``terrible mistake'' for Congress to deny the permanent extension
of U.S. trade benefits to China, as he joined with Republican
leaders in a harder pitch for the measure when it comes to a vote
later this month.
</P>
<P>
   Passage in the Senate is virtually assured, with at least 60
senators expected to back it in a vote planned for June. But the
vote in the House, scheduled for May 22, could be close with
organized labor leading the fight against it.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Clinton and Republican leaders expressed confidence
that they will have the 218 votes needed to win approval in the
House.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement Tuesday by Rep. Steny Hoyer, D-Md., that he
intends to support the bill should boost that confidence even more.
Hoyer is co-chair of the Democratic Steering Committee and the
highest ranking Democrat so far to come out in favor of permanent
trade relations with China. Several other Democrats and Republicans
also moved Tuesday from the undecided ranks to support the bill,
which gave House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, and other
leading backers of the measure even more cause for optimism.
</P>
<P>
   ``The battleground's been in the House. ... But we've picked up
a couple of good votes on our side, and the president seems to be
working as well. So, we're going to be driving hard (for final
passage),'' Armey said.
</P>
<P>
   He refused to say how many Republicans and Democrats are on
board in favor of the bill. But Rep. Robert Matsui, D-Calif., who
is leading the administration's effort in Congress on the measure,
said he believes that at least 160 Republicans will back the bill
along with at least 60 Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton stepped up his own lobbying efforts on behalf of the
bill Tuesday, urging House and Senate members not to succumb to
arguments that the permanent extension of normal trade status to
China will end up costing U.S. jobs, harming the environment and
reinforcing Beijing's disregard of human rights concerns.
</P>
<P>
   He also intensified his lobbying campaign by hosting a meeting
between undecided lawmakers and Hong Kong Democratic Party leader
Martin Lee, a critic of Chinese human rights abuses who believes
that improved trade relations with Beijing will lead to more
democratic freedoms.
</P>
<P>
   In two separate appearances before the Council for the Americas
and the Independent Insurance Agents of America, Clinton called
passage of the measure a matter of national security and insisted
the benefits to the U.S. economy would far outweigh any drawbacks.
He said granting permanent trade status would also increase the
likelihood that more democratic reforms will take hold in China.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a national security point of view, it would be a very,
very unwise and precarious move to say that the United States
doesn't care whether they're part of the world community or not,''
Clinton told the insurance organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``The answer is not to turn back,'' he added later in a speech
to the council. ``The answer is to keep going forward, to spread
the benefits to more people.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a terrible mistake for the United States ever to
send a signal that we have any policy other than full-steam ahead,
more engagement, more support, more commitment. I think that is
very, very important,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   As the president spoke, House Ways and Means Chairman Bill
Archer, R-Texas, was busy trying to drum up support for the
measure, which would extend the same kind of U.S. tariffs and other
benefits to Beijing that most other countries now have. It would
also eliminate the annual review by Congress that China must
undergo in order to keep its normal trade status designation.
</P>
<P>
   In an appearance at the U.S. Chamber of Commerce, Archer also
indicated he might back an amendment to the trade measure that
would create a commission to monitor human rights violations in
China if it would help persuade some undecided lawmakers to support
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``My preference is for a clean bill,'' Archer said. ``But
because I feel so strongly about the importance of extending
(permanent normal trade relations) to China, I am willing to look
at proposals which would ensure victory.''
</P>
<P>
   Passage of permanent trade benefits could help ease China's
entry into the World Trade Organization, even though Beijing is
expected to eventually gain admittance to the WTO anyway.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
