<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: MASHBURN, THE PLAYER ABLE TO ROCK THE KNICK BOAT 
</HEADLINE>
   By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It does not take a genius to handicap this one. The banged-up,
skill-challenged, hungry Heat will starve to death against the
Knicks on shots forced up as the 24-second clock winds down, on too
many paint-by-number offensive possessions. On Miami's 2000
tombstone will read an inscription that could be the title of Pat
Riley's next book.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eighty Is Not Enough,'' it will say.
</P>
<P>
   Unless they know something in Miami we don't. Unless Tim
Hardaway isn't talking about the health of his foot because he
doesn't want to divulge the source of his cure. Unless Alonzo
Mourning has developed a go-to move. Or unless Jamal Mashburn is
finally ready to do what coaches have been after him to do since
high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we were playing Tolentine, which had Adrian Autrey and
Brian Reese, and Jamal was like a man on a mission,'' said Tom
Murray, four decades the coach at Cardinal Hayes in the Bronx. ``He
went out and got 39. But, yes, sometimes there was frustration
because you wanted him to do more. Most of the time, he never had
it in him to just take over.''
</P>
<P>
   With Mashburn in 1990, Murray won his only city title, so this
was not meant as criticism, just an honest appraisal of who his
former player was, and is.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why we won,'' Murray said, ``because he was happy to
pass the ball, make the other kids better.'' Then Murray, no longer
in contact with Mashburn and more of a Knick fan than a Mash man,
said: ``I imagine Riley will run a lot of his offense through him
as the point forward, which is what he always wanted to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with rest, even with a full week for the Knicks and Heat to
sit around and feign mutual respect, Hardaway will not be more than
a caretaker with 3-point range. Mourning will be Mourning, the
earnest bull in the Knicks' chop shop, at times physically dominant
while utterly defensible come crunch time. That leaves Mashburn as
the potential arrow on Miami's growth chart.
</P>
<P>
   The series ``oxymoron,'' as Riley called him not long ago.
</P>
<P>
   He does not have to be Vince Carter, who wasn't Vince Carter in
Round 1. Yet, if the Mashburn who has shown up in the last three
New York-Miami playoff series surfaces again, the Heat will be
fortunate to get a game.
</P>
<P>
   Mashburn has averaged 8.4 points on 34 percent shooting in 17
games, 10 below his career scoring average. Two years ago in the
first round, it was an unsightly 6.2 points on 26 percent shooting.
Mashburn has set unofficial records for aborted drives following
promising first steps. He has seldom got inside, despite his
6-foot-8-inch, 250-pound body by Jake.
</P>
<P>
   He grew up near 159th Street in Manhattan, and Tom Murray can
still remember his father, `` Mash,'' coming to the games. It
turned out that Robert Mashburn had done some heavyweight boxing, a
sport completely incongruous with his son's personality and style.
</P>
<P>
   ``Always unselfish, the team player,'' said Murray. When he
became rich, Mashburn wanted to give back to his community, so he
started a summer basketball tournament for kids. He appreciated
what was done for him during his three years with Rick Pitino at
Kentucky, so he started a scholarship fund and wrote a check for
$500,000.
</P>
<P>
   He once told a reporter that he wished he could play music,
which he considered a real ``God-given talent.'' Basketball was
more of a vocation, he said, ``not a real big thing.'' He said he
wanted to maintain a healthy life perspective, not a great idea
when your coach is Riley and the next round's opponent is New York.
</P>
<P>
   For this edition of the Heat, the Eastern Conference semifinal
is life and death. Riley knows how much of his own reputation is
riding on Mashburn. His party line is that Mashburn has never been
completely healthy for these dysfunctional family reunions. He said
the real Mashburn stood up in the three-game sweep of Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's healthy and performing,'' said Riley. ``He's never been
ready before.''
</P>
<P>
   Is he prepared to drive into the teeth of the Knicks' defense?
Handle Latrell Sprewell occupying his release space on the
perimeter and the double-team help when he puts the ball on the
floor and Marcus Camby's long arms when Jeff Van Gundy decides to
play big? Is he ready for the pushing, the holding, the Madison
Square Garden heat?
</P>
<P>
   If health and the new rules do not help Mashburn this time
around, we will punctuate the thought that he is less than the sum
of his parts. ``He's a skilled player, always has been,'' Murray
said. ``And I always thought it was a skill sport.''
</P>
<P>
   It is. Just not as much when these teams meet. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
