<SLUG> BC-PRIMARIES-GOP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICAN PANEL SEEKS PRIMARY CHANGES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A Republican advisory commission Tuesday proposed a
tightly controlled, three-month, presidential primary season in
which the least populous states would go first and megastates,
including Texas, would vote last.
</P>
<P>
   The recommendation represents a major departure from the GOP's
traditional hands-off approach to the timing of delegate selection.
But commission Chairman Bill Brock, a former U.S. senator from
Tennessee and one-time Republican National Committee chairman, said
the proposal was a necessary response to the intense, ever-shorter
burst of early primaries which has grown over the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican commission also proposed prohibiting
winner-take-all primaries and instead called for awarding delegates
proportionally to any candidate receiving 15 percent support.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're concerned that too few people have a say in the
process,'' said Jim Nicholson, the RNC chairman, who established
the commission but refused to endorse its recommendations
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican commission's recommendations are subject to
approval by a series of party groups, including the full national
convention, where the proposal could run into the most opposition.
</P>
<P>
   The commission said that in 1980 only 21 percent of Republican
National Convention delegates were selected by March 15. This year
63 percent of delegates were chosen by that date.
</P>
<P>
   If the smallest-first primary plan is not adopted, the
commission proposed an alternative for rotating regional primaries
in which a different area of the country would go first every four
years.
</P>
<P>
   Under either system, states that did not follow the
party-mandated primary schedule could lose up to 90 percent of
their Republican National Convention delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Some senior party operatives were doubtful either plan would
pass muster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's enough weight behind either proposal,''
said an influential party figure familiar with the commission's
work. ``And each plan has a string of unintended consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Weddington, chairman of the Texas State Republican
Executive Committee, said, ``A change like this with so many
unanswered questions ... is going to have a difficult time'' being
adopted.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic nominating process, which is already more tightly
controlled by national rules, has been affected by similar early
bunching in the primary season, and a party committee has recently
completed a study.
</P>
<P>
   Having won the last two presidential races, Democrats are less
concerned than Republicans about how timing the primaries may
affect the result in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``Criticism about a front-loaded schedule has to be weighed
against a process that seems to be working well,'' the Democratic
Rules and Bylaws Committee said in a report last week.
</P>
<P>
   Major primary schedule changes ``would be very difficult to
implement,'' the Democratic report said, in part because almost
every state would have to change its election laws to accommodate
them.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic panel also expressed concern that concentrating
on small states first ``would not help the candidate design a
successful message with broad appeal in the general election.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic panel objected to the general lack of minorities
in the least populous states that would vote first. Eight of the 12
smallest states have less than 1 percent black residents. Six of
the 12 have less than 2 percent Hispanic residents.
</P>
<P>
   Definitive Democratic proposals are not expected until after the
November election and can be handled by the Democratic National
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are more under the gun because current GOP rules
give the party's national convention sole authority to establish
nominating procedures. One of the commission's proposals is for the
Republican National Committee to be given the power to change
nominating rules, but Weddington and other party figures said that,
too, could face resistance at the convention.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
