<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The Cowboys talked contract numbers with Barron
Wortham's agent, Scott Casterline, yesterday but they did not
strike a deal to bring the former Everman High School star home.
</P>
<P>
   Casterline said Wortham is open to a deal friendly to the
Cowboys' salary cap, but he cautioned that the linebacker is also
drawing interest from other teams.
</P>
<P>
   Wortham played the past six years with the Tennessee Titans and
started in Super Bowl XXXIV against the St. Louis Rams. However,
Tennessee signed former Cowboys middle linebacker Randall Godfrey
in the off-season, making Wortham expendable.
</P>
<P>
   Wortham, who was released last week, would give the Cowboys some
insurance in case Dat Nguyen doesn't work out at middle linebacker
or as an option to Darrin Hambrick at strongside linebacker.
\Nsubheds:Williams practices A day after signing a one-year deal,
cornerback Charlie Williams practiced with the team for the first
time.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who missed the minicamp last weekend and the first day
of the quarterback school on Monday, acknowledged being rusty.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, however, said it feels good to be playing.
</P>
<P>
   Despite drafting three cornerbacks, the Cowboys re-signed the
six-year veteran because they coveted his experience, durability
and versatility.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who played in 75 percent of the team's defensive plays
at cornerback last season, started his career at safety. The
Cowboys like that he can play both positions.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said he doesn't care where he plays, ``as long as I get
to play and hit somebody.''  &QL; 
Line shuffling
</P>
<P>
   With right tackle Erik Williams sidelined by a sore elbow and
right guard Solomon Page absent because of personal reasons, Tony
Hutson and Jorge Diaz played tackle and guard, respectively, with
the first unit.
</P>
<P>
   The shuffling might give Diaz a slight advantage in the battle
to replace Everett McIver at guard. Hutson and Page are also
candidates for the starting spot.
</P>
<P>
   Page, a second-round pick last season, is billed as the
favorite. He missed the first two days of minicamp last week,
returned for Sunday's practice, and then was gone again Monday and
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Diaz, a free-agent signee from Tampa Bay, is making the most of
the now unobstructed opportunity to familiarize himself with the
offense and center Mark Stepnoski.  &QL; 
Briefly
</P>
<P>
   Defensive tackle Chad Hennings missed practice for the second
consecutive day because of personal reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Receiver Joey Galloway has garnered most of the attention,
butCowboys coaches say receiver Chris Brazzell has done well, too.
Brazzell, 6-foot-2 and 193 pounds, has the size and speed to have a
chance to become a factor next season, coaches say.
</P>
</TEXT>
