<HEADER>
A3723 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-MCKNIGHT-     05-02 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-MCKNIGHT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCKNIGHT MAKING SURE COWBOYS HAVEN'T FORGOTTEN HIM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ James McKnight has shown this week at the
Cowboys' quarterback school that he has a full grasp of the three
R's.
</P>
<P>
   In his case, the three R's are receiving, rehabilitating and ...
making sure he was still remembered.
</P>
<P>
   McKnight, 6-foot-1 and 198 pounds, never took a snap for the
Cowboys in either a preseason or regular-season game in 1999
because he tore the anterior cruciate ligament in his left knee
during a noncontact drill during warmups for the Blue and White
Scrimmage at Wichita Falls on Aug. 5.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks later, he underwent major surgery, which came barely
two months after he had joined the Cowboys in a trade (for a
third-round pick) from Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``What am I going to do now? That's what I had to ask myself,''
McKnight said. ``Do I crawl into a hole and feel sorry for myself?
Or do I come back and rehab every day with a smile on my face, even
when I'm feeling like I'm in a hole?
</P>
<P>
   ``That was an easy choice for me. I'm not the kind of guy who is
going to let his teammates or coaches see him down. Instead, I
decided, I'm going to beat this thing.''
</P>
<P>
   McKnight, 27, added, ``The way I'm progressing right now, I feel
I can play five or six more years. And that's amazing. I just thank
God.''
</P>
<P>
   McKnight has attended all the off-season workouts, even the
unstructured ones in which Troy Aikman and the receivers have met
twice a week to work on getting down their timing. He has impressed
Aikman with his long-striding speed _ something that can get
overlooked on a team with Joey Galloway and Raghib ``Rocket''
Ismail.
</P>
<P>
   ``McKnight doesn't look like he's lost any speed,'' Aikman said.
``Actually, our team doctors have had tremendous success with ACL
surgeries, probably as much success as any \R team doctors\S in the
league. I can't think of anybody who has had an ACL \Rsurgery\S and
hasn't come back from it here.''
</P>
<P>
   McKnight generally stays an hour after most of the players leave
Valley Ranch, icing down his left knee and tending to his shin
splints, which have occurred since he began pushing himself in
practice. Through seven months of rehab, he remains a tireless
worker.
</P>
<P>
   Eight months after McKnight left Seattle for Dallas, Galloway
followed in a blockbuster deal in February for two first-round
draft choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to Joey on the phone a lot last year because he had
gone through a similar knee injury at Ohio State,'' McKnight said.
``I kept telling him how much of a family it is here. I told him,
`Joey, I love it out here. I'm not even playing and they make me
feel welcome.' I think that made his decision easier when Galloway
was ready to leave Seattle.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys receivers coach Wes Chandler likes McKnight's size,
intelligence and ability to run patterns.
</P>
<P>
   McKnight, whose best season in Seattle was in 1997 when he
caught 34 passes for 637 yards, is probably the leading candidate
to become the team's third receiver behind Galloway and Ismail.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's definitely a spot there,'' McKnight said. ``Remember,
we had a lot of injuries at receiver last year. So, I don't care if
you want to call me the `third' or `fourth' or `second' or `first'
receiver, I just want to have a chance to step up if something
should happen to Joey or Rocket. Just get me on the field. The rest
of it will take care of itself.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I really like his speed, his work ethic and the way he has
rehabilitated his knee since last year,'' coach Dave Campo said.
``These things are all positives when you're talking about James
McKnight.''
</P>
<P>
   McKnight knows that the competition will be stiff once the
Cowboys report to training camp July 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably the best bunch of receivers that we've had in
the 12 years that I've been here,'' Aikman said. ``We always had
Michael \RIrvin\S, an All-Pro wide receiver every year, but we had
never really and truly been able to complement him with that second
guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now have some legitimate speed receivers who can flat-out
run and make plays. So when you combine Galloway and Rocket with
receivers like McKnight, Jason Tucker, Chris Brazzell and Wane
McGarity, and then the tight ends out there like Jackie Harris and
David LaFleur ... it gives you some real options.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
