<HEADLINE>
ABC TRANSMISSION RESTORED AFTER TRUCE BY DISNEY AND TIME WARNER 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also DISNEY-MEDIA) 
 By BILL CARTER with STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Under increasing pressure, Time Warner restored the
signals of ABC television stations to 3.5 million homes Tuesday
afternoon after agreeing to a temporary truce in its contractual
impasse with Walt Disney Co.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement put off until July 15 a deadline for Time Warner
Cable and Disney to come to terms on how much the cable company
will pay Disney for use of three of its cable channels. Time Warner
had sought an eight-month extension on the talks.
</P>
<P>
   Homes in seven areas around the country, including parts of New
York, Los Angeles and Houston, had been without ABC for more than
39 hours when the programming resumed at about 3:21 p.m. Eastern
time. In New York, the actress Rebecca Herbst appeared, playing
Elizabeth Webber on the program ``General Hospital,'' crying
because her boyfriend, Lucky, no longer seemed interested in her.
Time Warner had cut off the ABC stations as of 12:01 a.m. Eastern
time Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner's decision came just before the Federal
Communications Commission was about to rule in favor of Disney's
request to force Time Warner to restore the signal until after the
current ratings sweeps month ends on May 24.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure had grown on Time Warner as politicians in Washington
and New York either urged Time Warner to put ABC back on the air or
declared they would hold hearings on the issue. ABC also planned a
joint venture with DirectTV, a satellite company, to buy and
install satellite dishes in Los Angeles, New York and Houston for
viewers seeking an alternative to Time Warner's cable service.
</P>
<P>
   ABC's ratings were not severely affected Monday night, even with
Time Warner blacking out 3.5 million of the 100 million homes with
television sets.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   A celebrity version of ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' drew a
rating of 22.1 (each point represents about 1 million homes). In
fact, in the New York area, where the signal was pulled in 1.5
million homes, about 15 percent of the total, the show exceeded the
national average.
</P>
<P>
   But in Houston, where almost half the city's homes are linked to
Time Warner cable, the falloff was noticeable as both
``Millionaire'' and many other ABC shows were down sharply.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's settlement came in full view of reporters assembled
for a news conference called by Time Warner to propose a new
October 15 deadline for the compensation talks. Disney officials,
responding quickly to a letter sent by Time Warner, simply changed
the date to July and faxed it to Time Warner executives, who, after
an impromptu huddle, accepted it in the middle of answering
questions about their October offer. Time Warner executives called
the acceptance of ABC's date a gesture of good faith.
</P>
<P>
   FCC officials had regarded the dispute as a private matter
between the two companies, and had urged them to resolve it between
themselves. But the FCC's preliminary analysis had concluded that a
1993 commission regulation prohibited the broadcaster from being
pulled from a cable system during a ratings sweeps month, federal
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC decision could come into play again over the new
deadline because July is also a ratings sweep month. Robert A.
Iger, the Disney president, said he was not thinking of the sweep
month angle when he suggested the date be changed to July. But in a
reflection of the continuing hostility between the two companies,
Mike Luftman, a spokesman for Time Warner, said, ``It's very hard
to accept that anything Disney says or does in this matter has an
innocent reason to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Government officials said they were relieved by Tuesday's truce
agreement, although frustrated that it had required a temporary
blackout that penalized millions of viewers. The FCC chairman,
William Kennard, called the situation a ``game of brinkmanship''
and said in a statement, ``The television sets of average consumers
should never be held hostage in these disputes.''
</P>
<P>
   Strong pressure had been building in political quarters to end
the impasse. Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., who heads the Commerce
Committee, had already scheduled a hearing for next Wednesday to
address issues raised by Time Warner's decision to take ABC off its
systems. After the truce was announced, McCain postponed the
hearing until July.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Other lawmakers, such as Sen. Charles E. Schumer, D-N.Y., had
written to the top executives of both companies asking that ABC's
signal be restored while the two companies continued to negotiate.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, in a news conference before the two sides broke
their stalemate, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani assailed Time Warner,
calling it an ``out of touch monopoly,'' with leaders who ``haven't
given us the courtesy'' of explaining their reasoning. In a
separate news conference, the City Council speaker, Peter F.
Vallone, established a commission to investigate and hold hearings
on the actions of the companies. Vallone threatened Tuesday to
subpoena the top executives of both companies to explain their
actions before a council committee.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement may not augur a new tone to future negotiations
between the companies. Disney executives said the company will
still go ahead with its satellite dish plan, in which the company
and DirectTV will offer to repay consumers for the entire $198 cost
of the purchase and installation.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Disney had previously set up a similar deal in Houston and more
than 15,000 homes had signed on with DirectTV as a result. That
program had become a serious factor in the growing enmity between
Time Warner and Disney, with the cable company's executives
charging that Disney was trying to undermine its business. As one
condition in the most recent negotiations between the two
companies, Time Warner has been demanding that Disney pay a fee for
every customer it has lost to DirectTV in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Luftman said Disney's decision to proceed with its plan to pay
consumers to switch to satellite distribution, after Time Warner
had taken a step to help resolve the impasse, was a ``nakedly
hostile act'' that was `'another indication of that Disney is
engaging in a campaign of destruction.'' The move ``can't help but
cast a dark cloud over the negotiations,'' Luftman said.
</P>
<P>
   Disney and Time Warner have been at loggerheads since their
compensation agreement expired in December. The dispute centered on
how much Time Warner will pay for Disney's Toon, Soap and Disney
cable channels. The payments are the means through which Disney is
compensated for allowing the cable system to carry the network's
broadcast stations. Disney had asked for carriage for new cable
channels as well as a sizeable subscriber fee for its existing
Disney Chanel, which the company wants to shift from a premium
cable channel to a basic cable channel.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner executives have maintained Disney made new demands
after America On Line announced its plan to merge with Time Warner.
Disney executives concede the proposed merger changed the landscape
of the media world so much that it caused them to reconsider the
terms they had previously been leaning toward agreeing to.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner said Disney's new demands would have pushed the
costs to Time Warner up beyond the December agreement about $300
million over 10 years. Time Warner executives said they would have
had no choice but to pass on the costs to their customers raising
monthly cable bills by $1.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Matson, the senior vice president of communications for
ABC, called the speculative $1 increase ``another bogus Time Warner
figure.'' Iger had previously called the $300 million figure
preposterous and Tuesday he said the companies were actually not
very far apart financially.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
