<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3726 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-VEEP-SELECTION-880(2T     05-02 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VEEP-SELECTION-880(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVICE IN VEEP RACE: WALK, DON'T RUN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Calif., N.H., Texas, N.Y., N.J., Mich, Mass.)   By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. _ It was not the spectacular golf course on
a cove overlooking the Pacific Ocean that led Gov. Tom Ridge of
Pennsylvania to fly here the other day to address a group of
Republicans (though he did squeeze in a round before his speech).
It was the chance to do something that a politician rarely does:
praise another politician more than himself. The object of his
affection was Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Richardson, the secretary of energy, cut short a visit to
India for meetings on nuclear proliferation last October so he
could be in New Hampshire to toss questions at Vice President Al
Gore in preparation for his first debate with Bill Bradley. After
only 28 hours in India, Richardson rushed to London and then flew
to Boston, where a waiting Gore aide drove him frantically to
Hanover, N.H., just in time to catch the vice president in the
parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   In the shadow of the presidential jockeying, a second
competition is well under way, for the spot as No. 2. Dozens of
governors, senators, House members, Cabinet secretaries, business
executives, retired politicians and maybe even a general are
maneuvering behind the scenes to get added to the candidates'
purported (and perhaps mythical) short lists.
</P>
<P>
   They are also seeking to score points with Bush and Gore:
stumping for them around the country, dispensing unsolicited
political and policy tips, and seizing every opportunity to say
flattering things about their party's standard bearer. Mindful that
they not appear unseemly, the one thing they dare not do is utter
two words directly to the candidate: running mate.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, for many, the watchwords are deftness and subtly.If you
are caught looking like you are actually campaigning, you may lose.
</P>
<P>
   Jack F. Kemp, the Republican vice presidential candidate in 1996
who did not lobby for the job, and, if anything, discouraged Bob
Dole from picking him, cautioned those who want to be considered:
``Keep your mouth shut, your head down _ and don't act like you
want it.''
</P>
<P>
   One big name politician in Washington who is frequently
mentioned as a possible vice presidential contender was eager in an
interview to make the case to a reporter for why he would be a
fabulous choice. But he insisted that his name not be used.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be quoted,'' he said conspiratorially. ``That
would be a good way to get off the list.'' Boasting about his
selling points, he said of the candidate, ``I won't say that I'm
one of his good buddies but I know him as well as anybody outside
his close friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Another politician, a U.S. senator from a battleground state,
was happy to offer reasons why the politician quoted in the
previous paragraph would not be such a fabulous choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he brings anything to the campaign,'' he said.
Then he offered himself as a possibility, saying, ``I'm a tough
campaigner.'' Excusing himself for speaking anonymously, he said,
``It's important not to look too anxious.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gore and Bush camps have only begun their painstaking hunts
for just the right running mate _ and to resolve perhaps the one
lingering mystery in the presidential sweepstakes before the
national conventions in late summer.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, Tony Coelho, Gore's campaign chairman, has been
making the rounds, informing some politicians _ even some that
others on the campaign said they did not consider hot prospects _
that they were in contention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to Coelho,'' said one politician. ``He told me I
would be considered. I said `thanks.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Coelho declined to discuss such conversations, and, in an
interview, would not even confirm that they were taking place. But
he chuckled at the attention he is getting from politicians who are
quietly trying to win him over.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if people were undermining their chances by being too
overt, he said: ``I don't think it hurts one way or another. It
identifies personalities _ and that's fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Warren Christopher, the former secretary of state, is running
the vice presidential selection process for Gore. The vice
president turned to him because Christopher had the same job in
1992, when he helped Bill Clinton settle on Gore, then a senator.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, has picked Dick Cheney, a former defense secretary and
White House chief of staff who served under his father, to conduct
his search.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in both campaigns said they would be looking for
contenders who could plausibly _ and admirably _ serve as
president, but also who would complement the strengths or
weaknesses of the nominee and add some zip to the ticket. Despite
the coming months of floating names and speculation about who is on
which list, the campaign officials said the decisions were not
likely to be made until just before the national conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Republican convention is first, Gore's choice may be
in direct reaction to Bush's. For example, Gore advisers said that
if Bush picked a woman, they might feel pressure to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   But Coelho said that because he and Gore knew most of the
contenders pretty well, one of the most important duties of
Christopher was to oversee their background checks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vetting process becomes important _ that will eliminate
some people,'' he said. ``That's what Warren does.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Even if they do not get picked, politicians say it burnishes
their image just to be mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Menendez, D-N.J., said that when a few of his friends
in Congress and in labor unions asked him if they could float his
name, ``I didn't dissuade them; it's an honor.'' Asked if an
appearance on Geraldo was useful in getting his name mentioned, he
said, ``Absolutely.'' At the very least, Menendez said, he would
get the opportunity to press a favorite cause: ``Why Hispanic
Americans should be voting Democratic in this election.'' Some
possible contenders are being pushed into the limelight by people
far removed from the actual selection process. Rep. David Bonior,
D-Mich., his party's whip, said he publicly cited Menendez and
Richardson because ``they are both really qualified and fine people
and deserve to be very seriously considered.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bonior also acknowledged that he thought it was important,
at the very least, for House members to get some attention. ``We
want our leaders considered for different positions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Several contenders said their model of what not to do was Gov.
John M. Engler of Michigan, who was viewed by many Republicans as
an unabashed self-promoter for the job four years ago, with
constant visits to Washington. Even so, while Engler did not get
picked, one strategist for Dole at the time said the nominee was
flattered by the attention.
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats say that Sen. John F. Kerry of Massachusetts has
been one of the most obvious practitioners of the
subtle-but-aggressive approach. He traveled to early primary states
to campaign for Gore and, the Gore campaign has noticed, has
delivered speeches on national policy that help raise his profile.
</P>
<P>
   On the Republican side, advisers to Elizabeth Dole made no
secret of her desire to help Bush _ and get her name out. After
ending her own bid for the Republican nomination, she frequently
stumped for Bush in early primary states. And she has the added
benefit that her husband, Bob Dole, trumpets her availability while
she plays coy.
</P>
<P>
   But Ridge is cited by many Republicans for most adroitly
positioning himself. ``He has the keenest political eye to what you
may have to do to be considered,'' said Chris Hennick, a former
executive director of the Republican Governors Association.
</P>
<P>
   Ridge is an obvious contender because he comes from a
battleground state, has a compelling biography as a Vietnam veteran
and is versed in national issues from his days in Congress. Most of
all, he gets along well with Bush. To many Republicans, his biggest
drawback is that he favors abortion rights, but that position could
help Bush appeal to independents and other swing voters.
</P>
<P>
   Ridge helped himself by successfully pushing for the Republican
National Convention to be held in Philadelphia. So he has a
legitimate explanation for traveling the country meeting with
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   In his appearance here before the Lincoln Club of Northern
California, a group of moderate Republicans, Ridge, brimming with
praise for Bush, spoke of the governor's ``candor, his
mischievousness humor, his directness, his decision-making
ability.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Bush's ``compassionate conservative message makes a lot
of sense.'' He defended Bush's controversial proposal to cut taxes
by nearly half a trillion dollars, saying, ``I don't think Gov.
Bush should abandon his plan to cut taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   After the event, Ridge insisted in an interview that he had been
careful not to campaign to be picked as Bush's running mate. ``I
don't think it's his style,'' Ridge said of Bush. ``I don't think
it's appropriate. It's certainly not my style.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Ridge's behavior has seemed strikingly similar to that
of another Republican who was sleeping down the hall from Ridge at
the lodge in Pebble Beach: Dan Quayle. But he was here to play
golf, not politics.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this passage from Quayle's book: ``The vice presidency
isn't an office you can campaign for,'' he said. ``But I had tried,
as subtly as I could, to make clear I was both qualified and
available.''
</P>
<P>
   Did Ridge knock on the former vice president's door for advice?
He laughed and said he did not even know Quayle was staying here.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-00 2119EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
