<HEADLINE>
PRIVILEGE WAIVED IN INQUIRY OVER WHITE HOUSE E-MAIL 
</HEADLINE>
   By DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration dropped its intention to
invoke executive privilege on Tuesday in a dispute over a
congressional request for some documents related to missing White
House e-mail messages.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the White House on Tuesday turned over seven documents
sought by the House Government Reform Committee, led by Rep. Dan
Burton, R-Ind. Burton's committee is investigating whether the
White House deliberately concealed the missing e-mail messages on
investigations ranging from campaign finance to President Clinton's
affair with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Kennedy, a White House spokesman, said on Tuesday that the
documents that had been turned over to Burton's committee were
handwritten notes of White House lawyers on discussions they had
had with computer experts about the e-mail messages that were not
produced when they were subpoenaed in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Although it had provided the committee on Monday with a one-page
list of documents it was declining to turn over, Kennedy said the
White House voluntarily waived any potential privilege claim on
Tuesday ``after hearing back from the committee that they were not
interested in a compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Burton's committee was preparing to hold additional
hearings on Wednesday and Thursday about the missing e-mail
messages. On Thursday, the former the White House counsel, Charles
F.C. Ruff, is scheduled to testify.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators from Burton's committee and the Justice Department
are trying to determine whether White House officials suppressed
large numbers of e-mail messages and covered up the existence of a
glitch in the White House computer system that made it impossible
to retrieve some e-mail correspondence. Investigators are also
looking into accusations that White House officials threatened
employees of a nongovernment contractor if they disclosed the
computer problem, according to court papers.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials have blamed a ``disconnect'' between their
computer technicians, who diagnosed the e-mail problem in June
1998, and their lawyers, who apparently did not understand that the
glitch might affect pending subpoena requests from Congress, the
independent counsel's office and Judicial Watch, a conservative
legal watchdog group here that has pursued lawsuits against the
Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   In a related matter, a White House memorandum showed that White
House technicians were asked to delete old e-mail messages that had
been sent to Sidney Blumenthal, a White House aide, before early
1999.
</P>
<P>
   The request to delete the e-mail messages ``is still being
mulled by senior management and OA (Office of Administration)
Counsel,'' wrote Daniel A. Barry, a computer specialist at the
executive office of the president, in a Jan. 6, 1999 memorandum to
his superiors. It was not known whether White House officials
permitted Blumenthal's e-mail messages to be erased from the White
House computers.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the request to delete the e-mail messages sent to
Blumenthal, Congress was preparing for Clinton's impeachment trial,
which began on Jan. 14, 1999, and concluded on Feb. 12, 1999, when
the Senate voted to acquit Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said: ``I have no reason to believe that that relates in
any way to the e-mail issue that the committee is investigating. It
appears that this is related to a computer space concern because we
are often encouraging employees to delete unnecessary e-mails so
the system does not get clogged.''
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal, who was traveling in Berlin on Tuesday, declined to
comment on the matter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
