<HEADER>
A3736 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-YOUNG-SUICIDES-(TRIMS     05-02 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-SUICIDES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOYS TOLD FRIENDS, BUT SUICIDE PLAN WENT UNREPORTED 
</HEADLINE>
  By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST HADDAM, Conn. _ In the hours before they killed themselves
in a fiery car crash in Monday's predawn darkness, Michael
Dombrowski and Jeffrey Barton, two eighth-grade pals who were liked
by many and understood by few, called their friends on a cell phone
to say goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   But for reasons that police investigators and school
administrators are still trying to fathom, none of the teen-agers
who received the calls reported them to the police or the boys'
parents, though Michael had been making increasingly overt suicide
threats in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He promised a lot of people he wouldn't do it,'' said a
14-year-old girl whom Michael and Jeff called before they died.
</P>
<P>
   After speaking with several friends on the cell phone, the boys
apparently drove an old Ford Bronco owned by Michael's father down
winding Route 151, past their school, and aimed the speeding sport
utility vehicle at a thick Norwegian spruce tree towering in front
of the First Church of Christ.
</P>
<P>
   It was the same tree where Michael's older brother, Daniel, was
killed six months earlier in a car accident along with another
17-year-old boy.
</P>
<P>
   It is not known exactly when Michael's and Jeff's car struck the
tree. When the first state trooper arrived at the scene, at 3:23
a.m. on Monday, the Bronco was engulfed in flames so intense that
state investigators needed dental records to identify the bodies of
both boys Tuesday. Michael was 13 and Jeffrey was 15, the police
said.
</P>
<P>
   The state police are investigating whether the boys used an
accelerant to make the car explode upon impact, said state police
Sgt. J. Paul Vance. The police are also investigating the phone
calls between the two boys and their friends, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Michael had grown alarmingly despondent over
his brother's death, friends said Tuesday. He had told his friends
for weeks that he would kill himself, then backed away from the
threats, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff had moved here a year ago and had a longer history of
emotional problems, school counselors said. He and Michael had
begun to hang around together about six weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, workers cut down the spruce tree, after church
officials expressed concern that its presence would induce other
young people to commit copycat suicides. For now, the residents of
this rural town along the Connecticut River are trying to figure
out why, given the warnings, no one stopped the two boys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why wouldn't they say anything?'' said Eva Bunnell, who lives
across the street from the 6-inch stump where the spruce stood.
``If the kids made as many calls as people are saying, that almost
sounds like a cry for help.''
</P>
<P>
   Bunnell said her 16-year-old son knew Michael and Jeff, and her
13-year-old niece, Nicky, had been particularly good friends with
Michael, whom she described as an outgoing, playful and _ at least
outwardly _ well-adjusted boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did real kids' stuff together,'' Bunnell said. ``They'd
paint their feet and walk over the pavement.''
</P>
<P>
   She, like many other town residents interviewed Tuesday _ many
of whom declined to give their names _ knew Michael, a lifelong
resident of East Haddam, and was aware of the torment that had
haunted him since his brother died in November.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff's emotional pain was more mysterious and entrenched, school
officials said. Both boys had been referred to professional
therapists by counselors at Nathan Hale-Ray Middle School, said
Cynthia Russo, a counselor there.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Kimberly Mawson, 29, who stood outside her home near the middle
school Tuesday talking with four of its students, said Michael and
Jeff had been on the phone with one female friend of theirs as the
two boys barreled toward the spruce tree. ``They were on the phone
when they hit the tree,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The first call Michael made in the hours before the crash was to
a 14-year-old classmate who spoke Tuesday on the condition that her
name not be printed. ``I picked up the phone and he's, like,
`Goodbye,''' the girl said Tuesday, standing among several friends.
``I said, `Where are you going?' and he said, `I love you.' And
then he hung up.''
</P>
<P>
   She did not alert the police, she said, because Michael had made
her promise not to tell anyone.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Other friends were quoted in The Hartford Courant on Tuesday as
saying that they tried to call the boys back, but could not get
through.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Steven M. Durham, the superintendent of the East Haddam School
District, said he did not know ``why youngsters weren't more vocal
about what their friends were doing.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the boys' suicide had left the town stunned, especially
after the November accident that killed Michael's brother and
another boy, Hunter Daniels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four young people in six months is more than a community
should have to deal with,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Dr. David Shaffer, a psychiatry and pediatrics professor at
Columbia University, said dramatic suicides of this type, performed
at the site where a loved one died or on the anniversary of such a
death, are rare.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that they told so many people and that they chose
that location and converted it into a kind of symbolic event,
clearly shows they were trying to make a statement of some kind,''
said Shaffer, who is president of the American Foundation of
Suicide Prevention. ``They didn't want their suicide to go
unnoticed.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that they way the boys killed themselves seemed to
indicate that they had made up their minds. ``I don't think there's
much the other kids could have done.''
</P>
<P>
   Tragically, he said, the two boys are part of a growing
demographic of youths who kill themselves. Suicides among children
10 to 14 years old increased by 109 percent between 1980 and 1997,
he said. For young people between the ages of 15 and 24, suicide is
the third-leading cause of death, behind unintentional injury and
homicide. Most are a result of mental illness, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither boy's family could be reached for comment Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
