<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3738 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-ROCKER-MOONING050     05-02 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROCKER-MOONING0503-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Road beckons rudely to Rocker
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When the Braves have talked about potential
distractions because of the John Rocker situation, they mainly
referred to media attention and their trip to Shea Stadium in June.
</P>
<P>
   But as they learned Monday night, distractions can take many
forms.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker was greeted not only with the usual boos as he sprinted
onto the field in Dodger Stadium. Fans threw objects onto the
field, the public address announcer threatened arrests, fans were
getting rowdy, and one vocal Braves fan was escorted from the
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   And then came the mooning.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the funniest thing I've ever seen,'' Chipper Jones
told reporters afterward. ``I laughed my butt off.''
</P>
<P>
   Players, fans and members of the media might have thought at
first that it was funny to watch the man sprint to the infield
dirt, turn around and drop his trousers to give Rocker a look at
his backside. By the time it settled in that he could have done
much worse, however, it wasn't as funny.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a wakeup call,'' Chipper Jones said. ``We needed to be
prepared for the worst. To be honest, I don't think that will be
the worst we see this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker laughed at the incident. But he seemed to be thrown off
his rhythm on the mound.
</P>
<P>
   The game situation was critical, with the Braves on the verge of
their modern-franchise record of 14 consecutive wins. The tying run
was at the plate with two out in the ninth of a 2-0 game. Rocker
gave up his first run of the season, on a single by Kevin Elster,
but pulled himself together to strike out Geronimo Berroa to end
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this is one of the places we really worried
about,'' Kevin Millwood said. ``But John's a big enough man to
handle it. It takes a pretty big coward to throw something from the
stands at a player.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Bobby Cox said afterward that he hoped the ninth inning
would be as bad as it got. And this is Los Angeles, supposedly a
mellow baseball town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a little excessive,'' said Jones, who was
nearly hit by what appeared to be a paint pellet. ``I don't have a
problem with people voicing their opinion, yelling and booing, but
I do when it comes to putting people in jeopardy.''
</P>
<P>
   L.A. was much more eventful than San Diego. One fan there was
ejected for throwing an object onto the field, but the games had no
other serious incidents.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker has been traveling with a security guard, who works for
Major League Baseball security, out of Atlanta. The guard has been
with Rocker off the field and at the ballpark, and he even has worn
a uniform and sat in the bullpen with him.
</P>
<P>
   But as the fan in L.A. proved Monday, once Rocker enters games,
security can't do everything.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Rocker still had a grin on his face as he walked past
reporters to say, ``Sorry,'' but he wasn't talking. If such fan
behavior continues, however, the situation could get tougher for
Rocker _ a lot of others.
</P>
<P>
   The boisterous behavior was applauded by an L.A. Times columnist
who wrote, ``In virtually every instance in this space, such
displays of trash-throwing and trespassing have been condemned as
dangerous and stupid. But just this once, you done good, Los
Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   That columnist was greeted with at least 50 irate e-mail
responses.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's made his own bed,'' Brian Jordan said of Rocker. ``Now
he's got to live with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
