u i BC-CHINA-U.S.-TRADE-ART-     05-02 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-U.S.-TRADE-ART-1000&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH CLOCK TICKING, CLINTON TRIES NEW APPROACH ON CHINA TRADE
BILL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton and his top aides, acknowledging that they
lack the votes to pass a decisive China trade measure later this
month, increased pressure on Congress on Tuesday by arguing that
the decision is as much about global leadership and the fate of
Chinese reformers as it is about the interest of American business.
</P>
<P>
   The emphasis on national security issues reflected a growing
feeling within the administration that the economic arguments in
favor of elevating trade ties with China, while strong, have proven
insufficient for wavering lawmakers. Labor unions have subjected
these lawmakers to an intensive campaign, as have other groups
opposed to granting China permanent normal trade relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a national security point of view, it would in my view be
a very, very unwise and precarious move to say that the United
States doesn't care whether they're part of the world community or
not,'' President Clinton told a group of independent insurance
agents meeting in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Just three weeks before Congress is scheduled to vote, National
Security Adviser Sandy Berger visited New York and gave a detailed
examination of the security issues at stake in the trade bill,
calling it the most important chance the United States has had in a
generation to shape China's future. He said a rejection would
threaten to set off a ``downward spiral'' in bilateral ties that he
likened, without using the exact words, to a second Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rejecting permanent normal trade relations would be the worst
possible blow to the best possible hope we have had in 30 years to
encourage positive change in China,'' Berger said during a lengthy
address at Columbia University. If the two sides start thinking of
each other as adversaries, he said, ``we will find ourselves
confronting each other across Asia and across the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The warning comes as the Clinton administration begins a final
push to persuade undecided members of Congress to vote in favor of
granting China the new trade status, which would allow United
States companies to benefit fully from a market-opening trade
agreement that paves the way for China to join the World Trade
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said that President Clinton has
allotted a large block of his own schedule in coming weeks for
lobbying members of Congress to sacrifice their annual review of
China's trading rights and to treat that nation as it does most
other members of the world trade body.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials and congressional supporters estimate
that they are still about 10 votes shy of the 218 votes needed for
majority approval in the House. Clinton and five members of his
cabinet have focused their lobbying efforts on about 30 lawmakers,
most of them Democrats, who they say will make the difference
between a narrow victory or defeat. Approval by the Senate appears
more certain.
</P>
<P>
   On Capitol Hill, opposing sides both claimed that the momentum
was shifting their way after the two-week House recess. But there
were signs that both sides were nervous about the final vote.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Archer, the Texas Republican heading the House Ways
and Means Committee, which has jurisdiction over the China trade
bill, warned business leaders that the outcome remained in
jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more concerned about getting a majority of votes today
than I was four weeks ago,'' Archer said. ``Failure to pass this
would create an unworkable trade environment that will slop over to
the rest of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   In a boost for backers of the bill, Rep. Steny Hoyer, D-Md., who
has opposed granting China trade privileges in the annual votes,
said on Tuesday that he would support permanent normal trading
status. Another Democrat who had been uncommitted, Lois Capps of
California, also declared her support.
</P>
<P>
   Over the recess, two supporters of the annual vote said they
would vote against the bill, Rep. Steve Buyer, R-Ind., and Rep,
Bill Luther, D-Minn.
</P>
<P>
   The president is planning a visit to a farm community to discuss
how the trade agreement might benefit farmers, perhaps by allowing
them to export more grain and meat. White House officials are also
considering inviting former presidents and cabinet secretaries to
the White House to highlight the fact that a bipartisan coalition
of former national leaders favors the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton invited a dozen members of Congress to join him at the
White House on Tuesday night for a discussion on China, and
arranged for Martin Lee, a prominent Hong Kong opposition leader
who favors granting China the new trade privileges, to attend.
</P>
<P>
   But the president has so far declined to accede to Republican
demands that he arrange a prime-time nationwide television address
on China, a step Republican supporters of the trade measure argue
is necessary. Administration officials said privately that the
president does not wish to commit to such a speech unless the
national networks agree to put it on the air, a tough sell during
sweeps month, when the networks compete fiercely to attract the
biggest viewership.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition to granting China elevated trading rights is dogged.
Labor unions have argued that the trade agreement will encourage
United States companies to shift production to China, where, union
officials say, low wages and lax labor standards make for unfair
competition. About two-thirds of House Democrats are expected to do
so.
</P>
<P>
   Some religious, consumer and environmental groups have also
lobbied against the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Most Republicans, reflecting overwhelming business support, say
they will vote yes. But a minority of hard-liners in the party
accuse the Clinton administration of appeasing Beijing even as they
say the nation steps up repression at home and threatens to become
more belligerent abroad.
</P>
<P>
   China is likely to join the World Trade Organization, a
regulatory body based in Geneva, even if Congress decides not to
grant permanent normal trade relations. But United States companies
would not get many of the benefits unless Congress agrees to give
up its annual vote.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
