<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-U.S.-TRADE-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: annual vote. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Berger said that the agreement is so beneficial to U.S.
companies that want to do business in China _ and requires so many
concessions by China's Communist-party controlled bureaucracy _
that Beijing would view rejection of permanent normal trade
relations as a seismic shift in United States strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chinese government and people simply will not believe we
rejected it for economic reasons,'' he said. ``They will suspect
that rejection is a strategic decision to pursue a course of
confrontation, contention and containment.''
</P>
<P>
   Failure to pass the accord would rebound to the advantage of
numerous hard-liners in Beijing who have opposed China's WTO
concessions all along, Berger said. In such a scenario, he said, he
considers it likely that China, already mired in a high-level
debate about ties with the United States, would turn inward, become
more repressive and adopt a more militant stance toward Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   He also said rejection would be a slap in the face to America's
Asian allies, especially Japan and South Korea, both of which have
urged Congress to elevate trade ties with China.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign that the administration and its congressional
supporters need more inducements, Archer, the House Republican,
reversed his earlier position and said he would consider parallel
legislation to the trade bill. Rep. Dick Armey of Texas, the House
majority leader, signaled he might support a similar measure.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Sander Levin, D-Mich., has proposed creating an executive
body that would have powers to monitor and report on China
compliance with international labor and human rights standards, as
well as it adherence to trade agreements. Levin has said that such
a commission might persuade some Democrats that that would still
have some oversight over China policy even if they voted to
sacrifice their annual review of the nation's trade status.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans had earlier been cool to the idea. On Tuesday,
Archer said that he would back it if it did not restrict trade and
provided that it would gain more congressional supporters than it
loses.
</P>
</TEXT>
