<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-COACHES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN PLAYING MORE, BUT COACHING LESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)   By LENA WILLIAMS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   While the average number of women's collegiate teams per school
is at a high, the percentage of women coaching them is the lowest
ever, a study of intercollegiate athletics released on Monday said.
</P>
<P>
   In the one-year period of 1999-2000, 205 new women's teams were
added, creating an average of 8.14 per school. In 1972, the number
was approximately two per school.
</P>
<P>
   The increase can be attributed to Title IX of the 1972
Educational Amendments, which prohibits sex discrimination at
institutions that receive federal funds. So, too, is the decrease
in female coaches, say R. Vivian Acosta and Linda Jean Carpenter,
the authors of the study.
</P>
<P>
   When Title IX was enacted, more than 90 percent of women's teams
were coached by women. Currently, 45.6 percent of the coaches of
women's teams are females, down from 47.4 in 1998. By 2000, there
were 7,771 head coaching jobs for women's teams, an increase of 534
from 1998. Yet, of the 534 new jobs in the last two years, women
have been hired in only 107.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news is reflective of a generation expanding its
wings in athletics because its members grew up as beneficiaries of
Title IX,'' said Carpenter. ``On the other side of the coin, women
have a bigger menu of job choices than they had before Title IX and
so now, both on the college and professional levels, are taking
advantage of the opportunities there.''
</P>
<P>
   Acosta and Carpenter, both retired professors of physical
education at Brooklyn College, began studying the impact of Title
IX on women's collegiate athletics 23 years ago. An update of the
study, which is issued every two years, is based on questionnaires
sent to 1,000 schools in 1997-98. It has a 75 percent response
rate.
</P>
<P>
   The study also found that the same five sports _ basketball,
volleyball, tennis, cross country, and softball _ continue to be
most popular among female athletes. But soccer has shown the
greatest growth of any sport in the last 23 years and is now
offered on 84 percent of college campuses. Lacrosse and golf have
grown exponentially in the past decade; gymnastics has declined
among women's programs and is being dropped by some men's programs.
</P>
<P>
   The study also found a percentage decline in female athletic
directors and administrators. In 1972, more than 90 percent of
women's programs were directed by a female head administrator.
Today, 17.8 percent of women's programs are directed by a female, a
decrease of 19.4 percent from 1998, and 23 percent of women's
athletic programs have no females anywhere in the athletic
structure.
</P>
<P>
   Of the study's many findings, Carpenter said she was most struck
by how the face of women's athletics has changed over the decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the old days, there used to be more junior varsity teams
and much broader variety of sports offered; that's been
narrowing,'' said Carpenter, speaking by telephone from her home in
West Brookfield, Mass. She also noted that the sports with
sustained growth are the ``sweaty, grunty and aggressive sports.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That tells me that there is a sense of self-confidence among
women today,'' she said. ``They can participate in sports that
bring them joy and society doesn't insist that they can't show
aggressiveness or assertiveness.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
