u f BC-SPAIN-TELEPHONE-NYT &LR;      05-02 0404
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPAIN-TELEPHONE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPANISH TELEPHONE COMPANY IN TALKS TO BUY ROYAL KPN 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Illustrating the growing pressure on telecommunication
companies to merge in Europe, Spain's largest telephone operator,
Telefonica SA, is negotiating to acquire the Netherlands' largest
telephone company, Royal KPN, for about 60 billion euros, or $54.5
billion.
</P>
<P>
   The combined company would have a market capitalization of 141
billion euros, or $128 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Talks between Telefonica and Royal KPN are just the latest round
in an effort by a number of once state-owned monopolies to create
pan-European networks with the scale to compete against the new
breed of telephone behemoths like Vodafone AirTouch PLC.
</P>
<P>
   The discussions, according to executives close to the talks, are
in their final stages, though the companies may still decide to
abandon the effort.
</P>
<P>
   An agreement is not expected until at least the end of this week
or early next week, leaving a series of hurdles _ including
surprise bidders _ and enough time to derail a deal. Adding
complexity to the negotiations is a third possible partner, NTT
DoCoMo Inc., Japan's largest mobile phone operator, which has also
been in talks with KPN. Executives close to the talks said those
negotiations could lead to a separate alliance among all three
companies' mobile telephone operations.
</P>
<P>
   While the details are not completed, the executives said, the
deal would be structured as a merger with each side controlling
half of the seats on the board of the combined company. Neither
company is expected to be paid a premium, the executives said.
Based on the stock prices of each company on Tuesday, Telefonica is
worth 83 billion euros while KPN is worth 58 billion euros.
</P>
<P>
   According to executives close to the talks, if Telefonica and
KPN proceed with the merger, the combined company may also make a
bid for Orange PLC, Britain's third-largest mobile phone operator.
A combination would also help finance coming auctions for
third-generation mobile telephone licenses set to take place
throughout the continent.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and investors seemed enthusiastic about the possibility
of a merger, bidding up the shares of both companies. Shares of KPN
rose 3.5 euros, or 2.9 percent, to 125, after a 9.6 percent jump on
Monday. Shares of Telefonica increased 2.26 euros, or 9.2 percent,
to 26.74.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
