<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3749 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DISNEY-MEDIA-NYT &LR;      05-02 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUBLIC RELATIONS BATTLE WAS POOR SUBSTITUTE FOR GAME SHOWS AND SOAP
OPERAS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also DISNEY-TIMEWARNER) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER with JIM RUTENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Howard Rubenstein, the public relations impresario,
had planned the broad outlines of Walt Disney Co.'s public
relations strategy well before Time Warner Cable pulled the plug on
the Disney-owned ABC network at 12:01 a.m. Monday.
</P>
<P>
   So when the channels carrying ABC programming faded to blue,
except for the yellow letters that declared ``Disney has Taken ABC
Away From You,'' Rubenstein and his clients were ready with their
campaign to portray Time Warner as a rapacious monopolist.
</P>
<P>
   The ensuing 36-hour all-fronts assault involved radio and
newspaper advertisements, in-person meetings between Preston Padden
_ Disney's chief lobbyist _ with media executives and an
early-morning call Tuesday from the Disney president, Robert Iger,
to Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   By Tuesday afternoon, when the 39-hour blackout of ABC
programming ended, the images of both media giants had been
muddied, but Disney appeared to have left a clearer message behind.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Dressler, the senior vice president for programming at Time
Warner Cable, said in an interview Tuesday that Disney hoped to use
the ABC blackout to make it appear that Time Warner was abusing its
power and to raise questions about the pending merger with America
Online.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were setting us up, that's the whole point,'' Dressler
said.
</P>
<P>
   Dressler acknowledged that by removing ABC from its systems,
Time Warner gave Disney ammunition in its attempts to paint Time
Warner as an unyielding monopoly. Still, he said, Time Warner had
no choice but to do what it did. ``At some point, you have to put
your foot down,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rubenstein said Tuesday that over the weekend, an ABC executive
``called me at home and said she thought Time Warner was going to
yank ABC off the air.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when we started talking about our strategic plan,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Disney's appeals to the public began well before last week.
Two months ago, in the Houston area, Disney's ABC affiliate,
KTRK-TV, began trying to capture the hearts and minds of
Time-Warner's customers, and entice them to buy satellite dishes
and discard their cable company. The lure was a $99 rebate,
courtesy of the station.
</P>
<P>
   The offer, coming at a time when the station was broadcasting
constant warnings that its signal might disappear from the sets of
Time-Warner subscribers, led to a war of full-page advertisements
in The Houston Chronicle, with the ABC affiliate casting Time
Warner as the villain and Time Warner offering $99 worth of free
pay-per-view films to counter the ABC initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the two companies ran competing advertisements again,
with the ABC affiliate's beginning, ``When Time Warner illegally
dropped ABC 13, they violated your trust as a viewer.'' It
continued: ``They want to retaliate against ABC for raising
questions about their stranglehold over your television, cable and
Internet access. Only an arrogant monopolist would drop its most
popular channel to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner's full-page ad, four pages further into the front
section of the newspaper, was more narrowly focused on the
satellite-dish rebate. It was headlined, ``Do the math before you
do the dish.''
</P>
<P>
   The Raleigh-Durham area of North Carolina also was a
battleground. Anders Gyllenhaal, the executive editor of The News
and Observer in Charlotte, said Tuesday: ``ABC and Disney have done
a better job of formulating a message. They have said: this is a
view of the future when the communications roadways are controlled
by a few large companies. Time Warner has not been as vocal in this
market with their side of the story.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Luftman, a spokesman for Time Warner Cable, said in an
interview Tuesday that they considered public relations a
sidelight, marginally relevant to the main objective of concluding
its deal with Disney.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just wanted to get the deal done,'' he said. ``This was
never fundamentally a public relations battle. Like any difficult
deal it had a public relations component to it. And certainly how
well you do on the public relations front has an impact on the
outcome, but its not going to dictate the outcome. Under the
circumstances we were placed in, I would have expected things to
come out pretty much the way they did _ a wash.''
</P>
<P>
   Gyllenhaal said that interviews in his area found little
sympathy for either company. ``Most folks see this as a battle of
titans where the little folks are getting a raw deal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Editorial boards in other areas began to weigh in Tuesday. The
New York Times editorial board, which met Monday with Padden in a
meeting planned the week before, and discussed the issue with Time
Warner spokesmen, published an editorial that said the threat to
Disney by a combined AOL and Time Warner was real. The Times and
ABC News are experimenting with jointly producing a daily Webcast
on politics and feature segments for ``20/20'' and ``Good Morning
America.''
</P>
<P>
   Padden also met with the editorial board of The Orange County
Register in California. The Register planned to publish an
editorial Wednesday. The public thought it was a plague on both
companies, said Schumer, who talked with both Iger and Time
Warner's chief executive, Gerald Levin, Tuesday. ``People didn't
care about the internal machinations. They just wanted their TV,''
he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-00 2149EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
