<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Monday, 05/01/00. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- May 2, 2000 -- CHINA-U.S.-TRADE -- Just
three weeks before Congress is scheduled to vote on China's entry
into the World Trade Organization, Samuel Berger, President
Clinton's National Security Advisor, visited New York's Columbia
University's East Asian Institute on Tuesday and gave a detailed
examination of the security issues at stake in the trade bill,
calling it the most important chance the United States has had to
shape China's future in a generation. President Clinton and his top
aides are arguing that the decision is as much about America's
global leadership and the fate of Chinese reformers as it is about
the economic interest of American business. (Edward Keating/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) SANTA ROSA, Calif. -- May 2, 2000 -- WINE BRATS -- Seven
years ago three twentysomething guys got together over beers at a
Sonoma pub to lament the sorry state of wine drinking in America.
The young men, all scions of prominent Sonoma Valley wine families,
were particularly disturbed about the wine-drinking habits of their
own generation. The common wisdom was that members of so-called
Generation X preferred margaritas to merlot and considered wine to
be elitist, boring and passe. The result was the founding of Wine
Brats. The founders, from left, Jeff Buncshu, Mike Sangiacomo and
Jon Sebastiani. (Christopher Chung/Santa Rosa Press Democrat)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) BEIRUT, Lebanon -- May 2, 2000 --
BEIRUT-MALE-BELLYDANCER -- It is belly dancing night in the Amor y
Libertad nightclub in north Beirut. And Mousbah Baalbaki, center,
quite possibly the only male belly dancer performing regularly in
public in the Arab world, is about to tweak tradition to the
delight of his adoring fans. There is a long tradition of male
teachers of belly dancing in Arab countries. But men who perform
the flirtatious movements, at least in mixed company, are rare.
(Courtney Kealy/The New York Times) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- May 2, 2000 -- HOLOCAUST-REMEMBRANCE --
Rabbi Michael Strassfeld, right, looks on as Jeanne Anderson reads
the names of victims of the Holocaust early Tuesday at the Lincoln
Square Synangogue in Manhattan. The annual reading coincides with
Remembrance Day in tribute to the 6 million victims killed by the
Nazis. (Vincent Laforet/The New York Times) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) MIDDLETOWN, Connecticut -- May 2, 2000 --
WOOING-STUDENTS -- Albert Dixon, of San Francisco, speaks to his
son Albert Dixon III, right, during a campus visit to Wesleyan
University in April. For the young Dixon, who had spent the better
part of a year pleading with colleges to accept him, the courting
by colleges like Wesleyan, which had accepted him, was a jarring
role reversal. (Ozier Muhammad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) EAST HAMPTON, N.Y. -- May 2, 2000 -- SCI-LYME-DISEASE --
Dr. Joseph Burrascano, an internist and small-town family doctor in
East Hampton who is regarded among his followers as a world leader
in effectively treating patients with chronic Lyme disease, during
an interview, Tuesday. Burrascano and many fellow doctors and
patients contend that it is only because of Burrascano's theories
on the proper diagnosis and treatment of Lyme disease that charges
are being made against him before the state medical board. (Maxine
Hicks/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) WASHINGTON -- May 2, 2000 -- CLINTON-TEENS-2 --
President Clinton and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton cast an eye
on the tribulations of raising teen-agers Tuesday, bringing in
experts from around the country for a White House conference on
teens. Ben Casey, director of the Metropolitan Dallas YMCA,
delivers the keynote address to the conference following an
introduction by President Clinton, who is conferred with his wife
Hillary. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) WASHINGTON -- May 2, 2000 -- REPUBS-PRIMARIES -- Few
voters in the nation's capital cast their ballots for presidential
candidates Tuesday in the district's primary. Republicans proposed
a presidential primary schedule Tuesday that would let small states
vote first in early March, with clusters of larger states voting
later through June. ``We're concerned that too few people have a
say in the process,'' said Jim Nicholson, chairman of the
Republican National Committee. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
*LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) SANTA BARBARA, Calif. -- May 2, 2000 -- SANTA-BARBARA --
California's boom town? It's not in the Napa Valley or Sonoma
County. The explosion of wineries around Santa Barbara. Local
winemakers, clockwise from top left: Steve Beckmen of Beckmen
Vineyards, Andrew Murray of Andrew Murray Vineyards, Alan Phillips
at Foley Estate, and Fess Parker at Fess Parker Winery. (Edward
Carreon/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) UNDATED -- May 2, 2000 -- GRAINS-OF-PARADISE -- Grains
of paradise, peppery and pleasantly fragrant, atop the flag of
Ghana, one of the countries where it is harvested in the wild.
(Tony Cenicola/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) WASHINGTON -- May 2, 2000 -- FUNDRAISING-CONGRESS --
Charles LaBella, former Justice Department Task Force head,
testifies before the Senate Administrative Oversight and the Courts
subcommittee, Tuesday. The subcommittee is studying Attorney
General Janet Reno's decision against an indpendent counsel
investigation of campaign finance issues involving President
Clinton and Vice President Al Gore. (Stephen Crolwey/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) EVANSTON, Ill. -- May 2, 2000 -- JACOBS-MANAGEMENT -- No
one has had a greater effect on management education in the United
States than Dr. Donald P. Jacobs, dean of the Kellogg Graduate
School of Management at Northwestern University, say his peers at
schools around the country. In 25 years at the helm, he created the
prototype of the modern business school, management experts say.
Jacobs, right, spoke with students during a party in early April
marking the 25th anniversary as head of the school. (Todd
Buchanan/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- May 2, 2000 -- ELLE-EDITOR -- Elaina
Richardson, the former editor-in-chief at Elle magazine, during a
recent interview. Richardson resigned her top spot at Elle to do a
highbrow disappearing act. She is going upstate to run the iconic
Yaddo, a nonprofit artists colony founded in 1900. (Librado
Romero/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- May 2, 2000 -- SHOWWORLD-REBIRTH -- In an
effort to dodge the city's efforts to rid Times Square of sex
entertainment establishments, Show World Center, which burlesque
historians say was once a widely imitated model for the industry,
has undergone a gradual but thorough transformation, giving over a
vast tract of mirror-tiled, runway-lighted acreage to theater
productions that are Off Off, but not so far from, Broadway. As
their director Aaron Beall looks on, Mark Greenfield and Melora
Griffis rehearse Chekhov's ``Vaudevilles'' on a stage were nude
dancers previously entertained. (Chang W. Lee/The New York Times)
*LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) BOSTON -- May 2, 2000 -- LAWYERS-DOTCOM -- Mike Kendall
works the phones in his office at Goodwin Procter &AMP; Hoar. Law firms
are hoping their younger lawyers will help attract dot-com
businesses. (Janet Knott/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) JERUSALEM -- May 2, 2000 -- HOLOCAUST-ISRAEL -- In front
of a portrait of a Jewish family that perished during the
Holocaust, Israeli soldiers observe a moment of silence in tribute
to the 6 million victims of the Holocaust as sirens wailed across
Israel Tuesday. The observance was held to reflect on the horrors
of the Nazi genocide. (Rina Castelnuovo/The New York Times) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- May 2, 2000 -- INTERNET-HOMEBUYERS-2 -- More
and more, prospective home buyers and renters are window-shopping
by computer. This is particularly true in the New York market,
where listings disappear so fast that waiting for the Sunday
classifieds can be risky. Barbara Corcoran, the chairwoman of the
Corcoran Group and Corcoran.com, in her Manhattan office. (Vincent
Laforet/The New York Times) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- May 2, 2000 -- INTERNET-HOMEBUYERS -- More
and more, prospective home buyers and renters are window-shopping
by computer. This is particularly true in the New York market,
where listings disappear so fast that waiting for the Sunday
classifieds can be risky. An apartment as seen in real life and on
a laptop displaying a photo posted on a real estate Web site.
(Vincent Laforet/The New York Times) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) WASHINGTON -- May 2, 2000 -- CLINTON-TEENS -- President
Clinton and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton cast an eye on the
tribulations of raising teen-agers Tuesday, bringing in experts
from around the country for a White House conference on teens.
President Clinton and his wife lead parents and their teenage
children to the East Room of the White House for the conference.
(Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) COLLEGE STATION, Texas -- May 2, 2000 --
BONFIRE-COLLAPSE-COX -- A commission investigating the collapse of
the Texas A &AMP; M University Bonfire in November 1999, which killed
12 people, issues its findings Tuesday concerning what went wrong.
Ryan Whitsitt, 13, in town to play in a baseball game, views some
of the flowers and a Texas A&AMP;M flag that have been left on a
chain-link fence that surrounds the site of the collapsed bonfire,
Monday. Ryan's mother said her son was curious about the site and
wanted to see it for himself. (Larry Kolvoord/Austin American
Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) PARIS -- May 2, 2000 -- ALAIA-FASHION-2 --Azzedine Alaia
fits a model in a stretch-wool dress with an open back. In mid-May,
Alaia, the Tunisian-born designer whose rare public displays of
genius place him somewhere between Charles James and the Shadow,
will present his largest collection in years. (Jean-Luce Hure/The
New York Times) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) PARIS -- May 2, 2000 -- ALAIA-FASHION -- A model wears a
knit skirt in a tiny flower pattern with a fitted wool jacket by
Azzedine Alaia. In mid-May, Alaia, the Tunisian-born designer whose
rare public displays of genius place him somewhere between Charles
James and the Shadow, will present his largest collection in years.
(Jean-Luce Hure/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
