<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BESTFOODS-UNILEVER-720-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BESTFOODS REJECTS $18 BILLION MERGER BID FROM UNILEVER 
</HEADLINE>
   By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unilever PLC, the Dutch-English consumer products giant that
agreed to buy Ben &AMP; Jerry's Homemade and Slim Fast last month, made
an unsolicited bid on Tuesday to acquire Bestfoods for $18.4
billion in cash. Bestfoods, however, rejected the offer as
``financially inadequate.''
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Unilever dated May 2 rejecting the offer, Charles
R. Shoemate, the chairman and chief executive of Bestfoods, said
that Unilever first approached him on April 20, requesting in
writing that Bestfoods consider a cash offer of $61 to $64 a share.
Bestfoods released the letter late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   That offer was to be considered at a Bestfoods board meeting
scheduled for Tuesday. On Monday, Unilever increased its offer to
$66 a share, Shoemate said, ``subject to certain conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   In the letter to Antony Burgmans and Niall FitzGerald,
Unilever's chairmen, Shoemate called Unilever's interest a
``validation of Bestfoods' global strategy in the consumer foods
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he said, the board had determined the bid was ``not in
the best interests of Bestfoods, its shareholders and other
constituents; and it is not opportune to consider a sale of the
company.''
</P>
<P>
   The offer is the second time in less than a year that Bestfoods'
name arose as a possible merger partner in an industry that
analysts say direly needs to consolidate.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall it was widely reported that Bestfoods, whose brands
include Hellmann's mayonnaise and Knorr soups, was in talks with
H.J. Heinz. At the time, Bestfoods denied any conversations were in
progress.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, recently, Shoemate did not rule out the possibility of
a combination. In the company's 1999 annual report, which was
published in March, Shoemate addressed the topic first by saying he
would prefer to remain independent.
</P>
<P>
   ``However, if we were to identify a partner with whom we could
truly create even stronger profit growth and enhanced value for our
shareholders, we would certainly be open to the opportunity,'' he
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``The annual report was almost an invitation,'' said John M.
McMillin, a food analyst at Prudential Securities. ``Looking at the
success of Kraft/General Foods in North America, it is hard to
argue against the benefits of consolidation. The issue is what is
Bestfoods' worth?''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey G. Kanter, who works with McMillin at Prudential, said
that on a cash flow basis the $66-a-share offer represented a
premium of ``about 33 percent'' over the average food industry
multiple. Over the last year investors have been unkind to food
stocks, discarding their predictable cash flows and earnings for
wild rides in technology shares.
</P>
<P>
   Bestfoods had revenue of $8.6 billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   The stocks have done a bit better recently. On the New York
Stock Exchange on Tuesday, Bestfoods closed at $50.56, down 75
cents a share. The stock has traded as high as $60 a share over the
last 52 weeks, and as low as $35.75.
</P>
<P>
   The $66-a-share offer, ``is a start,'' Kanter said.
</P>
<P>
   The analysts said the combination would make a good fit for both
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Unilever, which has Breyer's ice cream and Gorton's fish sticks
in its stable of food brands, as well as Lipton teas, has been
digging deep to augment and improve its offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Last month the company spent about $2.6 billion to buy Slim Fast
and Ben &AMP; Jerry's Homemade.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999 Unilever had sales of $43.7 billion. About half of its
revenues come from food, McMillin said.
</P>
<P>
   A purchase of Bestfoods would make sense, the analysts said,
because of the strength of its brands and its global reach. The
company, which is based in Englewood Cliffs, N.J., has operations
in 65 countries and sells products in many more.
</P>
<P>
   ``These companies overlap in a lot of emerging markets,''
McMillin said. ``At the end of the day, a Bestfoods takeover was
just a matter of time. It is the prettiest girl at the dance, and
it has a chief executive who is 60 years old.''
</P>
<P>
   McMillan predicted that Bestfoods would hold out for a higher
price. And he mentioned only one other company that might consider
making its own bid for Bestfoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the offer price gets into the $70-a-share range I don't
know how they can fight it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And there are not many companies that have as big a pocketbook
as Unilever. Only Nestle has one as large.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
