<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3759 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-EUROPE-NYT &LR;      05-02 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-EUROPE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACROSS THE ATLANTIC, MICROSOFT CASE ATTRACTS CURIOSITY 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, England _ This university town has been transformed
in the last decade by the arrival of companies like Microsoft,
along with a bevy of start-ups hoping to follow in its footsteps.
Now it is watching intently to see whether Microsoft's path will be
divided.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, Microsoft is viewed as the archetypical high-tech
success story,'' said John Cornish, director of product marketing
for ARM Holdings, a designer of microchips for hand-held devices
based in Cambridge that itself has become a hometown success story.
``The antitrust issues are a function of antitrust laws based on
U.S. history, which differs very much from the U.K. and Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   In Britain and on the Continent, the latest chapter in the
Microsoft tale _ the government's proposal last week to break the
company in two _ has received prominent attention in the media. The
French daily newspaper Liberation has even set up a forum on its
Web site for Parisian readers to weigh in with their views.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a bit further removed, but I think there is as much
interest here as there is in the States,'' said Derek McAuley, the
assistant director of Microsoft's research lab in Cambridge,
Microsoft Research Ltd. ``When I talk to my friends at the pub,
there is an understanding of the principles of antitrust, but there
is some confusion as to why this litigation is being brought to
bear against us.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, for many of the new-economy start-ups in Europe,
Microsoft has served as the ultimate example of an entrepreneurial
success story. William H. Gates, Microsoft's chairman, has achieved
a celebrity status in Europe that rivals the Spice Girls. And while
most Europeans have watched the breakup of state-owned monopolies
through deregulation, most have never seen the breakup of a
self-made company.
</P>
<P>
   But the European Commission, the executive unit of the European
Union, has kept a careful eye on Microsoft's practices, working
with the Justice Department in some instances to curb the software
giant's behavior. The Brussels-based commission is investigating
Microsoft's integration of certain server-related software
technology that has been integrated or bundled into Windows 2000.
The European Commission is also examining Microsoft's agreement to
acquire 29.7 percent of Telewest, the British cable TV operator,
from MediaOne.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a competition between antitrust authorities,'' a
spokeswoman for the European Commission said. ``At this stage, we
trust the Justice Department. Obviously, the bottom line is that
we're talking about a global marketplace and whatever happens in
the U.S. will have an impact everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the European Commission and the U.S. Justice Department
cooperated in an antitrust investigation that Microsoft settled by
changing contracts with personal computer producers and eliminating
some restrictions on software makers.
</P>
<P>
   Today, neither party is willing to settle, and this time around
the stakes are much higher. And so is the attention the company is
getting across the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft has used its operating system as a marketing vehicle
to the disadvantage of the customers,'' said a column in the German
business daily Handelsblat. ``At a time when the trend goes toward
software that is integrated into servers on the Internet, a
voluntary or a forced split-up would offer the chance for a new
beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   Readers of Liberation have been posting messages to its Web site
about the Microsoft case all week. ``The dismantlement of Microsoft
is not a cure-all to break the monopoly of Windows, but at least it
sheds light on the general contempt for Microsoft's practices,''
wrote a user identified as Erion.
</P>
<P>
   Not many companies in Europe compete head-on with Microsoft.
More often than not, the high-tech companies in Europe that have
prospered have been allied with Microsoft. From computers to
hand-held devices to set-top boxes for digital television, it is
hard to find a European version of Sun Microsystems or Oracle, two
American companies that have lobbied hard for a breakup of
Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Even British Telecommunications PLC, the once state-owned
telephone monopoly, has several alliances with the software maker.
</P>
<P>
   ``On one hand it does seem strange to try to break them up
because they are the ultimate start-up made good,'' said Peter
Bonfield, chief executive of British Telecom. ``But who am I to
judge the Justice Department? In terms of a company, we deal with
them. We don't feel threatened by them at all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-00 2154EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
