<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-00 2158EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000502.0347 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3762 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-REID-ARISTA0503-COX     05-02 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REID-ARISTA0503-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Big move: CD label chief heads to N.Y. after strong Atlanta run
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If there is one reason Atlanta has been called the
Motown of the South, it is Antonio ``L.A.'' Reid.
</P>
<P>
   And he is headed north.
</P>
<P>
   Parent company BMG has announced that Reid, co-president of
Atlanta-based LaFace Records, will replace Clive Davis as president
of Arista Records in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Reid, 42, starts July 1 _ the same day 10-year-old LaFace
Records is expected to be out of its 15th-floor Atlanta offices
(the lease expires) and a major transition in this city's
still-burgeoning music industry will officially begin.
</P>
<P>
   When LaFace Records opened here in October 1989, Atlanta was a
place where musicians lived, not where they did business. That
happened in Los Angeles and New York.
</P>
<P>
   But the success LaFace has had as a label _ finding, developing
and producing the best-selling female act in the country, TLC, and
doing the same for such multimillion-sellers as R&AMP;B singers Toni
Braxton and Usher _ has inspired other major artists (Madonna,
Elton John, Stevie Nicks) and labels (DreamWorks, Bad Boy) to
record in, draw talent from, move to and stay put in this city.
</P>
<P>
   And though no one knows what will happen to LaFace in the long
run, the departure of Atlanta's most influential music man is an
incredible loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been our magnet,'' Atlanta Mayor Bill Campbell said of
LaFace, ``our selling point and a source of pride.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Reid believes his Arista promotion will only help
LaFace, his absence from its day-to-day operations might well cause
jockeying among the labels that have sprung up since LaFace
arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to think that we have developed some really smart
executives and a very sophisticated music community in Atlanta,''
Reid said Tuesday from New York. ``There are some really talented
people there who will keep it going and keep it growing. And if it
doesn't continue to grow, it would mean that it was all weak in the
beginning. All built on quicksand. And forgive me for maybe
sounding immodest, but I think we established something real there.
</P>
<P>
   ``And whether it is (producer-Freeworld President) Dallas Austin
or whether it is (producer-artist-So So Def President) Jermaine
Dupri or whether it is (full-service record company) Noontime,
we're talking about some really talented musical teams there that I
believe with all my heart will keep things going.''
</P>
<P>
   And if they don't, Reid says, he'll be around to push them
along. He will maintain his Atlanta home and metro area businesses
(including the Fusebox restaurant and Hitco publishing company),
returning each weekend to them and his schoolteacher fiancee, Erica
Holton, whom he will marry June 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want somebody around there to think, `Aw, LaFace is
gone and L.A. is gone, now I'm going to take over,''' added Reid,
who has yet to find a home in New York. ``Forget about it. We will
still have a presence.''
</P>
<P>
   But it will hardly be the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally I think the music scene will be even better and
bigger,'' Dupri said Tuesday. ``I mean, now he will be in control
of all kinds of music, not just R&AMP;B and rap. And since people here
have such great relationships with him, that's going to mean more
work for us, in rock and whatever else. All this is a change for
the better.''
</P>
<P>
   The half of LaFace that Arista did not own when it struck its
joint venture deal has been sold to the label for an undisclosed
amount of money. Since rumors started surfacing in late 1999 that
Reid would replace Davis, a slow exodus began among LaFace's staff
of 60.
</P>
<P>
   And while LaFace's artists will remain under that brand, Reid
says only ``a handful'' of the label's senior level executives will
join him at Arista in New York. And ``about the same number, if not
less'' will remain at LaFace.
</P>
<P>
   Reid said he could not be specific about staff size because
``decisions are still being made, and I'm still in negotiations
with many of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who remain at LaFace when it moves to its
still-undetermined new Atlanta site will primarily find acts for
the label, not market them. That will now be Arista's job. As for
his replacement, Reid says he hasn't chosen a president and doesn't
plan to name one anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the right executive comes along, I'll do that,'' he said.
``But right now I'm still running it.''
</P>
<P>
   That leaves the label in an unclear position as the man who runs
its day-to-day operations prepares to step into the shoes ofDavis,
an executive soul queen Aretha Franklin calls ``one of the last few
music men left.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the label he founded 25 years ago is coming off perhaps
its strongest year _ highlighted by legendary guitarist Carlos
Santana's return to the top of the charts _ Davis's successor will
have his work cut out for him. Many high-profile pop artists
protested last year when rumors surfaced that BMG was pushing Davis
out _ but no one has publicly criticized Reid.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an incredible time to take the reins,'' Reid said. ``A
challenging time. But if (keeping up the momentum) wasn't a
challenge, I wouldn't want to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   In a related development, LaFace founding co-President Kenneth
``Babyface'' Edmonds is entering into a joint venture agreement
with Arista Records to form his own label.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am pleased to continue my close working relationship with my
friend and colleague Antonio Reid, for whom I have the utmost
respect,'' the Los Angeles-based Edmonds said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The work he and Reid did as producers for such artists as
Whitney Houston, Bobby Brown, Boyz II Men, Paula Abdul and Sheena
Easton earned them 33 No. 1 singles and three Grammy Awards. And
the label they started together 11 years ago has sold more than 50
million albums worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-00 2158EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000502.0348 </DOCNO>
