</P>
<P>
   Though the label he founded 25 years ago is coming off perhaps
its strongest year _ highlighted by legendary guitarist Carlos
Santana's return to the top of the charts _ Davis's successor will
have his work cut out for him. Many high-profile pop artists
protested last year when rumors surfaced that BMG was pushing Davis
out _ but no one has publicly criticized Reid.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an incredible time to take the reins,'' Reid said. ``A
challenging time. But if (keeping up the momentum) wasn't a
challenge, I wouldn't want to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   In a related development, LaFace founding co-President Kenneth
``Babyface'' Edmonds is entering into a joint venture agreement
with Arista Records to form his own label.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am pleased to continue my close working relationship with my
friend and colleague Antonio Reid, for whom I have the utmost
respect,'' the Los Angeles-based Edmonds said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The work he and Reid did as producers for such artists as
Whitney Houston, Bobby Brown, Boyz II Men, Paula Abdul and Sheena
Easton earned them 33 No. 1 singles and three Grammy Awards. And
the label they started together 11 years ago has sold more than 50
million albums worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
