u f BC-GERMANY-TELECOMS-NYT &LR;      05-02 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-TELECOMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
12 COMPANIES TO BID FOR BILLIONS IN GERMAN WIRELESS LICENSES 
</HEADLINE>
   By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ With barely any time to relax after
companies bid $35 billion for five new wireless communications
licenses in Britain, many of the same competitors lined up
Wednesday for a potentially bigger auction in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   German government officials announced that 12 companies,
including MCI WorldCom, have signed up for an auction of as many as
six licenses for so-called third-generation wireless voice and data
services. These licenses will be made available for an advanced new
series of high-speed services that could make it possible to
transmit video or surf the World Wide Web in full color using
mobile devices.
</P>
<P>
   But the staggering amounts of money offered in the British
auction, which ended last week, have raised new worries among some
industry analysts about the billions of dollars many companies will
have to borrow if they bid for licenses across Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Besides MCI, the list of bidders in Germany includes Deutsche
Telekom, which won a license in Britain through its British
wireless carrier One2One; Mannesmann AG, which is being acquired by
Vodafone AirTouch of Britain; E-Plus, a German mobile phone carrier
controlled by Royal KPN of the Netherlands and BellSouth of the
United States; and MobilCom AG, a fast-growing German rival to
Deutsche Telekom that has backing from France Telecom.
</P>
<P>
   All European Union countries plan to issue similar new licenses
in the next year or so, but there is a growing debate about whether
the licenses should be auctioned to the highest bidders or awarded
free through what amounts to a beauty contest.
</P>
<P>
   The supercharged bidding in Britain, which reached levels seven
times those officials originally predicted, has strengthened the
arguments on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   Many governments, like Germany's, have been mesmerized by the
prospect of windfalls that would enable them to either reduce
budget deficits or shore up existing programs.
</P>
<P>
   But others are worried that the billions paid for licenses will
translate into higher costs for users and could destroy companies
that miscalculate the potential benefits and bid too much.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts now believe that the bidding for licenses in
Germany _ which with 82 million people is a significantly larger
market than Britain with 60 million _ could reach as high as $50
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Germany is crucial for any company bent on providing services
across Europe. Companies like Deutsche Telekom, France Telecom,
Vodafone and KPN want to build up pan-European networks and acquire
licenses in at least the biggest markets.
</P>
<P>
   Other competitors appear to have more limited ambitions. Orange
PLC, the British carrier soon to be sold by Mannesmann, was a
successful bidder in Britain and has teamed up with Sonera Corp. of
Finland and Telefonica of Spain. The bidding strategies have
inevitably become intertwined with strategies for mergers and
acquisitions. Telefonica is now in talks to acquire KPN, and one of
the two would presumably drop out if they reach an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Vodafone is in a particularly complex situation. Having won a
brutal takeover battle for Mannesmann, Germany's biggest wireless
carrier, it must raise billions just to pay for its British license
and additional billions for anything it wins in Germany or other
countries.
</P>
<P>
   In order to gain antitrust approval for the takeover of
Mannesmann, Vodafone is disposing of Orange. It had been expected
to do that through taking Orange public, but it now appears to be
leaning toward an all-cash sale to another telecommunications
company.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the UMTS Forum _ for Universal Mobile Telephone
Standard _ an industry association aimed at promoting the
third-generation services, declared that countries would be better
off awarding licenses through beauty contests rather than through
auctions that could send the costs of new services to prohibitive
levels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
