<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-JUDGES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-PROSECUTOR CHOSEN IN INQUIRY OF CHIEF JUDGE  
 BY NEIL A. LEWIS  
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Ga., N.C.)   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A former federal prosecutor has been chosen to
investigate why the chief trial judge in Washington assigned
several criminal cases involving associates of President Clinton to
judges appointed by the president, lawyers in the case said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The former prosecutor, Joe D. Whitley, an Atlanta lawyer who
served in two Republican administrations, will look into why the
chief judge of the U.S. District Court for the District of
Columbia, Norma Holloway Johnson, bypassed the usual
computer-operated random selection scheme and assigned a handful of
Clinton-related cases to four judges named to the bench by Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Whitley was chosen by a special five-member panel of federal
judges who are undertaking the investigation in response to
complaints by a conservative legal group and Rep. Howard Coble,
R-N.C., chairman of the House Judiciary subcommittee on the courts.
</P>
<P>
   The cases being investigated involved Democratic Party
fund-raising and Whitewater. In one instance, Johnson, who was
herself appointed by a Democrat, President Jimmy Carter, urged
federal prosecutors to request a specific judge who had been
appointed by Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The cases include those involving Webster Hubbell, the former
Arkansas law partner of Hillary Rodham Clinton and onetime
associate attorney general in the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   Last year The Associated Press disclosed special assignments in
the Hubbell case as well as a case involving Charlie Yah Lin Trie,
a Clinton fund-raiser. At the time, Johnson said in a letter that
her decision was intended simply to shift complex cases to judges
with open schedules.
</P>
<P>
   She declined to respond to telephone requests for comment
Tuesday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Judges at the local courthouse who spoke on the condition of
anonymity said Tuesday that they believed the investigation had
little chance of producing any new information.
</P>
<P>
   One judge noted that because the investigation involved
Johnson's motives, there was little an investigation could do to
challenge her assertion as to why she bypassed the random selection
system. Another judge, a Republican appointee, said he believed
that Johnson made the assignments to enliven the workload of some
judges she favored with interesting cases.
</P>
<P>
   The special panel is headed by Judge Stephen F. Williams of the
U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit. Also on
the special panel are two other members of the appeals court,
Judges Judith W. Rogers and A. Raymond Randolph, as well as two
district court judges, Thomas F. Hogan and Thomas Penfield Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, Hogan and Jackson were nominated by President Ronald
Reagan, Randolph was named by President George Bush and Rogers by
Clinton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-00 2201EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
