<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Mont., Wis.)  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE STATES
</P>
<P>
   DRUG COSTS ARE ISSUE IN MONTANA: Brian Schweitzer, a Democratic
candidate for the Senate in Montana, has campaigned hard on the
high price of prescription drugs and the burden it puts on the
uninsured elderly. Schweitzer, who has taken retirees to Canada to
highlight the lower cost of drugs there, has exchanged television
fire with Citizens for Better Medicare, a lobbying coalition led by
the drug industry. Now the Democratic Senatorial Campaign
Committee, which believes Schweitzer has a good shot at winning one
of six seats the party needs to retake control of the Senate, has
produced a television spot urging voters to ``call the big drug
companies and tell them to get out of the way of Brian Schweitzer's
fair prices drug plan.'' Schweitzer, a farmer who has never held
elective office, is trying to unseat the Republican incumbent,
Conrad Burns.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Robin Toner
</P>
<P>
   THE REPUBLICANS
</P>
<P>
   GOV. THOMPSON NAMED PLATFORM CHAIRMAN: Gov. Tommy G. Thompson of
Wisconsin has been named chairman of the committee that will draft
the Republican platform at the party's national convention this
summer, an appointment that abortion rights advocates regard as a
sign that George W. Bush, the presumed presidential nominee, will
not ease the party's staunch anti-abortion position. Two years ago,
Thompson signed legislation outlawing the procedure that opponents
call partial-birth abortion. Kate Michelman, president of the
National Abortion Rights Action League, said the selection showed
that Bush, despite his advocacy of inclusiveness, ``cares about
what the far right of his party wants.'' Thompson said after his
appointment on Monday that he looked forward to ``serving on the
committee to articulate our party's most innovative ideas, the
principles that bind us together and our vision for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By Irvin Molotsky
</P>
<P>
   THE POLLS
</P>
<P>
   BUSH HOLDS NARROW LEAD: The latest USA Today/CNN/Gallup
presidential preference poll gives Gov. George W. Bush a 5-point
lead over Vice President Al Gore, 49 percent to 44 percent. The
poll also indicates that should Bush pick Sen. John McCain,
R-Ariz., as his running mate, he would widen his lead. Among all
voters, the poll found, two of three would not be more inclined to
vote for Bush if McCain were added to the ticket. But among
independents, two of five said they would be more inclined to vote
for Bush with McCain on the ticket. The poll, which surveyed 1,003
likely voters from April 28 to 30, has a margin of sampling error
of plus or minus 5 percentage points. In a USA Today/CNN/Gallup
poll taken three weeks earlier, Bush led Gore by 9 points.
</P>
<P>
   _ By B. Drummond Ayres Jr.
</P>
<P>
   WEDNESDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH: Palm Springs, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE: Atlantic City, N.J.; New York
</P>
</TEXT>
