<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-BROKER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINANCIAL CAFE.COM IS LATEST TO OFFER FREE STOCK TRADES 
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the Internet, brokerage firms are starting to use stock
trades the way banks used to use pens and lollipops: they are
giving them away to lure people onto their Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   The latest concern to forgo commissions on online purchases of
stock is the Financial Cafe.com, a start-up based in Seattle.
Despite being quite late to the electronic-brokerage party that
broke out a few years ago, Financial Cafe.com hopes to attract
customers to its other financial services by giving away trades
ordered at market prices.
</P>
<P>
   The venture is at least the third to offer free stock trades.
Last week, the Ameritrade Holding Corp., an established online
brokerage firm, introduced Freetrade.com, an all-electronic trading
service. Late last year, American Express started giving away
trades to certain investors. Those offers undercut the deep
discount brokers, including Ameritrade's flagship service and
FleetBoston Financial's SureTrade unit, that charge about $8 a
trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putting that zero out there gets people's attention,'' said
Alex Stein, an executive vice president of Gomez Advisors in Boston
and an adviser to Financial Cafe.com. ``Once you get their
attention, the key is to offer a high-quality service to retain the
customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Stein said the number of brokerage accounts at American Express
rose sharply after it introduced free trades for customers with at
least $25,000 in their accounts. The offer was so successful, it
seemed to overwhelm the company's systems, said Stein, whose
company tracks the responsiveness of e-commerce operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen their customer service go from stellar to one of
the worst, largely because they saw this fantastic influx of new
accounts,'' Stein said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of Financial Cafe.com said they planned to emphasize
service by having a higher ratio of service representatives to
customers than established firms have. The industry average is
about one representative for every 1,200 to 1,500 accounts, Stein
said, and Financial Cafe.com plans to have about three
representative to serve that many accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Robert M.D. Cross, chairman of Financial Cafe.com and former
chief executive of Yorkton Securities, a Canadian investment bank,
said the new venture would charge competitive rates for a range of
financial products, including bonds and mutual funds, and loans
against stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Koslow, the company's chief operating officer, insisted
that it would not treat no-cost stock trades as a loss leader. With
the deals the company has struck with its business partners, Koslow
said, it will need only a small number of accounts to become
profitable.
</P>
<P>
   The most important alliance is with FreeShop.com, a Web site
that collects information about discounts and free trial offers
from a variety of merchants. In exchange for an undisclosed amount
of equity in Financial Cafe.com, FreeShop.com plans to promote the
new venture to its list of more than three million customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of our customers are online transactors and a majority of
them have made purchases online,'' said Tim Choate, chairman and
chief executive of FreeShop.com, which is also based in Seattle.
They are obviously attracted by free offers, but Choate said he did
not know how many of them already had accounts with online
brokerage firms.
</P>
<P>
   For three months, FreeShop.com will be the exclusive promoter of
Financial Cafe.com. Choate said the arrangement was the first of
what his company hoped would be a series of ``jump starts'' that it
would provide for nascent e-commerce companies. With the stock of
his company, which went public last year, now trading below its
initial offering price, Choate said the company's most valuable
asset was its status as one of the most heavily visited sites on
the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Michele Pelino, an analyst with the Yankee Group in Boston, said
there was a potential liability in luring customers with an offer
that seems to good to be true.
</P>
<P>
   ``Offering free stock trades will draw traffic but is it the
traffic that you want?'' Pelino said. ``When you say something's
free, consumers tend to think you get what you pay for. That can
actually be a challenge in a way.''
</P>
<P>
   After talking with officials of Financial Cafe.com, Pelino said
it was not clear to her how the company could avoid losing money on
each free trade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
