<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PATAKI-ETHICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL CLEARS PATAKI IN TRIPS INDIRECTLY FINANCED BY CORPORATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York State Ethics Commission has found that
Gov. George E. Pataki and his aides did not violate the law in
allowing a nonprofit trade group largely financed by companies
lobbying his office to pay for trips he took to Hungary in 1995 and
1996.
</P>
<P>
   The commission concluded that the trips did raise ``ethical
concerns'' because the nonprofit group, the Hungarian-American
Chamber of Commerce USA, raised money from the companies
specifically for the trips.
</P>
<P>
   The commission, which is controlled by the governor's
appointees, said its inquiry had determined that the governor and
his aides were not aware that the group was soliciting money from
the companies, which included Philip Morris, Pepsico and two
pharmaceuticals giants, Pfizer and Bristol-Myers Squibb.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no evidence _ either from the witnesses interviewed
or the documents reviewed _ that anyone in the governor's office
(or elsewhere in state government) knew that HACC was soliciting
funds for the trips,'' the commission's executive director, Donald
P. Berens Jr., wrote in a letter released Tuesday in which it
announced its findings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Accordingly,'' the letter said, ``the commission has concluded
that neither the governor nor any state officer or employee
violated the state ethics law or sought to circumvent the law in
connection with HACC's funding of the governor's trips.''
</P>
<P>
   In the letter, which was sent to three advocacy groups that
filed a complaint about the trips, Berens noted that one of the
governor's aides had asked the commission before the first trip
whether the administration was required to examine the chamber's
finances, and the commission had responded that it was not.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Berens added, the commission would change its rules to
require that Pataki and his successors, when taking trips financed
by outside groups, ask whether the groups were raising funds for
the trips and from whom.
</P>
<P>
   The chamber, Philip Morris and some of the other companies
indicated in interviews last fall that the donations to the chamber
were not tied to the trips. The commission said it had determined
that they were but had decided not to take action against the
chamber or the companies.
</P>
<P>
   Under state ethics rules, companies with interests before the
governor are barred from paying for his travel. In this case, the
companies financed the trips, with donations of $5,000 to $20,000,
by funneling the money through the chamber.
</P>
<P>
   The commission had allowed the chamber to pay for the trips
because the chamber did not have business in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   The ethics panel opened its inquiry last fall after The New York
Times published several articles about the financing of the trips,
which were a combination of trade mission and family vacation. In
response to the commission's findings, Pataki's spokesman, Michael
McKeon, read a statement Tuesday: ``As we have said all along, what
we did was right and proper. The commission has now verified that
we followed the advice and guidance that they provided us, which
were the same practices used by the previous administration.''
</P>
<P>
   Blair Horner, legislative director for the New York Public
Interest Research Group, one of the three advocacy groups that
filed the complaint, said that if the administration was to be
believed, it was startling that no Pataki aides had scrutinized the
chamber's finances.
</P>
<P>
   ``This shows that the administration was ethically tone deaf
when this deal was first being put together,'' Horner said.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the trips last fall, the chamber's president,
Monika Szarka-Elling, said she did not know why Philip Morris and
the other corporations contributed to the chamber, which was
founded in 1992 and is based in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Szarka-Elling did not respond to two messages at her office.
Peggy Roberts, a spokeswoman for Philip Morris, declined to
comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-00 2231EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
