<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUERTORICO-PROTESTS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. PREPARES TO CLEAR VIEQUES DEMONSTRATORS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal authorities completed preparations on
Tuesday to clear demonstrators this week from a Navy range on
Vieques, a small island off Puerto Rico, even as FBI officials
continued to express misgivings about the operation they will lead.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Pentagon officials have insisted that protesters be
removed from a bombing range on the island before training
exercises begin. Louis J. Freeh, the director of the Federal Bureau
of Investigation, and other senior law enforcement officials have
warned of possible injuries, and even casualties, as federal agents
try to remove protesters from a range scattered with live
ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   But Freeh's questions about the operation have largely been
answered, the officials said, especially with an agreement reached
Tuesday that the Justice Department will obtain an order from a
Federal District Court in Puerto Rico authorizing the arrest of
demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days White House officials and Attorney General Janet
Reno agreed to mount the operation before the end of the week, top
law enforcement officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Alfonso Aguilar, the Washington representative of the governor
of Puerto Rico, said the protesters were failing to ``respect the
truth and respect the will of the majority of Puerto Ricans'' who
he said want the bombing range cleared.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrators are protesting an agreement reached on Jan. 31
between President Clinton and Gov. Pedro J. Rossello of Puerto
Rico. The plan allows the Navy to resume limited bombing practice
with dummy weapons on the Vieques range until a referendum is held.
</P>
<P>
   The referendum will allow residents of Vieques to choose between
letting the Navy resume full use of the range with live bombs and
ammunition or ordering the military to end all training by May 1,
2003.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, the protesters said that they would refuse to
comply with the expected order to leave the military base but that
they would not actively resist arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters held workshops on Monday to practice nonviolent
resistance in expectation that agents would haul them off the range
on Tuesday, said Lilda Medina, of the Coordinating Committee for
Peace and Justice in Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought they would come today,'' Medina said in a telephone
interview Tuesday. ``Trucks have been moving in and out of the camp
since yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   This week two Navy ships carrying 1,000 marines and sailors
arrived in waters near Vieques to support the federal special
weapons and tactics teams who will remove the protesters from the
range, on the eastern end of the island. The marines will stand
guard around the edge of the range, help dispose of unexploded
bombs and provide medical help.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy has described Vieques as the crown jewel of its
training ranges because it is the only site along the East Coast
where battle groups can use live ammunition during joint training
exercises that include amphibious landings of marines, shelling
from ships and aerial bombardment from fighter jets.
</P>
<P>
   Those exercises were suspended last year when a civilian Puerto
Rican security guard was killed in a bombing accident that touched
off widespread protests.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has also entered the Senate race in New York, which
has a large population of Puerto Ricans. On Tuesday, Hillary Rodham
Clinton, the presumed Democratic nominee, called again for a
permanent end to bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``A small, inhabited island should not be used for target
practice,'' Clinton said in a statement. ``Until such a referendum
occurs, I urge the Pentagon to negotiate a peaceful resolution to
this situation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
