<HEADER>
A3787 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BONFIRE-CAMPUS0503-CO     05-02 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONFIRE-CAMPUS0503-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Will the tradition continue?By Dave Harmon
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ Eleven students, their arms around each
other in a tight circle, shared whispered prayers Tuesday, a few
yards from the piles of oak, hackberry, and elm logs that
symbolized Aggie pride less than six months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Yellow crime scene tape still flapped from some of the twisted
trunks. A fence topped with barbed wire separated the students from
what is now the scene of Texas A&AMP;M's biggest tragedy and an
intensive investigation into why Bonfire fell, killing 12 people.
</P>
<P>
   Under slate gray skies Tuesday, students gathered around
televisions and packed Reed Arena, solemnly listening to the
bonfire commission's conclusions that the November collapse was the
result of years of ``organizational failure'' and unquestioned
adherence to tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Across the tree-lined campus, where the wounds remain fresh and
painful, learning why Bonfire fell didn't answer students' most
urgent question: Will Bonfire continue?
</P>
<P>
   The decision is now in the hands of A&AMP;M's administration, and
the students know that the future of this sacred Aggie rite remains
in doubt. But across campus, the vast majority of the student body
seems poised to fight for Bonfire's future _ in whatever form is
necessary to preserve safety and tradition.
</P>
<P>
   So they paused from the bustle of finals week to sign petitions
voicing their support for keeping Bonfire. They pulled on T-shirts
announcing their determination to see it burn again. They gathered
at the bell tower and marched to the arena en masse.
</P>
<P>
   But no one can forget that people died on the stack. And for
that reason, some students remain deeply torn over whether Bonfire
should serve as a tribute to those who died, or be halted to ensure
no one else will perish building the towering structure that has
become the burning symbol of Aggie pride.
</P>
<P>
   When bonfire commission Chairman Leo Linbeck Jr. called
Tuesday's meeting to order, a silence fell over the crowd. When the
commission showed a computer-generated simulation of the collapse,
some students took detailed notes while others struggled to hold
back the tears.
</P>
<P>
   Courtney Hill, a 19-year-old sophomore, wept during the
presentation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to put it out of our minds and it brings everything
back. ... We tried to heal all the wounds in our heart and it
brought everything back up,'' said Hill, who helped build the 1999
bonfire.
</P>
<P>
   In the cavernous lounge at the university's student center, more
than a hundred students watched the commission report on two
televisions. Afterward, Amie Jeffryes, 20, and Dennis Ellis, 21,
had mixed feelings about what should be done now.
</P>
<P>
   The details of the commission's report didn't seem to surprise
them. Jeffryes said she was glad the drinking and hazing that
accompanies bonfire construction was not found to be a factor in
the collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm relieved that it wasn't horseplay or alcohol or anything
like that,'' said Jeffryes, a sophomore from Mansfield. ``The
tunnel vision and cultural bias _ it was hard to have that slapped
in our faces.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I wasn't surprised by anything they said,'' she added.
``We all knew it, we knew Bonfire had problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Jeffryes wants the bonfire to continue. Ellis, a junior
from Dallas, isn't so sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they could guarantee me that no Aggie would ever die
building (Bonfire), I'd say do it again,'' Ellis said. ``If it
goes, I won't be sad to see it go, because 12 people lost their
lives, and nothing is worth those lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if Bonfire is banished, Ellis said, students would find a
way to make sure the spirit of the event survives at A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's something greater than a pile of wood burning,''
he said. ``Those 12 people will never be forgotten. I guarantee you
something will happen on the polo fields next year.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the polo fields were largely silent. Small groups of
students visited the remaining stacks of bonfire logs, bowing their
heads and grasping the chain-link fence.
</P>
<P>
   Most students seemed willing to compromise on the size or design
of the bonfire, even if that means handing over the planning to
professionals. For them, the important thing is that Bonfire lives
on as a student-built structure.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before the investigating committee's presentation,
hundreds of students gathered at the university's bell tower and
walked to Reed Arena to hear the results in person. Some called it
a march to support keeping the bonfire tradition alive; others said
they came simply as a show of student unity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to keep Bonfire and also show support for the people
who died,'' said Lacy Wilson, an 18-year-old student. ``We're
freshmen. We've never even seen the bonfire.''
</P>
<P>
   Her friend Kyle Wiesenborn, 18, said he would support whatever
the university decides. But he said he hopes to see Bonfire
continue. He wants to be a part of the tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be out there in a second if they did it next year,''
Wiesenborn said. ``I feel like it would be some sort of tribute to
the people who died.''
</P>
<P>
   Further back in the procession, 22-year-old Becky Howard wore a
T-shirt emblazoned with what she believes is the majority opinion
on campus: ``Keep the fire burning.''
</P>
<P>
   ``(The students) really want it to continue, maybe not in the
same way,'' said Howard, a senior from Arkansas. ``A lot of people
were out there (when the bonfire collapsed) and saw it, and they
don't ever want that to happen again. I think they're willing to
compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
