<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MENTAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
25 YEARS AFTER WILLOWBROOK DECISION, CELEBRATION AND CRITICISM
</HEADLINE>
  By SHAILA K. DEWAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was an unwieldy and not altogether happy reunion
of a very unusual class, the so-called Willowbrook Class.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five years after the patients of the infamous Willowbrook
State School won a class-action lawsuit that led to the widespread
deinstitutionalization of the mentally retarded, lawyers, doctors,
administrators and some class members themselves gathered to
celebrate the settlement, called the Willowbrook Consent Judgment _
and to criticize its aftermath.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s and early '70s, the conditions at Willowbrook,
including feces-smeared walls, naked inhabitants and frequent,
violent deaths, were well documented, most notably by Geraldo
Rivera, whose 1972 television expose was the impetus for a federal
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   In 1975, Gov. Hugh L. Carey signed the consent decree, thus
committing the state to establish noninstitutional homes for people
with developmental disabilities. Gov. Carey, former Gov. Mario M.
Cuomo, and Gov. George E. Pataki were all honored Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The conference, held on the campus of the College of Staten
Island, where the crowded, prisonlike wards of Willowbrook once
stood, was called ``Social Justice Has Prevailed.''
</P>
<P>
   But many of the 450 present said it had not: Some mentally
retarded people are still institutionalized; care still needs to be
improved, even in group homes; the state is not meeting the
promises it made in the settlement; and no reparations, or even
apologies, have been made.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The participants acknowledged that the decree had succeeded,
to a degree. Only 8 of the state's 20 mental institutions remain,
and the number of people in such institutions has decreased to
fewer than 1,000 from 25,000, according to the Office of Mental
Retardation and Developmental Disabilities, created after the
decree.
</P>
<P>
   But lawyers who represent the 3,600 remaining members of the
Willowbrook Class said the case was technically still open, and
that they often had to threaten to get an injunction to ensure that
the state met its agreements.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of a continuous game of chicken,'' said Beth
Haroulas of the New York Civil Liberties Union, adding that she
still saw reports of abuse, neglect and inadequate medical care in
group homes.
</P>
<P>
   And, she said, Willowbrook Class members are better off than
other mentally retarded people. Their case managers have lighter
loads _ 20 as opposed to 30 _ and the quality of their care is more
closely monitored.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the conference panelists made a point of saying there
was room for improvement.
</P>
<P>
   One with a particularly poignant story to tell was Bernard
Carabello, who entered Willowbrook when he was 3, and stayed for 18
years, despite the fact that he was not retarded. Carabello has
cerebral palsy, which does not impair mental functioning.
</P>
<P>
   Now a governor-appointed advocate for the developmentally
disabled, Carabello said the main problems in the field today
involved community relations: neighborhoods often do not welcome
group homes and those who live in them are often isolated from
their communities.
</P>
<P>
   Present problems aside, the gathering was, for some, an
emotional trip to the past. Several of the participants, including
William Bronston, one of the Willowbrook doctors who helped
organize the parents who filed the lawsuit, returned to the site
for the first time since the '70s.
</P>
<P>
   During one panel discussion, he called for an apology to be
issued to those who suffered.
</P>
<P>
   ``The parents,'' he said privately during a lunchtime
presentation of awards and speeches, ``have never been acknowledged
as Holocaust survivors, American-style.''
</P>
<P>
   As Jose Rivera took the podium to remember his brother, who died
while staying at Willowbrook, the faces of many parents and
siblings grew quiet and drawn. Some of them had lost relatives.
Others said they were lucky.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Nehbauer of Hastings, N.Y., whose son now lives in a group
home in nearby Scarsdale, told how she would make unannounced
visits to Willowbrook, where he was one of 90 children in a ward
with barely 12 inches of space between beds.
</P>
<P>
   Though she knew what the conditions were, she said, ``Our only
option was no option.''
</P>
<P>
   Diana McCourt, the wife of the writer Malachy McCourt, said her
daughter, Nina Galin, now lived in a group home in Harlem, where
she participated in a new one-on-one program that allowed her to
venture accompanied into the city.
</P>
<P>
   She remembered finding out what Willowbrook was like: ``I felt
totally enraged, totally terrified and also totally determined to
find like-minded people. I looked around to find the most radical
social worker by length of hair, and it worked.''
</P>
<P>
   Though conditions have improved, she allowed, she bristled at
honoring the former governors for their work.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were doing what they were paid to do,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And she agreed with Dr. Bronston's call for an apology.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel it's what establishes a human relationship between
people who provide services and those who receive them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-00 2244EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000502.0366 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 22:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3791 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BONFIRE-REACT0503-COX     05-02 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONFIRE-REACT0503-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Students find relief in findings
 &HT;    By Scott S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ The conclusion that a handful of
structural and ``behavioral'' problems caused last November's Aggie
Bonfire collapse clears the way for the 90-year-old tradition to
continue, many Texas A&AMP;M students and alumni said after a special
commission released its final report Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Students and alumni said they were heartened by the findings _
even though investigators faulted university officials over the
years for allowing students to make engineering decisions they
weren't qualified to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't think it was as harsh as I thought it was
going to be,'' said Julie Zimmerer, a junior.
</P>
<P>
   Former Texas Land Commissioner and 1998 Democratic gubernatorial
candidate Garry Mauro, who graduated from A&AMP;M in 1970, said it was
time to ``go about the business of solving the problems and stop
pointing fingers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad we did the report so that we would know that no
specific person in this bonfire cycle was responsible for the
deaths,'' Mauro said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No bonfire's worth a single student's life. But as far as what
I've read, these are things that can be corrected and we can
continue the bonfire tradition that's so important to all Aggies.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, several construction decisions resulted
in too much stress on a weakened structure. The report also said
university rules were not enforced and the rules came only as
reactive _ not proactive _ measures.
</P>
<P>
   Some students took umbrage at the commission's finding that the
students building the stack were poorly supervised by the
university and slipshod in their construction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that bothered me the most is that it made A&AMP;M sound
irresponsible,'' said Sarah Pinter, a sophomore. ``They made it
sound like students couldn't build it by themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Commission member Veronica Kastrin Callaghan said the collapse,
which killed 12 and injured 27, stemmed from physical failures
driven by decades of poor organization by faculty and students.
</P>
<P>
   She said the panel found safe bonfire construction was ``beyond
the capability of student leaders,'' and that hazing, alcohol use,
horseplay and minor accidents were ignored and tolerated throughout
the tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Junior Will Clark complained that the commission, which had
promised not to lay blame, blasted the university and students.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expected to hear causes and not to hear blame,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M University President Ray Bowen said earlier he would
resign if investigators blamed school administrators for the
accident. But he did not directly answer questions about that
statement Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Cantrell, a 1991 alumnus who sells high-tech equipment in
Austin, said Tuesday's results vindicate Bowen because they spread
the blame among numerous school officials and students over many
years.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the findings that student leaders did not have the
knowledge or skills to make engineering and construction decisions,
Cantrell said the school was right to allow the students' autonomy
because student control of the bonfire is a critical component of
the tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if you had a professional group come in and build
bonfire, it would absolutely not be the same,'' Cantrell said.
</P>
<P>
   Cantrell's wife Dannielle, an Austin real estate agent who heads
the Capital City A&AMP;M Club, agreed that Bowen and his administration
weren't to blame, saying the collapse was ``many years in the
making.''
</P>
<P>
   Cantrell said Tuesday's report should mark the end of the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why there would be any kind of criminal
investigation,'' said Dannielle Cantrell, who graduated in 1993.
``I'm not sure what else you would investigate. I'm not sure who
else you would bring in.''
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Governor Rick Perry, who graduated in 1972, made it clear
that he, too, wants the bonfire to continue. But he sounded a more
cautious note, saying ``if Bonfire is to continue, significant
design, procedural, and cultural changes must be made.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As a former Texas A&AMP;M student myself, I want to see serious
safety and oversight measures put in place so that this unifying
tradition can continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush, who didn't attend A&AMP;M, also urged
university officials ``to review and act on the findings so that we
do everything we can to make sure such a tragedy never happens
again.''
</P>
<P>
   The dominant feeling in Aggieland on Tuesday may have been
relief _ because the report at least leaves open the possibility of
the continuation of the tradition. Bowen will make that
determination in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't see taking away something that's so much of what we
are,'' said Amie Jeffryes, a 20-year-old sophomore at A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
