<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-RABBI-MURDER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO MEN CHARGED IN KILLING OF NEW JERSEY RABBI'S WIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDREW JACOBS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ Two New Jersey men who the authorities said were
paid to kill the wife of a prominent rabbi in Cherry Hill were
formally charged Tuesdau and ordered held without bail, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said that both men had confessed to their roles in
the murder of Carol Neulander, 52, who was bludgeoned to death in
her living room more than five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Until Tuesday, Rabbi Fred J. Neulander, 59, was the only suspect
charged in his wife's murder, a crime that has profoundly shaken
his former congregation, the largest in southern New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators have said they believe the rabbi wanted his wife
dead so he could continue his affair with a woman who had a radio
talk show in Philadelphia. The woman, Elaine Soncini, was
pressuring him to end his marriage, and prosecutors say he feared
divorce proceedings would bring out allegations of infidelity,
threatening his position as leader of M'Kor Shalom, the synagogue
he had founded 20 years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   As in the past, the rabbi's lawyers said Tuesday that Neulander,
the owner of two local bakeries, was killed during a robbery, and
that their client was not connected to her death.
</P>
<P>
   Neulander, who is free on $400,000 bail, had been facing trial
next month on murder and conspiracy charges. With the new
revelations, Dennis Wixted, one of Neulander's lawyers, said he
would ask the judge for more time.
</P>
<P>
   The two men arrested Tuesday, Leonard Jenoff, 54, of
Collingswood, and Paul M. Daniels, 26, of Pennsauken, are being
held at the Camden County Jail on charges of murder and conspiracy
to commit murder.
</P>
<P>
   An unsparing confession by Jenoff, a friend of Neulander's,
added a new dimension to a crime already brimming with lurid
detail. An account of the confession was reported Tuesday by The
Philadelphia Inquirer.
</P>
<P>
   Jenoff, who worked as a private investigator, said he believed
he was being paid to kill an anti-Israeli terrorist, according to
prosecutors. Neulander, Jenoff told them, had said that such a
crime would be forgiven by God. In addition to a promised payment
of $30,000, the rabbi, he said, offered to help find him a job with
Mossad, the Israeli intelligence agency. Only after hearing a news
account of the crime the next morning did he learn the true
identity of his victim, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although both men were charged with murder, Jenoff did not carry
out the crime as intended. At the last minute, paralyzed by fear,
he offered $7,500 to Daniels, his roommate at the time, to do the
deed.
</P>
<P>
   Jenoff's lawyer, Francis J. Hartman, said his client had
confessed because he was overwhelmed by feelings of guilt. ``He
knew the rabbi's trial was coming up and he was afraid he might be
acquitted, which he thought would be wrong,'' Hartman said. ``This
clearly was a spontaneous thing.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hartman said he was disappointed that Jenoff failed to tell
him about his meeting Friday with the Camden County prosecutor, Lee
Solomon. ``He thought he was being given immunity, which was not
the case,'' Hartman said.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Reinert, a spokesman for the prosecutor, said that Jenoff
had never been promised leniency for his cooperation. ``Will he get
some consideration down the road? I have no idea,'' Jenoff said.
``It was a horrible crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Solomon, he added, has not ruled out seeking the death penalty
for all three defendants.
</P>
<P>
   At Tuesday's arraignment, Daniels told Judge Linda Rosenzweig of
State Superior Court that he was unemployed, suffering from mental
illness and living on disability payments. Daniels, who did not
have a lawyer at the hearing, was ordered held on $400,000 bail.
Jenoff's bail was set at $200,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
