u p BC-NY-PATAKI-SENATE-NYT &LR;      05-02 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PATAKI-SENATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK SENATE RACE: MAYOR IS ILL AND GOVERNOR IS COY 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Where are those charred bits of zeppelin?
</P>
<P>
   In December 1998, Gov. George E. Pataki said, ``I would think
it's more likely that the Hindenburg would come back together than
I would step down as governor and become senator.''
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday, he repeatedly refused to rule out entering the race
for U.S. Senate if Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani was forced, because of
his prostate cancer, to drop out. The governor stressed that he
expected the mayor to remain in the race, and beyond that, he said,
``I'm not going to speculate.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor's ambiguous statements troubled some prominent
Republicans who said they worried that the remarks might detract
from the efforts made by Giuliani and his aides to present the
image of a campaign running full throttle and planning to stay that
way.
</P>
<P>
   Late Tuesday afternoon, Michael McKeon, Pataki's press
secretary, called a reporter, clearly exercised at the idea that
the governor's comments might become the basis of a news article.
``This is not him playing games,'' he said. ``This is him having
belief and faith in Rudy.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Giuliani's campaign loudly trumpeted a new appointment
and the mayor and his advisers talked about their efforts to win
the endorsement of the Conservative Party. Bruce Teitelbaum, the
mayor's campaign manager, made the 2{-hour drive here from New York
City on Tuesday to announce that Brendan Quinn, executive director
of the state Republican Party, had been named Giuliani's statewide
field director.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinarily, that would hardly be the stuff of a news conference.
But the race, which pits the mayor against Hillary Rodham Clinton,
has been no ordinary campaign, especially since the mayor disclosed
his illness last week.
</P>
<P>
   Teitelbaum all but said that the appointment, which formalized a
role that Quinn had already been playing, signaled that Giuliani
was in the race to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn, whose job description includes coordinating campaign
events with county chairmen and elected officials around the state,
is a natural choice to plug Giuliani into the resources of the
state party, and to quell the fears of Republicans upstate, who
complain that the mayor has not campaigned aggressively enough,
especially in that region.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said Tuesday that he planned to meet with Michael R.
Long, chairman of the Conservative Party. Long has all but ruled
out nominating Giuliani, in large part because the mayor has
refused to drop his opposition to attempts to ban the abortion
procedure that opponents call partial birth abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not going to change my position but beyond that I am not
going to discuss the meeting,'' Giuliani said. He said the timing
of the meeting had nothing to do with his announcement last
Thursday that tests showed he had prostate cancer, or with Sunday's
disclosure statement by a former congressman, Joseph J. DioGuardi,
that he intended to pursue the Conservative nomination. Still, the
mayor's announcement on Monday that he, too, planned to pursue the
nomination, and his statement on Tuesday that he would meet with
Long, seemed aimed at reinforcing the impression that his is a
vigorous campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Some leading Republicans complained that the comments by Pataki,
whose relationship with the mayor has been strained, would undercut
that impression. Giuliani has said that until he decides on a
course of treatment over the next few weeks, he cannot say
definitively whether he will stay in the race.
</P>
<P>
   The governor was asked Tuesday morning at a news conference here
whether he thought he might run for Senate, after all, given the
mayor's ill health. ``I believe that Mayor Giuliani's going to
run,'' he said, adding, ``I'm not going to speculate.''
</P>
<P>
   He was asked three times if that meant he was ruling out a
campaign, but did not answer directly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very strongly supportive of the mayor, and I'm hopeful
that the mayor will make the decision to stay in the race,'' he
said. ``I don't believe that he will find that there's any
impediment to his candidacy.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time around, he said: ``I love being governor. I want
to stay as governor. But I'm not going to speculate as to what may
or may not happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked later why Pataki did not just say no, he would not run _
and, while he was at it, scold reporters for asking inappropriate
questions _ Zenia Mucha, his chief political adviser, said: ``He
doesn't rule in or out anything. It's not in his nature.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
