<HEADER>
A3794 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-STARCOM-AD-COLUMN-NYT     05-02 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARCOM-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AD COLUMN: MERGER POINTS TO INCREASED USE OF MEDIA SERVICES 
</HEADLINE>
   By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just when Madison Avenue was looking for the latest merger
developments from Young &AMP; Rubicam Inc., another giant agency
company, the B Com3 Group in Chicago, generated some merger news of
its own.
</P>
<P>
   B Com3 _ formed this year when the Leo Group and the MacManus
Group combined and then sold a 20 percent interest to Dentsu in
Tokyo _ said Tuesday that it would merge its media services
agencies, Starcom Worldwide and Mediavest Worldwide, to form a
media planning and buying behemoth named the Starcom Mediavest
Group. (The name may be prosaic, but at least it's not puzzling
like B Com3 ).
</P>
<P>
   Starcom Mediavest will handle media services for accounts with
billings estimated at $16.6 billion. That figure would place the
newly merged agency second among all media brands in worldwide
billings handled, behind only Mindshare, part of the WPP Group, at
$17 billion. Among the major multinational clients of Starcom
Mediavest are blue-chip marketers like Coca-Cola, General Motors,
Kellogg, Mars, Philip Morris and Procter &AMP; Gamble.
</P>
<P>
   The merger points to the intensified focus on media services as
a critical tool for agencies in trying to sell goods and services
to increasingly choosy consumers. Media planning and buying were
not so important in the days when the choice of big television
networks on which to run a commercial was limited to ABC, CBS and
NBC, and the choice of large national magazines in which to run an
advertisement was limited to Collier's, Life, Look and The Saturday
Evening Post.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without the right media, you won't get the message through,''
said Bob Brennan, 41, the chief operating officer at Starcom who
will hold that post at Starcom Mediavest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jack and I often talk how we're on the verge of a nuclear arms
race among media agencies,'' Brennan said, referring to Jack Klues,
45, the chief executive at Starcom who will become chief executive
at Starcom Mediavest. ``This industry is going to consolidate
rapidly and war is going to begin. We want to go into the war with
as big an arsenal as we can find.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming soon to a theater near you, will be ``Dr. Strangead or:
How I Learned to Stop Worrying and Love the Infomercial.''
</P>
<P>
   In most countries, the separate offices of Starcom, formed in
1997 by Leo, and Mediavest, formed by MacManus last year, will be
combined by Jan. 1, 2001, and operate under the Starcom moniker.
That has already taken place in Mexico. In others, including China
and Greece, joint ventures were formed to handle media duties for
P&AMP;G.
</P>
<P>
   In some markets, however, Mediavest and Starcom will operate
separately, either because of conflicts preventing a merger or the
success of the individual media brands. In North America, for
instance, Mediavest will continue handling media for the Burger
King unit of Diageo and Continental Airlines, while Starcom will
continue handling media for McDonald's and Delta Air Lines.
</P>
<P>
   If those conflicts were ever to be resolved, ``we can instantly
consolidate,'' Brennan said.
</P>
<P>
   And in markets like Britain, where ``there's tremendous
opportunity to grow the two brands,'' he added, ``we can always
consolidate systems and nonproprietary research.''
</P>
<P>
   Starcom Mediavest will be run by a chief executive team of
Klues, Brennan and Kevin Malloy, 36, the chief operating officer at
Mediavest. Malloy will become executive vice president for
international operations at Starcom Mediavest and the chief
executive at Mediavest North America.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Moore, who had come out of retirement to lead Mediavest
after Irwin Gotlieb, its president, left to join Mindshare last
summer, will relinquish the reins again, as of July 1. Moore, 62,
will remain on the Starcom Mediavest board.
</P>
<P>
   The merger of Mediavest and Starcom brings the Leo-MacManus saga
full circle. The two had initially met in 1998 to discuss merging
only their media agencies, but the talks bogged down primarily
because of disagreements between Gotlieb and his counterparts at
Starcom.
</P>
<P>
   After Gotlieb defected to Mindshare, Roger Haupt, the incoming
chief executive at Leo, contacted Roy J. Bostock, chairman and
chief executive at MacManus, to propose merging the holding
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good things come to those who wait, I guess,'' Brennan said,
laughing, then pausing to add: ``And plan and fight and are
tenacious about their futures.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
