<HEADER>
A3796 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-KANSASCITY-SCHOOLS-NY     05-02 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KANSASCITY-SCHOOLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`F' FOR KANSAS CITY SCHOOLS ADDS TO THE DISTRICT'S WOES 
</HEADLINE>
   By DIRK JOHNSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite spending more than $2 billion over two decades to
improve education and attract more white students, the Kansas City
School District has essentially been judged a failure by a state
education review board, which has denied it accreditation.
</P>
<P>
   With the loss of state accreditation on Monday, public schools
in Kansas City, Mo., took another blow to its battered image.
Despite long and ambitious efforts stemming from a 1977
desegregation lawsuit, it remains a district where about 75 percent
of its students are members of racial minorities and where test
scores remain low.
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri Board of Education removed the status of
accreditation after the Kansas City schools failed to meet any of
11 performance standards.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin Demps Jr., the superintendent of schools, vowed earlier
this week to aggressively win back accreditation, saying, ``We have
been preparing to face the challenge it brings.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the district had seen improvements in the attendance
rate lately and had already begun several new strategies at
improving education, including a move for more demanding standards
on literacy.
</P>
<P>
   The problems of the Kansas City schools, and the long court
remedies designed to improve education and more fully integrate the
schools, have long been a centerpiece in the national debate over
race, test scores and the competing notions of raising academic
achievement.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of accreditation means the district has two years to
raise test scores, improve graduation rates and make progress in
other areas or face the prospect of a takeover by the state.
</P>
<P>
   The action by the state board also means that children in the
Kansas City School District can leave for suburban schools, and
that the Kansas City District would be forced to pay tuition and
transportation costs.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of accreditation came as no surprise. The board decided
last fall to strip the status from the Kansas City District,
effective May 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have known this day was coming since last November,'' Demps
said on Monday, promising improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Gwen Grant, an executive vice president of the Urban League in
Kansas City, expressed concern that a ``panic environment'' would
lead many parents to withdraw their children from the city's
schools.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging that serious problems endure in the district,
Grant said the state could have aggressively demanded improvements
without deeming the district a failure.
</P>
<P>
   Grant said that while the school district had spent lavishly on
new facilities and had instituted programs like those at a Greek
studies magnet school, designed largely to attract suburban
students, not enough attention has been paid to basic learning in
the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   The district has used magnet schools since 1985, allowing
certain schools to concentrate on special disciplines, a system
that was intended to increase the number of suburban students
volunteering to attend the city schools. Of the 37,000 students in
the Kansas City District, about 2,000 live in the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton Adams, whose daughter will graduate from a Kansas City
high school this year, blamed the district for putting too much
emphasis on the racial makeup of the schools, rather than
concentrating on academic standards.
</P>
<P>
   Adams, a lawyer who is black, said greater racial integration
would have come naturally if the district had focused more keenly
on making the schools better, regardless of the racial makeup.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to remove accreditation, he said, is ``stigmatizing
and embarrassing to students and staff at the schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Last November, a federal judge dismissed the desegregation suit,
saying the district had done all it could to end racial
segregation. But an appeals court reinstated the case in January,
noting enduring gaps between white and black students on test
scores.
</P>
<P>
   The district failed each of 11 performance indicators, including
test scores, dropout rate and attendance.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the Kansas City schools are failing. The district's
college preparatory school has some of the best test scores in the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Many Republicans in Missouri have long been critics of the
Kansas City School District, complaining that it was receiving a
disproportionate share of state money.
</P>
<P>
   A proposed bill in the Missouri Legislature would split the
district into five smaller units. Proponents of the measure say
smaller schools would be easier to manage.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Carson Ross, a Republican, noted that the two biggest
districts in the state, Kansas City and St. Louis, had the most
severe problems.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City District has also been forced to compete with a
growing number of charter schools, which are run independently.
Some 15 charter schools now operate in Kansas City, with requests
pending for two more in the next academic year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
