<HEADER>
A3799 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-FISCAL-NYT &LR;      05-02 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FISCAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBANY ACCORD ON DEBT PLAN CLEARS WAY FOR PASSING BUDGET
</HEADLINE>
  By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Gov. George Pataki and state legislative leaders
announced an agreement Tuesday to restrict the state's
much-maligned borrowing practices, clearing the way for final
passage of one of the timeliest state budgets in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki had refused to sign off on a final budget deal until a
debt reform package was agreed on. The proposal hammered out
Tuesday would for the first time impose a cap on the amount of debt
that the state could carry at any one time. The deal on debt limits
means that the Legislature will be able to begin passing budget
bills in the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   The debt issue is critically important to Pataki, a Republican,
in large part because he has been facing sharp criticism from
conservative groups and independent budget analysts for expanding
the state's overall indebtedness, even as the state has amassed
multibillion-dollar budget surpluses from year to year.
</P>
<P>
   New York's debt has grown by more than 30 percent in the six
years since the governor took office, bringing the total to more
than $37 billion, the largest for any state in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The debt is one of the major reasons that the state's credit
rating on Wall Street is among the poorest in the nation. It is
also forcing the state to spend nearly $4 billion a year on debt
service.
</P>
<P>
   The budget that Pataki and the leaders agreed upon calls for
spending $77.5 billion to provide hefty spending increases for
education, health care, transportation, public colleges and
universities and other programs. The finished product reflects the
state's continued economic prosperity, relying heavily on the
surging tax revenues that are largely generated by huge profits on
Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   The budget also provides a bounty of new tax cuts that would
save New Yorkers $1.3 billion a year when fully phased in over the
next four years. The biggest part is $330 million to reduce a tax
on utility companies that is passed on to consumers each month. The
package also establishes tax deductions for college tuition costs,
provides tax credits for low-wage workers and gives new tax breaks
to married couples whose marital status raises their taxes.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Tuesday, Pataki said the budget struck a
balance between new spending and tax cuts. He also said the plan to
restrict the state's rapidly growing borrowing would help place the
state on firm financial footing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This budget includes the most fundamental debt reform in the
history of New York State,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The state budget was due on April 1, but for the 16th
consecutive year, the Legislature and the governor failed to meet
that deadline.
</P>
<P>
   But the agreement reached Tuesday almost certainly means that
the governor and the leaders will complete their work this year
earlier than they have in recent memory. Last year, for example,
the budget was adopted on Aug. 4 _ 126 days overdue.
</P>
<P>
   To breach the gap between the deadline and this week's action,
the Legislature had to pass contingency budgets that kept spending
at last year's levels. While the delay does not cost the taxpayers
more, it does impose hardship on localities, particularly school
districts that need to know the amount of state money to plan their
own budgets.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's aides said the general fund budget, which consists of
revenues from state taxes and fees that are not committed to
specific purposes, would rise about 4.7 percent, or nearly $1.8
billion more than last year's $37 billion. The governor had
proposed a 2.3 percent, or nearly $1 billion, increase in general
fund spending.
</P>
<P>
   But this year's total state spending would increase by about
$4.1 billion, or 5.7 percent, to $77.5 billion, according to
another calculation. That calculation includes federal money that
passes through the state budget and other money that is not
included in the general fund. Pataki had proposed an increase of
5.5 percent, or $3.9 billion, in total state spending.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki and the Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver, a Democrat, and
Senate Majority Leader Joseph L. Bruno, a Republican, predicted
that the entire budget would be passed as early as this week.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest spending increase in the budget goes to education.
It provides a record $1.2 billion, or 8.7 percent, rise in state
aid to public school districts statewide, bringing the total amount
spent on education to about $13 billion. New York City is expected
to receive about $400 million of the total increase.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
