<HEADLINE>
A FRACTIOUS SNUCK IN TO SKIP DERBY
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: fraction in final section spelled out _ 59 and two-fifths
seconds) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Snuck In was withdrawn from the Kentucky Derby
on Tuesday after a fast but unruly workout and, on the eve of the
post-position draw, the outside gates may be in demand for the
126th running of the race on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Asmussen, the trainer of Snuck In, the Arkansas Derby
runner-up, decided not to enter the colt following a swift
59-second breeze at five furlongs. The time was crisp, but Asmussen
was not pleased with how Snuck In repeatedly tossed his head and
fought his exercise rider, Krissie Knorr.
</P>
<P>
   After discussing it with the owners, Bob and Lee Ackerley of
Ackerley Brothers Farms, they decided to wait until the Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   ``This work wasn't exactly what I wanted,'' Asmussen said of
Snuck In, who missed training time over the winter with an
abscessed hoof. ``We know he's fast. But the style he has now is
not the style to be successful in a race like the Kentucky Derby.
He needs to take a deep breath and relax. You don't see horses in
an argument early in the Derby who are there at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   The colt's withdrawal means Godolphin's China Visit will
probably make what is expected to be a full 20-horse field. With no
graded stakes earnings, the Dubai-based colt came here hoping for
defections. He has picked up two victories in his only official
starts, though he recently won a trial race in Dubai.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be very disappointing to come all the way here and
not get in,'' said China Visit's assistant trainer, Tom Albertrani,
who was here last year with Worldly Manner for Godolphin. ``It's
always exciting to be here and race and be a part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   POST-POSITION POKER
</P>
<P>
   When the post positions are drawn in a two-tiered system
intended to create television interest, look for trainers to send
their horses to the outside: three of the last five Kentucky Derby
winners have raced from the auxiliary gate, including the 1999
winner, Charismatic, who broke from post No.16. The trainers must
draw a low number to get an advantageous draft selection.
</P>
<P>
   In the first draw, for example, if the early favorite, Fusaichi
Pegasus, draws the No.1, then his trainer, Neil Drysdale, will
choose his post from the 20 spots.
</P>
<P>
   After a roughly ridden race in last year's full field and plenty
of speed going postward on Saturday, the trainer Todd Pletcher is
looking for middle-to-outside spots for his four horses _ More Than
Ready, Graeme Hall, Trippi and Impeachment. ``It looks like when
the gates spring, the momentum pinballs everyone inside,'' he said.
``You can get squeezed or roughed up pretty early. If you're
outside you have a better chance of staying clear.''
</P>
<P>
   D. Wayne Lukas agrees. The trainer of Charismatic, last year's
Derby winner, is looking for his fifth Kentucky Derby winner and
believes his top colt and front-runner, High Yield, will be better
served from the outside, where he also won with Thunder Gulch from
post 16 in 1995 and Grindstone from post 15 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can win it from anywhere,'' Lukas said. ``The one thing I
definitely don't want is a couple of young jockeys who aren't
proven in this race on either side of me.''
</P>
<P>
   BLINKERS OFF CAPTAIN STEVE
</P>
<P>
   Captain Steve, who won the Kentucky Jockey Club Stakes at
Churchill Downs last fall, continued to look better than his record
this year has indicated. The chestnut colt, owned and trained by
the team that won the 1998 Derby with Real Quiet _ Mike Pegram and
Bob Baffert _ skipped over the oval in an effortless 59 and
two-fifths seconds.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second time the colt, who has not won this year,
worked without blinkers, but this time by design. Last week,
Baffert forgot to put the equipment before a workout. Now Captain
Steve will abandon them altogether after seven starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He worked great,'' Baffert said. ``He worked today without
blinkers and he'll run Saturday without them. The last couple of
times he ran, the riders said he seemed to get edgy and a little
hot going to the gate. So we took the blinkers off for his workout
the other day and left them off again today. He's more focused now
with the racing experience he's had and I don't think he needs them
anymore.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
