<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-MAYFIELD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASCAR PUNISHES MAYFIELD TEAM FOR ILLEGAL FUEL AT TALLADEGA 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jeremy Mayfield and his team were penalized Tuesday by Nascar
officials, receiving suspensions, fines and a loss of points for
using illegal fuel in a Winston Cup Series race in Talladega, Ala.,
two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   The tough penalties, which included the second-largest fine in
Nascar history, came two days after Mayfield won the biggest race
of his career in the NAPA Auto Parts 500 in Fontana, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Mayfield, who drives a Ford Taurus, had 151 driver points taken
away, dropping him from 7th place to 14th in the Winston Cup
standing.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Kranefuss, who operates the team that he owns with Roger
Penske, was fined $50,000. He and the crew chief, Peter Sospenzo,
were suspended until June 6, or for three races.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Helton, Nascar's chief operating officer, announced the
penalties from the association's Daytona Beach, Fla., headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Through a routine postrace fuel sampling, we found a foreign
substance in the fuel of the No. 12 car following the race at
Talladega,'' he said in a statement. ``We took several fuel
samples, and the sample from the No. 12 car read considerably
different than the sample that was taken from our fuel source on
site.''
</P>
<P>
   An improper additive _ an oxygen enhancer that boosts horsepower
_ was discovered in the fuel tank of Mayfield's car, Nascar
officials said. Both Mayfield and Kranefuss issued apologetic
statements from their headquarters in Mooresville, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all embarrassed, and we're all going to make sure
nothing like this happens again,'' Mayfield said. ``There were some
things that were done wrong. But we're going to work to get back to
where we were before.''
</P>
<P>
   Kranefuss said that disciplinary action has been taken within
the team and he apologized to the team's fans, sponsors and
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mistakes were made and there were certainly some errors in
judgment,'' he said. ``People make mistakes, but we have to move
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Kranefuss said the additive had been put in the gas tank by an
unidentified crew member.
</P>
<P>
   Mayfield was unaware of what the crew member had done, Nascar
officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
