<SLUG> BC-GEN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. FANS SEND THE RIGHT MESSAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (begin ital) Today's I-love-L.A. edition of The Sporting Muse:
(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   - The moonshot at Dodgers Stadium Monday was the prettiest I've
seen at a Dodgers game since 1959, when Wally Moon was sending
moonshots over the Chinese Wall at the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   The last thing anyone should do is suggest that it is OK for a
fan to run on the field for any purpose. But as succinct messages
go, the 24-year-old fan who dropped trou and played Butthead to
John Rocker's Beavis couldn't have made his point better.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the overall reaction by fans in attendance to the
appearance of the loose-lipped Braves reliever was heartening. L.A.
stepped up and booed Rocker lustfully, letting him know what they
thought of his character assassination of a cross-section of
America in a December issue of Sports Illustrated.
</P>
<P>
   The mooning by Andrew Tellers of Bellflower was a much more
effective message than a rowdy chorus of ``Rocker sucks'' or any
other verbal epitath that fans shouted.
</P>
<P>
   Tellers was charged with a misdemeanor, delaying a sporting
event, and faces a court appearances May 22. But he'll likely have
no problem paying any fine.
</P>
<P>
   A friend seated in the same area as Tellers, in the field boxes
along first base, said fans in the area were passing bills to a
buddy of Tellers so he could make bail and pay his fine. ...
</P>
<P>
   -The down side of Monday's mooning is the prospect of other,
less discriminating fans deciding to play copycat. Since seeing
Monica Seles get stabbed by a fan, the sight of a fan running on a
field has an element of fear that needs to be taken seriously.
</P>
<P>
   And some fans do go overboard. Last week in San Diego, Braves
players caught some Padres fans throwing marbles at Rocker and
other players. When Rocker ran onto the field Monday, some Dodger
fans launched full bottles of water at him, water readily available
at some concession stands.
</P>
<P>
   If laid-back Southern California fans are found throwing marbles
and water bottles, one can only imagine the potential nightmare
when Rocker shows up in Philadelphia and New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's hope that's as bad as it gets,'' Braves manager Bobby
Cox said. ...
</P>
<P>
   -JaRon Rush is a nice young man, and I wish the ex-Bruin well as
he attempts the jump to the NBA. His family concerns are as much a
reason for his departure as the NCAA's pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   But his comments Tuesday underscores the myopic view many young
athletes have about college.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of taking responsibility for accepting money from a
scumbag summer agent, and for having a child long before he's
capable of supporting him, he blamed things on NCAA rules that
doesn't put any money into the pockets of players.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the spartan life as a college student-athlete
on a full scholarship, Rush said ``You just sit around bored all
day long and don't have any money to do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   I guess the thought of killing time by attending classes, doing
homework and making progress toward a degree didn't come to mind.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA needs to consider stipends to stem the early flood of
players to the NBA and NFL and to address the galling disparity
between its TV revenue ($6 billion deal with CBS) and direct
athletic subsidies ($0).
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps a better solution would be eliminating athletic
scholarships altogether. Take away the free ride and force
student-athletes to qualify and show progress like any other
student and you eliminate a lot of student-athletes who could care
less about the student part. ...
</P>
<P>
   -Back to baseball: The game would be a lot more interesting if
more pitchers adopted the philosopy of Boston's Pedro Martinez and
drove batters off the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez was labeled a headhunter while in Montreal, but anyone
with the control he has knew exactly what he was doing this week
when he put a fastball under the chin of Cleveland's Einar Diaz. He
was informing the Indians that the plate was his. If there were
more pitchers like him, maybe we wouldn't be kvetching about
homermania. ...
</P>
<P>
   -There were 931 home runs hit in the month of April, 195 more
than last year and an all-time major league baseball record. Now
imagine what that total would be if there hadn't been so many
snowouts and rainouts. The all-time one-month record is 980, set
last May and destined to fall this May. ...
</P>
<P>
   -The rich get richer: The Yankees apparently hold the early lead
in trading for Minnesota Twins pitcher Brad Radke this June or
July. They have moved off their can't-touch position regarding
infielder Alfonso Soriano, a natural shortstop whose path in New
York is blocked until, say, 2015, by Derek Jeter. ...
</P>
<P>
   -The Angels Darin Erstad will win the A.L. batting title. Since
he's hitting .449, that's not exactly a wild prediction, but I have
always thought Erstad was the kind of hitter who wins batting
crowns. But I still think he would provide even more offense for
the Angels if he hit third rather than leadoff. ...
</P>
<P>
   -NBA scuttlebutt: Spies say Tim Duncan will likely stay in San
Antonio and spurn free agent offers. They also say ex-Laker Eddie
Jones will aggressively pursue a new home because he wants to play
on a team with a title in its future. Would it be greedy to wonder
if he'd consider a return to Los Angeles?
</P>
<P>
   Insiders also say that while Vince Carter is the truth, he isn't
6-7 as he's listed in the NBA Register and he doesn't come close to
soaring as high or as far as Michael Jordan. He can be fronted,
something no one dared do against Jordan unless he liked being
dunked on. ...
</P>
<P>
   -Tiger Woods went on strike this week and didn't shoot any
commercials, because he happens to be a member of the striking
Screen Actors Guild (SAG), which raises the question if athletes
aren't due some kind of residual benefit since they play on TV so
often.
</P>
<P>
   Not that they need the money, of course, but you know it's only
a matter of time. ...
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-00 2310EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000502.0377 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3914 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BONFIRE-REPORT0503-CO     05-02 1848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONFIRE-REPORT0503-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Construction and organization blamed for Bonfire tragedy
 &HT;    By Mike Ward and Suzanne Gamboa
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ Construction mistakes by Texas A&AMP;M
University students and design flaws undetected for decades caused
the Aggie bonfire to collapse last November like a barrel that had
lost its hoops, an investigation of the accident concluded Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   And while assigning no blame for the Nov. 18 accident that
killed 12 and injured 27, the 700-page report _ which cost an
estimated $1.8 million and took four months to complete _ contained
a blistering denunciation of the lack of supervision by A&AMP;M
officials of the student-run project, criticizing what it called
``tunnel vision in decision making'' and a cultural bias at Texas'
second-largest university that allowed safety problems to go
uncorrected.
</P>
<P>
   ``While no one person is responsible for the collapse, the
aggregate effect of actions and decisions by students and
university officials over many years created the physical
conditions that made the collapse possible,'' the report states.
``In the commission's view, the evidence of ongoing problems with
Bonfire is so overwhelming that collectively these problems should
have triggered a broader re-examination of Bonfire _ one that
included Bonfire design and construction. Unfortunately, that did
not occur.''
</P>
<P>
   Leo Linbeck Jr., a Houston construction executive who headed the
five-member investigating panel, said he hopes the report will spur
change. The report contained no recommendation on whether the
bonfire should continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Texas A&AMP;M continues this without change, it would do
violence to the tradition of A&AMP;M,'' he said, stressing that the
90-year tradition can be built safely if changes are made. ``Some
good can come from the bad.''
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M President Ray Bowen, who sat solemnly as the report was
presented Tuesday to a crowd of 1,500 students and officials in
Reed Arena, the university's basketball stadium, promised a
decision within six weeks on whether the bonfire will continue.
University officials said more than 200 reporters from nearly 50
news outlets were covering the event, including representatives of
national news organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we do continue to have a bonfire it will be appropriate to
change the culture. That's essential,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bowen said his decision will be based on what is best for the
university, its students and families of the victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not made up my mind. It may be that we will continue
the bonfire. It may be that we will not continue the bonfire,''
Bowen said. ``I've said in a number of forums, if I had to let my
heart make the decision, we'd have a bonfire. My heart will not
make the decision. My brain has to make the decision.''
</P>
<P>
   But even though Bowen was emphatic that no decision on bonfire
has been made, students in the audience during the presentation and
a press conference afterward made it clear _ shouting ``whoop''
when they agreed with speakers, hissing loudly when they disagreed
_ that they hope there is a bonfire next November. In fact, A&AMP;M's
campus paper, The Batallion, reported Tuesday that students have
begun organizing for the next bonfire, despite a ban imposed by A&AMP;M
officials on such activities.
</P>
<P>
   Held each November on the eve of Texas A&AMP;M's football game with
archrival University of Texas, the bonfire annually draws tens of
thousands of Aggie diehards to College Station in what is billed as
a demonstration of Aggie's school spirit and ``burning desire'' to
beat t.u. _ a derogatory Aggie reference to UT. Through the years,
the bonfire has grown from a small, impromptu trash fire into a
teepee of logs into a wedding-cake-shaped fire.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, the deadly chain of events began
shortly after 2:30 a.m. when baling wire that was used to hold
together the first tier of logs on the unfinished, four-tier
bonfire began breaking apart.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators found that the student-builders had wedged too
many logs from the second tier into the top of the first _ a move
they thought would make the log stack more structurally stable,
since the logs were more crooked than usual.
</P>
<P>
   But what they did not realize was that the bonfire was built on
ground sloping slightly to the southeast, that the second stack was
built lopsided in that direction and that the whole bonfire was
being built more vertically than in some past years _ all factors
that, the report concluded, worked together to fuel the collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Within seconds after the wires began snapping, logs began
falling away from the southeast side of the first tier. The second
tier shifted and began to fall. And the centerpole snapped between
those tiers.
</P>
<P>
   Then the whole bonfire began to fall to the southeast, snapping
one of the four ropes anchoring the top of the centerpole and
breaking the centerpole off at the ground. Within seconds, it broke
again as the log pile fell _ its top ending atop of the pile in the
opposite direction of the fall.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the stack of logs weighed an estimated 2 million pounds
_ more than twice as much as a 747 jumbo jet, the report said. Most
of the victims were killed instantly, police said earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``This collapse happened very quickly,'' said commission member
Hugh Robinson, the chairman of a Dallas construction management
company. ``Eyewitnesses were stunned at how fast the stack fell to
the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, steel cables had been wrapped around the first
tier. But the report disclosed that student construction leaders
decided not use them last fall because they thought using them
might cause the bonfire to burn faster. Using them, Linbeck said,
might have reduced, but not eliminated, the risk of collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wiring itself was found to be a variety of strength, the
individual character itself was insufficient to stand the
stresses,'' he said. ``The lack of cabling around the stack on the
first level removed one of the factors of safety.''
</P>
<P>
   The report described the baling wire and cable as acting like
hoops on a barrel. Without the hoops, and with the pressure of the
second stack pressing down upon it, the first stack fell apart as
would a barrel's unrestrained wooden slats.
</P>
<P>
   The report ruled out as contributing factors the centerpole, the
soil beneath the bonfire, the guy ropes and an accident a few days
before the tragedy in which a crane hit a cross-tie on the
centerpole. It also ruled out sabotage and an earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   Through the years, the report notes, the design of the bonfire
had changed gradually from a teepee of logs in the 1940s to a
multi-tiered teepee that, by 1969, had reached a record height of
more than 109 feet. By the late 1970s, the bonfires had begun to
more resemble a wedding cake _ six tiers high bound with wire, 60
to 80 feet tall and a two-part spliced centerpole.
</P>
<P>
   But the report states those changes were made with little
consideration of structural issues since there were no blueprints
or designs, most of the student-builders had no experience or
expertise and university officials ineffectively supervised the
project.
</P>
<P>
   ``The physical failure and casual factors were driven by an
organizational failure,'' the report states. ``This failure, which
had its roots in decisions and actions by both students and
university officials over many years, created an environment in
which a complex and dangerous structure was allowed to be built
without adequate physical or engineering controls.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, the report notes, the bonfire project was plagued by
problems with hazing, harassment of workers, drinking by students,
fighting and other misbehavior _ conduct that the report said had
contributed to accidents and injuries that, between 1996 and 1998
alone, increased by 80 percent. ``In the experience of the
investigation team, Texas A&AMP;M is unique in allowing this level of
irresponsible behavior in and around a construction project of this
magnitude,'' the report states.
</P>
<P>
   And while those problems were ``not relevant to the collapse,''
the report states, they were part of a larger problem with Aggie
culture itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lack of a written bonfire design or construction
methodology,'' the report states, was an important protective step
that was not taken. It characterized the project as ``a world in
which design decisions are made with no written guidance, no formal
reviews and no knowledge of critical design factors.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Texas A&AMP;M's engineering school is among the top
ranked in the nation, its faculty never has been actively involved
in the bonfire construction. And in past years, the report says,
several ``clear warning signs about structural integrity'' were
missed by A&AMP;M officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``This tunnel vision in decision-making is due, in the
commission's view, to a cultural bias in which legitimate courses
of action outside past experience or contrary to the university's
pre-disposition are often not considered,'' the report states.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why did no one consider the '69 stack as a potentially
hazardous, 10-story structure held together with bailing wire? Why
didn't anyone interpret the quick recent burn times as a problem
with wire strength?''
</P>
<P>
   An unfinished bonfire stack teetered and nearly fell over in
1994 in what university officials blamed on wet soil. On Tuesday,
commission consultant Tage Carlson said a new review of that
incident shows that it was more likely caused by wire failures much
like the 1999 collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Suggesting the university should have been more pro-active in
dealing with bonfire problems and issues, rather than reactive, the
report states that ``the evidence of ongoing bonfire problems is so
overwhelming that collectively these should have triggered a
broader overall re-examination of bonfire _ one that included
bonfire design and construction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, this did not occur,'' said Commission member
Veronica Kastrin Callaghan of El Paso. ``It's a true example of an
organizational accident with causes that existed for some time
before the event.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the panel found safe bonfire construction was ``beyond
the capability of student leaders and that there was no appropriate
formal design. Although investigators heard that the stack always
had been built the same way over the years, ``bonfire never was
built the same way twice,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Reading from the report, Callaghan said the ``skills and
knowledge inadequacy of student leaders cannot be easily
corrected.'' It would also be prohibitively expensive to try to
train students every year.
</P>
<P>
   Bowen said that and other issues will weigh into his decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``The central message is clear,'' Callaghan added. ``The
collapse was about physical failures driven by organizational
failures whose origins span decades of administrations, faculty and
students. No single factor caused the collapse, just as no single
change will ensure that a tragedy like this never happens again.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
