<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3916 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-BONFIRE-PROBE-HNS &LR;      05-02 1451
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONFIRE-PROBE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BONFIRE REPORT FINDS DESIGN FLAWS, `TUNNEL VISION' 

</HEADLINE>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN WILLIAMS 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ The deadly Texas A&AMP;M University Bonfire
collapse was caused by poor design and construction methods that
were carried out for decades because of cultural myopia, which put
tradition over safety, a special commission reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Structurally, the report pegged the causes of the accident that
killed 12 people last fall on weak wiring used to couple logs, no
steel cables to bind the lower tier of logs and crooked wood that
allowed second-stack timber to be wrongly wedged into the first. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   But the strongly worded 36-page report also lay blame on the
Aggie culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``The university has a culture that instills bias and tunnel
vision in decision making. No credible source ever suspected or
thought to inquire about structural safety,'' the report said. ``No
one in the administration ever interpreted ongoing behavioral
problems as indications that safe Bonfire design and construction
was beyond the capabilities of student leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   Generally, the report, at a cost of nearly $1.8 million _ funded
by interest earnings on university student fees and other non-tax
revenues _ &UR;  &LR; was applauded by both critics and friends of the
90-year-old Bonfire tradition. The five-member commission was
appointed by university President Ray Bowen immediately after the
Bonfire disaster and ordered to find the causes of the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   However, it was not ordered to make recommendations, nor did it
specifically assign blame, responsibility or negligence for the
Nov. 18 tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   What happens next rests with Bowen, who plans to take at least
six weeks considering what action to take on the Bonfire after
seeking opinions from students, faculty and alumni.
</P>
<P>
   With about 3,000 people gathered in the school's Reed Arena, Leo
Linbeck Jr., the Houston construction executive who headed the
commission opened the presentation of the long-awaited report. He
got quickly to the point.
</P>
<P>
   ``This failure has roots in decisions and actions by both
students and university officials over many, many years. It created
an environment where a complex and dangerous structure was allowed
to be built without controls,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Later, in a terse statement that kept the crowd spellbound for
more than 20 minutes, commission member Veronica Callaghan, an El
Paso businesswoman, repeatedly criticized the Aggie culture for
allowing the collapse to happen despite prior warning signals.
</P>
<P>
   She said that the 1999 Bonfire came as a total surprise to those
involved when it should not have. ``Again, this is a result of a
cultural bias and represents a management barrier failure relevant
to the collapse.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission was especially harsh about the university's
failure to see the warning sign in 1994 when that year's structure
tilted under heavy rains and had to be pulled down. That failure
was wrongly written off simply to a rainy year, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the report showed that both students and university
leaders over the years did not employ the same type of safeguards
that eight other universities use for similar high-risk student
activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the commission's view, the evidence of ongoing problems
with Bonfire is so overwhelming that collectively these problems
should have triggered a broader re-examination of Bonfire _ one
that included Bonfire design and construction,'' said Callaghan.
``Unfortunately, this did not occur.``
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference minutes after being told that the Aggie
culture was resistant to change and bucked criticism, hundreds of
spectators routinely hissed at reporters asking challenging
questions or let out the traditional ``whoop'' when it was
speculated Bonfire would continue.
</P>
<P>
   After the report was released during the meeting and on the
Internet, Gov. George W. Bush released a statement commending the
commission for finding answers to the tragedy, and offering
condolences to victims' families, friends and classmates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I urge university officials to review and act upon the
findings so that we do everything we can to make sure such a
tragedy never happens again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bowen said he accepted the report and did not find fault with
any of its findings, including criticism of his and past
administrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I accept responsibility,'' said the president, an A&AMP;M
engineering graduate, who assumed his post shortly before the 1994
Bonfire failure.
</P>
<P>
   One university official who has had oversight of Bonfire, Bill
Kibler, predicted that Bonfire could continue after ``major changes
are made in the design.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it can still be a student event, if the design
changes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The commission chose five consultants who conducted 700
interviews with students, Bonfire consultants, critics and others,
as well as 250 student surveys. They also reviewed police reports,
photographs and 4,600 school documents.
</P>
<P>
   The consultants assessed the historical and current design of
Bonfire, and the historical and current cultural problems. The
result is a comprehensive document in easy-to-understand language,
which on the computer has computer-generated animation of how the
stack fell that largely satisfied even the harshest Bonfire
critics.
</P>
<P>
   The report illustrates how the design of the Bonfire changed
over the years, from a more stable Indian teepee style where timber
leaned toward the center into a more unstable wedding cake style
used since the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   The report criticizes the construction of such a mammoth
structure by students without engineering backgrounds needed to
provide more scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, the report absolves 1999 Bonfire student
leadership for blame, saying they accurately followed tradition as
they knew it.
</P>
<P>
   Changes made to the 1999 Bonfire, including the increased
wedging and lack of cables, came about because the student leaders
incorrectly believed they would make it safer. Students thought
that wedging logs from the second stack into the first would
strengthen it and that not using cables would cause the fire to
burn quicker.
</P>
<P>
   The report indicates that some of the preventable root causes
can be corrected. However, providing students with proper skills
may be impossible because of cost and the need to educate them
every year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if they make changes, then Bonfire can continue,''
Linbeck said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, though alcohol abuse, hazing and other problems occurred
during construction of the 1999 Bonfire, including alcohol use the
night of the collapse, there was no evidence those factors played a
role in the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, questions have been raised about the thoroughness
of a report paid for by the school. Some have criticized the
process as a way for the university to appear to have an unbiased
report, while at the same time, buying an investigation that can
later be used should the university be sued.
</P>
<P>
   None of the victims' parents have shown an inclination toward
suing the school. But that doesn't mean lawsuits won't be filed
against others involved, such as H.B. Zachry, the construction
company that provided a crane that ran into the Bonfire days before
it collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   Linbeck is head of Texans for Tort Reform, a group that included
Zachry officials and has been crucial in getting state laws changed
to make it harder for Texans to file punitive lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Linbeck said he did not want to talk about negligence
in the Bonfire collapse saying ``negligence is a legal term.''
</P>
<P>
   However, A&AMP;M graduate and author Irwin A. Tang, whose recent
book criticizes the administration for allowing Bonfire to
collapse, said the report too conveniently spreads the blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``The blame now lies with history,'' Tang said. ``To call it a
history of negligence on the part of the administrations makes the
negligence of this administration defensible and possibly
understandable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be true that the university administration has only
followed tradition and allowed students to design and build the
Bonfire, but that doesn't free them from responsibility for safety
of students on their campus.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, as proof that the A&AMP;M culture is hard to reign in,
Bowen was faced with a report in the campus newspaper that students
have started preparing for the 2000 Bonfire despite warnings not to
from university officials.
</P>
<P>
   The Battalion student paper reported that residence halls have
already selected crew chiefs and inducted them in a ceremony that
includes hazing. Bowen said he would investigate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
