<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAPA FOX RETURNS TO WORK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO - Rick Fox was back with his Lakers teammates Tuesday
afternoon, having made a difficult departure for the second time in
three days.
</P>
<P>
   First, he had to leave his team in the wake of a demoralizing
Game 3 loss to be in New York with wife Vanessa Williams for the
birth of their daughter. Then he had to leave his wife and baby in
New York, less than a day after Sasha Gabriella's arrival, to make
it back for Game 4 against the Sacramento Kings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was quite an experience, coming from being mostly down and
drained after the loss here to the adrenaline all the way through
yesterday,'' said Fox, still wearing the hospital ID bracelet,
before Game 4. ``Both (were) similar feelings of leaving something
behind that is dear to you. This race for a championship is
something I've focused on in my life with this team now for three
years and falling short (two) years in a row.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox said Williams' labor was quick, ``and she smiled through the
whole thing, which I don't know how she did.''
</P>
<P>
   The baby arrived at 1:22 EDT on Monday. By 7:30 a.m. Tuesday,
Fox was back on a plane, and he arrived in Sacramento around 4 p.m.
for the 7:30 game, hoping he could help the Lakers close out the
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being here is just an opportunity to, if needed, help in some
fashion,'' he said. ``I'm sure if I'm hurting us, (coach Phil
Jackson) will take me out. If I'm helping, he'll leave me in.''
</P>
<P>
   He admitted the situation had him distracted, a fact evident in
Fox's brief and unproductive Game 3 performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I realized how much of it was weighing in the
back of my mind, and a lot of it, the concern of obviously having a
healthy wife and baby,'' Fox said. ``Once the baby is here and
hearing my wife say, `Look, I know it's important to you and the
Lakers and the city, besides we want to play you guys in the
finals' - she's a Knick fan - `you better get there if you can.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And so, her unselfishness as a wife and mother should be
recognized and made a point of, because she was the one that pushed
me out the door and wanted me to get here. Splitting your focus is
one thing but knowing that your family is most important.... But if
we don't win this game tonight, I would be pretty sick to watch it
on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Stupid radio tricks: The Kings' flagship radio station attempted
a lame stunt Tuesday morning, made even more lame by the fact it
didn't pull it off.
</P>
<P>
   The station sent someone to the Lakers' hotel at 6:15 a.m.,
trying to deliver a package to Shaquille O'Neal. The rip-roaring
hilarious contents? A free-throw shooting brochure and a children's
rhyming dictionary (to aid O'Neal's rap career). The messenger
pounded loudly on a few doors, waking up other hotel guests, but
never even made it to the right floor, much less O'Neal's room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have beat them up if they knocked on my door at 6
a.m., harassing me,'' O'Neal said later. ``Quote me on that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
