u p BC-NY-NASSAU-ELECT-NYT &LR;      05-02 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-NASSAU-ELECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASSAU COUNTY VOTERS GIVE DEMOCRAT DECIDING SEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT WASHINGTON, N.Y. _ Democrats regained control of the Nassau
County Legislature on Tuesday night as Craig M. Johnson, a
Democrat, won a special election to succeed his mother, Barbara,
whose death in March had cost the party its first majority in 80
years.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats were propelled into power in this overwhelmingly
Republican suburb in November, when concern about the county's
collapsing finances fueled a voter rebellion that ended decades of
one-party rule. But their majority was a slim one _ one vote _ and
they lost it when Ms. Johnson died of breast cancer on March 9.
</P>
<P>
   With the balance of power in Nassau County at stake, the special
election to fill her seat became a bitterly fought three-way
contest.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Johnson, a 29-year-old bankruptcy lawyer, beat both a
Republican challenger, Linda H. Green, 52, a former North Hempstead
town clerk, and Benjamin L. Zwirn, 48, a former Democrat who ran an
insurgent campaign on the Green Party line.
</P>
<P>
   In unofficial results, with all precincts reporting, Johnson led
with 6,774 votes or 58 percent of the total, to 2,650 votes or 23
percent for Green and 2,278 votes or 19 percent for Zwirn, The
Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to thank the voters of this district for having
the confidence in me, and the confidence in the Democratic Party,
as the party that can restore fiscal stability to Nassau County,''
Johnson said on Tuesday night. ``The people are tired of politics
as usual.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote on Tuesday capped what can only be described as a
topsy-turvy year in Nassau.
</P>
<P>
   It is a wealthy county that went broke in boom times, a
Republican stronghold that voted the Democrats into power, a place
where old alliances have been thrown out the window.
</P>
<P>
   The overwhelmingly Republican county stunned the political
establishment last November, when an electorate that was angry over
the fiscal crisis, tax increases and a series of government
scandals ended decades of one-party rule in the county and gave the
Democrats a 10-to-9 majority in its legislative branch for the
first time in 80 years.
</P>
<P>
   Four months later, Ms. Johnson's death left the Legislature tied
9-to-9 as the county faced one of the worst fiscal crises in its
history.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, voters were still plenty angry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm steamed,'' said Erika Sotiriou, 65, a registered
Republican from Strathmore who was so incensed by what she saw as
the mismanagement of the county, and her fears that further tax
increases would be required to set things right, that she voted
Democratic. ``I'm upset that thy let it go this far; now we're
going to get zonked.''
</P>
<P>
   The root of the political tumult is Nassau's financial crisis.
Years of generous labor contracts and providing high levels of
services to residents without raising taxes finally caught up with
Nassau last year when the county found itself spending more money
than it took in.
</P>
<P>
   Nassau County managed to finish 1999 in the black only after
selling its hospital and using its share of the nation's settlement
with tobacco companies to plug its budget gap.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a tax increase that the Republicans passed before losing
control of the Legislature in November, the county faces a $200
million budget gap this year. This has led to service cuts, fee
increases and threats to lay off county workers.
</P>
<P>
   And Nassau, which relies on bond sales to meet its expenses, has
seen its bonds downgraded to the level just above junk status,
making it the worst credit risk among wealthy suburban counties in
the nation.
</P>
<P>
   But putting Nassau back on its feet could entail a number of
politically risky options. Some political analysts wonder why any
party would want control of the Legislature now.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Republicans win, they get the chance to be blamed for
things a second time, and if the Democrats win, they are still
stuck with the problems,'' said Arthur J. Kremer, a former state
assemblyman, who practices law in Nassau. ``You've heard of win-win
situations? This one could be win-lose.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
