<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-LANGENBRUNNER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOULDER INJURY PUTS LANGENBRUNNER ON SIDELINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAC ENGEL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif._ When Stars winger Jamie Langenbrunner didn't
attend Monday's practice it was no big deal. It was optional.
</P>
<P>
   When he didn't last long at yesterday's morning skate, it became
a big deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm good, but I don't know about my winger,'' Stars center Joe
Nieuwendyk said. ``He took a hard hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the hit, given by Sharks winger Dave Lowry on
Langenbrunner shoulder in Game 2, was so hard that it prevented him
from playing in Game 3 last night. He is listed day-to-day with a
bruised shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gone through this all year,'' Stars winger Mike Keane
said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Add Langenbrunner to the Stars' seemingly limitless ``Did Not
Play _ Injured'' list, forcing them to again shuffle their lines,
secure in the knowledge that they have skated on this patch nearly
all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not going to replace him,'' said Scott Thornton,
Langenbrunner's linemate. ``Hopefully it's a short term thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the third period of Game 2, Langenbrunner had his
head down near the blue line when Lowry slammed into him.
Langenbrunner then retreated to the bench in obvious pain, and team
trainer Dave Surprenant attended to him.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, Langenbrunner missed 11 games because of a pinched
nerve in his neck after a hit in Edmonton on Jan. 11 that caused
numbness in his hands.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate effects of Lowry's hit did not prevent
Langenbrunner, who has one goal and two assists in the playoffs,
from returning later in Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   Langenbrunner was playing alongside Thornton and Nieuwendyk on
the second line, giving Nieuwendyk, the reigning Conn Smythe trophy
winner, reason to smile being paired with his close friend.
</P>
<P>
   Now, rookie and normal fourth-liner Roman Lyashenko, who was a
healthy scratch for in Games 1 or 2, is up on the second line.
</P>
<P>
   It also changes the special teams, where Langenbrunner saw
action on both the power play and penalty kill.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a lot of ways to play positionally in hockey. In that
sense, anybody can step in and do the job,'' Thornton said. ``I
don't think it's going to be that difficult to play with somebody
else.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars should know. They've done it enough.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-02-00 2345EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000502.0383 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-02 23:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3929 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-RAC-DRYSDALE-TEX     05-02 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-DRYSDALE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRYSDALE DOESN'T PUSH HORSES, BUT HE GETS RESULTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Irony seems to gush through the life of Neil
Drysdale. The 52-year-old trainer has never run a horse in the
Kentucky Derby, but he has two horses, Fusaichi Pegasus and War
Chant, who figure to be among the Derby favorites this year.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday added to the irony when his election to the
Thoroughbred Racing Hall of Fame was announced. And possibly the
best compliment he received all day came from one of his Derby
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are very few trainers that I'd call a genius,'' said
Barry Irwin, the managing partner for the ownership group of The
Deputy. ``But in his own way, Neil's a genius.''
</P>
<P>
   Irwin has firsthand knowledge because he has used Drysdale as a
trainer. Irwin and his partners owned Prized in 1989. The horse was
accomplished, good enough to win the Molson Million at Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   That race was on dirt, and Prized never had raced on grass. That
didn't stop Drysdale from entering Prized into the Breeders' Cup
Turf. Packed into a race with the best grass horses in North
America and some of the best from Europe, horses that had spent
their careers running on turf, Prized won as a huge long shot.
</P>
<P>
   But compared to trainers D. Wayne Lukas or Bob Baffert, Drysdale
isn't as noticeable in the limelight. Though Drysdale has trained
five Eclipse Award winners, his style is less flashy than his
colleagues'. Irwin didn't send The Deputy to Drysdale because he
wanted a trainer who would be more demanding with the horse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Wayne's nature with his stable is to full-court press
all the time,'' said Todd Pletcher, a former assistant trainer to
Lukas who plans to run four horses in the Derby on Saturday. ``If
you want someone to train a horse like they're walking the ball up
the court, Wayne will tell you, `Don't come to me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Drysdale is walking the ball up the court with Fusaichi Pegasus
and War Chant. In fact, it's almost like a four-corners offense.
Both colts are among the most lightly raced horses in the field.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas Baffert has put 11 races into Captain Steve and Lukas
has raced High Yield 12 times, Drysdale has put Fusaichi Pegasus
and War Chant through a combined nine races. No horse has won the
Derby off as few as four prep races since 1918. But Fusaichi
Pegasus has won four of his five races (he was second in the
other), and War Chant has won three of four (he, too, was second in
the other).
</P>
<P>
   So, Drysdale is unfazed by history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've come here with talented horses,'' Drysdale said. ``If you
had to choose between experience and talent, I'd take talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Irwin isn't the only owner who has had some edginess with
Drysdale's schedule. War Chant is owned by Marjorie and Irving
Cowan, who also sent War Chant's dam, Hollywood Wildcat, to
Drysdale. Hollywood Wildcat won the Breeders' Cup Distaff in 1993,
but Irving Cowan admits Drysdale's schedule frustrates him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does sometimes,'' Cowan said. ``You want to see your horse
run. I don't mean every week, but every three weeks maybe.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can argue with his schedule, but you can't argue with the
results. He puts the horses first, not himself or the owners. I
respect that.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Cowan knows Drysdale won't hesitate to take War Chant out of
the Derby if the colt isn't running as well as he can. He did a
similar thing in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   That year, he trained A.P. Indy, who had won the Santa Anita
Derby and figured to be the second favorite in the Kentucky Derby.
But A.P. Indy developed a small crack the size of a pinprick in his
hoof wall. Drysdale scratched A.P. Indy out of the Derby the
morning of the race.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, Drysdale brought A.P. Indy back in a prep race for
the Belmont Stakes. A.P. Indy won that, won the Belmont, won the
Breeders' Cup Classic and was named Horse of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   It's a pattern Drysdale learned before he became a head trainer.
He was born and grew up in England. By 1970, he had come to
Southern California and started working as an assistant trainer to
Charlie Whittingham. A Hall of Famer, Whittingham won more major
races than any other trainer on the Southern California circuit,
and Drysdale was in his barn for four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned masses from Charlie,'' Drysdale said. ``He was a
very good teacher, very articulate. The things that stood out were
patience and putting the horse first.''
</P>
<P>
   And sometimes _ every now and then, eventually _ it puts
Drysdale in first. / nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
