<HEADLINE>
RACING'S PLAN EARNS ENDORSEMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. -- A plan to bring bettors back to tracks and
satellite betting outposts around the state got a ringing
endorsement from the state Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The $5.9 million plan presented Tuesday afternoon to the
California Horse Racing Board at its monthly meeting incorporates
direct marketing techniques and targeted advertising, according to
its author John Liebau.
</P>
<P>
   A key element of the plan is an $800,000 database that will
track the attendance and betting habits of participating race fans.
The program is similar to those employed by Las Vegas casinos and
airlines that offer frequent flyer miles. ``By tracking our
customers and how (often) they come to the track, we're hoping we
can cause them to come more frequently than in the past,'' said
Liebau, a San Marino resident who is president of Bay Meadows
Racecourse in Northern California.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our success will be measured by increased attendance and
handle,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Liebau cautioned that tangible results might be a long way off.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a long process,'' he said. ``The National Thoroughbred
Racing Association has been marketing our sport for three years now
and I still don't think we have the sport branded.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those who praised the database was John Van de Kamp,
general counsel and chief executive for the Thoroughbred Owners of
California.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we get the sense we are tracking our regular attendance,
this program will have statewide impact,'' Van de Kamp said.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of the $5.9 million will be spent on radio, television
and newspaper advertising In other business, the CHRB:
</P>
<P>
   (BOX) Approved contracts for stewards and veterinarians through
2001;
</P>
<P>
   (BOX) Agreed to extend for one year a drug testing agreement
with Truesdail Laboratories;
</P>
<P>
   (BOX) Passed a resolution praising former CHRB chairman George
Nicholaw;
</P>
<P>
   (BOX) Ordered stewards at Hollywood Park to investigate claims
by the Service Employees International Union Local 1877 that they
aren't receiving dues from assistant starters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
